<HEADER>
A6389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-SHANAHAN-NY     02-01 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-SHANAHAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANAHAN ALREADY TALKING REPEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Mike Shanahan repeated himself on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan, who became the first coach to win a pair of Super
Bowls in his first four seasons, addressed the Denver Broncos'
defense of the crown, just as he did last year after his team upset
Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them the off-season program starts the day after
tomorrow, and hopefully we'll have the same type of off season as
last year,'' Shanahan said after the Broncos' 34-19 victory over
the Atlanta Falcons in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   The coach has again set the bar high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder the second time,'' he said. ``But we decided that
this season we would be satisfied with nothing less than a Super
Bowl. It was our goal from the beginning. It was a high goal, but
our players really stayed in there throughout the season.
Obviously, this was a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   But now he may have to do it without John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left a bunch of guys trying to talk him into three-peat,''
Shanahan said after leaving the locker room. ``I don't know if
they're getting to him or not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's John's last game. I think there's a
chance it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to go out, what a way to go out,'' he said of
Elway, the game's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   When the Broncos' owner, Pat Bowlen, handed Shanahan the Vince
Lombardi Trophy, the coach said: ``It feels awfully good. I would
like John to come back for a third time. He's going to have to sit
down and talk with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   While Elway was the game's mvp, Shanahan did his own most
valuable part. He oversaw a game plan that the Falcons were not
prepared for _ most noticeably on the goal-line situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the plan was going to Howard Griffith,'' he said. ``We
felt that Atlanta did a great job on the goal line keying to the
primary ballcarrier.''
</P>
<P>
   So Elway faked handoffs to Davis and gave the football to
Griffith, who scored a pair of touchdowns, getting only a total of
9 yards on 4 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Those scores helped Shanahan achieve 32 victories over the last
two seasons, the Broncos having reacted to the constant pressure
from their coach to keep improving. It is why the Broncos haven't
lost a game in which they led at halftime since September 1996, and
it is why they outscored the opposition by 47-9 in the regular
season on opening drives.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have been relentless, and they have been relentless
over time. The even had to overcome what Shanahan describes as
``adversity'' _ the loss to the New York Giants after having won
the first 13 games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Shanahan is raising the bar even higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6391 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-HNS &LR;      02-01 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ If Super Bowl XXXIII turns out to be the last game of
Denver quarterback John Elway's magnificent career, he went out in
the kind of style usually reserved for legends.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elway was the unquestioned star of the Broncos' 34-19 victory
over the Atlanta Falcons on Sunday, throwing for 336 yards and a
touchdown to help Denver win its second consecutive Super Bowl. He
also ran for a touchdown and was the unanimous selection as the
game's Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won a car?'' Elway asked in regard to his MVP award.
``That's all I need _ another car.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway owns automobile dealerships in Denver, and after Sunday's
performance in which he helped pluck Atlanta's Dirty Birds, he owns
Colorado. He may enter the political arena after his retirement,
which he is expected to announce sometime in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to talk about retirement right now,'' Elway
said. ``I want to enjoy this win. This definitely throws a kink in
it (his retirement plans), but I don't have to cross that bridge
for a while. I got emotional a couple of times, but I think that
emotion helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   On a weekend in which Falcons safety Eugene Robinson brought
shame on his family and teammates after being charged with
solicitation of a prostitute, Elway was a shining example of
everything that is good about the game in front of a Pro Player
Stadium crowd of 74,802 and a worldwide television audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos are in position to become the first team to win
three consecutive Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of guys in this dressing room talking to John
about a three-peat, but I don't know if they'll be successful,''
Denver coach Mike Shanahan said. ``I don't know if it'll be his
last game _ I suspect it will _ but if you're going to go out, what
a way to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who completed 18 of his 29 passes, convincingly outplayed
his Atlanta counterpart, Chris Chandler. Chandler was 19-of-35 for
219 yards and a touchdown. He was intercepted three times in the
second half, when the Broncos blew the game open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We confused him,'' said Denver cornerback Darrien Gordon, who
intercepted two passes. ``Our coverage was good. It seemed like he
had happy feet. When the quarterback's got people in his face, it's
hard for him to step up and throw. All the credit should go to our
guys up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who sparked a 457-yard attack, was far from alone in
helping Denver become the seventh team to win consecutive Super
Bowls and the first since Dallas after the 1992 and 1993 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Terrell Davis rushed for 102 yards on 25 carries.
It was his seventh consecutive 100-yard playoff game, including
three this season. Fullback Howard Griffith scored on a pair of
one-yard runs. Receiver Rod Smith had five catches for 152 yards
and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's two interceptions set up touchdowns. He had four
interceptions combined in the Super Bowl and AFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' defense, which plays in the shadow of a highly
rated, well-publicized offense, surrendered only one touchdown
Sunday, and that came when the game was out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   In playoff victories over the Dolphins, Jets and Falcons, the
Broncos' defense allowed two touchdowns total, one on a one-yard
drive after a blocked punt against the Jets and the other in the
waning moments Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we don't give up many points,'' Gordon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though they didn't commit a penalty, the Falcons, who upset
Minnesota in the NFC Championship Game, didn't play as if they
belonged in the Super Bowl. Cornerback Ray Buchanan shot off his
mouth and guaranteed a Falcons victory, but the only thing
guaranteed was coach Dan Reeves' joining Minnesota's Bud Grant and
Buffalo's Marv Levy as the only coaches to lose four Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get it done,'' Reeves said. ``We missed that field
goal. We missed a fourth-down attempt. We had to settle for two
field goals. We threw three interceptions. You just can't win if
you don't score when you get in the red zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons could have been in much better shape after driving
into Denver territory four times in the first half, three times
inside the 20. But they wound up with only two Morten Andersen
field goals to show for their effort.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta reached Denver's eight-yard line before a third-down
sack of Chandler preceded a 32-yard field goal from Andersen. After
cornerback Ronnie Bradford intercepted a pass that bounced off
tight end Shannon Sharpe, who was knocked out of the game in the
first quarter with a torn medial collateral ligament, the Falcons
got the ball at Denver's 35. On fourth-and-one, running back Jamal
Anderson, who would finish with 96 yards on 18 carries, was thrown
for a two-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons again drove to Denver's eight, but Andersen missed a
26-yard field-goal attempt. When Atlanta reached Denver's 11, the
Falcons had to settle for Andersen's 28-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Broncos were taking advantage of just about
everything the Falcons gave them.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 3-0 on Atlanta's first series, the Broncos
went the distance on their opening possession. The 10-play, 80-yard
drive ended with Griffith scoring on a one-yard run. Elway was
3-of-4 for 67 yards on the drive.
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson was stopped on fourth down by the Broncos, Elway
and Davis took turns making plays to take them to Atlanta's eight.
That series ended with Jason Elam's 26-yard field goal that gave
Denver a 10-3 lead with 9:17 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons recovered nicely and advanced to the Denver eight,
but Andersen's missed field goal, especially one so short, seemed
to take something out of them.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, Smith got away from Bradford on the jam and
cut through the middle. Robinson, who couldn't have been in a good
frame of mind after his arrest, allowed Smith to get behind him for
what turned out to be an easy 80-yard touchdown pass. Elam made it
17-3 with 4:54 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Dwight's 42-yard kickoff return to the Denver 49 gave the
Falcons good field position. They drove to the 11, but after
Chandler threw two incompletions, they had to settle for Andersen's
second field goal and a 17-6 halftime deficit.
</P>
<P>
   On their first possession of the second half, the Broncos drove
from their 26 to Atlanta's 20, but Elam missed a 38-yard field-goal
attempt to ruin the scoring opportunity. It was his first miss of
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Denver did everything to let Atlanta stay in the game, but on
the Falcons' next two series, Chandler threw interceptions. The
first one was intercepted by cornerback Darrius Johnson, but the
Broncos wasted the opportunity when Elam missed a 48-yard
field-goal try.
</P>
<P>
   The next one was tipped at the line by tackle Keith Traylor and
intercepted by Gordon, who returned it 58 yards. This time, the
Broncos didn't waste it when Griffith scored on another one-yard
run for a 24-6 advantage four seconds into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler got the hat trick by throwing a third interception.
Once again, it was Gordon who prevented a touchdown by intercepting
the pass at the Denver two and returning it 50 yards to the Atlanta
48. Gordon set a Super Bowl record with 108 yards on interception
returns.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos capitalized. Davis got them off to a fast start on
the series by taking a short pass and turning it into a 39-yard
gain to the Atlanta nine. Two plays later, Elway ran a quarterback
draw three yards for a touchdown and a 31-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight, who had been close to breaking a touchdown for three
quarters, went the distance on the ensuing kickoff. His 94-yard
return for the touchdown pulled the Falcons within 31-13.
</P>
<P>
   Denver ended its scoring with Elam's 37-yard field goal with
7:08 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons finally scored an offensive touchdown when Terance
Mathis caught a three-yard pass from Chandler with 2:04 left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
