r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     02-01 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWING THE SUPER BOWL BROADCAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Super Bowl is irony at work.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 30 years now, America has collectively thrown a
Super Bowl TV party on a late Sunday in January in anticipation of
some good football, only to get the equivalent of a sedative.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, the only thing louder than Fox's Terry Bradshaw is
the sound of a few million Americans snoring through the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIII had its moments for Fox Sports and an audience
of 150 million Sunday, but they were all too brief and
significantly shorter than most of the ceaseless commercial breaks.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first quarter, one could surmise that Denver
was going to win and that any anticipation left would revolve
around point spreads, office pools and the entertainment value of
the commercials.
</P>
<P>
   By my unofficial count, only seven of the 33 Super Bowls can
officially be labeled as competitive, which means there's been a
whole lot of fill time in TV. Thankfully, John Madden is more than
capable of filling large gaps.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of TV sports critics have speculated that Madden isn't
as interested in his work as he was back in the '80s, when he
became a mythic figure in the business. But he certainly was in
tune Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Madden's antennea were up. On Denver's first
drive, Madden detailed the way the Broncos block for Terrell Davis
and how well they disguise things, to the degree that that
sometimes there's no one for the linement to block.
</P>
<P>
   By Atlanta's second drive, he noted how the Bronco defense had
already adjusted to the Falcons' game plan. After initally loading
eight men in the box, Madden picked up Denver's adjustment and
correctly forecast blitzes on three straight Falcon snaps.
</P>
<P>
   And when Atlanta's Dan Reeves decided to attempt a fourth down
converstion early, Madden called it ``a bad idea'' before Jamal
Anderson was gang tackled for a loss. ``In a close game in the
first half, going for a field goal with a guy like Morten Andersen
is automatic,'' said Madden.
</P>
<P>
   The game sort of went downhill from there, but Madden's
enthusiasm never flagged. He found several themes to replay from
different angles, ranging from why John Elway shouldn't consider
retirement to why Dan Reeves has no reason to feel disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   There were two things Madden and Pat Summerall did not talk
about much: Eugene Robinson's arrest Saturday night and the
Reeves-Mike Shanahan feud.
</P>
<P>
   I can think of a dozen respected play-by-play men who would have
strummed that feud all night. But Madden made a distinction during
the week that the feud was not going to have a big impact on what
happens in the game, and he barely mentioned it.
</P>
<P>
   Given the hyperbole of the Super Bowl, it was rather nice to not
have an issue tattoed on viewers. As far as the Robinson story, Fox
covered it several times in the pregame show, which is where it
belonged. Madden's only reference to it was posed as part of the
game plan: Would Denver attack Robinson early to see if his mind
was still on Biscayne Boulevard?
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Fox unit didn't fare as well as Madden.
Well-known for its technical toys and aggressive attitude, Fox was
rather bland Sunday. Fox's techno graphics were cool, especially
the lineup graphic that popped out of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no buzz to the telecast. The replays viewers saw
were the same replays you could see on any game in October. And
several times, the production team broke one of TV's ten
commandments by using an end zone corner camera for live shots.
</P>
<P>
   That's simply an ego shot. Producers and directors should know
better than to break the comfort wall for viewers. Using obtuse
angles for live shots breaks continuity. One can understand the
desire to try something new, but such experiments should be limited
to a Bears-Rams game in October.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Fox twice arrived late out of a commercial break into a
live play. The second time happened to be John Elway's long
touchdown pass to Rod Smith. Fox didn't try to bury the error; Pat
Summerall even joked about it, saying Fox got caught not being
ready just like the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Fox is at the mercy of an official on the field who is
supposed to hold play until the network is clear from its breaks.
</P>
<P>
   And America remains at the mercy of an event which produces good
games with the same regularity of a Blue Moon. ABC takes a whack at
keeping the audience (and Dan Dierdorf) awake next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
