<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN WARLORD LAID TO REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, South Africa _ Thousands of mourners from around the
country Sunday buried one of South Africa's most charismatic
figures and dangerous thugs.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed more like a political rally than a funeral. Police and
military formed a tight cordon around this small hillside town to
maintain order during the final rites of Sifiso Nkabinde, a
self-described warlord who was gunned down a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral passed peacefully. But many South Africans fear
Nkabinde's death could rekindle political violence ahead of
national elections later this year. For nearly a decade Nkabinde
was a central figure in the conflict in KwaZulu-Natal Province _ a
bloody rivalry between the African National Congress and the
Inkatha Freedom Party. The strife has claimed nearly 12,000 lives
since 1990 and almost derailed the country's first democratic
elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   National and regional political leaders across party lines have
appealed for calm while investigators search for Nkabinde's
killers. ``The death of Sifiso should not usher in a cycle of
revenge that will threaten to destroy the delicate democracy that
is taking its first steps in our nation,'' said Bantu Holomisa, a
friend and political colleague of Nkabinde, at the funeral Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC has blamed the killing on criminals. But many at the
grass-roots level are convinced that Nkabinde died in a political
attack. Ousted from the ANC in 1997 on suspicions that he was an
informer in the early 1990s for the apartheid police, Nkabinde
found a new political home in Holomisa's fledgling United
Democratic Movement, or UDM. He took his supporters with him, and
much of the mourning Sunday found expression in anti-ANC sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ANC said Sifiso was a spy,'' said one young man, refusing
to give his name. ``They have lied. We can't now say we'll have
peace when our brother is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In its final report, published late last year, the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission found Nkabinde responsible for leading
hit squads and flooding KwaZulu-Natal with weapons. A court
acquitted Nkabinde last year on 16 counts of murder, but his trial
coincided with a telling phenomenon. ``While he was in custody,
violence in Richmond decreased dramatically,'' says Gail Wanenberg,
a former TRC investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Wanenberg believes KwaZulu will be more peaceful without
Nkabinde. But her colleague, Jenny Irish, a longtime peace monitor
in the province, says the warlord's death fits into a troubling new
pattern. Random bloodletting may be less prevalent than it was in
1994, but political assassinations are on the rise. She counts 12
hits in the province in the past year, across the party spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would indicate that there are elements trying to create
instability among the parties in the region,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly troublesome because the ANC and IFP have
made important strides toward peace in the last year. Leaders of
the two parties have talked about an amnesty for KwaZulu that would
give perpetrators of past violence indemnity from prosecution.
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, the head of the ANC and President
Nelson Mandela's likely successor, has openly courted IFP chief
Mangosuthu Buthelezi.
</P>
<P>
   In political terms, the ANC's interest in finding peace with the
IFP is simple. Inkatha won control of the province in 1994, and the
ANC wants to capture it this year in its quest for a two-thirds
majority in Parliament. Nkabinde's death could disrupt the truce
between the two groups.
</P>
<P>
   Irish says that as long as the joint police-military force, at a
strength of nearly 1,000, remains in Richmond, peace will prevail.
But local IFP leader David Ntombela, a close friend of Nkabinde's,
offers no assurance that the ANC will be safe campaigning in
KwaZulu-Natal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem with the UDM,'' he said after Nkabinde's
funeral. ``But if the ANC comes here, that is their concern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6394 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-HURRICANES     02-01 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-HURRICANES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ZERO IN ON DEADLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ He had tried just about everything else. He had
offered explanations, theories, reasons for his team's funk. He
tried benching players then putting them back out there. He has had
many sleepless nights agonizing over line combinations, power-play
units, goaltending schedules. The players had a separate meeting
after their terrible performance in Pittsburgh with his blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Bruins coach Pat Burns decided to try something new _
brown shoes with a black suit _ in hopes of breaking the hex that
had his club on a four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Well, sort of. The Bruins didn't win, they didn't
lose, and they didn't even score but they earned a point in the
standings with a scoreless tie with the Carolina Hurricanes in
their matinee meeting at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't score but we had some great chances,'' said Burns.
``If you keep on doing that, sooner or later it's going to go in.
We kept them off the board. We got a point out of it and that's
what is important. Any point we can pick up from now to the end is
important. I thought we played hard right to the end. As long as we
have some passion and some emotion like this, we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Dafoe made 24 saves and picked up his 12th career shutout
in his 200th NHL game, his fifth blanking of the season. Carolina
netminder Trevor Kidd earned career shutout No. 15 with 36 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday, the Bruins had not posted two scoreless ties in a
season since 1955-56. In 1955, Boston and Detroit shut out each
other on Oct. 22 and Nov. 13. The Bruins' other 0-0 tie this year
was Nov. 7 at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The first period was a real tractor pull, with neither team
generating much. The second picked up quite a bit for both sides.
The third was the Bruins' best, with the home team generating many
quality chances, but Kidd wouldn't yield.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Ellett on the power play had one of the best chances when
he hit a post after taking a pass from Jason Allison. On a power
play later in the period, the Bruins were all over Kidd again but
couldn't beat him. With 36 seconds left in overtime, Tim Taylor had
a decent opportunity in front but couldn't finish. Boston had by
far the better of the opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins felt they deserved a better fate than the tie but
with the way their fortunes have been lately, they were thrilled to
have something other than a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we deserved to (win), the way we played,'' said right
wing Rob DiMaio. ``We just didn't find the net tonight. We had
plenty of chances to score, some great, great opportunities but the
puck didn't find its way in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good test for us. We knew we had to come out and do
something that was different than what we were doing. Things
weren't working, we were doubting ourselves a little bit. We came
out with a game plan that we were going to play a smart game and we
limited their chances. It was a good step, something to be positive
about.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a trying time for the Bruins lately but the coach is
keeping a stiff upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed, I'm not frustrated at all,'' said Burns.
``I'm certainly not going to walk around with a big smile on my
face thinking everything is going great. Things aren't going great.
I have sleepless nights, yes I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all kinds of line combinations. I even put brown shoes
on today with a black suit and that's not me. I'm not frustrated,
far from being that. I'm encouraged and we have to keep on being
encouraged. We're trying our damndest to win and we have to keep on
going.''
</P>
<P>
   If things don't change, it will be black shoes with a brown suit
next.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
