<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENNIS-AUSTRALIAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAFELNIKOV RIGHT ON MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ If the day's rubles were stacked up they'd tower
alongside Australia's loftiest peak, Mt. Kosciusko. But rubles
don't figure in the life of Russian tennis player Yevgeny
Kafelnikov any more. He deals in dollars now _ $434,000 of them for
beating a Swede, Thomas Enqvist, Sunday to take the Australian Open
title _ and, more importantly, the restoration of his devalued
pride.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov's once-brilliant career, reaching an early pinnacle
three years ago as he won the French singles and doubles (a rare
duet) at 22, was beginning to resemble the Russian economy. He was
making boo-boos, losing to who's-whos, and gaining only a
reputation as very uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's over. He's turned around. Yevgeny's a stubborn Russian
nut and I'm a crazy Ukrainian nut,'' Larry Stefanki, standing in a
hallway at Melbourne Park, raved after his guy's 4-6, 6-0, 6-4, 7-6
(7-1), title triumph. ``That's why we understand each other. Our
goal now: No. 1. Yevgeny can match Pete Sampras in everything but
the serve, and that will come.''
</P>
<P>
   If the champ's new coach, Stefanki, out of LaQuinta, Calif., and
before that Stanford, sounds like a fast-talking fight manager,
maybe that's what the prodigal, Kafelnikov, needed. Stefanki, a
decent player on the tour more than a decade ago, seems to
specialize in hard-rock cases. The last was surly Marcelo Rios,
with whom Stefanki served two terms. San Quentin might have been
easier time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fired myself the first time. It was just too tough,''
Stefanki said with a smile. ``His father begged me to try again.''
The second time around Stefanki tutored Rios _ the eighth dwarf,
Grumpy Jr. _ to the Australian final just a year ago, and No. 1 for
a brief stretch last spring. Then the grateful Rios fired him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcelo said he wanted to go in another direction. Where do
you go from No. 1?'' Stefanki said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But No. 1 remains the pedagogical aspiration for Stefanki. It
was reignited when, back home, he got a phone call from Kafelnikov,
an uninspired loser to an anonymous Swede at the US Open. The
caller made an offer for one of the best examples of detente since
Gorbachev was around. The Russian wanted an American coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working with Jonas Bjorkman, as nice a guy as you can
find. It's great when you're in demand. I had to choose between
Bjorkman and the crazy Russian, but I thought Yevgeny could go all
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm just one reason. The main one is probably his marriage
to Mascha last July, and their two kids, one a stepchild, the other
their new baby. That gives you a different look at things. But I
think I've got him thinking about what he can do in the next three
years, the window of opportunity, the Hall of Fame, maybe a Davis
Cup for Russia with that good kid, Marat Safin.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many guys have won on clay in Paris and a hard court like
here? Sampras hasn't. Rios couldn't handle the final a year ago (a
6-2, 6-2, 6-2, stomping by Petr Korda). I told Yevgeny just to slow
down, stay calm, and enjoy the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did,'' said Kafelnikov from behind a rusty, scraggly beard
that he vowed ``to shave off after I won, like Bjorn Borg used to
do. You don't get many chances like this, and you have to be able
to focus for a couple of hours, concentrate basically on this one
match. Marriage was a turning point for me. Other things, too, like
Larry, just to relieve the pressure in my head. I'm more flexible,
happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I could jump over the China wall with no
difficulties.'' Well, he did jump seven flights, from No. 10 to No.
3, right behind Sampras and Alex Corretja, while Rios _ a no-show
with a gimpy back _ has descended from No. 2 to No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``One for two ain't bad,'' Stefanki said of his family's
almost-double, the Aussie and the football game in Miami involving
his brother-in-law, Atlanta QB Chris Chandler. Larry, married to
Diane Chandler's sister, Kelly, is a regular golfing partner with
Chandler and an earlier QB, father-in-law John Brodie, the
ex-Niner.
</P>
<P>
   Stefanki took Rios to a different sort of court to recover
agreed-upon wages. Did he get his money? ``No. Kelly, my wife, said
let's forget about it. We don't want anything from that guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said with a grin, ``I hope Marcelo was watching the
TV, watching Yevgeny win.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Stefanki should open a reform school if he gets tired of
tennis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
