r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     02-01 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS GOOD, BUT DYNASTY TALK TOO MUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _Within certain Rocky Mountain precincts loud voices will
be heard proclaiming dynasty status for the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse the prolonged yawn from Mr. and Mrs. America and all
ships at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Credit, please, where it's due, and now with back-to-back world
championships, the Broncos deserve ringing applause for emerging as
the best team in the NFL salary cap-free agency era. Which, in no
way, is to be compared with what the Cowboys or 49ers accomplished
earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   And for the most glaring example of these Broncos being both
separate and not equal to the way-it-was in the NFL throne room,
there's the old Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   But as Super Bowls go, the 33rd edition here yesterday did have
a familiar storyline from yesteryear. There was much more blooper
than super for one participant, that being the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Dirty Bird was not a dance. It was messy offensive football that
soured the sweetest NFL story of this season. And with deep regret
for anyone living within a hundred miles of Texas Stadium, where
Dan Reeves remains loved by the populace, a 34-19 win for Denver
continued his bitter Super Bowl coaching legacy.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway can retire a double, back-to-back, Super Bowl winner.
If Elway so chooses to retire, that is. But his least-favorite
former coach, Mr. Reeves, continues to live in Super Bowl hell.
</P>
<P>
   Dan is now 0-for-4 in these things, three of them losses with
Elway in Denver. In those four games, Reeves' teams have been
outscored, 170-59. Yikes.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, there was the pregame humiliation for Reeves and
the Falcons, when 21 hours before kickoff, safety Eugene Robinson
was street-busted by the Miami police for seeking certain sexual
favors from what turned out to be an undercover female officer.
</P>
<P>
   Who the heck does Eugene think he is _ the president?
</P>
<P>
   But when the game kicked off, it was Chris Chandler and the
Atlanta offense that should have been arrested. And actually, jail
time was served in the defensive lockup of the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   How strange. Denver won this one with defense. Elway was voted
the MVP by a media panel that must have had its collective head in
the press-box sack lunch when the ballots were marked.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, by the way, was great, particularly since he lost
favorite target Shannon Sharpe to a knee injury on the ninth play.
But the game itself was turned early, and then often, by 11 guys on
defense. Any of them (Darrien Gordon? Bill Romanowski?) coulda and
shoulda been voted MVP, except when you play defense for the
Broncos, it's like being the second-highest mountain in Colorado.
Nobody cares.
</P>
<P>
   For obvious reasons, most of them involving a strong dislike for
each other, much of the pregame whisper last week was about the
Reeves-Mike Shanahan ``thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the MVC (Most Valuable Coach) of this Super
Bowl was Broncos defensive coordinator Greg Robinson, reportedly
not a favorite staff member of Shanahan's. But in crunch time _
meaning every time the Falcons threatened, which seemed like always
_ Robinson had his people in the right place. And his people
repeatedly made huge plays, most of them by blitzing, which spooked
Chandler while also keeping Jamal Anderson in check.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first half, the heart had been yanked out of
the Falcons due to the following:
</P>
<P>
   A first down at the Denver 10, but held to a field goal. Stuffed
on a third-and-one from their own 36, then on a third-and-one from
the Denver 26, which was followed by a fourth-and-one attempt by
Anderson that lost yardage. Reeves gambled in the right spot, but
it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta killer came next. The Falcons had two shots from
inside the Denver 10, did nothing, and then the impossible
happened. Morten Andersen missed on a 26-yard field-goal attempt,
leaving Denver with a 10-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It would get worse. On the Broncos' first play after Andersen's
goof, Elway got speedy receiver Rod Smith deep on Eugene Robinson.
That one went 80 yards for a 17-3 lead, and the lights went out in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson had as much chance against Smith as he did against the
Miami vice squad. But it was also flawed zone coverage that would
leave a safety deep on Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta even came back from that, drove to the Denver 10, yet
again came away with only a field goal. The Falcons' halftime
dressing room was a disaster area for mental health.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler had emerged as a quarterbacking Cinderfellow in this
NFL season, but pumpkin-time came in the second half. The first
three Atlanta possessions _ three interceptions. Lordy.
</P>
<P>
   Recount those MVP votes. And in Colorado, put Greg Robinson in
charge of that Jon Benet Ramsey case. Robinson certainly solved the
mystery of Chris Chandler and the Dan Reeves' offense, which had
confused many this season.
</P>
<P>
   But about the dynasty stuff _ don't get carried away, OK?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
