<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-1S     02-01 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUPER GAME BY ELWAY GIVES BRONCOS TWO IN A ROW
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs for rewriting throughout)  (ART ADV: Seven photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(sw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There was plenty of Denver defense and a gracious dose
of Terrell Davis running. Big-play interceptions abounded for
Denver, and cornerback Darrien Gordon returned two for a Super Bowl
record 108 yards. There were fancy Rod Smith catches, surprising
Howard Griffith scoring runs.
</P>
<P>
   There had been enough tough football through three quarters of
Super Bowl XXXIII that, with the Denver Broncos leading the Atlanta
Falcons by only 17-6, it seemed as if the teams could finish with
flair, offer a little drama.
</P>
<P>
   But there was too much Denver left. And so much John Elway. The
champions had not finished. They wanted more. They took it.
</P>
<P>
   Denver defeated Atlanta, 34-19, on Sunday night before 74,803
fans at Pro Player Stadium to win its second consecutive Super Bowl
championship. It was also the second-straight victory by an
American Football Conference team, after 13 straight National
Conference victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos scored 17 points in the game's first half and then
17 more in the fourth quarter alone. A sprint to the finish gave
the Broncos another sterling silver Vince Lombardi Trophy to
relish.
</P>
<P>
   A memorable moment for Elway, the Bronco quarterback. He was
expected to retire now, though he refused to say after the game.
Through his first 14 seasons he labored and longed for a
championship ring, and now in his last two seasons he has two
glowing rings. At age 38 Elway can leave having saved his best for
last, his best Super Bowl by far in five appearances _ completing
18 of 29 passes for 336 yards with 1 touchdown and 1 interception.
Those numbers _ which included the third-highest passing yardage in
Super Bowl history _ earned Elway the game's most valuable player
award.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Smith's 152 receiving yards on 5 catches, and Davis'
102 rushing yards on 25 carries, they helped give Denver a
remarkable 17-2 season that began with 13 consecutive victories and
ended with the Broncos, once again, as kings. Denver becomes only
the sixth team to win consecutive Super Bowl titles; the Pittsburgh
Steelers did it twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take their chances and blitz a bit, but that is not their
style of defense,'' Elway said of the Falcons, who failed to sack
him. ``They sit back and defend, so we weren't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just thrilled that we won. I'm thrilled to be a part of
this team. This is what we play for, and to have this opportunity
two years in a row is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway soundly outplayed Chris Chandler, the Atlanta quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler was 19 of 35 for 219 yards, with 1 touchdown and 3
interceptions. It was the interceptions in the third quarter that
hurt Atlanta most, especially the second one. It came with Atlanta
at the Denver 21 and looking to cut into a 17-6 Denver lead. But
Gordon swiped Chandler's pass, which had been tipped, and returned
it 58 yards to the Atlanta 24.
</P>
<P>
   Denver would take the ball and continue a drive early into the
fourth quarter that would result in a 1-yard touchdown run by
Griffith. That made it 24-6, and the Falcons would not recover.
Denver piled on more points _ an Elway dive for a touchdown with 11
minutes 20 seconds remaining that made it 31-6. Exclamation point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad,'' Chandler said. ``I just want to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta rookie Tim Dwight returned a kickoff 94 yards for a
touchdown with 11:01 remaining, and the Terance Mathis caught a
3-yard scoring pass for the Falcons with 5:04 remaining, to make
the score closer.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wondrous season for Atlanta and its coach, Dan Reeves,
which finished with a crashing thud.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a case of seizing the moment, and we just didn't
seize it,'' said the Atlanta linebacker Jessie Tuggle, who watched
his offense commit four turnovers and was disappointed when the
defense could only force one. ``Confidence. They played with
confidence, and took the fire out of our offense, and took the fire
out of our team. We are used to setting the tempo, and we did that
all year long by getting turnovers. They got the turnovers. They
put us in a position in this game where we were trying to play
catch-up and trying our best not to make things worse. They made it
where we couldn't play our normal game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another spirited, focused and fulfilling season for
Denver, which finished what it had started, dominating the Falcons
in much the manner it has dominated the National Football League
for two straight seasons, with a sparkling overall record of 33-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today our defense played like an offense,'' said Greg
Robinson, the Broncos' defensive coordinator. ``When we got the
interceptions, those were athletes making those plays and those
were athletes who took the ball and became offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said that Gordon's interception of Chandler completely
changed the game. ``We still had our chances in the third quarter,
and that was a huge interception,'' Reeves said. ``The ball was
tipped, Terance Mathis was wide open in the end zone, but they got
the interception. Our football team learned a heck of a lot being
here and hopefully can come back and they will know how to handle
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan, the Denver head coach, said: ``It was a great
performance by our defense. Any time your secondary is able to come
up with interceptions like they did, there is going to be a great
pass rush as well. So when you do that, which our defense has done
throughout the playoffs the last couple of years, they come up with
a number of big plays. They put pressure on the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   So does the Denver offense, which ran 65 plays and averaged 7
yards a play.
</P>
<P>
   No points were scored in the third quarter because both teams
blew offensive chances, especially Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter, Elam missed attempts from 38 and 48 yards after
long Denver drives. But on long Atlanta drives, Chandler was
intercepted, once by Darrius Johnson and once by Gordon. To
Chandler's credit, he hustled and made the tackle, preventing
Gordon from returning the ball all the way for a score. No matter,
though.
</P>
<P>
   Denver would embark on a drive that would result in Griffith's
1-yard touchdown run 4 seconds into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For most of the game, Denver's offense was the more efficient
one. The Broncos' first-half possessions went this way: touchdown,
interception, field goal, touchdown, punt. Add it up, and the total
was 17 Denver points. They came on a 1-yard run by Griffith with
3:55 left in the first quarter, on which the fullback bullied into
the end zone on a dive play; a 26-yard field goal by Elam, and,
with 4:54 left in the first half, a dramatic Elway-to-Smith 80-yard
pass on which Smith sprinted alone into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, meanwhile, advanced to the Denver 15, 26, 8 and 11
in the game's first 30 minutes but managed only two field goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half Denver won in total yards (266 to 148) and in
passing yards (199 to 80) and in style, execution and production.
</P>
<P>
   It was Smith's 80-yard touchdown grab that, early on, was the
game's signature play.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta kicker Morten Anderson had just missed a 26-yard
field goal that would have cut Denver's lead to 10-6. Instead,
Denver got the ball at its own 20 and instantly made Atlanta pay.
</P>
<P>
   Smith lined up wide-right and ran past cornerback Ronnie
Bradford. That was fine for Atlanta. Bradford appeared to be in
zone coverage and that was his job, to cover Smith for the first 10
to 15 yards and then to release him to help behind. That help was
Robinson, who initially looked ready to pick up the coverage.
Robinson, however, was spun silly by Smith. Smith ran at Robinson
and showed an out move; Robinson reacted to the out and Smith then
ran inside, past Robinson. Robinson could not recover. Smith had a
two-step edge and Elway delivered the pass in stride. Touchdown.
Atlanta was behind by 14 points rather than 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept coming up with their safeties and it looked like we
could go up top,'' Smith said. ``John gave me a great ball and I
ran for the goal posts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons should have realized that it was critical that they
pay attention to the second quarter. Denver was not outscored in
any quarter this season. For Atlanta, there was one such quarter _
the second. During the regular season, the Falcons were outscored
by 95-91 in the second quarter. In the playoffs, they were
outscored by 23-14. Today, it was 10-3, including Smith's big play.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, however, scored first. It took the opening kickoff and
enjoyed Dwight's 21-yard return to the Atlanta 37. A 25-yard
pass-interference penalty on cornerback Ray Crockett, who was
holding the Atlanta receiver Tony Martin, put the ball at the
Denver 21. Atlanta drove to the Denver 8 and then went backward.
Chandler was sacked for a 7-yard loss on a double, middle blitz by
Gordon, a cornerback, and linebacker Bill Romanowski on which
Romanowski got there first. Anderson converted a 32-yard field goal
and with 9:35 left in the first quarter, Atlanta led by 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Denver took the ball on the kickoff and set the tone for the
game. Atlanta gained a field goal on its first drive. Denver would
score a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of tight end Shannon Sharpe catching passes
over the middle in the Denver drive that covered 80 yards in 10
plays and took 5:40. Smith, of course, was in the mix, too. Sharpe
made catches of 12 and 14 yards. In between, Smith made a grab of
41 yards on which Bradford missed a tackle that could have cut the
gain in half. Griffith finished the drive with his 1-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta ran three plays and punted on its next series, beginning
a disturbing first-half trend. On a third-and-1 play, it could not
convert a first-down run. That would happen later in the half on
another third-and-1 and even on a fourth-and-1. But after the first
time, Atlanta got a nice break. It punted and then Elway threw an
interception. The ball bounced off the hands of Sharpe and into
Bradford's hands at the Denver 35 with 1:27 left in the first
quarter. What followed? The possession on which Atlanta failed to
convert on third-and-1 and fourth-and-1, turning the ball right
back to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons suffered the same problems late as they had early:
unproductive offense. Interceptions returned by Denver for long
gains. A committed Denver team intent on making its mark in pro
football history.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first Super Bowl and the first one for this organization
will always be sweetest for me,'' said Steve Atwater, the Broncos'
veteran safety. ``It was the first one for the AFC in a long time.
It meant so much to the people of Denver. But this second one is
pretty close. What a nice problem to have. We've got a couple now
that we can choose from.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
