<HEADLINE>
OPPORTUNITY KNOCKS FOR MCMAHON 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An Irishwoman was favored to win the featured race, the
3,000 meters, in Sunday's Terrier Classic. It just wasn't Marie
McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   After Olympian and four-time NCAA champion Sinead Delahunty
withdrew because of illness, though, the door was left open for
McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hoped I would get second behind Sinead,'' McMahon said
after winning the race at the Boston University Armory in 9:11.69.
``I had no idea what to expect and I am just coming back from
injury, a broken toe which kept me out for eight weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon is accustomed to making the best of unpredictable
situations.
</P>
<P>
   She was raised in Ennistymon, County Clare, in the Republic of
Ireland, where umbrellas are more practical than track shoes. But
McMahon overcame the rain and sleet to establish herself as a
world-class distance runner. She followed Delahunty's trail to
Providence College to run under the direction of Ray Treacy and is
now living in Boston preparing for the Irish national cross-country
championships and the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wet and damp in Ireland, more so than here, and there is
only one indoor track,'' McMahon said. ``I have to go 2 1/2 or
three hours from my home to train indoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy training here. The winters are a bit tough here, but
there are facilities and there are so many top athletes. You can
just jump into a race like this with some very good runners. And,
with this weather, you won't burn out training by the time summer
gets here.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon is focusing on the national championships in Donegal
Feb. 24, then the World Championships in Belfast. She finished 23d
two years ago in the World Championships in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   She increased the pace after a slow start to finish ahead of
Maribel Sanchez of the Central Massachusetts Striders in 9:14.22;
BU women's coach Lesley Lehane, who holds the track record of 8:44,
in 9:14.79; and Larissa Kleinmann, a BU student from Stuttgart,
Germany, in 9:16.66.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go out too hard, but with 10 laps to go, I
felt good, so I thought I would give it a good shot,'' McMahon
said.
</P>
<P>
   In other races:
</P>
<P>
   -- Kate Vermeulen, a West Virginia freshman, upset Kathy Fleming
of New Balance in winning the mile in 4:47;
</P>
<P>
   -- Kim Voyticky, a Duke student competing unattached, won the
800 in 2:07.80, ahead of Claudine Williams of LSU in 2:07.87;
</P>
<P>
   -- Rosemary Ryan, an Irish junior national team member, won the
5,000 in 15:55.92. Ryan, formerly of BU and competing for the BAA,
was far off the meet record of 15:17, set by Sonia O'Sullivan in
1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
