<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6409 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPER-BOWL-SPI &LR;      02-01 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-BOWL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS REPEAT AS SUPER BOWL CHAMPIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ If John Elway wants to go out on top, the record-setting
quarterback of the Denver Broncos should announce his retirement
today when he picks up his MVP trophy for Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   There were many heroes Sunday night as the Broncos defended
their world championship with a convincing 34-19 dismantling of the
Atlanta Falcons at Pro Players Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis, the regular-season MVP and 2,000-yard rusher, put
together his playoff-record seventh straight 100-yard game.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' defense kept the Falcons' offense out of the end
zone until the closing minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Darrien Gordon intercepted a pair of Chris Chandler
passes, returning them 58 and 50 yards to set up second-half
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom-used fullback Howard Griffith ran for two TDs, matching
his career total.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Smith caught five passes for 152 yards, including an 80-yard
TD pass from Elway that proved to be the play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the 38-year-old Elway was the best part of the Broncos'
methodical march to another Super Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thrilled to death that we won,'' Elway said. ``I'm
just thrilled to death to be part of this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I came back for,'' said Elway, who thought long
and hard about retiring after winning his first Super Bowl last
year. ``This is what I've been working nine months for.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the heart and soul of the Broncos return for a chance
at an unprecedented three-peat? Five other teams have won
back-to-back Super Bowls _ the Green Bay Packers (1967-68), Miami
Dolphins (1973-74), Pittsburgh Steelers (1975-76 and 1979-80), San
Francisco 49ers (1989-90) and Dallas Cowboys (1993-94). But no one
has ever made it three straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even going to talk about that,'' Elway said when the
first question asked was about his future. ``I'm just going to
enjoy this and cross that bridge when I come to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway has had a storybook 16-year career, but as far as Super
Bowls go, Sunday night was his finest hour _ actually 3 hours, 18
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After completing just 45 percent of his passes in the Broncos'
three Super Bowl losses and passing for only 123 yards in last
year's upset of the defending champion Green Bay Packers, Elway
was, well, Elway.
</P>
<P>
   He completed 18 of 29 passes for 336 yards, passed for one TD
and ran for another. Elway did have a pass intercepted, but only
because it went off the hands of tight end Shannon Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it is John's last game, but I think there is a
good chance it could be,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said. ``And
if you are going to go out, what a way to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   In a game that was expected to be a duel between Davis and the
Falcons' Jamal Anderson, it came down to Elway's ability to make
plays and Chandler's failure to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Falcons had first downs at the Broncos'
10-, 35-, 15- and 16-yard lines, but were able to score only six
points. They lost the ball on downs once when Anderson was stopped
for a 2-yard loss on a curious pitch play on fourth-and-one. On the
other occasion, Morten Andersen, the hero of the Falcons' overtime
win over the Minnesota Vikings in the NFC title game, missed a
26-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, the Falcons drove to the Broncos' 21 and 26
on their first two possessions, only to have one Chandler pass end
up in the hands of Broncos nickel back Darrius Johnson and another
be tipped by defensive tackle Keith Traylor and intercepted by
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``To try to explain what happened would sound like excuses,''
said Chandler, the former Everett High School and University of
Washington quarterback who was intercepted three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``And to do that to you guys,'' he added of the reporters
crowded around him after the game, ``is not important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta cornerback Ray Buchanan, who had guaranteed a Falcons
victory, was more direct and honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't win a game when you make as many turnovers as we
did,'' he said. ``That's not like us. But that was us today. We
didn't play how we were supposed to, how we're capable of playing
or how we have been playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had become the trendy pick to deny the Broncos and
Elway a second Super Bowl victory after storming through the
regular season 14-2 and upsetting the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   But that was underestimating Elway, and the things he continues
to be able to do.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk the past two seasons about how the Broncos
had become Davis' team, and with good reason. But that was
downright disrespectful to Elway.
</P>
<P>
   He was anticipating being the one who would have to win the
game, and was ready for the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that the whole week with all the talk about the
running games,'' Elway said of his role as difference-maker. ``We
knew we had to stop Jamal Anderson. They knew they had to stop
Terrell. A good defense can stop a good running back if they commit
enough players to doing it. So I knew I was going to have to make
some plays.''
</P>
<P>
   None was bigger than the 80-yard TD pass to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   It came with the Broncos nursing a 10-3 lead. It came on the
next play after Andersen had hooked his 26-yarder wide right. It
came when the Broncos most needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Elway set up the pass with a play-action fake to Davis and
bought Smith time to get open behind Falcons free safety Eugene
Robinson by rolling to his right. Then, Elway was suddenly a kid
again, rifling the ball to Smith, who caught the pass at the
Atlanta 42-yard line and outran Robinson to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd run that play to Terrell before and I saw Eugene bite on
it,'' Elway said. ``So I knew if we could set it up just right, Rod
could get behind him. It turned out to be a pretty big play.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pretty big game, one that could have been the last in
Elway's big-play career.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans in the crowd of 74,803 voiced their opinion on the
subject as Elway trotted off the field by holding up a huge banner
that read _ no, pleaded _ ``John, one more year. Please.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, the babbling Bronco, later seconded that emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old man still has that gift left in him,'' Sharpe said.
``He is going to sit down and talk about what he is going to do,
but we would love to have him back for another year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
