<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6411 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     02-01 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY STEALS GOOD ENDING FROM REEVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Poor Dan Reeves. His renewed health sustains him. His
Super Bowl fate haunts him.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that, after two weeks of scraping open the wounds on
their bitter parting, the Denver Broncos had the final word on
their old coach yesterday in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Two words, to be accurate _ John and Elway.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of Reeves, the recovering heart patient, absorbing a
fourth Super Bowl defeat _ and this time at the hands of his former
team _ smacks of a Greek tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   But John Elway always could steal a good show.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing for 336 yards and engineering as precise a game as any
quarterback in Super Bowl history, Elway again soared to the top of
the football world yesterday. The Broncos' 34-19 dismantling of the
mishap-prone Atlanta Falcons left no doubt of who has been the best
team in pro football for these past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was winning a world championship at the start of the
season,'' Denver coach Mike Shanahan said. ``We had a little
adversity. But we kept our focus.''
</P>
<P>
   His synopsis rang with understatement. The Broncos went a
razor-focused 17-and-2. They won their first 13 games. They scythed
through three playoff foes by a combined 63 points.
</P>
<P>
   Next time that you hear a team, any team, whine about how hard
it is to repeat as a champion, remind them of Elway and the 1998
Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Reeves. Again, like a Greek tragedy, he was done in by a
deadly mix of conspirators.
</P>
<P>
   His quarterback, for one thing. Chris Chandler's first night
under the Super Bowl big top produced a comedy of pratfalls. He
threw three interceptions. On seven of the Falcons' first eight
true possessions, they marched into Denver territory, only to leave
with only two field goals.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a turning point in Chandler's night, it came on
Atlanta's opening drive. The Falcons had whisked 55 yards to the
Denver 8-yard line. But on third down, linebacker Bill Romanowski
blitzed up the middle and crunched Chandler for a 7-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go in there and get seven and it's a real
momentum-builder for them,'' defensive coordinator Greg Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The very-Dirty Birds had to settle for a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   And so the day went. On the grand scale of Super Bowl history,
Chandler likely will be judged as bad as Elway was good.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' defense _ safety Eugene Robinson, in particular _ didn't
help, either.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was arrested Saturday night and charged with trying to
solicit the sexual services of an undercover vice officer. So much
for the Falcons' razor-sharp focus. Robinson was scorched for the
Broncos' second touchdown, an 80-yard Elway bomb to Rod Smith.
</P>
<P>
   On Denver's first 10 possessions, the only ones that really
mattered, the Atlanta defense forced the Broncos to punt only once.
Billed as being tough against the run, the Broncos' redoubtable
Terrell Davis ran and ran. He finished with 102 yards on 25
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Elway and the Broncos even lost the services of Pro Bowl tight
end Shannon Sharpe, who suffered a game-ending knee injury. It
didn't matter. Losing one target, Elway found another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played great,'' Sharpe said of Elway. ``The old man still
has the gift left in him.''
</P>
<P>
   And to think that people doubted. The Falcons' dramatic NFC
title game _ a triumph engineered by Chandler _ had won them
converts. There were bold suggestions, wasting valuable newsprint,
that tried to argue that Atlanta would have the edge for this game
in quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, puh-leese.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Ed McCaffrey, who caught five Elway passes in the
second half, assessed his quarterback's performance as
``unbelievable. I mean, John Elway is the Denver Broncos. He is
Denver. And he proved that today.''
</P>
<P>
   If, as some have suggested, Elway's skills are diminishing, then
maybe it's time for a new standard of skills to be written. OK, he
can't scramble like he used to. But Elway apparently still can see
what's happening in the secondary as well as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that speaks for itself _ him being named most valuable
player,'' Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to go out, what a way to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   What a way, indeed. Elway, however, still juked and stiff-armed
all postgame queries about his NFL future. There are seriously
strong feelings amongst the Broncos that last night was his final
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all hope he stays,'' McCaffrey said, ``and we'll all be
nudging him to stick with it. But the guy has done everything you
can do in football. He is one of the greatest players to ever play
the game, and I am privileged to have played with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Reeves, Elway had been a three-time Super Bowl loser. His
legacy _ and his inevitable Hall of Fame plaque _ will now show
that he has won two in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations to the Denver Broncos. What a great football
team,'' a gracious Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal script, Reeves, the sentimental favorite, would have
been the conquering hero.
</P>
<P>
   But John Elway always could steal a show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
