<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
JUAN Antonio Samaranch, the dirtiest of old birds, should have been
watching the Super Bowl on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he probably was. The Big Game had all the ingredients
that Samaranch's Big Games have thrived upon for decades now.
</P>
<P>
   Rampant commercialism. Lavishness. Star power as far as the eye
can see. Glitter and glamour. And sponsors, sponsors, sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, compared to the Olympic Games empire that surrounds
His Excellency _ which, by the way, Samaranch demands to be called
in International Olympic Committee documents and by underlings _
the Super Bowl is just a quaint little event.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Sunday pickup game compared to Samaranch's prime 16
Days of Glory. It's the nice little appetizer to Samaranch's feast.
</P>
<P>
   But how much more crumbling must the empire endure before it
strikes back, or worse, its sponsors revolt and the empire falls
apart around Samaranch chip by chip?
</P>
<P>
   The latest revelations in the bribes-for-votes scandal that has
rocked the hallowed walls of IOC headquarters in Lausanne,
Switzerland, literally have no borders. What began with disturbing
news that the pristine Salt Lake City corrupted itself and the
Games with bribes for votes now has expanded to include Sydney,
Australia; Nagano, Japan; Seoul, South Korea; and failed bid
attempts in Toronto and Manchester, England.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all these bombshells, Samaranch only has continued to
sit in his richly decorated Swiss bunker and done little more than
harrumph between manicures.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC president has promised investigations but delivered
little. When Dick Pound, the Canadian IOC board member leading the
investigation, told Samaranch of a $1 million offer made by Toronto
organizers hoping to manipulate the vote for the 1988 Games,
Samaranch did not investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when similar charges were made in a book by a British
journalist, Samaranch sued the publisher for libel instead of
investigating in hopes of finding the truth.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of at least 12 corrupt IOC voters becoming entangled
in the scandal, Samaranch has said he believes everything necessary
already has been done. He has refused to look deeper and
investigate more IOC voters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he hired an international public-relations firm and
told it to clean up the Olympic image. Part of the PR plan has been
never to call the cash payments, free housing, scholarships, jobs
and alleged prostitution ``bribes.'' In every document, every news
conference, Samaranch refers to them only as ``benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   When news of a decadent $2 million party by IOC bid cities in
1985 was revealed, Samaranch called such extravagance normal. When
Samaranch was implicated, admitting he has accepted gifts from
numerous bid cities, he claimed he should not be condemned for the
practice since he does not have a vote unless a ballot ends in a
tie.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, he says he is above the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has called for reform in how future bid cities will be
named, but as is the case with the IOC membership itself, Samaranch
plans to personally name the proposed 15-member committee.
</P>
<P>
   How will this change the corruption? How will it keep the
scandal from growing?
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has boasted of personally appointing more than half
the IOC membership, which also re-elects its president _ Samaranch
_ every time his term expires. Thus, every vote of every Games bid
is done by Samaranch's people, who answer to Samaranch and owe him
for their statesman-like lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has fazed Samaranch about this dastardly scandal. His
Excellency has done nothing but prove he would just as well let
critics eat cake.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps those who know the change should begin with
Samaranch have one hope.
</P>
<P>
   Would you like a Coca-Cola with your cake? Would you support the
official soft drink of the tainted Games?
</P>
<P>
   What about Visa? Would you use the official card used to hire
call girls for IOC voters?
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which is headquartered in Atlanta and was long
rumored to be the sole reason the Games landed there in 1996,
recently met with IOC investigators and demanded answers. United
Parcel Service, Xerox and Visa, each of which pays upward of $40
million for a four-year Olympic sponsorship, also have queried.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake Games might fold because there remains a $350
million sponsorship shortfall, and no one is knocking on the SLOC's
door anymore. In Australia, where the 2000 Summer Games will be
held, Caltex, a giant oil and gas sponsor, has pulled its $6.3
million Olympic sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope Samaranch caught a glimpse of the lavishness we
saw on Super Sunday. The sponsors, sponsors, sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   They could be slipping through Samaranch's fingers, and when
they do, only then could Samaranch fade away, too. And the Games
will be glorious again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
