<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CAN ELWAY ABDICATE THRONE? 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ OK, John, you coming back?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even going to talk about that,'' said the Most
Valuable Player in Super Bowl XXXIII. ``Let me enjoy this. I'll
cross that bridge later on.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the answer you'd expect John Elway to give. But we had
to ask. Does he really think life will get any better than this?
His Denver Broncos had just beaten up on the Atlanta Falcons by
much worse than the 34-19 final score would indicate, and he had
waltzed off with the MVP prize. Was this not a Jordanesque
statement?
</P>
<P>
   It was a complete MVP performance from a sure first-ballot Hall
of Fame player. In last year's Super Bowl, Elway was a game
manager. He handed the ball off to Terrell Davis and he tried not
to make any mistakes. This year was an entirely different story. In
order for the Broncos to repeat as World Champions, John Elway had
to be, well, John Elway. His response was to go 18 for 29 for 336
yards and one touchdown. He also scored on a quarterback draw.
There was no question who was going to get the MVP award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta talked all week about stopping the run,'' said Elway.
``They didn't say anything about the passing game. Anybody can stop
the run if they commit to it and want to do it badly enough. So I
was loooking forward to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Make Elway beat us. That would have been an unthinkable concept
in years past, but by the time Super Bowl week had arrived it had
become a given that the Broncos' offense now belonged to league MVP
Terrell Davis, the 2,000-yard man, and that Elway was looking
increasingly mortal. The Broncos thought this was ridiculous. They
didn't say much about this publicly, but inside their closed little
world they were praying the Falcons would adopt that approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to stop Terrell,'' said backup tight end Byron
Chamberlain, ``then we've got a Hall of Fame quarterback, and he's
gonna kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Broncos believed, and that's what happened in
Pro Player Stadium Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   What Elway did was even more impressive than the numbers because
he was forced to play the final three quarters of the game without
one of his primary offensive weapons. Shannon Sharpe, the great
tight end, injured a knee while making a 14-yard catch-and-run in
the first period, and after testing his leg he was gone for the
game. Chamberlain did a tremendous job as his replacement, but no
one on earth is going to suggest that Byron Chamberlain ever could
replace a Shannon Sharpe, even-up.
</P>
<P>
   Elway was also forced to play some stretches without Davis, who
was in and out of the game during the second half. So it was just
like old times, and even older times, with John Elway the focal
point of the Denver offense.
</P>
<P>
   Being the proud guy that all legit superstars are, Elway even
used the occasion to defend his performance of a year ago (12 for
22, 123 yards). ``I wouldn't say I `struggled' last year,'' he said
in reference to one particular question. ``I did what I was asked
to do. We had the running game going, so I stuck with that. This
year they took away the running game _ or partially took away the
running game _ so I'm glad I could keep up my end of the bargain a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   This has got to be an exquisite feeling for Elway. He gave
serious thought last year to retiring after bagging his first
championship, and it would have been a dramatic statement had he
done so. There were, in fact, serious questions being raised about
his reliability. Many people thought he would be getting out just
ahead of the posse. To be standing in front of the assembled media,
many of whom had written at length about him being the second-best
quarterback in this game, had to be a powerful feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I came back,'' he said. ``This is why I put in all
the work.''
</P>
<P>
   And work he does. Elway's biggest fans are inside that Denver
locker room. Asked last week what athletes he admires, Denver
offensive guard Mark Schlereth, he of the 22 surgical procedures
(with No. 23 scheduled for next week), said, ``I like the stars who
don't act like prima donnas when they have earned the right to be,
guys like John Elway. He earned the right long ago to skip drills
and get out of practices, and he never does.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was John's last game,'' said coach Mike
Shanahan, ``but if it is, what a way to go out. But I can tell you
there are a lot of guys in that locker room trying to talk him into
trying for a three-peat.''
</P>
<P>
   A guy like Elway is fueled by the competition and by challenges
of every description. He knows very well that no quarterback in NFL
history has won three championships in a row.
</P>
<P>
   He'd certainly have a decent chance. Shanahan isn't going
anywhere. Davis isn't going anywhere. Sharpe isn't going anywhere.
Ed McCaffrey (five catches, 72 yards) isn't going anywhere.
Hard-hitting Bill Romanowski isn't going anywhere. It doesn't seem
to matter much who's on the offensive line, because it looks as if
the wily Alex Gibbs can fashion a unit out of anything you give
him. The core of talent will remain, and we now know that the
Broncos know how to deal with all the peripheral stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Elway is well aware he can't do all the things he used to do,
but his body is in good shape and he still has a lot of weapons at
his disposal. Bet that he'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   I'd even go so far as to say that he would consider quitting to
be a betrayal of sorts. Remember that he couldn't win one for 14
years, and that some of his most aggravating moments had come in
Super Bowls. He's going to quit now when he's found the winning
formula? That's not how guys like him usually think.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a romantic. I like the idea of John Elway quitting on top. I
would wager that Mike Shanahan has a different viewpoint. And I
think he'll be again be greeting No. 7 on the first day of training
camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
