<HEADER>
A6416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-BOS &LR;      02-01 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY, BRONCOS REPEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ John Elway didn't just go out on top. He went over the
top.
</P>
<P>
   In what may well be his last game, Elway had his greatest Super
Bowl moment Sunday night at Pro Player Stadium, passing for 336
yards and a touchdown, running for another score, and leading his
Denver Broncos to their second straight Super Bowl victory. He was
named the game's Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' 34-19 win ended the Atlanta Falcons' Cinderella
season with an avalanche of pass completions and two long nights of
bad news.
</P>
<P>
   The first had come at 9 p.m. Saturday night when safety Eugene
Robinson was arrested and charged with soliciting an undercover
police officer for oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Barely 24 hours later, Elway was destroying the rest of the
Falcons' week in Miami with a performance fit for a king, which is
what he was.
</P>
<P>
   After he dove over from 2 yards out to score Denver's final
touchdown, Elway jogged off the field holding the ball over his
head. As he came to the sideline, Elway high-fived everyone he
passed on his way to the bench, a conquering hero home from what
may have been his last battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll remember that walk for the rest of my life,'' Elway said,
and surely he will, because if this was his last battle, it was a
marvelously designed one from the opening drive until Elway fell
into the end zone with the Broncos' final touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't mention anything about our passing game all
week,'' Elway said. ``I didn't take that personally because if they
don't stop Terrell Davis, he'd get 300 yards. But we went in
knowing we were going to have the opportunity to throw and if we
were going to win we would have to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway did that from the outset, but it was the Falcons who
started off with a bang, taking the opening kickoff 31 yards to the
37-yard line, and gashing the Denver defensive front with Jamal
Anderson, who had a 13-yard gain on the first play from scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson (96 yards on 18 carries) continued to pound down the
Broncos, but the Falcons' drive stalled on the Denver 8 when Bill
Romanowski sacked Chris Chandler for a 7-yard loss on third down.
The Falcons settled for a 32-yard Morten Andersen field goal,
giving them their only lead of the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos wasted no time answering that challenge, marching 80
yards while running an assortment of odd formations that seemed to
unsettle the Falcon defense.
</P>
<P>
   Denver lined up Davis wide on the opening play, with no running
back in the backfield, and went into a shotgun on second down. But
it was a play on third and 7 at the Denver 35 that set the tone for
the half. Wide receiver Rod Smith started out in the backfield and
then went into motion. After he turned upfield, he was wide open
and Elway found him for a 41-yard completion to the Atlanta 24.
</P>
<P>
   Three Davis runs and a 14-yard Elway-to-Shannon Sharpe
completion put the ball on the 1, and fullback Howard Griffith then
had his number called for only the fifth time this season. He used
the opportunity as well as you could, scoring the game's first
touchdown to give the Broncos the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The pace slowed briefly after that until Ronnie Bradford picked
off an Elway pass that bounced off the hands of Sharpe at the
Denver 36 and gave the Falcons another chance to attack.
</P>
<P>
   Attack they did, but on fourth and 1 at the Broncos 27, Atlanta
ran a toss right to Anderson and Denver's defense ran him down for
a 2-yard loss that gave the Broncos the ball and the momentum. They
marched 63 yards on 11 plays before settling for a 25-yard field
goal by Jason Elam that made it 10-3 with 9:17 to play in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons might have survived that, but they were again unable
to score a touchdown after penetrating the Denver 10 for the second
time. This time Chandler put too much on a pass to a wide open Tim
Dwight in the end zone on third down, and the ball sailed high and
wild over the receiver's head.
</P>
<P>
   After Andersen missed what is normally a chip shot, 26-yard
field goal attempt, Elway then drove a stake through the heart of
the Falcons and, in particular, poor, bedeviled Robinson. The
quarterback sent Smith on a deep in pattern against an Atlanta
zone, and Smith ran right by the safety, who had the deep coverage.
</P>
<P>
   As Smith sprinted downfield, Elway delivered a perfectly thrown
ball over his shoulder behind Robinson, and the receiver loped for
an 80-yard touchdown that made the score 17-3 with 4:54 to play in
the half.
</P>
<P>
   Only 22 hours earlier, Robinson had been arrested in downtown
Miami, a development that came hours after a tearful Robinson had
been presented the Bart Starr Award for community service and high
moral character.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the scrappy Falcons refused to wilt easily. They came right
back when Dwight returned the kickoff 42 yards to the 49, but once
again a good opportunity did not produce what Atlanta needed, as
the Falcons reached the 11 but could not score a touchdown. They
settled for Andersen's 28-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Although that reduced Denver's lead to 11 with 2:25 to play in
the half, the Falcons' inability to turn productive drives into
touchdowns was hurting them, and that, combined with the fact that
Elway was playing the best he ever had in a Super Bowl, was proving
lethal for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Elway was 9 of 15 for 199 yards and a score, which
was nearly twice his passing yardage in each of his last two Super
Bowl appearances, a hint that he was on the verge of coming through
on his hope of finishing what was expected to be his final game
with ``my greatest performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it was becoming his greatest Super Bowl performance.
After halftime, he twice took the Broncos into field goal territory
in the third quarter, only to have Elam miss both kicks. But Elway
remained unfazed, in part because Denver's defense responded by
twice intercepting Chandler throws to blunt Atlanta's efforts to
get back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The second pickoff proved most costly, because the Falcons had
moved to the Broncos 21 before Keith Traylor tipped a Chandler pass
intended for tight end O.J. Santiago and the ball was picked off by
cornerback Darrien Gordon and returned 58 yards to the Falcons 24
with time running out in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At this point it was still 17-6, but the Broncos had dominated
the quarter on both offense and defense. That superiority finally
overwhelmed the Falcons when Elway hit another critical pass, a
15-yard completion to McCaffrey on third and 6 at the 20 to set up
Griffith's second 1-yard touchdown run, this one at 14:56 of the
fourth quarter. That made it 24-6 and made clear whose night this
would be.
</P>
<P>
   If doubters remained, however, Chandler soon convinced them by
throwing his third straight interception, again to Gordon. On this
one, Gordon cut in front of Tony Martin at the Denver 4-yard line,
grabbed the pass on a full run, and sprinted 50 yards to the
Falcons 48.
</P>
<P>
   One 39-yard completion later and Elway had the Dirty Birds all
but plucked, a process he finished off himself when he burrowed in
on a 3-yard quarterback draw to make it 31-6 with a little over 11
minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, Dwight finally did what he'd been threatening all
night, breaking a kickoff for a 94-yard touchdown that allowed the
Falcons to avoid being the first team since Super Bowl VI not to
score a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   That score was a moral victory for the Falcons. After Robinson's
problems from the night before, they could use it. They just
couldn't use it to beat John Elway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
