<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-GAMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSUNG DENVER DEFENSE GROUNDS `DIRTY BIRDS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The ``Dirty Birds'' have been de-flocked by a bunch of
nobodies.
</P>
<P>
   Those overlooked, underpublicized no-names on the Denver
Broncos' defense held the Atlanta Falcons without an offensive
touchdown until the final three minutes in winning Super Bowl
XXXIII, 34-19, on Sunday before 74,803 fans at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a lot about them running against us, a lot about them
doing the ``Dirty Bird'' (touchdown dance), but in the end, only
the score matters,'' Broncos defensive tackle Keith Traylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback John Elway, likely retiring after his 16th season,
was picked as the game's Most Valuable Player after throwing for
336 yards, the third most in Super Bowl history. All-Pro running
back Terrell Davis rushed for a game-high 102 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But the Broncos wouldn't have won their second consecutive Super
Bowl without a defense that forced four turnovers, including
intercepting Atlanta quarterback Chris Chandler three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what our defense did in the playoffs,'' said
cornerback Darrien Gordon, who set a Super Bowl record with 108
yards on two interception returns. ``Miami, we blew them out. The
Jets, we shut them down. There was the same outcry about our
secondary (being weak), but we gave up only six points in two
games. When are people going to realize, our defense can play?''
</P>
<P>
   Until the Falcons' scored a garbage touchdown with 2:04 left,
the only touchdown the Broncos' defense had given up came on a
1-yard run by the New York Jets after the Jets recovered a blocked
punt on Denver's 1-yard line in the AFC title game.
</P>
<P>
   Six times, the Falcons reached inside Denver's 30-yard line in
the first three quarters, and they scored only six points.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the question is whether the Broncos can become the first
team in NFL history to win three straight Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``A three-peat definitely would put us in dynasty status,''
Gordon said of the Broncos, who have won an NFL-record 46 games the
past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' chances of winning a third Super Bowl in a row
could depend on whether Elway returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That chance goes to 95 percent, 98 (percent) with John coming
back, but we can do it without him,'' tight end Shannon Sharpe
said. ``I'm thinking of that already. I'm thinking about being in
Atlanta in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway wouldn't discuss after the game his chances of returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to cross that bridge,'' Elway said. ``This is
what I came back for and was working months for. Nothing feels
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was billed as ``The Feud,'' with Elway and Broncos
Coach Mike Shanahan going against their old boss, Falcons Coach Dan
Reeves. It was no contest.
</P>
<P>
   Denver jumped to a 31-6 lead against Reeves, who now has lost
four Super Bowls by a combined total of 178-59.
</P>
<P>
   Any chance the Falcons had ended in third quarter although
Denver's Jason Elam missed two field goals with the Broncos
leading, 17-6.
</P>
<P>
   After Elam's first miss, Chandler was intercepted by backup
cornerback Darrius Johnson at the Broncos' 30.
</P>
<P>
   Elam missed from 48 yards with 3:49 left in the third quarter,
but a Falcons turnover stopped another drive.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's pass was tipped by defensive tackle Keith Traylor at
the line of scrimmage and intercepted by Gordon at the Broncos' 18.
He returned it 58 yards to the Atlanta 24 to set up the second of
fullback Howard Griffith's two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in my face all day,'' Chandler said. ``They did a
good job up front of compressing the pocket. A lot of times guys
were just throwing their hands up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos frustrated Chandler from the outset. He drove them
to Denver's 7 on the first drive. But Broncos linebacker Bill
Romanowski blitzed and Chandler was sacked for a 7-yard loss on
third down, and the Falcons were forced to settle for a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their quarterback had a little bit of a history of getting
hurt and rattled,'' Romanowski said of Chandler, the ex-Cardinal
who was sacked twice. ``We felt we could get some hits on him and
that could shake him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver then went 80-yard in 10 plays to take a 7-3 lead, a
41-yard pass from Elway to wide receiver Rod Smith setting up
Griffith's 1-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos had extended the lead to 10-3 when Atlanta's Morten
Andersen missed a 26-yard field goal with 5:07 left in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, Elway threw deep to Smith, who beat free
safety Eugene Robinson for an 80-yard score and a 17-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In last year's Super Bowl, our running game was really
working,'' said Broncos wide receiver Ed McCaffrey of Davis' 157
yards in the victory over the Green Bay Packers. ``There was no
need to put the ball in the air. We took advantage of what was
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, they shut down our running games at times. So, we took
advantage of what was working. We threw the ball.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
