</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER'S LINE SCORE WAS BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Broncos quarterback John Elway could have played
Sunday's game in a tuxedo and not have had to send it out to be
cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver offensive line was that good. For two years in a row,
it has been the silent force behind Super Bowl victories.
</P>
<P>
   Elway got deserved kudos for his best Super Bowl performance.
But he was barely touched as his offensive line completely shackled
what had been an excellent Atlanta front four against all other
opponents this season, including the Minnesota Vikings in the NFC
Championship games.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought Minnesota, which set a scoring record in the league
this season, had the best offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Denver reaffirmed Sunday beyond a doubt that its is the best,
illustrated by its taking control of a Super Bowl again.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, this bunch dominated the Packers in the second half,
setting Terrell Davis up for the Most Valuable Player trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night in Pro Player Stadium, the Broncos line walled off
a quick, athletic gang of Atlanta tacklers and allowed Elway to get
through the game virtually unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a virtuoso performance. Not once in the game was Denver
flagged for a false start. And just once were the Broncos called
for holding, and it was a good penalty. One of the Atlanta rushers
had broken loose up the middle just before the end of the first
half, and he was hauled down and prevented from getting a clean
shot at Elway.
</P>
<P>
   With this kind of protection, Denver dominated the game with its
passing. The Falcons moved the ball but could not finish. Three
times, with the game up for grabs in the first half, they moved
inside the Denver 20, but they got only two field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's coaches were concerned before the game that Denver's
plan would be to spread them out on defense. When they last met a
year ago in Atlanta, Denver scored the first three times it touched
the ball by using four wide receivers and forcing Atlanta, which
likes to play zone defense, to cover man-to-man.
</P>
<P>
   The first two times they touched the ball Sunday night, Denver
went with all receivers and no one at the running back position.
That seemed to end any thoughts the Falcons had of blitzing Elway,
and without any pressure on him, Elway was able to function at his
best.
</P>
<P>
   Denver even complemented this part of its attack by having Elway
roll out of the pocket to the right to get a better look at his
receivers. In the AFC Championship game, the Jets rushers had
tipped and deflected a half-dozen passes on him.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Smith, the fastest of the Broncos receivers, got the
man-to-man coverage his coaches hoped he would. They kept Smith
away from Ray Buchanan, the best of the Atlanta cover men, and he
feasted on the rest.
</P>
<P>
   When it was still a game, he beat the slower Eugene Robinson
deep down the middle for an 80-yard touch-down, with Elway rolling
out of the pocket and getting a clear view.
</P>
<P>
   It is the popular belief that Elway can throw the ball with the
velocity of old only when he can step up in the pocket, or with no
one in front of him, to get all of his body into the throw.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets packed their defense into the middle of the field two
weeks ago, trying to force Elway to throw to the outside, where the
tosses must be longer. But Atlanta's middle was wide open all day,
and so were Elway's chances, and his receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons played like a team in its first Super Bowl. They
missed a bunch of tackles. Quarterback Chris Chandler was clearly
flustered. He had receivers open all night, and either threw the
ball poorly or didn't see the open man.
</P>
<P>
   He threw three interceptions in the second half on consecutive
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The wacky thing about Atlanta's offensive game was that the
Falcons played great on first down, ripping off big yardage, yet
never could make the big play after that.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson did a great job, but the Atlanta
passing game, which had been the best in the league this year with
a gaudy 15.8-yards-per-completion average, disintegrated.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams ran the ball well, but only one threw it well.
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos blitzed more than usual to pressure Chandler and
force him into bad throws. A few times he should have thrown the
ball away or simply taken the sack, rather than throwing it into a
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons seemed to get a big break early in the game when
Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe left with a twisted knee. The
Falcons thought he was the player they would have the most trouble
trying to cover. They were wrong. No one could handle Rod Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos defense gave up yardage but not points. Atlanta
didn't score a touchdown until the fourth period, when Tim Dwight
ran a kickoff back.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has established itself as the best team in football. And
``team'' is the appropriate word. The Broncos do things well as a
team, from the execution of their offensive line to their multiple
defensive schemes.
</P>
<P>
   They started out the season wanting to be perfect and couldn't
get over the top on that score. But they ended the season
unquestionably the best in the game, and they have a long time to
be happy with that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
