<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SAME SAD SONG FOR FALCONS' REEVES 
</HEADLINE>
 BOWL-FALCONS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The shadow of Eugene Robinson that hung over the Atlanta
Falcons and Sunday night's Super Bowl was so thick that it seemed
almost imposible to see the game. So much so that Atlanta coach Dan
Reeves felt Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler ``had played well
for his first Super Bowl'' and Chandler himself agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Chandler time and again turned his mind and his words
to a tipped pass in the third quarter that was intercepted by
cornerback Darrien Gordon at the Denver 18-yard line, when the
Falcons were trailing, 17-6, and threatening to tighten the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like I'd been throwing all day, Terance Mathis was
running a corner route on that play,'' said Chandler of the play
that dashed Atlanta's hopes. ``Their corners really sink way inside
and all I had to do was throw the ball over (Gordon's) head to the
corner. But their guy tipped it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was simply bad luck that defensive lineman Keith
Traylor barely was able to get the the tip of his middle finger on
Chandler's pass, allowing Gordon to make the easiest of
interceptions. But it was not bad luck that saw Atlanta four times
reach the Denver 21-yard line or better and come away with only two
field goals. A fifth time Atlanta reached the Denver 26 and came up
with nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to guess what would have happened if we hadn't had
the ball tipped,'' Chandler said in one variation of the theme he
returned to several times. ``That would have been a good chance for
us to score a touchdown and get back into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl quarterbacks are total failures when their team five
times delves so deep into enemy territory and comes away with a
measly 6 points. Once, in the first half, Chandler had Tony Martin
open in right corner of the end zone but he floated _ rather than
zipped _ the pass and it was broken up.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, receiver Tim Dwight was all alone in the end zone,
but Chandler overthrew him. Still another time, Chandler threw a
fade pass toward Martin in the left corner of the end zone and
Gordon made a superb play to break it up. And then there was the
pass to Martin near the goal line early in the fourth quarter that
also was picked off by Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Broncos leave the middle of the field open a lot,'' said
Chandler of that misread between him and Martin. ``We had talked a
lot during the week about it. It's like we're trying to flatten out
the post route and make it an in route. And Tony felt at the last
second he could go on top of the route and we were just thinking
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chandler's mind, though, it was that tipped pass, ``because
if Terance doesn't score there on the pass, it's going to be
awfully close to a score. Then, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was crushed that his offense had so few points to show
for so many scoring opportunities for his offense. ``The whole
thing boiled down to their stopping us in the red zone,'' said
Reeves. ``We had been so good down there all year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't make the plays when we needed to make them,'' said
Reeves, words that apply to any team that loses a Super Bowl. ``In
the second half, we had two plays where we felt we could get back
into the game, and two times we felt we were open, and we get one
of them tipped for an interception and then we throw an
interception on the other one.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was a crusher for Reeves, his fourth in a Super Bowl.
The final salt in the wound was his postgame meeting with Broncos
coach Mike Shanahan, when he had to congratulate his nemesis. In
1992, Reeves fired Shanahan, then his assistant in Denver, for
insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Mike after the game and congratulated him on a
great win and and also on his record,'' Reeves said, referring to
Denver's 17-2 mark. ``When you win the most football games of
everybody, that tells you you've done a tremendous job as a
coach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
