<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6423 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-ROBINSON-     02-01 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ROBINSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UPSTANDING REPUTATION IS TRIPPED UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN AND WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Forty-five minutes after Sunday night's Super Bowl,
safety Eugene Robinson finally emerged from the Atlanta Falcons
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who Saturday night was arrested in Miami and charged
with soliciting sex from an undercover police officer, read from a
script, saying, ``My lawyer has advised me not to discuss about my
arrest. That will be handled in due time by authorities. And I
feel, I strongly feel, I will be found innocent. But what I really
want to do now is to apologize to my Lord Jesus Christ, and
secondly to my wife (Gia) and kids, and thirdly to my teammates and
to the entire NFL and the (Atlanta) organization for any
distractions I may have caused.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret I was not maintaining the standards I had set for
myself,'' Robinson continued, ``and I will continue to try to make
amends to everyone who knows me. I want to thank a lot of the
football people, and this includes a lot of the fans, and a lot of
the players, and especially my family for praying for me at this
very low point.''
</P>
<P>
   This indeed, is a low point for Robinson, who Saturday morning
was honored for high moral character, presented the Bart Starr
Award as his family looked on with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night came the arrest, and Sunday night Robinson was
burned by Rod Smith on a second-quarter fly pattern for an 80-yard
Denver touchdown as the Broncos won, 34-19.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Calzadilla, a spokesman for the Miami police, said
Robinson offered $40 to an undercover policewoman for oral sex.
After his arrest, he was released to the custody of Atlanta general
manager Harold Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   In his biography in the Falcons press guide, Robinson is quoted
as saying, ``I tell people I'm a Christian who just happens to play
football.'' That's part of the reason Athletes in Action, renowned
in professional sports for its commitment to Christianity, chose
Robinson for the Starr Award, named after the great Packers
quarterback who was the Most Valuable Player in Green Bay's
victories in the first two Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   After his opening statements following Sunday night's Atlanta
loss, Robinson deviated from the script and said, ``I really got no
sleep (Saturday) night ... But when it came to the game, I was
really focused on the game ... I'm kind of ad-libbing on my script
here, but I don't really think we played well enough to win the
game. So I've got to take my hat off to the Denver Broncos.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said when he returned to the hotel, tears flowed, and
he spent hours on his knees asking God's forgiveness. ``Once again,
and I want to reiterate, I really believe and I strongly believe I
will be found innocent of this deal. However, I was not righteous
in this deal.''
</P>
<P>
   As to comments on the game, Robinson tried to explain the Smith
play as ``a mixup in communication in the secondary.'' But then he
said, ``I was trying to do a little too much out there. I was a
little too zealous out there ... That long pass really will haunt
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver coach Dan Reeves said Robinson's arrest wasn't a
distraction, but wide receiver Tony Martin summed up the feelings
of his teammates, Atlanta's fans, and much of football. ``I was
shocked that it was Eugene,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves chose to focus on the effect of the arrest on Robinson,
the man. ``I don't know anybody who hasn't made mistakes in their
lives,'' he said. ``We love Eugene unconditionally. That's the
thing we based everything on. Nobody is more embarrassed about this
than Eugene, but I'm not going to crucify him.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Atlanta sources, when Robinson returned to the
hotel after being released by police, his first stop was the room
of Reeves, where Robinson explained to the coach what happened.
After that conversation, Robinson then went to the rooms of several
veterans and told them of the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, most teams have moved out of the hotel
they had been in all week the night before the game and gone to a
smaller hotel closer to the stadium. There, the players were
virtually locked up until they took the team bus to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves not only kept his team in the same hotel, but he also
didn't hold meetings Saturday night, and reportedly did not have a
curfew.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was not with his family Saturday night. Police say he
was driving a car along Biscayne Boulevard, where prostitutes are
known to ply their trade, when he engaged the undercover agent in
conversation and reportedly propositioned her. The scene of the
arrest is just a couple of miles away from the Atlanta team hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years ago, almost to the hour, the life of the Bengals'
Stanley Wilson blew up, and it has been spiraling downward ever
since. On that Super Bowl eve in the same city, Wilson,
Cincinnati's starting fullback, did a large amount of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   When he did not show up for a team meeting, Bengals security was
sent to his room. They could hear Wilson inside, but he would not
open the door. Hotel security was summoned, forced the door open,
and went in. They found Wilson cowering in the bathroom, nearly
incoherent.
</P>
<P>
   A decision was made to remove Wilson from the team hotel and
take him back to the hotel where the Bengals had stayed earlier in
the week. Wilson was put in the custody of a Cincinnati police
officer who regularly traveled with the team for security purposes.
However, early Sunday morning, Wilson escaped and disappeared onto
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's team lost a last-minute heartbreaker to Joe Montana and
the San Francisco 49ers, 20-16, and many believe his absence
affected the Bengals' performance. He never played another game,
and in the years since, he has been arrested three times, most
recently for armed robbery. He goes to trial soon in California and
faces a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson had built a sterling reputation in the NFL. He has been
a Pro Bowl player, spending most of his career in Seattle, before
moving on to Green Bay and then Atlanta via free agency. In
Seattle, he was a four-time Man of the Year for his work wih the
Boys and Girls Clubs and Union Gospel Mission. In Green Bay, for
which he played in the Super Bowl last year, he worked to raise
money to fight cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, he has more interceptions than any other active
player. He has been a calming force for the young Falcon defense,
the player who makes most of the adjustments during the game.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's wife, his 11-year-old daughter, Brittany, and his
9-year-old son, Brandon, were at the team hotel when Robinson was
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's father, Samuel, was waiting with other members of the
family when Eugene was released. ``The children asked questions.
They have feelings,'' Samuel Robinson told the Associated Press.
``My son talked to both kids, and that's a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Robinson said he was ``very concerned'' for his
daughter-in-law. ``She's doing better  &UR; today &LR; ,'' he said. ``She had
to compose herself.''
</P>
<P>
   All week long Robinson, a Hartford native, had been telling his
younger teammates what not to do during Super Bowl week. He had
been telling them that one reason the Patriots had lost to his
Packers in the Super Bowl two years ago was ``because the Patriots
were out on the streets'' of New Orleans. All week long he had been
preaching that he had found the straight and narrow path because of
God.
</P>
<P>
   When asked during the week what consumes most of his
away-from-the-field time during Super Bowl week, he said,
``Probably your family. You have to put a limit of how much you
allow your family to intrude. You can't be worried about relatives
who need hotel rooms or tickets or anything like that. My wife is
great at insulating me from the rest of my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Reeves said the incident didn't distract the Falcons,
they all were aware of the matter beforehand. ``Anybody but
Eugene,'' Atlanta linebacker Henri Crockett told ESPN after news of
the arrest initially spread. ``He knows the do's and don'ts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ramifications of this are far-reaching,'' said Robinson
after the game, ``and you have no idea of the gravity of the
situation and how it's going to reach people and how it's going to
affect people. A good friend of mine said, `Confession is good for
the soul but bad for the reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Reputation I can deal with, but my wife ... that means so much
more. And I'm sorry I had to drag her through that episode, and I'm
sorry it even happened. It goes far beyond football ... my wife has
been so stellar. I don't want to minimize her pain and I'm deeply,
deeply sorry for what I did to her.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not condemn those who describe him ``as a
hypocritical Christian,'' and then cut off the questions.
</P>
<P>
   But they may not go away for quite a while.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
