<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6425 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-01 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SENSE OF SATISFACTION FROM SUPER BOWL SOAP OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Three-Penny Opera of Super Bowl XXXIII is over. The
Not-So-Three Amigos will go off into the sunset now.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway to The Decision. Mike Shanahan to next season's
killer game plans. Dan Reeves to a healing heart and an Atlanta
football team that is appropriately satisfied for its terrific
season, even if the Falcons found out Sunday that their quarterback
is nothing close to a Hall of Famer and their coach did not show
the Denver Broncos anything they could not handle.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage, Mike and John.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to opera, however, or soap opera, as the saga of
Dan, John and Mike has seemed this Super Bowl season, there was so
much left unsaid, so much left unresolved. It makes you feel a
little empty.
</P>
<P>
   As Bronco tight end Shannon Sharpe told us so succinctly in the
hyper-mouthed days leading up to Sunday's 34-19 Denver victory:
``John hates Dan. Dan hates Mike. Mike and John are best friends.
Enough said.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the story line of this Super Bowl in the south Florida.
A little steamy. A little seedy. And, like so many other human
dramas, one without a neat bow to tie it all up and send us off
feeling completely satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, Super Bowls imitate life.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, as Super Bowl MVP Elway was standing on the podium
addressing the media about everything except his future plans _
he'll cross that bridge when he comes to it _ his old coach
suddenly appeared from behind the curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves had come by to tell his old quarterback
``Congratulations.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the most awkward moments in sports, at least since
earlier in January when Chicago Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf handed
Michael Jordan his championship ring and the two barely made eye
contact.
</P>
<P>
   There was no love lost between Reeves and Elway. And no love
gained this week either. Reeves looked awkward doing what he felt
was right. He looked like he was in pain.
</P>
<P>
   For all the glory that will be heaped upon Elway for such a
stellar Super Bowl performance _ when Elway rolled out and threw
18-yard darts, when he bulled over the goal line for an ecstatic,
exclamatory quarterback draw, when he connected on a 80-yard
touchdown pass to Rod Smith like he was 28 years old instead of a
grizzled 38 _ there was a little sadness connected to his heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Elway still believes that Reeves has cost him dearly. Elway's
career will always be defined by ``what if'' the Broncos had won
any or all of those first three Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   While Elway says it is water under the bridge, he and his family
have certainly been candid in suggesting his career was severely
hampered by Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the best quarterback that ever played,'' Jack
Elway said about his son Sunday, after the younger Elway had reeled
off 336 passing yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yes, I think he is better than (Joe) Montana. There is the
possibility that John could have two more (Super Bowl victories.)
But John is perceptive. He thinks Mike is the most complete
football coach in the game. Mike knows the value of being
organized. He knows the value of personnel. He's a good listener.''
</P>
<P>
   A Super Bowl is surely bigger than any one person. It wasn't
Reeves vs. Elway and Shanahan, but even Elway's wife, Janet, spoke
this week about the different sort of career totals her husband
might have if things had been different.
</P>
<P>
   It is a strange way to wrap up a career, if this is it for
Elway.
</P>
<P>
   It was an awful weird twist of fate that in the very last game
of what has become one of the most compelling and (finally)
triumphant careers, Elway faced his old coach and came up big, as
if to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said all along that if they can stop Terrell Davis, they
would take their chance on being beat by John Elway,'' said Sharpe,
who got to watch the Elway MVP show from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you don't get to be the all-time best passing
quarterback by being so-so. What better way for him to showcase
that he is the best quarterback to ever play the game. Can the guy
still play? Yes. Can the guy play next year and the year after
that? Probably,'' Sharpe said.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's decision will come, although Sharpe joked that just like
after last Super Bowl he was going to find out Elway's decision
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, meanwhile, will go back to work with the Falcons, first
to prove that they were no Cinderellas this season, then to go
about the task of, maybe, finally, winning a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course this is disappointing, although we've come an
awfully long way to be a team in the Super Bowl,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you get here, the more they hurt. But it's like the
guy said in `Chariots of Fire.' `I'm not going to run if I can't
win,' to which the other guy said `You can't win if you don't run.'
This whole society is built on winning, but I'm just going to
congratulate the winner and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   If Super Bowl XXXIII taught us anything, it's that what happened
in the past will affect what you do today. Why do you think Elway
was pumping his fists? Why do you think after that 3-yard
quarterback draw for a touchdown, he ran off the field with the
ball?
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6426 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-ELWAY-HNS &LR;      02-01 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-ELWAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Going into the Super Bowl last year, John Elway's
spectacular career had included everything but a Super Bowl
champion's ring.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He got that ring.
</P>
<P>
   All that would beat that this year would be a ring and the Most
Valuable Player trophy.
</P>
<P>
   He will take home both.
</P>
<P>
   For Elway, the 38-year-old Denver Broncos quarterback who bucked
retirement for another NFL season, Sunday was the pinnacle. It just
doesn't get any better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to death to be a part of this team and thrilled
to death that I could help us win,'' Elway said after the Broncos'
34-19 win over the Atlanta Falcons. ``This is what we play for. To
be able to do it two years in a row is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   For at least one day, Elway refused to discuss his retirement.
It has been assumed the perennial Pro Bowler would retire at the
end of this season. But now, the incentive grows. No quarterback
has ever won three consecutive Super Bowls. But Elway won't say if
that's one more record he's putting on his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even going to talk about it,'' he said. ``I'm just
going to enjoy this win. I'm thrilled to death with this win, and I
will cross that bridge later on. I don't want to talk about
retirement right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He might no longer be in his prime, but even on the downside of
his career, Elway is better than most. Sunday, he didn't look like
he had lost a thing as he completed 18 of 29 passes for 336 yards
and one touchdown. A spectacular 80-yarder to Rod Smith was vintage
Elway, and the one fans will remember if this proves to have been
his last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Elway's still got it going on,'' Atlanta cornerback Ray
Buchanan said. ``Don't let anybody tell you to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   With 2,000-yard rusher Terrell Davis, Elway has had less
pressure over the past couple of seasons. And though Davis rushed
for 102 yards on 25 carries Sunday, Elway stole the show. Besides
the 80-yarder to Smith, Elway completed a 39-yarder to Davis and a
25-yarder to Ed McCaffrey. He spread the ball among six Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Elway said he was confident in the Broncos' passing game during
the week leading up to the game. ``The talk was about our running
game the whole week,'' he said, ``and they didn't mention anything
about the passing game. I really went into this game knowing that
we would have an opportunity to throw the football and that if we
were to win the game, it would probably be through the air because
they are a good run-defense team.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Elway, his teammates are certain they wouldn't have two
Super Bowl title rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did (play his last game), he sure is going out in
style,'' McCaffrey said. ``He is by far the best quarterback in the
game and probably of all time. I am extremely fortunate to have had
the opportunity to play for him and win two Super Bowls with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Denver coach Mike Shanahan: ``I have been around John for
at least 15 years, and I have the utmost respect for him and how he
handles himself, how he works, how he perseveres. He has kept on
working to possibly end his career with two Super Bowls. It speaks
for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   He has played 16 seasons, but if Elway walks away, it will be
because his mind is ready, not his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty great right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had a legacy long before winning his first Super Bowl. If he
leaves the game, he leaves having accomplished all he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' Elway said. ``It's something that I had
never done before, and winning the (MVP) award definitely hit my
heart. It definitely hit my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has hit so many others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0124EST &QL; 
