<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6427 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN--SUPERROBERTSON-H     02-01 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN--SUPER </SLUG>
 ROBERTSON-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ John Elway was very good. Eugene Robinson was very bad. And
therein, plain and simple, lay the difference in Super Bowl XXXIII.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hero. Goat. Star. Stupe. Leader. Loser.
</P>
<P>
   A real dirty bird, that Eugene.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson accounted for the XXX, Elway the III, as in !!!. If
ever two men represented the extreme opposite ends of the Super
Bowl experience, it would be Denver's fabled, fairy-tale-scripting
quarterback and Atlanta's suddenly infamous free (on his own
recognizance) safety.
</P>
<P>
   The former deftly directed his team to another NFL championship
Sunday _ 34-19 _ in what figures to be the final game of a most
prolific, almost perfect 16-season career. This after the latter
dragged his team down, down, down, both making a fool of himself
and likely thwarting any chance the 7{-point-underdog Falcons had
of steeling themselves sufficiently to stage an upset.
</P>
<P>
   All total, the Falcons' frog-to-prince-to-frog quarterback,
Chris Chandler, had a far worse 60 minutes of football, throwing
three second-half interceptions and making a mockery of his status
as the the NFL's top-rated red-zone producer during the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson definitely had the more miserable, and
debilitating, 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Having earned a champion's ring as a Packer two seasons ago,
Eugene was supposed to be Atlanta's chief mentor and motivator, the
wizened old pro who could set the more impressionable Falcons on
his knee and show them how to handle the pressures of the zaniest,
most draining week in sports. They hadn't been here before, you
know. Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   For the Falcons to have a chance, they needed for every little
detail to break perfectly for them. The most minor of distractions
figured to send them reeling helplessly off track, and there was
nothing minor about the arrest of the brightest, most articulate
and most senior member of the defense for soliciting the favors of
a streetwalker.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day he had received the Bart Starr Award for
selfless community service _ and, honest to goodness, his high
moral fiber _ he sneaked away from his family and the Falcons'
compound after dark, driving to a seedy drug- and
prostitute-infested stretch of Biscayne Boulevard near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   There, he allegedly offered a woman $40 for oral sex. She
happened to be a Miami cop working undercover. You are tempted to
ask what he could have been thinking, but the question is moot. He
clearly wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson should feel like the second-dumbest man in America
today. Were it not for the ongoing Washington circus, he would be
alone at the top.
</P>
<P>
   His inexplicable, practically unfathomable decision to slip away
from his family and wind up in the wrong place at the wrong time on
the eve of the most important day in his long-troubled franchise's
history takes a permanent place in Super Bowl history _ but not one
the NFL's mighty PR machine will be inclined to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson called his arrest ``a misunderstanding'' and suggested
that he will be exonerated. But he also felt the need to apologize
_ in the following order _ to ``my Lord Jesus Christ, to my family
and to my teammates, for whatever distractions I caused.'' No
matter how the case against him is resolved, he said he will not
feel ``righteous.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the police released him around 10 p.m., he admitted he
didn't sleep a wink Saturday night. A fine way to ready oneself for
a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson would be badly burned on the 80-yard Elway touchdown
pass to Rod Smith that set the game's inevitable course in the
second quarter. He was also juked off his feet by Terrell Davis on
a 39-yard fourth-quarter reception that led to the last Denver
touchdown, good for a 31-6 lead and assuring Atlanta of a humbling
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Guess Eugene's legs were dead and his thoughts elsewhere, like
on saving his marriage and repairing his image, although surely
it's shot in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   You feel sorry for his wife, Gia, to be sure, and their two
small children. But you also can't help but feel sorry for Dan
Reeves, whom Robinson betrayed just as badly, albeit in a different
way.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves lost his fourth Super Bowl Sunday, leaving him in the 0-4
company of Marv Levy and Bud Grant. Also, he lost it to the
organization with which he dropped the previous three, and to the
quarterback who, by all accounts, ultimately ran him out of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Sentimentally speaking, Reeves needed a win a lot worse than
Elway or Mike Shanahan, his former Broncos assistant. Elway and
Shanahan finally got theirs last year. Chances are now that Reeves
will never get his, since you must figure the Falcons, if 33 years
of ugly history are a reliable gauge, seem poor prospects to
reprise their lone NFC championship any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Having been a part of nine Super Bowls, Reeves understood the
value of leadership and experience under these skewed
circumstances. He had counted on Robinson to use his presumed ample
reservoir of both to help offset the Broncos' many advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the player kicked the coach squarely in his surgically
repaired heart. Once again, the mind boggles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
