<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-CHAMBERLAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBERLAIN DOES HIS PART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ This will not go down as one of the great Super Bowls,
but one thing it did have was a nice ``42d Street'' sub-plot.
</P>
<P>
   On the very first Denver possession, All-Pro tight end Shannon
Sharpe caught a John Elway pass, made his way toward the end zone,
took a fearsome hit, flipped upside down, and landed about a half
foot from the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last contribution he was going to make in Super
Bowl XXXIII. He had severly sprained his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Watching from his usual sideline perch was 27-year-old Byron
Chamberlain, a 1995 seventh-round draft pick whose job is to
understudy a star who normally needs no understudying. Suddenly,
this was, you know, it. The Big Moment.
</P>
<P>
   The first person to speak with Chamberlain was Terrell Davis,
his best friend on the team. Recalls Chamberlain, ``He said to me,
`This is what you've been talking about all this time. This is what
we've talked about at practice and sitting around both our houses.
This is your opportunity. Get out there and make some plays.'''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that it was very early in the game. The Broncos
immediately scored to make it 7-3 in their favor, but there was a
lot of football to be played and Shannon Sharpe is a very important
player for this team.
</P>
<P>
   There was, as it turned out, nothing to worry about. Chamberlain
blocked. Chamberlain caught three passes for 29 yards. Chamberlain
even caught two Morten Andersen onside kicks in the fourth quarter.
Chamberlain, in other words, did the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prepare myself every day as if I were a starter,'' said the
affable Wayne State product. ``Mike Shanahan teaches you to do
that. It helped that John threw one my way early on. That gave me
some confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos didn't change anything with Chamberlain in the game.
``Mike Shanahan believes in tight ends,'' said Chamberlain. ``I
knew he had faith in me.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV folks weren't quite ready for Chamberlain. Pat Summerall
and John Madden referred to him as ``Brian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that right?'' asked Chamberlain with a smile. ``The funny
thing is I do have a brother named Brian, and he was here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain said he had no idea how he was going to celebrate,
but that it definitely would involve both the Chamberlains and the
Davises. He will never forget the encouragement he got from a
league MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at Shannon go down, and I'm not sure what to
think, but Terrell was right there,'' recalls Chamberlain. ``He
said, `This is your opportunity. You can do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Chamberlain didn't let his buddy down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6434 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-ROBINSON-AZ     02-01 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-ROBINSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPLESS IN MIAMI, ROBINSON ALLOWS BIG TD  
 BUT SAYS ARREST WASN'T A FACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Atlanta Falcons wanted Eugene Robinson as a leader,
a veteran who had been to the Super Bowl, someone who went out of
his way to participate in community service, someone who could be
an example for a rising young defense.
</P>
<P>
   After they signed him as an unrestricted free agent last March,
Robinson played a vital role on the Bomb Squad defense that helped
the Falcons win the NFC title.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, on the eve of Super Bowl XXXIII, Robinson was
arrested by Miami police on a charge of soliciting a sex act from
an undercover police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Robinson, a free safety, went belly up in the game on
Sunday, being torched on an 80-yard touchdown pass from Denver
quarterback John Elway to Broncos wide receiver Rod Smith that
began the unraveling of the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Robinson, who said he broke a finger during the game
while tackling Broncos back Terrell Davis, said that he was
``confident I will be found innocent, however not righteous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize to my Lord, Jesus Christ, my wife and kids, and
the tremendous NFL family for the distraction this has caused,''
said Robinson, reading from a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Then, departing from his script, Robinson said that he got
``absolutely no sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still came to the game extremely focused,'' he said. ``This
incident did not affect my play. We just did not play well enough
to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lots of time last night to think about how I was going
to respond. The ramifications are far-reaching. Confession is good
for the soul, but bad for the reputation. I truly love my wife and
kids, and I regret that this has hurt them. My wife has been
stellar through this in her support and prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons Coach Dan Reeves and several players said they stayed up
with Robinson in support on Saturday night after he was released
from custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say it wasn't a distraction, I'm sure it was,'' Reeves
said. ``But it was not a major factor. My biggest job was to make
sure that he was ready to play, and he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan said that it ``blew right over''
in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We embraced and I said to him, `If there was ever anybody who
had never sinned, let them step forward,' '' Buchanan said. ``We
are brothers on and off the field, and brothers in Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were within striking distance, trailing, 10-3, and
driving in the second quarter. Then 17-year veteran kicker Morten
Andersen missed a 26-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   On the Broncos' first play following the miss, Smith cut past
Robinson in the middle of the field on a post route as Elway rolled
right. Smith made the catch and ran untouched to the second-longest
touchdown pass play in Super Bowl history. It was a rapid-fire
10-point swing that put the Falcons behind, 17-3, and seemed to sap
the life from the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the arrest had any effect on Robinson's performance, or
that overall of a defensive unit that had been strong all season _
one that beat the Minnesota Vikings and their highest-scoring
offense of all time in the conference championship _ is difficult
to assess.
</P>
<P>
   But without question, that quick scoring bomb turned the game.
Robinson said he broke his finger on a tackle of Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to bust Terrell's mouth,'' Robinson said. ``I broke a
finger I hit him so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   There were signs in Pro Player Stadium that read, ``Robinson for
President,'' and ``Give Him the Presidential Trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, Robinson had received a Humanitarian of the
Year Award. Following that ceremony, he had been poolside at the
Falcons hotel in Fort Lauderdale with his wife, Gia, and their two
children.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson started every game for Atlanta, making 94 tackles and
intercepting four passes. With 53 career interceptions, he is the
leader among active NFL players.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the Green Bay Packers' Super Bowl
championship team two years ago and was on the Packers team that
lost in the Super Bowl to Denver last year.
</P>
<P>
   He has said that ``I'm not pretentious and stuck up and all that
stuff. I'm just a regular guy. It's just part of my personality to
reach out. I tell people I'm a Christian who just happens to play
football.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
