<HEADER>
A6435 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-SMITH-AZR &LR;      02-01 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-SMITH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. SMITH GOES TO MIAMI, GETS TD  
 80-YARD PASS ON IMPROVISED PLAY HELPS BRONCOS BREAK ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ ``Keeper X-Post.''
</P>
<P>
   Ding. Bells rang and lights flashed in the mind of Denver
Broncos wide receiver Rod Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected to hear that,'' said Smith. ``It wasn't even
in the game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words from Denver Broncos offensive coordinator Gary
Kubiak, Super Bowl XXXIII swung to the Broncos in the second
quarter when the game's Most Valuable Player, John Elway, connected
with Smith for 80 yards, the second-longest scoring-pass play in
the game's 33-year history, and sent the Broncos to a repeat of
their NFL championship with a 34-19 win.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the first play after the Falcons missed a seemingly
easy field goal, the play completed a quick 10-point swing that
stunned the Broncos almost as much as it did the Falcons' Bomb
Squad defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been in the offense for four years, but we haven't used
it in about three or four weeks,'' Smith said. ``That's a tribute
to our coaches, the way they can adjust and put us in the best
situation to make plays. And it's a tribute to us. We're mature
enough and smart enough to adjust and make it go.
</P>
<P>
   ``After not catching a ball last year in the Super Bowl, this is
great. You want to feel you are a part of what's happening. I vowed
I was going to catch a ball. We wanted to get Terrell (Davis) the
ball enough to make them respect the run so they couldn't sit back
in nickel coverages.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   While the Broncos have the league's leading rusher in Davis, it
was the passing game, with Smith leading the way with five
receptions for 152 yards, that burned Atlanta after he was shut out
by Green Bay last year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had more than 1,200 receiving yards this season, yet his
fellow receiver, Ed McCaffrey, not Smith, is going to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Smith is going, ``but only as Ed's guest. He's taking
me.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey caught five passes for 72 yards as he worked
underneath Falcons' coverages in the second half. After tight end
Shannon Sharpe suffered a knee injury, backup Byron Chamberlain
stepped up with three catches as Elway threw for 336 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Smith ran his post route past Falcons safety Eugene Robinson,
the NFL career leader in interceptions among active players.
Robinson was arrested Saturday night by Miami police on a charge of
soliciting a sex act for pay from an undercover officer.
</P>
<P>
   It might have made the difference. Robinson might have been
overaggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Broncos had run Keeper X-Post. Elway kept the ball
on a bootleg. That was revealing, according to Broncos Coach Mike
Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came back to it and hit the big one to Rod, one of the
reasons we got that was that we had done the quarterback keep off
that earlier,'' Shanahan said. ``They jumped at our running game.
After we took a look at the (Polaroid) picture, we saw the safety
jump on it, so we came back with the pass route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there was one turning point, but that play
helped us get the momentum. It was big. The safety bit a little
bit, and Rod got behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the long touchdown pass ``will haunt me forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were supposed to rotate our coverage where (cornerback)
Ronnie Bradford was supposed to get a jam on Rod, but I don't think
Ronnie heard the call,'' Robinson said. ``Rod came off the line
straight. Now I have to make a decision. I had been trying to set
John Elway up for an interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``To John's credit, he threw it hard enough and far enough that
I had no shot at it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
