<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-GORDON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSIVE STAR GORDON FACES RAZZING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Two Super Bowl rings won't help Denver Broncos
cornerback Darrien Gordon escape the wrath of his friends and
family.
</P>
<P>
   First, they're going to get on him for ``being knocked out'' for
the first time in his football career.
</P>
<P>
   Then they're going to razz him for letting Atlanta quarterback
Chris Chandler tackle him on a 58-yard interception return.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon can take the abuse. He knows his two interceptions played
a big part in the Broncos beating the Falcons, 34-19, in Super Bowl
XXXIII on Sunday at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Both interceptions came after he suffered a concussion in the
second quarter when Atlanta running back Jamal Anderson kneed him
in the back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out for a little while,'' said Gordon, a sixth-year pro.
``I heard a big ringing in my ear, and it felt like I had just
awakened from a long sleep. I was out for only about two seconds.
It seemed like hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon regained consciousness in time to grab a pass that
defensive tackle Keith Traylor deflected to him late in the third
quarter. Gordon ran down the right sideline and appeared to be
headed for a touchdown when Chandler tackled him at the Falcons' 24
after a 58-yard return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the daylight, but I guess the heat and the humidity and
the shot I took from Jamal caused my leg to go out from under me,''
Gordon said. ``But I can't make any excuses. I let Chandler tackle
me in the open field. My family is not going to let me forget
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the fourth quarter, Gordon intercepted Chandler again.
He cut in front of wide receiver Tony Martin and intercepted at the
Broncos' 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was off a route that (Kansas City's) Andre Rison had run on
us a couple of weeks ago for a touchdown, and I was looking for
that route,'' Gordon said. ``It was in the same area of the field.
We call that the strike zone, and it was the exact same route, so I
sat inside for it. Chandler didn't see me, and he threw it right to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos entered the game with the NFL's 26th-ranked pass
defense, but they intercepted Chandler three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a lot of criticism all year,'' Gordon said. ``The
media said we gave up 300 yards a game passing, but the bottom line
is we don't give up many points. Our defense is based on stopping
the run with eight or nine guys in the box. It's just that our
offense is so high-powered that teams have to pass because we are
usually up 30 or 40 points in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos didn't allow Atlanta to score an offensive touchdown
until the final three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept Chris Chandler confused with a lot of different
looks,'' Gordon said. ``The guys up front did a great job with the
pressure. We got some tipped balls, and they (the Falcons) made
some bad decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Falcons' bad decisions was not to sign Gordon, who
was interested in joining Coach Dan Reeves in free agency. But they
didn't make a big run at him.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos linebacker Bill Romanowski thinks players on the
Broncos' no-name defense might become famous after Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had the best game with his two interceptions and 108
return yards, a Super Bowl record.
</P>
<P>
   ``People all over the world watch this game, from Africa to
Europe to Asia and all over,'' he said. ``There's a billion people
watching. It's a great feeling. It feels just as sweet as last
year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
