<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHX-OPEN-ARREST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAN, COPS SCUFFLE  
 GUN-TOTING SPECTATOR SUBDUED AT OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - A sunny day at the Phoenix Open turned scary
Sunday when a gun-packing fan was arrested after a scuffle with a
Scottsdale police officer on the hole Tiger Woods was playing.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas developed at the TPC of Scottsdale's sixth hole
moments after the leaders _ Rocco Mediate, Woods and Harrison
Frazar _ had teed off during Sunday's final round.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders walked within 5 yards of the arrest scene as it was
developing.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested on suspicion of aggravated assault on a police officer,
a felony, and disorderly conduct, a misdemeanor, was Brian K.
Murphy of Phoenix, who was carrying in his fanny pack a gun for
which he had a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, 40, was detained briefly in the Scottsdale Municipal
Jail and released Sunday evening. He was not charged, but the case
will be reviewed by the Maricopa County Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale police Officer Robert Rucker, who arrested Murphy,
said, ``I told the fan to be quiet, and he said, `I've got a gun,
too,' and squared off on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident began with a spectator yelling obnoxiously,
``Tiger, Tiger, Tiger . . .'' moments before Woods teed off. The
gallery was relatively small at that point, as the sixth hole is at
the farthest point on the course from the TPC's clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The police officer raised his palms, and the spectator raised
his. Then the man dropped his right hand and grabbed the officer.
They both tumbled over the ropes, where Murphy pulled Rucker's
jacket over the officer's head.
</P>
<P>
   That brought another Scottsdale police officer and an unknown
fan following the action into the fight, as they subdued Murphy and
handcuffed him. Another officer came to the scene to restrain
Murphy's wife, whose name was not given.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Artigue, tournament chairman for the Thunderbirds, the host
organization, said, ``It's very, very unfortunate when people like
that act out their emotions with this type of behavior. I'm
thankful it ended without serious consequence. It's impossible to
control every individual when you're playing host to over 400,000
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is, it happened near Tiger's group. The good news
was, security was there to make the apprehension.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Dirren, a Scottsdale Police Department spokesman, said that
a gun was found in Murphy's fanny pack, but he did have a permit to
carry it. He also confirmed that Murphy appeared to be intoxicated
when he was placed under arrest at 12:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have since found out that (Murphy) had been causing a
disturbance for approximately four holes,'' Dirren said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Woods expressed surprise that the fan had a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa!'' said Woods, who finished third in the tournament won
by Mediate.
</P>
<P>
   Woods added that it was the second incident in which an armed
fan, or fans, had gotten onto a course where he was playing. The
first time came during a junior tournament five or six years ago,
when two women in Dallas approached him with guns in their
backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might come to the point where it might be like a high
school, where you have to have metal detectors in order to go in,''
Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Mediate also expressed concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policeman that was following us told him, `Watch your
mouth,' '' Mediate said. ``And (the fan) pushed him. That's a big
mistake. (The police officer) put him on the ground. It scared the
heck out of me. I just wanted to get away.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mediate was even more concerned when he was told Murphy was
carrying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, great! He had a gun?'' Mediate said. ``It's just a
game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
