<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHX-OPEN-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S A BOULDER BETWEEN GOLFERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN, TIM TYERS  
 and JOHN DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - A loose impediment is in the eye of the
beholder. It can be a leaf, a worm casing, a cigarette butt.
</P>
<P>
   Or . . . it can even be a half-ton rock, as golf fans across the
nation learned on CBS' national telecast of the Phoenix Open on
Sunday, when nine fans came out of the gallery to remove a large
boulder that was obstructing  &UR; Tiger Woods' opportunity to hit his
second shot at the 13th green.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loose impediment is a loose impediment, no matter how big it
is,'' Woods said. ``A stone is a stone, whether it weights a ton or
a gram. I got a ruling from an official, who is in charge of
rulings. I asked his opinion and he gave his decision and I went
with it. If he had said, `No, you couldn't move it, then I wouldn't
have moved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a shot to the left _ there was a one-foot gap where I
could go left of the stone and under a tree branch. But it was a
pretty big cut (shot), though.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when a pistol-packing fan was arrested while following
Woods, winner &UR; Rocco
 &UR; Mediate and  &UR; Harrison Frazar, the case of the movable rock created
a brief firestorm, especially in the mind of CBS analyst  &UR; Ken
Venturi.
</P>
<P>
   Venturi thought the rock was embedded. He wondered aloud why, if
it were a loose impediment, did it leave a hole where it had been
resting?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was in that group,'' Venturi said, ``I would call him
(Woods) on it.''
</P>
<P>
   PGA Tour competition and rules official  &UR; Orlando Pope ruled that
the rock was not embedded and invoked case rule No. 23{, which
states, ``Stones of any size (not solidly embedded) are loose
impediments and may be removed, provided removal does not unduly
delay play.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, the rule book also reads spectators, caddies, fellow
competitors, etc., can assist a player in removing a large loose
impediment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ben Nelson, PGA Tournament director, said Pope made the correct
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at the area where the rock had been sitting and it
was a level surface with no indentation,'' Nelson said. ``Tiger was
very lucky that there were a number of people in the gallery who
were willing to move it for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, PGA Tour officials received numerous phone calls
during the telecast from irate viewers, claiming the ruling showed
favoritism and Woods should have been disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' second shot was bunkered beside the green, but he blasted
out and made birdie on the hole, moving to 8-under. &QL; 
Kaboom &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It figured that on a weird day featuring pistols and movable
boulders, that Scottsdale's
 &UR; Phil Mickelson would implode.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson started the day at 2-over and made the turn even, then
double-bogeyed No. 10, bogeyed No. 12, triple-bogeyed the par-3 No.
14, birdied No. 15 only to double-bogey No. 16. He finished with an
80, 11 over for the tournament, and tied for 61st.
</P>
<P>
   The top finishes by local golfers went to Paradise
Valley's &UR; Andrew Magee and Ahwatukee's &UR; 
 &UR; Mark Calcavecchia, who tied for 26th at 3 over. Sunnyslope's
 &UR; Jonathan Kaye tied for 33rd at 4 over, while Phoenix's &UR; Tom Purtzer
tied for 49th at 7 over.
</P>
<P>
   Tour rookie  &UR; Ted Purdy of Scottsdale finished 13 over, tied for
64th, while  &UR; Kirk Triplett of Scottsdale tied for 69th at 15 over. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
