<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHX-OPEN-BIRDS-NEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY BIRDS FLOCK TO NEST AT TPC  
 DRINKERS, DANCERS AND SMOKERS HAVE A BLAST UNDER THE CIRCUS TENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN CRENO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - Before the sun went down each day, the party
was in high gear at the Bird's Nest.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour's biggest party lured many people to the grounds of
the TPC of Scottsdale _ forget the golf. They were here to see and
be seen at the hippest watering hole in the Valley, if only for
five days of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Phoenix Open crowd fell about 45,000 from 1998, no
drop-off of any kind was registered at the jampacked site. The Nest
has a reputation as the best party on the tour, and it lived up to
that reputation last week.
</P>
<P>
   Men in golf shirts and Dockers fired up cigars on the patio and
knocked back beers, occasionally taking calls on their cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   The party uniform for women was jeans, tall shoes and tight
tops. The motto on one woman's shirt said it all: ``Got wine?''
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, the Nest isn't much for ambience. Its home is a
circus-size tent covering a slab of concrete near the clubhouse at
the Tournament Players Club of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hottest party in town. I've been going since it was
at the Phoenix Country Club,'' Sherie Jacobs of Waddell said.
</P>
<P>
   She and Kim Nguy, 26, of Chandler, shivered on the patio and
watched the people one night during the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Watched people do what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting drunk. Getting wild,'' Nguy said.
</P>
<P>
   At dinnertime, people already wanted to hit the dance floor.
They weren't particular about the music. They just wanted to jump
around, and soon the area in front of the stage looked like
Woodstock with golf shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a good time. People come here and cut loose,'' said
Tim Welch, 42, of Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   You knew a party was on when men who can't dance wanted to
anyway. Their wives and girlfriends rolled their eyes, laughed, and
tried to anticipate their mates' next moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment here is just nicer than a bar because everyone
is friendly and out to have a good time. It's innocent fun,'' said
Carrie Stewart, 21, a student at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   Duck Soup, a cover band with a Doobie Brothers look-alike on
guitar and a Drew-Carey-without-hair singer, was the house band.
There was a big cheer when they bounced onto the stage and started
pounding out old faves like ``Wooly Bully'' and ``Honky Tonk''
``Women''.
</P>
<P>
   A woman leapt onto the stage and danced so suggestively next to
the singer that he and security didn't have the heart to kick her
off, at least until the end of the song.
</P>
<P>
   Even John O'Hurley, who played J. Peterman on the ``Seinfeld''
television show and now appears in ads for Xerox and the Travel
Channel, got into the act. Introduced to the crowd during a break,
he received a huge cheer when he said, ``Is this the greatest party
on Earth?''
</P>
<P>
   It was, except for the two women who took swings at each other.
Friends intervened; no damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   People forgot the rules about smoking. They lit up in the tent,
mixing cigar and cigarette smoke with sweat from the roiling,
jammed crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't mind the `jampackedness' of it,'' said Carly
Ullinskey, 21, another ASU student. ``You can go in and dance for a
while, then come out and cool off.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a couple of Scottsdale police officers who arrived
early on their horses held the reins of their mounts.
</P>
<P>
   Both are Nest veterans of about 10 years, and they said the
crowd used to be much wilder before Open organizers set up the
high-profile police presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we weren't here, there would be more problems,'' officer
Kirk Toth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have been drinking on the course,'' officer Bill
Yedowitz said. ``By the end of the day, they're hammered. They
don't know when to quit. But overall, it's pretty good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
