<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6441 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PHX-OPEN-WOODS-AZ     02-01 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHX-OPEN-WOODS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALKY PUTTER DECLAWS TIGER  
 BIDS FOR BIRDIES FAIL TO DROP  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - Tiger Woods, with the help of some newfound
friends, managed to move a half-ton rock on Sunday, but golf's
youngest living legend couldn't budge a guy named Rocco by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was left wondering what might have been after finishing
the 72-hole Phoenix Open grind at 8 under and in third place
Sunday, with Rocco Mediate holding the $540,000 winner's check.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be that way. Mediate played back-to-back
rounds in the same pairing with Woods, whose booming drives and
pin-splitting irons have reduced bigger-named foes to mush in
head-to-head competition.
</P>
<P>
   Mediate not only withstood Tiger's presence, he outscored him,
137 to 138, over the two-day, 36-hole match-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of opportunities, especially from holes 10 through
14, where I could have had four straight birdies,'' Woods said.
``But I didn't do that, so I didn't put the pressure on him that I
needed to by playing with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt if I could put some heat on him with him having to
watch me, it could have been a different story. Rocco outplayed me.
More importantly, he outputted everybody. He made a lot of big
putts. I played with him Saturday and he made a few bombs. He hung
in tough today and, deservedly, won the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Mediate, it turns out, is your unflappable sort, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocco is Rocco,'' Woods said, smiling. ``Rocco doesn't change.
Whether he's shooting 80 or 60, he's still the same.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but Mediate, who started the day with a 6-shot lead over
Woods, admitted his comfort zone was more strained Sunday than it
was on Saturday against Woods. He said his case of early nerves
caused him to spend much of the front side scrambling to save par
en route to a two-bogey, two-birdie round of par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to shoot something under par on the front nine to get
a little closer to him and make it more realistic on the back
nine,'' Woods said. ``Because of the way he was putting, and the
way he has been driving, all he needed to do is right the ship _
and, boom _ he's going to make a couple of birdie putts, which he
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good birdie chance on Number 1 and lipped the cup. I
horseshoed a putt for birdie on Number 3. I had a few chances
early. I could have been 2-under after three with a chance to get
something going real quick, but I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of Woods' three birdies came on No. 13, after he
hit his drive left and behind a half-ton rock. A tournament
official ruled the boulder a loose impediment, and nine members of
the gallery were enlisted to move it. Woods hit his second shot
into a bunker, anyway, but managed to make birdie from the sand.
</P>
<P>
   It was the putter that failed Woods. In addition to wasting the
two birdie chances on the front side, he missed a 4-foot birdie
putt on No. 13 and wasted a must-birdie situation on the par-five
No. 15 when he hit a poor chip and then missed a 12-foot birdie
putt. He backed that up by missing another 12-footer for birdie on
No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the ball good. There's nothing you can do about it,''
Woods said of his day on the edge of the cup. ``You have to keep
believing in yourself. You're hitting good putts. I'm hitting the
putts on line. It's not like I'm having bad speed, the putts are
burning the edge. It's part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played as hard as I possibly could today. I went at it, gave
it everything I had, and, unfortunately, it wasn't enough. I didn't
make the key putts when I had to, or hit the ball close enough on
certain opportunities. But I can't say it was a lack of effort. I
wanted to win this tournament. I want to win every tournament.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
