<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6442 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-MAVERICKS-AZ     02-01 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-MAVERICKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY MOTIVES ALWAYS PURE, NASH MAINTAINS  
 GUARD SOUGHT `BALLPARK' DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When the report first came out of Dallas, it was an
eye-opener in Phoenix. According to those reports, point guard
Steve Nash had agreed to a six-year contract extension for $18
million with the Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   While that's nothing to sneeze at, it was far less than the Suns
had been told it would take to keep Nash during negotiations for an
extension before last summer's NBA draft. There were reports that
Nash and agent Bill Duffy were seeking a contract that would
average $8 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, believing they would be unable to keep Nash when he
became a free agent this summer, traded him to Dallas for the
rights to Notre Dame's Pat Garrity, a couple of players and an
unconditional 1999 first-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, General Manager Bryan Colangelo and Coach Danny
Ainge said Nash wanted to be paid starter's money and play
starter's minutes. And with Jason Kidd as the franchise
centerpiece, that wasn't going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   So they pulled the trigger on a deal rather than risk losing
Nash for no compensation _ just as the Minnesota Timberwolves lost
Tom Gugliotta to Phoenix and the Suns lost Antonio McDyess to the
Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Nash has his own team, the Mavericks, who visit America
West Arena tonight for the final exhibition game for both teams.
After this tuneup, the Suns open the 50-game, lockout-shortened
regular season Friday in Los Angeles against the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   And as it turns out, Nash got that starter's money, too. The
initial reports were wrong. Nash signed for about $33 million over
those six years.
</P>
<P>
   But Nash believes there are some misconceptions about his
motives. He insists he wasn't looking to break the bank, and he
certainly did not expect to replace Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said, financially, I had to look out for my best
interests,'' Nash said. ``They had to be in the same ballpark as
what other teams would offer, but I never said I wanted my own
team. I was happy to compromise my career if what I was paid was in
the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   And he insists it wasn't an $8 million ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand things can get misconstrued,'' he said. ``I think
my agent said the number needed to be between five and eight
(million dollars), but it depended on the team. If I was going to
Vancouver, then it had to be closer to eight.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because, as a Canadian citizen, Nash would have taken a
big tax hit in Vancouver, which is in his home province of British
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The money, to Nash, isn't as big an issue as the idea that he
had to have his own team to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never said anything about it being my team or having my own
team,'' he said. ``People understand that we only have so many
years to play and earn money. But I didn't say I needed to run my
own team. I was ready to sacrifice that part to stay in Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Nash figures the Suns couldn't justify paying a
backup point guard more than $5 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand it,'' he said. ``They probably didn't want to pay
that much for a second-team point guard. They had plans to go out
and sign free agents, and even though I wouldn't have counted on
the (salary) cap, the organization still has to pay that money.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash probably feels at times as if he never left, anyway. There
are four other former Suns on the Dallas roster, including Cedric
Ceballos, A.C. Green, John ``Hot Rod'' Williams and Michael Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Green and Finley were traded to the Mavericks as part of the
deal that brought Kidd to the Suns. Ceballos was traded last
February to Dallas for Dennis Scott and re-signed as a free agent
last week. The Suns renounced the rights to Williams, who signed as
a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   And Dallas assistant coach Donn Nelson, son of head
Coach/General Manager Don Nelson, is a former assistant to Suns
Coach Danny Ainge. In a move patterned after what the Suns did
first with Paul Westphal and later with Ainge, the younger Nelson
already has been designated as the club's next head coach.
</P>
<P>
   At a morning shootaround before Saturday's exhibition game
between the two teams, Donn Nelson said, ``It was like being at a
yearbook signing party.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson has even said that he hopes to model the Dallas
franchise after the Suns organization and utilize the climate and
improved quality of the franchise to attract future free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a few more 100-degree days and a lot more golf
courses to do that,'' Ceballos said, smiling. ``Obviously, the
organization is a plus in Phoenix, but it's the whole area. The
whole town is focused on the Suns. Even with the Cardinals,
Diamondbacks and Coyotes, the focus is mostly on the Suns. The town
closes when the Suns play, and whether they're winning or losing,
they sell out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back to Phoenix from the Lakers, they were in that
0-13 streak and the place was still sold out. That support is a big
key for players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I ever heard them boo a player was Kevin Johnson
in the (1993) Finals. Maybe one other guy. I think they booed (Dan)
Majerle once. In other stadiums, players get booed all the time. I
know they booed Tom Gugliotta in Minnesota after they traded for
him, and he ended up being an All-Star for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd has been on the other side, in Dallas, which has the
league's longest current playoff drought _ eight years without a
postseason appearance. But Kidd believes the Mavericks are close to
turning the corner to respectability.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got enough talent to beat anybody,'' he said.
``Michael Finley is one of the best two guards in the league, and
Steve is an up-and-coming point guard. He will have to feel his way
for awhile. It's a lot different when you have the reins to
yourself. But I know he's going to do quite well. The people in
Dallas have a great point guard to watch for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash said he saw himself playing a long time for the Suns, but
he's found a new home in Dallas. The trade, he said, has worked out
well for both sides
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worked out great. I really like all my teammates. It's
been easy because there are so many familiar faces. It's been a
good move. I miss my teammates in Phoenix, but there is no looking
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good about this team. I don't want to make any
predictions, but I think with some time and maturity, we can be
good with the talent and youth we have.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
