<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6445 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-PREDATORS     02-01 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-PREDATORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JAM' MAKES TOAST OF PREDA TORS  
 FORECHECKING COYOTES SPREAD IT ON THICKLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE - Jam.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it's not just something you put on toast or spread
on a piece of bread opposite peanut butter. It's also a catch word
Coyotes assistant coach John Tortorella likes to use when talking
about about his hockey team. It means ``hard hockey,'' Tortorella
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, after playing mostly like jelly on this four-game
road trip, the Coyotes showed plenty of jam in their 5-1 rout of
the expansion Nashville Predators.
</P>
<P>
   They jammed so much, in fact, they could have jumped on stage at
any one of the country joints that line the streets outside
Nashville Arena. They turned honky tonk into hockey tonk and then
quickly left Music City like a headline act on a world tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this,'' Tortorella said. ``We needed to get back
into a workman's-type effort, get back into our forechecking and
start playing with some jam, start competing. That's what we kept
talking about before the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a short-handed goal by Nashville's Greg Johnson midway
through the first period to drive the point home. After that, the
Coyotes (25-12-9) simply overpowered their first-year competitors,
burying them with five straight goals, including a deflection by
rookie Trevor Letowski just 50 seconds after Johnson's score.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Keith Tkachuk, who drew the ire of the Predators
(18-27-4) with a quote he'd like to take back about guaranteeing a
victory, led the assault with a goal and two assists, his third
three-point game of the season and his first since Nov. 24 against
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jeremy Roenick pitched in with a goal and an assist and
set the tempo, especially on the forecheck, by registering nine
official hits in the second period alone. The Coyotes also got
goals from Jyrki Lumme and Rick Tocchet and two assists from rookie
center Daniel Briere, who has four points in his past three games
since rumors began to surface the team might be searching for a
veteran playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   After getting embarrassed here a few weeks ago, 2-0, in a game
in which they showed no jam whatsoever, the Coyotes almost seemed
to be toying with the Predators by the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you have a nice win, the next game you're a
little more relaxed,'' Tocchet said. ``And I think this team just
needs to relax a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Predators, who were coming off impressive road wins
over Eastern Conference powers Buffalo and New Jersey, whom they
beat the previous night in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make excuses, but the puck was going in pretty easy
for them,'' said former Coyotes center Cliff Ronning, Nashville's
leading scorer. ``We were only in the game during the first period,
maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing without wingers Dallas Drake (bruised shoulder), Brad
Isbister (groin pull) and Jim Cummins (suspension), the Coyotes
were down to 10 forwards after rookie Tavis Hansen went to the box
for a fighting major. No problem. A defenseman came to the rescue
as Lumme flipped in a goal past Tomas Vokoun, who got the start
because No. 1 goalie Mike Dunham was in nets the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lumme's first goal in 23 games. About eight minutes
later, Tocchet scored his third in five games, the 401st of his
career. Roenick got one of the assists, his 100th in a Phoenix
uniform since his trade two years ago from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk scored his 19th less than two minutes into the third on
what looked to be an illegal two-line pass from Keith Carney,
making it 4-1. Roenick finished things with a fist-pumping snap
shot, his 17th, at 16:01.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we needed as a team,'' Tkachuk said. ``We
were struggling in our last bunch of games. . . . We needed a win,
period. I don't care how we got it, as long as we got it.''
</P>
<P>
   They did it with jam, something you can find on a supermarket
shelf and now, again on one of the elite teams in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they scored the short-handed goal, we started getting
into the game and working them down low,'' Tortorella said.
``That's our game, forechecking, and we've been missing that. It
came a little bit on the Island (in New York during a 4-4 tie
Friday with the Islanders) and we brought it into this game today.
It's a nice way to go home.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
