<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6447 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PHX-OPEN-FINAL-RO     02-01 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHX-OPEN-FINAL-ROUND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUDMOUTH SPARKS FIRE IN MEDIATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - Coming down the stretch of the 64th Phoenix
Open on Sunday, Rocco Mediate was starting to fade into the
afternoon haze. The easygoing Italian-American was 1 over for the
day, and the footsteps by Justin Leonard and Tiger Woods were
echoing in his ears.
</P>
<P>
   So were the words from the loud mouth of a fan, who had just
made the mistake of giving Rocco the incentive he needed to right
what looked like a ship sinking fast.
</P>
<P>
   On the par-3 12th green, Tiger was eyeing a short birdie putt,
and Mediate's 6-shot lead at the start of the final round was on
the verge of vanishing like a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm walking up there (to the 12th green), and this guy from
the gallery _ and I saw him say it _ said, `Knock it in, Tiger. If
you do, Rocco will fold like a cheap suit,' '' Mediate related.
``Well, that (ticked) me off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk over towards him and I pointed at him and (said), `Will
I fold like a cheap suit?' Well, I almost made the putt (for
birdie-2), and he says it again. If there wasn't water there
(around the green), I would have had to go after him. I was so
mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mediate got even on the next hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just roasted it off the 13th tee, hit a 2-iron just short,
pitched up to four feet and made my first birdie of the day,'' he
said. ``That got me going. I guess I should get mad every morning
when I come out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mediate's mood had come full circle by the time he was presented
the $540,000 winner's check.
</P>
<P>
   Although his par 71 Sunday had been shaky from the get-go,
Mediate had survived 36 holes of playing with Woods and his rowdy
fan club, good for a 2-shot victory over Leonard _ 3 shots in front
of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   As testament to a much tougher course, Mediate's 11-under 273
was the highest winning total at the TPC since Lee Janzen won by
the same number in 1993. It also added up to his third career
victory, and his first since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A straightforward guy, Mediate made no bones about his
less-than-stellar play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger, if he makes any putts, I'm not sitting here,'' said
Mediate, who seems to be back on track after a back injury in 1993
got his career going sideways.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, however, did putt exceptionally well, as his closing 66
matched the best round of the week. For his efforts, the
straight-shooting Texan received $324,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little different this year, but it was nice to get up
to the 16th tee and they were actually pulling for me,'' said
Leonard, who felt the wrath of the fans during a playoff with Phil
Mickelson in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't surprised to see Rocco play solid. I mean he's got
kind of a laid-back attitude and seems pretty relaxed. He's won
golf tournaments before, even though I'm sure he had some jitters
(today).''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who missed birdie putt after birdie putt, said he
``played as hard as I possibly could play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my chances,'' said Woods, who collected $204,000 after
posting 68.
</P>
<P>
   Some might say that Woods got more than his fair share of
breaks, including getting a boulder moved at the 13th hole that led
to a birdie that some fans perceived as unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the ruling, and the official told me it was a loose
impediment,'' said Woods of the rule (23{ in the Rules of Golf).
``I trust (the officials), and I had a shot to the left of the
boulder, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   To say this was a weird day _ a gun-packing fan also was
arrested on the sixth tee after scuffling with a Scottsdale police
officer _ would be an understatement. But boulders and guns aside,
Rocco was not the rock Sunday that he had been during the second
and third rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here (Sunday morning), I called my wife and said,
`I don't feel real comfortable,' '' said the 36-year-old from Ponte
Vedra, Fla. ``I didn't sleep good (Saturday night) for the first
time ever, because I always sleep good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had this feeling. You can get going a little funny here
and you're 3 over just like that.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, he was 1 over at the turn and looking in his
rear-view mirror at Leonard, who had started the day 7 shots back,
and Woods, who was 6 off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident at the 12th started the fire burning. Mediate
turned to his caddie, Pete Bender, and said, ``Nothing is ever
easy. Let's go. We have plenty of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The birdie at the 13th helped, but he came right back with ``my
worst shot of the tournament'' at the 14th that dumped him in a
bunker and led to a bogey. At that point, Leonard was 2 shots back,
and Woods was 3.
</P>
<P>
   The final turning point, he said, came at the notorious par-3
16th, where his 8-iron slid over the back edge of the green, inches
from rolling down a steep incline. From there, he knocked his first
putt from the fringe eight feet past the cup but holed it coming
back for a knee-knocking par.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixteen was the whole tournament, the whole day for me,'' he
said. ``When I walked up there (for the second putt), and Tiger had
just missed again (for birdie), I told Pete, `That's enough. I'm
just knocking this in right now,' and I made it.''
</P>
<P>
   A 2-putt birdie from 120 feet at the 17th didn't hurt his
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``A million miles away,'' Mediate said of the length of the
first putt. ``But the 16th hole let me birdie 17. I miss that putt
at 16, I probably don't birdie 17.''
</P>
<P>
   His ``most relaxing swing of the week'' came at No. 18, where
Mediate's 3-wood split the fairway, about 75 yards behind Woods'
monster drive. It didn't matter, as Rocco made a routine 2-putt par
to cap a wild and wonderful week.
</P>
<P>
   No hard feelings, either, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans were great, and Tiger was great about it,'' Mediate
said of the verbal shelling he faced over the past two days. ``He
said many times, `Oh, don't listen. Shake that off.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they weren't doing it because they don't like me. They
just want Tiger to win, which is how it's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not next year. Winning the Phoenix Open, or even coming
close, has its advantages. Just ask Leonard, who has experienced
both sides of its split personality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
