r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-CASSTEVENS-     02-01 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST WAY FOR ELWAY TO GO WOULD BE WHILE HE'S NO. 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI - It isn't easy to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Few athletes can make themselves walk away from the cheers at
the height of their careers, and Sunday night No. 7 stood on top of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos had won another Super Bowl. Thanks to John
Elway, the contest wasn't even close.
</P>
<P>
   At 38, under a full moon that seemed to shine just for him, the
oldest quarterback to start an NFL championship game put an
exclamation point on his remarkable career. Elway's Most Valuable
Player performance in Denver's 34-19 victory surprised the Atlanta
Falcons and maybe even himself.
</P>
<P>
   This was his game. His night. His finest moment.
</P>
<P>
   Elway upstaged KISS. He outdid Cher. Stevie Wonder. Gloria
Estefan. Big Bad Voodoo Daddy, which it turns out, isn't one
person, but an eight-member swing band.
</P>
<P>
   Elway made even bigger news than Eugene Robinson who was
arrested the night before the big game for allegedly requesting a
personal favor from an undercover police officer in high heels.
This isn't Washington. This is the ``Super Bowl.'' Eugene, WHAT
WERE YOU THINKING?
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's embarrassment was magnified, if that's possible, when
Elway beat him deep, throwing an 80-yard touchdown pass that did in
the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Denver won the Super Bowl almost in spite of Elway.
This time Elway ``led'' the way.
</P>
<P>
   This was the old John Elway, at his best. Of his five Super
Bowls, this had to be the sweetest because he played like a Hall of
Famer and Dan Reeves had to watch.
</P>
<P>
   If last year was about redemption, this was about going out and
having fun and sticking it to his former coach.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about gratifying. Elway kept completing passes, right and
left. The Broncos kept moving up and down the field. The Falcons
couldn't stop them. Reeves must have experienced flashbacks.
Earlier in the week the former Denver coach talked about Elway's
ability, in his younger years, to work magic. To turn what Reeves
thought were bad decisions into winning plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you all the times I thought ``No, no, no . . .
then yes, yes yes!'' Reeves said of Elway when they were together.
Over time they grew apart. The Falcons coach may have set a Super
Bowl record on this night for no, no, no's.
</P>
<P>
   Elway did everything except engineer another signature
fourth-quarter comeback. He didn't need to _ this game was over
long before then.
</P>
<P>
   The only suspense was waiting for the game to end so Elway could
be asked about his future. Will he walk away with two Super Bowl
titles and the MVP trophy in his arms? Why not? The timing is
absolutely perfect.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not easy closing the book. It wasn't for Joe Montana
even when he knew it was time to say goodbye. At 38 and past his
prime, the quarterback who led the 49ers to four Super Bowl
victories made it official at a public gathering. ``I never thought
the day would come,'' Montana said, ``when I would say the word
`retirement.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``One more year!'' fans chanted, like delegates at a political
rally, trying to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' Joe said, ``it's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Few can walk away as Rocky Marciano did. Keeping a promise to
his wife, the former heavyweight champ quit when he was ahead, 49
wins, no losses. Michael Jordan left the stage with the applause
ringing in his ears, the crowd on its feet crying, ``More . . .
more . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Elway is the MJ of Denver. He is that city's most beloved
citizen. He could run for mayor and win. When Rod Smith, who caught
Elway's game-breaking pass, came to the Mile High City, the first
thing he noticed was that Elway was everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was driving down a street and saw John Elway (car)
dealerships,'' Smith recalled. ``I thought, `He runs this part of
town.' Then I went north where I bought my truck and there were
more dealerships and I thought, `This guy runs the whole town.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Elway has done it all. He holds the all-time record for late
comebacks. He has won more games than any quarterback in history.
</P>
<P>
   He is 38. He missed five games this year because of nagging
injuries. Sore back. Sore hamstrings.
</P>
<P>
   Would you come back? Not me.
</P>
<P>
   Are you kidding? Not after this night.
</P>
<P>
   No way. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
