<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPIUM-SOUP-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANGHAI SOUP HAS AN SECRET INGREDIENT: OPIUM  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 375-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
 By TERESA POOLE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Shanghai's ``hot pot'' restaurants have come up with a
recipe for success that has unsuspecting customers soon coming back
for more.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by the city's health authorities of 45 such
eateries found that 11 of them had added a little extra something _
opium poppy flowers _ to the broth.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, reported in the city's main newspaper, the Wenhui
Daily, said that customers eating the spiced-up hot pot would
experience ``numbness,'' feelings of incapacity, and illness.
</P>
<P>
   While this might seem unlikely to tempt back customers, the
newspaper claimed that the added special ingredient could prove
addictive. Shanghai health officials refused to comment on the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone out in search of Shanghai's hot pot buzz would have a lot
of eating to do, however, as only 15 of the 82 hot pots tested by
the authorities were found to contain the illicit poppies.
</P>
<P>
   Giving hot pot customers a little more than they ordered is not
new, but the newspaper said the test results showed a higher
proportion of opium poppy contamination than in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Hot pot is a traditional Chinese dish, along the lines of
fondue, where diners cook pieces of meat and vegetables in a
central boiling vat of spiced broth or oil.
</P>
<P>
   In a country which regularly still lambasts Britain and other
``imperialist powers'' for the 19th century ``Opium Wars,'' it is
all rather embarrassing. Growing opium poppies is banned, and every
year teams are sent out to investigate illegal poppy planting.
</P>
<P>
   After 1949, the Chinese government stamped out opium dens and
virtually rid the country of drugs, but in recent years the problem
has returned with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   China now has more than half a million registered drug addicts,
and last year police confiscated 2.5 tons of heroin and 325 kg.
tons of opium. The statistics do not record how many gallons of hot
pot soup were seized.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide anti-drugs campaign recently toured the country
with the theme ``Yes to Life, No to Drugs.'' Shanghai may soon be
host to a new public information blitz: ``Yes to Hot Pot, No to
Opium.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 375-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
