<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6451 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPIUM-SOUP-INDEPENDEN     02-01 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPIUM-SOUP-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANGHAI SOUP HAS AN SECRET INGREDIENT: OPIUM  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 375-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
 By TERESA POOLE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Shanghai's ``hot pot'' restaurants have come up with a
recipe for success that has unsuspecting customers soon coming back
for more.
</P>
