<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S STRONG HEARTLAND JUST KEEPS PUMPING  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: CX, Midwest States)   (This 550-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Venture inside the Merchandising Mart in downtown
Chicago, a 1930's Art Deco monolith so large that it has a postal
code all of its own, and you will get an instant glimpse of the
state of the economy in the city and beyond across the American
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by strong consumer confidence, it continues to boom.
</P>
<P>
   True, there are areas of weakness. Farming is in crisis in the
region, largely because of collapsing hog prices. And an
unemployment rate that dipped to a meager 3.6 percent in the
Midwest last year means that finding qualified workers has become a
nightmare for many employers.
</P>
<P>
   But the plenitude of jobs coupled with low interest rates,
negligible inflation and high stock prices continues to deliver
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing bearish, for example, about the mood at Russ
Berrie and Company, America's best-known teddy bear wholesaler,
which has a permanent showroom for the retail trade in the Mart.
</P>
<P>
   A new high-end product line of ``Vintage Bears'' launched just
this month was sold out within two weeks. Each bear sells at retail
for $30 or more. Business in the showroom is up 1,000 percent over
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers have walked in a placed orders for $30,000 on the
spot,'' reports Geoffrie Cerese, director of sales, who says a
strong retail performance over Christmas explains the rush. ``Since
the new year, business has been rocketing. What is amazing is that
we would sell so many of these bears so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   One floor below Russ Berrie is Smartrooms Inc., a supplier of
custom cabinetry for kitchens and bathrooms. Its business is
benefiting from an explosion of new-home sales across the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brutally swamped,'' is the best description Smartrooms vice
president, James Livingston, can offer for the state of his
business right now.
</P>
<P>
   How long can it last? ``You have to reach a saturation point and
I can kind of foresee that,'' he replies, warning that one day
there will be more new homes than people to live in them. ``But I
think we have probably got another three years left. I sure hope
so.''
</P>
<P>
   The scramble by employers to find skilled workers may soon
become critical, however, which in turn could spell pressure on
wages and a new inflation risk.
</P>
<P>
   One Chicago-based bank, TCF National, revealed that it is even
sending scouts into city shopping malls. ``If we're being waited on
by somebody who's very good, like at a shoe store, we try to
recruit them,'' said a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   For recruitment firms, like Esquire Staffing Group with offices
in downtown Chicago, it means the pressure to find workers is
relentless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like this in the 40 years I've been
in the business,'' says Esquire Chief Executive Sherwin Fischer.
His consultants simply can't find enough people to fill all the
vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people are nervous wrecks and they don't dare take any
time off because they're making $2000 a day.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago he was predicting at least a slowdown during
1999, but now he is not so sure. ``Frankly, I don't see and end to
it.''
