<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6459 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPER-BOWL-SIDEBAR-SP     02-01 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-BOWL-SIDEBAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS' ROBINSON FALLS SHORT OF OWN SUPER STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Eugene Robinson was beaten down long before Rod Smith
beat him on a game-turning, 80-yard touchdown reception Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, the free safety for the Atlanta Falcons, had spent a
sleepless Saturday night after being arrested on a charge of
soliciting an undercover police officer for oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the same Eugene Robinson who became a team and community
leader while playing with the Seahawks and Green Bay Packers before
adopting the same role in his first season with the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the same Eugene Robinson who Saturday morning had accepted
the Bart Starr Award that is given for high moral character, and
was accompanied by his wife and two children at the Athletes in
Action event were it was presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe, and I strongly believe, I will be found
innocent in this thing, but not righteous by the standards that I
set,'' a solemn Robinson said after the Falcons' 34-19 loss to the
Denver Broncos in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the players, on all the teams, Robinson seems perhaps the
most unlikely for this to happen to.
</P>
<P>
   It was Robinson who had said earlier in the week he would not
allow his teammates to be distracted the night before the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was Robinson who stood outside the Miami Beach Convention
Center, the site of Friday night's lavish commissioners' party, and
offered of the Starr Award, ``A lot of awards are just awards. But
this is one I'd like to win because of what it means, why it is
given and who it is named after.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was Robinson at 9 p.m. Saturday on Biscayne Boulevard,
a major nightclub area frequented by prostitutes and drug dealers.
He was arrested after approaching an undercover police officer and
offering her $40 for oral sex, according to the police report.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was released to a team official and returned to the
team hotel near the Miami airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of time to think about this and quite frankly I
got no sleep,'' Robinson said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   After being released, he was consoled in his hotel room by
several teammates, including linebacker Cornelius Bennett and
cornerback Ray Buchanan, according to Samuel Robinson, the player's
father, who also was in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't say anything about what happened, and I didn't ask
him,'' Samuel Robinson told The Associated Press. ``But you could
see he was crushed. I've never seen my son with that look of
concern and disappointment in his entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson declined to discuss the specifics of the arrest or the
event that led to it, on advice from his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel, I strongly feel, that I will be found innocent,''
Robinson said. ``But what I want to do now is apologize first to my
Lord Jesus Christ, secondly to my wife and kids, and thirdly to my
teammates and the entire Atlanta Falcons organization for the
distraction that I may have caused them.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates refused to blame Robinson's situation for their
ineffective effort against the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that had anything to do with the emotion and the
attitude of the team at all,'' said rookie Tim Dwight, who returned
a kickoff 94 yards for a touchdown. ``The guys really huddled
around him. He's family, and people make mistakes. I don't think it
had one part to do with this ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves met at length with Robinson after he
was released Saturday night. He bristled after the game when
pressed about the impact of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate it happened,'' Reeves said. ``I don't think
it was a distraction. My biggest concern was Eugene Robinson. Was
he ready to play and be focused? I thought he did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But Robinson did not play a good game. Not that kind of
game that has become his trademark in being voted to the Pro Bowl
for three different teams and making it to each of the past three
Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   He missed tackles. He was often out of position. And he was flat
out beaten on the 80-yard TD pass from John Elway to Smith that was
the biggest play in the game _ a quick-strike score that pushed the
Broncos' lead from 10-3 to 17-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to Eugene is very unfortunate,'' said Broncos
fullback Howard Griffith, who scored two TDs. ``The thing about it
is that they lost the game. That will magnify the entire
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   As if it could get any bigger. It was all over the TV pregame
shows and the non-stop topic of conversation among the players and
reporters in the hours leading up to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret I was not maintaining the standards I have set for
myself,'' Robinson said. ``I will have to continue, trust me, to
make amends with everyone that knows me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
