<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6491 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAVE-OLYMPIC-SPIRIT-E     02-01 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVE-OLYMPIC-SPIRIT-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I.O.C. S.O.S.: GOLDEN RULES, NOT GOLDEN HANDSHAKES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 775-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 30 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First-class travel, the finest hotels, sycophancy on a level
normally known only to royalty: since all this is routine for the
114 members of the International Olympic Committee _ and their
husbands and wives _ why should they not expect a little extra when
pressed to decide which of the world's cities should hold an
Olympic Games?
</P>
<P>
   A college scholarship for a much-loved son, perhaps? A concert
engagement for a piano-playing daughter? Some expert, and
expensive, medical treatment? Even, for the less attractive, a
pretty female escort?
</P>
<P>
   Those politicians and businessmen who now express outrage at the
methods that have allegedly won Salt Lake City the right to hold
the Winter Olympics in 2002 are either naive or disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Bribery and the Olympics, the cynics point out, have long gone
together. But bribery and what the IOC calls ``the Olympic spirit''
have not.
</P>
<P>
   That is surely one reason why hard evidence of corruption has
been so long in coming: ever since Los Angeles, in 1984, proved
that the games could be a financial blessing rather than a burden,
the IOC leadership, the television companies, the advertising
sponsors and the bidding cities themselves have found it easier to
hold their noses than to get rid of the smell.
</P>
<P>
   After all, why make enemies of delegates who can cast votes
until the age of 80?
</P>
<P>
   How sensible it was of the organizers of last year's Winter
Games in the Japanese town of Nagano to destroy the relevant
records. How foolish of those strait-laced Mormons of Salt Lake
City to spill the beans.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious risk for the IOC is that the evidence will grow, the
public will be appalled, the sponsors will take fright and the
television companies will lose heart _ in other words, the modern
Olympics will slowly die.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a pity, not just for high-living IOC members and
high-earning athletes, but for millions of people throughout the
world who get pleasure from sport.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the flaws in the Olympic reality, the Olympic ideals _
of sporting excellence, fair play and brotherhood, across all the
lines of race, religion, politics and nationality _ are worth
promoting. The question is how.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the answer would be to sweep away today's IOC, in
particular its elderly and autocratic president, Juan Antonio
Samaranch, and start afresh.
</P>
<P>
   Let the games, the dreamers say, return to the amateur
principles espoused 105 years ago by the IOC's founding father,
Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, let them return permanently to Greece, birthplace of the
original Olympics, and so be rid of the unseemly haggling that
takes place on behalf of competing cities and countries. Or if the
games must be commercial, then accept the implications and auction
them to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   These arguments are unrealistic. The IOC is not about to vote
itself out of existence (and its lawyers will jealously guard its
ownership of the Olympic name and symbols, however tarnished).
</P>
<P>
   Nor are sponsorship and other contracts _ in 1995 the IOC
concluded television deals worth more than $5.1 billion over the
succeeding 13 years _ about to be torn up.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the arguments are flawed. When it is genuine,
amateurism makes sport the preserve of the rich; when it is phoney
(as in the pre-Samaranch era), it pays athletes less than they
should rightfully get.
</P>
<P>
   As for a straightforward auction, that would merely ensure the
games were forever held in the rich world, where the television
audience has bigger pockets and the sponsors are better rewarded
for their investment.
</P>
<P>
   The better answer is not to recreate the system but to reform
it. That must involve more than the handful of IOC expulsions
recommended by the committee's leaders last weekend, and more than
the proposed establishment of an independent ethics committee and a
small team, both with non-IOC members, to visit candidate cities.
</P>
<P>
   Other rules could be added, such as one stipulating a rotation
of the games between continents. But what is really needed is a
change in the IOC's composition.
</P>
<P>
   Because its members serve, without pay, until the age of 80, the
present mix of businessmen, former athletes, retired politicians
and sundry aristocrats is a recipe for quid-pro-quo cronyism.
</P>
<P>
   Better to have members elected by national sporting
organizations (rather than, as now, nominated by each other), paid
for their efforts and limited to a term of office of eight years,
two cycles of the Olympic calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The members and the bidding cities might still bend the rules,
but at least both temptation and opportunity would be weaker _ and
the Olympic spirit that little bit stronger. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 775-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
