<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6502 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP'S-NERDY-NUDZH-ECO     02-01 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP'S-NERDY-NUDZH-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE FORBES: THE GOP'S NERDY NUDZH  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,000-word ``separate buy'' profile of Steve Forbes
is from the current (week beginning 30 January 1999) Economist
magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silly slogans are the early-warning signals of an election
season, and the recent Conservative Political Action Conference was
full of them.
</P>
<P>
   T-shirts proclaimed ``Bauer Power'' in honor of powerless Gary
Bauer, a long-shot presidential aspirant. A stall sold Gore Blend
coffee, bland-tasting and decaffeinated. Stickers exhorted
conference-goers to ``Pave the Rainforest'' and ``Save the Male'';
another said, ``Don't steal, the government hates competition.''
</P>
<P>
   From all this pageantry, two conclusions flow. The first is that
the Republican primaries will be fun. The second is that the
ebullient clashes that they bring will be especially fun for
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   This second conclusion is reinforced by the contemplation of
Steve Forbes, one of several presidential hopefuls at this month's
conservative conference.
</P>
<P>
   At first sight, there is nothing fun about Forbes. His campaign
pamphlet, entitled ``A Strategy for America's Future,'' says
unfunny and unconvincing things like ``Tie the value of the dollar
to a fixed measure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign sticker says, boringly, FORBES; Forbes aides
say scintillating things such as, ``Steve is a real decent
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes himself has a nervous, wide-eyed stare, like an
accountant who has been plucked from the comforting tedium of his
spreadsheets and plonked before the TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for Democrats at least, the Forbes campaign affords a
cruel kind of humor. It is pointed and pointless at the same time:
it skewers other Republican hopefuls, but its own candidate seems
too gauche to make it to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of Forbes, and others like him, ensure that
Republicans will spend much of the coming year beating each other
about the head. Meanwhile, on the Democratic side, Vice-President
Al Gore seems likely (for the time being, at least) to face barely
any serious primary opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes's speech to this month's conservative powwow gave a taste
of head-beatings to come. He railed against ``professional
politicians'' and the ``Republican establishment'' _ meaning his
own party's best candidates for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He poured scorn upon ``the Washington political class and its
media pets'' _ meaning, presumably, Senator John McCain, a
telegenic Republican war hero who has expressed an interest in the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   And, repeatedly, Forbes denounced worn-out names from Republican
campaigns past, as well as the scions of political families.
</P>
<P>
   This was a way of lancing three rivals at once: Elizabeth Dole,
the wife of the Republican nominee in 1996; Dan Quayle, a former
vice-president; and, most of all, Governor George Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is the most charming and best-financed Republican around;
he runs America's second-most populous state; he is his party's
best hope of recapturing the White House. So Forbes strained
especially hard to damage him.
</P>
<P>
   He sneered at ex-President Bush, the father of the governor.
Daddy Bush promised a ``kinder and gentler'' conservatism; Forbes
lampooned the ``siren song of these mushy moderates.''
</P>
<P>
   Daddy Bush broke a promise not to raise taxes; Forbes boasted
that he comes from ``a family of tax-payers, not tax-raisers.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the younger Bush's talk of ``compassionate
conservatism,'' Forbes had this to say: ``Mealy-mouthed rhetoric
and poll-tested cliches are no substitute for a muscular,
substantive agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Forbes is not alone in his assault on Bush; other
Republican White House wannabes have gathered around, forming a
circular firing squad.
</P>
<P>
   The ``compassionate conservatism'' slogan is nothing more than
``weasel words,'' according to Lamar Alexander, the former
education secretary under President Bush; it is ``silly and
insulting,'' according to Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   But, of all the assailants, Forbes matters most. Despite his
gauche manner, he is the only one with the oomph to wound the
younger Bush seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes matters, first, because of money. He is the heir to the
Forbes publishing empire, and is prepared to spend his own millions
on his campaign. In 1996 Forbes entered the primaries late, and
spent his way to victory in two minor states. This time he will be
more formidable by far.
</P>
<P>
   He has been campaigning nonstop these past three years: he has
visited all 50 states, given more than 400 speeches, paid for 60
radio ad campaigns, and deluged journalists across the land with
tiresome press releases.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Forbes fortune will count for more than it did
last time around. The big-state primaries will happen almost
simultaneously in 2000, rather than being spread out, as they were
in 1996. This will make it impossible to campaign much in person:
expensive television ads will matter more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another reason why the Forbes campaign may
seriously wound Bush. The Texas governor may be charming, and
spectacularly good at the sweaty job of working crowds; but he is
short on striking policy proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, by contrast, is full of bold ideas. As in 1996, he wants
to scrap the tax code and replace it with a 17 percent flat tax,
free of loopholes and complex exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   As in 1996, he wants to replace health and pension entitlement
programs with individual savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In foreign policy, he delights hard-core Republicans by
denouncing multilateral institutions such as the IMF and the United
Nations, and by rekindling Ronald Reagan's enthusiasm for a
ballistic defense system.
</P>
<P>
   He is staunchly conservative on social issues: he opposes
abortion; he denounces euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, in sum, has ideas to please his party's social and
economic wings: he talks excitedly about ``rebuilding the Reagan
coalition.''
</P>
<P>
   If he were a charismatic man, he might well pull this off. But
he is too nerdy, and his inherited wealth makes him a disastrous
messenger for a reform that would abolish taxation on investments.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates _ governors and senators and former cabinet
members _ will assail the politically inexperienced Forbes for
regarding the presidency as an entry-level job.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a miracle, he will never make it to the White House. But
he may manage to wound his party rivals enough to ensure that none
of them gets there either. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,000-word profile of Steve Forbes, it
must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
