<HEADER>
A6504 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAKE-TIP-OFFS-ECONOM     02-01 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-TIP-OFFS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEISMIC SOOTHSAYING: NEW EARTHQUAKE THEORY CAUSES A RUMBLE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: California)   (This intriguing 825-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 30 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, CALIF. _ The earthquake which devastated central
Colombia on Jan. 25 took its thousands of victims by surprise. No
wonder, since predicting earth tremors is far from an exact
science.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of effort, most would-be earthquake forecasters
have concluded that it will never be possible to make specific
predictions of the precise time, location and intensity of a
seismic shake-up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they are pursuing statistical approaches, such as
estimating the chances that an earthquake of a particular size will
strike a given region within a certain period.
</P>
<P>
   So a promising new ``stress-transfer'' theory, which sets out to
explain how an earthquake in one place affects the probability of
subsequent earthquakes nearby, is causing a bit of a rumble.
</P>
<P>
   One of the theory's leading proponents, Ross Stein of the U.S.
Geological Survey, likes to explain its underlying principles with
a string of house bricks interconnected by elastic ``bungee''
cords.
</P>
<P>
   Having arranged the bricks in a line on a table, Dr. Stein
stands at one end and winds a small crank which tightens the cord
attached to the nearest brick.
</P>
<P>
   Once the tension in the cord exceeds the frictional force
preventing the brick from sliding along the table, the brick slips.
This causes the cord between the crank and the brick to go slack,
but tightens the cord between the brick and the next brick along
the line.
</P>
<P>
   As Dr. Stein continues to wind the crank, the bricks slip at
different times and by different amounts.
</P>
<P>
   As a whole, the system is unpredictable, but the movement of a
particular brick has a predictable effect on its two neighbors, one
of which becomes more likely to slip (as the cord between the two
tightens) and one of which becomes less likely to slip (as the cord
slackens).
</P>
<P>
   Earthquakes, says Dr. Stein, work in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   The constant turning of the crank corresponds to the inexorable
motion of the earth's tectonic plates, and each slip of a brick
represents an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Just as movement changes the tension of the cords, each
earthquake increases the stress in some nearby areas of the earth's
crust, and releases it in others.
</P>
<P>
   These small changes may not be enough to trigger subsequent
earthquakes immediately, but other earthquakes in the area become
more or less likely as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the particulars of an individual earthquake, the
stress changes it causes can be worked out using a computer model
of the region. The result is a color-coded map showing the change
in stress distribution _ and hence the change in probability of
subsequent earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   To test the theory, Dr. Stein, working with Geoffrey King at the
Institut de Physique du Globe in Paris, Jian Lin at Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution in Massachusetts and Shinji Toda of the
Electric Power Industry in Chiba, Japan, have looked at records of
aftershocks following major earthquakes, including the ones in
Northridge, Calif. in 1994 and the Japanese city of Kobe in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   They chose to study aftershocks because there are thousands of
them, and their statistical theory needs lots of data to work
properly.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, aftershocks were found to congregate in the regions
of increased stress as predicted by the model, while in the regions
of reduced stress (called ``stress shadows'') the number of
aftershocks was very small.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that even though the theory makes a number of
simplifying assumptions about the physical properties of the
earth's crust (for example, that it behaves like bricks and bungee
cords) there is a real link between changes in stress and the
probability of subsequent earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   As well as making short-term forecasts of aftershocks, the
theory can also be used to evaluate how a large earthquake changes
the long-term likelihood of other earthquakes in the region.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in a paper published in the Journal of Geophysical
Research, Dr. Stein and his team estimated that the Kobe earthquake
increased the probability that a similar major earthquake will
occur in the Osaka metropolitan area between 1997 and 2007 from 5
percent to as much as 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And although the timing of large earthquakes is as unpredictable
as ever, the stress-transfer theory's ability to predict the likely
locations of aftershocks could still be useful in the hours and
days after a major earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   With a modest increase in computing power, Dr. Stein says, the
forecasting algorithm (which currently runs on a desktop computer)
could be made to work in real time.
</P>
<P>
   Using data from automated sensors, a map showing areas most at
risk from aftershocks could then be generated and displayed on a
World Wide Web page within minutes of an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The general public and the emergency services would obviously
prefer a precise prediction several days in advance, but any
warning is better than none at all. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this interesting 825-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
