<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6521 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     02-01 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY WON'T BE UPSTAGED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the days leading up to Super Bowl XXXIII, there were those
observers who could not envision the Denver Broncos losing to the
Atlanta Falcons because they could not envision John Elway being
outplayed by Chris Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   It was their view that the 37-year-old Elway, a certain future
Hall of Fame member who ranks among the great quarterbacks in
football history, simply would not allow himself to be upstaged in
a game of such magnitude against Chandler, a long-time journeyman
quarterback who has played with six teams in his 11 NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, did Michael Jordan ever take a pratfall in a
championship setting against, say, a Bryon Russell? Did Bill
Russell ever lose to a Darrall Imhoff? Would Tom Hanks blow an
Oscar to some itinerant character actor?
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, we should have known all along that John Elway,
in perhaps his farewell appearance in a sport he's ruled for 16
years, would dispense a masterpiece Sunday in artfully
choreographing the Broncos' 34-19 win over the Falcons at Pro
Player Stadium in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   We should have known all along that Elway would dissect the
Falcons' defense with short passes, long passes and medium range
passes to an assortment of receivers in a 18-for-29, 336-yard MVP
performance that had those millions who viewed it afterwards
wondering why Elway would even be considering what now seems to be
such a scandalously premature retirement.
</P>
<P>
   We should have known all along that Chandler, when the game was
still was within reach of his reeling team, would revert to the
inconsistent, interception-plagued form that has been a hallmark of
his career before this season and responsible for his unsettled
employment record.
</P>
<P>
   We should have known all along that Elway would flourish
brightly in the pressurized conditions of the Super Bowl, while
Chandler would stagger ignobly by throwing three interceptions and
by not being able to come up with vital plays when his team was in
desperate need of them.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in this match, pure and simple, was in the
quarterbacking, with the Broncos receiving extraordinary play from
theirs and the Falcons receiving from theirs a hapless guy giving a
haunting impersonation of such other memorable Super Bowl failures
as Neil O'Donnell, Stan Humphries, David Woodley and Tony Eason.
</P>
<P>
   This was Elway's fifth Super Bowl and never has he acquitted
himself better, as he coolly threw one deft pass another to Rod
Smith and Mike McCaffrey and even to the injured Shannon Sharpe's
replacement, Byron Chamberlain, and as he turned the proceedings
into a classic recital of his extraordinary skills.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler would have moments when he would resemble the fellow
who masterminded the upset of the Minnesota Vikings, but he had too
many moments when he would resemble the Chandler who for good
reason was so unwanted for so many years around the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   I swear each time the Falcons advanced deep into Denver
territory, Chandler would rise up to betray them with his faulty
work.
</P>
<P>
   If he had played anywhere near as consistently against the
Broncos as he did against the Vikings, the outcome of this one
would have been a lot closer.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Broncos easily covered the 7{-point spread and were
in control for most of the game, the Falcons on several occasions
in the final half were on the threshold of making matters
interesting only to be stymied by the bumbling of Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic disparity between these two teams in this
tedious affair could be found in the John Elway vs. Chris Chandler
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' running back Jamal Anderson (98 yards rushing) held
his own against his celebrated counterpart, Terrell Davis (102
yards).
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' field goal kicker, Jason Elam, blew two easy field
goals, while the Falcons' Morten Andersen butchered only one from
point blank range.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams' offensive lines blocked well.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Broncos had the better of it on defense, but only
because of a huge assist from Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   There will be those who will trace the Falcons' fadeout to the
unfortunate experience their venerable safety and supposed team
spiritual leader, Mr. Eugene Robinson, endured Saturday evening
when he was busted by a vice cop and thrown into a Miami jail for
soliciting oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   It definitely gave those dreadful talking heads on Fox something
to bray about with their empty noggins during all those nauseous
hours of pre-game coverage---blessedly, I missed most of it because
I found arranging my socks chromatically to be far more
intellectually stimulating---but I doubt if Mr. Robinson's alleged
moral indiscretion caused Chandler to keep throwing passes into the
waiting hands of the Broncos' cornerback, Darien Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Robinson was beaten for a long touchdown when Rod Smith ran
by him to haul in a perfect Elway pass, but Smith and Elway have
beaten a lot of defenders across the seasons on such a play.
</P>
<P>
   And I doubt if Robinson had anything to do with the predictable
Falcon play-calling in the first half when the team twice was
stopped on third and one and once on fourth and one when its coach,
Dan Reeves, should have had Andersen attempting what would have
been a short field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves didn't exactly come up with an enlightened game plan
in his well-publicized showdown against the man he once fired, Mike
Shanahan, but I'm not sure it would have made any difference had he
done so.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Falcons' misfortune to face John Elway on a day when
it was all working for him, when his passes were on target, when
his blockers were giving him the necessary time, when his receivers
were latching on to every throw in their vicinity, when he seemed
magically charmed by the fates.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this guy considering permanently hanging up his cleats?
</P>
<P>
   He's on a talented team whose mightiest performer, Terrell
Davis, is a mere 26, and still is in his peak years.
</P>
<P>
   He's quite healthy.
</P>
<P>
   He could become the first quarterback in NFL history to win
three straight Super Bowls, a watershed achievement that has to
appeal to his competitive instincts.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the Atlanta Falcons and a worldwide audience graphically
were shown, John Elway still can pass and lead and spur his team to
heights quite befitting his own unique persona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 0225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
