<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 03:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6538 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIS-MEXICO-SFCHRON &LR;      02-01 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-MEXICO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS BEGINS TRADE-SEEKING MEXICO TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Gov. Gray Davis and a contingent of state leaders
arrive here Monday on a three-day trip to jump start
Mexico-California relations _ and they need only to look across the
street from their hotel to glimpse the business possibilities lying
in wait for them.
</P>
<P>
   That is the site of the historic Chapultepec Castle _ better
known to Americans as the punk-populated House of Capulet in the
hit film, ``William Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet'' starring
Leonardo DiCaprio and Claire Danes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, surrounding Davis' Hotel Marquis Reforma headquarters
are the same Mexico City streets that served as the gritty urban
backdrop for the 1997 Hollywood flick, and leading Mexican
entertainment executives like Rodrigo Gonzalez _ who are keenly
aware of Davis' arrival _ couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entertainment arena is growing substantially in California
and Mexico,'' said Gonzalez, general director of Mexico City's
entertainment giant Corporacion Interamericana de Entretenimiento
(CIE), whose firm has distributed U.S. films such as Spike Lee's
``He Got Game'' in Latin America. ``We're hoping for a lot more
business _ coming and going.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Davis' hope too.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this trip, the governor is looking to find ways to help
companies already doing business here and to open the doors for
others in high-tech, entertainment and agriculture and other areas
who want to work here,'' his press secretary, Michael Bustamante,
said Sunday in the suite overlooking the historic castle.
``Clearly, from a relationship-building standpoint, this trip is
important because the result will be greater trade and more jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaking is one area where the state still holds a competitive
advantage over Texas, which benefited mightily from Mexico's
strained relations with California during the tenure of former
Governor Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican leaders are more than happy to remind California
visitors that some of Hollywood's biggest hits have a ``Made in
Mexico'' label. The pricey blockbuster ``Titanic'' _ all $200
million worth _ would have cost far more if it had not been filmed
in Rosarito, Baja California, and on the back lots of Mexico City's
own Churubusco Studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mask of Zorro'' starring Antonio Banderas, ``Clear and
Present Danger'' with Harrison Ford, were both shot in Mexico:
``Honey I Shrunk the Kids'' was a product of Churubusco's
set-building genius and new high-tech imports _ all evidence of the
Mexico-Hollywood connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the areas that has the most potential,'' said
Gonzalez, whose firm, fresh from a joint venture and infusion of
investment capital, he said, hopes to distribute more Mexican-made
films in California and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen percent of your box office _ $1 billion _ is made up
of Latin consumers,'' Gonzalez noted. ``There hasn't been a big
outflow of Mexican productions _ and we hope some of these products
will flow through California, to good potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Davis' visit to Mexico is the kind of official trip _
including a meeting with President Ernesto Zedillo _ that Wilson
never made, it may not result in such sexy deals immediately,
experts say. But to steal the famous line from ``Casablanca,'' it
could be the start of a beautiful friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``These three days, by themselves, are really about laying the
groundwork for the myriad of opportunities that are out there,''
said Democratic Assemblywoman Denise Ducheny of National City,
Calif., who will accompany Davis. She said that, beyond
entertainment, she hopes to see environmental, academic, and
business links at all levels. ``This is the first level of
establishing a relationship with personal trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Other business leaders, too, say it is the open door they have
been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, nobody ever invited me to go down as a business
leader in communications and radio when the previous governor was
in residence,'' said Norman Pattiz, who chairs Westwood One, the
Los Angeles-based radio network giant and who is also a member of
the delegation. ``I live in Los Angeles, where the top three
stations are Hispanic. That's a very important area for us, and
we're looking for the opportunity to distribute Spanish-language
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Pattiz said the trip comes at a time when ``there's no question
that this is a very important market that needs more attention paid
to it. . . . This focus is long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who is accompanied by 19 business, academic and political
leaders and a few dozen members of the media, is slated to start
work tomorrow by meeting with Zedillo. He is also scheduled to hold
a session with Mexican Secretary of Education Miguel Limon Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   Among others along on the trip are Bruce Karatz, president and
chief executive officer of Kaufman and Broad; Ron Burkle, the
Ralph's supermarket magnate and a leading Democratic party donor;
and Richard Atkinson, the president of the University of
California.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the group heads to the financial center of
Monterrey, where there will be discussions with a broad spectrum of
top officials, including Mexican Secretary of Economic Development
Carlos Zambrano Plant. Davis plans to visit a leading business
administration school, then tour NEMAK, an automobile parts
manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   Even before his arrival here, the Mexican press has been
enthusiastic about the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a very positive response,'' said Delia Lopez, the
entertainment attache for the California State Office of Trade and
Development here. ``The message is that this is a way to restart a
relationship that has been hurt _ and they're looking forward to
what (Davis) has to say to make things better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited to see Governor Davis coming to Mexico because
it's important for him to have a broader view of what Mexico can do
with California,'' said Gonzalez, whose CIE ranks as Mexico's
leading entertainment promoter. The company sponsors California
tours of such Latin entertainment superstars as Luis Miguel. Once
California and Mexico establish a better bond, he said, the ripple
effects in these and other industries may continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the fastest-growing markets, for us, not only has been
the Latin population in the States, but in South America,'' he
said. ``Obviously, we see tremendous potential.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
