 NEWS AND FEATURE No 2517 - February 1, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. HOW NOT TO GET KILLED ON DEADLINE In ``hostile environment''
school, foreign correspondents and reporters learn how to improve
their chances of surviving kidnappings, cross-fires, ambushes and
other perils of the workplace. Here are things they never learned
in journalism school. By Ian Fisher. From The New York Times
Magazine. 1,800 words. 2. AN ESCAPE FROM AUSCHWITZ: A LOVE STORY
FOR THE AGES It sounds like a movie script, part ``Great Escape''
and part ``Love Story,'' only better, but it is true. It is a story
of love and bravery, the tale of how a young Polish patriot,
imprisoned by the Nazis in the Auschwitz death camp, fell in love
with a beautiful young Jewish girl and, certain that she was
doomed, improvised a daring escape. It is the story of how the two
were then separated, each certain the other had died, and went
their separate ways. And it is the story of how, decades later ...
but no, the story is too good to give the ending away. From Der
Spiegel. 2,000 words. (English translation available.) 3. WHERE DID
AIDS COME FROM? The origin of the virus HIV-1, the main cause of
the worldwide AIDS epidemic, has been a matter of debate ever since
its discovery in 1983. Its origins in wild primates (apes and
monkeys) has long been accepted, but which ones and how could it
have been transmitted? The first question has now been answered. By
Eleanor Lawrence. Nature News Service. 1,000 words. (N/A France and
Spain.)
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
THE MYSTERIES OF BILL CLINTON Article on the Clinton scandal by
Gabriel Garcia Marquez, who knows Clinton personally. From Cambio
magazine. 2,000 words. (English translation available.) Not
available Colombia, Brazil, Mexico, Venezuela, Spain, Italy, Peru,
Chile and Argentina.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
A RETURN TO ASIAN VALUES - AND VEGETARIANISM When her son became a
vegetarian at age 9, it was not easy for Rekha Basu. She believed
in vegetarianism in principle, especially in Asian countries like
India, where it has prevailed for thousands of years and seems to
work better with the ecology, economics and culture. Now she is
sure. With Bic Macs and red meat being introduced to Asian
countries, obesity is springing up in places it was never seen
before and land-use is driven by the much less efficient need to
feed cattle than humans. By Reka Basu. New America News Service.
800 words. 
____________________________________________________________________
_____ 6. WHAT'S DOING IN NICE Ideas on events, sightseeing, hotels
and restaurants in Nice, (where the 115th organized Carnival there
- Feb. 13-28 - promises to be one of the best two-week parties this
vibrant Provengal city has ever seen.) By Corinne Labalme. New York
Times Way To Go! 1,800 words + photo + map.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
WHY AMERICA NEEDS TO BE CONCERNED ABOUT THOSE
</P>
<P>
   FARAWAY CIVIL WARS The threat of war in Europe now looms as
likely as ever, as elections return Bosnian hardliners to office
and violence flares in Kosovo. The prospects of achieving a lasting
peace in the region are slim, and these problems are likely to vex
American policymakers for years to come. By Steven R. David.
Foreign Affairs magazine. 1,100 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
PROBING THE PAST If you want to see a time machine, go to room 2677
in the geology building at UCLA where there is a 5-foot-tall,
20-foot-wide piece of equipment housed in stainless steel. It will
not, however, accept human passengers. What goes inside is a flake
of rock. By analyzing the atoms in the rock, this machine can take
you back to the time when the Himalayas were formed, or when life
appeared on Earth. By Kathy A. Svitil. Discover magazine. 1,000
words + photos. 9. REDEFINING QUALITY TIME The idea of ``quality
time'' is meant to be reassuring to busy parents. It suggests that
even if your time with your children is limited, when you use it
wisely you can make up for a lack of ``quantity time.'' This
article takes a closer look at what quality time really is. By
Frances La Barre. From Child magazine. 1,500 words. 10. WHAT NOT TO
BUY FOR BABY A sort of shopping psychosis overtakes the mind of a
father fresh from the delivery room. Here's a quick guide to what
you need and what you don't. By Jeffrey Goldberg. Slate. 1,300
words.
</P>
