<HEADER>
A6675 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN03-CO     02-01 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Baseball diplomacy an insult to exiles
 &HT;    For release Feb. 3, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The ping-pong diplomacy promoted between the United
States and China in the Kissinger '70s opened doors to the Asiatic
communist monolith that remain open today, thereby allowing us to
look in on a continuation of harsh rule and zero tolerance toward
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   And now, under the guise of increased people-to-people contact
with Cuba, the State Department and Baltimore Orioles owner Peter
Angelos are working to open some doors to the Caribbean communist
monolith _ with a series of baseball games. In this case, however,
we already know of the harshness of Castro's rule; there are
hundreds of thousands of Cuban exiles in Miami to document it.
</P>
<P>
   What happens as a result of the Orioles visiting Havana in late
March will have little effect in Salt Lake City, Tulsa, Minneapolis
or Pittsburgh. But it will have a considerable impact in Miami,
which is the capital of the Cuban Diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   What makes matters worse is that the Orioles, by quirk of
inter-league play, are scheduled to come to Miami June 7, 8 and 9
to play the Florida Marlins. I assure any and all that if the
Orioles make good on their intent to play in Cuba, likely in front
of Fidel Castro himself, that the reception they get in Miami in
June will be beyond rude, perhaps violent.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, Miami's recent history is scarred by fierce
Cuban exile reaction to entertainers who have performed in Cuba.
More than one concert has been canceled here, the result of exile
aversion.
</P>
<P>
   While it is easy to identify these actions as being distasteful
to the American way of life _ whatever that is these days _ one
needs to better understand the exiled Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   There are many things about them that do not sit well with me,
their own failure to accept the tenets of our Constitution's First
Amendment chief among them.
</P>
<P>
   But they also must be understood as a people who endure the
emptiness of a lost country, separated families, appropriated
properties, the failure of the Bay of Pigs and of U.S. Neutrality
Acts that freeze them in a vacuum of non-counterrevolutionary
existence.
</P>
<P>
   They watch with anguish as other nations have normal relations
with a country that denies its people the slightest token of
dissent, as new hotels rise with foreign funds, and as U.S.
companies, hoping not to be left out of a new Cuba, seek ways to
divert the four-decades-long boycott the U.S. has placed on the
communist island.
</P>
<P>
   The most rabid Cuban exiles would seek to strengthen that
boycott, but the reality of it is that it isn't doing much to
crumble Castro, that the Cubans are getting enough help from
elsewhere, and that the boycott itself remains a perfect receptacle
into which Castro places his excuses for the failure of his rule.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Cuban-Americans have achieved in this country, they
have done it on their own; they came over with but the shirts on
their backs _ stripped to the economic bone by Castro. What
happened to Cuba since 1959 is seen by Cuban exiles as their
personal holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how damning the reports on Cuba from Human Rights
Watch, no matter how documented the evidence of political prisoners
and earlier kangaroo court executions, Castro mesmerizes the
non-exile world with his charisma. Even baseball owner Angelos is
trying to get into the act, delayed still by haggling with the
communist regime over percentage of profits such a series would
bring.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that the Orioles will go to Havana, but it is an
insult to all those Cuban-borns in Miami and those also playing in
the major leagues today who, along with their families, have
suffered Castro. And to add to it by bringing the Orioles into the
anti-Castro hotbed of Miami in June is to rub salt in a very open
wound or, worse, to enrage the wounded tiger even more.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
