<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 08:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6681 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-ON-     02-01 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-ON-DAWSONS-CREEK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RISING TIDE OF `DAWSON'S CREEK' 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a color slide of James Van Der Beek and Michelle Williams
in a scene from ``Dawson's Creek.'' 
 By SIMON HOUPT  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's late at night, and Dawson Leery has just climbed through
Jennifer Lindley's bedroom window.
</P>
<P>
   As crickets chirp outside, he whispers to her with a throaty
desperation, saying something about love and lust. The two
teen-agers kiss _ tentatively at first, then with a greater
intensity and, it seems, a fair amount of tongue action.
</P>
<P>
   Jen's teddy bear falls silently to the floor ... and she starts
to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cut!'' the director hollers. ``Why is it that everyone who
kisses James can't help laughing?''
</P>
<P>
   James, of course, is James Van Der Beek, the cuter-than-cute
actor who plays the lead role on one of television's hottest shows,
the WB network's ``Dawson's Creek.'' In less than a year, the show
has gone from being a midseason replacement on a marginal network
to an authentic hit, especially popular with the highly
sought-after teen market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy. It was just this little show we were doing down
here in Wilmington, N.C.,'' says Van Der Beek, who at 21 is the
eldest of the four main cast members. ``We never expected it to be
this big ... All of a sudden we were on billboards, and it started
to dawn on us _ `Wow, I can't believe how many people are
watching.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot, 15-year-old Jen (Michelle Williams) arrived in the
fictional town of Capeside, Mass., next door to Dawson, setting his
hormones jumping. After a few heavy kisses, the two broke up and it
wasn't long before Dawson turned to a blossoming romance with his
longtime friend, the tomboyish Joey Potter (Katie Holmes).
</P>
<P>
   But this season has seen a reversal of fortune: After Joey
unexpectedly dumped him, Dawson has once again fallen for Jen's
seductive allure.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like pure soap opera, but that leaves out the impact of
screenwriting phenom Kevin Williamson, the creative force behind
the show and one of its executive producers. The screenwriter of
hit movies such as ``Scream'' (1996), ``I Know What You Did Last
Summer'' (1997) and ``Halloween: H2O'' (1998), he based the
television series loosely on his own adolescence in tiny New Bern,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after Williamson himself, Dawson is an angst-ridden
16-year-old who aspires to be the next Steven Spielberg. Or maybe,
to judge from the movie posters in his bedroom, the next Kevin
Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   The hip, media-savvy intelligence that has the fictional Dawson
admiring the work of his own creator is part of the show's appeal.
``Dawson's Creek'' takes the emotional turmoil of adolescence
seriously, but always knows when to drop in an entertaining
pop-culture reference. One episode, which had all four of the kids
serving time in Saturday detention, was a nod to the seminal Brat
Pack flick ``The Breakfast Club'' (1985).
</P>
<P>
   But fans most often justify their addiction by pointing to the
show's crisp, hyper-realistic dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been shows that have captured exactly the way teens
speak, word for word, like `My So-Called Life,''' Van Der Beek says
during a break in shooting. ``Our characters speak the way
everybody feels, the way people would speak if they had a day to go
over an argument in their head, pull out a thesaurus and then go
back and give someone their comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very eloquent teen-agers and we have taken a sound
beating for that,'' agrees 20-year-old Joshua Jackson, who plays
Pacey Witter, Dawson's wisecracking best friend. ``These kids may
speak with the intellect and the language of a 30-year-old, but
they still have the emotional core of 15- and 16-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why people who are older than the kids are watching the
show,'' Jackson adds. ``And that's why 15-year-olds watch the show
as well, because they can relate on a one-to-one basis with what
we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just 'cause we're talking about sex,'' Williams
says, drawing a laugh from her co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, Katie Holmes adds, ``I just think everyone can
relate to first kisses and the confusion of being a teen-ager.''
</P>
<P>
   Off camera, the actors describe themselves as the best of
friends. That's part of Williams' problem with the kissing scene,
actually.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange situation,'' she says, ``to be in front of a
large crew and kissing somebody that you're intimate with on a
friend-to-friend basis. And all of a sudden _ `Oh, your tongue in
my mouth is kind of strange!'''
</P>
<P>
   The group dynamic between the four is so strong that Jackson
indicates their closeness to Williamson by calling him ``the fifth
Beatle.''
</P>
<P>
   Although all four actors had done film work previously,
``Dawson's Creek'' has put them on a very fast track to stardom.
Just ask Jackson, whose resume includes more than a dozen movies,
including all three ``Mighty Ducks'' films and the recent ``Apt
Pupil'' (1998).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my college experience,'' he says. ``If I was in a dorm
right now, I figure it would be the same thing _ except I might be
having to study courses I didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has been in films such as ``A Thousand Acres'' (1998)
and ``Halloween: H2O,'' but she isn't comfortable yet with the
public attention, and frets about being a role model for young fans
of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only 18, and I'm still making mistakes and still
learning,'' she says. ``So to be put into that position _ it's kind
of precarious, because my choices aren't necessarily right for
everyone else out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that the glare of the Hollywood spotlight is several
thousand miles away. The show is shot in quaint Wilmington, N.C., a
small town with cobblestone streets that seems still alive with the
spirits of proper Southern belles.
</P>
<P>
   The setting helps Van Der Beek get in touch with his character.
Like Dawson, he grew up in a small town _ Cheshire, Conn., where he
reports that he was anything but a teen sensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've often wondered why so many girls are attracted to
Dawson,'' he says, ``because I was that big of a dork in high
school, and nobody had a crush on me.''
</P>
<P>
   His background includes a smattering of theater work and one
film _ ``Angus'' (1995) _ but it wasn't until he was called in to
audition for ``Dawson's Creek'' that his career really took off.
Currently starring in the feature film ``Varsity Blues,'' he admits
that his life will probably never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as meeting people now, it's different, it's an
adjustment,'' he says with Dawson-esque pensiveness. ``It's not
necessarily a bad thing, it's just a matter of getting comfortable
with the social role of being someone of whom an autograph is
requested. Frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of strange,'' he says. ``You haven't changed at all,
it's that everyone around you treats you differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the changes, however, Van Der Beek says he has no
trouble tapping into the angst that fills Dawson's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone remembers those miserable school dances where
you're just walking around trying to look like you had somebody to
be with,'' he says. ``Memories like that _ getting a tray in the
cafeteria and having no one to sit with _ I'm sure you remember the
first girlfriend who dumped you, the one who broke your heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things that stay with you, no matter what you've
experienced or how much you've grown.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Simon Houpt is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
