<SLUG> BC-SINGER-WILLIE-NELSON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD WILLIE STYLE: FOR WILLIE NELSON, ALL ROADS LEAD TO MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of country singer Willie Nelson. 
 By J. POET  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Willie Nelson's tour bus sits in the parking lot of a Washington
motel. The rest of his band is checking in and getting ready for
the coming evening's gig, but Nelson is hard at work.
 &HT;    He's been on the telephone all morning, doing interviews to
promote his new album, ``Theatro'' (1998), watching television and
sorting through paperwork for Farm Aid, the organization he started
to help save American family farms. The 65-year-old singer may be
tired, but he changes gears from one subject to the next without
apparent hesitation.
 &HT;    ``One of the rules of the road is flexibility,'' Nelson says in
his familiar Texas drawl. ``If the map says it's 300 miles to the
next gig, it's usually 400. If you think the show is at 8, you'll
go on at 9:30, so you learn to be patient and flexible.''
 &HT;    Nelson has hit the nation's capital to perform in a benefit for
the Campaign for a Landmine Free World. One of the late Princess
Diana's favorite causes, the anti-landmine campaign came to
Nelson's attention through the efforts of fellow country star
Emmylou Harris.
 &HT;    ``Emmylou told me about it while we were working on `Theatro'
with (producer) Daniel Lanois,'' Nelson says. ``Today they are
mainly blowing up children, and we're one of the few countries that
hasn't signed the treaty to ban them.''
 &HT;    Nelson's association with the anti-landmine crusade may be new,
but through the years he's been tireless in his support of good
causes, including his own Farm Aid, an organization that helps
family farms fight the forces that are driving them toward
extinction.
 &HT;    ``I grew up on a farm,'' Nelson says. ``My parents divorced when
I was 6 months old, and they left me with my grandparents, who had
a small farm in Texas. I worked the fields and raised hogs and
calves for FFA (Future Farmers of America) shows, and learned
patience from watching the seasons turn and the crops grow. It's a
hard life, but it was satisfying.
 &HT;    ``Farm Aid grew out of a remark Bob Dylan made during the Live
Aid concert,'' the singer recalls, ``something about farmers in
this country going to bed hungry, just like they're doing in the
rest of the world. Since I'd grown up on a farm, I started to
investigate the issue, and I was shocked by what I found out.
 &HT;    ``Between 1980 and 1983, 2 million farmers lost their land,''
Nelson says, his tone hardening, ``and since 1983 we've been losing
family farms at the rate of 500 a week. Agribusiness doesn't seize
the land outright, but the price controls they lobby for take just
enough money away from the farmer to make it impossible to meet
payments. With the exception of what they did to the Indians, it's
the biggest land grab in American history.
 &HT;    ``That's why I started Farm Aid, to help folks fight back,'' he
says, ``and every cent we make goes to the farmers.''
 &HT;    Nelson's musical career also owes much to his days on the farm.
Both grandparents played music, and Nelson learned to play the
guitar by watching other farm hands during the informal picking
sessions that marked the end of each day.
 &HT;    ``When I was growing up,'' he recalls, ``country music was like
folk music. It was all around you _ it was simple and full of
feeling.''
 &HT;    After a hitch in the Air Force, Nelson drifted from job to job,
eventually landing a position as a disk jockey on a country station
in San Antonio, Texas. It was then that he began writing his own
tunes.
 &HT;    ``I'm a lazy writer,'' he says with a laugh, ``and I usually
wait until a lyric or a title comes along and let the song write
itself. If somebody asks me to write about a specific idea or
feeling I can usually do it, but for myself I tend to wait until it
happens on its own.''
 &HT;    In the early 1960s Nelson moved to Nashville, where country star
Ray Price gave him a gig with his band and signed him to his
publishing company. When Nelson placed ``Crazy'' with Patsy Cline,
his songwriting career took off and with it his own performance
career, although the confessional style of Nelson's lyrics often
put off the Nashville movers and shakers.
 &HT;    ``Country music used to be about strong feelings,'' Nelson says.
``When it became big business they sent it to a 12-step program,
and when it came back it was squeaky clean, like a loaf of white
bread in a plastic bag. It makes some people a lot of money, but
what's the point?''
 &HT;    Nelson eventually left Nashville and went back to Texas, to play
for folks ``in beer joints'' who still loved real country music.
 &HT;    Then RCA released ``The Outlaws,'' a compilation of hits by
Nelson, Waylon Jennings and Tompall Glaser, and pitched it to the
rock-'n'-roll generation. It went gold and established Nelson's
commercial viability, leading to a series of gold albums for
Columbia, starting with ``Red Headed Stranger'' in 1975.
 &HT;    ``CBS said I could do whatever I wanted,'' the singer recalls,
``but they were unhappy with `Red Headed Stranger' when I brought
it to them. The fact that it went platinum made them easier to deal
with, but I had the same battle every time I turned in a record.''
 &HT;    For the next decade Nelson accumulated Grammy Awards and gold
records while living a notoriously hedonistic lifestyle, including
a well-publicized incident in which he smoked pot on the roof of
the Carter White House.
 &HT;    But as country music went mainstream, Nelson's soft-spoken brand
of honky-tonk music went out of style. Columbia dropped him, and in
1991 the Internal Revenue Service hit him with a huge bill for
delinquent taxes.
 &HT;    ``I had no record deal and owed a bunch of money,'' he says,
``but I've always taken things one day at a time, so I got through
it. I've never followed trends. I just play what I play, and
luckily the crowds continue to grow, and I keep getting better as a
musician. I've got more fame than I do money, which probably
helps.''
 &HT;    It was that fame which led to his current recording deal with
Island Records. When Island president Chris Blackwell heard that
Nelson didn't have a contract, he offered him one _ and included a
promise of complete artistic control.
 &HT;    ``I think `Theatro' is one of the best things I've ever done,''
Nelson says. ``I played the songs live with my band _ some old
favorites, some new material _ then let Lanois work his magic with
those space-age rhythms of his.
 &HT;    ``My instinct is to follow the melody and pay attention to the
phrasing and the feeling of the lyric,'' Nelson adds. ``But the
most important thing is the melody _ it's what attracts you to a
song in the first place. You don't want to get too fancy with the
arrangements.
 &HT;    ``If you have a good song and a good singer, you can't go
wrong.''
 c.1999 J. Poet  
