<SLUG> BC-LAURA-DERN-IN-OCTOBER-SKY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAURA DERN: BORN TO ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Laura Dern in a scene from ``October
Sky.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's a safe bet that no Oscar nominee ever made a screen debut
at an earlier age than Laura Dern.
 &HT;    Yes, that's Liza Minnelli as an infant in Judy Garland's arms at
the end of ``The Harvey Girls'' (1946), but check out ``Rebel
Rousers'' (1970).
 &HT;    That otherwise-undistinguished biker movie, filmed in 1967,
stars Bruce Dern, Jack Nicholson and Dern's then-wife, Diane Ladd,
as a visibly pregnant woman. Yes, she was really pregnant _ and,
yes, that baby grew up to be Laura Dern, future Oscar nominee.
 &HT;    ``I waited until the day the film wrapped until I gave my mother
her first contraction,'' Dern says, laughing. ``You see, I didn't
want to start a career off with people thinking I was difficult.''
 &HT;    The only difficult thing about Dern these days is finding her.
She's on television, she's in the movies and, these days, she's in
bridal shops.
 &HT;    No, she isn't about to marry boyfriend Billy Bob Thornton.
 &HT;    ``It's my mother who is getting married on Valentine's Day,''
she explains, ``and I'm standing up as her maid of honor. It's such
a cool thing to calm your mother's wedding jitters.''
 &HT;    If you haven't been invited, you'll have to settle for seeing
Dern in Showtime's recent, critically acclaimed telemovie ``The
Baby Dance,'' or on the big screen on Feb. 18 with ``October Sky,''
a story about young boys in a coal-mining town who dream of
creating their own rockets.
 &HT;    Dern also recently wrapped the southern comedy ``Daddy and
Them,'' due out this fall, written and directed by Thornton. Kelly
Preston, Jim Varney, Andy Griffith and Dern's mother, Diane Ladd,
co-star.
 &HT;    Fresh from that positive experience, Dern _ sipping tea in a
suite at Los Angeles' Park Hyatt Hotel, tall and wispy-thin in a
gray suit, with miles of glossy-blond hair falling softly to her
shoulders _ is even willing to talk about her previously hush-hush
relationship with Thornton, the Oscar-winning writer/director/star
of ``Sling Blade'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``Billy Bob and I were friends for a long time, which I think is
a great way to get to know someone,'' she says. ``You can only be
close to another person if there is that solid friendship backing
it all up.''
 &HT;    The two met on the set of the famous ``Ellen'' coming-out
episode in 1997. Dern had recently ended a long relationship with
actor Jeff Goldblum.
 &HT;    ``We started out talking to each other about changes in our
lives,'' Dern recalls. ``Meeting Billy Bob really was perfect,
because we sympathized with what the other person was going
through. I think to meet on that level was a great gift.''
 &HT;    ``October Sky,'' set in 1950s West Virginia and based on the
true story of rocket scientist Homer Hickam, casts Dern as the
boys' idealistic, inspirational science teacher, Miss Riley.
 &HT;    ``I loved that these boys followed what their hearts wanted them
to do,'' Dern says. ``The film is an example that an extraordinary
teacher can make all of the difference. Homer needed Miss Riley to
tell him to listen to his own voice and believe in himself.
 &HT;    ``I think this film shows how desperately you as a parent want
to protect your own child,'' the actress adds. ``Parents often
think they're doing the right thing, but it turns out to be
limiting. You can do damage to your child because of your own
fears. You need to sometimes put those fears aside and tell your
child, `You can do anything.'''
 &HT;    That's the voice of experience talking.
 &HT;    ``When it came to acting, both of my parents said, `Don't do
it,''' she admits. ``They told me not to act, because acting
doesn't feel good a lot of the time. The funny thing is that they
were always very supportive in terms of my acting work after I
started.''
 &HT;    Dern grew up on film sets with her father and mother, who split
when she was a little girl. Cameos in a couple of her mother's
movies, most notably ``Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore'' (1974),
only whetted her appetite.
 &HT;    At 9, Dern formally announced to her parents that she wanted to
follow in their footsteps.
 &HT;    ``My dad didn't have a strong opinion about it one way or the
other, but my mother was against it,'' the actress recalls. ``My
mother was scared for me because she's a woman _ she had very
specific fears about me getting caught up in looks and age and
being rejected because of physicality and not working. She worried
I would have a great success and then not work.
 &HT;    ``I could understand her point of view,'' Dern says, ``because I
lived with my mom, and I saw on a day-to-day basis what this
business does to a woman. My mother wouldn't consciously let me see
her upset about not getting a role, but I think every child can
sense when a parent is upset. I would feel badly for her when
someone else got a part she wanted so much.''
 &HT;    Ultimately, the 9-year-old made a deal with her mother.
 &HT;    ``Mom said, `OK, study for a few years and, if you're still into
it, then you can get an agent,''' she recalls. ``The fact that I
studied for two years and spent every weekend in acting class
scared her. I didn't say, `Oh, I want to play with my friends and
blow this off.'''
 &HT;    At 11, Dern got her reward.
 &HT;    ``I met an agent through a friend, and my mother allowed me to
go on an audition,'' the actress recalls. ``I got my first movie
role in `Foxes.' And my mother was devastated _ I remember her
crying, `Now you're going to think it's so easy.'''
 &HT;    Bruce Dern says there was no going back after his daughter
starred with Jodie Foster in ``Foxes'' (1980).
 &HT;    ``She was a natural,'' he says in a separate interview. ``People
ask all the time if I gave her advice or helped her with the roles
because she was so young. I didn't really have to teach Laura a
lot. It was very evident at about 11 years old that Laura got it.
 &HT;    ``It's a magical light bulb that went off inside of her, which
doesn't happen very often to anybody,'' he recalls. ``When I saw my
daughter had this talent, it was a very emotional moment for me. I
saw her get into character, and I was so moved. I thought, `She
understands it, she feels it.'''
 &HT;    That gift led to the critically praised ``Smooth Talk'' (1985).
She followed that with two films for director David Lynch, ``Blue
Velvet'' (1986) and ``Wild At Heart'' (1990), winner of the Palme
d'Or at the Cannes Film Festival. In 1991, she earned a
best-actress Oscar nomination as a likably sluttish Southern girl
in ``Rambling Rose.'' Her other credits include ``Teachers''
(1984), ``Mask'' (1985), ``Haunted Summer'' (1988), ``Fat Man and
Little Boy'' (1989), ``A Perfect World'' (1993) and the blockbuster
``Jurassic Park'' (1993).
 &HT;    ``I don't want to sound like some revolting stereotype of an
actor,'' Dern says, ``but I really think a character has a life of
her own. If you're lucky, you bring a character to a scene in a way
where you never quite know what her response will be like or what
will come up, despite the fact that there is a script. There are
things that I do where I surprise myself.''
 &HT;    And her audience, too, especially the younger ones who know her
from ``Jurassic Park.''
 &HT;    ``To kids, I'm the lady who stuck her hands in dinosaur poop,''
she says, laughing. ``I always have kids looking at me wide-eyed in
airports and asking, `Was it real dino poop?' I get that all over
the world.
 &HT;    ``Of course I tell them, `Yes, it was real,''' she adds. ``Why
shatter the illusions?''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
