<HEADER>
A6684 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDANA-BREWSTER-IN-T     02-01 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDANA-BREWSTER-IN-THE-60S-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AHEAD TO THE PAST: JORDANA BREWSTER TAKES ON `THE '60S' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jordana Brewster in a scene from ``The
'60s.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Going to Yale in the 1960s must have been an amazing experience.
But what if you had to choose between the two _ Yale or the 1960s?
 &HT;    That was Jordana Brewster's dilemma.
 &HT;    The 18-year-old actress, best known for her three-year stint on
the soap opera ``As the World Turns,'' chose to defer her freshman
year at Yale to play hippie in ``The '60s,'' a four-hour-long
miniseries that will air Feb. 7 and 8 on NBC.
 &HT;    ``I was all packed and ready to go,'' the effusive actress says
by telephone from her parents' home in Manhattan. ``But when I got
the role, I just had to do it.''
 &HT;    The role was Sarah Weinstock, one of several characters whose
experiences from 1960 to 1969 are woven into ``The '60s.''
 &HT;    ``Sarah goes from being a Barnard College girl who's a bit
conservative to a girl who gets involved in the peace movement,''
Brewster says. ``Her parents want her to express her ideas and be
idealistic, but they don't necessarily want her to act on them.
They want her to be comfortable, get married and have children.
 &HT;    ``That's what women were supposed to do, which is sick.''
 &HT;    Rounding out the cast are Jeremy Sisto as an emerging radical,
Josh Hamilton as a pacifist, Julia Stiles as a pregnant hippie,
Jerry O'Connell as a shellshocked Vietnam vet and Charles Dutton
and Leonard Roberts as members of a black family who become
embroiled in the civil-rights movement.
 &HT;    Brewster, who lives in Los Angeles, was born in 1980 and has no
firsthand knowledge of the 1960s _ though she does have a family
connection to the era: Her grandfather, Kingman Brewster, was the
controversial president of Yale for most of the decade.
 &HT;    ``Kids now attach cliches to the '60s,'' the actress says. ``We
think of free love, flower power, being a hippie, smoking a lot of
pot and not having to worry about the consequences of our actions.
 &HT;    ``People also tend to generalize the era and assume it was only
about one movement or that everybody was a hippie,'' she adds.
``What's good about the miniseries is that every character has a
different point of view, and that lets you see the diversity of the
'60s, the different mentalities people had.
 &HT;    ``I read a lot of books and tried to get familiar with the
movements, with the war,'' Brewster says. ``None of that was as
helpful as tapping into the mentality and emotions that were going
on, and I did that through music, by listening to Bob Dylan
incessantly.''
 &HT;    During the production, Brewster sported bell bottoms, go-go
boots and love beads, and participated in the re-creation of the
student takeover at Columbia University. She visited the set during
the recreation of the Woodstock concert, and met Carnie Wilson,
daughter of Beach Boy leader Brian Wilson, who plays Mama Earth, a
woman who runs a commune.
 &HT;    The scope of the production daunted Brewster, she confesses.
 &HT;    ``To be honest, I was very scared and tentative the first couple
of weeks,'' she says. ``It's a huge thing to do justice to, the
'60s.
 &HT;    ``We were told that we were bringing the story of the '60s to my
generation,'' the 18-year-old says, ``and I had people in their 40s
and 50s telling me I couldn't possibly understand what was going
on. That made it even scarier.
 &HT;    ``I finally had to remember that I'm acting,'' she adds. ``And
by feeling the character's emotions, as draining as it was, I think
I understood the character and a little of the bigger picture.''
 &HT;    Brewster arrived at ``The '60s'' fresh from Robert Rodriguez's
``The Faculty'' (1999), a box-office disappointment that cast her
as a high-school cheerleader who joins several other students to
save her school _ and mankind itself _ from aliens who have taken
over the bodies of the faculty.
 &HT;    ``Talk about a completely different experience,'' she says
breathlessly. ``I liked one particular review, which said, `In the
midst of all these pretentious movies, here's a fun one.'
 &HT;    ``That was my first feature,'' the actress says. ``To work with
Robert Rodriguez off the bat was amazing and, like on `The '60s,' I
was intimidated. I was shaking the first couple of days.
 &HT;    ``I was still 17 when I did the movie,'' she adds, ``so these
situations are very abnormal compared to what a typical kid goes
through. I felt like I was in high school, because we were all
thrown together and had to hang out.''
 &HT;    Brewster particularly appreciated the chance to work
occasionally with the established actors who played the possessed
faculty members, especially Robert Patrick and Famke Janssen.
 &HT;    ``I liked the movie a lot,'' Brewster says, ``and thought the
chemistry between all of us was very cool. I didn't see the adults
work very much, so it was a surprise to see what Robert and Famke
did.''
 &HT;    The daughter of a former model and a banker, Brewster was born
in Panama and raised in London, Brazil and Manhattan. She caught
the acting bug as a girl, and spent her early teens splitting time
between high school and the soap opera ``As the World Turns,'' on
which she played Nikki Munson.
 &HT;    Actresses who have moved on to the big screen tend to knock the
soaps, but Brewster recalls the experience as an invaluable working
education.
 &HT;    ``It depends on the soap you're on,'' she says. ``Some of them
want ratings, so you have to have your shirt off constantly and
it's all about melodrama.
 &HT;    ``I was on `As the World Turns,' which has been on for 40 years
and is pretty realistic. I got to learn from some wonderful actors.
 &HT;    ``On a soap, because your performance is on for one day, you're
allowed to explore and allowed to make mistakes,'' Brewster says.
``You don't get that chance with movies, where people see it over
and over and all of your mistakes are magnified because you're on a
big screen.
 &HT;    ``I got a chance to explore and also to develop a sense of
professionalism,'' she says. ``I couldn't go out and party with my
friends if I had to be on the set at 7 in the morning with 20 pages
of dialogue memorized.''
 &HT;    Having finally gotten her break and been cast in two
high-profile projects, Brewster now plans to turn her attention to
Yale. She'll begin classes in fall 1999, and hopes to emulate Yale
grad Jodie Foster by acting during summer breaks.
 &HT;    It's a calculated risk for a recent Seventeen Magazine cover
girl who is only now generating buzz. Today's Hollywood hot ticket
can be tomorrow's yesterday's news.
 &HT;    ``You can be huge at one point and then, in five years, be
nowhere,'' Brewster admits. ``That scares me to death, so I'm
trying to be smart.
 &HT;    ``I want to play different characters,'' she says. ``I never
want to act solely for money or fame. I plan to study literature,
and I think I can only help my acting by learning about characters,
by comparing a character's inner monologue to his or her actions.
 &HT;    ``I think the life experience I'll acquire at Yale will only
help, too,'' she adds. ``I'll be hanging out with kids my age and
be secluded in New Haven.''
 &HT;    All of which reinforces Brewster in the gamble she's taking.
 &HT;    ``Heat is heat, and it's transient,'' she says. ``I want to act
until I die, but I'm not kidding myself. I'm 18 _ I realize that my
career is not really in my control, and I hate that aspect of the
business.
 &HT;    ``Going to school is the one thing I can control,'' she
concludes. ``Hopefully I'll grow and learn as a person, and get
better as an actress.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
