<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX02 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Trent Tries the 12-step Cure
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENT: Hello. My name is Trent and . . .
</P>
<P>
   GROUP: Hi, Trent.
</P>
<P>
   TRENT: . . . and I'm an impeachaholic.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP: Ahhhhh.
</P>
<P>
   TRENT: I suppose my story's old hat to you, but it is painful
for me to tell anyway.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP: Go on. We understand.
</P>
<P>
   TRENT: It started when I saw those other Republicans, the ones
over in the House, whooping it up for impeachment. Sure, they were
a bit out of hand, some of them, and a lot you could say were even
over the top. But it looked like fun, too, and I thought . . . I
thought . . .
</P>
<P>
   GROUP: It's OK. Go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   TRENT: I thought, when the party came over to the Senate, that I
could have just a little impeachment and let the rest go. You know,
just a few days of it. Just a little social impeaching.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP: Oh oh.
</P>
<P>
   TRENT: I figured, well, what harm can a few lawyers' arguments
do? Judges hear them all the time and don't get hooked. So, sure,
maybe you get a little bit high _ all that 90-proof talk about the
president being just about the worst crook since Charles Manson, or
maybe O.J. since he and O.J. are so much alike, what with the women
and all and Clinton lying all the time about everything to
everybody and HAVING HIS WAY WITH THE RULE OF LAW AND...
</P>
<P>
   GROUP: Whoa. Slow down. Take a deep breath, Trent.
</P>
<P>
   TRENT: Sorry, but you get the idea. That stuff can go right to
your head. And those boys who showed up from the House, they're a
hard-partying crowd. You try to cut them off or even say you've had
about enough impeachment yourself, and the next thing you know
you're back in the bar with them. They say, ``Hey, let's have a
round of witnesses'' and you say ``How many?'' and they say
``Fifteen'' and you say ``I just want to go home'' and they say
``But you can't. Be polite. You can't disrespect us, so tell you
what: let's just have three witnesses _ for the road, you know?
Sort of a nightcap.''
</P>
<P>
   (His voice trails off.)
</P>
<P>
   GROUP: Take your time.
</P>
<P>
   TRENT: I knew I was in trouble. Old friends started staying away
from me. I could lose my job. So I made a firm deadline for
quitting.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP: (applause)
</P>
<P>
   TRENT: I said to myself, no more impeachment. Hey, I'm a grown
man. I can handle this stuff and I know when enough is enough. But,
darn those House fellows. They say ``What could be wrong with just
a couple of weeks more?'' And, really, what could be? So Henry Hyde
throws his arm around me and says, ``C'mon, some videotaping _ you
never know what you might see, if you get my drift _ have you seen
'JenniCam' on the web? Doesn't that sound like fun?'' And I say
``Well . . .'' and Henry says, ``You don't want make Bob Barr mad,
do you? You never can tell what he might do when he's like this.''
So I say, ``OK, but if we don't quit impeaching by, I say February
12, I don't know what I'll do,'' and Henry says, ``Loosen up,
Trent. All we have to do is vote for another week of impeaching if
we want to. Or another month.''
</P>
<P>
   So what do you folks, think? Do you think I should . . . Hey,
where did everybody go?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
