<HEADER>
A6797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN02-COX     02-01 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Born with a mission to make great music
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Music is love,'' Robert Shaw told us. And Atlanta
believed him.
</P>
<P>
   The city that almost fired Shaw in 1972 nevertheless had a love
affair with him over decades _ not just Shaw the musician but Shaw
the man. The Atlanta Symphony director emeritus who died last week
was loved for his earthy ``cracker barrel'' laugh as well as the
spirituality of his music.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Robert Edge was one of those who led the revolt
against the symphony executive committee who wanted to fire Shaw in
the 1970s. ``They thought he was too `avant garde' for a
traditional Southern city,'' he said, ``It still gives me cold
chills that we almost lost him.''
</P>
<P>
   Edge and Shaw were close personal friends, but Edge never got
over his awe of Shaw's passion and intellect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he was given a special mission in life,'' he said,
``and you could sense it _ there were no holds barred when Robert
delivered the music the composer wanted to convey.'' Edge, who
serves on the Board of the Metropolitan Opera in New York, believes
Shaw was the nation's most provocative spokesman for the arts,
gifted with words as few musicians are. ``He believed there was a
time in the history of man when the church was a great human force
_ and that today, the arts play that role.''
</P>
<P>
   Edge paused _ ``just meditating,'' he said sadly as he collected
his feelings about his friend's death. When the news came, Edge had
been preparing to teach a church class on ``Samson and Delilah,''
the Saint-Saens work based on the Old Testament that the Atlanta
Opera will perform this season. Words about Samson in the opera's
first Act seemed perfect when applied to Shaw: ``(Ah!) the breath
of God has passed through his soul.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shaw's views on the relationship of worship and the arts
were complex, says Lois Reitzes, program director at WABE (public
radio), who knew Shaw well from a dozen years of interviews and
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a minister, Shaw was a vocal critic of televangelism,
which he once called, ``the crystal Christ-o-ramas, the Sunday
Spectaculars of bigotry and contempt for men's minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Worship, Shaw said, ``doesn't require you to check your mind at
the door.'' But he was never contemptuous of the people's music _
folk hymns, carols, and spirituals, he found ``tuned and polished
by generations of unintentional composers, nameless amateurs who
loved their God and wanted to praise him.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unpublished lecture Shaw gave at Trinity Presbyterian
Church in 1982, he linked worship and art in a profound way:
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, at least, the arts may provide the day by day
confirmation of a Creator's hand still at work in the lives and
affairs of men.''
</P>
<P>
   When Reitzes heard Shaw had died while attending a play at Yale
that his son Tom was directing, she recalled a story Shaw had
shared with her. The maestro had just returned from a stay at the
family get-away in rural France. And he told Reitzes proudly that
then-14-year-old Tommy had ``birthed a sheep'' while they were
there. ``We read and sing about sheep,'' he said, ``but, really,
how many 14-year-olds qualify to be shepherds?''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Shaw was a modern shepherd. He led us through the
valleys of requiems, the whole littered landscape of serious sound,
so we might not fear spiritual heights. And like a shepherd, his
first concern was for those in his care, his musicians, his
audience, his Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   I'll never forget his words on receiving a prestigious cultural
award from the French government. ``Music,'' he said ``is not
conductable. It is singable and playable.''
</P>
<P>
   Then raising his own hands which had shaped the finest chorale
music in this country, he insisted with a shepherd's humility,
``These hands make no sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Until his death Monday, he was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
