<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We Americans are growing bigger, but not for the better
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By and large, we are getting larger.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 20th century, Americans have been getting taller
and heavier. With better prenatal care, fewer childhood diseases
and much _ much _ more food, we have been pushing our bodies to new
heights and widths.
</P>
<P>
   But will this trend continue in the next century? Are we on our
way to becoming a land of 7-foot giants?
</P>
<P>
   The answer depends on many factors, including genetics, diet
changes, cultural attitudes and medical breakthroughs. We could end
up being bigger, or perhaps thinner. If we start getting smaller,
it wouldn't be the first time that happened.
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologists say men who lived about 10,000 years ago often
grew to be 6-footers. In the days when we hunted and gathered our
food, we were big, robust people who stood about as tall as today's
Americans. We started shrinking when we began farming and settling
into cities.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem surprising because we assume farming created more
food for prehistoric people. It did, but having more food in a
permanent settlement encouraged us to have more babies. As
populations rose, we each got less food and more disease. Primitive
agriculture was good enough to boost birth rates, but not good
enough to produce strapping young adults, so human beings began to
shrink.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two centuries, that trend reversed dramatically as
farming methods improved. U.S. Army records, which go back to
colonial times, give us a good measure of growth: On the eve of the
Civil War, Americans were the world's tallest people, with men
averaging 5 feet, 6 inches. By World War I, Army recruits were up
to 5 feet, 7 inches. In World War II, our soldiers stood about 5
feet, 8 inches. Today, they average 5 feet, 10 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Although Americans are tall, we no longer are the tallest people
in the world. Today's big folks are found in the Netherlands and in
Scandinavian countries where everyone has access to good health
care. Millions of Americans fail to reach their maximum height
potential because their mothers don't get prenatal care. And many
U.S. babies get little medical care.
</P>
<P>
   But once we make it past the earliest stages of life, we get
plenty of food. Double cheeseburgers, sweet treats and
calorie-loaded beverages are making us much heavier.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention found that among
adults studied between 1988 and 1994, about 35 percent were
overweight. That was a 9 percent jump from adults studied from 1976
to 1980. Nutritionists say the weight gains among children are
especially alarming; about 25 percent of kids now weigh too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't gained any height in the past 25 years, but we have
gained a lot of weight,'' said Richard Steckel, a professor of
anthropology at Ohio State University. ``We're taking in too many
calories ... and not getting enough exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will happen in the next century? With technology taking
over ever more tasks, our lifestyles could become even less
strenuous. Our best hope for reversing that trend may be to get
both schools and employers to promote exercise during lunch hours.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that drug companies may develop a pill to
stop the body from absorbing calories from fatty foods. In fact,
one company, Hoffmann-La Roche, already is seeking Food and Drug
Administration approval for just such a drug, called Orlistat.
</P>
<P>
   But if we can develop pills to help slim our bodies, can we find
other drugs to make ourselves taller? Steckel said that although
some companies may try to develop such pills, it would be unwise to
do so because ``we're already pretty close to our optimal size,''
he said. After men reach a height of about 6 feet, 1 inch, they
actually start to become less healthy. Extremely tall people often
have heart problems and die at younger ages, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So over the next century, we may pick up a couple of inches in
height, but we will not turn into giants. As for our waists, Gerald
Berenson, a heart and weight expert at Tulane University, believes
we will start to find the will power to change simply because the
health consequences of obesity are becoming so clear. ``We're going
to have to plateau off because we just can't keep ballooning like
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mgeewax(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
