<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Socks ready to kick up his heels
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ When the Clintons first moved into the White
House, I paid particular attention to stories about Socks and how
he was adjusting to his new home. I worried he might get stuck in
an elevator or maybe slip out the front door and be trampled by a
crowd of demonstrators on Pennsylvania Avenue. Most of all, I
wondered where they were going to put the sandbox.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as memory serves, there have been cats in my life.
There was always a ``Putsy'' or a ``Jackie'' in the house, and once
there was a ``Booger'' (named for his disgusting habit of doing his
business in the piano).
</P>
<P>
   The cat-loving genes were inherited from my mother's side of the
family. Grandmother Parker never had fewer than 15 or 20, and they
all lived in. Each had an individual personality that was catered
to. Charlie McCarthy, a giant white tomcat insisted his meals be
served on the upstairs screen porch. Tommy preferred his sandbox in
the butler's pantry. Baby liked coffee with heavy cream.
</P>
<P>
   Granddaddy Parker often compared his family's food and vet bills
to those of the Clyde Beatty circus, but no stray was ever turned
away. When the '29 crash came along, the same courtesy was extended
to vagrants. As a kid, a visit to grandmother's always meant a new
face to talk to over a plate of food on the back porch.
</P>
<P>
   First cat Socks has had more media coverage than the average
housecat and for obvious reasons: (SET ITAL)His(END ITAL) house is
the big White one inside the Beltway. For a while, Socks' home life
seemed idyllic. He napped in sunny patches on the Oval Office
carpet, and went for rides on his president's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Socks has always taken his Top Cat position seriously as
evidenced in his official White House portrait. In spite of the
silly bow tie someone hung around his neck, Socks' feline dignity
and nobility manage to shine through.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Buddy, the chocolate Lab. Immediately, the news shifts to
the mundane: Buddy is being housebroken; Buddy is learning tricks.
Socks turns up his nose. What's the big deal? he wonders. How tough
could it be learning not to have accidents on the carpet? And as
for rolling over and playing dead - forget it. Cats don't do
tricks. From time to time, they may indulge in amusing antics, but
certainly never on command.
</P>
<P>
   People do not train cats, no matter what they claim. What passes
for training to us is little more than a cat's desire to indulge a
human. Truth is, our cats train us. Mine have done a hell of a job.
</P>
<P>
   Each morning, I am awakened by a ladylike mew from Little Sister
Stella. A gentle paw on the cheek will usually do it, but if it
doesn't, she shifts to plan 2 where she grabs a mouthful of my hair
and pulls. Folks are usually fooled by her small stature and
dignified demeanor, but make no mistake, she rules with an iron paw
_ albeit one concaled in a furry white glove. Stella and
</P>
<P>
   Biddy have trained me to keep fresh butter in their licking dish
and to buy only vanilla ice cream. And on the rare occasion when I
fall short of their expectations, I am duly punished. Cats do not
suffer fools gladly.
</P>
<P>
   Before anyone sets pen to paper to give me what for, let me
assure you I love dogs. Once I even had a puppy. Two weeks into her
potty training, a neighbor told me that no matter how I coaxed, the
pup would not use the sandbox. Said I'd have to take her outside to
pee. Made sense to me - the inside was all used up anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back at the White House, Buddy is dazzling folks with
his good humor (I'm told he was smiling as he bit the hand of the
Marine helicopter pilot who was playing ball with him) and his
willingness to obey commands as he wags his way through the
remaining months of his master's term.
</P>
<P>
   And as for Socks? The first cat has decided he's seen it all and
is looking forward to retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail to: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
