<HEADER>
A6800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN02-COX     02-01 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Continuing daytime medical drama of parent who overdoes it
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I coached Little League 10 years ago. I have yet
to regain my voice.
</P>
<P>
   I can speak, but what once was resonant became an intercom rasp
most commonly associated with ``Would you like fries with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Recently I agreed to coach my son's basketball team. Quickly my
voice went from bad to barely audible. Add a bout of the Central
Texas crud, the super germ known to spend the winter in area
sinuses. I've had more than one person come up lately, thump my
larynx with a middle finger and ask, ``Is this thing on?''
</P>
<P>
   So I went to a specialist, Dr. Cleophes D. Tunnel. He examined
me at his Carpal Diem Center for Repetitive Stress Ailments.
</P>
<P>
   I told him my problem. Actually, I couldn't talk, so I sketched
it for him on scratch pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh hum. Yes. Yes, indeed. And the doggie did what on that
lollipop tree?''
</P>
<P>
   Flustered, I had to gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voice. Gone,'' I rasped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh hum. Tell me your family history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I sighed deeply and set about to sketch my life story _ Mom,
Dad, the covered wagon, everything. After 45 minutes of frantic
diagramming, the pencil dropped from my limp, exhausted hand. Dr.
Tunnel stroked his chin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. Uh hum,'' he said, peering over my heiroglyphs. ``Yes,
indeed. Quite clearly. A case of chronic accute PTBVBD.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is..?'' I rasped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Post-T-Ball Voice-Box Disorder. We see it in coaches and
parental spectators. Very common.''
</P>
<P>
   This provided little solace. Long ago I figured I shot my wad,
locution-wise, with all those hours of shouting ``Get it to the
pitcher'' to 6- and 7-year-olds who were chasing a little white
ball like a pack of blind harp seals. I was, however, interested to
find out it had a clinical name.
</P>
<P>
   Since I had the doctor there, I inquired about some other
lingering injuries I suspected might have been caused by repetitive
motions as a parent.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote out, ``shoulder pain.'' He asked me to sketch out common
family activities, which I did.
</P>
<P>
   I told him about following our kids around and videoing their
every action for posterity. In particular, I sketched out the
plight of recording PTA musical programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh hum. Yes. That's it. You suffer from carpal camcorder
condition. Very common among modern parents _ 63 percent of my
patient load, in fact.''
</P>
<P>
   When I complained about a stiff neck, and of repetitive trips
jockeying unruly kids kids to school, to the park, to the ends of
the earth, he was quick with a clinical hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carpal carpool condition, unquestionably.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what about this wrist problem?'' I rasped. I've had the
soreness since my boys were small. ``We used to play little games
in the wading pool, over and over,'' I told the doctor. ``You know,
'ashes, ashes, we all fall down.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have diagnosed your own problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ring-Around-the-Rosie wrist. Some sufferers also have a
collateral condition we call Ring-Around-the-Rosie rump.''
</P>
<P>
   Fascinating as I found this _ the fact that all of my ailments
had clinical definitions _ I began to realize that Dr. Tunnel
hadn't suggested any treatment for the problem that brought me to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside the wrist problem, and the camcorder shoulder, and
the carpool neck ache, I wrote down a demand: ``Please. Prescribe
something that will save my voice.'''
</P>
<P>
   He took out a pad, scribbled, handed me the scrip, shook my hand
and smiled as he excused himself.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until later, moritified before a chuckling pharmacist,
that I realized what Dr. Tunnel had prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't yell.''
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday.
E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
