<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Venture capital flowing to Atlanta
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta is a growing hub of venture capital, according
to the most recent issue of DigitalSouth magazine. It says the city
has added two new venture capital firms in the past year _ Monarch
Capital Partners and Live Oak Equity Partners. In addition, Atlanta
has added new regional offices for venture capitalists Mellon
Ventures and Arete Ventures. Overall, DigitalSouth says venture
capital is hot. It says ``venture capital is to today's Harvard
Business School graduates what investment banking was in the
'80s.''
</P>
<P>
   Catch up on what futurists are saying about how the PC will
evolve in the February issue of PC World. The magazine says by next
year, there'll be microprocessors with speeds of 700 megahertz. But
that's nothing compared with other advances expected within the
next several years. Those advances include intense 3-D graphics,
full-motion MPEG-2 video and real voice recognition. There'll also
be ultra flat but sharp screens and notebook computers the
thickness of a slice of bread.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Solitaire has long been one of the most popular games among both
children and adults. Not surprisingly, that also holds true on the
computer. There are plenty of versions of solitaire for the PC. Now
GT Interactive has released the latest one, available for both PCs
and the Mac. Called ``America's Greatest Solitaire Games,'' it
includes 37 different games of solitaire. You'll find ``Klondike,''
``Pyramid,'' ``Free Cell,'' ``Eight Off'' and ``Golf,'' among
others. The company has also added new features such as undo, redo
and replay. There are eight different background graphics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thunder Brigade'' is a new computer CD game featuring flying
tanks. The tanks are the advance weapons of interplanetary warfare.
You play one of three federations fighting for control of a dozen
different planets. There are 30 different missions, conceived in
3-D detail. Published by Interactive Magic and Blue Moon, ``Thunder
Brigade'' is available only for PCs with Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Learn about the new ``Dilbert'' TV show on UPN at the official
company Web site. The site features thumbnail sketches of upcoming
shows, behind-the-scenes interviews with animators and producers,
and technical information about the show's production. It's based
on the famous cartoon strip of the same name. You'll find the site
at http://www.unitedmedia.com/comics/dilbert/tvshow/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
