<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In 25 words or less, kids' take on taxes
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It only costs a stamp and they're too young to be
audited, so why not? The folks who make TurboTax are sponsoring a
contest to get grade school kids to contribute their 2 cents' worth
about taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit, the company that makes TurboTax, a tax preparation
software program, is sponsoring a contest called ``Kids Speak Out
About Taxes.'' The contest asks kids in the third through fifth
grades to take no more than 25 words to tell how they think the
feds should spend their parents' tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   One kid will get a $1,500 contribution toward an education
individual retirement account established in his or her name by
Intuit. Ten semifinalists will get a $50 U.S. Savings Bond.
</P>
<P>
   All of the winning entries will be published in a newsletter
sent to members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The contest runs until Feb. 26. It is open to all elementary
school children in grades three through five who are legal
residents of the United States and who attend American public,
private or parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   Participants can enter the contest over the Internet, by fax or
by regular mail. To enter online, go to the Taxes area of
Quicken.com at http://www.quicken.com. To enter by fax or mail,
include this typed information: your name, the name and address of
your school, what grade you're in, your complete home mailing
address, your home phone number, and fax and e-mail addresses if
you have them.
</P>
<P>
   Entries can be faxed to 619-784-1385, or mailed to: TurboTax
``Kids Speak Out About Taxes'' Contest, Intuit Public Relations,
6220 Greenwich Drive, San Diego, CA 92122.
</P>
<P>
   For a complete set of contest rules, send a self-addressed
stamped envelope to the above address.
</P>
<P>
   Site coordinates job opportunities
</P>
<P>
   The folks behind the Monster Board and the Online Career Center
have joined forces to bring you http://www.monster.com, an online
job-hunting site.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which launched this month, lists 145,000 jobs and more
than 1 million resumes.
</P>
<P>
   The new sites offers a feature called ``my monster,'' which lets
you customize the site. Users can access a password-protected site
and create and store online resume, cover letters and material
about job searches. Membership is free.
</P>
<P>
   The site also offers resume tracking, which lets anxious job
hunters see how many times their resume is looked at by prospective
employers. The site has a privacy option that lets job-seekers
choose to not reveal their contact information.
</P>
<P>
   Online job sites are among the Internet's most popular.
MediaMetrix lists Monster.com as one of its 500 most popular Web
sites for December. A Forrester Research study predicts dollars
spent on online recruitment advertising will grow from $105 million
in 1998 to $1.7 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves strike at office
</P>
<P>
   A computer security company sponsored a study of computer theft
_ the low-tech kind _ and found most computers are most frequently
stolen from offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Kensington Technology Group Computer Security Survey asked
251 information services or information technology workers at
companies with at least $10 million in revenue. They found most
laptop computers are stolen inside the office, 41 percent. Cars and
cabs, 12.4 percent; airports, 8.4 percent; and hotels, 5.6 percent,
also ranked high on the list of likely theft sites.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies, 62 percent, use things like security guards,
gates and badges to keep employees from stealing computers. Fewer
companies used cable and locks and motion alarms to prevent theft,
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune 1000 companies are more likely to have experienced
computer theft and to have lost more money to hardware, software
and information theft than smaller companies with more than $10
million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
