<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6809 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOBUDDY02-COX     02-01 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To sharpen skills, pick proper search engine for each job
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most of us spend a lifetime searching, whether it is
for the secret of life, our lost car keys or for the place you
stashed your Aunt Sally's recipe for chili.
</P>
<P>
   Just as you'd suspect, life on the Web mirrors life. As the Web
has become a tool, instead of just an amusement (when is the last
time you heard someone say they planned to ``surf'' the Web?
Nowadays we navigate it), the ability to search for needed
information has become more important.
</P>
<P>
   While it is mildly amusing to be searching for information about
wartime Germany for your child's homework project and to get
instead dozens of pages about German shepherds, German measles and
German chocolate, it isn't good use of your limited time.
</P>
<P>
   There's an art to searching the Web, and today we'll talk about
some techniques that will help make your own searches _ whether you
are using the Web for fun, school or work _ more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to know is that not all search engines are the
same. Each has a personality all its own. There are way too many
search engines to cover them all, but we'll talk about a few of
them and, as we do, discuss the kind of search that each does best.
That way, you can start by tailoring the choice of a search engine
to the information you seek.
</P>
<P>
   For a search such as the one in our example, Yahoo!
(http://www.yahoo.com) is best. If your topic is general and it is
likely that a lot of resources exist, go to Yahoo!. But if your
search is very narrow and for information that is likely to be
rare, try AltaVista (http://www.altavisita.com) instead. And when
you're really at a loss, searching for needles in haystacks, try
Dogpile (http://www.dogpile.com), which in turn uses multiple
search engines. You'll get a lot of hits that way, but the downside
is there will be more information to sift through.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's talk about ways to sharpen your search. As you
probably know, these engines seek out pages that contain the search
words you use. That's why it's important to select words precisely.
Most searches are literal. If you are looking for German shepherd
dogs and then use the word ``canine,'' with most search engines,
you'll only get pages with that specific word.
</P>
<P>
   We'll use AltaVista as an example of a way to narrow a search.
Let's say you are looking for information on wartime Germany. You
could simply type in the words ``German war WWII world war II'' and
you're likely to get a lot of hits. But, based on the way AltaVista
works, you would find pages that contained any one of those words.
So you'll also find pages about German culture, about every war
since the War of the Roses, and any page with the word ``world'' in
it.
</P>
<P>
   With AltaVista, you instruct the search engine to find pages
with a combination of words. By putting a plus sign in front of
words, you let AltaVista know the word must appear. So if you
changed your search to something like this (+Germany +world +war
+WWII), you would only get pages that had each word. You'll get few
hits, but the likelihood increases that each page will have the
information you seek. Since each search engine requires different
techniques, be sure to read the help section on those pages to get
tips for narrowing your search.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it's a good idea to explore carefully when you find a
page that is on the money. Many of the pages you find will offer
links to similar sites. That way you can use the expertise of the
designers of the good pages to locate similar ones.
</P>
<P>
   If you follow today's advice, you should be able to do a better
job when you search. I cannot, however, help you with your car
keys.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
