<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A02-COX     02-01 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you tell me who pays for the gown Laura Bush wore for
the inauguration proceedings? Do Gov. and Mrs. Bush, out of their
private funds, or does the tax payer? _Melanie G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your tax dollars are safe. While the rent is free at the
Governor's Mansion, little else is. The Michael Faircloth-designed
gown was paid for with personal funds, says governor's office
spokeswoman Karen Hughes. (Its price has not been made public.) To
add to the ``aaahhhhh'' factor, Mrs. Bush received flower-shaped
earrings as an inaugural gift from the governor. Meanwhile, Gov.
Bush wore a new tuxedo, a Christmas present from Mrs. Bush. So much
for that ``no new tuxes'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to know if you can get for me the recipe for mesquite
bean jelly. _Jake Pickle
</P>
<P>
   A: The mesquite bean jelly recipe seems like a challenge because
the beans must be at a certain stage in maturity _ when the red
color begins to show on the pods. For a copy of the directions,
courtesy of the Travis County Extension Service, send me a stamped,
self-addressed envelope. And, Congressman, let me know how your
first batch turns out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have some beautiful red and yellow leaves that I would like
to preserve. Is there a way to preserve their color? _Dyan D.
</P>
<P>
   A: No guarantee, but some good ideas. A nice drink of glycerin
works on freshly cut magnolia branches, but the leaves have been
off the tree for a bit. The professionals at Preserved Flowers
suggest dipping the leaves in floor wax. A friend whose dinner
table always reflects the seasons shared her secret. She collects
interesting leaves and pods and stores them in plastic trash bags
with a twist tie in the garage. (A spritz of insecticide or diluted
soap water kills any bugs). The leaves are out of the sun and wind.
Do not place anything heavy on the bag. Leaves are pretty hardy and
should last several years without much tending.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know where I can get a one-handed knife? It is used by
people who are paralyzed on one side, and I would love to get one
for my sister. _Pat N.
</P>
<P>
   A: The knife is probably a ``rocker knife,'' which allows an
individual to cut with a rocking motion rather than a sawing
motion. It is available in various sizes from catalogs such as
Enrichments, at (800) 435-8573. A similar product is the
all-in-one-hand cutlery set _ a combination lightweight knife and
fork, designed to be operated by either hand alone. The fork
retracts for easy closing and the user's lips are protected from
the knife's edge. For a consultation on the hundreds of products to
aid your sister, call Assistive Devices at 346-0889. There are also
cutting boards and plates with corners and spikes to anchor foods.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need to store a wooden armoire in a commercial storage
room. Is there anything I can do to help retain the natural beauty
of the wood? Is it harmful to store this for a long time? _Patricia
Abram
</P>
<P>
   A: When you say commercial storage, do you mean
climate-controlled? If the temperature is kept between 60 and 85
degrees and the humidity is regulated, the armoire will be fine.
Here are a few points on storage from Michael Christian at
Restoration Shop. If possible, store the armoire assembled; if not,
place the doors and sides flat (on plywood or some sort of pallet
to protect from moisture). Rest the base against the flat sides and
the bonnet on the base. Resting these pieces flat avoids the
dreaded potato chip effect that can happen when wood warps. Before
placing in storage, give the armoire a lemon oil treatment and make
sure it is covered with a dust protective cloth. Check on the piece
in three to six months just to make sure all is well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a teacher and I contribute to TRS (Teacher Retirement
System). I have also worked at various jobs in the summers to get
in my 40 quarters with the Social Security system. How will my
pensions be distributed and will I be able to qualify for both when
I retire? Some say I will only receive TRS benefits, while others
tell me I will get both, but at a smaller percentage. _ James Hood
</P>
<P>
   A: I put your questions to the professionals at the Teacher
Retirement System and the Social Security Administration. TRS
spokesman Howard Goldman says some school districts elect to
participate in Social Security, some do not. Regardless of your
district's decision, TRS benefits are not affected by other jobs
you may have had over the years. Meanwhile, over at the Social
Security Administration, Sandra Talbot notes benefits depend on
your ``average covered earning over your lifetime,'' which is
calculated by a standard formula. If you receive a pension from a
job ``where you did not pay Social Security taxes, a different
formula may be used to figure your benefit amount.'' For a free
estimate of what your benefit will be, call (800) 772-1213. Bottom
line? You do receive both TRS and Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a problem with silverfish in our house, especially in
the kitchen cabinets. We have used moth balls, but to no avail.
Also, a friend told me that moth balls are toxic. _ Sue A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Moth balls are toxic _ careful around pets and children.
Silverfish are annoying and are commonly found in moist, warm
locations (sink and faucet fixtures). Try eliminating the moisture
where they appear. Readers have reported success with herbal
remedies such as vetiver (dried or oil). Another solution is
unwrapped sticks of Wrigley's Spearmint gum _ a reader suggestion,
not Wrigley's.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What final disposition is made of the module panels removed,
and the hundreds of bolts and pins used to stabilize the new space
station connection during the Endeavour's mission? _ Jeanne M.
</P>
<P>
   A: This hardware, says NASA spokesman Phil West, has been
returned to NASA in Houston and will either be reused on future
modules, employed for training crews or used for engineering
purposes on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Southwest Indian Foundation is a source for quality
crafted Native American jewelry, pottery and gifts from sources
like the Navajo tribe as well as the pueblo tribes of the Zuni,
Laguna, Acoma and Hopi. This nonprofit organization uses proceeds
to benefit Native Americans. For a catalog call (800) 504-2723.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
