<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-TOOLS02-COX     02-01 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'll do it my way, just like in the good old days
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Because this column appears in the technology section
of the newspaper, I am often mistaken for a technological sort of
person, riding right out there on the cutting edge of science.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, every time I get near the cutting edge of anything I
wind up in need of Band-Aids. Technology so seldom actually bends
itself to my will that I'm usually startled when, upon screwing in
a new light bulb, it actually lights up.
</P>
<P>
   This lamentable condition was demonstrated yet again the other
day when it was decided that I should cover an event that was going
to be held a hundred miles or so from home, and would not end until
very close to deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Now, gather round, children, and let me tell you how we did this
sort of thing in the olden days. In the olden days we didn't have
things like computers. We didn't have cellular telephones, either.
Reporters carried a notebook, several cheap pens and some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   If the event took place somewhere the telephone company hadn't
grown any pay phones, we knocked on somebody's door and asked if we
could use their telephone. Since there weren't any 800 lines, and
nobody had thought of calling cards, we called the office collect.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was an archaic interaction in which the reporter
dictated over the phone, to someone at a typewriter in the office,
a usable story, or a portion thereof. Now, with the New Technology,
having to take dictation from a reporter appears to be a fate so
degrading as to warrant self-immolation.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, it was decreed that in order to file a story
following this event, I should take a Macintosh Powerbook, along
with a small contraption that would connect the Powerbook to my
cell phone. Why, with this, I could file from anywhere, even from a
speeding car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't work,'' I told them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it will,'' they replied. ``It always works.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for me, it won't,'' I said. ``Things like this never work
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   No amount of whining would get me out of it, because, I was
told, the office was too shorthanded to take dictation.
</P>
<P>
   As if we were longhanded in the olden days.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, I was sitting in a burger joint, starving
while my companions taunted me with their Biggy Fries, finishing up
a piece written on the Powerbook in pidgin English in a dark car
careening at 90 mph down the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   After innumerable contretemps with the Powerbook, which I hope
never to see again, I finally got everything hooked up and did what
I had been told to do. As expected, it did nothing. Zilch. Wouldn't
even dial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' they had told me. ``You'll see the numbers run
right across the screen of your cell phone.'' Nothing, except for a
few stray grains of salt, ran across the screen of my cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   So I unplugged the apparatus and called the office. To my great
good fortune, it was answered by a gentleman named Doug Payne,
whose olden days, while not so elder as mine, are olden enough to
include shame-free dictation. My gravelly whine synched with his
typing system, and the story was transmitted in the olden way.
</P>
<P>
   Codgers uber alles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
