<HEADER>
A6830 &Cx1f; tad-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMENTARY-BJT02-COX     02-01 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, February 2, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ Marilyn Geewax's weekly column looking at
issues raised by the coming of 2000. This week: How our average
height and weight may change in the coming century. (Geewax,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ A trip to Dr. Tunnel to find out
what's wrong with my voice revealed an unexpected diagnosis:
PTBVBD. ``Which is..?'' I rasped. ``Post-T-Ball Voice-Box Disorder.
We see it in coaches and parental spectators. Very common.'' (John
Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ Pulitzer winner Michael Skube's weekly lifestyle
commentary. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ When the Clintons first
moved into the White House, I paid particular attention to stories
about Socks and how he was adjusting to his new home. I worried he
might get stuck in an elevator or maybe slip out the front door and
be trampled by a crowd of demonstrators on Pennsylvania Avenue.
Most of all, I wondered where they were going to put the sandbox.
As far back as memory serves, there have been cats in my life.
(Elizabeth Schuett, a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio,
writes twice a week for Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ ``Music is love,'' Robert Shaw told
us. And Atlanta believed him. (Martha Ezzard is on the editorial
board of The Atlanta Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ (Lane, Daytona Beach
News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WALKER-COLUMN _ LONGVIEW, Texas _ Teens turned out in great
numbers to support Pope John Paul II. The reason why is because
they hear no uncertainty from him about what he believes is right
and wrong. That's not true for many of the adults from whom today's
teens seek guidance. And John Paul II doesn't wait for young people
to come to him. He seeks them out. So should we. (Walker, Longview
News-Journal) MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
