<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Car trouble? Maybe online expert can help
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once upon a time, before the age of computers, cars
were the chief source of aggravation in most folks' lives. The act
of keeping them in good repair and figuring out their intricacies
took up great chunks of free time.
</P>
<P>
   Now computers create the same worries. So it is only fair that
today, with the help of the Web, we investigate ways computers and
the Internet can help solve your automotive problems and worries.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that, for instance, you have a 1991 Ford Taurus that
makes a strange ker-plunka, ker-plunka sound when you attempt to
drive up an incline. You could drive it down to the dealership that
sold it to you (which isn't such a dumb idea), or you could try to
find out a little about the problem in advance (not so dumb
either). That way, even if it isn't something you can fix yourself,
you'll sound a bit more knowledgeable at the garage.
</P>
<P>
   There are several Web sites that offer advice and tips, but the
beauty of the Allexperts.com auto repair page is that you can ask
specific questions. If you go to the page at
http://www.allexperts.com/cars
</P>
<P>
   /repairs.shtml you'll be able to click on the model of car you
own and then send e-mail to an expert. Since this is a free service
and since the experts are all volunteers, it's a good starting
point. And there is a fairly straightforward description of each
expert's qualifications. That way, you'll have a fair idea of how
much faith to put in the advice you get.
</P>
<P>
   The Automobile Troubleshooter at
http://www.diadex.com/expert/auto/index.html isn't as personal as
our first site, but it is free and can be helpful. You start by
selecting the general type of automotive problem _ for instance,
whether the engine will start, or transmission problems.
</P>
<P>
   Then you'll be asked a series of questions. Each question
presumably narrows the list of probable problems. It's not the sort
of information that will offer you a sure-fire answer to your
problem, but it does do a good job of rounding up the logical
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Our next Web site is run by Tom and Ray Magliozzi (a.k.a ``Click
and Clack: The Tappet Brothers''). These are busy brothers. They
have a national radio show and also produce a syndicated column.
The Web site, at http://cartalk.cars.com/, has a lot of features,
including an archive of past columns.
</P>
<P>
   But let's talk about that ker-plunka, ker-plunka sound we
mentioned earlier. A lot of times novices tend to describe car
problems in terms of the noise they make. You may be surprised to
know that _ just as is true with a physician _ sounds are important
to a mechanic, too.
</P>
<P>
   This site offers you the opportunity at
http://cartalk.cars.com/About/Noises/ to actually listen to a
sampling of sound files and try to match them with what you're
hearing from your car. It's a novel approach to remote diagnostics,
and even if it doesn't work, you'll have fun trying.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you'll notice _ if you search the Web for automobile
advice sites _ that many of the places you find are commercial.
You'll pay (usually about $20) for advice by e-mail. Without ruling
on the merits of these sites (to really judge them fairly, you'd
have to submit a series of questions and then compare the results
with what a real-world mechanic would find), we'll just note that
if you are willing to pay for advice, a mechanic locally (even one
not as skilled) has a real advantage over distant experts, since he
or she can actually see and hear the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
