<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apple comeback stems from iMac
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Powered by a little computer that looks like an
iridescent gumdrop, Apple Computer continues to grow stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Its iMac computer was ranked No. 1 or 4, depending on what
survey you believe, in sales among all computers in the final three
months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That's one heck of an accomplishment for a company that had been
all but written off a year ago. Now listen to what top analysts are
saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question (Apple will be) a strong player,'' Stephen
Baker, a research analyst at PC Data, recently told online news
service ZDNet.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest industry survey, PC Data ranked the iMac as the
top seller among PCs in last year's fourth quarter. It said the
iMac accounted for 6.2 percent of volume sales and 7.2 percent of
the dollar amount.
</P>
<P>
   Since its August debut, the iMac has captured 6 percent of all
computer sales, according the PC Data survey. It has stayed among
the top five best-sellers since August. In the fiercely competitive
PC world, in which new models are continually introduced at lower
prices, few stay on top for long.
</P>
<P>
   The same may be happening with the iMac. While No. 1 through the
last three months of 1998, the iMac's position began eroding
sharply in December. It lost its first-place mantle to Compaq's
Presario models.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Apple has tried jazzing up the iMac,
announcing it will now come in five new iridescent colors.
</P>
<P>
   PC Data's survey ranked the iMac higher than other competing
surveys. ZD Market Intelligence, for example, ranked iMac the
fourth-best-selling PC.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two surveys is in what was counted.
ZD Market Intelligence counted only sales at retailers, such as
electronic superstores.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, PC Data counted both retail and mail-order sales.
</P>
<P>
   Mail-order sales are significant for the Mac. Mac enthusiasts
tend to be more sophisticated about computers than their PC
counterparts. Many know exactly what they want, shopping strictly
by price.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of prices, it is the one area in which most analysts
believe Apple remains vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Says ZD Market Intelligence analyst Matt Sargent, in an online
interview, ``To improve results in the retail stores, Apple needs
to continue to lower the prices of its systems to compete more
effectively against sub-$1,000 offerings from PC vendors.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
