</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODEMS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cable modem a marvel, but not a miracle
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The two little green lights shine unblinking, all
through the night.
</P>
<P>
   And all through the day, too. The connection stays constant,
from desktop to the Internet whether the computer is booted up,
shut down or just plain crashed. But get that computer running,
open your Netscape browser and you are on the Net with the promise
of stunningly fast surfing and blazing downloads.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cable modem.
</P>
<P>
   But is it everything you've wanted? You have to wonder, whether
you use the 'Net for business or entertainment, amusement or
commerce. Because you have heard the talk _ not to mention the
hype. Talk of broadband via cable modem or digital subscriber lines
from a phone company, billion-dollar deals involving Internet or
phone companies aiming to offer fancier content via zippier access.
</P>
<P>
   You have added interest if you have a dial-up service to the
'Net and been angered by frequent busy signals _ not to mention
aggravated by that annoying sound a modem makes dialing in to the
server. Or maybe you've had the connection broken a few times. Most
of all, you have perhaps been frustrated at how long it takes to
download files, to view video clips or graphics.
</P>
<P>
   If that is you, you are looking for a better way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is broadband,'' proclaims MediaOne. ``This is the way.''
So we took a look, hoping to answer _ at least partially _ some of
the questions that would be asked by any potential customer. For
instance: Just how fast is it?
</P>
<P>
   In theory, cable modems are more than 100 times faster than a
standard modem. A cable modem can handle more than 10 million bits
of information per second, vs. 28,800 bits for many modems and
56,000 bits for the fastest dial-up modems.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the number can be a lot lower for any method you
use to connect. MediaOne says you should expect no more than about
1.5 million bits per second from the cable modem, since
transmission speeds are dependent on a number of factors. If you
hit a clogged server or a congested line, it won't matter much that
you have lightning speed on the final leg of the trip, said Tom
Buttermore, MediaOne's director of high-speed data.
</P>
<P>
   Critics _ often folks from the phone companies _ argue that
cable modems are oversold, that cable doesn't have the reliability
of a phone line. Would you lose your 'Net link as often as your
cable television? What happens in a storm? Also, if all your
neighbors were to sign up for cable modems, it could affect the
speed. But cable companies shrug off that criticism, saying they
can install more equipment in the neighborhood to take care of it.
</P>
<P>
   During my most intensive downloading, I haven't seen the average
speed of my cable modem break past 100 kilobytes per second _
roughly 1 million bits of data _ based on the count on the bottom
bar of my browser. Not bad at all, but not radically better than
what I get at work through a T-1 line.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm not going to have a high-speed T-1 line at home, only a
dial-up modem. And the real story isn't the numbers _ it's the
time. If you compare it with ad nauseam waits for downloading, then
the cable modem is definitely a treat. When I downloaded a new
version of Netscape on my 28.8 modem, it took about 52 minutes. A
few months after, the cable modem was installed and I started
thinking about a Netscape upgrade. It took about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   I peeked at a trailer for the new ``Star Wars'' flick, a preview
file consisting of 969,000 bits of data. It took 2 minutes to
download and made me wish I'd gone to the Jedi academy.
</P>
<P>
   What is installation like?
</P>
<P>
   It isn't like a dial-up modem that you are expected to set up
yourself. And it isn't like a phone line that can be turned on by
the flick of a switch in some central office while you are out.
</P>
<P>
   Three trucks _ count 'em, three _ came to my house. Lines were
strung from the poles in the street, connected to the house and run
inside. A network interface card was popped into the computer and
some software configured.
</P>
<P>
   It took several hours. My presence was required.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I did order the complete package that included phone
service, along with cable television and the cable modem. That
clearly made the process more labor-intensive. (And as for the
MediaOne phone service, that's another story.)
</P>
<P>
   What's it like to use? What if there's trouble?
</P>
<P>
   The basics are a cinch. You are always connected, so you don't
need to either dial-up or wait for the connection. You launch the
browser, sit back a few seconds, and you are there.
</P>
<P>
   If there is trouble, MediaOne runs a technical support unit from
7 a.m. to midnight. The two times I needed them, they were patient
and helpful. I called once when I lost my connections and e-mail
after installing a new operating system on the Mac. The voice on
the other end was friendly, and her first question was about the
little green lights. ``Are they on?'' I assured her they were.
``Cool,'' she said, and walked me through a rewrite of my browser
settings. I was back in business in five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   What can you do with a cable modem that you couldn't do without
it?
</P>
<P>
   That could be the critical question. And the answer is less
dramatic than you'd think _ that is, if time means nothing to you.
After all, a dial-up modem can do the same things. But they do it
an awful lot more slowly than broadband.
</P>
<P>
   Do you want to watch a video clip, a 1.5 million-bit file? On a
standard modem, downloading that takes 6 minutes and change. Even
with a 56k modem, it's still at least 3 minutes. On the cable
modem, it should come in under 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Again, your mileage may vary _ remember that your connection
cannot help with congestion in a server in, say, Chicago. But in
most cases, broadband may not be the only way, but it sure is the
faster way.
</P>
<P>
   And some things that dial-up just can't do. For example, the
cable modem permits you to listen to ``streaming audio'' _ radio or
music _ while doing other work.
</P>
<P>
   The Net as a whole seems to be moving toward speed. Portal sites
are teaming with broadband providers to design content with high
speed in mind. Although analysts say the shift will take years, the
logic seems inexorable: Today's broadband experience will look
shabby compared to what's coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 56k-encoded video looks crummy on a 56k modem, and it looks
crummy on a cable modem, too,'' Buttermore said. ``But you are
starting to see more content for broadband.''
</P>
<P>
   So you just sit down that first day, turn on your Net radio and
start watching video clips?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. ``Streaming'' data that make up audio and video
require specialized software like RealPlayer or Shockwave. Some
cable companies will set up your computer with that software, known
as plug-ins. MediaOne offers the next best thing, a free and
convenient download of plug-ins from its home page.
</P>
<P>
   But it took me a while to realize that, since the company hadn't
mentioned it during the installation and I was too boneheaded to
investigate the home page. Instead, I floundered around a bit,
searching for the right software and tentatively downloading this
and that. So the service seems not yet pitched for the newbie who
wants to log on and instantly watch video. The assumption seems to
be that anyone getting a cable modem is savvy enough to get the
advantages without hand-holding _ not an accurate assessment in my
case.
</P>
<P>
   If you have never downloaded anything before, or if you expect
instant karma, you might get impatient. And it's not the download
time, but the hassle. But once you go through the drill with the
the plug-ins, you should be set.
</P>
<P>
   Is a cable modem worth the money?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that one you can only answer for yourself. But if you
mostly use the Net for e-mail, a cable modem will not radically
change your experience. You'll have mail a bit quicker; that's
about it. In general, there's a kind of sliding scale in which you
measure your need against the price. (Unless you are wealthy, in
which case, what are you waiting for?)
</P>
<P>
   Prices differ by company. MediaOne charges a one-time $100 fee
plus about $40 a month if you already have its cable television
service and $50 a month if you do not.
</P>
<P>
   So ask yourself where quick Internet access ranks against the
other telecommunications costs in your life.
</P>
<P>
   That $40 is a little above the average for what people pay for a
wireless phone and about twice the cost for local wired service. It
is about 50 percent higher than the basic bill for cable
television. It compares with $20 from many Internet service
providers for unlimited access to the Net via a dial-up modem.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the money, is there a downside?
</P>
<P>
   Sure. The worst thing about a cable modem is the higher
expectations. You think you will have instant access to whatever
you want on the Web _ you won't. You think your own computer's
foibles will disappear _ forget it. You think that software will
always behave _ ha!
</P>
<P>
   You will expect video to look like it does on television, but it
won't. Mostly the playbacks are on spaces about 1 inch square.
That's adequate for watching but a far cry from prime time TV.
</P>
<P>
   You will, in short, run into many problems that are beyond the
control of the cable modem. It's like having a six-lane driveway
that connects you to the interstate of the Internet. It won't keep
your car from breaking down, and it won't stop you from getting
trapped in congestion outside Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It's always on _ so what?
</P>
<P>
   The continual connect has its advantages, mostly the obvious
ones. No wait for the modem to dial and no busy signals when it
does. If you tend to jump on and off the Net during the day, having
a waiting link lets you shave a few minutes and some annoyance.
That alone may not be worth the $20 premium over a typical Internet
service provider.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe the whole package is. If you are running any kind of
business that uses the Net, the expense, if modest, and the
guarantee of access can be critical. If you are a consumer with
disposable income, what about the value of hassle-free connections
plus entertainment and news?
</P>
<P>
   After all, in recent weeks I have watched clips of ``The Thin
Red Line.'' I've listened to attorney Charles Ruff talk about the
Clinton impeachment trial on a desktop radio while I surfed
elsewhere. After some frustrating fiddling with the plug-in, I've
heard and saw Sheryl Crow and was convinced that every day is a
winding road.
</P>
<P>
   I have also struggled with temperamental software that has
repeatedly paralyzed my poor Macintosh. There has been torrential
rain, angry winds and several brief power failures.
</P>
<P>
   Through all that, those green lights have stayed on. So far.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
