<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 STEERING IN fILTHY WATERS  
 (For release Wednesday Feb. 3)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While I generally disapprove of cursing and refrain from doing
it unless sorely provoked by something like a television commercial
or a broken shoelace, I sympathize with the Michigan canoeist who
was ticketed for cursing after he fell out of his boat.
</P>
<P>
   According to a sheriff's deputy, Timothy Boomer, 24, unleashed a
three-minute tirade of undeleted expletives loud enough to be heard
by people a quarter-mile away, including a woman and her two small
children.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Boomer faces a maximum of 90 days in jail and a
$100 fine for violating an 1897 state law that prohibits cursing in
front of women and children.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union is trying to get the case
dismissed on the grounds that the old (and seldom enforced) law is
an unconstitutional violation of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   While the Associated Press story did not explain how or why
Boomer fell out of his canoe, a three-minute string of cursing
strikes me as an appropriate response to such a mishap.
</P>
<P>
   The tirade might be somewhat longer if an expensive camera fell
overboard, or somewhat shorter if all that got wet were some empty
beer cans and a half-full bag of stale potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   Canoes are notoriously hard to steer, especially if you try to
drink beer and eat stale potato chips while paddling.
</P>
<P>
   A canoe can sense when you're reaching for a beer or a
potato-chip bag and will instantly veer toward the nearest
half-submerged log or overhanging tree limbs dripping with
poisonous snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse is the fact that canoeing is often a
husband/wife-boyfriend/girlfriend undertaking, meaning that
emotions are usually frayed long before anyone steps in the boat.
</P>
<P>
   An ostensibly peaceful glide down the river can quickly turn
into the kind of domestic tragedy that makes the movie ``The
Shining'' seem like a romantic getaway.
</P>
<P>
   I recall a canoeing adventure some years back in which my wife
and I were accompanied by another married couple, Vicki and Dan.
Dan, being the more experienced canoeist, took the rear seat of the
canoe so that he could drink beer and eat potato chips unobserved
while his wife did all the paddling. Occasionally, Dan would pause
from eating and drinking long enough to bark some helpful canoeing
advice to the back of Vicki's head, such as ``The left the left the
left! Paddle on the left, dammit!''
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes of this, Vicki quit paddling altogether and
got into an animated discussion with Dan about where he might want
to stick his paddle, seeing as he wasn't using it anyway. This, of
course, was the signal to the canoe to veer sharply in the
direction of some low-hanging branches over which a long dark snake
about as big around as Mark McGwire's forearm was draped.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki turned around just in time to see the snake drop into the
canoe where her lap would have been had she not already departed
the canoe in a modified half-gainer, sending the camera, the
lantern, the tent, the food and, most tragically of all, the beer
into the river with her.
</P>
<P>
   As she floundered about in water that she (understandably)
thought was teeming with snakes sporting fangs the size of turkey
basters, Vicki commenced a barrage of profanity that far exceeded
the three-minute mark set by Timothy Boomer of Michigan, the
so-called ``cursing canoeist.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were any nearby mothers with children who were offended
by Vicki's tirade, they did not make their presence known. It's
possible that their ears melted or they spontaneously combusted,
it's really hard to say. Even the snake, which turned out to be
sized more along the lines of Calista Flockhart's pinky than Mark
McGwire's forearm, seemed stunned and embarrassed. I think if it
was capable of leaping back into the tree, it would have.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the snake and Vicki traded places and our canoeing
adventure resumed. Vicki dried off and calmed down and Dan even saw
fit to paddle some in order to catch up with the beer floating down
the river.
</P>
<P>
   That provoked some cussin', too, but nothing too outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
