<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     02-01 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT: THE SOAP OPERA THAT AMERICA WANTS CANCELED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The impeachment soap opera continued last week, with Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., whining about a U.S. Senate motion to dismiss the
articles of impeachment. House Judiciary Committee Chairman Hyde,
using a ``poor me, you've hurt my feelings'' voice, noted that he
had looked up ``dismiss'' in a thesaurus and found it meant
``disdain,'' ``reject'' and ``disregard.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow attorney Hyde missed the first listed synonym,
``acquit.'' Hyde was over-acting, which isn't necessarily a sin in
soap opera land, and over-reacting, which has become the meat and
gravy of political discourse nowadays. The Democrats' motion to
dismiss was voted down by the Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. House impeachment managers were wringing their hands
about the number of witnesses they wanted to parade before the
Senate, only to be spurned by the Senate leadership. The House
witness wish list was trimmed to three: Monica Lewinsky, Vernon
Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely they will only appear for depositions.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers seem to have forgotten that the Senate has
``the sole power to try all impeachments'' according to Article I,
Section 3, Clause 6 of the U.S. Constitution. ``Sole power'' means
precisely that. The phrase ``sole power'' is only used twice in the
Constitution, both in regard to impeachment. In other words, the
Senate can do what it pleases in an impeachment trial, no matter
what House managers think.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution grants the House of Representatives the ``sole
power of impeachment'' in Article I, Section 2, Clause 5 _ but it
does not give the House the authority to tell the Senate how to try
an impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the U.S. Supreme Court can interfere with that
authority. In the Judge Walter Nixon vs. U.S. (1993) case, a
majority of the Supreme Court concluded that whether an impeachment
process is proper or not is a political question that can only be
answered by the legislative branch of government. Chief Justice
William Rehnquist wrote for the majority that the Constitution
forbids the judiciary any authority to review impeachments and
impeachment trials.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is correct in describing impeachment as a
political process. This impeachment stinks of it.
</P>
<P>
   House managers and the Senate devotees of the radical right
became hysterical after President Clinton delivered his State of
the Union address on Jan. 19. It was presidential. It spoke to
issues that Americans have on their minds, avoided any mention of
impeachment and it was delivered with consummate skill.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment fanatics burned on their own pyres. Their screams of
outrage could be heard on TV sets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   This is one soap opera that Americans want canceled _ yesterday.
And they won't forget. They have seen the right-wing of the
Republican Party shamelessly drive the rest of their party over
this impeachment cliff, as if they were no more than a troop of
lemmings.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Senate and House leaders claim they are only carrying
out their constitutional duty _ continuing the farce by deposing
witnesses who have testified numerous times already _ as much as
they hate to do so. In light of the high court's 1993 decision,
however, the Senate can truncate the trial process anytime and in
any manner and still be fulfilling its constitutional duty. The
Constitution has very little to say about the process. It grants
the Senate authority to try impeachments, says senators must be
under oath or affirmation, tells who presides when a president is
impeached, and spells out the vote necessary to find a person
convicted of an article of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   That's it.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate could have dismissed the case after senators had
heard the articles of impeachment. It could have dismissed the case
after House managers defended the articles, or after White House
attorneys rebutted the charges.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP must appease the Pat Robertson, Gary Bauer, Pat
Buchanan and James Dobson wing of the party. They are not easily
appeased. They have been after Clinton's head since he was first
elected.
</P>
<P>
   They were dismayed by the nerve of American voters to elect a
Democrat as president. They were disgruntled by the polls that
showed two-thirds of the American public didn't want Clinton
impeached. And they deplore the fact that more than two-thirds of
Americans want the trial over and Clinton to remain in office. So
they shake their sage heads and wag their fingers at the loss of
purity and morality in our nation.
</P>
<P>
   These are the simple men. Complexity of the human spirit is
beyond their ken. They do not understand that a person may not be a
faithful spouse yet still be a rightfully acclaimed brain surgeon
or great leader. These are the simple men. They do not even
understand the complexities of human relationships and human
frailties, because they have not looked deeply into the dark
recesses of their own hearts.
</P>
<P>
   These are the simple men, the black-or-white men, the
self-righteous men. And the world is beyond them. But they had the
money and political clout to drag a proud political party into its
saddest hour.
</P>
<P>
   When this impeachment process has finally run its course, we may
find that it becomes a watershed for the Republican Party. The GOP
may be forced to shake off its self-righteous wing, or face the
consequences dealt out by voters who are tired of being preached at
by those they elect to grapple with real problems the nation faces.
</P>
<P>
   This impeachment isn't a morality play, it's a third-rate soap
opera.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
