<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6870 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIFORNIA-BUDGET-HNS     02-01 0202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA TO RECEIVE MILLIONS FOR MILITARY CONSTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon is seeking $296.8 million for new
military construction projects in California for the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1, according to the Clinton administration's budget
proposal released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The overall figure represents a $75.3 million increase over the
current year's military construction budget for the state. Only
Hawaii _ at $324.6 million _ would receive more military
construction money.
</P>
<P>
   The sum includes $58 million to replace 339 family housing units
at Edwards Air Force Base, Beale Air Force Base and Vandenburg Air
Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   Other California projects include $13.6 million to replace a
medical and dental clinic at Los Angeles Air Force Base, $21.5
million to upgrade bachelor enlisted quarters at the San Diego
Naval Hospital and $54.4 million for a berthing wharf at the Navy's
San Clemente facility.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's request must be reviewed and approved by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The total military construction budget for the new fiscal year
is $8.5 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
