<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS COULD USE COURSE ON JUDICIAL SYSTEM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Public opinion polls are more prevalent than
gushing noses during Austin's cedar fever season, and still another
survey was released last week.
</P>
<P>
   This one indicates that most Texans think highly of judges but _
as we already knew _ have some pretty strong doubts about
journalists, politicians, auto mechanics and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by the University of North Texas in
cooperation with the State Bar and the Texas Office of Court
Administration, is part of a campaign to boost the public image of
the courts and the legal profession.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, though, the poll will probably slam the door _ once
again _ on any legislative effort to replace Texas' money-driven,
partisan judicial election system, which many critics believe is a
blight on the courts, the legal profession and state government in
general.
</P>
<P>
   The poll shows that the vast majority of Texans _ 70 percent _
want to keep electing their judges. Only 20 percent favor the
alternative, promoted for years by would-be reformers, that judges
be appointed by the governor and keep their offices in periodic
retention elections.
</P>
<P>
   The finding, which reaffirms earlier, similar surveys, will
solidify some already pretty strong legislative opposition to
changing the judicial selection system.
</P>
<P>
   Several previous efforts have failed, and Gov. George W. Bush
also is a strong supporter of electing judges.
</P>
<P>
   The survey doesn't differentiate between partisan and
nonpartisan elections, which also have been suggested as a possible
reform, but that distinction won't matter in the legislative
debate.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also shows that most Texans believe there aren't enough
female and minority judges and most believe campaign contributions
influence courtroom decisions _ two problems often blamed on the
partisan election system _ but voters still want to elect judges.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Supreme Court Justice Greg Abbott _ who, like his
colleagues on the high court, has advocated an
appointment-retention system for selecting appellate judges _ said
the Legislature should scrap the elective system anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, he said, should ``take a leadership role and not just
follow polls.''
</P>
<P>
   More leaders, however, would be easier to find if the poll
weren't so lopsided.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott and the other Supreme Court justices, instead, can
console themselves with warm assurances that 71 percent of the
poll's respondents consider all judges honest and ethical and that
77 percent put members of the Supreme Court in that category.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if anyone thinks those high marks are inconsistent with
another finding in the same survey that 83 percent of Texans
believe that judges' decisions are influenced by campaign
contributions, I wouldn't argue.
</P>
<P>
   Several survey results, in fact, seem inconsistent. Or, perhaps,
they simply reflect a low level of public knowledge about what
lawyers and judges do.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Why do so many Texans consider judges honest and ethical but
only 40 percent, as the survey indicates, put lawyers, as a class,
in that category? Except for some justices of the peace, judges
were trained as lawyers and most practiced law before they assumed
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   As Walt Borges, a consumer watchdog, pointed out, ``People don't
change just because they put on a robe.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Many people have long considered lawyers a money-grubbing lot,
a perception that has been strengthened in recent years by civil
justice reformers' attacks on plaintiffs' lawyers and high legal
fees. But despite their opinions of lawyers' ethics, 77 percent of
the poll's respondents believed that lawyers are competent.
</P>
<P>
   _ While the vast majority of poll respondents had a high opinion
of judges' ethics, only 26 percent considered politicians ethical.
As long as judges are elected in Texas, however, they have to be
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   _ Half of the respondents thought that a criminal defendant has
to prove his or her innocence, despite Americans' long-standing
right to a presumption of innocence. The governor is right. There
have been too many social promotions in Texas' public schools.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, there is one other major inconsistency that wasn't
covered in the poll but is directly related to it. Although they
want to keep electing their state judges, the vast majority of
Texans, especially in the cities, don't have the slightest idea who
their judges are, much less how competent _ or ethical _ they are.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
