<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT PATIO NEEDS AIR, HEAT-TOLERANT PLANTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My open-air patio is 12 feet by 16 feet, has a concrete floor
with a drain, and narrow 11-inch flower beds surround three sides.
The north side is the back of my two-story home; the east is a
6-foot-high brick wall, and the south side is the brick wall of my
garage. The west side is also a bricked wall, but has no bed. The
only circulation comes from west-end doors to the garage and into
my townhome. During the summer the temperatures are unforgiving.
Most of it gets sun until midafternoon in the warm months.
</P>
<P>
   To date, only green and variegated airplane plants, Confederate
jasmine growing up the north wall and Carolina jessamine on the
south side have lived and actually thrived. Soil tests show the
soil contains an excess of phosphorus, which may be causing iron
and zinc deficiencies. I have been advised to avoid future
phosphorus applications and apply limestone and possibly iron and
zinc.
</P>
<P>
   Can I plant immediately after adding the minerals? Can you
recommend any flowering plants that would be candidates for these
conditions? When is the best time to prune the jasmine/jessamine?
The Confederates take over everything.
</P>
<P>
   A: If possible, use a fan to improve air circulation. The tall
ones found at hardware/home stores these days are fairly
attractive. It would make your time outdoors during hot weather
more enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   I like to wait a while after amending the soil before I plant.
Give the earth a little time to settle. It's true that our soils
often have an abundance of phosphorus, but without realizing that
this abundance is simply tied up in the soil, we add more to
encourage flowering plants to produce at maximum levels. Lime makes
a soil more alkaline; sulfur makes it more acidic. Some plants
prefer one over the other, but generally a neutral soil is good for
a wide range of plants.
</P>
<P>
   Given an organically enriched, well-draining soil and improved
air circulation, plants that usually tolerate summer temperatures
and at least a half day of sun include angelonia, a tender
perennial that produces a profusion of purple flowers; `David
Verity' cuphea, a dwarf cigar plant; mildew-resistant, mounding
Mexican zinnias (Zinnia linearis), available in crisp white or
tangerine; purple or pink globe amaranth (gomphrena);
butterfly-attracting pentas; portulaca; newer varie- ties of
periwinkle; and the tall, wispy spider flowers (Cleome).
</P>
<P>
   You can add interest with plants grown for their
colorful/textural foliage: `Solar Sunrise' coleus, the more
sun-tolerant caladiums and the many succulent sedums.
</P>
<P>
   I would consider adding a large container _ perhaps a cobalt
blue pot containing yellow bells (Tecoma stans), a prolific bloomer
that flowers from spring until frost.
</P>
<P>
   Prune your vines after they have bloomed. You can snip them back
during the growing season as well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Bradford pear in my front yard has roots that spread out
into the lawn and spoils the appearance. If I cut those roots, will
it kill the tree?
</P>
<P>
   A: You could remove a few minor roots over a period of time, and
with some trees, it is possible to remove one large root per year.
But I would suggest talking to an arborist before attempting to cut
anything major.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a corn stalk plant about 7 feet tall that I have had
for several years. I've kept it in the house under a skylight. For
the past month the bottom leaves turn brown and die. Every week I
cut those off. I usually water once a week. Any advice?
</P>
<P>
   A: When lower leaves darken and appear to be rotting,
overwatering is often the problem. If the lower leaves are drying
up, then it could be a matter of too much heat, too little light or
too little water. You'll need to do a cultural check.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that a tree stretching over the skylight has shed
leaves, therefore allowing in more sun and heat? Assuming the light
is still adequate after all these years, does the plant sit too
near a heat register?
</P>
<P>
   It seems weekly watering would be sufficient, especially in
winter, but if the temperature has been higher, then the soil may
be drying more quickly. Check soil moisture before watering next
week. If it is dry deep in the pot, water. But do not let the plant
sit in a saucer of drainage water for too long. If the soil is
moist just below the surface, hold off on watering.
</P>
<P>
   The corn plant likes high humidity. Increase, if necessary, by
standing the pot on pebbles in a tray of water. Your plant might
also benefit from repotting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
