<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6976 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOMMER-LEGACY-AZR &LR;      02-01 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOMMER-LEGACY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREDERICK SOMMER HAD HIS OWN FRAME OF REFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Frederick Sommer was a thin, frail man with an Old
World elegance who enjoyed mystifying his audience.
</P>
<P>
   The artist, who died last week at 93, lived down a narrow side
street in Prescott in a tiny wooden house he shared with his wife
of 70 years and the floor-to-ceiling shelves filled with his books.
</P>
<P>
   He would sit like a spindly Buddha in his corner chair and say
astonishing things:
</P>
<P>
   ``The unknown is the most friendly thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Or: ``Our fundamental empathy is to the structure that content
reveals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred was Prescott's own guru,'' recalls ``Arizona Republic''
</P>
<P>
   photographer Christine Keith, who was friends with Sommer. ``If
you felt like talking aesthetics, you could always go over and
knock on his door, and if you brought a pint of ice cream, he'd let
you in.''
</P>
<P>
   Weston Naef, who is curator of photography at the J. Paul Getty
Museum in Los Angeles, remembers meeting Sommer for the first time:
</P>
<P>
   ``I first met Sommer about 30 years ago at a gallery show in New
York. And my first impression _ I was a much younger man _ was that
he was a formidable and inscrutable person, whose own persona was
projected not only through his photographs, but also through a
stream of rather philosophical conversation that was not always
completely comprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``As 30 years passed, and we reunited to work on the show we
mounted at the Getty in 1994, my experience was 180 degrees from
the first meeting. Everything was totally comprehensible. Had the
passing of years made me a wiser person, or had he become a softer,
gentler, more communicative person? Probably both of those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Naef wound up negotiating the purchase of 100 of Sommer's prints
for his museum, making it the largest and most representative
collection of Sommer's art outside Sommer's Prescott home.
</P>
<P>
   And (begin ital) that (end ital) collection _ Sommer's own
prints, negatives and notebooks _ will now find its way to Tucson's
Center for Creative Photography as part of its Sommer archive.
</P>
<P>
   His photographs are spare and enigmatic, and although they are
printed with great beauty, the images themselves are as far from
pretty as Timbuktu is from Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his better known are of butchered chicken parts; dead,
skinned coyotes; and Arizona landscapes with no discernible subject
and no horizon. He has created photographic negatives from candle
soot deposited on glass, and reconstructed children's dolls out of
mismatched body parts.
</P>
<P>
   Sommer was a strict believer in high art. He was not a
pop-culture kind of guy. He was one of the last surviving members
of a group of photographers who strove in the first half of this
century to make photography accepted as a fine-art medium. His
friends and acquaintances included Edward Weston _ who stayed with
Sommer during Weston's famous Guggenheim trip in 1937 _ Alfred
Stieglitz and Paul Strand.
</P>
<P>
   But no one ever mistook Sommer for a warm and fuzzy type. He
developed something of a reputation as a recluse, living in
Prescott, far from the art world, and avoiding much human contact,
outside a close circle of friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost anybody who is sensitive and lives on a high level of
abstraction, like Fred, doesn't want to be bothered by curiosity
seekers,'' says Richard Landis, a Prescott artist and friend of
Sommer. ``He kept himself away from such people. But he had a guest
house there with several bedrooms right next door so that people he
wanted to see could visit. He was no hermit.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to anyone invited in, no one could be friendlier than
Sommer. He was solicitous and curious, and seemed to long for
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, such talk was never about who's-doing-what or
whatever-happened-to. It was always talk about ideas. Ideas were
more comfortable to Sommer than any easy chair.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why he has never been a popular artist. He
didn't photograph glorious landscapes, like Ansel Adams, or his dog
dressed up in a ball gown, like William Wegman. No, his art was
always about ideas, and those ideas were abstruse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He developed a personal vocabulary, like his `poetic logic,'
'' recalls Landis. ``It was strange. He would give a talk to a
visitor and he could baffle with his vocabulary. They could see the
enthusiasm and conviction, but couldn't quite tell what he meant.''
</P>
<P>
   But in part, that incomprehensibility was his means of
illustrating his central concern: the way the human mind creates
order and meaning from chaos. Humans cannot stand gibberish; they
look to discover what meaning might be hidden, creating metaphor
from rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of the world is complete, but our perception is
far from complete,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his best-known images, a blob of melted metal,
retrieved from a burned-out car, is superimposed on a Victorian
wood engraving to create a surreal Madonna and Child.
</P>
<P>
   The secret of this picture is that, although it is only a blob
of metal, we can't help but see it as a Madonna and Child. Our
brain forces us to make sense of what is essentially nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   That inbred rationality, which he called ``poetic logic,'' works
like a chemical agent on all the strange elements he chose to
present to us.
</P>
<P>
   For Sommer, what was most amazing wasn't the weirdness of the
human mind, but its orderliness. We will make sense, no matter what
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art is a pursuing of structure,'' he once said to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could take five pebbles, not necessarily pretty ones, just
ordinary pebbles, and toss them down and the way they land would
describe a structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Some pebbles would be closer to others, some farther away. The
artist must find the visual connections that tie the pebbles
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend my time connecting things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The richness is much greater than if you just have a few
pretty stones lying around.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you increase the number from five to 300 pebbles?
</P>
<P>
   ``The richness is even greater, more sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   So Sommer sought to bring together in his drawings and
photographs images that initially seem random.
</P>
<P>
   ``The structure of images is found in the arrangement of our
minds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This drive even shows in the ordering of photographs in the book
``Frederick Sommer: Images and Words,'' published in 1984 by the
Center for Creative Photography.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Solomon is the center's director of publications and
public information. She worked with Sommer on the book.
</P>
<P>
   They tried several ways of sequencing the images that covered
his life's work, looking at them chronologically and thematically,
but none of the sequences worked to Sommer's satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he dumped them all together and pulled them out at
random,'' and formed the sequence the book now has.
</P>
<P>
   Many who knew him had the experience of listening to Sommer
``skip read.'' It was an uncanny performance. Skip reading, which
Sommer invented, calls for the reader to run his finger down a
page, picking up words at random and forming new _ and wonderfully
poetic _ sentences from the fragments.
</P>
<P>
   If I skip read the beginning of this story, I might come up with
something like:
</P>
<P>
   ``Frederick died like a thing in the world who was felt for the
first time.''
</P>
<P>
   It creates poetry from prose, art from chaff.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, Sommer could pick a book and page at random and
spout what seemed like brilliant poetry. He would point out that
the poetry was entirely in the mind of the hearer.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of bright stones pebble the night sky and we make
constellations out of them. We structure the heavens with our
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a night sky shattered into shiny pinpoints, ancient
humans grouped them into comprehensible patterns _ constellations _
and created order where none existed.
</P>
<P>
   Sommer would scissor up the night sky and patch it together at
random so we might have the labor of reinventing the
constellations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complications of a work of art are not problems, but
riches,'' Sommer said.
</P>
<P>
   And he is now a star in one of those constellations. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
