<HEADLINE>
REEL ARIZONA PUTTING UP WITH TRASH TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Two cowboys talk about the devil in the Burt Lancaster
Western ``Ulzana's Raid.'' One explains, ``He said if he owned hell
and Arizona, he'd live in hell and rent out Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   That's only the beginning of what Hollywood pictures have to say
about Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Movie Manhattan is full of witty sophisticates loving and
losing, while cinematic Beverly Hills symbolizes shallow wealth
drowning in glitz. Arizona, meanwhile, has a bit of an identity
crisis, as far as filmmakers go:
</P>
<P>
   From ``Smoke Signals'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Mars, Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   What a young Native American (Adam Beach) calls the desert
outskirts of Phoenix when he has to walk through the desert.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Wedding Singer'':
</P>
<P>
   Adam Sandler explains how he knew his fiancee wasn't the right
one for him. ``We were flying to the Grand Canyon once, and I
hadn't been there and Linda had and you would think she'd have
given me the window seat. But she didn't. I don't know. It's a
little thing.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Jerry Maguire'':
</P>
<P>
   The Tom Cruise romancer contains two psychic plot points:
</P>
<P>
   1. The Arizona Cardinals make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   2. They beat the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   From ``My Fellow Americans'':
</P>
<P>
   James Garner, as an ex-president, discounts an attempt made on
his life in Arizona because the woman ``used a starter pistol.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``L.A. Confidential'':
</P>
<P>
   Kim Basinger plays a high-price call girl from Arizona who has a
pillow on her bed with a map of the state on it.
</P>
<P>
   Her dream: to make enough money to return to Bisbee, where she
grew up, and open a dress shop because ``the girls in Bisbee need a
little glamour.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Basinger says to a successful politician, ``Some men get
the world. Others get ex-hookers and a trip to Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we could make that our new state motto.
</P>
<P>
   From ``In the Company of Men'':
</P>
<P>
   A cruel business executive explains that when younger hotshots
take over the company, the losers will be sent into oblivion or, as
he puts it, ``the Phoenix office.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Nothing to Lose'':
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona sheriff searches for the bad guys, who are somewhere
out in the desert. He tells his deputy, ``If there's so much as a
sneeze out there, I want to feel the mist.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``That Old Feeling'':
</P>
<P>
   Old flame Dennis Farina disapproves of Bette Midler's flamboyant
new hairstyle, saying, ``Your hair looks perfect _ for a madam in a
saloon in Tucson.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Fools Rush In'':
</P>
<P>
   An Eastern WASP broiling in the Arizona summer says, ``White
people can melt out here.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``I'm Not Rappaport'':
</P>
<P>
   Oldsters Walter Matthau and Ossie Davis try to scare a NYC drug
dealer by telling him they're mob bosses from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Is that as tough as our hoods get? Mobsters with walkers?
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Truth About Cats and Dogs'':
</P>
<P>
   Janeane Garofalo and Uma Thurman test Ben Chaplin's romantic
affections by posing this dilemma to him: ``If you were stranded in
that bubble thing in Arizona, who would you take with you: ``Time''
magazine's Woman of the Year or ``Playboy's'' Playmate of the
Year?''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Practical Magic'':
</P>
<P>
   Aidan Quinn, playing a cop from Tucson, impresses Sandra
Bullock's daughters by fixing saguaro-shape pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Twilight'':
</P>
<P>
   Liev Schreiber, an ex-con who served time in a Yuma prison,
says, ``If you want to learn to kick ass, there's no better place
than Yuma.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Paulie'':
</P>
<P>
   In this kids' movie, a talking parrot explains that ``if you see
a sunrise at the Grand Canyon, it's like seeing the first sunrise
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Deep Impact'':
</P>
<P>
   This asteroid-hits-the-Earth thriller implies that Arizonans are
really bad drivers.
</P>
<P>
   In an early scene, an Arizona astronomer drives wildly down a
mountain road at night, while a nitwit Arizona truck driver drives
up the road.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man looks where he's going. They crash. The astronomer
dies. Oddly, the scene has absolutely nothing to do with the rest
of the movie. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
