<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7004 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     02-01 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DASTARDLY BUG DOWNSIDE OF DADHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When you're a parent, you often think not of what you
give to your child, but what your child gives back to you:
unconditional love, trust, a sense of purpose, and every kind of
disgusting-fluid, body-aching, night-sweat sickness you can think
of.
</P>
<P>
   That's something you don't learn when reading up in how-to
guides on birthing techniques and diaper changes and whatnot. You
won't find a chapter titled, ``A Guide to Sharing Illness, or, You
Get What They Get, Only Much Worse.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems as if the whole Valley has the flu lately. Of course,
not everyone is catching it from kids. Shake a hand, open a door,
stand too close to a stranger's sneeze, and the next thing you
know, you are lying on the couch, delirious from fever, convinced
you remember why you thought that buying a time share in Florida
was ever a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something particularly cruel about catching it from
your own child. So far, the worst thing your little treasure has
done was cry during church or soil a diaper when your mother-in-law
was holding her. Now she has inadvertently landed you one step away
from a croup tent.
</P>
<P>
   You can't hold it against her, of course, but at the same time,
you can't help but wonder how many more times she will hurt you in
one way or another, purposely or not. It's probably too great a
leap to go from her giving you a cold to imagining her dating a
juvenile delinquent with multiple body piercings just to drive you
crazy. But strong-enough cough medicine will do that. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deflating experience
</P>
<P>
   Of course, illness is no picnic for the kid, either. And you are
unselfish. No matter how crummy you feel, your first priority is
getting your child healthy again.
</P>
<P>
   A sick child is a sad thing indeed. Normally, my daughter spends
her time laughing, pulling hair and, if you get close enough,
biting your nose with a pair of surprisingly sharp teeth.
</P>
<P>
   But the first time she ran a high fever, she just sat there,
looking like a balloon someone had let most of the air out of. None
of the usual tricks worked _ tickling her bellybutton, making
squeaking noises, letting her play with Earl E. Bird (a
stuffed-animal favorite), nothing.
</P>
<P>
   We tried small doses of children's Tylenol _ normally the
impetus for a major battle. But not now. Listlessly, she swallowed
the medicine. She simply had no fight left in her. That deflated
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   We called the pediatrician, of course. If you are a first-time
parent, you call the pediatrician every time the baby cries, stops
crying, eats too little, eats too much, snores, laughs or does
anything other than lie quietly and look vaguely happy. Sometimes
then, too.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get the professional word that all you can really do is
wait it out (although a little bubble-gum-flavored medicine may be
involved), you begin to think about yourself. At some level, you
know that to care for your child properly, you need to feel better
yourself. &QL; 
No time for soaps
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet any attention you pay to your own illness is accompanied by
guilt. How dare you worry about your own health _ you've got a sick
kid to think about!
</P>
<P>
   It's a whole new lesson in selfless behavior. Alone, you would
call in sick, bury yourself under mounds of blankets and lie on the
couch, watching afternoon soaps while awash in a sea of
decongestants.
</P>
<P>
   But now there are diapers to be changed, bottles to be washed,
burps to be coaxed. You may feel like a truck has run over you, but
you no longer have time to worry about it. Self-pity isn't an
option when you're out of Wet Ones, no matter how bloated your head
may feel. Parenthood doesn't include sick days.
</P>
<P>
   A child's illness _ and the inevitability of your accompanying
one _ moves you beyond the isn't-she-cute, unqualified joy of
having a child to the down-and-dirty reminder that you have signed
on for the good times and the bad. You're part of something bigger
now; someone depends on you. For everything.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as everyone recovers, it's almost a little gift. No
one likes to be sick. But everyone likes to be needed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
