<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-VOTERS-BOS &LR;      02-01 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-VOTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA KILLING REIGNITES FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, South Africa _ In his youth, Sifiso Nkabinde wasn't
skillful on the soccer field. But his peers let him play anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came from a rich family, so he bought the ball,'' said
Matthew Ngubane, a former schoolmate. ``And he was kind of a
bully.''
</P>
<P>
   A rich bully he lived, a rich bully he died. Saturday, a week
after he was killed in a spray of automatic gunfire outside the
town grocery, Nkabinde _ revered populist and reviled warlord _ was
carried home in a golden casket.
</P>
<P>
   Throngs of chanting supporters lined the narrow country road as
the hearse arrived at his house. So, too, did scores of heavily
armed soldiers and police officers, there to keep the peace in a
town famous for political violence. Sunday his supporters buried
him.
</P>
<P>
   A charismatic and coercive leader, Nkabinde was a central figure
in the bloody internecine war between supporters of the African
National Congress and the Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom Party during
the late 1980s and early 1990s. And while that conflict settled
down after the 1994 elections, violence continued to follow
Nkabinde.
</P>
<P>
   His death last week left this small town tense and uncertain.
Many residents hope the killings _ 107 since 1997 _ will now taper
off. Others worry that Nkabinde's demise could rekindle interparty
violence ahead of national elections this year. Just hours after
his death, 11 people were gunned down in their home. Five of the
victims, all from one family, were buried Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The police and military, mounting a force of nearly 1,000, hope
to make it through this weekend of funerals without further
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ireland's Belfast, Richmond is divided between rival
factions. On one side of the divide, ANC supporters live in mud
huts and cinderblock houses. On the other side, in similar
structures, live backers of a fledgling opposition group called the
United Democratic Movement.
</P>
<P>
   That line between Ndaleni and Magoda townships is a stark legacy
of Nkabinde.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Magoda in 1961, Nkabinde grew up in a political
household. His father was a local Inkatha leader. At first Nkabinde
pursued a career in teaching, but by the mid-1980s, frustrated that
Inkatha leaders weren't serving the people, he entered politics.
</P>
<P>
   Nkabinde joined the ANC, received military training in its camps
in Angola, and returned to South Africa in 1989. He rose quickly
through the ranks, becoming the party's second in command _
according to some accounts _ by having his rivals eliminated. In
1995 he became the ANC's leader in the area.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, amid allegations that he had worked as a
spy for the police and Inkatha during the violent years before the
1994 elections, the ANC expelled Nkabinde.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter warlord took his supporters with him, and a line was
drawn between Migoda and Ndaleni.
</P>
<P>
   Nkabinde fell under serious scrutiny of the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission, the panel charged with investigating the
apartheid era. He was also charged with 16 counts of murder in
Richmond from the early 1990s. The case against him fell apart last
September, when witnesses failed to testify, and Nkabinda returned
to Richmond. Almost immediately, he found a political home in the
new UDM, which swelled with his supporters _ and almost
immediately, the killings started again in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday, a huge crowd chanted and danced on the Magoda
line as the violet hearse passed, carrying carried Nkabinde's
casket home.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred yards away, divided by massive military vehicles
and party affiliation, curious residents from Ndaleni watched from
the ANC side of the line. When the hearse rounded the corner, it
was escorted by 30 vehicles belonging to the police, the military,
and Nkabinde's private protection team.
</P>
<P>
   Nkabinde's supporters resent how the ANC treated him. They
reject the claim that he was a spy, and they say that he was the
only politician who looked out for the people. Many say that since
1994, the ruling ANC has not delivered water and electricity to
their township as quickly as it has to Ndaleni.
</P>
<P>
   The people in the crowd say they will never again support the
ANC. Their leader is gone, but not their fight. ``We are not afraid
of violence,'' one supporter said. ``Since we were young we have
had violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
