<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7012 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOODOO-FUNERAL-BOS &LR;      02-01 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOODOO-FUNERAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNERAL FOR THE `CHICKEN MAN': SHRUNKEN HEADS, INCENSE, JAZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Armed with a walking cane and bag of the magic
potion called gris gris, the ``Chicken Man'' haunted the streets of
the French Quarter for years, a penniless and gentle wraith. But he
got a princely send-off Saturday with a colorful, rare voodoo
funeral that attracted hundreds of spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rich man can have millions and a big funeral, but have no
friends and have nothing,'' declared Earl Bernhardt, a Bourbon
Street jazz impresario, during one of the eulogies. ``Chicken Man
had many friends. He died a rich man.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Chicken Man, whose name was Fred Staten, was so
poor that his body lay in limbo for more than a month following his
death at the age of 61 on Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Bernhardt, whose faltering nightclub had been blessed years ago
in a voodoo ritual led by the Chicken Man and grew into a
successful venture, paid for his cremation and last rites after
learning that his body was being shuttled between the coroner's
office and various funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a spectacle the Chicken Man _ who gained his
nickname because he used to bite the heads off chickens during
voodoo rituals _ would have loved.
</P>
<P>
   Throngs overflowed three adjoining chapels at the funeral home,
where the air was rich with incense. Two black voodoo priestesses
lectured, chanted, danced, and sang before an altar decorated with
shrunken heads and tiny skulls, while young white acolytes swayed
to a mystic beat. In a requiem for ``our beloved Chicken Man,'' a
priestess named Ava mixed soil and water for his eternal journey,
then added a dollop of his ``favorite dish'' from a bottle of gin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French Quarter was his church,'' said Ava, in a white
turban. ``He gave everything away to anybody,'' serving as a
minister to all, ``purple and green, straight and gay. Now the
Chicken Man is on the other side, he has become one of our
ancestors like Marie Laveau,'' the legendary ``Voodoo Queen'' of
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Another priestess named Miriam, also wearing a turban, along
with a robe festooned with plastic snakes, produced a fat, writhing
live serpent for a final dance before the remains of the Chicken
Man were borne off in a glass-cased hearse pulled by two white
horses.
</P>
<P>
   The cortege was accompanied by a mounted police escort, and a
jazz band and voodoo bongo drummers, including a figure in a long
black dress whose facial powder failed to hide his 5 o'clock
shadow. Hundreds marched and danced in the ``second line,'' which
traditionally follows the mourners at jazz funerals, as the
procession wound through the narrow streets where the Chicken Man
once roamed.
</P>
<P>
   With the first of the Mardi Gras parades beginning this weekend,
the final journey of the Chicken Man was an appropriate prelude to
the season of pagan festivals.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans' history of voodoo dates back more than two
centuries. The practice was imported by Haitian slaves who fused
Catholic symbols with rituals developed by their African ancestors
to communicate with the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Voodoo became widespread here, creating a bond between thousands
of oppressed blacks. According to Bethany Bultman's travel book,
``New Orleans,'' in 1782 ``the governor of Louisiana sought to
outlaw the practice of voodoo out of the fear that its evil forces
would serve as a rallying point for a slave uprising.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being stamped out, the spiritualism was raised to an
art form in the 19th century by Marie Laveau (1794-1881), whose
remains are enshrined in a crypt in St. Louis No. 1 Cemetery on the
edge of the French Quarter. Believers, as well as tourists, still
use stones to carve X marks on the face of her tomb.
</P>
<P>
   Since the city lies below sea level, bodies are put to rest
above ground. The tomb of former Mayor Dutch Morial, the father of
the present mayor, occupies a space next to Laveau. Several
cemeteries claim to contain the remains of the Voodoo Queen's
daughter, Marie II, who became a popular practitioner herself.
</P>
<P>
   Voodoo remains a genuine observance among cults who buy their
``potents'' from F &AMP; F Botanica on North Broad Street. The manager,
Felix Figueroa Jr., says the shop does not necessarily cater to the
voodoo trade, but adds, ``We carry spiritual and religious
products, candles, incense, statues, herbs. We've got everything
you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Voodoo assumes a phonier and more commercial form along Bourbon
Street, where several shops specialize in trinkets for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, crowds lined the sidewalks as the ashes of the Chicken
Man were noisily led down Bourbon Street and around the corner to
his resting place in a voodoo temple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
