<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER LESSON IN AU PAIR CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ We have been hearing a lot lately about the ``rule of
law,'' as if the law were immutable, exempt from the influence of
power and prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   We know better, of course. One of the dispiriting lessons at
century's end has been just how much class and race shape judicial
outcomes, or just how pliable the rule of law can be.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the disparate resolutions of similar cases in
Massachusetts courtrooms last week.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day that lawyers settled a civil lawsuit to prevent
Louise Woodward from profiting from the death of Matthew Eappen,
jurors convicted Luis Restrepo of killing his girlfriend's baby.
Beyond the coincidence of timing _ Restrepo was indicted in the
death of 9-month-old Tiffany Delgado on the same day 8-month-old
Matty Eappen suffered his fatal injuries _ these two Middlesex
County infanticide cases have proceeded as if in parallel
universes.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, the rule of law meant one thing for Louise, the
British au pair who killed the son of Newton doctors, and another
for Luis, the illegal Colombian immigrant who killed the daughter
of a Lowell mother on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Restrepo sat in jail for almost two years awaiting trial. Now
that the trial is over _ he was convicted of involuntary
manslaughter last Thursday _ he sits there still.
</P>
<P>
   How unlike the Woodward case. Found guilty of second-degree
murder by a jury, Louise saw a judge reduce her conviction to
manslaughter, set her sentence at the 279 days served, and release
her _ all in the course of a single day.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no such judicial sense of urgency, no compelling
desire for ``closure'' in the case of Luis Restrepo. He will not be
sentenced until Feb. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Why the long delay? Will it really take a month to prepare a
sentencing report on his immigration status, his third-grade
education? Or do those circumstances explain why Luis languishes in
jail while Louise studies law in England?
</P>
<P>
   At least Restrepo has had interesting company in recent days in
the Cambridge jail. In addition to the usual offenders and
defendants awaiting trial, Wilson Lee, a Chinatown restaurateur,
spent four days in a cell atop the county courthouse last week.
</P>
<P>
   His crime? Bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   His West Newton neighbors are offended by his unfinished
McMansion on Wykeham Road. The ``White Elephant'' and the ``Sugar
Cube,'' they call it. In their pique at Lee's lack of conformity
and lack of progress on his dream house, they pressured the city to
make the interloper complete his architectural curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   The white contemporary certainly stands in stark contrast to the
brick Tudors that line the street. The chain-link fence around the
work site does lack something in aesthetic appeal. But the city did
approve Lee's building plans. He does pay his property taxes. He
says he has spent $118,000 in the last six months to try to
complete work on the home for his wife and three sons.
</P>
<P>
   Did he get in over his head? Perhaps. Did he underestimate the
enmity of his conformist neighbors? Surely. But contrast the law's
treatment of Wilson Lee in Newton with the law's treatment of
absentee slumlords in Boston, where otherwise healthy neighborhoods
are blighted by abandoned buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Did Richard Campana of Wellesley go to jail to answer for his
rodent-infested property in the South End? Did Stainer Dewing of
Newton do time for a Jamaica Plain house targeted by vandals for a
decade? Was Edward Franco of Randolph jailed for abandoning his
buildings on Blue Hill Avenue?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the city last fall published photographs of their city
properties alongside pictures of their suburban homes in their
hometown papers. Two of the three are in the process of selling or
renovating their properties.
</P>
<P>
   In Newton, an unusual house gets you jailed. In Boston, an
abandoned building gets you embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Topazio, Lee's attorney, can only imagine what will
happen at his client's next court date on Feb. 10. Earl Howard,
Restrepo's lawyer, is no more certain what will happen on Feb 23.
He does know there will be no civil suit to stop Restrepo from
profiting from the death of Tiffany Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   The rule of law may be uncertain, but the rules of the
markeplace are not: Luis is not Louise; his is a story no one wants
to buy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
