<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINAL-MORSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SHIPS, END OF THE DOTTED (AND DASHED) LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ At midnight Sunday (Jan. 31) the most
evocative of maritime signals, SOS, went the way of the dodo and
the gramophone as Morse Code becomes officially obsolete after
serving mariners for a century.
</P>
<P>
   Under a world agreement forged by the United Nations, the famous
dot-and-dash code is done as an official channel of maritime
communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morse was the language of the sea when I first went to sea 41
years ago,'' said Captain Ronald W. Warwick, 58, skipper of the
Queen Elizabeth 2, legendary flagship of the Cunard Line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you hardly ever hear it. It's been overtaken by new
communications technology.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, nearly all of the world's tens of thousands of
oceangoing freighters, container vessels and passenger liners will
be required by international law to be equipped with high-tech
safety gear, known as the Global Maritime Distress and Safety
System, which automatically signals to rescue stations ashore when
a ship gets into serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The signals give the name and precise location of the vessel,
along with details of the emergency, such as shipboard fire,
explosion or collision. The system can be activated instantaneously
in a catastrophe and includes satellite positioning beacons that
float free from a sinking ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system should ensure that no ship in distress can vanish
without a trace, and that more lives can be saved,'' said William
A. O'Neil, secretary-general of the International Maritime
Organization, the London-based UN agency responsible for sea
safety.
</P>
<P>
   But there is concern that thousands of freighters and even
passenger ships belonging to companies based in the Third World
will ignore the new regulations, putting their crews and passengers
at huge risk in the years ahead as stations on land and the
dwindling numbers of radio officers at sea stop monitoring the old
emergency frequencies, even on busy shipping lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big change, and will have a major impact,'' said
Kathleen Fleming, a marine communications officer with the Rescue
Coordination Center in Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it's an improvement, but there is concern about the
fewer radio operators,'' she said. ``The real nightmare is there
may come a time when there is a ship in danger, going down, sending
out a `Mayday' or Morse on old radio equipment, and nobody is
listening on land or sea.''
</P>
<P>
   The old systems will not be phased out immediately by coast
guards and other rescue groups, however, and most modern skippers,
including Cunard's Warwick, see the new equipment as a leap
forward. Indeed, many top-line vessels, the QE2 among them,
switched to the global distress systems two or three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, old salts mourn the passing of a grand sea tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Morse Code and the radio officers who sent it saved a lot
of lives over the decades,'' said Warwick, whose father, William
Warwick, also served as captain of the QE2. ``But something better
has come along, and ships that use it will be safer.''
</P>
<P>
   That something better is not just the Maritime Distress System,
which bounces calls off satellites, but also advances in
communications technology that have made e-mail, faxes and
crystal-clear phone calls as commonplace on the bridge of a ship in
the most remote sea as in a business office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, given the speed of change, it's perhaps a bit of a
surprise that radio telegraphy has survived at sea as long as it
has,'' said Harrison Drown, a retired merchant marine officer in
Newfoundland. ``Kind of amazing, in the last days of the 20th
century, that there are ships still at sea that rely on the sure
hand of a Morse radio officer for all their communications.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Boy Scouts scrapped the Morse Code requirement in 1991
as an antiquated skill _ although a hugely popular feature on the
organization's web site allows visitors to translate their names or
short messages into Morse Code.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts-born inventor Samuel F. B. Morse sent his first
successful message, ``What hath God wrought,'' in 1844, in an era
when steamships were noisy novelties and treadle-powered sewing
machines the ultimate in high tech.
</P>
<P>
   The telegraph, dependent on cables, remained useless to vessels
at sea until near the end of the 19th century, when Guglielmo
Marconi devised the wireless telegraph, precursor to radio.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping history was made in March 1899 when an off-course
steamer, the Elbe, slammed into a lightship in the Strait of Dover,
off southeast England, and started to sink. Lifeboats were summoned
by wireless _ the first use of the device in sea rescue, according
to the International Maritime Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In the 100 years since, ships in trouble on the high seas have
relied on radio to call for help. According to the International
Maritime Organization, the signal SOS was adopted as the standard
distress signal a few months after the Titanic disaster of 1912, in
which more than 1,500 passengers and crew, of 2,200 aboard, lost
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular myth, SOS does not stand for ``Save Our
Ship,'' ``Save Our Souls,'' or ``Send Out Succor'' _ it stands for
nothing at all, but was adopted worldwide because it is so simple
to remember and send in Morse Code: dot-dot-dot dash-dash-dash
dot-dot-dot. The other international distress call, ``Mayday,''
used in voice radio communications, is a corruption of the French
``m'aider,'' or ``help me.''
</P>
<P>
   The new international maritime regulations require that all
freighters and passenger ships over 300 gross tonnage, and
operating on deep sea routes, be equipped with the new satellite
signaling systems and telecommunications equipment, starting
Monday. The rules do not apply to coastal vessels, most commercial
fishing craft or pleasure boats.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lloyd's Register, the London-based shipping
intelligence group, there are 56,359 vessels over 300 tons
worldwide. How many will comply with the newest law of the sea is
an open question.
</P>
<P>
   Other shipping sources estimated that a third of all ships,
especially those operated by companies in developing countries or
former Soviet Bloc, will ignore the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with officials of shipping organizations in the
United States, Canada, Britain and Singapore suggest that almost
all ships operated by North American and western European firms, as
well as companies based in advanced nations of Asia, have made the
switch to the advanced gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our members have installations aboard their ships,''
said Kathy Metcalf, director of maritime affairs for the
Washington-based Chamber of Shipping of America. ``But there is
concern that, globally, there are a lot of ships that aren't ready
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the new distress signaling devices, which cost
anywhere from $35,000 to $55,000, still have some bugs and quirks.
So even those who see the equipment as a major advance in rescue
technology raise some concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Odd things can happen,'' said Fleming. ``We've received alerts
that indicated a vessel in trouble'' in the North Atlantic ``that
turned out to be in the Black Sea or off the coast of Vietnam. But
these are oddities, and are a matter of making a link to the right
rescue coordination center.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, ships in trouble have relied on radio officers
signaling in Morse or by radiotelephone to reach other ships or a
radio station on shore. The nearest ships would respond, while
alerting the nearest rescue centers to send help. It could be a
haphazard affair _ not much different than the chaos and confusion
that surrounded the sinking of the Titanic _ with frantic calls for
help bouncing from one radio operator to the next. Rescuers were
often not in direct contact with the crew of the sinking or damaged
ship, and were forced to rely on third- or fourth-hand relayed
radio messages for sea coordinates.
</P>
<P>
   The UN-mandated global distress and monitoring systems not only
send an automated distress signal but also put endangered ships in
direct radio contact with the nearest rescue coordination centers,
whether Boston or Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The equipment has already been proven in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system gives us an instant lock on the ship, lets us know
where it is and what kind of trouble it's in,'' said Jack O'Dell, a
spokesman for the US Coast Guard. ``It takes more of the `search'
time out of search and rescue. And, in rescue operations, saved
time often means more saved lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Morse Code that has served ships for so long is
about to become the territory of ham radio enthusiasts and other
hobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professionally, Morse Code is finished,'' said Neal McEwen, a
historian of telegraph and radio in Dallas. ``But with tens of
thousands of hams out there talking from Japan to Russia to the
USA, it's going to remain very much a living language of the
airwaves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
