u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SITCOMS-2TAKES-BOS     02-01 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SITCOMS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV'S COURT JESTER IS IN TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ When it comes to situation comedies, Larry
Charles knows whereof he speaks, having won a pair of Emmys as a
writer on ``Seinfeld'' before going on to take the reins of ``Mad
About You'' as executive producer for two years.
</P>
<P>
   So what Charles has to say about television's signature genre is
worth heeding, especially since it seems to reflect a growing
consensus in Hollywood that the post-``Seinfeld'' era has been no
laughing matter for those who worry about the state of the sitcom
art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The form right now is in desperate need of re-inventing,''
Charles said. ``To some degree, you're seeing an exhaustion of the
sitcom formula. The audience is so knowledgeable of sitcom cliches
that they're ahead of the series. So they figure, why not watch
`Animal Planet'? It's more unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles's diagnosis was echoed by a striking number of TV comedy
stars and producers who expressed concern during interviews with
the Globe that the genre they work in is stagnating at precisely
the wrong time. They know that, in the words of ``Home
Improvement'' star Tim Allen, ``network television is especially
vulnerable'' because disenchanted viewers can disappear in a
channel-click to cable. Yet at this moment the sitcom, a primary
engine of network television ever since America decided that it
loved Lucy in the early 1950s, appears to be running out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: With the all-important February ratings sweeps period
slated to begin on Thursday, only six sitcoms rank among the 20
highest-rated shows, two fewer than last year and only half as many
as five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998-99 season has seen viewers continue to drift away from
comedies to TV newsmagazines and cheesy ``reality'' shows like
``When Good Pets Go Bad.'' Intensifying the exodus of viewers is
the loss of those twin tent poles of comedic brilliance,
``Seinfeld'' and ``The Larry Sanders Show,'' and the perception
that such reliable comedies as ``Frasier'' have sprung creative
leaks this season.
</P>
<P>
   So what's gone wrong with the once-beloved form, and what should
the next phase of sitcom evolution look like? Among people who live
by their wit _ acting in, writing, or producing TV comedy series _
a sense of urgency underlay the answers they offered.
</P>
<P>
   To Drew Carey, star of ``The Drew Carey Show,'' an ABC comedy
focusing on working-class life in Cleveland, the answer is simple:
Sitcoms must kick their addiction to stale, shopworn formulas _
especially the yuppies-in-Manhattan formula _ once and for all, and
break out in new thematic directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to write a sitcom now, do not make it about a
single woman working at a media company in New York,'' asserted
Carey. ``It just bugs me. There are plenty of cities in America:
Cleveland, Boston. You just have to get some other subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   But the success of Carey himself _ and of Tim Allen, Jerry
Seinfeld, and Roseanne _ has contributed to another one of the
genre's problems: an overreliance on shows that grow out of
stand-up comedians' acts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Diminishing returns
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once, shows like ``Roseanne'' energized the sitcom genre by
transferring the freewheeling personae developed onstage to the
half-hour television format. But the law of diminishing returns has
kicked in with a vengeance; more and more, something _ namely
laughter _ is lost in translation when stand-ups go sitcom. The
result is ``The Jeff Foxworthy Show'' and Carol Leifer's ``Alright
Already'' (both canceled).
</P>
<P>
   The problem could run deeper than TV's reliance in the past
decade on the same two formulas, however. It could simply be that
the sitcom form itself is getting played out after nearly 50 years.
Dean Valentine, president and CEO of the UPN network, believes the
ironic detachment favored by contemporary audiences has undercut
the popularity of sitcoms, which depend on both a cheerful
suspension of disbelief and on viewers embracing fictional
characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels fake before they even open their mouths,'' said
Valentine. ``Especially for young people, familiarity breeds
irony.'' Eighteen-year-old Marnette Patterson, who appeared in
``Something So Right'' and costars in the WB network's upcoming
``Movie Stars,'' agreed, saying the trouble with sitcoms is ``they
get a lot of older kids to play 15-year-olds with dialogue written
by 35-year-olds. They're just not funny. They try so hard to be
funny; that's what makes them so stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone believes that sitcoms have fallen on hard times.
Leslie Moonves, president of CBS Television, insisted that
``television, right now, show for show, is as good as it's ever
been.'' However, UPN's Valentine acknowledged that even some sitcom
writers in Hollywood believe the form is ``exhausted,'' having
``explored all the possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps not all. Many stars and executives, even those from
rival networks, say the way out of sitcom limbo lies along the
seriocomic path blazed by two ``dramadies'': ABC's ``Sports Night''
and Fox's ``Ally McBeal.'' Scott Sassa, the new president of NBC
Entertainment, went so far as to call ``Sports Night'' one of his
favorite shows.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
