<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7031 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GONE-BOS &LR;      02-01 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THIN ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WHILE I WAS GONE 
By Sue Miller. Knopf. 266 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the promises of middle-aged wisdom is that you will enjoy
the capacity to understand the idiocy of youth. For parents, this
hard-won insight holds a special kind of irony; still, nobody who
lives beyond the age of recklessness gets away unscathed. Jo
Becker, the protagonist whose moral reckoning is at the center of
Sue Miller's novel, has been doubly enlightened: She's the mother
of three just-grown daughters, and she managed to survive the
emotional and psychic bedlam of the 1960s. Having traded in the
confusion of her 20s (and of Cambridge, Mass. in 1968) for the
steadfast predictability of a reasoned, pastoral life, she's a fall
from grace waiting to happen. Jo's story relies upon the peculiar
blend of darkness and intuition that often belongs to Miller's
fiction, and when her past comes back to haunt her, it does so with
the eerie, long-fingered reach of history _ the sense that what you
did Wednesday will nearly always matter tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I Was Gone'' is a riveting novel, which isn't to say
that it's always a good one. It possesses the dramatic allure of
Miller's better work, ``The Good Mother'' and ``Family Pictures,''
and it showcases what is probably Miller's greatest asset: her
ability to construct a grainy, close-focus portrait of her
characters, both in relation to each other and in their interior
lives. But the road from here to there isn't always easy: awkwardly
conceived scenes, forced dialogue, indefensible comma splices
galore. For all her talents, Miller can be a leaden stylist, and
her shortcomings are actually unnerving in someone of such
emotional depth. That said, the cumulative force of events in
``While I Was Gone'' propels the novel to a convincing close. And
the story it tells _ one of moral consequence and the indelible
stamp of time _ grows deeper as it heads toward its inevitably
shadowy conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Now 52, Jo lives with her husband, Daniel, in a small town in
Western Massachusetts, the last of their girls having just flown
the nest for college. She's a veterinarian in Adams Mills, he's a
minister; together, they've probably treated most of the lost sheep
in their extended flock. It's the kind of life that seems enviably
rich and quiet from the outside: an old farmhouse with dogs at the
door and risotto in the kitchen, work that matters, a gentle
partner you can talk to (and go fishing with) for the rest of your
life. But the story opens with Jo's disconcerting moment of
near-prescient estrangement on an otherwise pristine afternoon, and
whether the storm clouds are actual or projected, her foreboding
makes the Beckers' shared life seem all the more precious.
</P>
<P>
   When a woman shows up at Jo's office a few days later with her
husband's dying dog, Jo realizes she knew the man 30 years ago _
they both lived in a group house in Cambridge, in the days when the
doors went unlocked and the strains of marijuana and bad guitar
went unchecked. His name, Eli Mayhew, is too distinctive to belong
to anybody else; so are his scientist's credentials, which in the
ensuing three decades have made him a renowned biochemist. Eli
himself returns to Jo's for the somber task of euthanizing his dog,
and the intensity of that encounter sets in motion a renewal of the
friendship _ and of the memories that made them both flee the scene
of what Eli remembers as ``a rotten decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the bucolic tints of Jo's present life, she had to
stumble around first to find her way; when she met Eli and the
other members of the Cambridge house, she was running away from a
naive (and short-lived) marriage to a medical student in
Philadelphia. She landed in Cambridge with a waitress job and a new
name, whimsically produced, she believed, as evidence of a new
life. Her strongest connection in the Cambridge house was to a
gorgeous, free-spirited young woman named Dana Jablonski _ Dana,
who loved Jo but didn't quite trust her, who seemed to love
everyone a little too desperately, and whom Jo found late one night
stabbed to death in the living room. The murder was never solved.
</P>
<P>
   Or forgotten, needless to say, though Jo has done a good enough
job of making it recede until Eli reappears. Now the link to her
past _ to the hope and chance of youth _ as well as to what was
probably the worst night of her life, Eli quickly becomes a
mesmerizing presence in Jo's otherwise ordered existence. What she
chooses to do with this specter of history will become the dance at
the center of ``While I Was Gone,'' both in its action and in its
thematic overtones. Risking everything for a nostalgic version of
what may never have been, Jo has to confront her own failings as
well as the fraudulent rewrites of history. It's hardly a pretty
story, but Jo's reliving of it affords her the chance to realize
that her current world is built on bedrock, rather than the smoke
and mirrors of memory.
</P>
<P>
   Through this prismatic reality Miller achieves a number of
lovely relational choreographies. With his gentle restraint and
abiding quiet, Daniel is in line for being the finest character in
the novel, as well as the finest man; the mother-daughter torments
and glories, particularly between Jo and her wild child, Cass, are
evocatively rendered. Few contemporary writers can be so fiercely
candid and acute as Miller about the emotional fear-rides of
parenting, or about the payback for living through it. And Daniel's
faith, while hardly contagious to his wife or daughters, provides a
semblance of sanity (and a moral reference point) within the realm
of private suffering that life often presents. These strands are
part of the design of Eli and Jo's reconnection, and they help
weave a resolution that, for all its sadness, is still testament to
the examined life.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes the clunkers of ``While I Was Gone'' that
much more incongruous. Several veterinary scenes seem more
dutifully researched than heartfelt; some of the dialogue wouldn't
make it through a Miller fiction class; and certainly the idea of a
``homicide department's cheerful office,'' gallows humor
notwithstanding, seems laughably oxymoronic. Jo's attraction to
Eli, however irrational or rooted in the past, happens with a mere
flick of punctuation. Such problems don't usually belong to a
writer of Miller's experience, and for that reason alone they feel
gratingly thoughtless, or at least ill-considered. Still, ``While I
Was Gone'' has an emotional resonance that grows on you, and that
outlives its more specific flaws. Youth itself may be wasted on the
young, but the harsh facts of moral redress _ the repercussions of
love and hate _ are something we usually get to live with the rest
of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
