<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-HEIR-BOS </SLUG>
  
 JORDANIAN HEIR BRINGS TALENTS TO DAUNTING TASK
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ After coming of age in the preppy environs of
Deerfield Academy in Western Massachusetts, he is now a commander
of an elite military unit who spends his free time online at an
Internet cafe, racing cars, parachuting and practicing Tae Kwando.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Crown Prince Abdullah, the oldest son of the ailing King
Hussein and the newly appointed heir to the throne of this desert
kingdom. He sounds straight out of Gentlemen's Quarterly magazine.
And even has the requisite snakeskin cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   It is not exactly the profile one would expect of a ruler of a
nation strategically poised between Iraq and Israel. So Abdullah,
who turned 37 Saturday, has a lot to prove as regional fears grow
about the stability of the Hashemite dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   He did not make a good first impression on Friday (Jan. 29),
palace sources say, when his poor command of classical Arabic
became evident in an address to the nation. A crisis looms in
neighboring Iraq, and Abdullah's experience in foreign policy
leaves him ill equipped if it should erupt soon, the sources add.
</P>
<P>
   As one former Jordanian prime minister put it, ``Let's just say
he is untested.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Abdullah will be an accidental king. As his
father's health deteriorated rapidly last week, the oldest son from
Hussein's second marriage was not viewed as a likely candidate for
successor.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Abdullah has had history thrust upon him, he brings
with him considerable strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``He represents a new generation of Jordan to be headed by a new
generation of Hashemites,'' said Sharif Fawaz Shalaf, a former
Jordanian ambassador to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As a young military commander destined to take over Jordan's
armed forces, Abdullah was in close personal contact with soldiers,
and therefore with all levels of Jordan's diverse society. He has a
deep understanding of the nation and a common touch that many
analysts compare to that of his father, according to one former
palace official. The vast majority of Jordan's 3.5 million people
are Palestinian Muslims from the West and East Bank of the Jordan
River. The rest are a mix of Arab and Bedouin Muslim tribes, Arab
Christians, and Circassians, who fled czarist Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah served with soldiers from all of these sectors,
especially the Bedouin tribesmen, who make up the heart of Jordan's
military. And they seem deeply loyal to him, gauging by the palace
reception he held in which thousands showed up to pay their
respects last week. His military experience also gave him the
opportunity to see how economic decisions made from inside the
palace directly affect soldiers' lives. It also gave him an
on-the-ground feeling for the daunting challenges that face him in
improving Jordan's flagging economy.
</P>
<P>
   For 34 years, the erudite and loyal younger brother of Hussein,
Prince Hassan, 51, was expected to take the crown. When rumors
surfaced two weeks ago that Hassan was out, palace watchers
believed 18-year-old Hamzah, eldest of Hussein's three children
with his fourth wife Queen Noor, would be made king.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah himself, insiders say, was surprised when he was made
heir to the throne just 12 hours before the king left for a
last-ditch effort to treat his lymphoma cancer. It seems the
decision came down to a matter of timing. Hussein's illness did not
give him enough time to make the constitutional changes needed for
Hamzah to succeed him. So he opted for Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   Fahed Fanek, one of Jordan's most influential commentators and
palace observers, said, ``He will rule very differently from his
father. . . . Jordan needs a king who will become more symbolic,
and less of a decision maker. The whole situation tells us that
Abdullah will help make the transition to a more democratic,
constitutional monarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Another important asset for Abdullah is his wife. In 1993, he
married Rania Yassin, a Jordanian of Palestinian origin. Her
potential reign as queen is warmly welcomed by Jordan's Palestinian
majority who believe it will keep Abdullah attuned to the ties that
link Jordanians and Palestinians in their dealings with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah and Rania have two children, a 4-year-old son, Hussein,
and a 2-year-old daughter, Iman. Abdullah, like his father, had a
reputation as a wild man, but he has toned down in recent years,
especially since his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah's mother, Toni Gardiner, was the daughter of a British
army officer working in Jordan. In 1960, she converted to Islam,
and became King Hussein's second wife. They were divorced in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah was sent off to boarding school in England at age 4.
But he spent most of his youth in the rolling hills of Western
Massachusetts, attending Eagle Brook Academy and then Deerfield
Academy. He graduated in the class of 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Deerfield instructor Charles Danielski taught the young prince
biology and describes him as an ``okay, but not spectacular''
student.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked hard, he was an enthusiastic kid,'' said Danielski.
</P>
<P>
   His American accent and his poor command of classical Arabic are
serious issues for the crown prince. A brief televised address
Friday to a meeting of Arab interior ministers was the first time
many Jordanians heard him speak.
</P>
<P>
   John Stobierski, a classmate who is now a lawyer in Greenfield,
played on the Deerfield football team with Abdullah. ``He was
small, but tough. Kind of a fireplug,'' says Stobierski.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his favorite pastimes was trying to lose the Secret
Service guys,'' says Stobierski, referring to the US agents who
shadowed him.
</P>
<P>
   After Deerfield, Abdullah, like his father, attended Britain's
Royal Military Academy at Sandhurst. Brief stints at Oxford and
Georgetown University followed, although he has no degree from
either.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of the crown prince has been met with some private
reservations by Jordan's palace watchers. But Stobierski said, ``I
think he'll surprise people. There's a lot of substance there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
