<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7042 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-ESSAY-REVIEW     02-01 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-ESSAY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER-EVALUATED ESSAYS: LOOKING FOR THE TIDY MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
By JANNY SCOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So it has come to this. The essay, the great literary art form
that Montaigne conceived and Virginia Woolf carried on, that the
writer Edward Hoagland likens to jazz or a butterfly's flight, has
sunk to a state where someone thinks it is a bright idea to ask a
computer if an essay is any good.
</P>
<P>
   The new computer, which is called e-rater (sort of like
In-Sink-Erator, the company that makes machines to grind up kitchen
garbage), will be used along with a trained human to grade the two
essay questions on the Graduate Management Admission Test taken by
200,000 business school applicants each year.
</P>
<P>
   E-rater's interest is not exactly that of Addison and Steele or
E.B. White. Humor is outside its jurisdiction, as are irony and
surprise. E-rater likes subordinate and complementary clauses and
words like ``however'' and ``therefore'' that some people think
suggest a tidy mind.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when essays were thought to be more than the
sum of their therefores. They were distinguished by their
originality, insight and personal voice, by their graceful style,
lack of affectation and willingness to meander. Instead of stomping
toward a conclusion, many never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   A genuine essay is ``the movement of a free mind at play,''
writes novelist and critic Cynthia Ozick; it is ``a stroll through
someone's mazy mind.'' The essayist is free ``to hop from thought
to thought, to begin with the finish and finish with the middle, or
to eschew beginning and end and keep only a middle.''
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, Samuel Johnson and other great essayists were
used as models to teach theme writing in schools. But in the
factory of freshman composition, the meaning of ``essay'' has
eroded to a point where it is almost equivalent to any old hunk of
prose. As a result, shortly after Robert Atwan started editing his
annual book series, ``The Best American Essays'' (Houghton
Mifflin), a dentist sent along an article on root canal that he had
published in a dental journal and said was the best essay he had
ever written.
</P>
<P>
   The telltale signs of a bad essay are at least as familiar as
the virtues of the great ones. There is the obligatory ``thesis
statement,'' Atwan says. Then come three paragraphs of exposition,
then a concluding paragraph summarizing the preceding three, along
with the phrase ``Thus we see that . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to forget the school essay before they can
write,'' said Ian Frazier, the writer. ``They have to forget `not
only but also' constructions. That's dead. Nobody wants to read
that, not even teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter the e-rater.
</P>
<P>
   The impulse behind e-rater was not, of course, doing Max
Beerbohm one better. The idea was to cut costs, among other things.
Instead of two people grading each essay, the Graduate Management
Admission Council, which administers the test, could have one
trained human and one machine.
</P>
<P>
   And what a machine! E-rater is ``the most highly developed,
holistic electronic writing assessment application to date,'' said
Frederic McHale of the admission council. It is a computer bulked
up on a high-protein diet of high-scoring answers to past
admission-test essay questions.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Burstein, a scientist at Educational Testing Service in
Princeton, N.J., who led the team that invented e-rater, says the
computer looks for what she called syntactic variety, such as
different kinds of clauses. It also looks for words associated with
organization of ideas, such as ``first,'' ``second'' and ``third.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not trained to score Montaigne,'' she said. ``It's not
designed to score creative writing and irony and metaphor and
poems. It's designed for a specific purpose, to score the kinds of
essays we see on standardized tests.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible (therefore!) to say how Montaigne might have
fared. He never did have to analyze the annual report of Olympic
Foods or agree or disagree with a statement like, ``Nations should
cooperate to develop regulations that limit children's access to
adult material on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Much business writing seems to aspire to little more than
lowest-common-denominator order and clarity. And, with home
computers already editing for gender neutrality and pointing out
when sentences exceed 31 words, why not let e-rater be the enforcer
of corporatese?
</P>
<P>
   ``For business letters, I think it's OK,'' Ms. Ozick conceded in
an interview. ``On the other hand, this is no way to teach somebody
to think. If an essay represents thinking at its purest and most
original, this is a terrible template to put over the human mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, however, said he understands the impulse. Strangers
keep cranking out manuscripts on computers and shipping them off to
him. ``It would be great if one machine wrote it and another
machine read it,'' he said, ``and we would all be free to go about
our business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7043 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUARD-BOSNIA-ART-2TAK     02-01 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUARD-BOSNIA-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE SWIRLS AROUND EX-SERB PRISON GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN AND STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Mass. _ A former guard at a notorious Bosnian Serb
prison camp has settled with his family in Everett, stirring
intense debate among Bosnian refugees over whether he was an
accomplice to ``ethnic cleansing'' or in fact used his position to
help victims of the slaughter in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   No evidence has surfaced that Jezdimir Topic, 56, participated
in atrocities that occurred at Trnopolje, one of three camps around
the city of Prijedor in northwestern Bosnia where thousands of
Muslims and Croats were raped, tortured, and executed during
systematic efforts by the Serbs to drive them from the region in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Topic's defenders acknowledge that he worked at the camp, armed
and in uniform. But they said he actually tried to help victims of
the Serbs and finally fled with his family because of the mass
killing.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that Topic had not disclosed his background as a
guard, the Immigration and Naturalization Service said after a
Globe inquiry that it would investigate his case.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Topic nor his family would be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Dragana Zubcevic, a family friend who escaped the Serb siege of
Sarajevo in 1992, said Topic and his family have been getting death
threats from other Bosnian refugees who, she said, have no evidence
but are looking for a villain.
</P>
<P>
   Zubcevic said Topic, whose wife is a Muslim, ran away from his
guard position after risking his life in attempts to save his
wife's family and other Muslim friends.
</P>
<P>
   However, three former prisoners at Trnopolje identified Topic as
a guard who offered no help to them, and they said they never saw
him help others. The former prisoners, each of whom had known Topic
for decades and confirmed his identity from a photo provided by the
Globe, said that rather than offering assistance, Topic refused
even to recognize them.
</P>
<P>
   Tesma Elezovic, 51, said she spotted Topic immediately in August
1992 when she and 30 other women were transferred to Trnopolje from
Omarska, another brutal camp run by the Serbs. She said Topic was
dressed in a Serb military uniform, carried an automatic rifle, and
was standing next to the camp commander, Slobodan Kurozovic, who
was later indicted on charges of committing atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked toward us and then he turned his back,'' said
Elezovic, who lives abroad but asked that her location not be
revealed. ``Then Slobodan told them to register us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jadranka Cigelj, an ethnic Croat who said she grew up on the
same street as Topic and has known him since she was 8, also said
Topic did nothing when he saw her, even though ``I looked like a
long stick with two eyes and some teeth at the top'' after losing
46 pounds in 54 days at Omarska. ``He pretended he didn't see me,''
she said bitterly during a telephone interview from Zagreb,
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners at Trnopolje slept outside or on a crowded
concrete floor in a converted elementary school. They ate
infrequently, they said, sometimes going days without meals while
under constant threat from Serb soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought he could just move away, move to Boston and come
away clean as a whistle,'' said Nusreta Sivac, 48, of Bosnia, who
also said she knew Topic long before the war. ``His attempt to run
away is not successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Farquharson, Boston district director of the INS, said
Topic's file contained no information indicating he had disclosed
his experience as a guard at Trnopolje before entering the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did not divulge'' such associations to immigration
officers overseas ``it would be a very serious, major consideration
in revoking his refugee status and resulting in his removal from
the United States,'' Farquharson said. ``If all of this is
verified, this gentleman is going to face the serious prospect of
having his refugee status revoked.''
</P>
<P>
   Topic is at least the second Serb to turn up in the United
States whose actions in the war have been called into question.
Last year, Nikola Vukovic, a former Bosnian Serb soldier charged
with frequently beating Muslim and Croat prisoners with metal
pipes, bats, and other objects, was discovered living in suburban
Atlanta, working for a company that makes compressors for air
conditioners and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Vukovic's alleged victims have sued him in US District
Court in Atlanta, accusing him of genocide, torture, and other
crimes against humanity. Vukovic has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Roberts, counsel for the San Francisco-based Center for
Justice and Accountability, which helped file the suit, said the
group has received unconfirmed reports of other Serbs living in the
United States who may have been involved in human rights abuses.
Serbs accused of having a role in so-called ``ethnic cleansing''
operations also have surfaced in Canada, Germany, Switzerland, and
Australia as part of the mass exodus of refugees that followed the
war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Topic and his wife, Muniba, who works for the International
Rescue Committee helping to resettle Bosnian refugees, live with
their two grown daughters in a neat, two-family house in Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Zubcevic, the family friend, said Topic's ``children shake every
time the telephone rings because callers say they will kill their
whole family. They question why his wife is working when he is a
murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like to talk about our past,'' Muniba Topic said in a
conversation on her front porch two weeks ago. ``Here we live, we
work, we enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
