<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERB-GUARD-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     02-01 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERB-GUARD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (a and i coding)  
 EVERETT, Mass.: ... enjoy it.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a reporter came to the side door recently after Topic was
observed on the street, the younger of his two grown daughters,
Arijana, answered. She said her father does not speak English and,
in any case, ``we don't want to discuss'' his role in the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Topic has been in Massachusetts since at least 1995, when he
obtained a driver's license. His presence in the Boston area
continues to be a matter of deep dispute within the 1,100-member
Bosnian refugee community in Massachusetts, among refugees
elsewhere, and among officials and advocates concerned with
immigration and human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   The camps at Trnopolje, Omarska, and Keraterm symbolized some of
the gravest abuses of a war that enveloped thousands of innocents
in its inhumanity and gore. According to indictments issued by the
International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia, the
camps were established for the specific purpose of killing Muslims
and Croats, or so frightening and abusing them that they would flee
the area around Prijedor. The Trnopolje camp was the largest of the
three, and was the one to which most women, children, and elderly
people were taken and confined with minimal shelter and inadequate
sanitation and food.
</P>
<P>
   Trnopolje ``served as the staging point for the mass deportation
of all those who survived the initial attacks and camp regime,''
tribunal investigators found in a genocide indictment issued
against a Serb leader in 1997. ``It also served a much more
sinister purpose: the sexual assault, rape, and torture of many of
the women detained there by camp personnel. . . . In many instances
the women and girls were taken from the camp and raped, tortured,
or sexually abused at other locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition, many prisoners both male and female were killed,
beaten, and otherwise physically and psychologically maltreated by
the camp personnel and other Serbs. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   One survivor of Trnopolje, who was in the camp from May to July
1992 and asked not to be identified, said 20 to 30 uniformed Serbs
normally were stationed there to control about 3,000 detainees. She
said that made it impossible for guards to be unaware of the
outrages that were being committed.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions were relatively better at Trnopolje than they had
been at Omarska, said Cigelj, who spent five days at Trnopolje in
August 1992. ``Trnopolje was a four-star hotel compared to Omarska,
even though people were constantly beaten,'' she said. ``Life was
worth nothing in either camp, absolutely nothing, but in terms of
gradations of horror, Omarska was worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Elezovic said that even though she lost 77 pounds at Omarska,
the Serbs gave her just one meal _ a watery soup flecked with meat
_ after she arrived at Trnopolje. She spent the rest of her stay
eating bread and a few pieces of macaroni given to her by other
prisoners who acquired the food when relatives were allowed to
bring it to them.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Topic initially were raised within the refugee
community about two years ago. Rita Kantarowski, director of the
office, said after the IRC became aware of the Topic issue ``we
followed it up with the community'' by holding a meeting at the
agency's office. The concerns raised ``did not have anything to do
with the person who works here,'' Muniba Topic, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kantarowski said some people at the community meeting said Topic
did help detainees in the camp, but she was unable to say whether
anyone who was not a family member gave such testimony. ``I am
satisfied with the research I have done . . . that there is no
basis'' for disputing his refugee status, Kantarowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Zubcevic said Topic told her that he would have gone ``crazy''
if he had remained at the camp, and fled because of the killing he
witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very good person,'' Zubcevic said. ``He cried once
when he explained how the Serbian army had killed women and kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But camp survivors and other critics said Topic is now making
excuses for his complicity in killings at the camp. They said that
Topic, then in his late 40s, was under no obligation to join the
military and they asserted he must have been fully aware of the
Serbs' grisly tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who are responsible because they committed
war crimes and there are those who are responsible because they did
nothing to prevent them,'' Cigelj said, adding that she believes
Topic was in the latter group. ``All those people who put on a
uniform are responsible for letting this type of political program
surface and flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Zakim, regional director of the Anti-Defamation League,
said it is important to learn the truth about Topic because
``identification and eventual prosecution sends a message to the
people who are there now that `you will be held accountable.' I
hope that would send a shiver down the spines of people who are
there committing atrocities today.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always have a ready excuse that they had no choice, or
that they tried to help,'' Zakim said. ``It's the oldest one in the
book. People who perpetuate atrocitiesz. . . often depend on the
apathy or silence of people who consider themselves mere
bystanders.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Cigelj said, some soldiers did help some prisoners, but
she said she never saw Topic do that.
</P>
<P>
   Sivac said that even soldiers who tortured prisoners were known
occasionally to perform acts of kindness. She said the deputy
commander at Omarska, who since has been indicted, once brought her
a small package of cigarettes and toiletries. ``That helped me,''
she said, ``but he was responsible for the death and torture of
hundreds of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigelj, a lawyer and political activist, said Topic's inaction
seemed worse considering she had known him most of her life. She
described Topic as a friendly, unassuming, slightly arrogant man
who went by his childhood nickname, Giga. He and his wife were
elementary school teachers before the war, she said, adding that
during their childhood, her family shared a home with the family of
Topic's best friend, so she saw Topic often.
</P>
<P>
   After identifying Topic through his photo last week, she said,
``I couldn't believe I would see the day when someone would send me
a photo of Giga and I would have to confirm that he was a person
who participated in something like this, where other people were
hurt. It's very difficult to face something that was part of your
childhood and then see it in this light.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Frank Phillips of the Globe staff contributed to this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
