<TEXT>
<P>
   Pope's Plea for Clemency Spares Prisoner's Life
</P>
<P>
   When the ailing Pope John Paul II briefly visited St. Louis on
his fifth U.S. trip, high on his agenda was to urge the nation's
often restless Roman Catholics to follow Vatican teaching more
closely. In a special plea, he called the death penalty ``cruel and
unnecessary,'' even for ``someone who has done great evil.'' And he
didn't balk at specifics, asking Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan to
spare the life of Darrell Mease, a triple murderer set to die Feb.
10.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, who has approved 26 executions in six years, commuted
Mease's sentence to life in prison. ``I was moved'' by the pope's
concern, Carnahan said, though he stayed firm in his support of
capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   NATO Issues Kosovo Threat
</P>
<P>
   The NATO alliance threatened warring Serbian and ethnic Albanian
forces in Kosovo with military action unless they agreed to a call
by the United States, Russia and four of the European allies for
peace talks on autonomy for the province.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said it was prepared to bomb Serb military targets and take
action against Kosovo Liberation Army rebels unless they began
peace talks near Paris by Feb. 6 and worked out an agreement within
seven days after that. France and Britain, which will lead the
talks, said they were willing to provide peacekeeping forces if
needed to reinforce a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CRAIG R. WHITNEY
</P>
<P>
   A Warning on Social Security
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to shore up Social Security is to use the
federal budget surpluses now anticipated by both parties. But
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned Congress and the
administration that the surpluses are not a sure thing. If
Washington really wants to be sure of putting the retirement system
on a sound footing, Greenspan said, it will probably have to do it
the old fashioned way, through politically painful tax increases
and benefit cuts.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   First U.S. Hand Transplant
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons in Louisville, Ky., performed the first hand transplant
in the United States, and the world's third. The recipient of the
donor hand was Matthew David Scott of Absecon, N.J., who lost his
own in a firecracker accident in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The rarity of hand transplants largely reflects an ethical
controversy over the benefits of a procedure that is not essential
to life and results in a lifelong need for anti-rejection drugs,
which can lead to infection and other illnesses. But if recipients
regain sufficient use of their new hands, such transplants might
become more common.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   Newswoman Wins Bias Case
</P>
<P>
   Janet Peckinpaugh, once the top-rated anchorwoman in
Connecticut, had set out to become an avenger for women denied the
chance to grow gray on the air. Instead, a federal jury in Hartford
found that the city's CBS station had let her go because of her sex
_ not her age _ and awarded her $8.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict resulted from the station's ritual pairing of a man
and a woman at the anchor desk, a practice as basic to local news
as zippy music and cheery banter. In 1994, Ms. Peckinpaugh's
station had a stable of three anchorwomen and two anchormen, and
wanted to cut that to two pairs. Witnesses said the women had to
audition, while the men had a free pass. Ms. Peckinpaugh, now 48,
became the odd anchor out.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MIKE ALLEN
</P>
<P>
   Introducing La Nina
</P>
<P>
   El Nino, the big pool of warm water that appears from time to
time in the tropical Pacific and disrupts weather patterns around
the world, became a household word a year ago. Its opposite number,
La Nina, which makes the tropical Pacific colder than normal, may
be less familiar but is solidly in place now, Federal scientists
say, altering atmospheric circulation in a different way than El
Nino did.
</P>
<P>
   Among the results, they say, have been record snows in Buffalo
and Chicago, record numbers of tornadoes in the nation's
midsection, all-time low temperatures in Indiana and Maine and an
extremely wet and unusually warm second half of January in New
York. La Nina is expected to stick around until May or June.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WILLIAM K. STEVENS
</P>
<P>
   Ford Buys Volvo Car Unit
</P>
<P>
   Henry Ford took pride in building Model T's that the common man
could afford. But the market for basic transportation is
increasingly unprofitable as manufacturers in places like South
Korea churn out lots of cheap cars. So Ford Motor Co. has announced
that it will also try to become a larger maker of luxury cars by
buying the car operations of Sweden's Volvo for $6.45 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said it would keep Volvo's research, design, management and
much of its manufacturing in Sweden, and would not change the cars.
Ford gives its luxury divisions a lot of independence. How many
Americans know that Ford has already bought Jaguar and Aston-Martin
in the last decade?
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEITH BRADSHER
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell Tax Case Reinstated
</P>
<P>
   When a federal judge threw out a tax fraud case last year
against Webster L. Hubbell, it was a signal defeat for Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr. The judge described Starr in terms that
delighted his enemies, calling him a runaway prosecutor. But there
was redemption for Starr when a divided appeals panel reinstated
the case, allowing him to continue his campaign to press Hubbell to
provide damaging information about his longtime friends, President
and Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   Good News for the Lazy
</P>
<P>
   Monday it's February. If traditional patterns hold, half the
people who resolved Jan. 1 to stick to an ambitious exercise regime
will have relapsed into guilt-encrusted sloth.
</P>
<P>
   But must it be all or nothing? Not at all, says a study in The
Journal of the American Medical Association. Everyday activities
like raking leaves or climbing stairs, it says, can do just as much
for heart and lung fitness _ if they're done long enough. In other
words, don't rush to quit the gym, but if you do, there are
moderate alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Cautioned on Iraq
</P>
<P>
   As the Security Council tried to decide how to keep Iraq from
re-arming with nuclear, biological or chemical weapons, the body
created to disarm the nation, the United Nations Special
Commission, delivered a lengthy report full of cautions about
taking Saddam Hussein at his word.
</P>
<P>
   Unscom's report detailed how over almost eight years Iraq has
consistently lied, changed stories, destroyed evidence and
obstructed inspections under a concealment policy written by top
officials. Russia, Iraq's strongest supporter, wants Unscom
abolished. The United States wants to preserve something akin to
the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Scandal Widens
</P>
<P>
   The fallout continued from the biggest corruption scandal in
Olympic history as the International Olympic Committee expelled six
members for receiving improper benefits in the bidding for the 2002
Winter Games in Salt Lake City. A seventh member resigned, another
was given a warning and three remained under investigation in the
scandal, which involved the receipt by some members of cash and
gifts totaling an estimated $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's executive board also recommended an overhaul of
the system of bidding on the Games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &QL; 
UNDATED: the Games. &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Growing Lexicon of Offense
</P>
<P>
   Another word died last week, said Sol Steinmetz, a New York
lexicographer.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was in an uproar about whether the new mayor was
right to accept the resignation of a white aide who had offended a
black colleague by using the word ``niggardly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Anthony Williams said the aide, David Howard, had used
poor judgment even though the word has no racial links; it comes
from a Scandinavian word for ``miserly,'' which predates the slur
it sounds like by several hundred years. (Now the mayor is in
trouble with some activists who, like Howard, are gay _ another
word that has been through some changes in recent years.)
</P>
<P>
   After the smoke clears, there will be agreement on one thing,
predicted Steinmetz: ``No one is going to risk using that word
now.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, linguists are finding an expanding list of benign words
shunned because they either sound offensive or might otherwise be
misconstrued.
</P>
<P>
   Chicanery _ deception by trickery, from the Old French chicaner,
to quibble _ is sometimes avoided as an affront to Hispanics
because it closely resembles the word chicano. Terms like queer the
deal, chink in the armor and nip in the air are also on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   Another phrase in full retreat is ``to call a spade a spade,''
first used by Plutarch and once synonymous with ``to call a bucket
a bucket'' _ meaning to call things by their true names or to be
straightforward to the point of rudeness.
</P>
<P>
   Not all misunderstandings involve such sensitive matters as race
or ethnicity, of course. And some perfectly innocuous-sounding
words have acquired a bad reputation unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Sheidlower, senior editor in the Random House reference
department, said ``picnic'' has recently come under suspicion
because of an untrue story that it refers to parties in the
countryside where black children were ``picked'' and assaulted.
(The known parentage of the word goes back to mid-18th-century
French pique-nique, but beyond that, its roots are unclear.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to accept the fact that some words are of
unknown origin,'' Sheidlower said. And that's how rumors about
words get started.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MELINDA HENNEBERGER
</P>
<P>
   With Sweets, It's Nurture, Not Nature
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, scientific studies have demonstrated what
everyone else has always known: Women love chocolate. In study
after study, women rate this most irresistible of sweets as their
No. 1 food craving. So intense is this peculiarly female devotion
that scientists have suggested a woman's burning desire for
chocolate might have a biological basis. Researchers have even
suggested that opiates or other chemicals in chocolate thought to
be capable of mimicking the brain chemistry of a person in love
might be what makes women reach for that extra truffle.
</P>
<P>
   But the days when science provided sweet comfort for female
chocolate addicts may have ended. According to a study to appear
later this year in the journal Appetite, researchers report that
not all women are so obsessed. Spanish women who crave sweets were
considerably less attached to chocolate and no more enthralled by
it than Spanish men.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that American women adore chocolate, researchers
suggest, is that people tend to crave and enjoy familiar foods.
American women, drowning in a chocolate-saturated culture, can't
help but learn their naughty little addiction.
</P>
<P>
   So why don't American men go wild for their Ghirardelli as well?
Researchers suggest that in a culture in which gals pop bonbons and
guys carve up steaks, chocolate, along with quiche, may be one of
those foods that real men just won't eat.
</P>
<P>
   This theory also suggests that women could, by repeated
exposure, teach themselves to crave other foods instead, like
sweetened rice cakes. Until researchers come up with a more
palatable hypothesis, women chocoholics will have to seek
reassurance elsewhere, possibly the nearest chocolate shop.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAROL KAESUK YOON
</P>
