</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-SECRECY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRECY IS A WORKING TOOL IN THE HANDS OF THE SENATE
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The cameras were yanked, the lights unplugged and
the doors slammed against the public and the press last week,
leaving the country's premier deliberative body to deliberate by
itself. The Senate had concluded that the only way to resolve
several thorny procedural issues surrounding President Clinton's
fate was to seal itself off.
</P>
<P>
   Though most Democrats voted to keep the sessions open, they
showed little outrage after they lost. And once the sessions began,
some of them dared to see some virtue in the closed-door process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with what Louis Brandeis said: `Sunlight is the
strongest disinfectant,''' said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. ``And
the public has a right to know about things as important as this.
On the other hand, the fact of the matter is when you close a
proceeding, you get more interactive dialogue because people are
just talking to one another, as opposed to talking to a much larger
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., was one of six Democrats who voted
with Republicans to close the discussion on whether to call
witnesses in the impeachment trial. ``Most proceedings ought to be
open,'' he said. ``But I felt there was a capacity in a closed
session for this particular issue to be more frankly discussed and
to become less polarized quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that when the Senate votes, perhaps in two
weeks, on whether to hold its final deliberations in secret,
Democrats will vote to close the doors. But it does recognize the
hazards of governing in the age of television: Politicians love the
camera, but alas, they say, they can't speak freely in front of it.
</P>
<P>
   This produced the conundrum last week of senators popping out of
their closed sessions to say that they were so statesmanlike inside
it was too bad the public couldn't see them. It seemed to matter
little that by the end of the week, whatever understanding had been
reached in private had vanished as a politically cleaved Senate
voted strictly along party lines to take videotaped depositions
from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate first convened in 1789, its members assumed that
they would conduct their business in private. The Continental
Congresses had been closed. The Constitutional Convention had the
windows nailed shut when it met in 1787.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure, the Senate gave way to public sessions; it
changed its rules in 1929 to make secret sessions the exception
rather than the rule. Since then, the Senate has conducted 45
secret sessions, most of them involving national security. The last
three were to discuss the procedures for Clinton's trial.
</P>
<P>
   The real action of governing takes place out of camera range
anyway. Spending bills are drafted in secret, proposals are floated
in private huddles, deals are hatched in hideaways. By the time
these items come up for a vote, most Senators have made up their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the year, the Senate chamber is a pretty lonely place,
with senators speechifying for the cameras and little real debate.
Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., one of only three Republicans who voted
to keep last week's sessions open, said the most amazing thing
about the sessions was not that they were closed but that all 100
senators attended. Normally when a senator speaks on the floor,
Specter said, ``it's like a tree falling in the forest.'' Closing
the doors, he said, forced the rare moment when ``all of your
colleagues are listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameras in the chambers only give the illusion of openness, says
Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School for
Communications at the University of Pennsylvania. ``We've created a
public arena in which we offer conclusions, but we don't show the
process of getting there,'' Ms. Jamieson said. The question is how
to create a public forum for thoughtful exchange, she said, in
which a politician would not be hurt politically for speaking
frankly, conceding points to opponents or mulling complex thoughts,
which senators say they can do behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Bound to secrecy on pain of expulsion, senators couldn't say
exactly what they had accomplished last week, but their
generalities demonstrated the gulf between private discourse and
public. ``There were some things that were said on both sides,''
noted Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., ``that you could not have said
if it was in front of the whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN chief executive Brian Lamb disagreed. ``It's a lot easier
for all of us to make decisions behind closed doors,'' he said,
``but I don't see any evidence that this is more efficient or
better. These are very talented, rough-and-tumble people who were
elected in a very open process out there. They ought to be able to
handle it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Senate meet in private, it did not even debate
why it should do so, sparing members the lasting televised images
of anyone on the floor arguing to exclude the public. This left
Lamb lamenting that the lockout had generated so little concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't care because they're sick to death of the
subject,'' he said. ``They're pounded to death with it every night.
They have heard every argument, watched every possible scenario.
You can see why people are starting to say we have too much
openness. But democracy was never a pretty picture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
