<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7050 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEARCH-FOR-TRUTH-BOS &LR;      02-01 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEARCH-FOR-TRUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HAS TRUST GONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The president, the national role model, is portrayed as a
lecherous liar. The Olympic Games, once held up as a paragon of
global harmony and promoter of world peace, are a cesspool of
corruption. In scholastic sports, where youngsters are supposed to
learn about winning with grace and losing with character, coaches
deflate the scores of blowout games they report to the local
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   What's a person to believe in?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a whole element of civil society that is based on
trust and the norms and values we develop from that,'' says Michael
Johnston, a political scientist at Colgate University. ``People
look at the president or the Olympics and project those values on
distant people and institutions. And when those values are under
assault, it can be a real crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   In times of crisis, we often turn to religion, and studies show
that people who attend church regularly are happier than those who
do not. But here, too, truth fails us: As it turns out, Americans
tend to lie about how often they go to church.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists C. Kirk Hadaway, Penny Marler, and Mark Chaves
found that many fewer Americans attend church weekly than the 40
percent figure that is commonly reported.``It is more like 22 or 23
percent, a little lower for Protestants and a little higher for
Catholics,'' says Hadaway, a sociologist with the United Church of
Christ. ``We found that most of the people misreporting their
attendance see themselves as weekly attenders, but with the
realities of life, competing things to do on Sunday, that it is
hard for people to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Some psychologists and social scientists think we are becoming
social hermits _ turning inward to family and friends for our main
source of inspiration, our balm for the daily wounds of the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a kind of retreat from a world that is hard to
understand, is not very friendly, is not very comfortable, but you
have to deal with from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.,'' says Boston College
Sociology Professor David Karp. ``People need comfort, they are
looking for places to find comfort and family and friends are
places where they get it.'' While family, certainly can, at times,
be hard to understand and uncomfortable, the movement inward, says
Karp, even has a name: cocooning.
</P>
<P>
   As defense mechanisms go, it isn't a bad one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strong connection between close, supportive
relationships and well-being,'' says David G. Myers, a professor of
psychology at Hope College in Holland, Mich., and author of ``The
Pursuit of Happiness: Who is Happy and Why.''
</P>
<P>
   The three things that are often considered to make people happy
are money, friends, and faith. But having lots of money, Myers
says, does not necessarily make one happier.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it can corrode a sense of values, according to Barry
Schwartz, a Swarthmore College professor of social theory and
author of ``The Costs of Living: How Market Freedom Erodes the Best
Things in Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems with the Olympics, Schwartz says, is that since the
1984 Los Angeles Games, which Peter Ueberroth turned into a cash
cow instead of money loser, there's been too much money at stake
for host cities. ``I have a feeling the International Olympic
Committee (which selects the host cities and some members of which
received bribes) was more negligent than avaricious. When there is
that much money floating around, it is impossible to resist, and I
think it is a wonderful example of how markets corrupt things that
we would otherwise value.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington these days, there is talk that a censure of
President Clinton for his sexual involvement with a White House
intern _ considered the likeliest outcome of his impeachment trial
in the US Senate _ could involve a hefty fine. That, says Schwartz,
``would be the worst possible lesson to teach.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, indeed for a year now, Clinton is being punished
with shame. He's being reminded over and over again: You ``
`cheated on your wife, you cheated with a child who worked for you,
you lied to your friends, family, under oath, and to the country.
You are beneath contempt and you are a disgrace and we will fine
you.' Shame is the most powerful of human emotions and it is hard
to imagine anyone being more shamed than Clinton. If you fine
someone, then the shame no longer counts,'' Schwartz says.
</P>
<P>
   It is the idea of a moral compass, a shared sense of what is
right, that helps us cope with the deceit that seems to be defining
the news these days. While religion can help, its reach is limited.
And that, Hadaway says, ``makes the family all that more important
and it also makes the individual and individualism more of a silent
feature of modern society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I am worried about some of these trends,'' Hadaway
says. ``It makes family more important but what are the
alternatives for faith development? You can log on to chat rooms,
the United Church of Christ has a Web site with a prayer chapel,
but those are supplements, not replacements.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been several studies regarding the fraying of
associational bonds, such as Harvard University professor of
international affairs Robert Putnam's 1995 paper titled ``Bowling
Alone.'' It argued that the general trend away from organized
social orgnizations _ like bowling leagues, which experienced a
precipitous drop while the number of people bowling (presumably
with family or friends) increased _ is a ``vanishing form of social
capital'' that made American democracy so strong.
</P>
<P>
   While Jean-Paul Sartre believed that ``hell is other people''
there are plenty of surveys that indicate having friends and being
married make people much happier.
</P>
<P>
   Personal relationships may be under siege from a lack of time,
and half of all marriages may end in divorce, but giving priority
to close relationships is one of the keys to happiness, says Myers.
``There are few better remedies for unhappiness than an intimate
friendship with someone who cares about you.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous studies indicate that married people are happier and
more satisfied with life, Myers says. For example, a National
Opinion Research Center survey between 1972 and 1994 found that 40
percent of married adults said they were ``very happy'' _ almost
double the percent of ``happy people'' who were never married.
</P>
<P>
   While some might argue that happier and more socially outgoing
people would be more likely to marry, Myers suggests the increased
happiness is primarily due to the beneficial effects of marriage _
``friendship sealed by commitment reduces loneliness and offers a
dependable lover and companion.''
</P>
<P>
   And where but family and friends are youngsters supposed to go
to learn the value of truth, when other traditional sources such as
teachers, coaches, even pastors, have sometimes revealed themselves
to be less-than-honest?
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the changed scores, ``It does not take an ethicist
to point out the dishonesty and lack of integrity in something like
that,'' said Nicholas Dixon, a professor of philosophy and sports
ethicist at Alma College, in Alma, Mich. ``If you can't trust the
score, what can you trust?''
</P>
<P>
   It is not a good thing, Johnston believes, that we are becoming
social hermits with ``half of our interaction with close friends
and family and half with unseen faces on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too early,'' Johnston said, ``to blow sirens and say `We
have a crisis.' But we should worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
