<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7057 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-01 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A REPUBLICAN RAILROAD WE'RE ALL RIDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One important lesson of the GOP-driven impeachment trial lies in
how Republicans have manipulated, if not dangerously undermined,
the democratic process as they make their reckless assault against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   All their rhetoric about following the ``rule of law'' and
``doing our constitutional duty'' is nothing more than a
hypocritical attempt to use their numeric superiority to remove, if
not destroy, a Democratic president duly elected by the people, of
the people, and for the people.
</P>
<P>
   There is no other way to explain last week's party-line vote
against dismissal of the impeachment charges against Clinton. And
there is no other explanation for how the same partisan vote
occurred on the motion to depose three witnesses: Monica Lewinksy,
Vernon Jordan, and Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties know that right now Republicans have the votes,
thus the power, to approve or defeat any motion, except the one
that counts: to remove Clinton from office. The votes of 56 to 44
against dismissal of the charges, and the vote of 56 to 44 for
deposing three witnesses make it clear that the GOP does not have a
two-thirds majority vote for conviction. That is why the GOP
members of the House and Senate are doing virtually all they can to
achieve their purpose in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate Republicans are hoping that deposing Lewinsky,
Jordan, and Blumethal will result in some explosive new disclosure
that will reverse the public's support of Clinton and give
justification to their removal efforts.
</P>
<P>
   While their chances are less than slim for such a disclosure,
Republicans feel they have nothing to lose with their desperate
attempt to get their witnesses to say something _ anything _ that
lends credibility to their political quest to remove Clinton or
force him to resign. Barring that, they hope to pile on enough
embarrassment so that his eight-year presidency is marked in
history by shame, not achievement.
</P>
<P>
   But the most notable aspect of this impeachment trial is not the
GOP's use of its numeric power against a president they couldn't
defeat at the voting booth. It's the Democratic senators', and the
electorate's, inability to stop or neutralize the Republicans'
assault.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Senate Democrats may be unable to stop the GOP
from approving a motion that would taint Clinton forever, despite
the expected acquittal vote in the Senate. This motion _ called a
``finding of fact'' but really a conviction without removal _
requires only a simple majority vote, which the GOP has.
</P>
<P>
   This move amounts to an underhanded attempt by Republicans to
skirt the Founding Fathers' constitutional requirement for a
two-thirds vote for conviction. If they are successful, Clinton
will forever be labeled a convicted criminal _ even as he continues
in office _ making unnecessary the original GOP goal of removing
him.
</P>
<P>
   After all, having a president convicted of criminal charges
remain in office is almost as humiliating as having him convicted
and removed from office. Either way, the Republicans get what they
want; Clinton goes down in history as a tainted president for lying
about his sex life with Monica Lewinsky _ regardless of the fact
that this adulterous affair posed no threat to the Constitution or
to America, and thus falls short of true grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for the Democrats, and the electorate, to stop the
GOP's blatant attempt to exploit three thoroughly questioned
witnesses in the hope that at least one will help legitimize their
planned partisan vote on a ``finding of fact'' against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While the Democrats and the electorate may seem powerless to
stop the GOP, that can change. Since Republicans have made a sham
of the impeachment process, Democrats are justified in going beyond
their verbal protest to a visible, unified, dramatic statement that
would expose this process as the one-sided GOP sideshow it is.
</P>
<P>
   In such a statement, Democrats could say that they will not
participate in any further GOP shams, such as voting on a ``finding
of fact'' that would allow the GOP to label Clinton a ``criminal''
before the actual impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats could further state that the only vote in which
they will participate will be the vote on impeachment. The outcome
of the vote, as the GOP well knows, will be acquittal. Even a few
GOP members are likely to join the Democratic vote against
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   While a censure vote after the acquittal is still likely, it
would be entirely appropriate for the Democrats to argue that the
GOP lost its opportunity for such a vote when it pushed for a
politically-motivated ``finding of fact.'' Then they could simply
walk out of the chamber, leaving Republicans with a meaningless,
one-sided vote on censure.
</P>
<P>
   And that would be an appropriate ending for an entirely
inappropriate, reckless, partisan assault that was more threatening
to democracy and the Constitution than anything that happened
between Clinton and Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
