A7063 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      02-01 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Jan. 31, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-IDENTITY-REVIEW (Washington) _ For a generation,
Republicans have represented resurgent American conservatism. But
now, with the budget balanced and significant reductions in crime,
welfare, divorce and single motherhood, Republicans find themselves
defined by impeachment and their argument that President Clinton
represents a nation in moral decline. They are also finding that
Americans are leery of a party that appears to be pressing for
moral cleansing. By Richard L Berke. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-CONSERVATIVES-REVIEW (Berlin) _ If the late '90s have
produced a dirty word in Europe, it is perhaps `conservative.' The
right-of-center ideology that played an important role in
privatization, advancing the market economy and facing down the
Soviet Union has fizzled. At the beginning of the decade,
conservatives were in charge or on the rise nearly everywhere in
Europe, but today there is not a single major country where that is
true. By Roger Cohen. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   ZERO-TOLERANCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Zero-tolerance'' policies of
seizing cars, boats and other property of persons suspected but not
convicted of drug trafficking or other offenses pleased
criminal-justice conservatives, but enraged scores of motorists,
boat owners, civil libertarians and policy analysts. Critics
complained that draconian steps tie up enforcement personnel better
deployed elsewhere, swamp overburdened administrative systems and
worse, provide little if any deterrence. By David Johnston. (`a'
category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-RITUALS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Although resisting major
change, the Catholic Church has been enacting lesser changes in
ritual and practice designed to render ancient religious customs
compatible with the spirit of the times. In much of this, experts
say, the Vatican struggles to take into account the sensibilities
and convictions of a widely varying membership in broadly differing
societies. A recent statement on exorcism is an example. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   DISEASE-CLUSTERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Disease clusters are
concentrated areas in which an unusually high percentage of people
succumb to some type of illness, possibly caused by local
environmental conditions. Every time a disease cluster turns up,
communities worry, scientists scramble for a cause and, as in ``A
Civil Action'' lawyers start suing. Yet over and over again,
despite years _ sometimes decades _ of efforts to link the disease
with a cause, scientists usually come up empty-handed. By Gina
Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-DEBT-REVIEW (Washington) _ The end of the annual budget
deficit is hardly the end of the government's financial troubles,
and it marks the beginning of a new debate over how fiscal policy
should be used to shape the nation's future. The cumulative the
national debt built up over decades of deficit spending remains an
economic millstone of considerable proportions. And only now do
Congress and the White House have the luxury of debating what to do
about it. By Richard W. Stevenson. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   EARTHQUAKE-HOUSES-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Americans viewing the
devastation caused by the earthquake in Colombia might be tempted
to knock on wood. Wood-frame houses, the type generally built in
the United States, can stand up far better in quakes than the
outwardly solid masonry homes that crumpled so quickly in Colombia.
By Andrew Pollack
</P>
<P>
   SEX-MUTANTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Evolutionary biologists have long
wondered why sexual reproduction took precedence over asexual
reproduction. Now, a new report shows there is indeed a purpose to
sex: to sweep away the bad mutations that would otherwise drag us
toward terminal degeneracy. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-SECRECY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Much of the Senate debate
during the impeachment trial has been over to the degree to which
the proceedings should be conducted publicly or in closed session.
A look at the background of Senate secrecy and openness. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-ESSAY-REVIEW (Undated) _ So it has come to this. The
essay, that great literary art form, has fallen to a state where
someone thinks it is a swell idea to ask a computer if an essay is
any good. The new computer, which is called e-rater, will be used
along with a trained human to grade the two essay questions on the
Graduate Management Admission Test taken by 200,000 business-school
applicants each year. By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   SOVIET-ESPIONAGE-REVIEW (Washington) _ A new book, `The Haunted
Wood: Soviet Espionage in America _ The Stalin Era,' offers a new
look at what communist spies were really up to in this country
before and during World War II. It is a staggering account of
sloppiness and stupidity among the Soviets and their American
agents. And it underscores how much the most powerful people in
Washington freely gave Moscow when faced with a common enemy in
wartime. On balance, it appears that Moscow gained more from its
open alliances with the United States than from its secret American
underground. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HUSSEIN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Shakespeare showed royalty to
be larger than life, but in the end very human. Now, from the
Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan, comes evidence to support that
portrayal: a most extraordinary document in the voice of a
modern-day king struggling with his own mortality as he grapples
with issues that were the stuff of the 16th century.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
