<SLUG> BC-URBAN-SPRAWL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE SPRAWL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Battling sprawl has suddenly crystalized as a major quest of the
nation's public life _ but, typically, with almost all of the
attention focused on the easy half of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, states and communities are busy enacting
more than 110 anti-sprawl ballot questions such as big land buys
and growth curbs that passed in November; some 200 measures _ a
record _ were on ballots nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has made attacking land-gobbling growth
and the strip-malling of America a key theme of his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, the regional Environmental Protection Agency
office is convening a big-name ``Smart Growth Strategies for New
England'' summit in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But while ideas abound for stopping future sprawl through land
protection, zoning, transit, and architectural innovations,
planners and environmentalists are generally hard-pressed to figure
out how to fix the vast swaths of sprawl that already plague the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   From southern New Hampshire to Massachusetts' Route 9, and
throughout virtually every metropolitan area from New Jersey to
Atlanta to California, the landscape has filled up with six-lane
fast-food strips, big-box stores in asphalt lakes, and archipelago
subdivisions where you need a car just to buy milk or mail a
letter.
</P>
<P>
   While this region has fared far better than almost anywhere else
in resisting the trend, former Massachusetts environmental affairs
secretary Trudy Coxe declared last year that ``sprawl is the single
most important environmental issue facing any of us in New England
today.''
</P>
<P>
   So what, exactly, qualifies as sprawl? Richard Moe of the
National Trust for Historic Preservation has offered this widely
accepted definition: ``Low-density development on the edge of
cities and towns, poorly planned, land-consumptive, auto-dependent,
and designed without respect to its surroundings.''
</P>
<P>
   A broad national consensus is emerging that many of us hate
living this way and we want to save what remains of the country
from following suit. But given that so much sprawl is already with
us, is there any hope for retrofitting livable, walkable, pleasant
communities?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult, but not impossible, to do,'' says state
Representative John H. Stasik, a Framingham Democrat who formerly
chaired the town's planning board. ``Once you've built your
Levittown, your 40-foot-wide-roads that just crawl on forever, it's
tough to go back and plant the trees and add the sidewalks. But it
doesn't mean you can't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Morrish of the Design Center for the American Urban
Landscape, based at the University of Minnesota, admits that as a
profession, planners have a far better handle on reviving downtowns
and saving pastoral landscapes than fixing what lies in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today it's all about the edge and the center, because the
middle isn't recognized as being on fire,'' Morrish says. ``It's
more complex there, and we don't have any simple answers.''
</P>
<P>
   All that said, there are a handful of examples of efforts around
the country that could guide a sorely needed national discussion of
how to improve the sprawly environments that already dominate so
many communities. Some approaches include:
</P>
<P>
   --Manufacture a downtown. Several communities whose post-World
War II growth was driven largely by malls and automobiles have
decided to create village centers, including Schaumburg, Ill.,
northwest of Chicago, Warren Township, N.J., and the Atlanta suburb
of Smyrna.
</P>
<P>
   Shaumburg has spent more than $8 million amassing the 31-acre
town square site, a former strip-mall eyesore, and highlighted it
with a six-story clock tower. It has has attracted the Chicago
area's second largest public library and plans for 16 stores as
well as busy civic-event schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Smyrna, whose small downtown had been sliced in half to widen
the main drag between Atlanta and Marietta, has won national awards
for its made-from-scratch downtown. It features a city hall,
library, police station, and stores surrounding a brick town square
_ and, notably, 22 Back Bay-style homes on alleyways that sold out
in three months.
</P>
<P>
   But in Massachusetts and other states, existing zoning codes
often bizarrely forbid or at best complicate efforts to allow the
typical 19th-century village landscape so many people want, with
municipal buildings, churches, stores, and homes sitting
cheek-by-jowl.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, these efforts can result in artificial downtowns,
places like Mashpee Commons on Cape Cod or Reston Town Center in
the famously master-planned Virginia suburb. Both are well-received
antidotes to surrounding sprawl, but to some critics, they remain
ersatz places where people drive five miles to park in a giant lot,
then walk around in a contrived movie-lot downtown only tenuously
linked to the rest of the community.
</P>
<P>
   --Use new transit to spawn a downtown. ``Transit-oriented
development'' is one of planners' most popular buzzwords these
days. It describes matching new railroad and transit stations with
more permissive zoning to encourage creation of fairly dense,
walkable residential districts like Brookline or Cambridge and
commercial space within walking distance of the train stop.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
