<HEADER>
A7068 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     02-01 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Feb. 7)  
(mk) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE SENSE OF REALITY: STUDIES IN IDEAS AND THEIR HISTORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Isaiah Berlin. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $13.
</P>
<P>
   In nine essays, the eminent philosopher argues that the search
for a utopian society is the pursuit of a fantasy and that ideas
have consequences, but rarely those that are expected. ``For anyone
wanting to understand the twists and turns of the history of ideas,
this book will be indispensable,'' John Gray wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLOUDSPLITTER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Russell Banks. Harper Perennial, $15.
</P>
<P>
   This sprawling novel about the abolitionist John Brown, selected
by the editors of The New York Times Book Review as one of the best
books of 1998, is narrated by his third son, Owen, and is less a
historical epic about slavery than a domestic drama about the
challenge of living with a fanatic. The story tracks Owen's growth
from introverted son to struggling disciple to firebrand officer in
the bloody holy war of his father, whose failed raid on Harpers
Ferry in 1859 was one of the fuses that touched off the Civil War.
Last year in these pages, Walter Kirn praised the book's ``rich and
soulful'' language.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PILLAR OF FIRE: AMERICA IN THE KING YEARS, 1963-1965 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Taylor Branch. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17.
</P>
<P>
   This middle volume of a planned trilogy on the life and times of
Martin Luther King Jr. covers such fateful events as the
assassinations of John F. Kennedy and Malcolm X and the signing of
the Civil Rights Act of 1964. ``By giving King such epic treatment,
Branch implies that he was an epic hero,'' Alan Wolfe wrote here in
1998. ``The great merit of Branch's stunning accomplishment is to
prove definitively that he was.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEARING THE CROSS: MARTIN LUTHER KING, JR., AND THE SOUTHERN
CHRISTIAN LEADERSHIP CONFERENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David J. Garrow. Quill/Morrow, $16.
</P>
<P>
   This book maintains that while the victories of the civil rights
movement were not King's alone, his leadership was indispensable.
In 1986 the reviewer Howell Raines, said ``Garrow has provided the
fundament of fact on which future King biographies must rest.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VISITORS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anita Brookner. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
</P>
<P>
   This intensely introspective novel focuses on an emotionally
remote 70-year-old widow struggling to maintain her dignity in a
world without happy endings. ```Visitors' may be the book Brookner
has spent her life aiming toward,'' Jacqueline Carey wrote last
year. ``Nothing distracts us from the lesson that even failure can
entail an incredible triumph of will.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOREIGN CORRESPONDENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Geraldine Brooks. Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after reaching out to pen pals in the Middle East,
Europe and America to escape her isolated childhood in 1960s
Australia, a journalist travels abroad to seek them out. In 1998
the reviewer Valerie Sayers, called this a ``charming and sharply
intelligent'' memoir ``full of a generous interest in the life
beyond the self.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DESTINY OF FIRE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Zo Oldenbourg. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $13.95.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 13th-century France, this novel chronicles the suffering
of a noble family that was part of a pacifist sect deemed heretical
by the Roman Catholic Church, and whose members were persecuted
during the ensuing Albigensian Crusade. ``Oldenbourg brings back to
us the cruelty and terror of one of the unhappiest episodes in the
long story of man's inhumanity to man,'' Thomas Caldecot Chubb
wrote in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNICORN'S BLOOD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia Finney. Picador USA, $14.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tale of intrigue at Queen Elizabeth I's court
involving the pursuit of a stolen diary said to contain secrets
that could threaten the queen's reign. ``Finney's intricate novel''
is ``swiftly moving and deftly woven,'' Julie Gray wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TSAR: THE LOST WORLD OF NICHOLAS AND ALEXANDRA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Kurth. Photographs by Peter Christopher. Back
Bay/Little, Brown, $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   This account of the last reigning Romanovs acknowledges their
political blunders and moral failings while emphasizing their
benevolent acts and abiding love for each other. In 1995, Francine
du Plessix Gray called the narrative ``amply documented and
compellingly written'' and the color photographs of Romanov sites
``as beautiful as any pictures I've seen of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOSCOW: GOVERNING THE SOCIALIST METROPOLIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy J. Colton. Belknap/Harvard University, $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   This book traces the history of the Russian capital and the
politics that shaped it. In 1996 our reviewer, Stephen Kotkin, said
the author succeeds in ``superbly demonstrating the depth of the
Soviet-era contribution to the ancient city's outer face and inner
structure.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HORACE AFOOT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Frederick Reuss. Vintage Contemporaries, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The hero of this novel is a monkish middle-aged oddball, living
in a small town, who succumbs to the tug of intimacy when he
befriends a dying librarian and a self-destructive woman. The
result is ``a sly satire of Midwestern life and a restrained
account of how a closed heart comes to be unlocked,'' David Sacks
wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUMMER OF BETRAYAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Hong Ying. Translated by Martha Avery. Grove, $12.
</P>
<P>
   A young poet's life unravels after she gets swept up in the 1989
Tiananmen Square protests and later finds her lover in bed with
another woman. ``Hong Ying's prose ... is both sensuous and
lapidary, eloquently expressing the novel's wide emotional and
intellectual range,'' Philip Gambone wrote in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
