<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7070 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URBAN-SPRAWL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     02-01 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-SPRAWL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... train stop.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One example of a community that has been struggling to o this
is Gresham, Ore., a Portland suburb. For 30 years, various plans
were floated for development of an old county fairgrounds,
including standard megamalls. None ever materialized, and since
1995, the city has instead been trying to develop a European-style
Civic Neighborhood surrounding a new transit stop. An 846-unit
apartment complex proposal has come up, but many other elements are
stalled. ``It's tough pushing the market, and that's what we're
doing with this project,'' city community development director Max
Talbot acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   One limitation to this approach is that normally the most easily
constructable transit lines follow abandoned railroads that,
sometimes deliberately, avoid population centers.
</P>
<P>
   And when transit is badly sited, it can actually drive sprawl.
In small suburbs south of Boston such as Carver, Halifax, and
Plympton, the revival of the Old Colony commuter railroad is
pushing explosive subdivision construction to serve an influx of
downtown workers seeking affordable homes.
</P>
<P>
   While the Old Colony line is easing traffic on Boston-bound
highways, some see it perversely spawning sprawl in the region.
``You can't get to virtually any of these stations without getting
in your car,'' says Mark Primack of the Wildlands Trust of
Southeastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   If these communities _ none with full-time planners _ had the
gumption and resources, Primack and other environmentalists
contend, they could take steps to focus much of the coming
residential development in zones within, say, a 10-minute walk of
the train station. That would ease pressure to turn the countryside
into two-acre lots that atomize the landscape and make people need
their cars to run any kind of errand.
</P>
<P>
   --Inject housing. By some accounts, the way to battle sprawl is
to encourage shorter trips, not bigger roads _ thus reducing
traffic and sprawl by keeping people closer to where they work and
shop. One obvious way to do this is to encourage development of
housing in shopping malls and suburban office campuses that now
feature traffic jams by day and desolation by night.
</P>
<P>
   In the Buckhead section of Atlanta, perhaps America's sprawl
capital, luxury condominium complexes have begun to rise in the
middle of shopping mall parking lots along the Buckhead Loop,
encouraging 24-hour urban life. Besides allowing at least some
workers and shoppers to walk instead of drive, retrofitting housing
into office parks and shopping malls has the added benefit of
making them slightly more community-like places.
</P>
<P>
   But, addressing a topic many officials acknowledge but won't
describe out loud, Framingham's Stasik admits that in suburbs, the
idea of apartments or townhouses in malls ``always brings up images
of low-income housing and Section 8,'' the rental voucher program
blamed for turning communities seedy.
</P>
<P>
   Anecdotal evidence suggests huge pent-up demand for semi-urban
townhouse living within walking distance from work and shops. But
there are few local examples of in-mall living (Masphee Commons's
new second-story apartments are a rare exception) to encourage
tradition-bound developers to take the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   And even if it builds community, letting developers build more
can create controversy. ``A lot of times when a multi-use proposal
comes up, all it is seen as doing is increasing someone's profit,''
observes Lincoln developer William G. Constable, a top leader of
the new Massachusetts Environmental Collaborative, a coalition of
local groups that has made attacking sprawl a top goal.
</P>
<P>
   --Blow things up. Rockville, Md., and Park Forest, Ill., are two
communities that have torn down failed shopping malls to open up
space for new Main Street downtowns with housing, and storefronts
with on-street parking.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, local officials tore down the 1972-vintage
Rockville Mall, a fortress-like failure of Lafayette Place
proportions that went bankrupt barely a decade after it opened.
</P>
<P>
   The city streets that had once criss-crossed the 7.7-acre site
were recreated. A 13-screen cinema complex opened in November as
the showpiece of a planned $300 million town center complex
including restaurants, more than 1 million square feet of offices,
and, perhaps someday, apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Park Forest, south of Chicago, has spent more than $6 million
over the last three years razing the 1950s Centre Mall and
re-creating a Main Street. But to date, only a third of the core
downtown storefronts are occupied, efforts to turn parking lots
into senior housing and apartments are moving slowly, and debt and
maintenance costs are piling up.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, one small example is in Yarmouth on Cape Cod, where the
town bought a decrepit drive-in along Route 28 to create a
waterfront park, a first step toward an emerging plan to redevelop
the famously horrendous Route 28 strip into a more livable
thoroughfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff may appear to be just a drop in the bucket here and
there,'' acknowledges Stuart Meck of the American Planning
Association, but he sees evidence it shows growing acceptance for
turning tired malls into real neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With success stories so rare, the prospects for reversing sprawl
through new community-building construction leave many
environmentalists feeling the only hope is try to stop more sprawl
from happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprawl is this insidious system,'' says Armando Carbonell of
the Cape Cod Commission, driven by a desire to get away from the
congestion of the last new subdivision and strip mall to go in up
the road. ``The reason people wind up creating sprawl is because
they want to get away from it,'' Carbonell says.
</P>
<P>
   John DeVillars, the regional EPA chief and organizer of
Tuesday's summit (dubbed ``Sprawlapalooza'' by some EPA aides),
said in a seemingly hopeless case like Route 9 in Framingham or
Route 1 in Saugus, ``The best thing we might do is buy a camera,
take some pictures and go community by community with a slide show
and say: `Warning, this could happen to you.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
