<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S NEW BLUEPRINTS HAVE KENNEDY IMPRINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's Exhibit A:
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy I advocate combines incentive for good corporate
citizenship _ improved protections for workers' rights, increased
investment in education, training, technology, and research _ and
greater wage and benefit security for all workers.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's Exhibit B:
</P>
<P>
   ``We should create new incentives to extend pension coverage to
all workers, not just the 48 percent who are currently covered, by
establishing a new class of multi-employer, portable pension
accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds right out of President Clinton's State of the Union
speech. But it's not. It's Senator Edward M. Kennedy, speaking
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The point is neither that the president is a thief nor that
Kennedy is a prophet. But their fascinating relationship, now with
six busy years of history, is as close to Shakespeare's marriage of
true minds as one can imagine in politics.
</P>
<P>
   It began in domestic policy at the beginning in 1993, with their
alliance in reauthorizing the government's education programs, from
Head Start to college loans and grants-in-aid, and giving an
initial shove to New Democrat (Clinton) and Enduring Democrat
(Kennedy) ideas like national service and charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   And it began in foreign policy around the same time when Clinton
became the first president to make a serious effort to break the
violent stalemate in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   It has never stopped, from health care to 100,000 new teachers,
from a higher minimum wage to a proposed end to job discrimination
against gay people.
</P>
<P>
   Around here, it has finally become chic to notice that nobody in
Congress has a more extensive ability to get things done than
Kennedy _ across the aisle and between the branches. But what is
usually lost in the insider game is an appreciation for the breadth
of the idea shop he has operated.
</P>
<P>
   And in the president's case, the endless fascination with his
political skills and his New emocrat roots in the mid-1980s has
missed the method in his madness.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton likes to tell friends, one reason for all the
wrenching change in his first five years (in crime,
budget-balancing, welfare, and military readiness) was to get some
monkeys off the Democratic Party's back so that a fresh round of
progress would be possible on the foundation of a vibrant economy.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, it is impossible to examine this year's State
of the Union without encountering the Kennedy in Clinton again and
again: from prescription drugs under Medicare to the patients' bill
of rights; from long-term- care financing to equal pay for women;
from a fresh round of new opportunities for the disabled to
legislation targeting hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The connection on universal savings accounts is especially
topical.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Kennedy was thinking ahead in the immediate
aftermath of Clinton's victory in the budget wars over Newt
Gingrich. He and then-Republican Senator Nancy Kassebaum had
already led the president to the idea of secure health insurance
that could travel with a worker from job to job.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy turned to retirement security. His diagnosis then was
Clinton's last month _ roughly 70 million workers have zero pension
coverage. And for two-thirds of the elderly already, Social
Security benefits make up more than half their income, and for more
than 40 percent, the percentage is 75.
</P>
<P>
   In a different budgetary environment, Kennedy's universal
accounts relied solely on tax incentives.
</P>
<P>
   With the possibility of long-term budget surpluses in a healthy
economy, the president could sweeten the pot with targeted
subsidies for lower-income working families that would work pretty
much like the employer match that swells 401(k) accounts.
</P>
<P>
   For Kennedy back then and Clinton now, the idea is far from a
scheme to redistribute wealth. Instead, it is a means of making the
same opportunities available to all workers and to far more small
companies via the budget surplus that federal tax policy now
provides for more established firms and higher income workers who
can make maximum contributions to investment plans.
</P>
<P>
   When Kennedy first proposed universal accounts, the concept of
``corporate responsibility'' was much in the air, thanks to
agitation that stretched from many liberals right through the
presidential movements of politicians like Ross Perot and Pat
Buchanan. And the senator's idea was to target his tax breaks on
``most favored companies'' that didn't do things like move
operations to Mexico or drop health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   It never went anywhere, but as Kennedy noted in a memo to the
White House in December, universal accounts would be a perfect
means of promoting retirement investment that could supplement
basic Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Politically and substantively, he argued, they were far
preferable to individual accounts that rely on a percentage of
Social Security tax revenue and would eventually lead to major cuts
in the basic benefit, a competing notion the president had
considered.
</P>
<P>
   For the zillionth time, Clinton agreed. Someday, some university
genius will get a doctorate figuring out in depth how these two
pols operated in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, it's enough to know that one of the most
consistently reliable clues to the direction of the Clinton
administration has been the thinking of a relentlessly innovative
policy wonk named Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
