<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Feb. 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUDGET &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 1{ pages of coverage on the Clinton
budget.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-CLINTON (Washington) _ The president's new budget is
presented. By John M. Broder. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-ASSESS (Washington) _ Trying to set the framework for an
entirely new kind of fiscal planning: the era of surpluses. A news
analysis by Richard W. Stevenson. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SPEND (Washington) _ A longer look at various categories
of spending: benefits, military, justice, resources, etc. (1800
words)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-REVENUE (Washington) _ Intriguing new plans to increase
revenue. By David E. Rosenbaum. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments in the Senate's impeachment
trial of the President: Monica Lewinsky is deposed today, the first
of three witnesses sought by the House managers. By Alison Mitchell
and Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LEWINSKY (Washington) _ The scene and mood surrounding
the return and deposition of Monica Lewinsky. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-JORDAN (Washington ) _ A look at the role of Vernon
Jordan, who will be deposed on Tuesday. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DENVER-MOOD (Denver) _ Denver goes crazy over another Broncos
victory and is feeling proud that it is a finalist for the
Democratic convention. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-DEATH-PENALTY (Trenton, N.J.) _ The New Jersey Supreme Court
has upheld the state's death penalty law, rejecting a claim that
black felons were at greater risk of receiving the death sentence
than whites. The court deliberated on the matter for two years and
had appointed a retired judge to conduct a study on the death
penalty as applied to blacks and whites. He found a nearly equal
percentage of blacks and whites accused of capital crimes received
the death sentence. By Julia Preston. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Washington) _ Developments on the troubled Yugoslav
province.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WESTERN-WALL (Jerusalem) _ About 200 strictly Orthodox
Jewish yeshiva students surrounded a group of American Reform
Jewish rabbis who went to pray at the Western Wall this morning,
booing loudly and hurling insults like, ``Go back to Germany'' and,
``They are nothing but biological Jews.'' By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-U.S. (New Delhi) _ American officials said today that
there is momentum for a sequence of steps that would lead to a
substantial easing of economic sanctions imposed on India, as well
as to India's signing of the test ban treaty, probably by mid-year.
By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro) _ Stanley Fischer, the No. 2
official at the IMF, arrives in Brazil. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Dili) _ All sides in East Timor fear violence
if Indonesia troops pull out quickly.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The World Briefing column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-TIME (New York) _ AT&AMP;T and Time Warner, as expected, form a
joint venture to offer local telephone service and other
communication services in 33 states. The companies will provide
AT&AMP;T-branded cable-telephone service to residential and
small-business customers over Time Warner's cable television
systems. They expect to begin service in one or two cities by the
end of this year and offer broader operations in 2000. By Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   SOCGEN-PARIBAS (Undated) _ Societe Generale buys Paribas for 16
billion euros, or $18.2 billion, in stock, creating Europe's
second-largest bank and ushering in the long-awaited consolidation
of the French banking business. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Testimony continues in the
Microsoft antitrust trial. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSICO-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Pepsico is due to report earnings
after the close and is expected to come in at 23 cents a share. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   AXA-GUARDIAN (Undated) _ Axa, Europe's largest insurance
company, buys Guardian Royal Exchange of Britain for 3.45 billion
pounds, or $5.7 billion, in cash and shares, expanding its auto-,
property- and health-insurance businesses in the United Kingdom. As
part of the transaction, Axa's Sun Life and Provincial Holdings
unit will sell Guardian's American business to Liberty Mutual for
$1.47 billion and its German business to to Axa Colonia for 1.66
billion marks, or $970 million. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 25
points, or 0.3 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 5 points, or
0.2 percent. Elsewhere, prices fell 0.2 percent in Tokyo and rose 1
percent in Hong Kong. They were up 1.3 percent in Frankfurt, 1.6
percent in London, 4.3 percent in Brazil and 0.4 percent in Mexico.
On the American debt market, the long bond was down 30/32 point,
with the yield at 5.15 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
