<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-KETCHUP-BOS &LR;      02-01 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-KETCHUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KETCHUP AD CLAIMS DON'T FIT THE FACTS, CRITICS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an eye-catching ad, not least because it implies that
ketchup may help prevent cancer. And it's catching the eyes of more
than just consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Public health researchers and consumer advocates are seeing red
over it. US agencies that regulate food labeling and advertising
are looking at it. And cancer patients are calling to find out
where they can get a purified form of the supposed preventive
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, the Heinz ad has spawned a new controversy amid the
growing debate over health claims for food and dietary supplements.
</P>
<P>
   The full-page color ad has run in the New York Times Magazine,
USA Today, and elsewhere, and it features ketchup slowly pouring
out of a Heinz ketchup bottle, with a headline suggesting that the
naturally occurring chemical that makes tomatoes red _ lycopene _
may prevent cervical and prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When can we make health claims to the public? What are the
legal issues that impact upon advertising? What are the ethical
standards that companies should use when quoting people's work in
their ads?'' asks Dr. Steven K. Clinton, an Ohio State cancer
prevention specialist whose research on lycopene was footnoted in
the ad without his knowledge, and to his dismay.
</P>
<P>
   While preliminary evidence has found an association between the
consumption of fresh, cooked, and processed tomatoes and a lower
risk of some cancers and other diseases, public health researchers
and advocates say it is too soon to make pronouncements about
health benefits, particularly from ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature to make a strong statement about ketchup
preventing cancer. One of the concerns, too, is the context in
which ketchup is taken. If it's part of a Big Mac, that may not be
ideal,'' said Dr. Edward of the schools of medicine and public
health at Harvard. Giovannucci, who worked with Clinton on some of
the research, was also surprised by the ad.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest evidence so far suggests an association between
consumption of tomatoes and tomato products, particularly tomato
sauce, and a lower risk of prostate cancer. While Giovannucci, lead
author of that study, said it could be something other than
lycopene at work, he added that the findings seem to support the
role of the chemical.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not enough to justify the Heinz ad, say critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is completely off the charts,'' said Dr. Sidney Wolfe,
director of Public Citizen Health Research Group, a
Washington-based consumer advocacy group founded by Ralph Nader.
``They're essentially making a medical claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Under US law, medical claims have to be approved by the Food and
Drug Administration as being supported by ``significant scientific
agreement'' before they can be placed on food labels. They also
have to meet truth-in-advertising standards of the Federal Trade
Commission. The FDA has never approved a claim that
lycopene-containing foods may reduce cancer risk.
</P>
<P>
   While federal regulators will not say whether they are
investigating the Heinz ad, both the FDA and the FTC have had it
brought to their attention, spokeswomen said.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Foster, director of corporate communications for the
Pittsburgh-based H.J. Heinz Co., said the campaign is aimed at
educating the public about the possible benefits of lycopene. She
says it makes no health claim about ketchup and does not involve a
food label.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not prescribing ketchup to cure cancer,'' Foster said.
``What we have is a consumer education program that talks about the
health benefits of lycopene. I think that the ad very nicely points
out that lycopene is found in a number of processed food
products.'' A chart in the ad, which ran last month, compared
ketchup's lycopene content to soup, sauce, and canned and fresh
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   But Bonnie Liebman, director of nutrition for the consumer
advocacy group, Center for Science in the Public Interest, said the
chart is misleading, because it cites lycopene content per ounce,
not per serving. ``People don't eat one ounce of each of those
foods. They eat less of ketchup than of any other,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The usual serving size for ketchup is a tablespoon, or half an
ounce; for tomato sauce, it is at least four ounces, Liebman said.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz's Foster defended the presentation and stressed that its
goal is to educate the public about the naturally occurring
chemical. She pointed to the headline's wording, ``Lycopene may
help reduce the risk. . .'' as evidence. ``It does not say ketchup.
It says lycopene.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are bombarded by competing, and sometimes confusing,
messages about what's healthy to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, it confuses the public. They're just going to
throw up their hands and say, `I'm going to eat whatever I want,'
'' said Liebman, whose Washington-based group focuses on dietary
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The ad ``contributes to that kind of confusion.'' Liebman said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, supplement marketers won on appeal a suit against
the FDA after it refused approval of claims for antioxidants,
omega-3 fatty acids, fiber and folic acid. The marketers argued
that the government, which could still file its own appeal,
violated their First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   Makers of food products, from cereals to orange juice, have also
been courting endorsements from health organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The Heinz ad, in fact, features the seal of the Cancer Research
Foundation of America, a Virginia-based nonprofit that has received
$60,000 from the ketchup maker for nutrition research. Stephanie
Guiffre, media relations director for the foundation, which
channels about $1 million a year into cancer prevention research,
said this is the first time it has taken part in such a campaign,
undertaken only after a stringent review.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing by putting our logo on the ad is endorsing
the use of lycopene,'' said Guiffre, who acknowledged that more
research is needed into its cancer prevention potential. ``We're
not endorsing the product.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society has not endorsed lycopene or
ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's risky to emphasize single nutrients or single foods. The
number of studies and data for lycopene is still limited,'' said
Dr. Michael Thun, who heads up epidemiological research for the
organization. The society has endorsed products that it judges to
have scientifically supported cancer prevention potential, such as
Nicorette gum.
</P>
<P>
   Since the ad first ran three weeks ago, Clinton, whose work was
cited by Heinz, has received about 50 inquiries from desperate
cancer patients looking for pure lycopene, from other companies
worried about Heinz gaining an edge, and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The implications of this extend from science to marketing, to
different industries in the marketplace, to concerned people at
risk, all the way to cancer patients,'' said Clinton, who recently
left the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute for Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this ad that's very carefully worded, there's an implied
health benefit. The message that people take home is, `This is good
for me. It will prevent prostate and cervical cancer, and it's
endorsed by scientists and a cancer research organization.' That's
the message people take home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
