<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SITCOMS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     02-01 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SITCOMS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 PASADENA, Calif.: ... favorite shows.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proponents of such blends of drama and comedy say they offer
sophisticated writing about grown-up issues while creating
original, distinctive, fully realized worlds. That, some say, is
the best way to pull back viewers at a time when one sitcom after
another gets bogged down in puerile sexual banter. (Sassa's recent
call for less focus on sex in NBC's comedies was seen by some as a
tacit admission that sitcoms are in a rut, especially given that
NBC rose to dominance primarily on the strength of its sitcoms.)
</P>
<P>
   Shows like ``Sports Night'' work because they do not insult the
audience's intelligence. ``Play up to the audience, that's a big
part of it,'' said Kelsey Grammer, star of ``Frasier.'' ``Assume
that they are more intelligent than you are. That seemed to work
with `Frasier.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
More animation
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, as writers and producers try to rejuvenate TV
comedy, they are increasingly turning to animation. Five new
animated shows are premiering on UPN and Fox at midseason,
including Larry &QC; 
Charles's new project, ``Dilbert,'' on UPN. Animated programs like
Tom Snyder's upcoming ``Home Movies'' offer not just a change in
format but a take on the world that's different from that in
traditional live-action sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also too many warmed-over concepts in the works
that suggest Hollywood still doesn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, during an interview session with TV critics in
Pasadena, Calif., earlier this month, writer/producer Daniel Paige
called for an overhaul of sitcoms, saying, ``The sitcom form needs
to grow if it's going to survive. The audience is just too smart.
You can't keep spoon-feeding them the same things.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Paige's new sitcom on the WB network, ``Zoe, Duncan, Jack &AMP;
Jane,'' does just that. At bottom, it is essentially a younger
version of NBC's much-copied ``Friends,'' right down to the
brother-sister duo.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when sitcoms like NBC's ``Veronica's Closet'' trade in
snideness and nastiness at the expense of genuine humor, some
believe television comedy needs to adjust its very attitude and
tone. ``People are bored with cynical humor,'' insisted Jenna
Elfman, star of ABC's ``Dharma &AMP; Greg.'' She added that the
cynicism of many contemporary sitcoms is compounded by their
artificiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genuinely funny things that have you at home rolling on the
couch are because there's some moment of truth,'' said Elfman.
``But if you are trying to be funny, going for comedic stuff
instead of the truth of the situation or the moment, then people
will just squirm and be embarrassed for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Burnett, the executive producer of ``Late Night with David
Letterman'' and the upcoming ``The Late Late Show with Craig
Kilborn,'' is plunging into the sitcom world with a project called
``Stuckey's,'' but he agrees that too many sitcoms have the ring of
falsity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them are very artificial,'' said Burnett. ``Whereas
`Sanders' portrayed reality in such a true and funny way, and
`Seinfeld' developed its own language, most sitcoms now are about a
bunch of smart comedy writers thinking of clever turns of phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Danson's new role
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of television's greatest sitcoms was ``Cheers''; the show's
star, Ted Danson, now plays a cantankerous doctor who revels in
political incorrectness on CBS's ``Becker.'' Danson says that the
sitcom genre can revive by being more venturesome.
</P>
<P>
   ```Seinfeld' broke all the rules, and the next great show ...
also will break some rules,'' said Danson. ``You have to be willing
to risk, to go into places that have never been touched before, and
then trust that the network and the powers that be will give you a
chance to put it on.''
</P>
<P>
   But rule-breaking comedies are also more likely to be the target
of protests from pressure groups, making networks even more
reluctant than usual to take risks (there has already been
criticism, for example, of Eddie Murphy's ``The PJs''). That has
been coupled with an economic trend that some say has helped
diminish the quality of sitcoms. Program costs for established hit
sitcoms are beginning to go through the same roof pierced by
``Seinfeld'' and ``ER.'' NBC ponied up $73 million to keep ``Mad
About You'' on its schedule for the 1998-99 season, including $1
million apiece per episode for Helen Hunt and Paul Reiser, only to
see the show's ratings plummet. With costs like that in mind,
networks are increasingly prone to keep shows on the air because
they own a piece of them and control their costs, not because
they're any good. Conversely, they are quicker to pull the plug on
shows provided by an independent production company.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big problem is the ownership of shows by the network,'' said
Peter Casey, co-executive producer of ``Frasier.'' ``I honestly
feel that they favor their shows over shows that they don't have a
piece of, in terms of keeping them on the air longer.''
</P>
<P>
   But some argue that producers like Casey symbolize another part
of the problem: namely, that they are tempted to take on too many
projects because the pool of talented writer-producers has grown so
shallow that networks turn to them time and again. This year, Casey
and his fellow ``Frasier'' executive producers David Angell and
David Lee shouldered the double duty of creating ``Encore!
Encore!'' while trying to keep their existing show at the top of
the heap.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot: ``Encore! Encore!'' was a critical and ratings
disaster, and the quality of ``Frasier'' began to slip.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no universal agreement on the cause or the
solution, the sense that sitcoms are in the doldrums clearly has
many in Hollywood worried. Not the insouciant Kathy Griffin,
though. The carrot-topped costar of ``Suddenly Susan'' had the
answer at her fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good sitcom should be engaging. You should be able to watch
two minutes and you're in,'' said Griffin. ``And you need a funny
red-haired sidekick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
