<HEADLINE>
POPCORN'S NEW KERNELS OF WISDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, when she was a fledgling trend seer, Faith
Plotkin saw her own future and legally changed her last name to the
infinitely more memorable Popcorn. Now the chairwoman of
BrainReserve, a marketing consulting firm, she makes her fortune
selling predictions to companies great and small.
</P>
<P>
   She has written two popular books: ``The Popcorn Report,'' a
bestseller in the 1980s, and ``Clicking,'' published last year.
After reading the latter, I wanted to ask Popcorn about some of her
ideas for the future, especially a concept she calls AtmosFear.
It's a kind of rampant environmental paranoia rife with all sorts
of fabulous marketing opportunities, according to Popcorn, at
least. Unfortunately for me, Popcorn's publicist said Madame Faith
is booked solid through the millennium and can't spare five minutes
to talk to anybody who isn't already scheduled. The publicist
didn't specify whether Popcorn was booked through the false
millennium or the genuine, but either way, I can take a hint.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Popcorn became an overnight media darling when she
identified a trend and coined the term ``cocooning'' to describe
people retreating to the comfort and safety of their nests. The
cocooning concept grows larger by the day, ``a driving force in
American culture and society,'' as Popcorn modestly acknowledges in
``Clicking.'' And yet I can't help but wonder: If everybody is
cocooning, how come nobody is ever at home when I try to call them?
They all can't have caller ID, can they?
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn is so successful at anticipating trends that now others
are paying her the sincerest form of flattery, trying to
out-Popcorn Popcorn, as it were. ``Clicking'' led me to another
book, ``Iconoculture: The Future Ain't What It Used to Be,'' by a
trio of prognosticators who clearly covet a piece of Popcorn's
action, Vickie Abrahamson, Mary Meehan, and Larry Samuel. Many of
their predictions bear certain striking similarities to Popcorn's.
How are we to account for this? Maybe the future is out there,
waiting for us to grab it with both hands and make the most of it,
just as our graduation speaker said it would be. In light of
AtmosFear, I suppose we should remember to wear rubber gloves.
</P>
<P>
   In the prediction business, it's not enough just to be able to
identify trends. You also have to be able to reinvent the language
for marketing purposes, to give trends catchy, media-seductive yet
somehow vaguely annoying terms. I think of it as Popcorning.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of ``Iconoculture'' clearly have taken a page from
Popcorn's books and invented Popcornisms galore. In
``Iconoculture,'' cocooning becomes bunkering, AtmosFear is
germonella, and pleasure revenge (``cutting loose and savoring
forbidden fruits'' like single malt Scotch and gourmet ice cream)
becomes vice versing.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Clicking'' Popcorn gives us, among many new terms,
EVEolution, for marketing to financially savvy women; mancipation,
marketing to the nonstereotypical male; down-aging, appealing to
those who won't allow age to dictate their behavior. The authors of
``Iconoculture'' are more than up to the Popcorn challenge with
terms such as eatertainment, the mania for theme restaurants;
Zentrepreneurism, for people who combine social activism with
business; beehiving, for the trend toward forming small communities
bound by shared interests _ like predicting the future, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   After reading ``Clicking'' and ``Iconoculture'' back to back, I
was left with the impression that the authors of both books are, in
large part, pointing out the obvious. Of course, nobody ever went
broke doing that, myself included. It's practically a job
qualification in my line of work. Should I go into the prediction
business? Should I change my name, possibly to something snack-food
related? Dee Dee Dorito? It has a certain ring, but not the Popcorn
ring, I'm afraid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
