<HEADLINE>
GROUNDS FOR BACTERIA HYSTERIA UNDERLIE WIDENING RECALL OF MEATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As more Americans trace illnesses to listeria-tainted processed
meats and more plants recall packaged products, health officials
worry openly about ``listeria hysteria.''
</P>
<P>
   But while some consumers are overreacting, feeling nauseous at
the sight of a hot dog, public health specialists say listeria
ho-hum would be far worse.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: This bacteria kills more than 20 percent of those it
strikes. Its serious victims are primarily pregnant women and
fetuses, the elderly, and those with a compromised immune system.
(Compare that to a death rate of less than 3 percent among those
who get food poisoning from salmonella and E. coli.)
</P>
<P>
   Every week, more sicknesses and deaths are being tied to a
particular strain of listeria found at a Michigan meat plant run by
Bil Mar, a subsidiary of the Sara Lee Corp. As of last week, 79
illnesses nationwide were linked to this Sara Lee plant, including
15 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Of that, five cases come from Massachusetts, including the death
of a fetus.
</P>
<P>
   And it's too early to know the full extent of listeria's recent
damage. Given its incubation period of anywhere from three to 70
days and an average incubation of three to four weeks, it could
still be some time before officials know the true extent of the
recent outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to consumer anxiety, the list of recalled products keeps
growing. In the past two weeks, Thorn Apple Valley and Oscar Mayer
announced listeria-related recalls. Together with Sara Lee's
recall, which was announced last month, the list includes such
brand names as Ball Park, Hygrade, Oscar Mayer, and Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Deli managers are noticing customers' anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are asking lots of questions, such as what kind of
brands we sell,'' said Bobby DeDominicis, general manager of B &AMP; D
Deli in Brookline, Mass., which sells mostly the deli's own
prepared meats. ``I've noticed these questions more in the past
month.''
</P>
<P>
   But health officials say there's more information on listeria
that should settle some nerves. Most healthy people can ingest
listeria with no problem, perhaps just a mild stomach reaction.
</P>
<P>
   And while often fatal, the bacteria is relatively rare. About
1,800 serious listeria-related illnesses are reported nationwide
each year, said federal health officials. That compares to 40,000
cases nationwide of salmonella food poisoning, and 20,000 cases of
E. Coli-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual about this year's outbreak is the ability of
health officials to identify a Michigan plant as the source. In
most years, listeria cases are logged in every state and the
sources are random. Last year in this state, there were 34
listeria-related deaths, with no one source identified.
</P>
<P>
   For now, public health officials are stepping up their warnings
about this bacteria for those with weak immune systems and women
who are pregnant. They are advising these groups to avoid eating
any kind of processed meats, as well as soft cheeses, such as brie,
in which listeria often hides.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a pregnant woman is healthy, health officials say she is
more prone to react strongly to listeria, and the bacteria can pass
to her fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials say they have long known that pregnant women
were vulnerable to listeria, but its rarity gave it low priority in
the list of warnings to this group.
</P>
<P>
   Until public health specialists understand the scope of the
problem, they urge the public to take precautions such as
re-cooking processed meats and cooking raw meat thoroughly. Because
this soil-based bacteria can also be found on vegetables, they urge
consumers to wash vegetables thoroughly before eating.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Kludt, epidemiology program coordinator for the
Massachusetts Department of Public Health, said people should also
practice general hygiene, washing their hands, knives, and cutting
boards after exposures to uncooked foods. Even watch the hygiene
practices of your local butcher or deli manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be slicing meat on the same machine they used for the
Sara Lee meat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
$1 mystery revealed
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that nothing is truly free, a Westwood, Mass. mother
grew understandably suspicious when she received a survey in the
mail with $1 in cold cash. It was clear the $1 was hers to keep,
whether she ultimately filled out the questionnaire or not.
</P>
<P>
   She worried that this was a guilt-inducing ploy to get her name
on a marketing list, which would trigger hundreds of annoying calls
and solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the sender was vague. The survey, called the
``National Survey of Apparel Purchasing,'' asked questions about
how she chose and bought apparel. The questions included how many
children she had, her income, her educational background and
whether she took vacations outside the country.
</P>
<P>
   The three-sentence letter was from Frederick L. Barbour II,
president of The Barbour Group. A self-addressed return envelope
went to a place called ADE of Wisconsin in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredibly anonymous,'' she said. ``It raised my
antennae.''
</P>
<P>
   She asked us to check it out, and we did. After doing a
reverse-directory search of the address, we discover the ADE is
actually Accurate Data Entry, a company operated out of a basement
in Milwaukee. When we called, the receptionist said she knew about
the survey and promptly replied, ``Oh, it's for Lands' End.''
</P>
<P>
   So, we called Lands' End, the apparel mail-order business based
in Dodgeville, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Lands' End-sponsored survey,'' said Anna Schryver, a
company spokeswoman after checking with her marketing folks. ``It's
a blind survey. We don't want to bias the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to make sense. But who is Frederick Barbour? Schryver
said he's an independent marketing consultant. We asked if he would
call us, just so we could ask about his $1 survey-completion
strategy. She said she'd leave a message for him, but couldn't give
us his number. We have yet to hear from him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Infant carrier recall
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US Consumer Product Safety Commission has announced the
recall of 240,000 ``Baby Bjorn'' infant carriers because infants
can fall out of the leg openings. Nine infants have slipped through
the openings, including six who suffered fractured skulls. The
carrier is made by Regal and Lager Inc. of Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
