<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK BEFORE YOU CURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VERONICA FLORES  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A group of adolescent girls that I work with know
my limits on abusive language: I don't want to hear them call each
other or anyone else ``stupid,'' much less anything worse.
</P>
<P>
   I and the other women who help with the group have explained to
them that we want them to show respect for one another. The sell is
tough with these spirited girls, especially when they're arguing
and, like so many adults, don't think before they hurl insults. So
it's with a great deal of curiosity last week that I watched a
Michigan town attempt to prosecute a man for cursing.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Boomer is charged with violating a 102-year-old Michigan
law when he cursed in front of a woman and two children after his
canoe tipped over Aug. 15 on the Rifle River near Standish.
According to news reports, Boomer loudly let loose with some choice
four-letter words.
</P>
<P>
   It's illegal in Michigan to ``use any indecent, immoral,
obscene, vulgar or insulting language in the presence or hearing of
any woman or child.''
</P>
<P>
   The act is illegal in Texas, too. The police call it
``disorderly conduct,'' although the law isn't specific to gender.
</P>
<P>
   A judge now is considering whether to drop the charges against
Boomer. Civil libertarians are challenging the case as a trampling
of the right to free speech. Whether or not you agree, it's most
certainly a demonstration of the decline in the nation's civility.
</P>
<P>
   While my observations are limited to my nearly 33 years of
living, the loss of grace seems to have begun before I arrived and
has accelerated since.
</P>
<P>
   While I don't swear like a sailor, I'm also no prude. Sometimes
only a four-letter word is befitting the pain of a stubbed toe.
However, I've always marveled at the restraint of a longtime friend
who invented her own swear word _ ``sugarfoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Cursing is as old as the devil. While many find it offensive,
some have found it intellectually stimulating. Mexican writer
Octavio Paz, for example, devotes the entire fifth chapter of
``Labyrinth of Solitude'' to an examination of a word this
newspaper can't print. Suffice to say it's been a fightin' word for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   But at what point does cursing cross the line? For that matter,
is there a line? Hollywood and the boob tube so gratuitously push
the envelope with Jimmy Smits' bare butt and other similarly
salacious clips, the line becomes blurred before we can find it.
</P>
<P>
   Some Michigan residents who oppose the law that entangled Boomer
told reporters that those within earshot could simply just walk
away from the offensive language. They're right. But how do you
explain to children like those who heard Boomer that such language
is improper when so much of it is occurring around you?
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Boomer insisted that the incident was simply ``clean
fun.'' He's changing his tune, as the news media attention has
ratcheted up. ``It bothers me very much. It reflects badly on my
parents,'' he told the Detroit News. ``My parents didn't raise me
this way.''
</P>
<P>
   If only he'd thought of that before he opened his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Veronica Flores is a columnist for the San Antonio
Express-News, P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
