<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7090 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-HISTORY-HNS &LR;      02-01 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-HISTORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK HISTORY: GLEANING LESSONS FROM A LIFETIME 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The train of history runs smoothly through the
memory of Edward Qualles, coasting along the tracks of his 96
years. For much of this century, and Qualles has lived through just
about all of it, the train has been part of black America, its
mournful whistle and rumbling journey a symbol to urban and rural
communities.
</P>
<P>
   For urban blacks living on the ``other side of the tracks,'' the
train was emblematic of the barriers separating them from the
larger community. For rural blacks, it was a reminder of a larger
world to explore.
</P>
<P>
   And for many blacks, Qualles included, the railroad was the
vehicle they rode into the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   February is ``Black History Month,'' when public attention is
paid to a history that is often ignored the rest of the year. But
black history, any history, isn't simply found in books and museums
or in the lives of famous people. History surrounds us every day in
the experiences and conversations of senior citizens such as
Qualles, people whose lives of dignity, honor and perseverance
enrich our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Qualles was born outside Greenwood, Miss., in 1903. He was
plowing the field at age 9 when someone told him that the Titanic
had sunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go on a boat anyway,'' was his response.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen, he watched the Klan march through downtown Greenwood.
Not knowing that the light-complexioned youth was black, they
didn't bother him.
</P>
<P>
   Qualles laughs at the thought that he put one over on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I guess I did.''
</P>
<P>
   This was in the early 1920s. As he sits in his San Antonio home
today, a television report airs about the first day of the trial of
one of the men accused of killing a black man in Jasper, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Qualles attended Tougaloo College in Jackson, Miss. When George
Washington Carver came for a lecture, he helped the scientist set
up his exhibit. During his summers in college he began working as a
cook on the Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad, known as the ``Katy.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating, he went to work full time for the railroad,
becoming the chef in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   ``The railroads had better paying jobs,'' he says. ``And you got
to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   He met the great black labor leader A. Philip Randolph, who
founded the Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters, the first black
union, and who originated the idea for the March on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Randolph, Qualles helped organize Local 645 of the
Dining Car Employees and led them through two successful strikes.
</P>
<P>
   After the Katy stopped its dining car service in the mid-'60s,
Qualles became the assistant chef of the San Antonio Country Club
and the chef at other San Antonio eateries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cooked in every place that had a stove,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His mind still sharp, he reads and keeps up with current events.
He lives alone in the home he shared with his wife of 57 years,
Catherine, who died in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably the happiest and most gentle human being I've
ever known,'' says his friend Odell Couch, who checks on him daily.
</P>
<P>
   Qualles' advice to young people is to ``be literate. And you've
got to be literate in business, take care of business and prepare
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   So the train of history can keep moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
