<HEADLINE>
MOVIES REVIEWED RECENTLY BY THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``The Hi-Lo Country'' Woody Harrelson satisfyingly fills
some pretty big boots here, playing a rip-roaring
last-of-a-dying-breed cowboy who returns from World War II to find
that the world he left is being gobbled up by big ranchers,
squeezing out independents like him. It's a colorful and likable
performance, but he's so much bigger than the characters
surrounding him that they seem inadequate. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !! ``She's All That'' Bright, above-average teensploitation
movie. Its plot is formulaic: Babe magnet bets his pals that he can
turn the most unpromising zero into a prom queen, only to find that
he falls in love with her. What makes it work is that it's unafraid
to try for real feelings. It nails them, thanks to a simpatico cast
led by Freddie Prinze Jr. and Rachael Leigh Cook. Matthew Lillard
is a stitch as an airhead TV celeb who thinks he's a cool dancer.
(PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
