A7096 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-01 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORIED ADVICE IN AVOIDING THE IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This is a time when too much has been said too
often about the impeachment trial of President Clinton. The
endlessly repetitive talking heads on cable television, each hoeing
the old partisan ground again and again, are beginning to sound
like a lecture in the Tower of Babel.
</P>
<P>
   The nation waits, stupefied, observing this tiresome and no
longer instructive process winding toward what is heralded to be
the end. Yet no one can be certain when the curtain will finally
fall, as one day's implied agreement between the Senate Republicans
and Democrats evaporates the next day.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of this depressing state of affairs, I renewed a
longstanding search for some favorite books of my youth. I must
have devoured six or seven of the author's works, as quickly as
school work and other absorbing distractions of pre-teen years
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I found myself in a library in recent years I would
pore through the catalog searching to find again these enjoyable
books. The search was complicated because I could not exactly
recollect the author's name.
</P>
<P>
   It was Altscheler or Altschuler, or something like that. But no
hunt, through card or computer, found anything resembling that name
and the subject he wrote about.
</P>
<P>
   His books were fictionalized histories of the Civil War's many
battles, written for young readers. But no specific title lodged in
memory, complicating the search.
</P>
<P>
   So for all this time, a kernel of dissatisfaction and
frustration abided. Recently, I turned to a visiting daughter and
her husband who heavily employ computers in their daily work, to
help find what so long had been elusive. It seemed particularly
apropos for a mood depressed by the impeachment's hollow oratory.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the problem was simple. Stefanie suggested using a
book-finding Web page and Paul helped me maneuver through the
necessary paths. There were some false turns to the Library of
Congress catalog, which, once I had gotten to it, with the kids
looking over my shoulder, I expected should definitely provide the
information. But because I lacked the precise name or a specific
title, this did not get me where I wanted to go.
</P>
<P>
   In describing the books to Paul and what they had meant to me so
many years ago, how much history they had helped me learn in their
pleasurable way, I recalled that one book was about a General
Thomas, who became known as the Rock of Chickamauga, for his
tenacious stand against the Confederates in Tennessee in 1863.
</P>
<P>
   That lead took us to a search engine Stefanie used
(www.bibliofind.com).
</P>
<P>
   Chickamauga produced an extremely long list of book titles, but
none written by anything resembling the author's name as I
remembered it.
</P>
<P>
   We went on to a second page and ran into good luck. In the
middle of that listed we found a bookshop in Ashville, N.Y., that
had a copy of ``Rock of Chickamauga,'' by a writer named Joseph
Altsheler.
</P>
<P>
   A breakthrough at long last, and a bit of vindication for the
powers of memory to survive the decades. With the name Joseph
Altsheler in hand, correctly spelled, we turned to the search again
and found a listing of 50 books, including at least seven on Civil
War battles and subjects. Joseph Altsheler, it turns out, also
wrote extensively about the American West and Indians, about World
War I, among other subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did a long search finally end in success, but having a
fulfilling experience using the Internet to find something that you
really wanted keenly to find, and could not accomplish any other
way, was a satisfaction second only to rediscovering Altsheler's
writings.
</P>
<P>
   It was a welcome contrast to previous attempts to use the
computer to find useful or necessary information expeditiously. All
previous disappointments were overcome. This was a high point that
lightened and lifted the spirit and was a reminder that in the
muddles of public discourses, small victories, personally
meaningful, can still be won.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the sense of accomplishment of finally having success
correctly using the computer. It's enough to steel you for the next
impeachment round.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-IMANI-BOS &LR;      02-01 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-IMANI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLEAR WINDOW INTO THE LIFE OF A TEEN MOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
IMANI ALL MINE 
By Connie Porter 
Houghton Mifflin, 212 pp., $23 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imani looks just like her mama.
</P>
<P>
   She has the same squib of a nose, the same lips, the same wide,
flat fingers. Her mama, Tasha, sees it, sees it every time she
holds Imani _ even if others think the baby may favor her daddy,
whose name Tasha won't even speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what nobody say, who they say they might see in
her. It's only me in her,'' Tasha says, with a hint of defiance.
``When I be getting up with her at night, it be my own face looking
back at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Imani's mother is a 15-year-old high school student.
</P>
<P>
   We've all seen, if not known, girls like Tasha. They're at bus
stops and train stations, in malls and in city parks, popping gum
and pushing baby strollers. A heady combination of attitude and
innocence, they are the faces behind the statistics and headlines
about children having children. Often they elicit onlookers'
disapproval or pitying clucks of the tongue rather than
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes Tasha, the heartbreaking narrator of ``Imani All
Mine,'' memorable is author Connie Porter's sympathetic but
unsentimental portrayal of a teenage mother. Porter neither
endorses nor condemns teen motherhood; she simply presents its
matter-of-fact realities through the stark, almost poetic
vernacular of Tasha, a teenager raised on the uncompromising
streets of inner-city Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   As with most teenagers, Tasha's pregnancy was unplanned. Given a
choice, she would never have become a statistic; she was raped by a
knife-wielding teenage boy whose attention earned her trust.
Ashamed, she kept her pregnancy a secret from her mother, Earlene,
for most of her term, concealing her body with baggy sweatshirts
and pants. Once her mother discovers the pregnancy _ one morning,
while Tasha is getting dressed for school, Earlene notices the
telltale swell of her daughter's breasts and belly _ it's clear why
Tasha withheld her news. Earlene flies into a rage, hitting her
daughter across the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hell wrong with you? What were you thinking about,
doing this?'' Earlene asks, each question punctuated with a slap.
``Why you ain't tell me? Why you ain't tell me? Why you ain't tell
me?'' In her own way, Earlene means well. She wants more for Tasha
than the single motherhood that truncated her own life.
</P>
<P>
   When her mother asks the name of the father, Tasha falls silent.
``I just curled myself around my baby. I couldn't say his name to
Mama. I couldn't even say it to myself.'' Later that day, while
Tasha is sitting in her second-period math class, her water breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Once the child is born, Tasha falls in love with her daughter
straightaway. This baby is someone who needs her, someone she can
call her own. When she first holds the baby, she stares at the
child ``to see who was in her face,'' and is reassured when it
``was only me I seen there.''
</P>
<P>
   She christens her daughter, Imani, an African word for
``faith.'' Tasha continues her studies in a high school where so
many students have babies that on-site day care is provided. She
juggles a life of exams, gym classes, and 2 a.m. feedings. She
loves her daughter, but at times reacts violently when the child
won't stop crying.
</P>
<P>
   Tasha's flashes of fury reflect the violence outside her window,
where rap songs exploding from boom boxes take the place of
whispered lullabies. Her neighborhood is ruled by the drug dealers
who dangle different brands of sneakers from telephone wires to
advertise their illicit wares. Random gunfire scars the silence of
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They be shooting around here sometimes at night,'' Tasha says.
``Pop pop. Like firecrackers.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter's use of black street idioms, as well the book's
narration by an African-American girl who arches her back against
hardship, may remind some of ``Push,'' Sapphire's intense,
overpraised 1996 novel. It's a lazy comparison. Honest and
unpretentious, ``Imani All Mine'' doesn't revel in trying to shock
its audience with its harsh depictions. Porter has a firmer grasp
on her characters' essential humanity. They emerge as true, whether
it is Mrs. Poole, the teacher who imparts parenting advice to her
students, or Earlene's ingratiating white boyfriend, Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Though the violence near the book's conclusion is inevitable, it
is no less shattering. Yet as in her acclaimed first novel,
``All-Bright Court,'' Porter sifts hope from the ashes. She finds
grace notes in her characters' dogged endurance, always letting
light shine through lamentable lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
