A7098 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-01 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEACE NUTS' VS. THE `SCHOOL OF ASSASSINS' 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In 1990, when he staged his first protest
against the School of the Americas at Fort Benning, Ga., the Rev.
Roy Bourgeois was joined by about 10 friends and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   In November, for the ninth annual School of the Americas Watch
rally, the Maryknoll priest had a little more company.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 people showed up _ 2,319 of whom peacefully
trespassed onto the U.S. Army base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through some real desert years,'' Bourgeois said. ``It
was so cold during our 40-day fast on the steps of the Capitol, we
could never get warm. But we learned you just gotta hang in there
and be faithful. Now we've reached a moment where the movement to
close the school has really taken root.''
</P>
<P>
   A recap of the desert years must include the seven prison
sentences (nearly four years of incarceration) that Bourgeois, 60,
has served for his civil disobedience. Several other priests, nuns
and lay activists have been locked up as often.
</P>
<P>
   One 18-month stint, spent in a federal pen in Minnesota, was
Bourgeois' punishment for a particularly inventive crime.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing an Army surplus store uniform, he walked onto the Fort
Benning base, climbed a pine tree and hid until lights-out. Then,
using a boom box, he blasted a platoon of Salvadoran recruits
inside the school's barracks with a tape of a speech for peace by
the late Oscar Romero.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop of El Salvador, Romero was slain in 1980 while
celebrating Mass. The military mind behind his killing and hundreds
of other political murders was the leader of the Salvadoran death
squads, Roberto D'Aubuisson _ a graduate of the School of the
Americas who died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by the U.S. Army in 1946 to train Latin American
soldiers to defend against ``instability'' in their countries, the
school moved in 1984 from Panama to Fort Benning near Columbus, Ga.
It carried with it its nicknames, ``School of the Assassins'' and
``School of the Coups.''
</P>
<P>
   Also among its 60,000 grads is former Panamanian Gen. Manuel
Noriega (currently serving a 40-year prison sentence in Florida for
drug dealing).
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Freedom of Information Act, the U.N. Truth
Commission and their own persistence, Bourgeois and his associates
say they have documented proof that at least one of every 100
School of the Americas graduates has returned home to such
countries as Honduras, Guatemala, El Salvador or Colombia, ``not to
promote democracy, but to rape, kill, torture and participate in
massacres.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The school keeps saying there are only a few graduates who've
done these things,'' Bourgeois said. ``But, it's not one or two or
three. If one of every 100 graduates of, say, Boston College goes
on to kill, rape and torture, don't you think somebody's going to
shut down that school and investigate?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, a Defense Department study confirmed the existence of a
long-rumored training manual that advised students about the
efficacy of blackmail, beatings, torture, false imprisonment,
executions and bounties for enemy dead.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Pentagon declassified the manual, providing the
School of the Americas Watch with some potent evidence. Since then,
leaders of the school have emphasized that such tactics are no
longer taught, that changes have been made, including a mandatory
course in human rights. They maintain that the school is just the
symbol of a much larger agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The starting point of this issue is really not the School of
the Assassins,'' he said. ``The point is the reality in Latin
America, one in which the majority of people struggle in poverty
just to survive. For so long, Latin American militaries have been
defending a socio-economic system that keeps the rich rich and the
poor poor. And we (the United States) have helped them. Our policy
there is not a pretty picture.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, courses in human rights seem absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look at the SOA curriculum, we don't see these
soldiers being taught the skills that will let them return to their
countries to help heal the wounds of poverty and political
oppression,'' the priest said. ``If the army really wants to teach
them democracy, it should shut that school down and send some of
those soldiers to American universities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois received a Purple Heart as a Naval officer in Vietnam
before he was ordained in 1972. In 1989, after he learned that
several School of the Americas graduates were linked to the murders
of six Jesuit priests, their housekeeper and her 15-year-old
daughter in El Salvador, he moved into a small apartment across the
street from Fort Benning.
</P>
<P>
   To him, ``This is really not a complicated issue.'' And that
simplicity, he believes, accounts for the exponential growth in the
number of his fellow protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Told that his group's self-sacrificing obsession with the School
of the Americas might be viewed by some as a mission of peace nuts,
Bourgeois laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are nuts to want to help the poor, to try to
alleviate suffering, to feel compassion for their brothers and
sisters in Latin America, we need more nuts,'' he said. ``Give me
the nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
