r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-01 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVEN IS WITHIN REACH ABOVE LAKE TAHOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH LAKE TAHOE, Calif. _ It feels pretty much like cheating _
taking the Aerial Tramway up the face of Gunbarrel Run, then the
Sky Express to the rim, at 10,000 feet, looking down across the
vast cobalt-blue expanse of Lake Tahoe, backed by snow-flecked
forest and an azure sky.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, this is definitely cheating. Anybody who has climbed
mountains knows that getting a view like this is supposed to
require dramatic personal sacrifice. That is what it takes, for
instance, to reach the summit of 9,735-foot Mount Tallac, set on
the southwest rim of the Tahoe Basin, which overlooks Lake Tahoe
and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   But not at Heavenly, the world-class ski resort at South Lake
Tahoe, set within minutes (by shuttle) of slick casinos. By tram,
it is just minutes to some of the most eye-popping views anywhere
in the West.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I avoided the place because it just seemed too
yuppie, too crowded, too fast-paced for a backwoods kind of guy,
but I've been won over this winter. What has done it are two
visits, two winners, and views that speak with a thousand quiet
voices.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to visit is between Sunday and Thursday, when the
casinos have less than 100 percent occupancy. That is the only time
significant discounts are available at South Lake for lodging. That
is also when the runs are less than packed, and when even an
average schusser can enjoy the moments without feeling pressure
from the warp-speed types.
</P>
<P>
   And right there is what makes the board or ski experience at
Heavenly the best in the Tahoe Basin. The place is simply so big,
covering such a vast amount of terrain, that your average bear can
find a virtually unlimited number of runs to suit her skill level.
</P>
<P>
   Heavenly has 4,800 skiable acres that straddle the
California-Nevada border _ more than any other ski area in the far
West _ 82 runs, 27 lifts, and the longest mountain descent in the
far West, 5.5 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the place is set up for intermediate skiers and
boarders, making it ideal for the maximum number of people, and
with high-speed trams, quads and lifts, they are delivered quickly
to the promised land.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the place has won me over this winter is because of
its sheer size and the speed of the lifts, which diffuse the number
of people on the mountain. Another is that by making visits during
the week, and when there are not holidays, I've avoided the crowds
and the high-ticket lodging.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that I just got married here to my long-lost college
sweetheart, in a beautiful little chapel overlooking the lake,
minister and all. Yeah, that could definitely have something to do
with it. But, hey, after all, no place is prettier in winter than
Tahoe.
</P>
<P>
   Every trip should start with a lodging reservation (either
direct to a casino, or to the Tahoe Reservation Line at
800-288-2463) and a phone call to get the latest on road conditions
(800-426-7623).
</P>
<P>
   I've driven U.S. 50 in all conditions, including white-out
blizzards, and you simply must make certain that your driving
skills and your vehicle can handle anything before heading up the
hill beyond Placerville, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Always stop in Placerville and fill up your gas tank. In case
there is a long jam-up near the summit from an accident, which
occasionally occurs, this way you will be able to keep your engine
running to stay warm without running out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Tahoe is the crown jewel of skiing in the West, and Heavenly is
the best of the best; and hence, a ski holiday can be a pricey
ticket, adding up lodging ($75 to $150 and up per night), lift
tickets ($106 per day for two) and meals ($50 and up for two per
day). That's roughly $250 to $300 per day, not counting travel
expenses and equipment rentals.
</P>
<P>
   Once you catch a glimpse of the view, though, little seems to
matter. There are many ways to take in that spectacle and then
experience the sheer exhilaration of heading down a run,
occasionally stopping to slow down the experience and absorb the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   To make it work, Heavenly has three main base-level staging
areas, two in Nevada and one in California. From any of these, you
take a tram (California Lodge), a quad (Stagecoach Lodge) or a lift
(Boulder Lodge) up the hill to mid-level staging areas. Here you
take lifts to higher elevations and to a network of runs, lifts and
four on-the-mountain lodges.
</P>
<P>
   The pinnacle of them all is the Skyline Trail, which starts on
the mountain rim, reachable by the Sky Express, with more than 10
intermediate routes and one black diamond available to get back
down.
</P>
<P>
   For non-skiers, you can take the Aerial Tramway ($14) from
California Lodge up across the face of the famous Gunbarrel Run,
and then to the Top of the Tram Lodge. A beer and a cup of wine
will cost $10 here. A half hour later, you realize you just paid
$38 for two, and for what? Why, for that view, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it is priceless, and getting here without having to
walk is definitely cheating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
