<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FLEMING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENEE FLEMING MAKES HER SOLO MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Renee Fleming shines as the brightest soprano star in opera
today. But she's arrived at a period in her career and in her
personal life when she wants to concentrate more on recital
appearances, which are less time-consuming _ if hardly less
labor-intensive. Fleming's daughters, 6 and 3, are now in school
and preschool in Connecticut and not as portable as they used to
be; Fleming wants to stick near home so she can spend more time
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the soprano is a born recitalist. When she sang in
Seiji Ozawa Hall at Tanglewood two summers ago, Andre Previn went
on record saying that it was the best vocal recital he'd heard in
his life. Fleming is now near the end of the American segment of
her first major international recital tour (14 concerts in all).
</P>
<P>
   After Fleming sang a Friday matinee performance of Haydn's ``The
Creation'' with James Levine and the Boston Symphony last December,
she unwound with coffee and pastry in her hotel lounge and talked
about her life and career. She was happy with the performance she'd
just sung. ``Singing `The Creation' is like sending your voice to
Canyon Ranch. I jumped at the chance, because I'd never sung the
whole thing before, although I studied the arias when I was in
graduate school and sang one or two of the solos. My first manager
was exclusively interested in opera, so that's where I started and
where I stayed, so far. I've had little opportunity to sing in
oratorio _ believe it or not, I've never sung `Messiah.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A glamorous image &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fleming creates a glamorous image onstage, but she leaves it
there; she's very down to earth, not to say streetwise, about her
career. She's a worker, and that's why she has continued to develop
and improve during the dozen years since her first appearances as
Frasquita in ``Carmen'' and Belle in Thea Musgrave's ``A Christmas
Carol'' at the Virginia Opera in 1986; most careers can be charted
only in terms of decline once celebrity is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's been easy. More than once, Fleming has been in the
wrong place in the wrong role at the wrong time, even since
arriving at the very top of her profession. That moment can
probably be dated 1994, when Sir Georg Solti cast her in concert
performances of Mozart's ``Cosi fan tutte'' that led to London
Records signing her as an exclusive artist _ the first American
singer London had signed to such a contract since Marilyn Horne,
more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming's parents, both music teachers, had warned her that
performing was a risky career. At New York's Potsdam State College,
she majored in music education: ``My parents said, `Don't even
think about a performance degree.' '' Fleming's first important
teacher was Patricia Misslin, who encouraged what has remained a
career-long interest in contemporary music. After hours Fleming
sang with a jazz trio and astonished famous professional jazz
musicians with her command of the idiom. (Next month, she will
record her first jazz album.) After graduating from Potsdam State,
Fleming did graduate work at the Eastman School of Music in
Rochester before moving on to the Juilliard School, where she
started studying with Beverley Johnson, who remains her teacher
today.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '80s, Fleming won a Fulbright grant to study in
Europe with soprano Arleen Auger and the collaborative pianist
Hartmut Hoell. Praised for her articulate and even trills in ``The
Creation,'' Fleming accepted the compliment on Auger's behalf.
``She showed me how she did it, and then I could do it too. She was
a wonderful singer and teacher. The work I did that year with
Hartmut Hoell is what makes it possible for me to be a serious
recitalist today. To study with someone like that was so thrilling
and so instructive; he's a genius. Helen Yorke, the pianist with
whom I sang at Tanglewood, also worked with him at that time. It
was very intense, and both of us adored it. That year I really
learned to speak German; the other languages have come in since.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Demoralizing classes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At this same time, Fleming participated in master classes with
the legendary retired diva Elisabeth Schwarzkopf, an experience
that she found demoralizing although she feels that some press
accounts of this episode have been ``blown up way out of
proportion. What Schwarzkopf had to offer was tremendous, but the
technical aspects of what she was asking for I was not able to do
until much later. I don't think she was in tune with the level of
student she was working with. I still love her singing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming came back from Europe with some vocal problems; she was
trying to put her voice into a straitjacket _ later she remarked,
``I didn't have any vocal problems, so I invented some.''
Nevertheless, her career began to take off when she sang the
Countess in ``The Marriage of Figaro'' for Houston Opera in 1988;
it became one of her signature roles, and she sang it everywhere.
As her career expanded, so did a measure of controversy: She seemed
a competent but generic soprano, though one with an uncommonly
pretty voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people may not have counted on,'' Fleming says, ``is that
I am a voracious learner, and that I was working in the most
methodical way to improve; I would say that the first 10 years I
worked with Beverley Johnson were almost entirely spent on
technical work. When I started out, I had no high notes and I
couldn't sing softly; now I do, and now I can. Now I'm on a
maintenance program, and technique is not the complete focus of my
work. I'm interested in my emotional development and in the
expressive power of singing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming's first years were filled with exploratory ventures. She
performed roles she doesn't think she'll sing again, like Konstanze
in Mozart's ``The Abduction From the Seraglio'' and Eva in ``Die
Meistersinger,'' and a lot of one-off parts for special occasions.
``Now I want to stop adding so many roles, and want to repeat them
instead, and, hopefully, improve on them. But I don't want to get
typecast as a specialist, as a Mozart-Strauss singer, for example;
I'd be missing out on too much.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Problems at La Scala &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can stretch,'' says Fleming, in understatement. She has
excelled in coloratura roles of the bel canto period, and she plans
to keep performing them, though she ran afoul of the claque at La
Scala when she sang Donizetti's ``Lucrezia Borgia'' last fall. ``I
loved the opera, the cast, the rehearsal period. And who knows what
caused it all, except that it was organized, and it was basically
five or six guys in the audience _ but five or six very loud ones.
There was no problem with the general audience, which was screaming
for these guys to come downstairs. I was able to black it out and
sing, but it wasn't easy to get back onstage for the next
performance.'' Fleming didn't sing the whole run of ``Lucrezia
Borgia,'' but she'll fling down the gantlet Feb. 8 when she takes
her recital program to the stage of La Scala.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming's bel canto roles include ``Il Pirata,'' ``Maria
Padilla,'' ``La Sonnambula,'' ``Il viaggio a Reims,'' and ``La
Straniera.'' She has recorded ``Rosamunda d'Inghilterra'' and, in
live performance, Rossini's ``Armida,'' a role most sopranos since
Callas have avoided (she confesses that she loves to listen to some
of her own daredevil feats on Sony's live recording of the opera).
She has sung many of the Mozart/Strauss favorites as well, and made
Dvorak's ``Russalka'' into another signature role. Among her
contemporary operas are Corigliano's ``The Ghosts of Versailles,''
Susa's ``The Dangerous Liaisons,'' and Andre Previn's ``A Streetcar
Named Desire'' (``It's like singing two Salomes back to back, but I
love it _ you would never guess it was anyone's very first
opera''). Her French operas to date include ``Manon,'' ``Thais,''
``Herodiade,'' ``La Dame Blanche,'' and ``Faust,'' with ``Louise''
on the way. Her next recording is ``Star-Cross'd Lovers,'' an album
with Placido Domingo of love duets from Shakespeare operas paired
with the parallel scenes acted by Lynn Redgrave and Timothy Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   Her anchor through all of this, Fleming has often said, has been
her home life and marriage to actor Richard Ross, though the couple
is now in the middle of a painful divorce. That was one unstated
reason the soprano withdrew from the Metropolitan Opera's new
production of Verdi's ``La Traviata'' late last fall. Naturally
some people attributed this cancellation to diva whim, but few
divas appear less whimsical than Renee Fleming. ``Bad behavior,
makeup, practicing kicking your train in front of the mirror _ I
think there are more important ways to be a diva than this. It's
about the music, not about the ego. What matters is what happens
when you open your mouth to sing; you should give joy to people,
you should touch somebody's heart. When I listen to someone sing, I
want to be touched spiritually. Right now, I am concerned about
being who I am, about continuing to grow, about seeing where it
will all go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
