<HEADLINE>
ICE CLIMBING IN ADIRONDACKS BECOMES A HOT PASSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (With: ICE-CLIMBING-INFO.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEENE, N.Y. _ Ice-climbing guide Nick Yardley knew the right
face of Pitchoff Mountain would be crowded on a recent Saturday
morning. So in order to save prime parking for the nine students in
his beginning ice climbing seminar, he sent a helper ahead to shoo
away other cars from the tiny pullout on the side of state Route
73.
</P>
<P>
   Once parked, we climbed up the steep snow, wearing clunky
plastic climbing boots and rigid, 12-point crampons that bite into
the ice. At the base of the cliffs, there were three ropes already
set up for us to tie into. Within the hour, two other groups
arrived, and every conceivable route on the ice face had a climber
on it, crampons on each foot and high-tech, pick-shaped ice axes in
each hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be prepared to be miserable,'' the Welshman warned us when we
first met. ``You're going to spend the day either freezing to death
or sweating profusely.''
</P>
<P>
   Misery must love company, because an awful lot of people are ice
climbing these days. We were here for the third annual Adirondack
International Mountaineering Festival on Jan. 16 and 17. But crowds
on Adirondack ice is becoming the rule here, even on normal
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   These days, instead of finding virgin ice on popular routes,
climbers are finding the frozen flows and waterfalls turned into
pegboards by the dozens of climbers who preceded them. Some climbs
are becoming a nearly mindless activity of putting your ax blade in
holes made by the climber before you.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the downfalls of success, climbers say. The
popularity that resulted in the overwhelming success of the
Mountaineering Festival also has led to lines at the base of
climbs.
</P>
<P>
   Ice climbing, despite the inherent dangers and expensive gear,
is threatening to become as mainstream as rock climbing, its
warm-weather cousin. So many climbers attended the festival that a
Saturday night slide show was packed nearly to capacity. They so
overwhelmed an all-you-can-eat pasta dinner that dozens of climbers
had to stand and wait while cooks hustled to a nearby grocery store
to pick up more food.
</P>
<P>
   What this shows, climbers here say, is that the climbing world
at large finally is starting to notice the Adirondacks after
decades of ignoring the region in upstate New York. Climbers came
to the mountaineering festival from as far as Washington, D.C., to
take lessons from some of the world's greatest alpinists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most congested day (on ice routes) in the history
of the Adirondacks,'' said Don Mellor, a guide and author of
``Climbing in the Adirondacks,'' a bible for anyone who attempts
vertical routes here.
</P>
<P>
   Mellor, who taught a popular seminar called ``Steep Ice for the
Weak and Chicken-hearted,'' said he thought a mountain festival was
a stupid idea three years ago. He was contacted by his friend Vinny
McClelland, the festival co-organizer and owner of the Mountaineer
outdoor equipment store.
</P>
<P>
   Mellor wondered: How many people would come all the way up to
the Adirondacks to celebrate mountain climbing? A lot, it turned
out.
</P>
<P>
   This year, more than 300 climbers made their way north to help
raise money for local fire departments and non-profit groups like
the Access Fund, a group dedicated to keeping climbing areas around
the country open to climbers.
</P>
<P>
   Classes ranged from snowshoeing to advanced ice-climbing to
learning how to travel safely in avalanche country. And, for those
of us who have never ice-climbed before, a class for beginners.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes of instructions, we were gripping ice tools
and confidently shoving crampons into the ice. Yardley, a guide in
North Conway, N.H., was full of tips:
</P>
<P>
   Put your entire arm into driving the ice tool forward. Look for
dishes in the ice, which are stronger than bulges and won't shatter
as much. Keep your ankles below your toes when you kick your feet.
Take advantage of every rest position. Don't clutch the ice tools
hard, or else your fingers will get cold and lose strength. Walk
with your legs splayed out, like a cowboy, and you won't puncture
your expensive Gore-Tex bib overalls with crampons (one unfortunate
soul did just that later in the day).
</P>
<P>
   Eight hours after the class first met, we were climbing like
pros and begging for more.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night was the infamous pasta dinner, where dozens of
climbers still in their shells and fleece waited for the cooks to
come back from the store. ``It'll be 10 minutes,'' the man at the
door said, but after a half-hour it was apparent that wasn't true.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the beer was locally brewed Kobor Wheat, and
only $1 per cup.
</P>
<P>
   An even bigger crowd showed up for the slide show by Barry
Blanchard, one of the world's most talented ice climbers. Blanchard
dazzled the crowd for 90 minutes with tales of death-defying
climbs.
</P>
<P>
   After the show, Blanchard said he was impressed by Adirondack
ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a couple really noteworthy ascents,'' he said. ``I'd
like to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, climbing does have its dangers. Take what happened to
one man we met the next day while back-country skiing to Avalanche
Lake. He joined us as we looked up the 500-foot cliffs, then
pointed to a popular and easy climb in a notch in the cliff called
the Trap Dike.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, our friend had been climbing unroped,
carrying skis strapped to his pack to ski the steep slides on the
far side. He was about 100 feet up when he slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe how fast it happened,'' he recalled. ``It
was like someone tied a rope to my ankle and hooked it up to a John
Deere tractor.'' Before he knew it, he was bouncing and flailing
back down the ice-filled gully.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing I could do,'' he said. ``It happened in slow
motion. Ripped my pack to shreds, cracked my helmet.'' Amazingly,
he got snagged in some trees that broke his fall, along with some
ribs and his ankle. Rescuers carried him out and he recovered.
Several years later, he's back on skis and climbing again.
</P>
<P>
   These days, he uses a rope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1410EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
