<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7106 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-01 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S BEST BET FOR DAUGHTER'S IRA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am considering helping my daughter to set up an IRA, both
with advice and with funding to the extent that I can. What are
your thoughts about conventional versus Roth IRAs for a 40-year-old
self-employed homeowner?
</P>
<P>
   G.O., Gearhart, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are two basic things to think about when contemplating
a Roth IRA versus a traditional account. One is the likely tax
bracket of the IRA's owner in retirement, and the second is the
period of time the money will be saved before retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The latter factor is easy enough to understand. With a Roth IRA,
the owner pays the taxes up front, contributing after-tax dollars
rather than taking the tax deduction which has long been one of the
most attractive features of traditional IRA. With the Roth, the
owner foregoes that deduction, but in compensation, all of the
money accumulated in the account can be withdrawn tax-free in
retirement. If it's a long investment time frame, the amount of the
investment earnings should dwarf the amount of the original
contribution. Suppose, for example, that your daughter opens a
$2,000 Roth IRA this year and leaves the funds invested until she
is aged 65. If she's in the 28 percent tax bracket, she will forego
the $560 tax deduction that she could have realized by using a
traditional IRA.
</P>
<P>
   But if she goes with the Roth account and the IRA money produces
average annual returns of 10 percent over the next 25 years, at
that point she will have amassed $21,668 in the account. Not only
can that money be withdrawn with no tax consequences, but there are
no strictures dictating mandatory withdrawal schedules after age 70
1/2 (as there are with traditional IRAs and other tax-deferred
saving programs). The only stricture on penalty-free withdrawals
from Roth accounts is that the owner must be past age 59 1/2 when
they are taken, and the funds withdrawn must have been in the
account for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   Withdrawals can also be taken before age 59 1/2 without penalty
if the owner becomes disabled, or withdraws up to $10,000 to be
used for a first-time home purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to get back to that first factor _ the owner's tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly if the owner of an IRA is in a very low tax bracket, it
makes little sense to go with a traditional IRA. Since the tax
break is a deduction rather than a credit, a person who faces
little or nothing in the way of tax liability will get little or no
short-term benefit from a traditional IRA. A perfect example of a
person who would greatly profit from a Roth account would be a
teenager with a part-time job. Since the wages aren't likely to be
high enough to generate a significant tax liability, when this
person saves through a Roth IRA they sacrifice very little up front
and they get a whole lot in retirement. As an example, if a
17-year-old puts $1,000 in a Roth IRA that earns 10 percent
returns, that $1,000 would grow to $97,017 by the time the owner
reaches age 65 _ and all of it can be withdrawn tax free.
</P>
<P>
   But let's look at the other end of the spectrum. If a person is
relatively close to retirement age, is in a fairly high tax
bracket, and anticipates that he or she will be in a lower tax
bracket in retirement, a traditional IRA is the better choice.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a person who is in the 31 percent tax bracket now,
who will retire in 10 years, and who will pay a 28 percent tax in
retirement. If this person put $2,000 in a traditional IRA and it
earns 10 percent average returns for 10 years, the account will be
worth $5,187.
</P>
<P>
   If it is then withdrawn and a 28 percent tax paid, the owner
will net $3,735. In contrast, if this person went with a Roth IRA,
investing $1,380 (after using $620 to pay the taxes due taxes now)
he or she would build a pool worth only $3,579 after a decade,
using the same assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   Two other factors should also be considered in weighing a Roth
IRA.
</P>
<P>
   First, if a person is uncertain of what their financial
situation will be in retirement but is optimistic that they will be
in a comfortable situation, the Roth IRA seems attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if people worry that tax rates in general will be higher
by the time they reach retirement age _ and certainly people in
their 40s and younger should consider that all this talk about the
possible crash of the Social Security system is well founded _ they
can buy themselves a nice insurance policy by going with a Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, one final factor when it comes to your daughter's
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions to both Roth and traditional IRAs are limited to
$2,000, and the owner must earn at least as much as the
contribution. As a self-employed person, your daughter might open a
SEP-IRA or establish a Keogh plan _ both of which allow higher
levels of contributions than IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   When you consider that if your daughter made the maximum
contributions to either a traditional or Roth IRA until age 65 and
if the accounts earned 10 percent returns, she would have a total
of $204,920 in the account _ a sum which would produce a mighty
thin income stream right now, muchless after 25 years of inflation
has sapped its buying power.
</P>
<P>
   So the short lesson is that neither a Roth nor a traditional IRA
is likely to be enough for a 40-year-old who won't be able to count
on any other significant income stream in retirement. It's a nice
start, but she should be thinking of other plans as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 32 years old and have worked for almost two years,
earning about $29,000 a year. I put 15 percent of my salary in a
401(k) program invested in stock mutual funds, and also have
taxable accounts in AIM Constellation and AIM Balanced funds, with
a combined value of about $3,850; I add $100 a month to these
accounts. Finally, I have $10,000 in a CD and $4,000 in a savings
account. My goals are to get a used car and a house this year or
next. I would buy the house with my brother, dividing the costs. I
am also dreaming of having enough money to live in retirement. Can
I achieve these goals _ and how can I do it?
</P>
<P>
   P.L., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think your idea of building a solid retirement pool
is a dream; if you continue to put 15 percent of your earnings in a
401(k) program or some other retirement plan _ raising the dollar
amount contributed every time you get a raise _ you should end up
in nice shape.
</P>
<P>
   But the other goals seem more problematical. While I don't know
a great deal about the San Diego real estate market, details in
letters from correspondents over the years lead me to believe that
both real estate prices and real estate taxes are substantial.
Let's suppose you considered the taxable mutual fund accounts and
your $10,000 CD money as being available for a real estate
purchase. Since you view a home purchase as a short-term goal, the
stock funds would be the wrong vehicle for saving _ stock funds are
simply too volatile for a short-term saving program. Better to
stick to CDs or money market funds. Now, if you continued to add
$100 a month to this pool, after two years, you would have about
$17,786, presuming 5 percent average returns from the accounts.
Then the next question is whether $35,572 (with your brother
matching your contribution) is enough for a down payment, and
whether you would could then be able to budget enough to pay your
share of the mortgage, taxes, insurance, and other costs of
home-ownership. My visceral sense is that you'd be cutting a very
thin line, if it can work at all. Better, I think, to consider this
a five-year savings program, at which time your savings would
amount to $24,459, and presumably your salary would have advanced
to a stage where the costs of home ownership won't seem as
oppressive as I imagine they would be now.
</P>
<P>
   As for the car, you're going to face the same kind of problems _
buying a car, even a very used car, is just a beginning. Then comes
insurance, registration costs, regular maintenance _ and you have
to be prepared for the prospect of significant repair bills. The
more used the car, the more significant the repairs are likely to
be. I know nothing of your living expenses, but my guess is that if
you analyze your situation carefully you'll find that you can view
the house and the car only as an either/or proposition. And if you
do get hung up on that debate, I'll give you my perspective: Houses
last longer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I need advice from you on a fee-for-service basis.
</P>
<P>
   M.R., Arlington, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sorry, but no can do. This question seems to come up with
some regularity, and as fond of money as I am, I must decline: I'm
a journalist and not a financial planner, and thus it would be
illegal for me to provide individual investment advice on a fee
basis.
</P>
<P>
   (Questions? Send letters, including your name, address and
telephone number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
