<HEADLINE>
HAVING AN ICE TIME IN THE ADIRONDACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interested in ice climbing in the Adirondacks? Here is some
information that will help:
</P>
<P>
   _ Guide services in the Adirondacks:
</P>
<P>
   Adirondack Rock and River, 518-576-2041
</P>
<P>
   Adirondack Alpine Adventures, 518-576-9881
</P>
<P>
   _ Books to read:
</P>
<P>
   ``Climbing Ice'' by Yvon Chouinard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountaineering: Freedom of the Hills,'' an excellent guidebook
that covers all facets of mountain travel and safety, by the
Mountaineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice Tools and Techniques'' by Duane Raleigh (published by
Climbing Magazine).
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice World'' by Jeff Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Climbing in the Adirondacks'' by Don Mellor (a guidebook for
the experienced).
</P>
<P>
   _ Note: Climbing can be extremely dangerous. You should not try
ice climbing until you are familiar with rope safety, anchor
systems and ice-climbing techniques, as taught by an expert.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ice climbing is not cheap. Assuming you have the right winter
clothes (an expensive venture to begin with), here's your minimum
investment, in addition to the clothing:
</P>
<P>
   Two technical ice axes: about $300 each.
</P>
<P>
   Mountaineering boots (rigid-soled, must accept rigid crampons):
$200 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   Rigid crampons: $100 to $150.
</P>
<P>
   Helmet: $50 to $90.
</P>
<P>
   Rope (dry-coated, some prefer using double ropes): $100 to $250.
</P>
<P>
   Harness: $40 to $80.
</P>
<P>
   Various carabiners, nylon slings and a belay device: $50 to
$100.
</P>
</TEXT>
