A7115 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHORS-BALL-SPI &LR;      02-01 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-BALL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR'S SEARCH WAS A HARD JOURNEY BACK TO SLAVE DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was something that seemed necessary in his quest to confront
his family's past as slave holders in South Carolina, Edward Ball
thought, something he had to at least attempt. He would try to
track down and meet with some descendants of the slaves from the
various Ball plantations around Charleston, a personal attempt at
racial reconciliation that was opposed by many in his own family
and that filled him with fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a good idea to make some small gesture toward
the black families that our family had damaged,'' Ball said in an
interview. ``But I was afraid people would be angry, would refuse
to see me. I was afraid I would make people even more upset and I
might hurt them by bringing up painful memories. Worry was my
mind-set, and also fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball persisted, despite the doors that slammed in his face,
despite the New York black newspaper that castigated his plans. He
persisted because he also experienced moving moments that he will
never forget.
</P>
<P>
   They are the soul of Ball's remarkable ``Slaves in the Family''
(Ballantine, 453 pages, $15.95), which was the surprise winner of
the recent National Book Award for non-fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The award was such a surprise to the 40-year-old writer that,
moments before it was announced, he was perched on a men's room
sink scribbling possible acceptance remarks on a cocktail napkin _
until a stranger recognized him and he quit.
</P>
<P>
   There is still a certain shocked aura about Ball, a man of
Southern reserve and patrician bearing in a serious pin-striped
suit. The writer, who was educated at prestigious Brown University,
has not only seen his first book win the National Book Award. It
was also named ``the most overrated book of 1998'' by Salon
magazine, the Internet publication. These contradictory assessments
bring a bemused smile to Ball's face.
</P>
<P>
   He is far less sanguine about other criticism he has received,
particularly from those who prefer that slavery's horrors remain
buried in the past and those who think that his frank apologies to
two black families for his ancestors' sins amount to nothing more
than exercises in liberal guilt or even ``self-flagellation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand there is a lot of resentment out there,'' Ball
emphasized. ``I have given talks where people stand up and say this
slavery thing was settled 100 years ago, or people who say they
were born long after the Civil War, so what has this to do with me?
Comments like that remind about how many Germans say they had
nothing to do with Auschwitz and that was settled long ago, so why
make people upset about it now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand those comments because most of us don't want to
acknowledge that events of the past influence our daily lives
today. We like to think that we invented ourselves, that we are
masters of our own destinies, and that a background as white people
doesn't have anything to do with where we are professionally or
socially. But I truly think that my advantages as a white person
have catapulted me ahead of black people, in education, in jobs, in
housing. It is simply dishonest to say otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball's heartfelt words make him an easy target in this jaded era
when genuine emotion has been so undermined by politics and
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But Ball _ who admits feeling ``not guilt, but accountability''
for what his ancestors did _ is not content with mere talk. He
shared some of his publisher's advance with the black families who
were kind enough to let him tell their stories. And he has now
pledged 25 percent of his earnings from ``Slaves in the Family'' to
establish a foundation to undertake some projects that will involve
both members of the Ball family and descendants of their slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a reparations program,'' Ball said. ``That would
be impossible, I wouldn't know where to begin, even if there had
been a fortune handed down in our family from slave days, which
there is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are baby steps we are taking, involving a handful of
individuals, some black, some white, doing what is within their
power to reckon with a legacy we share.''
</P>
<P>
   That shared legacy, as uncovered by Ball's research,
contradicted Ball family legends of being benevolent owners of
their human property.
</P>
<P>
   Ball ancestors, who owned an estimated 4,000 slaves, turned out
to have run the largest U.S. company involved in the lucrative
African slave trade; to have ripped apart some slave families
forever; to have acceded to cruel punishments of slaves that
included whippings and amputations of limbs; to have engaged in
sexual relations between masters and slaves.
</P>
<P>
   That shared legacy, thanks to the voluminous records in the Ball
family, also allowed Ball to present descendants of his family's
slaves with the first information about some of their ancestors.
One of the lingering wounds of slavery has been that many African
Americans have had much of their family past erased.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why something remarkable often happened when Ball
shared the fruits of his research.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first few meetings with black families when it was
frightening for all of us, I could sense that we were communicating
and finding common ground,'' Ball emphasized. ``They were curious
and they wanted to know more _ and the more we talked about the
hard stuff, the more they wanted to know. I soon got clued in that
this was something that black people wanted to do, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So there may be no more powerful image from the pages of
``Slaves in the Family'' than that of a white man and a black man
walking across what once had been Limerick plantation.
</P>
<P>
   Ball had asked Thomas Martin, a retired school principal, if he
might want to visit the place where the writer had discovered his
grandfather had been born. Martin, who had never heard of the
place, readily agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The two men walked in silence across land that showed no trace
of its former use, except for the row of stately oaks leading to
where the plantation house once stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hallowed ground,'' Martin said after a while. ``I feel
like I'm walking in the footsteps of Jesus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1418EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7125 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHORS-BRANCH-SPI &LR;      02-01 1769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-BRANCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOGRAPHER PUTS MARTIN LUTHER KING ON CENTER STAGE OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty years after his murder, the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr. has streets and schools named after him all over the country.
His birthday is a national holiday. Almost everybody knows his name
and acts respectful when it's mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   While that is entirely appropriate, the man himself is being
distorted in the process, contends writer Taylor Branch. ``King is
presented as a goody-goody,'' he said. ``His call to non-violence
is seen as nothing but a form of good manners. Just be nice.
Nothing could be further from the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch is now researching the third and final volume of his
history of the civil rights movement, whose overall title is
``America in the King Years.''
</P>
<P>
   The first book, ``Parting the Waters,'' won the 1988 Pulitzer
Prize for history and covered the years 1954 to 1963. The second,
``Pillar of Fire,'' published in 1998, covered 1963 to 1965. (Both
are now in paperback.) The third and final book, ``At Canaan's
Edge,'' will cover 1966 to 1968 and take Branch well into the next
century to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally I planned to take three years and write one book,''
he said in an interview. ``I've spent 16 years and I'm still
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in his early 50s, Branch grew up in Alabama and retains in
his speech a bit of soft drawl. Although he did not participate in
the civil rights movement, the upheaval of it changed his life and
made him see the world and his place in it in a new way. Once he
got into journalism, he decided that period was the one he wanted
to explore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't satisfied with what had been written,'' he said.
``What was missing was the human stories. That's what I've tried to
provide. I'm not writing a King biography. A good biography gets
down to the heartbeat of its subject. That would be difficult for
me as a white person to accomplish. Instead I'm trying to present
King amid the thousands of people who gathered around him and
helped him make history.''
</P>
<P>
   In this, Branch is remarkably successful. The narrative that
extends over 1,500 pages in the first two books gathers thousands
of threads together without bogging down or losing its dramatic
edge. In the end, what Branch has described is nothing less than
one of the most decisive and important periods in American history,
with King at its center.
</P>
<P>
   Branch's cast includes such giants as Fanny Lou Hamer, Diane
Nash Bevel, James Bevel, Robert Moses, Julian Bond, Andrew Young,
Septima Clark, Medgar Evers, Stanley Levison, Bayard Rustin, Rabbi
Abraham Heschel and Malcolm X, with a wealth of new material on
Malcolm X's last days.
</P>
<P>
   There are an equal number of memorable, murderous heavies and
plenty of people who couldn't rouse themselves to do more than
deplore both sides. As King put it, ``Shallow understanding from
people of good will is more frustrating than absolute
misunderstanding from people of ill will.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the Rev. Jesse Jackson doesn't make an appearance
in either book. ``He's pissed about that,'' said Branch, smiling.
``He'll be in the third book.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch begins before King was born, exploring the significance
of the church for black Americans, not only as places of worship
but centers of community information, credit unions and even
people's courts. White bigotry was so common it wasn't notable even
to most white people of good will unless accompanied by violence.
</P>
<P>
   Will Rogers, who famously said he ``never met a man he didn't
like,'' was offended in the 1930s when the NAACP asked him not to
use the most derogatory racial slur for black people in his NBC
radio broadcast. He had opened the show by using it four times.
Eventually, he agreed to use the less offensive term of ``darky.''
</P>
<P>
   The integration of the armed forces after World War II set off a
firestorm in the South. Six black veterans were lynched in the
first week after their return. After that, black veterans rarely
wore their uniforms in public.
</P>
<P>
   Branch does a masterful job at bringing this period to life,
setting the stage for King and the movement he came to lead, not
only covering the well-known events such as the Little Rock school
integration crisis and Rosa Parks in the bus boycott, but giving
them vital context.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Eisenhower gets good press these days but not from
Branch, who ably shows him to be a racist by anybody's definition.
</P>
<P>
   John and Robert F. Kennedy are romantic figures to many
liberals, and yet they come off remarkably badly when responding to
King. They'd be stunned by Branch's title, ``America in the King
Years.'' They thought they were living in the Kennedy years.
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy could never wrap his brain around the idea
that King was a major figure. Robert, as attorney general, got
bullied by J. Edgar Hoover into signing the order to wiretap King
and even at the end of his life hadn't managed to free himself of
Hoover's insane view of King. (Both Kennedys expressed the idea
that Hoover was out of his mind, Robert referring to him as a
psycho.)
</P>
<P>
   While King was in Sweden to accept the Nobel Peace Prize, Robert
wrote in his journal that he never had a conversation with King
about anything but communism and its effect on the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   That was Hoover's agenda, even though the FBI director knew the
American Communist Party had fallen from its membership heights in
the 1930s of roughly 80,000 to about 5,000 in the 1950s. So many of
those 5,000 were FBI informants, writes Branch, that Hoover toyed
with the idea of taking the party over, as he had the votes.
</P>
<P>
   And yet he relentlessly focused on his anti-Communist crusade,
seeing King as a public enemy and Communist dupe. Branch
graphically describes how the FBI hounded King. King was held in
such low repute by Hoover that he instructed his men not to warn
him if they heard of an assassination threat.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon Baines Johnson was a different story. He had an
instinctive sympathy with civil rights and pushed hard to support
it, even though he understood he'd be losing the Southern states to
the Republican party for the foreseeable future. Two weeks into his
presidency, he warned his Senate mentor, Richard Russell of
Georgia, that ``if you get in my way'' on the civil rights bill,
``I'm going to run you down.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Branch said during the interview, Johnson's
inability to rise to the challenge of non-violence got him and the
country stuck in the Vietnam. ``He said repeatedly that he didn't
want to be in the war, but if he appeared to be chicken or yellow,
the people would desert him.'' Johnson turned on King when King
voiced strong criticism of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Branch thinks the Free Speech Movement and anti-war movements on
college campuses were at their hearts missed opportunities because
they failed to link with the more complex and sophisticated civil
rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They covered the civil rights movement the way Pat Boone
covered Little Richard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   King was a living witness to the power of the non-violent ideal,
and as such he's taken more seriously outside the United States
than in it, Branch said. ``John Hume in Ireland said King is his
greatest inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who have said King helped shape their lives include
Vaclav Havel in the Czech Republic, Aung San Suu Kyi in Myanmar and
the leaders of the uprising at Tiananmen Square in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did Germans sing `We Shall Overcome' when the Berlin Wall
fell?'' asked Branch. ``That was in honor of King. Anyone who
thinks his impact is limited to black people hasn't begun to
understand him.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pillar of Fire,'' Branch writes that ``King believed the
roots of democracy can be found not in French or Greek philosophers
but in the Hebrew prophets and their idea of equal souls. He
believed that humans could transcend enemy thinking. At stake was
nothing less than the capacity to lighten the stain of evil and
demonstrate the possibility of justice in the world's design, which
for King was the realization of God's presence. His moral intensity
in this regard struck President Kennedy as narrow and stifling.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides King, the major figure in ``Pillar of Fire'' is Malcom
X, with a wealth of new material about the turmoil of his life at
its end. Malcolm X never believed in non-violence or even in
democracy, but he had the honesty to admit his position of ``waste
your enemies'' was hollow, as Elijah Muhammad wouldn't let him or
anyone else defend Black Muslims who fell under physical attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire Malcolm X's honesty, and his ability to see his own
flaws and reinvent himself, not once but several times,'' said
Branch.
</P>
<P>
   In his history, Branch touches on the subject of King's
extramarital affairs, which came to light thanks to the FBI taps on
King's phones, hotel rooms and living quarters. ``King suffered
great guilt on this subject,'' said Branch. ``Anyone expecting a
human being to be perfect is not realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch pointed out that non-violence was ``the first idea from
the 1960s to be discarded, and yet it changed not only the country
but the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch said he finds it disheartening that supporters of
anti-affirmative action initiatives, including the recently passed
Proposition 200 in Washington state, claim King would have been on
their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're using King's language without his spirit,'' Branch
said. His eyebrows shot up when he recalled reading that Newt
Gingrich claims to have been part of the civil rights movement
because he was in the South as a volunteer for Barry Goldwater's
presidential campaign in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means Gingrich was completely opposed to the civil rights
movement,'' he said. ``Republicans got a foothold in the South in
1964 for the first time since the Civil War specifically because
they opposed civil rights. But the reporter didn't know his history
and let the claim stand unchallenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked in the interview who is providing moral leadership in the
country today, Branch paused. ``Clinton is the best president on
civil rights we've had since LBJ,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But moral leadership, being in the vanguard of positive social
change, doesn't come from presidents. It comes from the people. The
people have to lead their leaders. Not too many hopeful voices are
raised now, but Jesse Jackson has kept faith with the ideal of
non-violence. We need more people to understand the civil rights
era so they can carry the best of it on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
