<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Feb. 2:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-NEWBORNS (Chicago) _ Researchers at an annual AIDS
meeting report results from a study in Africa showing that a
simple, short drug regimen produces striking reductions in
transmission rates of the AIDS virus from mothers to newborns. The
regimen involves giving relatively inexpensive drugs to the women
from several weeks before delivery, during labor and a week after.
Worldwide, 600,000 babies a year are born with HIV. By Lawrence K.
Altman. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STARDUST (Undated) _ For decades, science has known of the
importance of star dust in the cosmic scheme of things, especially
in matter more elaborate than the simple elements made in the
primordial Big Bang. But scientists have never had pure samples to
study _ but soon will, if everything goes as planned. On Saturday,
NASA is to launch a probe meant to capture interplanetary and
interstellar dust in some of its rawest and purest forms, including
many thousands of grains from a comet. By William J. Broad. (1875
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-KOOP-CRUSADES (Undated) _ At 82, Dr. C. Everett Koop remains
active working with a band of students at the institute that bears
his name. Foremost among their efforts: fighting the tobacco
industry. But Koop, the fiery surgeon general of the Reagan
administration, has other crusades as well. Among them: inadequate
medical education, obesity and vast gaps in the health care
network. By Holcomb B. Noble. (1980 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NITROGEN-EXPLOSIVE (Undated) _ For a century chemists
doubted that such a substance could exist, but scientists at an Air
Force laboratory have created a freakish form of nitrogen believed
to be one of the most violently explosive substances ever made. By
Malcolm W. Browne. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COLORS-POISONS (Undated) _ Many of the world's most
astonishingly beautiful creatures _ from dazzling fluorescent frogs
to iridescently radiant butterflies _ are its most poisonous. Their
bodies laced with toxins, these animals find safety not in hiding
from their enemies but in drawing attention to themselves. They
adorn their foul-tasting flesh in a rainbow of easy-to-remember
warning colors, loudly reminding every predator who's had the
misfortune to taste one, never to try again. A new study suggests
that certain toxic species develop the colors only when they are
present in large enough numbers to make a difference. By Carol
Kaesuk Yoon. (1175 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUANTUM-ETHER (Undated) _ That ethereal stuff known as
``ether'' _ which even survived in the popular thought despite a
trashing by Einstein _ has become a universal field of ``quantum
fields.'' This stuff is hard to define, but it is what you have
when there is nothing else. Theorists spend a lot of effort
thinking about it. Recently new light has been shed on the subject.
An essay by Malcolm W. Browne. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MONEY-PSYCH (Undated) _ Psychological researchers have
amassed an impressive body of data suggesting that satisfaction
simply is not for sale. Not only does having more things prove to
be unfulfilling, but people for whom affluence is a priority in
life tend to experience an unusual degree of anxiety and depression
as well as a lower overall level of well-being. Likewise, those who
would like nothing more than to be famous or attractive do not fare
as well, psychologically speaking, as those who primarily want to
develop close relationships, become more self-aware, or contribute
to the community. By Alfie Kohn. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YMCA-COMPETE (Undated) _ The battle between private health
clubs and nonprofit, tax-exempt centers like the YMCA now is
shifting to a courtroom with health clubs complaining they must
subsidize their competitors who save thousands a year in taxes. By
Liz Neporent. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health an fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Contrary to previous reports, women who drink moderately _ up
to one and a half alcoholic drinks a day _ may face no increased
risk of developing breast cancer, according to a decades-long study
of 5,000 women in Framingham, Mass. In fact, the study by
researchers at Boston University School of Medicine suggests that
breast cancer risk may even decline slightly as alcohol consumption
rises from none to one and a half drinks a day. But other research
is contradictory. (365 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A California study of the rapidly growing number of women
having children after the age of 40 showed that, like their younger
counterparts, almost all of the women had healthy babies. But
things were a lot more complicated along the way, especially for
first-timers. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Apple-shaped children _ those with more fat around the
midsection _ have more heart disease risk factors than their
pear-shaped peers, according to a study reported yesterday. (280
words)
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: More than
60 percent of Americans get little or no exercise, despite repeated
reminders about the myriad rewards of regular physical activity.
But now there's good news for the idle. Two studies show that
people don't have to exercise in the traditional sense _ as in
jogging, aerobics and cycling _ to glean many of the health
benefits of activity, including weight control. All you have to do
is incorporate more movement into your daily routines. By Jane E.
Brody. (1225 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STROKE-RECOVERY (Undated) _ Doctors have found a bold new
way of helping people who have had strokes recover the ability to
talk and move their limbs in the first weeks and months after brain
injury. Patients are given low doses of the common stimulant
amphetamine along with intense physical therapy _ a combination
that appears to accelerate recovery in many people. By Sandra
Blakeslee. (1370 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOSAGE-CHIP (Undated) _ Engineers from the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology have built a prototype of a sophistical
medicine delivery system: a kind of micropill, a dime-sized silicon
microchip that could release a combination of drugs on a
preprogrammed schedule or by remote control. By John O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: on using an atomic
force microscope as a writing instrument, termites' mating habits
and measuring the way muscles work. (685 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Are guinea
pigs rodents? Probably, based on structural features and fossil
evidence, though some scientists studying DNA evidence suspect
otherwise. By Claiborne L. Ray. (300 words)
</P>
