<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RULES GRANT A LIMITED TAXPAYER PRIVILEGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may have heard about new rules that shield your
conversations with your accountant.
</P>
<P>
   In a lot of ways, they sound like the attorney-client privilege,
which protects certain communications between a lawyer and client,
but they're not as broad.
</P>
<P>
   While the new Internal Revenue Service rules are similar, there
are lots of loopholes in the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   This complicated set of new rules, which gives a certain amount
of confidentiality to communications with nonattorneys over tax
advice, are part of the IRS Restructuring and Reform Act of 1998.
The rules only apply to communications after July 22, 1998. Any
communications made before that date aren't covered by the law.
</P>
<P>
   The privilege applies only to communications between taxpayers
and tax professionals authorized to practice before the IRS. That
includes certified public accountants, enrolled agents and enrolled
actuaries.
</P>
<P>
   While the privilege sounds attractive, it's filled with many
land mines:
</P>
<P>
   _You may assert the privilege only in civil tax matters before
the IRS and in any noncriminal tax case in federal court brought by
or against the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you intentionally didn't report your income or
underreported your income or took deductions you weren't allowed to
take, and you knew you weren't allowed to take, in order to lower
your tax,'' said Rhett Buck, a certified public accountant and
attorney in Houston. ``That's criminal fraud and the information
concerning that wouldn't be privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if you inadvertently failed to include income, that
would be civil fraud and that advice would be protected, said Buck,
chairman of the tax special projects committee of the Texas Society
of CPA's Houston chapter.
</P>
<P>
   _You may not claim the privilege over the actual preparation of
your tax return because the purpose of filing a return is to
disclose information to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most taxpayers, talking to a CPA about your taxes and your
tax return is going to be protected,'' Buck said. ``What's not
protected is the actual providing of the information to prepare the
return. It's planning the return vs. actually preparing the
return.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the limitations, the confidentiality privilege is good
news for taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than what the taxpayer had before, which was no
privilege when they were talking to their accountant,'' said Larry
Campagna, a partner and tax attorney at Chamberlain, Hrdlicka,
White, Williams &AMP; Martin in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules are an added layer of protection. Although Texas
law says that accountants should keep confidential the information
they receive from their clients, that doesn't apply in federal tax
matters, Campagna said.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to maintain the new privilege, you must keep your
mouth shut about tax advice you get from your accountant or
enrolled agent.
</P>
<P>
   If you blab that information to your locker-room buddy or any
other third party, you've waived the privilege because that
information is supposed to be confidential between you and your
accountant.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you share the information with your spouse and
you're filing a joint tax return, you could claim the privilege,
Buck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campagna's Rule No. 1 in dealing with the IRS is to keep
quiet,'' Campagna said. ``Speak only when spoken to and tell as
little as possible. Sometimes one word in the wrong situation can
be one word too many.''
</P>
<P>
   As with any new law, especially one dealing with taxes, lawyers
are still trying to figure out what's firmly defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess,'' said Steven Salch, tax partner at Fulbright &AMP;
Jaworski in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, can accountants or even lawyers within accounting
firms advise clients on the issue of whether the privilege applies
to them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the privilege provision will be in the Internal Revenue
Code, maybe it is considered to be tax advice, but advice about the
applicability of a privilege generally has been considered to be
legal advice beyond the purview of accounting work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other thing is that the government would consider disclosure
of privileged information to another federal agency a waiver of the
privilege, Campagna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what if that disclosure were compelled by law?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the IRS is just starting to sort out the ambiguities in the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are gray areas and there are exceptions, and at this
point, no one knows how this is going to be interpreted by the
courts,'' said an IRS official, who asked to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   To voice comments, telephone 713-220-2000 and dial in code 1003.
Send e-mail to pamela.yip(at)chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
