<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-AFRICANAMERICAN-AR     02-01 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AFRICANAMERICAN-ARTS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS SERIES EXPOSES BLACK ARTISTS' DILEMMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rondell Sheridan always felt he was getting the cold shoulder
from Russell Simmons, the self-made peddler of such culturally
aesthetic fare as the stand-up comedy series ``Def Comedy Jam.''
So, bumping into Simmons in New York City, he simply asked why, and
Simmons simply said: Sheridan wasn't ``revolutionary'' _ from
Simmons' vantage point, Sheridan's political, social and cultural
affinities didn't do much to aid the consciousness of black
liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons was referring to Sheridan's comedy act.
</P>
<P>
   Seems ever since he'd stepped on stage more than a decade
earlier, Sheridan had found success in delivering a race-neutral
act to a collection of black and brown, but mostly white, faces.
His material wasn't born out of racism or deep-seated pain due to
poverty or oppression _ but of a well-adjusted, impeccably mannered
youngster educated in Catholic schools and reared within one of
Chicago's black, middle-class, middle-of-the-political-road
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't use skin color as a reference. Still, it's hardly a
good feeling knowing you aren't accepted because your artistic
ideology is perceived to be out of step with your own homeboys.
</P>
<P>
   Producers of the six-hour PBS series ``I'll Make Me a World: A
Century of African-American Arts,'' which began Monday and
continues Tuesday and Wednesday, had long envisioned it as a
catalyst for national discussion on black arts, and it's certainly
that. The documentary is the final project of the late Henry
Hampton, whose earlier work included the groundbreaking ``Eyes on
the Prize'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it serves up the engaging personal tales of a selective
group of African-American artists _ noting their desires, ambitions
and struggles to create art that mirrors their lives _ it clearly
illustrates the ideological schisms that have long tainted the
achievements of black artists like Sheridan.
</P>
<P>
   Watching most of the six hours, I was reminded that before Alice
Walker's novel ``The Color Purple'' drew allegations that it
depicted only negative black male images, writer James Baldwin had
stirred the pot with a 1948 essay denouncing so-called protest
novels, such as Richard Wright's ``Native Son,'' for
``oversimplifying black life.''
</P>
<P>
   Black artists were tossed into conflicting camps: those like
Wright and activist and scholar W.E.B. Du Bois, who thought art
should advance the race; and those who felt it necessary to defend
the freedom of expression at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   So it appears that even then, the most accomplished black
artists couldn't escape the nagging notion that black art couldn't
simply be art, just as they couldn't walk away from the societal
debate over whether black people in America could simply be
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the thought prevailed that art must reflect a certain
political and racial consciousness or put forth positive images
while steering clear of the uncomfortable truths referred to, in
code, as dirty laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly other American ethnic and religious groups have
similar concerns. But African-American artists actually start out
knowing that consumers demand that art not only inform and
entertain, but provide an uplifting experience with moral and
social responsibility. All too often, black artists end up being
judged not on artistic merit but whether the image criteria have
been met.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rock learned this the hard way this past year, less
because of his outspoken criticism of black leaders and stars
(because Rock is an equal-opportunity offender, he usually escaped
prolonged criticism) than for a photo spread in Vanity Fair in
which he sported a minstrel black face, a painful reminder of
belittling cinematic atrocities. Rock's response: It's comedy; get
over it.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just it. Nothing is ``just'' ... when it deals with
race, and with nationalists and separationists and
multiculturalists and Afrocentrics and integrationists weighing in.
</P>
<P>
   The recent protests over two television series _ ``The Secret
Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer,'' a sitcom about a black butler during
the Lincoln administration, and ``The PJs,'' an animated comedy set
in a housing project _ zeroed in on the black producers and stars
affiliated with those shows and questioned their own
``self-hatred,'' prompting one black producer to relate the
atmosphere to 1950s McCarthyism.
</P>
<P>
   MORE .MDUL/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   Poet Saul Williams, one of the many artists featured on the PBS
series, prefers to call it a ``consciousness shift'' in the right
direction. ``People are more aware,'' he says during an interview.
``More sensitive in terms of what's happening. They're asking,
`What are we listening to? What are we watching? What are we
seeing?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But one must wonder what kind of chilling effect it all has on
free expression and whether black artists are falling short of
exposing certain truths, particularly when the truth hurts.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Michael Howard, one of the actors supplying voice to ``The
PJs,'' says any artist allowing ideology to dictate what they say
or do is ``endangering quality.'' He says it's unfortunate that a
performer can't just make a creative expression and let it be what
it is.
</P>
<P>
   His comments got me to thinking about comedian Steve Harvey,
who, when we met a number of years ago, was doing two completely
different stand-up acts _ one for black audiences, another for
whites. (Television fame has enabled him to consolidate acts.)
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that Spike Lee, applauded for his ``militant
filmmaking'' in ``Do the Right Thing'' and criticized for airing
dirty laundry in ``School Daze'' (dealing with the long-simmering
skin color debate among blacks), feels the tug from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   Says Lee, ``I've always felt that you have to try to get to the
truth, and let the chips fall where they may.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Lee is becoming part of the elder generation he used to
mistrust, and a new vanguard is emerging. These younger artists
have had better opportunities in education and employment, and have
experienced fewer instances of the type of blatant racism suffered
by their parents and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder artists in their 20s seem to talk of ``transcending''
the barriers of ``blackness,'' which is, of course, ludicrous. What
the young artists are saying, unfortunately, is that they want to
appeal to as many people as possible to get as much as possible,
which is, if anything, the strong pull of our current material
world.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if the emerging black aesthetic will be grounded even
less in the premise of race as a source of conflict than the notion
that black artists have a right to choose from all that America
offers. Writer John Edgar Wideman made this point in the second
hour Monday, saying that the whole purpose of writing is to get
outside one's own skin.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one could count me among the confused, as my hope is
that black art remains a way to heighten consciousness while
respecting others' pain. Yet if the next century of
African-American art becomes synonymous with what could be viewed
as ideological propaganda, I want no part of it.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1448EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERB-GUARD-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     02-01 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERB-GUARD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (a and i coding)  
 EVERETT, Mass.: ... enjoy it.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a reporter came to the side door recently after Topic was
observed on the street, the younger of his two grown daughters,
Arijana, answered. She said her father does not speak English and,
in any case, ``we don't want to discuss'' his role in the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Topic has been in Massachusetts since at least 1995, when he
obtained a driver's license. His presence in the Boston area
continues to be a matter of deep dispute within the 1,100-member
Bosnian refugee community in Massachusetts, among refugees
elsewhere, and among officials and advocates concerned with
immigration and human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   The camps at Trnopolje, Omarska, and Keraterm symbolized some of
the gravest abuses of a war that enveloped thousands of innocents
in its inhumanity and gore. According to indictments issued by the
International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia, the
camps were established for the specific purpose of killing Muslims
and Croats, or so frightening and abusing them that they would flee
the area around Prijedor. The Trnopolje camp was the largest of the
three, and was the one to which most women, children, and elderly
people were taken and confined with minimal shelter and inadequate
sanitation and food.
</P>
<P>
   Trnopolje ``served as the staging point for the mass deportation
of all those who survived the initial attacks and camp regime,''
tribunal investigators found in a genocide indictment issued
against a Serb leader in 1997. ``It also served a much more
sinister purpose: the sexual assault, rape, and torture of many of
the women detained there by camp personnel. . . . In many instances
the women and girls were taken from the camp and raped, tortured,
or sexually abused at other locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition, many prisoners both male and female were killed,
beaten, and otherwise physically and psychologically maltreated by
the camp personnel and other Serbs. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   One survivor of Trnopolje, who was in the camp from May to July
1992 and asked not to be identified, said 20 to 30 uniformed Serbs
normally were stationed there to control about 3,000 detainees. She
said that made it impossible for guards to be unaware of the
outrages that were being committed.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions were relatively better at Trnopolje than they had
been at Omarska, said Cigelj, who spent five days at Trnopolje in
August 1992. ``Trnopolje was a four-star hotel compared to Omarska,
even though people were constantly beaten,'' she said. ``Life was
worth nothing in either camp, absolutely nothing, but in terms of
gradations of horror, Omarska was worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Elezovic said that even though she lost 77 pounds at Omarska,
the Serbs gave her just one meal _ a watery soup flecked with meat
_ after she arrived at Trnopolje. She spent the rest of her stay
eating bread and a few pieces of macaroni given to her by other
prisoners who acquired the food when relatives were allowed to
bring it to them.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Topic initially were raised within the refugee
community about two years ago. Rita Kantarowski, director of the
office, said after the IRC became aware of the Topic issue ``we
followed it up with the community'' by holding a meeting at the
agency's office. The concerns raised ``did not have anything to do
with the person who works here,'' Muniba Topic, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kantarowski said some people at the community meeting said Topic
did help detainees in the camp, but she was unable to say whether
anyone who was not a family member gave such testimony. ``I am
satisfied with the research I have done . . . that there is no
basis'' for disputing his refugee status, Kantarowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Zubcevic said Topic told her that he would have gone ``crazy''
if he had remained at the camp, and fled because of the killing he
witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very good person,'' Zubcevic said. ``He cried once
when he explained how the Serbian army had killed women and kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But camp survivors and other critics said Topic is now making
excuses for his complicity in killings at the camp. They said that
Topic, then in his late 40s, was under no obligation to join the
military and they asserted he must have been fully aware of the
Serbs' grisly tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who are responsible because they committed
war crimes and there are those who are responsible because they did
nothing to prevent them,'' Cigelj said, adding that she believes
Topic was in the latter group. ``All those people who put on a
uniform are responsible for letting this type of political program
surface and flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Zakim, regional director of the Anti-Defamation League,
said it is important to learn the truth about Topic because
``identification and eventual prosecution sends a message to the
people who are there now that `you will be held accountable.' I
hope that would send a shiver down the spines of people who are
there committing atrocities today.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always have a ready excuse that they had no choice, or
that they tried to help,'' Zakim said. ``It's the oldest one in the
book. People who perpetuate atrocitiesz. . . often depend on the
apathy or silence of people who consider themselves mere
bystanders.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Cigelj said, some soldiers did help some prisoners, but
she said she never saw Topic do that.
</P>
<P>
   Sivac said that even soldiers who tortured prisoners were known
occasionally to perform acts of kindness. She said the deputy
commander at Omarska, who since has been indicted, once brought her
a small package of cigarettes and toiletries. ``That helped me,''
she said, ``but he was responsible for the death and torture of
hundreds of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigelj, a lawyer and political activist, said Topic's inaction
seemed worse considering she had known him most of her life. She
described Topic as a friendly, unassuming, slightly arrogant man
who went by his childhood nickname, Giga. He and his wife were
elementary school teachers before the war, she said, adding that
during their childhood, her family shared a home with the family of
Topic's best friend, so she saw Topic often.
</P>
<P>
   After identifying Topic through his photo last week, she said,
``I couldn't believe I would see the day when someone would send me
a photo of Giga and I would have to confirm that he was a person
who participated in something like this, where other people were
hurt. It's very difficult to face something that was part of your
childhood and then see it in this light.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Frank Phillips of the Globe staff contributed to this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
