<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7176 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     02-01 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENSURE THE PROGRAM THAT HELPS ENSURE OUR PROSPERITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Save Social Security first! That was the most commanding
challenge in President Clinton's State of the Union message. He
laid down the gauntlet for action this year.
</P>
<P>
   The way Congress responds to this call will be more important to
the American people than how the Senate wraps up the out-of-steam
impeachment imbroglio or how the legislative branch handles any
other recommendation in Clinton's hourlong address.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter what you think of Clinton personally. Love
him, hate him, admire or merely tolerate him _ Social Security is
larger than any politician's fate and bigger than either party's
pride.
</P>
<P>
   Americans may not know or really care much how their
congressional representative votes on a myriad of issues, including
some consequential ones.
</P>
<P>
   But the people are watching what Congress does this year with
Social Security. Lawmakers, be sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who remembers America before Social Security should know
how important it has been and is. It was the New Deal's most
significant and pervasive social innovation. Today it is the most
stabilizing institution of American society.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other single facet of 20th-century life, Social
Security has immunized this country from recurring economic
depressions. It has broadened the base of our American marketplace.
Banished the specter of the poorhouse. Cushioned the financial
problems, haunting fears and psychic agonies of aging. Freed
children from the economic strain of caring for dependent parents.
And, for countless millions, enriched life's twilight years with
dignity and self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   A fortunate few could complain egotistically that they've put
more into the fund than they'll ever personally draw out. But we of
whom that's true are among the program's most fortunate
beneficiaries. We have ridden the prosperity wave that it set in
motion.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but we'd have done better individually, some argue, to have
put all those contributions into Coca-Cola stock. Be honest. How
many of us would have done that? How many of us did?
</P>
<P>
   And the question we pass over so glibly: Exactly how reliable
was the stock market before we had Social Security? In 1929, its
value shrank 40 percent in three months. Where would the Dow Jones,
that giddy reflection of our economic health, be today had it not
been for the steady discipline of Social Security's national
retirement savings plan that undergirds that economy?
</P>
<P>
   For years we've taken Social Security for granted. We've
borrowed from it to fight wars, build weapons and finance other
needs that we didn't want to pay for at the time. For 60 years its
trust fund reflected a healthy surplus. Policy-makers have drawn
from it _ sometimes to cut taxes and mask willful deficits. Now
it's payback time.
</P>
<P>
   If we want our grandchildren to enjoy Social Security's
blessings, as the four or five generations before them have done,
we'll make the task of reinforcing its declining balance our No. 1
priority. We'll do that first, before somebody fritters away or
divides up our immediate good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, we're like a family that has fallen heir to
unexpected wealth. We can invest it in blue chips and make sure our
children, and theirs, are never in need. Or we can cash it in, quit
work and take the family to Las Vegas while it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   Today, because of fortuitous planning or providential blessing,
we have a budgetary surplus for the first time in 30 years. At our
present rate of economic growth, the projected pattern of federal
revenues and expenditures, if continued, will yield foreseeable
surpluses reaching into the trillions during the first quarter of
the coming century.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants us to commit about 62 percent of those surpluses
over the next 15 years to building up an adequate reserve fund for
Social Security. He would have a board of independent experts
invest approximately one-fourth of that money in the stock market
on our behalf, hoping to increase its value. The remainder would be
invested, as at present, in U.S. Treasury bonds. They yield less
annual return than many stocks but are the safest investments on
earth.
</P>
<P>
   Nodding to Republican suggestions in a bid for bipartisan
cooperation, Clinton would approve letting about 1 percent of the
surplus support voluntary individual retirement accounts, giving
workers a supplementary source of old age income. Each would get an
annual lump sum to invest, with matching contributions from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Some objections are heard to various phases of this plan. If
lawmakers don't like it, they should try to improve on it, not just
criticize and obstruct it. The president's outline amounts to
openers in the most important game that Congress can play this year
for the American people and our economy's future.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made a similar, though less specific, proposal last
year. This time he has fleshed it out. It is bold. It is concrete.
It isn't perfect. But it's far better than no plan at all. Congress
wasted last year and did nothing. It has already lost the first
month of 1999 _ the Senate debating impeachment charges, the House
in what amounts to a monthlong recess.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks are keenly aware of the problem looming ahead for our
Social Security trust fund as baby boomers reach retirement. People
are weary with inaction and fed up with diversions. If Congress
doesn't like the president's plan, for whatever reason, then let's
see a better one.
</P>
<P>
   The American people expect action this year _ thoughtful,
decisive action. They deserve no less.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
