<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following
photos are part of tonight's New York Times Photo Package, moving
Sunday 1/31/98. Photo clients will automatically receive these
photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may download them from either the
Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on
Newscom at 305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases
by calling 212-556-4204.
<TEXT>
<P>
   (NYT21) MIAMI -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- FBN-SUPER-BOWL-7, 1-31 -- The
Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway, a unanimous choice for MVP
of Super Bowl XXXIII, in which the Broncos defeated the Atlanta
Falcons 34-19, enjoying a second straight Broncos' Super Bowl
victory. Elway, right, congratulates his workhorse running back
Terrell Davis, the league MVP, on another incredible season. The
38-year-old Elway hedged on whether he would retire or come back to
try to make the Broncos the first team to win three straight Super
Bowls. (Jose R. Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MIAMI -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- FBN-SUPER-BOWL-6, 1-31 -- The
Atlanta Falcons and their head coach Dan Reeves watch time fly away
along with their chances for a Super Bowl victory Sunday. Reeves'
old team, the Denver Broncos, defeated the Falcons 34-19 in Super
Bowl XXXIII. The Broncos beat an Atlanta team that was its own
worst enemy, and Elway got a measure of revenge on Reeves, who
coached him in three Super Bowl losses and left Denver in 1992 at
odds with the quarterback. (Jose R. Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) MIAMI -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- FBN-SUPER-BOWL-5, 1-31 -- The
Denver Broncos linebacker Bill Romanowski enjoying a moment of
glory after the Broncos defeated the Altanta Falcons 34-19 in Super
Bowl XXXIII Sunday. Super Bowl XXXIII swung on defensive stands by
the Denver Broncos and missed chances by the Atlanta Falcons.
``That's what you've got to do -- you've got to keep them from
scoring touchdowns,'' said Romanowski. ``We preach that, and we
live it.'' (Jose R. Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MIAMI -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- FBN-SUPER-BOWL-4, 1-31 -- The
Denver Broncos 38-year-old quarterback John Elway scoring a
touchdown in the fourth quarter of Super Bowl XXXIII Sunday, in
which the Broncos defeated the Atlanta Falcons 34-19. Elway, who
was the unanimous choice for MVP, completed 18 of 29 passes for 336
yards and one touchdown and ran 3 yards for another score. The
total yardage was third best in Super Bowl history. (Jose R.
Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SHELTON, Conn. -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- INTERNET-SMUT-TRIAL,
1-31 -- Mitchell S. Tepper, head of the Sexual Health Network,
opposes a new federal law meant to shield children from commercial
pornography on the World Wide Web. Critics of the law say that if
it goes into effect, it could force a variety of Web site operators
to choose between self-censorship or prison. Backers say the law is
necessary to prevent commercial sites from making graphic sexual
images available to all visitors, including children. (Thomas
McDonald/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- INTERNET-MUSIC-SALES, 1-31
-- Recordings by the guitarist Billy Squier can be received over
the Internet using software from A2B Music. A2B's Howard Singer, at
the keyboard, says the potential customer base is growing, but he
frets that people may get used to free music. (James Estrin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ARMENIA, Colombia -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- COLOMBIA-QUAKE-3,
1-31 -- People setting up temporary makeshift huts in the city of
Armenia after their houses were destroyed by the earthquake that
measured 6.0 on the Richter scale, and was the worst to hit the
area in more than 100 years. About 35,000 families, or 180,000
people, have been left homeless, and over 1000 people were killed,
the Colombian Red Cross has announced. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ARMENIA, Colombia -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- COLOMBIA-QUAKE-2,
1-31 --A child salvaging some food from a relief truck distributing
food to people in need after the earthquake which measured 6.0 on
the Richter scale, and the worst to hit the area in more than 100
years, struck the city of Armenia. About 35,000 families, or
180,000 people, have been left homeless, and over 1000 people were
killed, the Colombian Red Cross has announced. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ARMENIA, Colombia -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- COLOMBIA-QUAKE-1,
1-31 -- Isabel Cristina Marquez, a 28-year-old waitress from
Elmhurst, N.Y., and her husband Farid Losso, 29, who still lives in
Colombia, in front of the house where the family used to live
before it was destroyed by the earthquake that rocked the city of
Armenia. Like many of the tens of thousands of Colombian immigrants
who live in the New York region, Ms. Marquez leads a split life.
She lives here and there, dividing her time evenly between two
countries. ``We've lost our home here in Colombia,'' she says.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MIAMI -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- FBN-SUPER-BOWL-3, 1-31 -- The
Denver Broncos Darrien Gordon knocking a pass away from the Atlanta
Falcons Tony Martin during the second quarter of Super Bowl XXXIII
at Pro Player Stadium. (Jose R. Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MIAMI -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- FBN-SUPER-BOWL-2, 1-31 -- The
Denver Broncos wide receiver Byron Chamberlain making a flying
reception during second quarter action at Super Bowl XXXIII at Pro
Player Stadium. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MIAMI -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- FBN-SUPER-BOWL-1, 1-31 -- The
Atlanta Falcons Jamal Anderson (32) is stopped by the Denver
Broncos defense in the first quarter of action at Super Bowl XXXIII
at Pro Player Stadium. (Jose R. Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PHOENIX -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- ARIZ-HOSPITAL, 1-31 -- A
patient watching television at the civil rehabilitation ward at the
Arizona State Hospital for mental health care. The hospital's
113-year history has been checkered with pride and pain, but the
last few years have been some of the hardest for the hospital.
Budget cuts and staff reductions have left ASH scrambling to find
enough nurses and technicians to care for those who have been sent
here by civil and criminal courts across the state. Treatment has
suffered, and morale and pay are low. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- CALIF-NEWSPAPERS-MEDIA, 1-31
-- In a little more than two years, William Dean Singleton has
become the No. 2 newspaper publisher in Southern California, buying
up a string of small dailies in a pincer-like move around the
dominant paper, The Los Angeles Times. Some say the expansion may
hinder The Los Angeles Times, which is owned by the Times Mirror
Co., from pursuing growth in the suburbs. (Brian Brainerd/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- NATIONAL-GEOGRAPHIC-MEDIA,
1-31 -- National Geographic is starting to use newsstands in order
to revive its fortunes and halt a steadily declining circulation.
It is the first time in the Geographic's 111-year history that it
has resorted to use of newsstands, which it has long scoffed at as
downscale but now sees as the means for attracting the diverse and
younger readers it so desperately needs. (Ruby Washington/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 31, 1999 --
INTERNET-LOBBYISTS-PROFILE, 1-31 -- Marc Rotenberg, from left, Dave
Banisar and David L. Sobel of the Electronic Privacy Information
Center oppose plans to include identification features in a
computer chip. Privacy advocates say the feature, intended to
enhance the security of electronic commerce and safeguard against
software piracy, would make it easy for online marketers, even
governments, to track people on the Internet. (Marty Katz/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MARRAKESH, Morocco -- Jan. 31, 1999 --
MOROCCO-SINGLEMOMS-2, 1-31 -- A woman and a child in the streets of
Marrakesh, Morocco. In general, women are treated as inferior under
Morocco's Koranic laws: they are legal minors, inherit only half a
share, need permission from a male relative to marry and can be
repudiated by their husbands. But a woman who has a child out of
wedlock is treated with even more disdain. (Marlise Simons/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) AGADIR, Morocco -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- MOROCCO-SINGLEMOMS-1,
1-31 -- Young women and a baby they are looking after in a day care
center run by a Swiss foundation in Agadir, Morocco. In a country
where abortion is forbidden by law and a woman who has a child out
of wedlock is treated with even more disdain, the center is an
important service for unmarried mothers, who become social
outcasts, even rejected by their families. (Marlise Simons/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- BLUE-THEATER-REVIEW, 1-31 --
From left, June Watson, Pearce Quigley and Mary Macleod in Caryl
Churchill's production of ``Blue Heart,'' at the Majestic Theater
of the Brooklyn Academy of Music. Directed and acted with a finesse
and wit that are far more warm than chilly, the production feels
like a love poem to the endless possibilities of theater, even as
it exposes its limitations. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- DANCE-GISELLE-REVIEW, 1-31
-- The Eifman Ballet of St. Petersburg performing ``Red Giselle''
at City Center. Boris Eifman's choreographic essay on the life and
mental illness of the Russian emigre ballerina Olga Spessivtseva is
expressed in a style with cartoonlike simplicities. One can contest
the ballet's picture of good and evil. But one also has to admire
the impact of Eifman's choreography and the sheer originality of
his theatrical vision. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Jan. 31, 1999 -- U.S.-MUSEUMS-MOBS, 1-31 -- The
most popular exhibition in the United States last year, ``Monet in
the 20th Century,'' at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston, which
counted 565,992 visitors during a three-month run that ended on
Dec. 27. Population differences notwithstanding, nearly everyone
credits the current success of American museums to marketing. (Evan
Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
