<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7211 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-NAMES-HNS &LR;      02-01 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-NAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN A NAME? A CENTURY COULD MAKE THE DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Once, 20th Century Spring Manufacturing seemed
like a bold name. So did 20th Century Insurance, 20th Century Forum
and, of course, 20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But in 11 short months those names will seem instantly
old-fashioned. It might not compare in gravity to the looming year
2000 computer glitch, but millennial name angst is here.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 21st century technically does not begin until 2001,
the 20th century is likely to seem passe a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies with soon-to-be outdated monikers are scrambling
for new ones or at least studying the possibility. And if they
decide to modernize, it might not be easy to snag a name reflecting
the new century.
</P>
<P>
   More than 15,000 Web site names using ``2000'' and 600 using
``21st'' _ as in 21st century _ have been registered by Network
Solutions Inc., which has exclusive rights to register domain names
on the Internet. The glut includes everything from
virtualnanny2000.com and wrestlemania2000.com to
21stcenturystocks.com.
</P>
<P>
   And the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office already has more than
1,000 applications for the word millennium and close to 300 for
21st Century. From 21st Century Cable TV and 21st Century Toys to
the real estate giant Century 21 _ which has sued smaller companies
to keep their mitts off what it considers its territory _ scads of
names are taken. Already gone are Millennium Vanilla (taken by a
Philadelphia manufacturer) and ``the health drink of the 21st
Century'' (taken by the Massachusetts makers of Aloaide, an aloe
vera soda).
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium, schmillennium'' is taken too, registered as the
``Official Mockery of the New Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   A decision to change a company name may be more complicated than
plunking down money for a search and some new stationery, for loyal
customers might be lost in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company was started 40 years ago, and then it meant
advanced technology,'' said Mike Pavloff, operations manager at
20th Century Spring Manufacturing in Santa Clara, Calif., where
officials are pondering a name change. ``Now (the founder) is
saying, `What are we going to do?' There's controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, company employees were instructed to answer the phone
using the abbreviation TCS, but customers were confused, Pavloff
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they got the wrong number,'' he said. ``Our first
shot would have to be a letter to customers'' explaining the name
change.
</P>
<P>
   At 20th Century Insurance near Los Angeles, that would be more
than 1 million customers. The company hasn't decided whether to
alter its name, but has sponsored four focus groups to test the
potential effects, spokesman Ric Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys showed that customers weren't bothered by the old name,
he said. But just in case, the company has reserved the right to
use 21st Century Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They associate the name with the level of service,'' Hill
said. ``Changing our name would be no inexpensive process. You've
got to change stationery, signs, notify customers and
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Twentieth Century Forum, a nonprofit organization that supports
composers and sponsors new music concerts in the San Francisco
area, wouldn't use 21st Century Forum even if it were available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something about that is too unwieldy,'' said Executive
Director Steph Zlott, who nonetheless wants his organization _
which is about new, not old music _ to be identified with the
cutting edge. Sometime this year, the name will become New Music
Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Twentieth Century Fox Film Corp. isn't changing its name, though
it has applied for rights to the name Twenty-First Century Fox. But
the movie studio probably has nothing to worry about in the name
department, since with some corporate giants ``the name becomes
inseparable with the product,'' said Edward Saentz, a brand
consultant at Interbrand.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be true for all companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you think of doing business with 20th Century
Pharmaceuticals?'' Saentz said. ``That name would be detrimental.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Newbury, owner of 21st Century Home Improvement in San
Francisco, is happy with the date in his company's name. So happy
that he fought off colossal Century 21's attempt to take it away
from his small enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to San Francisco and found someone who wasn't going
to knuckle under,'' said Henry Bunsrow, a lawyer who represented
Newbury in federal court. ``The court recognized that 21st Century
was a common name. Our position was that Century 21 didn't own
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was settled out of court last fall, with Newbury
keeping his name and agreeing to pay a ``nominal'' licensing fee to
Century 21. Officials from Century 21, which Bunsrow said wanted
the name for its own home improvement businesses, did not return a
telephone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   In order to use a new name, companies must make sure it's
available. Registering as a trademark requires filing an
application with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.
</P>
<P>
   By law, a trademark must be used for commercial purposes. This
differs from cyberspace, where it is possible to register a Web
site name just so someone else can't have it. ``Cybersquatters''
have been doing just that, then offering to sell the names to
interested parties. Someone even nabbed the name billgates.com, but
the megamillionaire hasn't shown interest in buying it.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, survival of the millennial name shake-up may call
for buying a T-shirt, tank top, jacket or bandanna emblazoned with
``I survived the 20th Century,'' a trademark phrase owned
exclusively by a man in Pontiac, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   And for those totally fed up with the problem, there is the 22nd
century to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Abeleite, president of Twenty-Second Century Development, a
commercial development company in San Jose, Calif., did, and he is
happy he won't be around to see if that name gets obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to get to about 106 but I won't make it to the next
millennium,'' he said. ``I'll leave that to another person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
