<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWITZERLAND-TURNER-02     02-01 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWITZERLAND-TURNER-0202-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV MAVERICK TURNER TAKES A CHARITABLE TURN
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVOS, Switzerland _ ``The more I've given away, the better I
feel about it,'' a super-rich Ted Turner told a small group of
fellow super-rich donors from around the world Monday at an
exclusive seminar entitled, ``You Can't Take It With You: Making
Philanthropy More Effective.''
</P>
<P>
   As vice-chairman of Time-Warner Inc., the always colorful Turner
is hardly in the same league as Microsoft Corp.'s Bill Gates, who
at that moment was sitting on a panel in a much larger room only
some 50 yards away. Gates, 43, has so far given away $4 billion
from a stash of Microsoft stock that has made him the world's
richest man.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Turner has been no slouch in that area either, having
pledged $1 billion of his own considerable fortune to the United
Nations and pushing for others to give. The generous gift added to
what was already a world-renowned reputation as a big-time
philanthropist, one which Turner will often downplay with a little
folksy rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in a 700-foot apartment,'' Turner had told the Cox News
Service, referring to his loft at Atlanta's CNN Center, ``so I
could become homeless and jobless at the same time. I'm afraid to
leave the place. I do whatever I'm told to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will I have to retire at age 65?'' he asked. ``I don't know,
I'm afraid to ask. I'm married to Jane Fonda and I also do what she
tells me to do. But it's not so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case, Turner, 60, somewhat exaggerated for
effect. But there was no doubting the fact that on his first visit
to the World Economic Forum, an annual conclave of the rich and
powerful, the maverick founder of CNN made a deeply favorable
impression on his fellow networking participants.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night at a session called, ``What Is Required for
Further Global Progress,'' Turner cast aside his prepared remarks
to deliver a 15-minute highly personal resume of his life and times
that ended with an emotional appeal for broader support for the
U.N.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Turner and his wife dined with U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan as well as several newspaper editors and
columnists. ``Ted is a very great man,'' Annan said, recounting the
story of how, on an apparent spur of the moment, Turner told him he
planned to announce the huge gift the next day at a U.N. dinner to
be held in Turner's honor.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the philanthropic group on Monday, Turner said,
``When I first got the idea for helping the U.N., my thought was to
buy up the organization's debt and then sue the United States
government to pay up. But it proved to be too big a hunk and,
besides, I found out that our government wasn't legally liable to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I said to myself I'll just give the money the U.N. But then
my lawyers told me that there was no way that the body could accept
it. So I told them there must be some way to swing this cat. What
about (setting up) a foundation? They said that just might work.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner then set up the United Nations Foundation to deal with
such global issues as population control, improving the environment
and raising children's' health standards, particularly in the
developing world.
</P>
<P>
   But the charitable unit, which is open to all givers, has also
had its share of bureaucratic entanglements. ``God knows, the
General Assembly is not CNN,'' said Adele Simmons, president of the
MacArthur Foundation which, among other things, bankrolls ``genius
grants.'' Turner nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   While in Davos, Turner also attended what he called ``a
billionaires' party,'' with some 20 attendees. ``We focused on
monitoring overseas giving in the developing world,'' he said. ``If
you're not careful, the money will disappear,''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Turner has bankrolled a private foundation that is
named after himself. ``We're giving away $12 million a year or
about 12 percent of our capital,'' Turner said in a brief interview
with the Cox News Service. ``We're dipping into capital and
planning to step up our spending. It will get the bulk of my money
when I'm gone.''
</P>
<P>
   A major current priority of the private foundation is
eradicating toxic wastes, Fonda noted.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
