<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7281 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-HISPANICS-TEX     02-01 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HISPANICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY VOTE FIGURES FOR BUSH RE-EXAMINED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It quickly became the stuff of political legend.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed Gov. George W. Bush won half of the Hispanic
vote in his November re-election, and within weeks, the figure was
spread in national and international reports about a potential
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, who typically get about a quarter of the
Hispanic vote, the exit poll numbers seemed unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   And they may be.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at what really happened on Election Day indicates
that Bush got significantly less than the 49 percent of the
Hispanic vote that he was credited with in the exit poll conducted
on behalf of major television networks and newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts and polls declare that Bush's Hispanic vote totals
were between the upper 30s and the lower 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is important, given the flood of attention that
Bush received for a White House bid following his Nov. 3
gubernatorial win.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers, magazines and television stations throughout the
United States and abroad have given extensive coverage to Bush's
purported Hispanic vote totals, repeating the 49 percent figure as
fact. Even the governor's own official biography on a state Web
site touts the 49 percent figure.
</P>
<P>
   The poll results were cited by the Bush camp as proof that a
compassionate conservative leader can ``erase the gender gap, open
the doors of the Republican Party to new faces and new voices, and
win without sacrificing principles.''
</P>
<P>
   The exit poll conducted election night by the Voter News Service
of New York _ which continues to be used by all major television
networks and newspapers _ showed that Bush got 49 percent of the
Hispanic vote and 27 percent of the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Rice University political scientist Bob Stein, who helped
design the questionnaire in Texas for the Voter News Service, said
Bush's showing among Hispanics, while extraordinary, was not as
strong as the original survey showed.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush's vote percentage among Hispanics, after adjusting
the data with appropriate weighting for precinct anomalies, was
somewhere between ``the high 30s and low 40s.'' He said Bush's
percentage among black voters was probably in the low 20s.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign referred calls about the exit poll to the
governor's consultant, Karl Rove. Attempts to reach Rove were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   For Texas Democrats still smarting over their crushing defeat in
the state elections _ they lost every statewide office _
calculating the magnitude of Bush's support among minorities is not
idle nit-picking.
</P>
<P>
   If the traditional Democratic coalition is falling apart, to the
benefit of their rivals, they might be politically doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Stein's take on the Hispanic vote jibes with two other exit
polls done on Election Day. An exit survey done by the Willie
Velasquez Institute in San Antonio showed Bush got 39 percent of
the vote, while Democrat Garry Mauro received 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A second exit poll, conducted in El Paso by a professor at the
University of Texas at El Paso, showed Bush got 37 percent of the
Hispanic vote there. (Bush won El Paso County by just over 600
votes, the first Republican governor to win the county.)
</P>
<P>
   Getting that level of Hispanic support is exceptionally high,
but not necessarily unprecedented for a Republican. Ronald Reagan
is estimated to have won at least 40 percent of the Hispanic vote
in Texas in his landslide 1984 presidential re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders Anderson, a political scientist at Texas Southern
University, said Bush got ``an unusually high percentage'' of the
black vote, although not as much as his brother Jeb Bush, the new
Florida governor.
</P>
<P>
   Exit surveys, so named because they are taken as voters ``exit''
the voting booths, are used heavily by networks and news services
so that winners can be projected in time for the evening newscast
or morning newspaper delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Murray Edelman, editorial director of Voter News Service
acknowledged that his exit survey is not designed specifically for
racial breakdowns but rather for calling elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This exit poll is not geared toward giving you the best
possible estimate of the Hispanic vote,'' Edelman said. ``We're
geared toward projecting a winner. If I were doing a Hispanic
study, we would design it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The margin of error for the racial breakdowns in his poll
(including both blacks and Hispanics), for example, is plus or
minus 8 percentage points. The Willie Velasquez poll had a margin
of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Edelman also noted that only four of the 30 precincts he used
for surveys were in heavily Hispanic areas. But he said the
discrepancy with other polls could be explained by Bush's better
showing among Hispanics in areas that aren't dominated by them.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Democratic consultant Peck Young called Bush's inroads
into the Hispanic vote an ``interesting but totally personal
phenomenon from which the GOP should take little long-term
comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stein and others say dissecting the numbers misses the
larger point, which is that Bush's approach and message cut deeply
into the Democratic coalition: ``It ain't about the percentage,''
Stein said. ``It's about getting more votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Campos, a Democratic political consultant in Houston who
specializes in Hispanic candidates and issues, said Bush attracted
Hispanics by rejecting harsh stances on immigration and other
divisive issues associated with such Republicans as former
California Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Bankrolling a massive TV ad campaign _ in both Spanish and
English _ didn't hurt either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a heavy media presence,'' Campos said. ``I give Bush
four stars for knowing how to play the game. He is good. He is
good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is Austin bureau chief for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (512) 476-4294, or e-mail:
jroot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
