<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7283 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-US-GAP-NYTSF &LR;      02-01 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-US-GAP-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 UNFORTUNATELY, RUSSIA and the U.S. AREN'T EQUAL PARTNERS  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column. To publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must
be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. Or
DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 c.1999 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The visit of Madeleine Albright, U.S. secretary of state, to
Moscow in late January was apparently cordial, with smiles and even
friendly embraces.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, Mrs. Albright recalled the old formula of
U.S.-Russian ``strategic partnership,'' which must have pleased the
sickly Russian president. All of this, however, only underscored
that both sides had good reasons not to dramatize the obvious
problems in their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In itself, the fact that the dialogue has not been broken off
and is proceeding in a civilized tone is welcome. But it would be
wrong to minimize or try to gloss over the seriousness of the
discord that has emerged. In fact, it goes far beyond U.S.-Russian
relations as such.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate this point, let us look at recent history.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, as leader of the Soviet Union, I and the rest
of our new Soviet leadership sought ways to radically improve the
situation in the world. It was clear to us that this could not be
done without cooperation with the United States. It took a lot of
hard work by both sides, including successive summits and tough
arms-control treaty negotiations, to end the Cold War with America
and start building a partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Interaction between the vast Soviet Union, and later Russia
alone, and the United States was to be a pivotal factor in shaping
new international politics as a whole. Now if this pillar weakens,
the consequences must affect far more than just the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the root causes of what is happening, I would say
that the Russian political establishment bears much of the
responsibility for the gap, the imbalance, in the U.S.-Russian
relationship. By abolishing the Union with the other former Soviet
Republics, from which Russia derived so much power, my successors
left America without a strong and credible partner.
</P>
<P>
   Very quickly, the United States succumbed to the euphoria of
``victory in the Cold War,'' and the whole idea of a cooperation of
equals to bring about a better world _ the kind of cooperation that
ended the Cold War and helped to untie the knots of some
longstanding conflicts _ was eventually forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   So when Russian politicians complain that the United States is
ignoring Russia's views, yes, they have a point. But it is not
something that began today, or even yesterday. And they have
themselves to blame for much of it.
</P>
<P>
   As a dominating power, stronger in every way than Russia, the
United States, which had been the Soviet Union's equal partner,
acts in ways that, instead of untying the knots of conflicts, ties
some of them even tighter.
</P>
<P>
   For example, defying the views of key members of the U.N.
Security Council, it imposed a unilateral will as regards the
policy toward Iraq, and the policy went badly astray. Instead of
implementing UNSCOM's mandate and normalizing life in the region,
U.S. actions had dire results: a breakup of the coalition that
helped reverse Iraq's aggression toward Kuwait. One-sided Western
policies in the former Yugoslavia had similar consequences.
</P>
<P>
   And yet few lessons have been learned. It is all too obvious,
and very dangerous, that this ``new world disorder'' has inspired
little humility in the West. Today the United States is not working
to restore genuine interaction within the United Nations and other
multilateral mechanisms. Instead, Washington is seeking to
rationalize and justify its policy of totally ignoring the Security
Council. It is also giving NATO, which is dominated by U.S. policy,
the functions of a self-appointed world policeman.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, the United States is undermining the momentous
1972 arms-control treaty which limited anti-ballistic missile
systems. Recently, much soothing rhetoric has surrounded this, but
in fact the U.S. secretary of defense has stated publicly that
America could withdraw from the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder that this kind of behavior has caused a backlash
in Russia, however weakened the nation is. True, Russia has
sometimes overreacted, but it's a big mistake to call its reaction
a trivial resentment _ so-called sour grapes _ at the loss of
superpower status. After all, Russia is very clearly not alone in
objecting to these tendencies in U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States continues to push aside countries that seek
equitable relationships, it may well find itself standing alone, or
in serious contention with many governments on all kinds of issues.
The outcome would only be negative for international politics, and
for all people in the world.
</P>
<P>
   What a shame that in President Clinton's much-praised State of
the Union message, Russia was no longer regarded as a partner in
need of support but rather as a source of potential threats to be
defused. It is important for us to cooperate in eliminating weapons
of mass destruction _ but is this the only area of relations with
Russia to be mentioned by the U.S. president to the American
people?
</P>
<P>
   For many years, the U.S. policy has been focussed on personal,
strong support for the figure of the Russian president. This policy
has failed, as I have many times said it would. But I feel that not
nearly enough has been done to draw the proper conclusions from
this error.
</P>
<P>
   A serious course correction is needed in U.S. policy. Without
it, Mrs. Albright's happy assurances that relations with Russia are
developing positively will sound increasingly hollow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __ Translated by Pavel Palazchenko. &LR; __
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston. He also writes a
monthly commentary column for La Stampa, a newspaper in Turin,
Italy.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
