<HEADER>
A7296 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-AMERICANS-110     02-01 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-AMERICANS-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
 
(DUPLICATION ALERT: Story also moving in ``k'' commentary
category) 
WHY DON'T WE CARE ABOUT THE SLAUGHTER IN THE BALKANS? (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, a quiz: Where is Srebrenica, and what is its
significance?
</P>
<P>
   These are not trick questions. More than 400 stories in my
newspaper since 1992 contain references to Srebrenica, not to
mention hundreds of additional reports on radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   Yet until the day before last, I would have failed my own test.
I did not know Srebrenica was a town in Bosnia, nor that in July
1995, 7,000 Muslim men who lived there were marched off and
slaughtered by Serbian soldiers, their hands wired behind them as
they were shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those newspaper stories labeled the massacres of
Srebrenica the worst European atrocity since World War II. But to
me, they never happened. How many of you passed the quiz?
</P>
<P>
   My belated introduction to Srebrenica came after a much more
recent tragedy in the Balkans: 45 ethnic Albanians from the Serbian
province of Kosovo slaughtered in a ditch. Television footage
showed bloated bodies in colorful clothes heaped one atop another.
Some had their eyes gouged out. Another man in the village of Racak
lay decapitated near his home. The victims included a young woman,
a boy not much older than my 7-year-old son, and several elderly
men.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by those images in a Sunday evening newscast, the
ongoing Balkan tragedy finally grabbed me. I was horrified and
mystified by hatreds that could engender such cruelty. Why now, and
not five years ago as children dodged bullets in Sarajevo, I can't
really say. I do know that my concern feels woefully tardy. And I
know that in this country I am not alone. Which leads to another
question: Where the Balkans are concerned, why do so few of us seem
to care?
</P>
<P>
   The answer may be as complex as the Balkan animosities
themselves. To blame our collective indifference on selfishness
alone is to miss the lingering influences of our history, and the
significance of geography (buffered on both sides by oceans) that
has made this country unique.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, minding our own business is an American tradition,
historians say. None other than President George Washington, in his
farewell address, warned against foreign alliances that might
jeopardize American freedom or interests, a sentiment also endorsed
by Thomas Jefferson and other early American presidents, says Gene
A. Smith, an associate professor of American history at Texas
Christian University in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   That tradition of isolationism continued through the 19th
century and beyond. The United States was only reluctantly dragged
into both world wars. The Cold War effectively shattered old
notions that we could hunker down and go it alone, but foreign
entanglements were justified then almost exclusively by the fear of
communism's spread. It was the realpolitik of Nixon's Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger: foreign action was justified only when it
served the nation's strategic self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1977 with the administration of Jimmy Carter, our
government's stance softened. Humanitarian concerns now
occasionally dictate U.S. foreign policy. The Balkans are an
example. Though the region lacks critical strategic significance,
the United States brokered a peace treaty between the Bosnians and
Serbs in a 1995 summit in Dayton, Ohio. American troops were the
backbone of Bosnian peacekeeping forces. American diplomats are
deeply involved as the dangers escalate in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But we average Americans maintain our remove, by and large,
content to live in ``geographic illiteracy,'' as TCU's Smith calls
it. It's a notion promoted by humankind's natural inclination to
avoid unpleasantness, and the seeming security of living with
oceans on either side.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary philosopher Sam Keen finds yet another cause of our
Balkan ambivalence: The complexity of problems there. Keen says
that despite studying the causes of the conflict, he has yet to
fully understand them. Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic rivals
Saddam Hussein as evil's reigning poster boy, but beyond that, very
little is clear about the conflicts in that region. Enmity between
Serbian Orthodox Christians and Muslims dates back centuries.
Innocents are in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes too much sustained attention to know what's going on,
so I think our tendency is to block it out,'' Keen says. ``We're a
very pragmatic people in that sense. We don't like to give
attention to instances of evil and tragedy where we can't think of
what we would do, if we could do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans, he says, necessarily put on the blinders to avoid
what he calls ``compassion fatigue.'' Somewhere in the world is a
new slaughter almost every day, a new famine, more photographs of
starving children in a far-off place where rebels hinder attempts
at humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're baffled,'' Keen says. ``We don't know how to do good
anymore. So often, the old, clear answers are not good answers.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
