<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7299 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-AMERICANS-2nd     02-01 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-AMERICANS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: good answers.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keen often encourages audiences at his lectures to keep their
blinders intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them to forget the massive thing of evil out there or
you're going to feel impotent because of it all,'' he says. ``But I
tell them to choose something to find out about. Pick an issue.
Maybe it's land mines or nuclear weapons or unlimited arms sales.
Find out enough about it so you know what to do. Then forget about
Kosovo. Or find out about Kosovo, learn what it is we should be
doing there.''
</P>
<P>
   Then forget about the other places, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the wrong tack to take is that tack that says, `Oh,
we're guilty. We should feel guilty about everything,' '' Keen
says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brooks Harrington, an ordained minister and now a Fort Worth
trial lawyer, says it's not just distant tragedies we ignore. We
drive by Kosovos every day, past neighborhoods of suffering people
different from ourselves. As in Kosovo, Harrington says, it seems
part of human nature to want to look the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington recalls his experiences as pastor of Diamond Hill
United Methodist Church in a struggling neighborhood of Fort
Worth's north side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamond Hill was two miles from downtown,'' Harrington says.
``I would go down there and tell stories about kids who lived in
homes without running water, or no heat in the wintertime, and
people would be shocked. But what really pressed their buttons was
when I would start to talk about gangs, and how the gangs were
spreading into their neighborhoods. Then a lot of people would get
interested who wouldn't otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Balkans were oil-rich, or if Serbian terrorists attacked
U.S. interests, troubles in that part of the world would have been
settled long ago, Harrington believes. It boils down to
self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two most destructive words in the English language are
`us' and `them,''' Harrington says. ``A lot of what ethics is about
is `Where do you draw the line?' Everybody draws one, but where do
you draw it? To some people the only `us' is me. To some people,
the only `us' is my family. To some people, the only `us' is people
of my race or people of my class.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start getting into more sublime areas of ethics when you
start realizing the distinctions between `us' and `them' are
suspect. It's all `we.' But as a practical matter, how do you live
that out?''
</P>
<P>
   In a world in which the United States is the only superpower,
the question will increasingly beg an answer, says Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation needs to focus on certain questions of terrorism
and how that's going to play in years to come,'' Smith says. ``But
there's also this question of what humanitarian mission should the
United States play.''
</P>
<P>
   Few Americans can now venture an informed opinion. I was among
those who until recently was content to look the other way. Then I
saw the recent footage of bodies in the ditch, and learned of
Srebrenica. And for some reason a hard reality finally dawned: Only
happenstance and geography stand between me and the same fate.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, where the Balkans are concerned, it seems worth my
while to pay attention. Oceans or not, Srebrenica doesn't seem so
far away.
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Madigan is a senior writer for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at tmadigan(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
