<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-QUAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS ON SHAKY GROUND AS THEY TRY TO MEET QUAKE SAFETY CODES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A law requiring California's 450 hospitals to
meet earthquake safety standards by 2008 could cost up to $20
billion in the coming years and lead to higher health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital groups say some directors may find retrofitting costs
prohibitive and decide to rebuild instead. Others may be forced to
close their facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law has incredible ramifications for health-care delivery
and for consumers,'' said Roger Richter, senior vice president of
professional services for the California Healthcare Association in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1994 law, hospitals have until Jan. 1, 2001, to submit
plans to the state on how they will meet the seismic standards.
Anxiety is already evident, however, in a health-care industry
faced with a mandate but without ready means to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most profound piece of legislation that
will impact hospitals for the next 50 years,'' said Nathan Nayman,
head of the Hospital Council of Northern and Central California, a
San Francisco-based trade association.
</P>
<P>
   The law imposes a uniform standard of seismic safety for
hospitals statewide _ to withstand a magnitude-7 or greater
earthquake _ regardless of the level or risk of their seismic
zones.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 450 acute-care hospitals _ facilities offering
medical, nursing, surgical, anesthesia, laboratory, radiology,
pharmacy and dietary services _ have among them some 1,300 separate
buildings that will need structural changes or have to be rebuilt,
according to a California Healthcare estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them will be closed or turned over for administrative or
other uses by the Jan. 1, 2008 deadline. (By a third deadline, Jan.
1, 2030, California hospitals must meet an even higher standard of
compliance.)
</P>
<P>
   Then-Gov. Pete Wilson signed the law in 1994 after the
Northridge earthquake in which several Southern California
hospitals were damaged. The intent of the law is to ensure the
facilities withstand powerful earthquake so they can serve the
injured.
</P>
<P>
   The law also required that they meet safety standards imposed
after the 1971 San Fernando Valley earthquake in which 47 people
were killed when a Veterans Administration Hospital in Sylmar
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Rural hospitals are especially vulnerable because of the high
cost of compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any (pre-1973) rural two-story hospital is in a world of
hurt,'' said Sharon Avery, executive director of the Rural Health
Care Center, part of the California Healthcare Association. Rural
Health Care represents 72 small facilities in towns of fewer than
15,000 people. Almost all of them are affected by the law, she
said, and it's unclear how they would meet the requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the beginning of the end,'' said Charles
Norton, administrator of Biggs-Gridley Memorial Hospital in
Gridley. ``These are our alternatives: shut the doors; make a
Band-Aid station out of it; make a clinic building out of it; see
if the people in the community want to invest in a fund-raising
campaign to make it seismically sound _ perhaps for $2 million _ or
affiliate with a larger group,'' Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Retired State Sen. Alfred Alquist, D-San Jose, who guided the
1994 seismic bill through the Legislature, said it was a compromise
among various health and state interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great problem we have in government is how much safety can
we afford,'' he said. ``There is no such thing as absolute safety
so it's a constant battle to get the best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, Kaiser Permanente has voluntarily spent some $300
million on seismic improvements to its 26 acute-care hospitals in
the state. By 2008 the total may reach $2 billion, said Kip
Edwards, senior vice president for facilities at the Oakland-based
health company.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser plans to replace its downtown Los Angeles and Fontana
hospitals, Edwards said. Others facilities, including those in
Walnut Creek and Vallejo, are being upgraded. All other Kaiser
sites are being inspected to determine what work needs to be done,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Healthcare West, which operates St. Mary's and St.
Francis Memorial medical centers in San Francisco and five other
area facilities, also is in the process of analyzing its needs _
and possible sources of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the state should help the industry renovate and develop
sufficient capacity,'' said Wade Rose, a vice president for
Catholic Healthcare West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The communities will ultimately demand that a public health
crisis is not created by the demand to implement the regulations _
the crisis being the lack of adequate health care facilities,''
Rose said.
</P>
</TEXT>
