   &UR; SCIENCE  &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-NEWBORNS (Chicago) _ Researchers at an annual AIDS
meeting report results from a study in Africa showing that a
simple, short drug regimen produces striking reductions in
transmission rates of the AIDS virus from mothers to newborns. The
regimen involves giving relatively inexpensive drugs to the women
from several weeks before delivery, during labor and a week after.
Worldwide, 600,000 babies a year are born with HIV. By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STARDUST (Undated) _ For decades, science has known of the
importance of star dust in the cosmic scheme of things, especially
in matter more elaborate than the simple elements made in the
primordial Big Bang. But scientists have never had pure samples to
study _ but soon will, if everything goes as planned. On Saturday,
NASA is to launch a probe meant to capture interplanetary and
interstellar dust in some of its rawest and purest forms, including
many thousands of grains from a comet. By William J. Broad.
</P>
