<HEADLINE>
AN ERA OF NEW HOPE FOR AIDS SUFFERERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SURVIVING AIDS 
Written, produced and directed by: Betsey Arledge 
Narrated by: Edward Hermann 
On: PBS, 8 p.m. Tuesday 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a 1994 Massachusetts gubernatorial contest that was not
exactly a nail-biter, the most compelling storyline involved the
Democratic nominee for lieutenant governor, a little-known
Episcopal priest from Somerville named Robert Massie.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard not to be impressed by this political novice who,
despite his HIV infection, was the picture of robust good health as
he trekked the state or tangled with his GOP counterpart, Paul
Cellucci, in two spirited debates.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Massachusetts General Hospital were more than
impressed by Massie's virtually unheard-of natural resistance to
AIDS. As a NOVA production called ``Surviving AIDS'' describes in
absorbing detail, they were inspired by Massie to undertake a new
approach to fighting AIDS, one that may hold the promise of a
weapon against an epidemic that has killed 500,000 Americans and 11
million people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surviving AIDS'' offers the satisfactions of a high-stakes
scientific mystery yarn along with glimpses into the lives of
Massie; Steve Crohn, another man who also has a natural immunity to
HIV; John Ceravsky of Boston, a patient who courageously agreed to
stop taking anti-HIV drugs as part of an experiment at Mass.
General; and a pair of young twins infected with HIV but kept
healthy by anti-AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they form the basis for what NOVA persuasively calls
``this era of new hope.''
</P>
<P>
   It all began with Massie, a hemophiliac who contracted HIV from
a contaminated blood product in 1978, six years before AIDS came to
public attention.
</P>
<P>
   In some mysterious fashion, Massie's immune system constructed a
defense against HIV; rather than being destroyed as is usually the
case after HIV infection, the ``T cells'' that facilitate the
body's immunity stayed healthy. ``We were all amazed,'' says
researcher Dr. Eric Rosenberg. ``We thought that people who were
HIV-infected weren't able to mount this kind of immune response.
And here was someone who clearly did, and did it in a way we never
saw before.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Massie has remained free of AIDS symptoms and has
become one of the longest-surviving people infected with HIV. He
ruefully admits that he wonders whether he will be better-known as
experiment subject 161-J rather than for his writing or other
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Could well be. According to NOVA, studies of Massie by an MGH
team including Rosenberg and Dr. Bruce Walker have yielded new
experimental approaches to combating AIDS, such as intervening with
anti-viral drugs early in the disease to help shore up the immune
system against attacks by the HIV virus.
</P>
<P>
   In the most throat-catching sequence of ``Surviving AIDS,'' we
see two beneficiaries of such treatments, 3-year-old twins Caroline
and Jeffrey, who were only expected to live a couple of years after
they contracted HIV from their mother. But they began receiving
anti-AIDS drugs, the youngest patients ever to receive them. Their
adoptive parents, a selfless and loving pair who remind us of the
quiet heroism exhibited by so many friends and relatives of AIDS
patients, gave them the medication at regular intervals around the
clock.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the toddlers' immune systems have returned to normal and
they are, for now, healthy, though the HIV lingers in their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Two of NOVA's strengths, clarity and context, fuse as
``Surviving AIDS'' makes clear how vital the Massie-inspired
approaches to controlling AIDS are, because devising a vaccine for
the disease has proven more difficult than expected, and may be
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But in a hype-free and reasoned manner, NOVA suggests while an
AIDS-free world might not be attainable, it is nonetheless
reasonable to hope that every AIDS patient can become ``a long-term
survivor.'' A closing shot of Bob Massie smiling at his baby
daughter underscores how fine a world that would be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
