<HEADLINE>
BIRD LOVERS SEE PROMISE IN STRUGGLE TO SAVE CONDORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARBLE PEAK RANCH, Calif. _ On a foggy, windswept mountain 2,500
feet above the Big Sur coast, seven of the rarest birds on the
planet took tentative flight Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly an hour after a net dropped away on a big wire enclosure,
the first of the birds _ a 10-month-old male known, prosaically, as
No. 94 _ hopped onto the rocky ridge and then, awkwardly, flew a
few dozen yards down the ridge. Later, he tried again. Soon, he was
making a series of tight, soaring flights over a rock-strewn
canyon, joined by another bird, then another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There they go!'' said naturalist Kelly Sorenson, watching from
a nearby ridge.
</P>
<P>
   The birds were California condors _ huge black scavengers with
wingspans of 9 feet and the ability to fly 300 miles in a single
day in search of carrion.
</P>
<P>
   Shot, poisoned and electrocuted to the very brink of extinction,
the condors in the 1980s became the subject of a high-risk recovery
program. The remaining 22 condors were trapped and taken to zoos.
There, according to the plan, they would be safe to breed, and
their progeny would later be returned to the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists and environmentalists predicted cataclysmic
failure, saying the plan would simply guarantee the condor's
extinction. But advocates say that events like Saturday's _ in
which seven zoo-bred condors were released into the rugged Ventana
Wilderness _ show the program is working.
</P>
<P>
   The release brings to 56 the number of condors now in the wild
in California and Arizona, said Sal Lucido, president of the
Ventana Wilderness Society, the nonprofit group that released the
birds in partnership with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
Another 100 are in zoos.
</P>
<P>
   The program has emphasized preventing the condors from having
contact with humans, and it also has made sure that all the birds
spend time with an adult condor before release _ a so-called mentor
bird that serves as a surrogate parent.
</P>
<P>
   After about nine months, condors are ready for release. The
birds set free Saturday were first put in an enclosure on the
ridgetop here in December to acclimate. When the day of release
approached, a stillborn calf was left on the hillside _ a first
meal. Then, as a group of about 100 bird lovers and
environmentalists watched from about a mile away, the enclosure was
opened.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Burnett, a field supervisor watching through one-way glass,
said the birds made no move to leave at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the other birds seem to be waiting to see what 90's going
to do _ it's kind of funny,'' he said on a two-way radio. But
finally, one after another, the birds took off.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists fastened tiny transmitters to the wings of the
condors to monitor them. They'll also continue to leave food out
for the birds. The seven that flew off Saturday join seven condors
released one year ago. All those birds are doing well, roosting in
a redwood grove near the Big Sur Lodge in Monterey County.
</P>
<P>
   The next big test for the recovery program will come when the
birds reach adulthood. If they successfully reproduce in the wild,
scientists will be able to proclaim the recovery program a success.
</P>
<P>
   But Art Palmer, of the Earth Island Institute, injects a note of
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the question is what is going to happen to these birds
long-term, given that most of the problems that caused the collapse
of the condor are still prevalent,'' he said. ``There's still
development of condor habitat, and wind farms and high-tension
wires, and people with guns.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Ventana group's work has made Lloyd Kiff, science
director for the Peregrine Fund, an Idaho nonprofit organization
that also breeds condors, less pessimistic about the condor's
chances in California.
</P>
<P>
   On the Central Coast, ``the birds still have a lot of space to
move around,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``And if people
will refrain from shooting them, there's no reason they can't
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The creatures that are the focus of the unusual $1
million-per-year rescue program are the largest birds in North
America that can manage flight and one of the oldest species on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance, condors are magnificent creatures. Their
plumage is black with white trim. Their wings can span as much as
11 feet from tip to tip.
</P>
<P>
   Condors have been observed flying more than a mile high, and to
range more than 350 miles from their nests. The adult birds have
bare, reddish-orange heads and necks and keen red eyes that, during
flight, constantly scan the ground for food.
</P>
<P>
   Graceful in flight, the birds are ungainly on the ground,
especially after a full meal: Condors have been observed to have
difficulty getting airborne after gorging on a dead animal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
