<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7389 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-STROKE-THERAPY-2T     02-01 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STROKE-THERAPY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AMPHETAMINE THERAPY HELPS SOME STROKE PATIENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By SANDRA BLAKESLEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doctors have found a bold new way of helping people who have had
strokes recover the ability to talk and move their limbs in the
first weeks and months after brain injury. Patients are given low
doses of amphetamine, the common stimulant, along with intense
physical therapy, a combination that appears to accelerate recovery
in many people.
</P>
<P>
   But, doctors caution, the treatment is experimental and may not
be appropriate for all stroke victims, especially elderly people
with heart disease or other serious ailments. Nevertheless, it is
the first effective treatment ever found for helping people recover
function after the acute phase of a stroke has passed.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke in
Bethesda, Md., is conducting a clinical trial of the method to see
if it should be widely recommended for stroke patients. ``We are
doing everything we can to encourage research in this area,'' said
Dr. John Marler, acting director of the division of experimental
therapeutics and clinical trials at the institute.
</P>
<P>
   There are three ways to combat strokes, Marler said. One is to
prevent them by helping people reduce their risk factors. Second is
to treat the injury within three hours using drugs, known as clot
busters, that can restore blood flow and help stave off brain
damage. But, he said, the majority of stroke victims wait many
hours or even days before going to a hospital and by that time, it
is too late to use clot busters. The third chance to intervene is
days or weeks after the stroke occurs and this, he said, has been
the most neglected area of stroke research.
</P>
<P>
   People used to wait to see what happened next, said Dr. Leonardo
Cohen, a neurologist at the institute who is running the new
clinical trial. ``But the idea that you cannot do anything in this
period has shifted dramatically'' with new findings from basic
neuroscience research, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The adult brain is ``plastic,'' meaning it can make new
connections rapidly and can repair itself. Stroke doctors are
learning how to nudge this process along, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Broderick, a professor of neurology at the University
of Cincinnati Medical Center, estimates that each year 730,000
Americans suffer strokes, when blood flow in the brain is suddenly
blocked or an artery ruptures. Half of these patients end up with
some degree of permanent damage. Recent efforts to develop
so-called neuroprotective drugs to use during the acute phase of
stroke have not panned out, giving doctors more reason to look at
the post-injury period.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dennis Feeney, a professor of psychology and neuroscience at
the University of New Mexico at Albuquerque, began by looking at
animals. He discovered that rats with brain injuries similar to
stroke could walk 24 hours after receiving a single dose of
amphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like exactly the wrong thing to do,'' Feeney said.
``Giving speed to a stroke patient, you'd think it would kill
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic notion was very radical, like pouring gasoline on a
fire. But it makes sense, he said, given what happens to brain
cells during and after a stroke. Many neurons in the damaged region
are temporarily stunned rather than killed. They may have been
hooked up to cells that are now dead and messages are no longer
coming in, as if the phone line has been cut. Such cells do not
know what to do, so they sit confused, waiting for instructions,
Feeney said. Eventually some of them die but others find ways to
make new hookups and start functioning, which is the basis of
spontaneous recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these stunned cells are near the site of the stroke
itself, but others lie far away in other brain regions, Feeney
said. These depressed neurons are a bit like a fire gone to embers.
Sprinkling them with gasoline might actually help.
</P>
<P>
   Feeney and others have shown that amphetamine works by causing
the brain to release a substance called noradrenaline throughout
the brain. Noradrenaline is a so-called modulator that makes cells
wake up and attend to things that are interesting, Feeney said. It
makes brain cells more responsive and is involved in learning and
memory. Other drugs, including the stimulant called Ritalin, also
release noradrenaline and have been used for stroke therapy. Drugs
that decrease noradrenaline will slow or prevent stroke recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Amphetamine may promote the growth of new nerve connections and
protein synthesis, said Dr. Larry Goldstein, director of the stroke
center at Duke University in Durham, N.C. It is why some students
take amphetamine when cramming for tests. The drugs may influence
learning as well as keep a person awake.
</P>
<P>
   Feeney also found that animals had to be free to move around
naturally when they got the amphetamine. If prevented from moving,
they did not improve. Physical activity and the drug are
interactive, he said. Dosage and timing are also important. Too
much amphetamine harms animals and too little does no good. Feeney
also learned to wait for the injury to stabilize before giving
amphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Feeney discovered the amphetamine link in 1981. By the late
1980's, the results of three human clinical trials by various
groups were published. As in the animal experiments, people got
better when the drug was paired closely with physical therapy
within a month of the stroke. But if the amphetamine was given a
couple of months after the stroke or without physical therapy,
there seemed to be no benefit.
</P>
<P>
   At the Aphasia Center of Texas Woman's University and the
University of Texas Southwestern Medical School in Dallas, Dr.
Delaina Walker Batson has studied 57 stroke patients, 26 of whom
have received amphetamine plus physical therapy. Treatment begins
10 to 40 days after the stroke, Dr. Batson said. Patients are given
10 milligrams of drug every four days. There is no evidence of
increased blood pressure or heart rate, she said, even in severely
injured patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give the drug and look at our watches,'' Dr. Batson said.
``We wait 30 minutes and start therapy, pushing the patients until
they can no longer do what we ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Batson said she was inspired by neuroscience research
showing that after injury a territory of cells sits ready and
waiting to be reorganized. Whatever behavior gets there first is
established, she said. ``This means that in giving speech therapy,
we don't give them simple word naming,'' Dr. Batson said. ``We push
them to use full phrases. We set high goals for a high level of
recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   It works, Dr. Batson said. Treated patients achieve in six weeks
what usually takes six months to achieve. Patients taking dummy
pills tend to reach a plateau after a few months of physical
therapy. A year later, long after both groups are not taking pills,
the patients who took amphetamine are far ahead of those who did
not. ``This is not a panacea,'' Dr. Batson said. ``These people
have very large lesions with profound motor and language deficits.
But they can go home and live a life and even take dancing lessons.
They may still have a little trouble being understood, but they are
not in nursing homes.''
</P>
<P>
   The treatment has worked well in a handful of people, but there
are good reasons why the therapy is not used more widely, Goldstein
said. First, doctors are conservative and do not want to harm
fragile, sick patients, he said. The risks are not yet known.
Second, amphetamine has a terrible reputation as an addictive drug.
Doctors are loath to use it on anyone. Third, amphetamine is an
old, inexpensive drug that cannot be patented. Pharmaceutical
companies have no incentive to run expensive clinical trials to
test it in stroke patients.
</P>
<P>
   Feeney says that just because the therapy's mechanism is not
completely known is no reason not to use it. Until recently
scientists did not know how aspirin worked, he said. Stroke
researchers are looking for magic bullets that manipulate one tiny
part of brain based on elegant theories, he said, ``but maybe you
need a sloppy drug like amphetamine that releases neurotransmitters
all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After all,'' he said, ``to move your little finger, you have
to use every neurotransmitter in your brain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
