<HEADLINE>
GUINEA PIG IDENTITY CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Are guinea pigs rodents?(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Probably, based on structural features and fossil evidence,
though some scientists studying DNA evidence suspect otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Novacek, senior vice president and provost of the
American Museum of Natural History and curator of vertebrate
paleontology, said that there were studies, primarily of
mitochondrial genes, suggesting that guinea pigs might not be
rodents, but might belong to their own separate order.
</P>
<P>
   (Mitochondrial DNA is carried by the structures in cells that
act as cellular power plants. It is inherited in a different manner
than ordinary DNA is.)
</P>
<P>
   However, Novacek said, most of these studies were based on a
limited sample of genes in a limited number of orders. To get a
better answer, he said, far more gene sequences should be studied
for more mammals.
</P>
<P>
   He added that recent analysis also showed that by using the same
data as some of these studies, but employing another commonly
accepted model of gene evolution, guinea pigs can be placed in the
rodent group.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he said, the traditional kind of evidence in mammal
evolution is very strong that guinea pigs belong in the order
Rodentia, both from morphology (structural features like the head
and and the development of the gnawing teeth) and from paleontology
(fossils from Central Asia).
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail
to Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to:
Question(AT)nytimes.com Questions of general interest will be
answered in this column, but requests for medical advice cannot be
honored and unpublished letters cannot be answered
individually.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
