<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-YMCA-COMPETE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH CLUBS CRY FOUL AS YMCA GOES UPSCALE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Capital YMCA Service Center in downtown Washington
is a far cry from the Y's of old. It boasts two spacious fitness
centers, offers little in the way of community services and does
not allow children on weekdays. Members can also choose between a
basic membership and the more glitzy athletic membership, which
gives customers access to a second gym, laundry service and sauna.
</P>
<P>
   These facts are the essence of a long-standing feud between
nonprofit organizations and commercial health clubs.
</P>
<P>
   For years, private health club owners have complained that
YMCAs, community centers, hospitals and other not-for-profit
organizations can open fitness centers and pay no taxes on them
while competing directly and unfairly with health clubs that pay
taxes. Health clubs, they say, are the only businesses forced to
pay taxes to support their competitors. They also say that
nonprofit organizations have strayed from their original mission of
community outreach and have begun courting affluent adults who may
otherwise become dues-paying members of their clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Y in Washington is symbolic of a nonprofit endeavor that
has lost its way,'' said John McCarthy, executive director of the
International Health Racquet Sportsclub Association, a trade
organization for health clubs. ``It is parading as a public charity
but doesn't deserve that label.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Maier, director of association advancement for the YMCA in
the United States, said that nonprofit organizations running
fitness centers are being wrongfully criticized. ``Our mission
statement is clear: We put Christian principles into practice
through programs that build healthy spirit, mind and body for
all,'' he said. ``Some of our critics try to isolate one aspect of
our mission and say it doesn't belong. But it is all intertwined,
and fitness is an important part.''
</P>
<P>
   Debby Hirshman, executive director of the Jewish Community
Center on Manhattan's Upper West Side, agrees. ``We use our tax
savings as a way to make our facility affordable and
nonexclusive,'' said Ms. Hirshman, whose group is building a new
50,000-square-foot center, to open next year, complete with an
exercise area, Olympic-sized swimming pool and gymnasium.
Memberships are expected to cost $927 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The battle recently moved into the courtroom. Last month, a YMCA
in Secane, Pa., near Philadelphia, opened a ``wellness center,''
despite protests from local health club owners. The Sports Club in
Woodlyn, just a few miles from the new building, ultimately filed a
complaint _ the first of its kind _ with the state claiming that
the new Ridley Area YMCA violated Pennsylvania's Act 55, the
Institutions of Purely Public Charity Act, which declassifies the
``promotion of health'' as a charitable act and states that a
charity cannot compete directly with a small business by offering
overlapping services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no need for this Y to be built because there are
already 14 fitness centers within three miles of it,'' said David
Cohan, owner of the Woodlyn club. Cohan claims that several smaller
clubs have already gone out of business as a direct result of the
Y's opening. ``They offer the same things we do while enjoying a
mind-boggling laundry list of tax advantages.'' Membership at the
Sports Club costs $627 per year, compared with $360 for the YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mattson, lawyer for the Ridley Area YMCA, said his client
was in compliance with Act 55 because the Y was undertaking
activities specifically outlined in its charter. ``My client has
made a commitment to this community, and we believe this includes
health club services,'' said Mattson, who added that the YMCA
offers community outreach programs like child care, after-school
programs and classes for older people.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania is the first state with a law that defines
competition between charities and small businesses. If it is found
that the Ridley Area YMCA is in violation of the new law, then the
YMCA must reconfigure its services or forfeit its tax exemptions.
The original case was dismissed by a lower court and is expected to
be appealed to the Court of Common Pleas of Delaware County, Pa.,
this year. Several other states are considering similar
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, of the trade group for health clubs, was quick to
point out that most nonprofit organizations did important work and
deserved their tax breaks. ``Most are a valuable asset to their
community,'' he said. ``Only a very few abandon their charitable
principles by operating like full-scale, for-profit health clubs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
