<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7400 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX     02-01 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR'S MERCY MAY BE HIS DOWNFALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB RAY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The governor of Missouri did a courageous and compassionate
thing last week, but his brave act of mercy may end up costing him
his political career.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a personal plea from Pope John Paul II, Gov. Mel
Carnahan commuted the death sentence of Darrell Mease, a convicted
triple murderer.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Associated Press, a message from the pope was
relayed to the governor Wednesday afternoon by the Vatican's
secretary of state, Cardinal Angelo Sodano. Later, after a prayer
service at a St. Louis church, ``the pope came down from the altar
and personally asked the governor to `extend mercy' to Mease,'' the
wire report said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, in what some regard as a true miracle, Carnahan,
who still maintains that he is a supporter of capital punishment,
commuted Mease's sentence to life.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he made the decision in response to the pope's
direct plea ``because of a deep and abiding respect for the pontiff
and all he represents.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a most commendable act by this politician who is likely
to be a candidate for the U.S. Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   In a day when many politicians ``against'' the death penalty
have to declare their support ``for'' capital punishment in order
to get elected, it was refreshing to see Carnahan take such a gutsy
stand on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of action, however, that can ruin political
careers in a country where most people not only favor capital
punishment, but believe it ought to be applied more often and more
swiftly. Surely, it will cost Carnahan some votes, but I hope it
will gain him some as well.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the governor feels he can weather any political storm over
this issue by winning over Missouri's Catholic vote. Of all the
religious groups in this country, Catholics have been among the
least hypocritical on the issue of the death penalty _ staunchly
opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   As much as I applaud Carnahan's decision to grant a reprieve in
this one case, the fact that the governor plans to return to his
usual death-penalty stance reiterates one of the major problems
with capital punishment in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's act, no matter how laudable, underscores the
arbitrariness and capriciousness of this ultimate punishment.
Whether acting on conviction, conscience or papal plea, the
governor's decision to spare one life and ignore the destruction of
another makes it a pathetic act of mercy.
</P>
<P>
   We saw a similar example in Texas just two weeks ago when there
were two Death Row inmates _ both proclaiming their innocence _
scheduled to die within two days of each other. One received a stay
from the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals just hours before he was
scheduled to die.
</P>
<P>
   The courts and the governor of Texas refused to even look at the
case of the other man, sealing his fate to die by lethal injection
Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I renew the appeal I made most recently at Christmas for a
consensus to end the death penalty, which is both cruel and
unnecessary,'' the pope told a St. Louis crowd attending the
largest indoor Mass ever held in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   If we repeat that message long enough, maybe a few more people
will hear it.
</P>
<P>
   And, just maybe, instead of one man saving one life, there will
be many more people in this country fighting to save the lives of
the thousands of men and women on Death Rows across America.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
