r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BOWL-ANALYSIS-HNS     02-01 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BOWL-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL XXXIII: EXCESSIVELY GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The field at Pro Player Stadium was half-covered in
glitter and confetti, tamped down by a late-evening shower, as
though something of enduring magnificence had just occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The real themes of Super Bowl XXXIII, though, were found
elsewhere. They were in John Elway's mind, and Eugene Robinson's
soul, and Dan Reeves' eyes, and even Shannon Sharpe's knee. The
football was fine enough as it goes, but Denver's 34-19 victory
here Sunday almost borders on afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Broncos beat the Atlanta Falcons the way a snake
eats an egg _ slowly, but wholly. The subplots gave this game its
flavor, its context, and its place in history. You'll need more
than the usual half-hour video primer from NFL Films to make full
sense of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, the Broncos quarterback, paved his way to retirement, if
he so chooses, with his best Super Bowl performance, throwing for
336 yards and one touchdown and running for another en route to the
Most Valuable Player award. But it was the rheumy look in his eye
during the National Anthem that got people to thinking we were
seeing his last, and best, waltz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I was crying,'' he said, building up to a
brief stream-of-consciousness rap that hinted at retirement without
actually saying it. ``I definitely got a little bit emotional out
there, and I was just really kind of thanking God for the
opportunity and to stand there and finally get going and look
around to see what was going on because this is the greatest game
in the world and so, yeah, it was emotional, definitely emotional
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, the Falcons safety who played Elway's foil on the
killing 80-yard touchdown pass to Rod Smith in the second quarter,
confronted not only his on-field failings but also the destruction
of his reputation after being arrested for soliciting a sex act
from an undercover Miami policewoman. Unlike most people Saturday
night when smacked full-face with their inexplicable recklessness,
he not only explained it to the world, but he seemed almost eager
to do so, turning on its head the tale of the fallen angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say a lot about this, because it's in the hands of my
lawyer,'' Robinson said with an almost intimidating earnestness.
``I was innocent but not righteous in this deal. A friend of mine
told me, `Confession is good for the soul, but bad for the
reputation.' My reputation, I can deal with that. But the hurt I
caused my wife and my children is what gives me the pain. I know
some of you will say, `Hypocritical Christian,' and like that.
Well, I deserve that. I'll take that.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Reeves, now a four-time Super Bowl loser,
with interest compounded by the fact this meal was force-fed him by
the two people he still believes ran him out of Denver, Elway and
Mike Shanahan. He spoke from the high road, but his eyes betrayed
his sadness, even when he stood at the side of Elway's podium and
congratulated him. He never spoke of the foul aftertaste, choosing
to hide behind the losing coach's traditional curtain of platitudes
rather than focus on the stabbing pain in his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't play well,'' he said without the jut-jawed
conviction with which he usually tackles a question. ``I knew if we
didn't play well, we would get beat, and that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about Elway or Shanahan, surely none of the candor that
marked his soliloquy of 10 days earlier when he spoke so earnestly
of how he felt Elway and Shanahan hurt him in Denver. He couldn't
raise that issue again because, in the frontier justice that is
football, the winners talk, and the losers listen.
</P>
<P>
   Even the week-long episodic sitcom, ``Your Mother; My Mother?
No, Your Mother'' between tight end Sharpe and Atlanta cornerback
Ray Buchanan ended with a strange serendipity. Sharpe's only catch
came in the first quarter, setting up Denver's first touchdown, but
he was hit sharply in the left knee by Buchanan, tore a ligament
and missed the final three quarters. He didn't do enough to talk
the talk, but Buchanan didn't do enough to talk the talk, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great time,'' Sharpe said of everything but the hit.
``I did my job as far as getting you media guys hyped, and Ray did
his job as far as getting you media guys hyped. I said it before.
It was just talk. It was just hype.''
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed just hype. But when superimposed upon John Elway's
future, Eugene Robinson's torment, Dan Reeves' place in football
history, and even Lawrence Taylor's election to the Pro Football
Hall of Fame, it took Super Bowl XXXIII over the top. Part
melodrama, part crime story, part Kabuki, part angry man theater
... and a football chaser. It was all too much, the way Super Bowls
are always billed but never play out, the triumph of excess at its
most gloriously excessive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
