<HEADER>
A7429 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BOWL-COMMERCIALS-H     02-01 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BOWL-COMMERCIALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST SUPER BOWL COMMERCIALS AS DULL AS THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You know it's a letdown when the Super Bowl is
so boring that you can't wait for another commercial. And you know
it's a long, wasted day when you're bitter that the commercials
weren't funnier or more daring.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we put too much pressure on advertising agencies to
score with Super Bowl ads. Because this year there was precious
little to speak of, and perhaps only one that you'll remember to
talk about around the water cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com's ads featuring cynical kids talking about work were
far and away the most memorable. ``I want to have a brown nose.''
``I want to be underappreciated.'' ``I want to be forced into early
retirement.'' Black and white. Hilarious and chilling all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday marked what looks to be the end of the Budweiser Frogs _
which couldn't come soon enough. Talk about a campaign that was
played out.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a rundown, with star ratings, of most _ but not all _ of
the day's ads:
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Hut's New York style pizza. It worked with Spike Lee and
his ``You got nothin'!'' rants, but failed with Fran Drescher and
her bad Audrey Hepburn look.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's use of Hal the computer and the memory of ``2001: A
Space Odyssey'' to mock others for not being Y2K ready. Spooky and
wry and it made a point.
</P>
<P>
   The MasterCard ``priceless'' campaign with a host of cartoon
characters was well conceived and retro. Olive Oyl and Wonderbra _
nice.
</P>
<P>
   The Budweiser frogs series. Yawn.
</P>
<P>
   Selsun Blue. What? Why waste your money?.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi One ad with the ``Reservoir Dogs'' poof: All style, no
substance. Like the drink.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria's Secret promo for its on-line fashion show. It had the
jiggle factor for male football fans, but are they really going to
jump into cyberspace instead of watch ``SportsCenter'' for
highlights? Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   The Bud lobster trying to stay alive. Beats the frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Cracker Jacks ``really big bag'' ad. Very funny and creative:
The giant bag falls off a car trying to park in a garage and
crushes a man at a game, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The Visa Check Card. The guy locked in the bathroom at his
date's house was decent, the Buckingham Palace guard without his
uniform was clever.
</P>
<P>
   The Budweiser Dalmatians' sibling rivalry, well, was nothing
special.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com: We love cynical.
</P>
<P>
   Frito-Lay BBQ Doritos: Can we end the lame
hot-chick-makes-dumb-guys-drool genre right here?.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-Up ``un'' campaign: Confusing and not very interesting.
Undo it.
</P>
<P>
   Mail Boxes Etc. scored by doing a simple ad highlighting a
customer who makes ice cream. Full of charity and good spirit,
which made it stand out.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T ``If this is you'' campaign: If this is your idea of
selling something, start again. And enough with the
bold-words-across-the-image look. That's so early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Light ad where two guys have to choose between their
six-pack and toilet paper. ``Paper or plastic'' is the punch line?
And a rule to remember: Never blow all your money on ``lite'' beer.
Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Crispy M&AMP;Ms. Not even Halle Berry in a swimsuit could save this
bomb. And Patrick Warburton's ``Seinfeld'' act is sooooo tired.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell: The slacker kid who only wants to work from noon
to 3 p.m. This is a good campaign (only one aired) and it should be
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Progressive Auto Insurance: Who sold out ``ET''? This is a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota ad with Steve Young on a blind date with a woman who
doesn't watch football or TV: Quick, intelligent and funny.
</P>
<P>
   California Cheese, moon made of cheese riff: Almost, but not
quite.
</P>
<P>
   Hotjobs.com daydreaming security guard. Very good and very
creative. Who knew there'd be two Super Bowl ads _ both good _ from
on-line companies trying to get people new jobs?
</P>
<P>
   The World Wrestling Federation and it's ``wholesome image''
campaign. Funny and violent _ two great qualities in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   American Express and Jerry Seinfeld getting out of New York to
get a life: As usual, this was great. ``I can't feel my face!''
``I'm going crazy out here!'' More of these, please.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Express and its misplaced Stanley Cup ad: Almost, but
not quite (a familiar feeling to the day).
</P>
<P>
   Michelob beer and its football player traded for a case of beer.
Wasn't a frog, but it wasn't much either.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel: What? Who are these people? Do they own Selsun Blue?.
</P>
<P>
   The Land Rover boy-seeking-friend ad. Not clever enough to be a
Super Bowl ad, but not bad for a regular Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Just for Feet: Did anybody else get a weird slavery overtone
from this ad that tried too hard and fell flat? Let's see, a
barefoot man in Kenya is running _ or is he being hunted? _ then he
passes out and wakes up with shoes on his feet and screams. Wow.
Too much salsa or this was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL fan ``Thank You'' campaign. Wonderful (if not entirely
sincere). Keep it into next year.
</P>
<P>
   Buy.com: Thus ends the on-line creative thing. A man sniffing a
dog's butt is like you're not even trying.
</P>
<P>
   Budweiser billiards: There comes a point when beer ads blend
together. This is that point.
</P>
<P>
   The day also featured quite a bit of advertising for future
movies, some of which looked intriguing. Unless it happened on a
nature break, Nike didn't advertise and that's a shame. While there
were a handful of really good ads, there weren't five you're dying
to replay to friends, ones you'll remember next week or any that
packed a wallop to your senses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
