<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE INDEPENDENT COUNSELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the famous words of Steve Forbes: Stomp it, kill
it, never let it rise again.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' target for massive destruction during the 1996 GOP
presidential campaign was the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   This time the object of derision is the sweeping statute
authorizing the office of independent counsel, which has been
leached of all respect by Kenneth Starr's abuse of his powers.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any Washington politician who still likes the
independent counsel law, that worthy has lost his or her tongue or
is in hiding. It is the legislative equivalent of a poison pill.
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, the danged thing lapses in June if Congress does not
renew it. Letting it conveniently expire provides a dignified,
bipartisan way out of a well-intentioned concept that has become an
uncontrollable legal and political monster.
</P>
<P>
   For months, politicians of both parties have been publicly
counting nails in the coffin of the independent counsel law. When
Attorney General Janet Reno rejected Republican pressure to seek an
outside counsel to investigate charges of campaign finance abuse by
President Clinton and Vice President Gore, GOP Sen. Fred Thompson
declared that to be the ``final nail'' in the statute's coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there have been so many additional lid-fasteners on
that political box that the law can be promptly buried without
tears.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Reno also declined to appoint another independent
counsel to probe charges of campaign finance hanky-panky by former
Clinton aide Harold Ickes. It sent a signal that she is fed up with
the congressional habit of demanding Democratic officials be
investigated for potential wrongdoing by overzealous prosecutors
with unlimited budgets, authority and self-righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   The public was also reminded once again of the lengths to which
Starr's office will go to keep kicking Clinton while he is down: A
report leaked that Starr had decided he could constitutionally
indict Clinton for a criminal offense while Clinton is still in
office and is actively considering doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Both the legal basis for an indictment grounded in Starr's
ambiguous and contradictory evidence and the interpretation of a
permissive Constitution are on dangerously shaky ground.
</P>
<P>
   Such a decision would set off a political and constitutional
furor bound to backfire against the Republicans in the 2000
elections. A new Newsweek poll indicates that by a 65-to-30-percent
margin, voters say the president should not be indicted and tried
for his actions during the Monica matter even AFTER he leaves
office.
</P>
<P>
   Sensibly, the majority feels that enough is enough. The vision
of a former president of the United States _ leader of the free
world, for pity's sake _ going off to jail in leg irons and
handcuffs for lying about illicit sex is too ludicrous to
contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   And the timing of the leak, coming in the midst of Clinton's
impeachment trial, seemed designed to meddle once again in the
Senate's decision-making process, adding another Clinton-is-a-crook
story to the public relations mix.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Starr has shown much consideration lately for judicial
objectivity. He intervened on behalf of the House prosecutors to
arrange their interview with Monica Lewinsky, threatened Webster
Hubbell and Susan McDougal with further jail terms despite their
dwindling usefulness as anti-Clinton witnesses and indicted Julie
Hiatt Steele for lying when she said Kathleen Willey had not told
her Clinton groped her.
</P>
<P>
   The picture this projects is of a judicial process run wild.
Starr himself cannot be stopped; the law lets him go on until he
runs out of gas. But the law itself can be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The two committees with jurisdiction over the statute, the House
judiciary Committee and the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,
are partisan snakepits that have already shown an inability to
reach common ground. The GOP majority on the House committee rammed
through the impeachment articles and a similar GOP majority in the
Senate conducted inconclusive hearings into campaign finance
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Those committees are unlikely vehicles to produce the delicate
legislative tinkering necessary to reshape the law into a fair,
balanced system recognizing the concept but creating sensible
restraints. Republicans opposed the law when it was used against
GOP president Ronald Reagan; now that Democrats have had a taste of
that particular bitter medicine, they oppose it too.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, this columnist supported the law, as a means of
avoiding the potential conflict of interest of having the Justice
Department investigate administration colleagues. But the cure
turned out to be worse than the ailment. Five independent counsels
are now at work investigating Clinton and four present or past
members of his Cabinet. One indictment for lying, that of
Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, recently ended in an acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   There may be some way eventually to reauthorize the law with
strict restrictions capping its duration and budget and limiting
its powers to probes of official misconduct rather than private
impropriety. But that is not possible in today's polarized
political climate. So give it a rest for awhile. Maybe we will feel
the need to come back to it, maybe not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
