r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINECOOKIES-TEX     02-01 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINECOOKIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERSPACE TOUTED AS SAFER FOR GIRL SCOUTS THAN DOOR-TO-DOOR
SELLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE S. DAILEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLESON, Texas _ Brittany Williams has taken Girl Scout cookie
sales into a new neighborhood: cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-year-old Brownie has taken to the Internet to sell those
celebrated thin mints and other popular Girl Scout cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brittany doesn't prefer one method over another, she
says, ``It's better than having to go door to door when it's cold
or hot.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the low-tech method has proved more successful than the
high-tech way. The Frazier Elementary School second-grader has sold
more than 100 boxes of cookies by e-mailing Internet users in the
area and 358 boxes the old-fashioned way, surpassing her personal
goal of 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize that I was going to sell so many,'' Brittany
said.
</P>
<P>
   A few troops around the country have Web pages offering cookies
for sale. But some local Girl Scout officials say local troops
don't offer such an ordering system, and they don't know of other
area girls who are using e-mail to make individual sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say that is unusual,'' said Sue Blocker, services
manager for Three Corners Community, a center that assists Girl
Scouts in Burleson and the nearby communities of Crowley and
Joshua.
</P>
<P>
   But Cathy O'Neal, spokeswoman for the Circle T Council, which
includes Three Corners and Fort Worth, said that Brittany's
approach will probably catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany's mother, Kim Williams, said it already has.
</P>
<P>
   The mother-daughter team has been contacted for e-mailing tips
by Girl Scouts in 11 states, including Oregon, California, and
Florida, the mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Williams thought of the idea. Using the People Search
function on her Internet service provider, she sought America
Online users in Burleson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we exhausted everyone in Burleson on AOL, we actually
went out on the Web using the Netfind People Finder,'' the mother
said. ``The first 400 were AOL users; the last were with other
providers.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter then e-mailed a sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My troop is selling cookies to go to summer camp,'' the letter
reads in part. ``My mom told me that this is safer than going door
to door, and I'm learning about marketing and computer skills. Girl
Scout cookies are really good. ... They are $3 a box and you pay
when they come in, which is right after Valentine's Day. Thank You,
Brittany and Troop 3444.''
</P>
<P>
   Brittany makes printed copies of the e-mailed information and
will make the deliveries and pick up the money.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Williams said most of their Internet customers are rural
residents who don't get door-to-door sales calls. But Brittany has
also gotten responses from lawyers, real estate agents and
businesspeople who congratulate her on her ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   Doy Cloninger, a Burleson resident who responded to Brittany,
said he was about to delete her message along with a lot other
trash e-mail when he noticed that it was sent from Burleson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a pretty good marketing idea to e-mail
someone. (It's) easy access,'' Cloninger said. ``It just seems like
it was easier than going door to door.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Williams said she screens all e-mail before Brittany sees
them. Mother and daughter compose thank-you e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said the Circle T Web page has a number that people can
call if they want to find out how to get cookies in their area.
</P>
<P>
   And Internet browsers can e-mail the San Antonio Area Council
for information on how to order cookies. Girl Scout Troop 1035 in
northern Virginia has obtained certification as a safe shopping
site and takes major credit cards for orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Girl Scouts have stepped up in technology,'' Kim
Williams said. ``It's using today's technology to do something
they've done since 1912.''
</P>
<P>
   Brittany has already sold beyond the maximum amount needed for
prizes. Her extra sales will win her ``cookie credits'' that are
applied toward summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany's e-mail address is getacookie(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
