<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain will drench sections of the Northeast as a warm front
pushes northward along the Atlantic Seaboard. Gusty onshore winds
will reach gale force on the New England coast. Farther inland,
cold air trapped in the valleys from northeast New York to southern
Maine will allow for a period of freezing rain during the morning.
Wet snow will be mixed with sleet in the higher terrain of northern
Vermont, New Hampshire and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front pushing off the East Coast will end the showery
rains from the Middle Atlantic states to northern Florida. A few
thunderstorms will persist over southern Florida. Clouds will
linger across the Appalachians with scattered showers developing
along the west slopes of the mountains as a new cold front
approaches. There will be breaks in the clouds in the Carolinas and
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific air will stream east across the Plains as high pressure
builds over the central Rockies. Seasonably mild weather along with
sunshine is expected from Nebraska to Texas. The Gulf Coast will
stay dull as a stream of moisture from the central Pacific merges
with the tail end of a front in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Despite gusty, drier winds from the northwest, clouds will cover
most of the upper Plains with some flurries in the Dakotas. A cold
front racing into the Northwest will produce rain and strong winds
on the Washington and northern Oregon Coast. Snow levels will rise
in the northern Cascades. The Southwest will be bright and milder.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Moon Matters
</P>
<P>
   There are times when weather forecasters pay attention to the
moon. For example, the surge of water associated with a landfalling
hurricane is highest around the time of high tide, and it is
further magnified when the moon is full. Low tide, which recedes to
its lowest mark when the moon is full, can also pose danger. On
Monday, strong ocean winds pushed water onshore along the east
coast of Florida. Then, around 2 p.m., as low tide began in earnest
in response to a nearly full moon, water that was piled-up near
shore flowed swiftly out to sea, raising the risk of dangerous rip
currents.
</P>
</TEXT>
