<HEADLINE>
FROM MICROSCOPE TO PEN  
 YOUNG TERMITES IN LOVE  
 MEASURING MUSCLE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers at Northwestern University have performed a bit of
alchemy in the lab: turning a precision analytical instrument, an
atomic force microscope, into a precision writing instrument.
</P>
<P>
   An atomic force microscope uses a fine stylus that rides the
surface of an object in order to render it in molecular detail. One
continual problem with such microscopes is the tendency of a small
amount of water to condense in the tiny gap between the stylus and
the object.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers turned the problem into an opportunity. They
noticed that the water moves by capillary action between the stylus
and the object, and theorized that it could be used to transfer a
chemical, a few molecules at a time, much as the nib of a pen
transfers ink to paper.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwestern researchers used an oily compound called
octadecanethiol, or ODT, as ink, and a thin layer of gold fused to
mica as paper. They were able to write lines of ODT a few dozen
molecules wide _ about 30 nanometers, or slightly over a millionth
of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, who described the technique in the journal
Science, suggested that it could have applications in the
manufacture of minuscule electronic circuits. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How tough can it be to be a termite, acting (literally) like a
bump on a log, chomping wood to its heart's content?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty tough, apparently, at least when love is concerned. A
termite's life can be a real soap opera, according to a recent
study by a Cornell University biologist.
</P>
<P>
   The biologist studied the mating habits of Zootermopsis
nevadensis, a type of termite native to California woodlands. She
found that within an hour or two after a male and female get
together on a log to establish a nest, their eyes, and hearts,
start to wander.
</P>
<P>
   Some females, according to the study, will invite a second male
to the nest site to fight the first for mating rights. And for
their part, some males will simply fly off in search of different
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Since nevadensis couples cooperatively care for their young,
such mutual choosing (or re-choosing) of mates, which is common in
vertebrates, makes sense. Just as a person might decide that a
boyfriend or girlfriend is less than perfect for creating a family,
a termite would want the best possible partner for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that in making a second choice for a mate,
female termites often chose males with bigger heads (the better to
butt and bite an opponent). Males, though, often opted for females
better suited to reproduction, with bigger bodies and more room for
storing fat.
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The basic mechanism by which muscles work is no mystery.
First-time biology students learn about the interleaved proteins in
muscle fiber, actin and myosin, and how myosin uses adenosine
triphosphate, or ATP, as an energy source to move along the actin
filament and pull it in one direction. That action, repeated
countless times across a muscle, is what causes contraction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Japanese researchers have discovered exactly how far the
myosin ``head,'' as the working end of the protein is known,
travels. Using a very thin crystal needle to which a myosin
fragment was attached, the researchers measured how much the needle
deflected as the myosin was brought in contact with an actin
filament in the presence of ATP.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that instead of a smooth movement along
the actin filament, the myosin traveled in discrete steps, with
each step 5.3 nanometers long, or about two 10-millionths of an
inch. The myosin can move in two to five steps in rapid succession,
producing total travel of about 11 to 30 nanometers (which may
account for some earlier measurements of myosin travel that were in
that range).
</P>
<P>
   Rather than breaking down an ATP molecule for each step, myosin
makes the multiple steps through only one ATP cycle.
</P>
</TEXT>
