<HEADLINE>
(EDITORS: REPEATS COLUMN FOR JANUARY 29)  
  
</HEADLINE>
   Daughter Faces Status Question 
 &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  My daughter works as the personal assistant to a woman
who is wildly successful in the multimedia world. She works
exclusively for this woman, at this woman's office. Her employer
pays her by the hour as an independent contractor, so she receives
no benefits, no vacation and must pay self-employment tax on her
earnings. Is this proper and legal?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer:  &LR; The facts are pretty sketchy but, off the bat, I'd say
that your daughter is very likely being illegally misclassified as
a contractor.
</P>
<P>
   She's not alone. Confusion over employee/contractor status is a
growing problem nowadays, from small startups to Fortune 500
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of years, we've been dealing with questions
like this a great deal,'' said Conley Baker of the Employers Group,
a California nonprofit that provides human resources help to its
member firms. ``I think it has to do with downsizing. Companies
need work to be done but don't want to hire people as regular
employees to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service used to have a checklist of 20
different criteria for telling whether someone is an employee or
independent contractor. Recently, they've boiled these down to
three major categories:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Behavioral control &LR; . &LR;   &LR; Contractors generally have great
freedom to do the work any way they want _ any time, any place, as
long as the job gets done. Employees, on the other hand, follow
directions from their employers about how, where and when to do the
job.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Financial control &LR; . Contractors are usually paid a flat fee
for an entire project and risk losing money if the job takes longer
than expected, while employees are paid a weekly, monthly or hourly
wage and incur little personal financial risk. Contractors also
tend to invest in their own tools and business materials, while
employees use equipment and materials supplied by the company.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Type of relationship. &LR;   &LR; Contractors tend to be hired for
limited amounts of time, while employees are hired on an open-ended
basis. And contractors tend to perform work that is not a key
aspect of the company's business: An accountant who is hired to do
a once-a-year audit is probably a contractor, while the bookkeeper
who handles day-to-day office finances is probably an employee.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that your daughter is an employee for a variety of
reasons. She's paid hourly on an open-ended basis, she's working
solely for this one woman, and I bet the boss directs her work and
sets her hours.
</P>
<P>
   Your daughter should approach her employer and politely explain
that she doesn't want the company to run afoul of the IRS or other
agencies by misclassifying her.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, there are big financial risks to an employer who
messes up here _ such as liability for back payroll taxes,
unemployment taxes, disability insurance and other benefits, and
workers compensation payments.
</P>
<P>
   Want more information on how to determine if someone is an
employee or an independent contractor? See IRS Publication 15A, the
Employer's Supplemental Tax Guide. You can get it by calling (800)
TAX-FORM or visiting the IRS Web site at  &LR; www.irs.ustreas.gov &LR; . You
may also want to read the excellent guidebook, ``Hiring Independent
Contractors: The Employer's Legal Guide,'' by Stephen Fishman (Nolo
Press).
</P>
<P>
   Burning Bridges
</P>
<P>
   Q: About seven months ago, I quit a job that I'd held very
successfully for five years. Now I'd like to return to the company,
but the human resources department isn't returning my calls. I
think that I'm being blacklisted because of critical things I said
about my old manager during my exit interview. At the time, I was
told the exit interview would be confidential. Is it fair to hold
my honest comments against me this way? Can they refuse to hire me
back because of things I said in a supposedly-confidential
interview?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Like much in the working world, this company's refusal to
hire you back may not be fair _ but it's completely legal.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have the right to hire or reject whomever they want,
as long as they're not discriminating on a basis such as race or
gender.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies even have formal policies against rehiring anyone
who's quit _ no matter how good their performance was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I hired back a woman who had left for four months and I
had a number of human resources people say to me, `I'm surprised
you had her come back,''' said Patricia Stansbury, CEO of Stansbury
Staffing Consultants and president of the Northern California Human
Resources Association.
</P>
<P>
   This company should, of course, have the basic civility to
return your calls and tell you what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   But don't hold your breath waiting for that. Write them off your
job-hunt list and move on to other employers.
</P>
<P>
   And in the meantime, try to draw some lessons from this episode.
</P>
<P>
   One is to avoid burning bridges when leaving jobs. It can be
tempting to say ``Whee-hoo! Take this job and shove it!'' the
minute you get an offer from a new employer.
</P>
<P>
   But six months or two years from now, the company you're leaving
may look awfully good again. So make sure you end your stay at any
job in a professional fashion _ giving plenty of notice, staying
engaged in your work through the end and offering to help train
your replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson is to remain equally professional during exit
interviews. Perhaps you did this, and the company just didn't want
to hear any criticism at all. But perhaps you let off steam in a
way that alienated them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to tell the truth,'' Stansbury said. ``But be
circumspect. Keep your comments on very specific behaviors and
situations. If you talk about how a manager always came in late
while he was asking his employees to be on time, they shouldn't
hold that against you. But never get into character assassination.
If you bad-mouth a manager's personality, it will just be
considered gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MORE ON MATERNITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Last week's column included a question about maternity leave
rights from a woman who had been laid off from her job, became
pregnant and is now about to be called back to work. Attorney
Judith Kurtz of San Francisco points out that California's
pregnancy disability leave law applies to all pregnant employees,
regardless of how long they've been on the job. So if this woman
returned to work for even one day, California law would make her
eligible for up to four months of pregnancy disability leave,
including about six weeks off after childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
