<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, February 2, 1999,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ARENA _ ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting System is expected to
announce Tuesday that Philips Electronics has purchased the naming
and major sponsorship rights to Atlanta's new downtown arena. The
deal would give Philips, a Netherlands-based conglomerate whose
North American consumer electronics division is based in Dunwoody,
a broad platform to market its products. (Saporta, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AVADO-EARNINGS _ Avado Brands announced a 154 percent increase
in operating income from its four core brands- Canyon Cafe, Don
Pablo's, Hops Restaurant Bar and Brewery and McCormick &AMP; Schmick's.
Including charges, the company reported a loss for the fourth
quarter. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-MADISON _ Follow on Madison connection to companies
slapped with trading suspensions; details of prior run-ins with
Securities and Exchange Commission by a Peter Tosto. (Clothier,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/STOCK-FRAUDEXPLAIN _ Generic explainer on stock frauds. One
way to do it is to buy stock in cheap or worthless companies, hype
the companies through press releases, word of mouth, the Internet,
etc, and then sell the stock if the price goes up. (Chambers,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   AMD _ AUSTIN, Texas _ AMD continues negotiating with Gateway
Inc. to get its K6 chips in Gateway products. Reports on the Web
that it was a done deal help boost AMD stock on Monday. (Gallaga,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-PTECH 0129 -- The demand for goods and services is being
heard and answered daily on the Internet, the world's
fastest-growing bazaar. Listeners include the transportation
industry, with players like Travelocity, and the book and record
distributors like Amazon.com, Barnes &AMP; Noble and many more.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most intriguing, however, are the players that give
quotes, such as auto, life and health insurers _ and that classify
people in mere seconds based on factual information about our
lives. They get high marks from the consumer arbiters like
Kiplinger and Money magazine, too. (Ernest Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
