<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAINTS-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     02-01 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAINTS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PREPARE FOR SAINTS': WHEN `FOUR SAINTS' SHOOK UP THE OLD GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First produced in 1934, in the midst of the Depression, the
Virgil Thomson-Gertrude Stein opera ``Four Saints in Three Acts''
remains one of this century's most famous avant-garde works.
</P>
<P>
   An insouciant piece that contains neither four saints nor three
acts, the opera cheerfully thumbed its nose at convention: Stein's
willfully hermetic text dispensed with plot, sequential time and
discernible meaning, while Thomson's American-inflected, almost
naively tuneful score defied traditional operatic standards.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that an all-black cast and Florine Stettheimer's
shimmering cellophane sets, and you had one of the most
talked-about events of the day: a show that caught the imagination
of cafe society and became (albeit briefly) the longest-running
opera on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Prepare for Saints,'' the journalist Steven
Watson argues that the success of ``Four Saints in Three Acts''
``epitomized the mainstreaming of modernism'' in 1930s America. The
intertwined lives of the opera's collaborators and the story of the
show's evolution, he suggests, provide ``a window onto the
brilliant generation that defined modern taste and stylishness in
the early years of the Depression.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach Watson takes in this book is similar to that
employed in his 1991 book ``Strange Bedfellows: The First American
Avant-Garde,'' which took on a slightly earlier period in American
culture and profiled such artists as Ezra Pound, Eugene O'Neill,
Alfred Stieglitz and Marcel Duchamp.
</P>
<P>
   Here as there, Watson weaves together biography, cultural
history and plain old gossip to create a smart, lively but
sometimes skin-deep narrative focused around personalities and
anecdotes. The volume's coffee-table-book tendencies are
unfortunately underscored by inane charts and sidebars like ``1920s
Paris: Trans-Atlantic Residents and Hotspots'' and ``Americanisms
and American Chic.''
</P>
<P>
   For the lay reader, however, Watson does an engaging job of
conjuring up the overlapping worlds his subjects inhabited: the
feud-ridden expatriate community in Paris where Thomson and Stein
met in the 1920s, and the trend-setting bohemia of 1930s New York,
where Thomson would find the patrons and promoters who would get
``Four Saints'' produced.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's quick thumbnail portraits of his principals, often
based on one another's acerbic words, are equally incisive. Stein
emerges from these pages as a ``modernist patriarch'' who radiated
a ``papal authority'' _ an arrogant, difficult woman who coveted
fame despite her reputation for deliberate obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Her writing, a kind of cubism translated into prose, Watson
reminds us, was once described by Edmund Wilson as ``registering
the vibration of a psychological country like some human
seismograph whose charts we haven't the training to read.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Thomson, he comes across as a worthy sparring partner for
Stein, a sharp-tongued, consummately assured Wunderkind whom Auden
once compared to an intimidating butler at an English country
house. Convinced that dissonant modernist music had reached a dead
end, the future music critic found his voice as a composer in
setting Stein's texts to music, a discipline that inspired in his
work a new simplicity and a renewed allegiance to his own
Midwestern American roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gertrude was wonderful to set to music because there was no
temptation to illustrate the words,'' Thomson observed. ``For the
most part you didn't know what it meant anyway, so you couldn't
make it like birdie babbling by a brook or heavy heavy hangs my
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the task facing Thomson was a daunting one. Stein's
libretto, which invoked the lives of the early Spanish saints as a
kind of metaphor for the lives of artists _ similarly consecrated,
Thomson argued, ``to a nonmaterial end'' _ had not assigned parts
to individual singers, and read, Thomson recalled, as ``a quite
impressive obscurity.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Stein's childlike verses (``Pigeons on the grass alas'')
yielded little in the way of conventional meaning, Thomson was
forced to rely almost exclusively on sounds and rhythms. He set
everything Stein wrote (including the stage directions) to music,
assigned lines to lesser characters and turned St. Teresa into two
figures so he could write duets.
</P>
<P>
   His friend Maurice Grosser later pieced together a scenario for
the opera _ less a narrative than a series of tableaux or vignettes
that would anchor the music and words on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the opera produced would prove nearly as difficult as
putting it together. By 1932, Watson reports, when Thomson arrived
in New York in search of backers, the Depression had deepened:
``The Metropolitan Opera had nearly gone under, and commercial art
galleries were closing as quickly as they had opened during the
boom years of the 1920s.''
</P>
<P>
   Two intersecting groups of supporters would play a crucial role
in providing the cash and cachet necessary for turning ``Four
Saints'' into the phenomenon it became.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a group of wealthy New York socialites with
advanced cultural tastes, a group that included such hostesses as
Muriel Draper and Constance Askew, the gossip columnist Lucius
Beebe and the editor Frank Crowninshield.
</P>
<P>
   The second was a group Watson calls ``the Harvard modernists'':
a close-knit band of Cambridge friends that included Lincoln
Kirstein, the future ballet impresario who would bring George
Balanchine to the United States; the architect Philip Johnson;
Alfred Barr, the director of the new Museum of Modern Art; A.
Everett ``Chick'' Austin Jr., who as director of the Wadsworth
Atheneum in Hartford, Conn., would provide both a venue and
financing for ``Four Saints,'' and Kirk Askew Jr., who, along with
his wife, Constance, would organize the New York-London salon where
Thomson met John Houseman and Frederick Ashton, the eventual
director and choreographer, respectively, of ``Four Saints.''
</P>
<P>
   The role these Harvard alumni would play in the revamping of
American culture has been written about before _ most notably by
Nicholas Fox Weber in his 1992 book ``Patron Saints: Five Rebels
Who Opened America to a New Art'' _ but Watson dexterously
orchestrates his sketches of them to give the reader an
impressionistic sense of the world that fostered ``Four Saints.''
</P>
<P>
   The reader wishes that Watson had devoted more space in this
volume to the role the opera played in its creators' careers and
its enduring legacy. (The multimedia work of Robert Wilson and
Philip Glass, for instance, is consigned to two glancing
paragraphs.)
</P>
<P>
   But that perhaps lies beyond the ambitions of this book, which
in the end aspires less to critical analysis than to simple
portraiture _ to chronicling ``those blazing years'' when modernism
was brought ``into the settings of the old guard: the opera, the
museum and the ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PREPARE FOR SAINTS'
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Stein, Virgil Thomson and the Mainstreaming of American
Modernism
</P>
<P>
   By Steven Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 371 pages. Random House. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
