<P>
   OLY-IOC-CONFERENCE _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Until the Salt Lake
bribery case broke, the IOC's biggest headache was doping. Years of
scandals, dating back to Seoul (where a Russian ship docked in a
nearby harbor was used to test athletes before their real tests)
and going through shaky tests in Atlanta, have embarrassed the IOC
into a conference beginning Tuesday that could lead to more
complete testing. But long-time observers wonder if it's just
business as usual. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/OLY-IOC-JUAN _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Amid increasing calls
for the resignation of Juan Antonio Samaranch, the International
Olympic Committee on Monday sought to clarify the record on what it
called ''inaccuracies and presentations'' circulating worldwide
about its embattled president. The question of whether Samaranch,
78, has the support to remain as the head of the IOC has
intensified as details continue to surface of improper payments
made to members from cities bidding to host the Olympic Games.
(Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IOC-BIDS _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta's Olympic bid team spent $4.8
million lobbying the International Olympic Committee in the final
two years of their campaign to win the 1996 Centennial Olympic
Games, according to financial records. That's $56,000 per IOC
member. Also, Billy Payne has received the IOC's request for
evidence of excesses in the bid effort. (Turner) 18
</P>
