<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER ROUND IN THE DRINK-A-DAY DEBATE  
 SLIMMER CHILDREN, HEALTHIER HEARTS  
 HAVING BABIES AFTER 40 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contrary to previous reports, women who drink moderately _ up to
one and a half alcoholic drinks a day _ may face no increased risk
of developing breast cancer, according to a decades-long study of
5,000 women in Framingham, Mass. In fact, the study by researchers
at Boston University School of Medicine suggests that breast cancer
risk may even decline slightly as alcohol consumption rises from
none to one and a half drinks a day.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings, published this month in the American Journal
of Epidemiology, should prove reassuring for women who stay within
current dietary guidelines to limit alcohol consumption to one
drink a day. However, they are unlikely to end the ongoing
controversy over the risk of alcohol for women, because previous
studies have linked alcohol consumption in any amount to a risk of
breast cancer greater than that found among nondrinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Although some studies have found no increased risk, a combined
analysis of 38 studies published in 1994 concluded that one drink a
day raised a woman's risk of breast cancer by 10 percent over that
faced by nondrinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Dr. R. Curtis Ellison, senior author of the new
report, pointed out that ``because light alcohol consumption
markedly reduces a woman's risk of heart disease and stroke,
longevity is greater for light drinkers than for abstainers.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol in moderation is known to protect the cardiovascular
system, and several studies have suggested that moderate drinking
can lower the overall death rate among women by 5 percent to 20
percent. Dr. Matthew Longnecker of the National Institute of
Environmental Health Sciences pointed out in an accompanying
editorial that, at most, alcohol would account for only about 2
percent of breast cancer cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston researchers, led by Dr. Yuqing Zhang, noted that in
most previous studies, breast cancer risk rose primarily among
women who consumed two or more drinks a day.
</P>
<P>
   They said the findings were more likely to reflect the habits of
the average American woman, who consumes no more than one drink a
day.
</P>
<P>
   _ JANE E. BRODY
</P>
<P>
   Pear-Shaped Is Better
</P>
<P>
   Apple-shaped children _ those with more fat around the
midsection _ have more heart disease risk factors than their
pear-shaped peers, according to a study reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies have shown that adults with more weight around
their waists have higher blood pressure and lower levels of
high-density lipoprotein (``good'' cholesterol) than those whose
weight gravitates around the hips and thighs. But the association
between body shape and cardiovascular disease risk factors had not
been well studied in children and adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   In the current study, which was published in Circulation, the
journal of the American Heart Association, researchers from
Cincinnati measured body fat distribution, blood pressure and blood
fat in 127 boys and girls between 9 and 17 years old. They also
used electrocardiograms to determine the size and thickness of the
left region of their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found higher levels of blood fat and
triglycerides and lower HDL cholesterol in the apple-shaped
children. Systolic blood pressure (the upper number) was also
highest in the apple-shaped children and those with high overall
body fat. In addition, the size of the left side of the heart was
larger for children with chubby stomachs. This region tends to
thicken when high blood pressure makes the heart work harder to
pump blood, the researchers explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where fat is distributed appears to be a more important
influence on cardiovascular risk factors in young people than total
fatness,'' said Dr. Stephen Daniels, the lead author of the
Circulation study.
</P>
<P>
   _ LINDA VILLAROSA
</P>
<P>
   Difficult Journeys, Happy Endings
</P>
<P>
   A California study of the rapidly growing number of women having
children after the age of 40 showed that, like their younger
counterparts, almost all of the women had healthy babies. But
things were a lot more complicated along the way, especially for
first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   Not that long ago, every woman who became pregnant later than
her 35th birthday was considered high risk, and women were often
counseled against pregnancy as their 40s approached, said Dr.
William Gilbert, chief author of the study, which was published
last month in the journal Obstetrics and Gynecology. But
contraception and careers have changed the traditional timetable,
and more and more women are beginning to have babies at ages long
after their mothers had given away the cribs.
</P>
<P>
   The study, the largest of its kind, looked at all 1.1 million
childbirths recorded in California in 1992 and 1993. Of those,
24,032 involved women older than 40, including 4,777 giving birth
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   That represented a doubling of the percentage recorded a decade
before, said Gilbert, who is the chief of the maternal-fetal
medical division at the University of California Davis Medical
Center in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first-timers who had the highest levels of
complications during pregnancy and delivery. Rates of high blood
pressure and diabetes during pregnancy were more than double those
found in first-time mothers in their 20s.
</P>
<P>
   And more than 60 percent of the older new mothers required
surgical intervention during delivery, including Caesarean sections
for 47 percent, twice the rate of their younger counterparts, the
study found. Women over 40 who had already had children had lower
levels of complications, but still had Caesareans at twice the rate
of younger women who were already mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the study's other findings were more promising.
The researchers noted, for example, that there was no statistically
significant difference in infant mortality between younger and
older mothers.
</P>
<P>
   But motherhood over 40 is not easy, Gilbert concluded. Older
women have a harder time conceiving and have more miscarriages.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you really want to do it,'' Gilbert said, the
California study ``shouldn't stop you. It should prepare you for
what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN O'NEIL
</P>
</TEXT>
