<HEADLINE>
HEARING OVER THE JET ENGINES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to figure out what the actors are saying in an in-flight
movie can be exhausting. But a remedy is now widely available:
noise cancellation headsets.
</P>
<P>
   These devices generate sound waves that cancel out or reduce the
rumble of the jet engines, which, researchers say, agitates the
brain and makes passengers feel tired.
</P>
<P>
   The filtered, higher-pitched sounds that remain _ music, for
example, or the voice of the person sitting next to you _ are
bright and clear. Since the 1950s, military and private pilots have
been wearing the headsets to protect their ears and to better hear
radio transmissions. In 1992, they were introduced to the public on
Japan Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent flight, sitting in the back of a Boeing 727, I
compared the most widely available headsets. All the tested
headsets have adapters; instead of using the devices airlines
provide, passengers can plug in their own headsets to listen to
in-flight movies and music (in coach class, you usually still have
to pay to see the movie). Except for a Sony model that fits in the
ear, all were comfortable enough for hours of listening.
</P>
<P>
   The Noisebuster ($69, NCT Group Inc., Stamford, Conn.), was most
effective in silencing the plane's jet engines. The system, which
runs on a pair of AAA batteries, uses lightweight plastic
headphones and a tiny, nearly weightless plastic box to generate
the noise canceling sound waves. For information:
www.nct-active.com or (800) 278-3526.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines is installing the company's systems in the
first- and business-class seats on its international routes. And
Maxell will soon begin marketing the headsets under its name.
</P>
<P>
   Brookstone's Wireless Noise Reduction System ($79) was almost as
good. Its black-and-gray headsets are bigger because the
noise-canceling generators are in the over-the-ear pieces. It is
easy to leave the set on accidentally, so users might want to carry
extra AAA batteries. Information: www.brookstone.com or (800)
351-7222, or at Brookstone stores.
</P>
<P>
   Sony makes an in-the-ear model and two black plastic headsets.
The ear model (estimated selling price: $179.99) is lightweight,
but it may be uncomfortable for some people. Sony makes the most
expensive headsets (also $179.99); not tested was a $89.99 model.
Information: www.sony.com/electronics (under ``accessories'') or
(800) 222-7669.
</P>
<P>
   The high price of the Sony headsets, however, buys the least
noise reduction. Sony specifications say they lower noise by 10
decibels, compared with up to 15 for the Noisebuster and 16 for the
Brookstone. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
