<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7519 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-ELVIS-HNS     02-01 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-ELVIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KING IS BACK IN FINAL VOLUME OF BIOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients0  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 C.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elvis Presley was heading toward Hollywood, driving his van
somewhere outside Flagstaff, Ariz., with his hairdresser-guru Larry
Geller riding shotgun and the knuckle-grumbling crowd from
Graceland sitting in back, when he saw the face of Joseph Stalin in
the clouds above and watched it turn, by long billows, into the
face of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Presley pulled the van over to the side of the road and grabbed
Geller for a run through the tilted desert, yelling, ``I thought to
myself, why Stalin?'' When the cloud image changed to Jesus,
Presley told Geller, ``He smiled at me and every fiber of my being
felt it. For the first time in my life God and Christ are a living
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Geller remembered Presley saying ``Oh, God, Oh, God,'' over and
over, ``then he paused and added a peculiar aside _ `Can you
imagine what the fans would think if they saw me like this?'''
</P>
<P>
   That's as good a story as any to introduce Peter Guralnick's
``Careless Love: The Unmaking of Elvis Presley,'' a 766-page tome
tracking Presley's life from the time he got out of the Army in
1960 until his death in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The Stalin-Jesus sighting would've come in March of 1965, when
Presley was 30 years old, caught between his search for some kind
of truth through books like ``The Impersonal Life'' and
``Autobiography of a Yogi'' and making sure ``Girl Happy'' made
good money so his next Hollywood whirl would be guaranteed at half
a million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the incident of the Stalin cloud at a recent
bookstore reading, Guralnick said, ``Elvis needed that vision. It
was important to him, especially, to see Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   It was important, but not enough to change Presley's life
around. Soon after the Jesus sighting he was rolling the boat in
movable bedrooms with star-lusting women, continuing to turn out
one bad movie after another. Further down the line came his heavy
drug use, the surreal episode of Gog-meets-Randyman in the Oval
Office, and the birth of Lisa Marie, who has just turned 31 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know what to make of Elvis Presley in the spring of
1968, when he wouldn't sleep with his wife, Priscilla, because
she'd had a child, compromising her purity. It's also hard to know
what Presley would've made of Lisa Marie as a grown-up, of the
tabloids feeding off her life and her bodkin marriage to Michael
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably would've come down to what he thought of Michael
Jackson,'' said Guralnick, pointing out that Presley judged people
by what he could see, by how they treated those around them,
usually giving them the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He memorized Gen. Douglas MacArthur's farewell speech, and
Martin Luther King's `I Have a Dream' speech,'' said Guralnick.
``His politics were pretty much like Merle Haggard's _ all over the
place. You could read what you wanted into him, and for my own
purposes, I guess, I kind of saw him as a Stevensonian Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of an all-across-the-country acceptance of Presley and
a Hollywood-Vegas feel to his post-Army career, the bulk of
Presley's story belongs to the South, said Guralnick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have happened anywhere else but the South,'' he
said. ``In no other part of the country did they have the closeness
of the black and white cultures the way it was in the South. They
had segregation, yes, but the music _ sitting on porches at night,
whites listening to black music _ it was like nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a truly democratic vision. If you kept your ears open,
you couldn't miss it, and Elvis kept his ears open.''
</P>
<P>
   Presley took that democratic vision from Tupelo to Memphis to
Hollywood, a journey that produced Guralnick's first volume _
``Last Train to Memphis,'' a 560-page reliving of Presley's rise
that, together with ``Careless Love,'' puts Guralnick's two-part
biography within 200 pages of ``War and Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a length when I started out. I didn't have any
set number of pages,'' said Guralnick, 55, a native of Boston and
veteran music reporter who has also written ``Feels Like Going
Home: Portraits in Blues and Rock 'n' Roll'' and ``Searching for
Robert Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Guralnick's refusal to take sides in the saga of Elvis _
his inability to find real fault with traditional villains such as
Col. Parker, Dr. George Nichopoulos and the Memphis Mafia _ that
has brought critical praise for ``Careless Love.''
</P>
<P>
   People want to be able to blame someone for Presley's
drug-taking, even though their own friends and family may have
taken drugs for years, said Guralnick. ``If there is no clear path
in our own lives, why should there be a clear path in history?'' he
asked. ``It's not up to me to judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Presley's '73 Demerol breakdown there were signs he
was teetering on the edge _ not the least of which was a grotesque
visit to the White House at Christmastime of 1970 to beg President
Nixon for a federal narcotic agent's badge, a spur-of-the-moment
look into Presley's own heart of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   After handing a note to a White House guard, Presley was invited
into the Oval Office, carrying a silver-plated Colt. 45 for the
president, signed glossies of Priscilla and Lisa Marie, and his
growing collection of police badges. The Secret Service took the
.45 for safekeeping and Nixon welcomed Presley into his office,
where the singer showed off his cufflinks and Vegas belt and sat
down to talk about the evils of drugs in American society.
</P>
<P>
   Presley got the OK for his badge, then told Nixon, ``Mr.
President, would you have a little time just to say hello to my two
friends, Sonny West and Jerry Schilling?''
</P>
<P>
   As Nixon shook hands and handed out presidential cufflinks,
Presley played the role of the raw American to the hilt, saying,
``You know, they've got wives, too,'' and together with Nixon
rummaged through a desk for suitable gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Since then pictures from the episode _ Nixon in gray, shaking
hands with Presley in blue velour, both grinning oddly at each
other _ have become postcards popular with everyone with a taste
for the bizarre, Democrat and Republican, teetotaller and druggie
alike.
</P>
<P>
   Guralnick said, ``I've come to see it as two lonely people
finding a common thread in each other. ... Both looked at the film
`Patton' over and over, both thought communism was a real threat,
both shared a kind of a wish for privacy that was beyond their
reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the common thread could just have been loneliness,
pure and simple _ the same kind of loneliness that created the
singular world around Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, said Guralnick, he was hoping he wouldn't have to
write of Presley's death, even though he knew it was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when I watch `Chinatown,' my knowledge of that
ending is suspended to give me more pleasure in watching the movie,
and I used that same suspension of disbelief with the book. ...
Like, `Gee, maybe it won't turn out the way we think it will.'''
</P>
<P>
   Guralnick shook his head, saying, ``What he did is just put his
voice out there. It comes through in the Sun Sessions, in the '69
medleys, in his gospel sides. He transcended things, really.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
