A7531 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX     02-01 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOUCHERS NOT THE BEST ANSWER FOR EDUCATION PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been increasingly fashionable in recent years, in Texas and
elsewhere, to verbally bash public schools _ particularly big urban
districts that have large numbers of students achieving at low
academic levels.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a proposed cure for what ails public schools, there is
growing momentum for government-funded school voucher programs _
essentially, a movement to allocate tax dollars to send students to
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   There are several proposed bills in the Texas Legislature to
fund experimental voucher programs whereby students from
poor-performing public schools in select urban districts could
receive vouchers to finance their education at other public or
private schools of their choosing. Tony Garrett, chief of staff to
state Rep. Domingo Garcia, D-Dallas, forecasts that vouchers could
become the ``No. 1 emotional and headline-grabbing issue'' in
Austin, the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   The push for vouchers clearly has gained political momentum. But
no matter how hard I try, I just can't get comfortable with the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   I know that many thousands of students in Texas public schools
have failed to get a good education. I know that, as a parent, I
would be quite frustrated _ probably to the point of tears _ if I
had a child performing poorly in a public school of weak academic
standing.
</P>
<P>
   But vouchers aren't the panacea. If we've got problems with our
public schools, let's focus on fixing them instead of quitting on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some obvious measures:
</P>
<P>
   _Let's raise pay for Texas public school teachers to at least
the national average (it now ranks 38th among the 50 states in
teacher pay).
</P>
<P>
   _Let's keep insisting, as has Gov. George W. Bush, on much more
accountability from public school students and educators. In recent
years, we've escalated accountability in numerous ways, from having
students take the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills tests to
rating schools' academic standing from exemplary to low-performing.
Now Bush is pushing for a major reduction in ``social promotion''
of students (the practice of advancing students to the next grade
even if they bomb academically). I'm all for the guv on that one.
</P>
<P>
   Because we are insisting on more accountability, Texas public
school students have ranked near the top nationally in the 1990s in
terms of the degree of improvement in academic performance. And the
number of schools rated ``low-performing'' has plunged.
</P>
<P>
   _Let's keep employing flexible, common-sense measures to target
specific problems. For example, many school districts are granting
sizable bonuses to teachers who gain certification in math, science
or bilingual education _ areas in which the teacher shortage has
been most critical.
</P>
<P>
   _Let's make sure we have adequate school facilities _ not fancy,
but adequate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Let's take note of the fact that many public school students
are getting an excellent education. And it's not just public school
teachers and administrators who might be at fault when a student
fails. Many parents show virtually zero interest in their
children's education. Many students show little self-motivation and
might fail just as miserably in a private school.
</P>
<P>
   Now, back to vouchers, or the routing of public money to private
schools. A majority of private schools have a religious
orientation. Whatever happened to the cherished American principle
of separation of church and state?
</P>
<P>
   Public money should go to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The private schools should take care of the private schools.
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Z. Smith is a columist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. He can be reached at (817) 390-7724, or
e-mail: jzsmith(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
