<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7540 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-ABDULLAH-0202-     02-01 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-ABDULLAH-0202-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW HEIR TO JORDANIAN THRONE MAY HAVE HUSSEIN'S FLARE FOR DRAMA
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 500 words.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ No one expected him to ever be heir to the
throne when Jordan's Crown Prince Abdullah got married in 1993. But
he did give his guests something to remember: An army buddy
parachuted into the palace garden and cut the wedding cake with a
sword.
</P>
<P>
   This week, amid congratulatory visits by international
dignitaries as varied as U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
to the son of Libyan leader Moammar Khaddafi, the 37-year-old
prince had clearly not come down to earth himself.
</P>
<P>
   The visits are a sign that Jordan is a key to maintaining peace
in the region. And, while the little country is not named after the
recently-retired American basketball star, there's a lot of
commotion around the new ``Heir Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, people who like him claim that they know him well,
yet not much at all. They cite his long record of army service and
dedication to his country, but they say they don't know what he
thinks about Iraq, or Israel, or democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Educated mostly in the United States and England, he speaks
excellent English. He also speaks street Arabic. But his classic
Arabic, a difficult form used in writing and for official speeches,
is noticeably weak.
</P>
<P>
   The big question will be how much time he has to brush up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs time. He is open-minded. Personally, he is
acceptable,'' said former Jordanian Prime Minister Ahmad Obeidat.
But, he did not hazard to guess what kind of policies he would
have: ``He has no precedents.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah's father Hussein is the king, but he has cancer and
last week he shocked his little desert kingdom by moving aside the
brother who had been heir for 33 years. He appointed Abdullah in
his place.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah was sworn into the new job of crown prince at the
airport, as Hussein, propped on a cane, headed back to the United
States for another series of radiation treatments.
</P>
<P>
   There was palace politics behind the move. Hussein wrote in a
letter to the former Crown Prince Hassan that ``parasites'' were
sewing discord among family members. Also, the King had long been
thought to favor Abdullah's little half-brother for the job, but he
is only 18 and too young to be next in line behind such a sick
king.
</P>
<P>
   But, there as a traditional logic in the choice of Abdullah. The
first son is supposed to inherit the throne. In a male-dominated
culture, Arab men are referred to by the names of their first sons.
Hussein is Abu Abdullah -- father of Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   In an October interview with an Arabic London daily, Abdullah
said he loves it when his people call his father that.
</P>
<P>
   Both me love racing cars and flying airplanes. They attended the
Royal Academy at Sandhurst, a military school in England. Abdullah
is a general in the Jordanian army, a paratrooper and head of a
special forces unit. They are both known for their charm and touch
with the common man.
</P>
<P>
   In classes at Georgetown University, Abdullah studied under an
Israeli professor, long before his country made peace with Israel.
Newspapers in Israel reported last week that he was an excellent
student.
</P>
<P>
   But, he also had a playboy image in his youth -- as did Hussein,
who has married four times.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah was married that day in 1993, to Princess Rania, a
Palestinian. More than half the Jordanian population is
Palestinian. The prospect that she could be queen set off an odd
round of gossip in a country always heavily influenced by
outsiders. Hussein's wife was born in the United States. The
displaced Hassan is married to a Pakistani and people debated
whether a Palestinian queen would be preferable.
</P>
<P>
   In a picture published of the prince's family, Rania wore blue
jeans and he had snakeskin boots. With them were their children,
2-year-old Princess Iman and the first born son, 6-year-old Prince
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   While the elder Hussein ails in Minnesota, he consults with
Abdullah, who is in charge back home. He faces a host of problems,
with the Jordanian economy in shambles, a peace treaty with Israel
that is highly unpopular with the Jordanian people, and the United
States pounding Jordan's neighbor and former ally, Iraq, with air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   As Abdullah waited last Thursday for Secretary of State Albright
to drive away after their brief meeting, he paced nervously at the
top of the palace steps. The short, stocky prince, occasionally
paused in a military stance, feet together, hands behind his back.
But, he wore a blue business suit and a broad smile.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
