<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-VICTORIA-MUSE     02-01 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-VICTORIA-MUSEUM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONDON MUSEUM'S `GOOD OMEN' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Md., Texas, Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Victoria and Albert Museum has not been a happy
house in recent years. It was thrown into disarray in 1988 when
eight senior curators were dismissed overnight as part of a
management shake-up. It was deluged with bad publicity when it
introduced admission charges in 1996. And more recently it has been
under attack from traditionalists for backing an adventurous scheme
to add an ultramodern extension to its late 19th-century red brick
building.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's troubles did not end there. After some National
Lottery profits were assigned to arts projects in the mid-1990s,
the Tate Gallery, the British Museum and the Royal Opera House
quickly won financing for expensive expansions and renovations.
When it was the Victoria and Albert's turn to seek funds, it was
turned down, not only for its avant-garde extension but initially
also for renovation of its British Galleries. Understandably, it
began to seem like the Cinderella of South Kensington.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, the V&AMP;A, as it is widely known, finally got a
break: The Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea unexpectedly
authorized construction of the proposed extension, known as the
Spiral, that had provoked such a storm of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In one daring decision, approved by eight votes to four and
overruling a recommended rejection by planning officers, the
council gave a huge boost for modern architecture in London and a
much-needed vote of confidence for the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a good omen,'' said Alan Borg, who became the
museum's director in the fall of 1995 after running the Imperial
War Museum. ``We benefited from the feeling that it was time
Britain did something in architecture. But it was also recognition
that we are a dynamic museum, with lots of things that other
museums don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   On that, there is no debate. The V&AMP;A has the world's largest
collection of applied and decorative arts, spanning 2,000 years and
embracing ceramics, metalwork, jewelry, furniture and textiles.
</P>
<P>
   Its 4 million art objects, of which only 20 percent can be shown
in its 12 acres and seven miles of galleries, also include
sculptures, paintings (among them, the priceless Raphael tapestry
Cartoons), drawings, prints and photographs. And as home to the
National Art Library, it is a respected research center and
publisher of art books.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in an era when museums compete more with blockbusters than
with scholarship, the V&AMP;A is bound to struggle for media attention.
It regularly puts on original shows of design through the ages, but
these cannot compete in glamour _ or attendance numbers _ with,
say, the recent Cezanne and the coming Jackson Pollock
retrospectives at the Tate Gallery or the current crowd-pleaser,
``Monet in the 20th Century,'' at the Royal Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to refocus the public perception by showing that this
museum is part of the contemporary world,'' said Borg, a
57-year-old art historian, in a recent interview. ``And we aim to
do this more visibly and with a higher profile.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the museum began to do so with ``Cutting Edge,'' a
1997 show of avant-garde fashion that drew 230,000 visitors. The
museum will also present ``Design and the Digital Age'' this summer
and ``brand.new,'' a show about branding new products, next year.
Its main event in 2000 will be ``Art Nouveau 1890-1914,'' a major
exhibition on art and design that will travel to the National
Gallery of Art in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, of course, will identify the V&AMP;A more with the 21st
century than construction of the Spiral, the ``tumbling boxes''
extension designed by the American architect Daniel Libeskind (who
has just completed the new Jewish Museum in Berlin). But there is a
catch: If the V&AMP;A is to have any hope of raising the $110 million
needed to build the Spiral from lottery grants and private
contributions, it must first polish its image.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, it began this ``profile-building,'' as Borg puts
it, in North America in 1997 with an ambitious exhibition, ``Grand
Design: The Art of the Victoria and Albert Museum,'' organized and
presented first by the Baltimore Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The show has traveled to Boston, Toronto and Houston, and it
will be seen at the Fine Arts Museums in San Francisco from Feb. 13
through May 9. Its final stop will be the V&AMP;A itself, for a
three-month display starting on Oct. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond presenting a selection of prized objects in a way that
illustrates the museum's unusual history, ``Grand Design'' also
seeks to remind visitors that in the 19th century the V&AMP;A served as
a role model for many American museums, including those of
Baltimore, Boston, and Brooklyn, N.Y. ``The idea was to use the
museum as an overtly educational instrument, to teach art and
design, to be useful, to do something for the public,'' Borg said.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, in creating the Museum of Manufactures in 1852, just
after the Great Exhibition of 1851, the government saw it
principally as a way of raising the standards of British design in
the context of the Industrial Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Its educational role was added by its founding director, Henry
Cole, who saw the museum being ``elevated from being a mere
unintelligible lounge for idlers into an impressive schoolroom for
everyone.'' Renamed the South Kensington Museum, it opened on its
present site on the corner of Exhibition Road and Cromwell Road in
1857.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But by May 1899, when Queen Victoria gave the museum its present
name in memory of her consort, the V&AMP;A had lost its populist touch.
``It had become more of an ivory tower, an elitist center of
scholarship, a display for people who already knew what they wanted
to see,'' Borg said. Even now, while the V&AMP;A has many fervent
admirers, a good many Londoners stay away, believing erroneously
that it is a museum of Victorian art.
</P>
<P>
   In looking to the future, Borg has therefore sought inspiration
in the museum's earliest years. ``When the V&AMP;A was founded, they
did what we're thinking of doing now,'' he said. ``Our focus should
return to our original mission. It is to help and be part of the
creative industries of today. I think the museum should be trying
to lead taste, to show people what is good design from the past and
the present. We should take some risks; we can even say, `This will
be the next big thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the museum is not yet out of the woods. It carries some
of the scars of the decision by the former director, Elizabeth
Esteve-Coll, to revamp _ some would say destroy _ the curatorial
staff in 1988 in the name of breaking up what she called
``fiefdoms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reforms knocked the stuffing out of the curators,'' said
Anna Somers Cocks, the editor of The Art Newspaper, who worked as a
curator in the V&AMP;A from 1973 to 1986. ``Something had to be done,
but it was just done in the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Bindman, a curator who began working at the museum
just weeks before the shake-up, is more upbeat. In 1993, she left
the V&AMP;A and moved to New York, where she worked at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art through 1996. Now she is back in London working
freelance. ``The V&AMP;A has had a hard time recovering,'' she said,
``but I now see a more positive attitude, a noticeable improvement
from when I left, perhaps because the museum is going back to its
roots.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over admission charges, though, is not over. From
1985, visitors were asked to make voluntary contributions. When
Borg broke ranks with the Tate Gallery, the British Museum and the
National Gallery by charging an entrance fee of 5 pounds, or $8, he
blamed inadequate government financial support.
</P>
<P>
   But with museums measuring success by attendance figures, he
paid a price: Visitors to the V&AMP;A fell from about 1.4 million in
1995 to just over a million in 1997, with a 5 percent recovery in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, after the British Museum came close to charging
admission, the government finally promised funds to help museums
operate without charging. But the outlook is still confused.
Although the V&AMP;A charges an entrance fee to its building, it does
not sell tickets for special exhibitions, while other ``free''
London museums earn handsomely from ticket sales to blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   Further, in the case of the V&AMP;A, it is not clear how much
compensation it will receive for ending admission charges.
</P>
<P>
   Borg clearly has plenty on his plate with managing the museum's
800-member staff and $65 million annual budget, promoting its new
contemporary image and finding the money for the $50 million
renovation and reorganization of the British Galleries. (The
Heritage Lottery Fund finally came through with a $25 million
grant, but the V&AMP;A must find the rest.) As a result, many London
art experts believe that the Spiral is too ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   In a signed editorial in The Art Newspaper last July, before the
Spiral won building permission, Ms. Somers Cocks told Borg that ``a
general has to know when to retreat tactically in order to win the
campaign.'' While approving of the design, she said the museum
should finding better ways of spending its energy and ``not delude
itself that the Libeskind building would solve the attendance
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, Ms. Somers Cocks said that the Spiral, unlike
the British Galleries, was not indispensable. ``I have nothing
against the building, but the national lottery has already given
sums of money to major projects in London, and its policy thrust
now is toward smaller projects outside London,'' she said. ``So it
will be very difficult politically to give money for this
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Borg, though, is unfazed. He said that the success of the new
Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain, had shown what modern
architecture can do for a city. He also noted that according to
polls commissioned by the V&AMP;A, public attitudes toward the Spiral
in London had gone from largely hostile to slightly favorable. The
building is also known to enjoy the approval of some members of
Prime Minister Tony Blair's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as changing opinion resulted in planning permission,
we're not unhopeful that opinion will also swing the lottery
institutions,'' Borg said. ``The next 12 months are important
because we have momentum, we have support. Once we have the money,
it will take four years to build.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with lottery grants, though, he will still need private
donations. ``My initial aim with such a striking building is to
find someone to put their name on it, like Tate,'' he said. ``We
will happily do that _ for the right sum. In fact, I already have a
list of the 200 wealthiest people on earth, although there are some
constraints. Some of the people are perhaps not appropriate.'' He
smiled thinly and added, ``For example, I wouldn't want Saddam
Hussein's name on the building.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
