<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING USED TO GRANDEUR IN A QUIET VILLAGE OUTSIDE CARMEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 7.) 
 (ms) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stretch of Route 1 that runs through Carmel, Calif., does
not inspire. A generation ago, the highway was the place where the
romance of the open road met the wild beauty of California's
central coast, but now the cars form an unbroken chain, and the
beleaguered motorist who turns east onto Carmel Valley Road runs
right into a big, fat shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Press on, however, and the hubbub fades away. As the road climbs
into the Santa Lucia Range, it makes its way through Carmel Valley
Village and passes the little wineries that make up the Carmel
Valley appellation, California's tiniest. The looming, arid hills
begin to assert their power, and the Carmel River's silver thread
can be glimpsed far below, following the road. About 13 miles into
the hills, a very discreet turnoff leads to an iron gate that
guards the road to Stonepine.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers with a reservation, the mild anxiety of waiting
for the automatic gate to swing open is the last unpleasant moment
they will experience until, on leaving, they see the gate from the
other side. Like one of those plastic guns that attack static
cling, Stonepine, a resort and equestrian center that belongs to
the Relais and Chateau group, instantly eliminates stress, worry,
and feelings of low self-esteem simply by allowing its guests to
live, if only for a day or two, the life of the very, very rich.
</P>
<P>
   The estate is large. Together with the equestrian center,
formerly a thoroughbred training and breeding operation known as
the Double H Ranch, it covers more than 300 acres. At its center
stands Chateau Noel, a vaguely French-Italian villa with pinkish
walls and red tile roof that was built in the 1920s as a wedding
present for Henry Potter Russell and Helen Crocker, a member of the
Crocker banking dynasty. Since 1983, when the estate was purchased
and turned into a resort, their gracious style of living has been
available to the traveler with an urge to splurge.
</P>
<P>
   Stonepine is not priced for the faint of heart. The eight suites
in Chateau Noel range from $375 to $750 a night, and the three
private cottages on the grounds run from $750 to $2,500. The price
includes breakfast. It does not include a 10.5 percent hotel tax
and a 10 percent service charge.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to think of the steep tariff and the service charges
(18 percent is added to the dinner bill) as the price of admission
to a better way of life. Once inside the gate, you are rich. Your
house, reached by a narrow, winding half-mile road, is spacious and
elegant, surrounded by gardens, a waterfall, a small golf course, a
swimming pool and tennis courts. The fine gravel in the driveway
has the quiet, tasteful crunch that says money. You are cosseted by
staff members whose only desire is to please, and the no-tipping
policy removes any hint that money might be a motivating factor.
</P>
<P>
   On arriving at Stonepine, my wife, Nancy, and I found the place
in crisis mode. The first fall rains, sudden and violent, had
knocked out electricity to the area, and as we settled in, the
outlines of our room were blurring with the fading light. As
scurrying hotel employees placed small votive candles on the main
stairway and along the hallway outside our room, lending a magic
touch to the surroundings, the manager sent his minions into town
to stock up on flashlights. ``Make sure you pour plenty of wine
tonight,'' I heard him whisper to a waiter.
</P>
<P>
   All rooms at Stonepine have a theme. The $400 Wedgwood Suite,
for example, has a soft-blue color scheme, and a chaise longue. The
intriguing-sounding Don Quixote, reached through concealed doors in
the first-floor library, comes with a separate sitting room, two
bathrooms and direct access to a secluded garden patio. (Porcelain
figurines of Don Quixote and Sancho Panza take care of the theme.)
At $500 a night, we had taken the Chanel Suite, an expansive
chamber decorated in gray. The gray satin covers on the two double
beds and the heavy gray curtains gave off a pearlescent glow. The
floral-patterned wallpaper was a muted beige-and-gray. Very
soothing.
</P>
<P>
   Off in one corner, a round table continued the theme. It
supported a coffee-table book with the title ``Les Bijoux de
Chanel'' and two framed photographs of Coco herself, along with a
plate filled with fruit and cheese, and a half-bottle of wine
labeled Chateau Noel.
</P>
<P>
   The wine, a 1993 cabernet made for the resort by nearby Durney
Vineyards, was very attractive, but the pear was tough, the
strawberries tasteless, and the crackers stale. The decor was hit
and miss too. A less than stunning Monet reproduction hung on one
wall, a feeble print in the manner of Toulouse-Lautrec over the
fireplace. When the electricity came back on a few hours after our
arrival, the bathroom chandelier cast its sparkling light on a
plastic wastebasket that could have come from Woolworth's.
</P>
<P>
   While they surprised us, these false notes did little to disturb
the overall effect of grand luxe. The large bathroom, equipped with
plenty of mirrors at all the right heights, included a bathtub with
Jacuzzi, a separate shower and a fancy amenities basket filled with
Crabtree &AMP; Evelyn products, all of them containing jojoba oil,
which seems to be the ingredient of the moment. A fireplace, well
stocked with dry firewood, provided both warmth and atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Through the tall French windows, we looked over a lawn and
gardens bordered by colossal stone pines, evenly spaced like
sentries. Beyond the trees were wooded hills that, in the
crystalline air, seemed to lie within arm's reach. The stone pines
were fascinating. Stern and totemic, they were covered in bark that
looked like rectangular leather plates. Attached to the plates were
acorn woodpeckers, dashing fellows with black-and-white bodies and
swept-back red coifs that methodically drilled round holes, each of
which they then stuffed with a nut, turning each tree into a
savings bank. The jackhammer pounding of the red-headed woodpecker
was not for them. These birds did quality work, tapping lightly and
intermittently, like a cobbler working on an expensive shoe.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1829EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
