<HEADER>
A7577 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-$ADV07-1     02-01 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-$ADV07-1STADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 
UNDATED: expensive shoe.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less welcome was the plaintive yowl of a small cat with
puffed-out black fur and lamplike yellow eyes that had become
stranded on the roof. The concierge, risking life and limb, stepped
out on the tiles in an effort to bag the beast, which simply shrank
a little further into the rooftop vegetation. We ended up trying to
buy silence by placing tidbits of food on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Guests in search of nothing more than solitude and fresh air can
find both at Stonepine. They can loaf in the nooks and crannies of
the hotel (the colonnaded walkway overlooking the back lawn is
prime territory), enjoy the gardens, or, with the resort's color
map in hand, wander the hiking trails that wind along the
surrounding hills and ridges, so fragrant with wildflowers that a
puff of wind unleashes a honey-scented wave. A quick browse through
the guest book can be entertaining too. Bill Gates has breezed
through the week before we stayed (``Thanks!'' was written in an
extrovert's bold hand), and so has Warren Buffett. One's peers, in
other words.
</P>
<P>
   Energetic guests, especially horse enthusiasts, can take
advantage of the equestrian center. The old Double H Ranch, created
in the 1930s, was California's first center for breeding and
training thoroughbreds. Among its graduates were Majestic Prince,
winner of the 1969 Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes. There's
still a little three-furlong race track for workouts, and spacious
riding rings where for $35 an hour three trainers give lessons in
trail riding, English saddle, Western saddle, jumping, and carriage
driving and sulky driving. The resident horses appreciate a scratch
behind the ears. One pair, honey-colored twins with long blond
bangs, brought a touch of glamour to the stock, like equine Gabor
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the horses are available for trail riding, and we were
both keen to take a riding lesson and perhaps head out on the
trail. Alas, the cowgirls at the equestrian center told us, the
rains had made the paths too slippery, creating a ``potential
liability situation.'' Was this how the West was won?
</P>
<P>
   It was too cold to swim, and neither of us plays tennis. Croquet
was an option, but in the end we reached for a quiver of arrows and
a couple of bows and headed for the archery range. Movie fans may
recall the climactic moment when Robin Hood, seemingly defeated
when his rival hits the bull's-eye, releases a shot that splits the
offending arrow in two. It's harder than it looks.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, guests assemble in the drawing room for
champagne and canapes, prelude to the evening meal, which is served
on two long tables in the dining room. On the night we had dinner,
the diners at table No. 1 quickly became a well-disciplined unit
bent on high-volume hilarity. Table No. 2 accommodated a Swedish
couple at one end, and, many yards out of speaking range, Nancy and
me at the other. It was a quiet meal.
</P>
<P>
   By New York restaurant standards, the cooking was good but not
exceptional. The $65 fixed-price dinner began with an innocuous
vegetable consomme, then picked up momentum with a salad of mixed
greens, walnuts and apples, dressed with a champagne vinaigrette.
The pan-seared tenderloin, served with rosti potatoes, was
fork-tender and succulent, the duck breast in port wine sauce
richly satisfying. The third choice, sauteed sea scallops with a
lemon cream sauce, had been exhausted by the roisterers at Table 1.
Dessert was a fine lemon souffle with raspberry sauce, followed by
cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   The wine list, heavy on California wines, especially local
producers like Durney, Jekel and Chalone, was modestly priced, with
most bottles falling in the $35 to $65 range.
</P>
<P>
   The choicest duck scraps went straight to the roof. Even for a
stray cat, it's only the best at Stonepine.
</P>
<P>
   Stonepine is at 150 East Carmel Valley Rd., Carmel Valley,
Calif. 93924; (831) 659-2245, fax (831) 659-5160. Prices for suites
and cottages range from $375 to $2,500 a day, breakfast included.
</P>
</TEXT>
