<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Tuesday, Feb. 2. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments in the Senate's impeachment
trial of the President: Monica Lewinsky is deposed today, the first
of three witnesses sought by the House managers. By Alison Mitchell
and Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BLAIR (London) _ Twenty months after Tony Blair led
Britain's ``new'' Labor party to power, there are two images of
him: the first is that he is youthful, articulate, and a visionary,
a leader of a nation in dramatic transition. The other is that he
is all style and fluff, with little substance. A look at what is
actually inside the enticingly wrapped package he is offering
Britain for its future. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-CLINTON (Washington) _ The president's new budget is
presented. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-NEWBORNS (Chicago) _ Researchers at an annual AIDS
meeting report results from a study in Africa showing that a
simple, short drug regimen produces striking reductions in
transmission rates of the AIDS virus from mothers to newborns. The
regimen involves giving relatively inexpensive drugs to the women
from several weeks before delivery, during labor and a week after.
Worldwide, 600,000 babies a year are born with HIV. By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-RECRUITING (Aboard the USS HARRY S. TRUMAN) _ The Navy
spent $4.5 billion to build this, the nation's newest carrier. It
has two nuclear reactors, the latest electronic, computer and
navigational equipment and, for the long ``cruises'' to come,
amenities for the crew, like televisions in almost every berth.
What the Navy cannot put aboard the Truman is a full crew. The
ship, commissioned by Clinton last July to join the nation's other
carriers, is not alone. Two weeks ago, the Navy disclosed that it
has had as many as 22,000 empty positions, or billets, in a force
of 372,000. The vast majority of those were aboard the Navy's 327
ships, rather than on shore. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-TIME (New York) _ AT&AMP;T and Time Warner, as expected, form a
joint venture to offer local telephone service and other
communication services in 33 states. The companies will provide
AT&AMP;T-branded cable-telephone service to residential and
small-business customers over Time Warner's cable television
systems. They expect to begin service in one or two cities by the
end of this year and offer broader operations in 2000. By Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STARDUST (Undated) _ For decades, science has known of the
importance of star dust in the cosmic scheme of things, especially
in matter more elaborate than the simple elements made in the
primordial Big Bang. But scientists have never had pure samples to
study _ but soon will, if everything goes as planned. On Saturday,
NASA is to launch a probe meant to capture interplanetary and
interstellar dust in some of its rawest and purest forms, including
many thousands of grains from a comet. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SOCGEN-PARIBAS (Undated) _ Societe Generale buys Paribas for 16
billion euros, or $18.2 billion, in stock, creating Europe's
second-largest bank and ushering in the long-awaited consolidation
of the French banking business. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
