<HEADLINE>
NEW POLICE CHIEF FIGHTS CRIME WITHIN HIS OWN FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico _ In the past month, Moctezuma Rodriguez
has gone from working security in Las Vegas to riding herd over a
border city police force plagued by corruption, scandal and the
arrest of 12 officers for attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over as Nuevo Laredo police chief Jan. 1, Rodriguez
has fired more than 120 officers _ roughly 25 percent of the force
_ and all six of his commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible we've arrived at this point; we can't even
believe it,'' Rodriguez, 49, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to regain the respect of the city,'' the Nuevo
Laredo native continued. ``People are fed up with what has been
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, officers not only have been able to shake down
people for bribes, but have been bought or intimidated by rival
drug cartels competing to ship marijuana or cocaine across the Rio
Grande and into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, 12 officers were arrested and charged with
attempted murder for attacking a police officer from another city.
The officer was critically wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be narcotics trafficking,'' Rodriguez said. ``What
else could it be?''
</P>
<P>
   In October, two officers were kidnapped and haven't been seen
since.
</P>
<P>
   In December, two others, including the son of an ex-commander,
were killed when AK-47 fire shredded their Volkswagen beetle patrol
car. Each officer was hit more than a dozen times, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To kidnap police, to murder police, this shows what is going
on,'' Rodriguez said. ``There has been no respect for the law or
fear of the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe this city of about 400,000 people is caught in
a battle between the Arrellano Felix cartel, based in Tijuana, and
the cartel of the late Amado Carrillo Fuentes, which is based in
Ciudad Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   From his first day on the job, Rodriguez has made his terms
known to the police: Be professional and enforce the law, or be
fired or jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Before being hired in Nuevo Laredo, he was part of the security
detail at the Binon's Horseshoe Hotel and Casino, one of downtown
Las Vegas' most-storied clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in Nuevo Laredo vow to reform the city's corrupt image.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to change everything,'' Councilman Eliseo Huerta
said. ``The principal issue here is public security.''
</P>
<P>
   Council members also are considering ways to provide more money
for a police force that is so poor, some officers don't have guns.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hopes to rebuild the force with a fresh batch of
recruits scheduled to enter the police academy this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for people who want to serve for the right
reasons: To enforce the law and serve Nuevo Laredo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the city's new mayor, Horacio Garza, who took office the
same day as Rodriguez, is appealing to the federal government to
send more drug-enforcement agents to combat the cartels and help
keep the streets safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we live in fear we will never advance,'' Garza told a news
conference last week. ``I'm tranquil. Justice is on our side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
