<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEDBUD-SURPLUS02-COX     02-01 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDBUD-SURPLUS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOCIAL SECURITY SURPLUS TAPPED FOR SPENDING INCREASES
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's five-year budget released
Monday would use extra Social Security Trust funds to help finance
his plans for new domestic programs and increased military
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Despite expectations of huge surpluses down the road, the
government's operating budget next year is expected to continue to
run at a slight deficit of $12 billion, which would be borrowed
from the overpayment into the Social Security fund.
</P>
<P>
   During the full five-year period, the budget calls for using
$145 billion from the retirement fund surpluses to help pay for
increased spending in child-care subsidies, health care, education
and defense, said Carol Wait, president of the fiscal watchdog
group Committee for a Responsible Budget.
</P>
<P>
   Wait was among budget experts raising doubts about the rosy
fiscal picture painted by the Clinton budget, which assumes soaring
surpluses for the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economic house is in order and strong,'' the president
said as he unveiled his spending and tax plan. ``If we manage the
surplus right we can uphold our responsibility to future
generations. We can do so by dedicating the lion's share of the
surplus to saving Social Security and Medicare and paying down the
national debt.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Wait said that the nation would reduce the debt much
faster without enacting the Clinton budget, or any other changes in
existing programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put the government on auto pilot, we would be buying
down the debt held by the public, because that's what the Treasury
does with surpluses,'' she said. ``He (the president) is proposing
to buy down less debt than we would under current law.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reichauer, a former congressional budget director,
credited Clinton with reserving the ``great bulk'' of Social
Security surpluses for paying down the debt. But he also added,
``If I had my druthers, I certainly would like to see the Social
Security surpluses used exclusively to pay down the national debt
and delay tax cuts or spending initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some experts are far less sanguine than the White
House budgeteers, who predicated their plans on five more years of
an economic boom that is already the longest since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``No projected surpluses are secure,'' said Bradley Schiller, an
economist at American University. ``If the economy slides into
recession, those surpluses will disappear like mist when the sun
comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you assume the surpluses are real, then there's the
question of what really should be done with them,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the president asserts that he wants to save Social
Security first, the reality is that he's significantly increasing
domestic and military spending with this budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bixby, policy analyst with the Concord Coalition, a group
that is pushing for reforming Social Security's finances, said he
foresees difficult battles ahead in persuading the president and
Congress to use surpluses for reducing the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's politically much more attractive to say we're going to
return it to the taxpayers or use it to pay for Medicare drugs or
some other program,'' Bixby said. ``It doesn't make a very good
campaign slogan. But it appeals to people like me.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
