<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWLES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowles calls affair 'grossly inappropriate,' but says Clinton
should remain in office
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ President Clinton deserves censure, not
removal from office, for trying to hide his ''grossly inappropriate
affair'' with Monica Lewinsky, former White House chief of staff
Erskine Bowles said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a sharply critical appraisal of his former boss and golfing
buddy's conduct involving Lewinsky, Bowles said Clinton's marriage
has been damaged and his presidential accomplishments, from welfare
reform to balancing the federal budget, forever tainted.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has paid an enormous price for this big mistake, and I
think people forget that,'' said Bowles, 53, who has returned to
investment banking in Charlotte after leaving the White House last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in the offices of Carousel Capital, a merchant
bank Bowles rejoined last month, he said he ''never, not once,
publicly or privately, offered the president any leeway on what he
did, nor did he want any....Nobody, including the president,
approved of what he did....It is inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   ''And then he did every single thing that he could do that was
humanly possible to keep it a secret,'' Bowles said, ''a secret
from me, from the other members of the Cabinet, from the White
House staff, from his wife, from his child and from the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, two wrongs don't make a right,'' Bowles said. ''But
I don't believe that it rises to the level that the founding
fathers had in mind when they talked about overturning the will of
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be remembered as ''someone who accomplished an
extraordinary amount in spite of going through investigation after
investigation after investigation after investigation,'' Bowles
said, referring to a string of federal inquiries culminating with
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation into Clinton's
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do I think a censure is appropriate?'' Bowles said.
''Absolutely. And I think that is the way it should have gone to
begin with...I assure you that an overwhelming majority of the
Democrats would vote for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowles added that he believes that, once the president leaves
office, ''Ken Starr has the right to prosecute him just like any
other American.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
