A7605 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-WRAP-COX     02-01 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-WRAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons leave Miami in post-Super Bowl daze
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As the Atlanta Falcons milled about the lobby of the
team hotel here Monday morning, rummaging through Super Bowl
souvenirs whose prices had been slashed, they looked out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody was moving slowly, defensive end Lester Archambeau and
fullback Brian Kozlowski each had one leg encased in removable
casts, and center Robbie Tobeck hobbled around, carrying but not
using crutches.
</P>
<P>
   They had been thumped by the Broncos 34-19 the night before in
the first Super Bowl appearance in the franchise's 33 years. It was
impossible to tell, however, if they were reeling more from the
game or the sequence of events leading up to it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some mild protestations to the contrary, the Falcons
were distracted when free safety Eugene Robinson was arrested and
charged at 9 o'clock the night before the game for soliciting oral
sex from a female undercover police officer.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (16-3) didn't do Sunday as they did in the 11-game
winning streak that preceded the Super Bowl, and it's possible to
speculate that the circus-like atmosphere before the game enveloped
them.
</P>
<P>
   Only four of 53 players had played in Super Bowls. And coach Dan
Reeves' decision to allow families to stay with players in the team
hotel might have been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Security at the hotel was slack enough that fans constantly came
and went all week. The team did not, as many do, switch to an
undisclosed, more secure hotel the night before the game, even
though the NFL made provisions for the Falcons to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, though, said he thought the week of preparation went
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our organization did a great job. It was
tremendously organized,'' he said. ``Our concentration was good. We
had the approach all year where families were allowed to stay with
the team, and we're not a team that stays in a hotel the night
before (home) games.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Changing hotels) was a possibility. (But) I did that once,
and it was a fiasco. There's all kinds of different ways to do
things. I don't think that affected us at all, staying here,
particularly when you're playing a 6 o'clock game.''
</P>
<P>
   All week, though, in addition to socializing about town,
especially early in the week, and coping with mandatory media
sessions, players signed autographs, posed for pictures, played
mediator in family discussions _ and practiced a few hours each
day.
</P>
<P>
   Things got off to a shaky start the Sunday before, when the team
arrived and wide receiver Terance Mathis complained publicly about
Pro Bowl players and 10-year veterans being allowed to leave the
plane first.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, a few players, especially Pro Bowl cornerback
Ray Buchanan and Pro Bowl left tackle Bob Whitfield, said all kinds
of strange things to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Sunday, a defense that grew more stout through the
season gave up a 457 yards and a season-high 34 points while
mounting a weak pass rush against Denver quarterback John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said all along that we're going to have some guys who get
caught up in the hype. That's the Super Bowl,'' said linebacker
Cornelius Bennett, the first player to play for a losing team in
five Super Bowls, after four with Buffalo. ``Everybody wants to
look good, do good and say good things. Sometimes, it doesn't
always work out right.''
</P>
<P>
   On offense, a unit that during the season scored on 89.1 percent
of its possessions inside its opponents' 20-yard line kept
misfiring down close.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta reached the Denver 8-, 26-, 8-, 11-, 21- and 26-yard
lines during the game and got two field goals, missed one, threw
two interceptions and turned the ball over on downs.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons led the NFL with a plus-14 turnover ratio during the
season, but lost that battle 4-1 to Denver. Chris Chandler threw
interceptions on the first three possessions of the second half,
resulting in 14 Denver points.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, you wish the guys hadn't said some of the things
they did,'' Reeves said. ``But I never have been one to (muzzle
players). Overall, I'm proud of the way our guys handled this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
