<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7608 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-BIDS-COX     02-01 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-BIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta organizers spent nearly $8 million to win games
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (i) International and (s) Sports categories.)By
Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's Olympic bid team spent $7.8 million lobbying
the International Olympic Committee in the final two years of a
whirlwind campaign to win the 1996 Centennial Olympic Games,
financial records reveal.
</P>
<P>
   Half of that amount was spent directly on travel for the Atlanta
team and the IOC, plus entertainment and gifts for IOC members and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the widening vote-buying scandal in Salt Lake and other
Olympic cities, no one has suggested the millions spent by the
Atlanta bid team circling the globe to secure votes and hosting IOC
members in high style was excessive or improper. And the amount
pales in comparison to the total spent by some of Atlanta's
competitors for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   But the bid committee's tax returns clearly illustrate the high
price to engage in bidding wars between cities seeking to land the
Olympics and reap billions in economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It's a seven-days-a-week world of first-class travel, four-star
accommodations, lavish entertainment and suitcases loaded with
personal gifts that easily overwhelms any city effort to woo
national sporting events or political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's bid campaign was run almost entirely on private
donations from philanthropies and corporations, and on
merchandising. More than $12 million was taken in during the
four-year fund-raising campaign, according to tax returns released
to the Atlanta Journal-Constitution by the nonprofit Georgia
Amateur Athletics Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The GAAF was created in 1987 to manage the bid effort. Billy
Payne, who headed the bid, was its president; then-Mayor Andrew
Young was chairman. The GAAF was the predecessor to the Atlanta
Committee for the Olympic Games, which was incorporated in 1991
after Atlanta won the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the funds was spent in the final two years
leading up to the successful September 1990 vote in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The bid group, known as the Atlanta Organizing Committee, spent
$376,545 on the four-day trip to Tokyo. It was a heady time and
there were many checks to write: Dozens of Atlanta bid volunteers
and staffers required air fare, hotel rooms and charter buses. More
than 300 Georgians accompanied the bid team to Tokyo for the IOC
session _ from most of the Atlanta City Council and then-Mayor
Maynard Jackson to the 60-member ``Dream Team'' youth group. The
AOC picked up part of their tab.
</P>
<P>
   A high-tech interactive display was in an exhibition hall, a
hospitality suite stocked with food and drink and a requisite huge
celebration party after the win. All IOC members found bedroom
slippers and embroidered pillowcases, courtesy of Atlanta, in their
hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Watkins, a key AOC member who organized these events,
remembers leasing an ``Atlanta House'' near the hotel for added
hospitality and throwing a party at a banquet hall for the several
hundred visitors from Atlanta two days before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the final nine months of the campaign, the AOC spent $3.1
million on everything from IOC member visits to Atlanta and bid
team travels around the globe to public relations and a handsome
five-volume bid book for each IOC member.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta bid team _ led by attorneys Payne, Charlie Battle
and Horace Sibley along with Young and volunteers Watkins and Linda
Stephenson _ traveled to IOC members' homelands and hosted them and
their families in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Battle, the AOC's primary international emissary, said a bid
team member visited the homes of 85 of the 87 voting members on the
IOC. In the last nine months before the vote, those visits cost
$401,694.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-eight IOC members came to Atlanta, with the bid team
typically putting them up at the Marriott Marquis, feting them in
private suburban Atlanta homes and providing a car and driver for a
tour of the venues under construction.
</P>
<P>
   The bid team spent $646,879 on these visits _ an average of
$9,513 per visitor _ during the nine-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Details of how the money was spent are not known. All documents
related to the bid _ other than the public tax returns _ are packed
in boxes at the Atlanta History Center. The GAAF refused to make
them available to the public at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Scrutiny of Salt Lake City Olympic bid documents by special
investigatory bodies has revealed as much as $1 million in cash,
medical and travel expenses and lavish gifts going to IOC members
in that city's successful campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has moved to expel six members for taking improper gifts
and payments from Salt Lake bidders, and four others have resigned.
The IOC says it is expanding an internal investigation to include
candidate cities from 1996 through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound, chairman of the IOC's investigation, said he sent
letters to two dozen bid committees of Winter and Summer Games
requesting details of any suspected misconduct by IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Yarbrough, spokesman for the Atlanta bidders, said Monday
they had not received the letter, but he was preparing a response
anyway. ``We hope to have it finished as quickly as possible very
early in the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta bid officials have steadfastly maintained they conducted
their campaign within the rules and that no IOC members abused
their position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about my part in it, what I know about it, what we
did and how we did it,'' said Battle, who is now president of
Central Atlanta Progress.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta's competitors are speaking out about excesses.
Manchester officials complained about visiting IOC members trying
to collect twice or three times for expenses for a single visit to
the candidate city in England.
</P>
<P>
   And Toronto officials said 26 of 69 IOC members who visited the
city broke IOC rules either by bringing more than one guest, coming
more than once or staying longer than allowed.
</P>
<P>
   They said the most blatant abuse by IOC members was the
misappropriation of travel expenses and airline tickets or passes
provided by Toronto officials.
</P>
<P>
   Battle said the Atlanta team will tell the IOC they did not
experience the problems of other cities. ``We have always been
interested in convincing people we did this in a very honorable
way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
