<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-JUAN-COX     02-01 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-JUAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Committee sets out to clear up misunderstandings surrounding
Samaranch
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (i) International and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Amid increasing calls for the
resignation of Juan Antonio Samaranch, the International Olympic
Committee on Monday sought to clarify the record on what it called
``inaccuracies and misrepresentations'' circulating worldwide about
its embattled president.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic scandal broke with allegations that IOC members
accepted nearly $800,000 worth of goods and services from Salt Lake
before the city was awarded the 2002 Winter Games. Details continue
to surface about improper payments made to members from other
cities bidding to host the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC, seeking to play down the notion that Samaranch, 78,
thirsts for an imperial lifestyle, said in a two-page release that
he serves as a volunteer and denied that he resides in a posh suite
at the five-star Palace Hotel. Instead, Samaranch is said to reside
in a ``small suite'' at a cost of about $211 a night, which the
hotel discounts to $70 when he travels out of town. Suites at the
Palace start at $433 a night for those walking in off the street.
</P>
<P>
   If suitors to host the Olympic Games opt to treat him like
royalty and address him as ``excellency,'' it is their doing, the
IOC said. The committee's statement said Samaranch imposes no such
demands and would prefer a more humble treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The statement makes no reference to Samaranch once having
commissioned an unsuccessful publicity campaign to win himself the
Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of the IOC spin effort are that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Samaranch requested several years ago that people stop
referring to him with the diplomatic courtesy title of
``excellency,'' which dates to his service as Spain's ambassador to
the former Soviet Union and to the People's Republic of Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   _ He served only as undersecretary of sports to Spain's former
fascist dictator Franco, not in a cabinet-level minister's
position.
</P>
<P>
   _ He does not request luxury cars, such as stretch limousines;
bid or host cities select his means of transportation. Nor does he
ask for luxury accommodations when he visits cities.
</P>
<P>
   _ While acknowledging that he accepts gifts from cities and
various officials, Samaranch said he does so on behalf of the IOC
and the gifts are either displayed in the Olympic Museum or kept in
storage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all these stories, but if someone will check they
will find 90 percent of the rumors are untrue, especially the way
they handle our president'' said IOC member Alex Gilady, a longtime
Samaranch friend and an NBC vice president. ``Really, this is a
modest man who lives in a bedroom and a half-room in the Lausanne
Palace, and people put it like it's a full-floor suite and that he
demands the presidential suite when he travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Check in Salt Lake or Atlanta, check in the files if his
office ever requested anything,'' Gilady said. ``This is for
(cities) to do what they think is right. Did you see him ride in a
limousine in Atlanta (during the Games)? No, he was traveling
around in a van, not even a sedan.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is whether Samaranch, IOC president since 1980, can
survive the widening scandal. The criticism has not subsided, even
after four members resigned and another six were targeted for
expulsion. Samaranch is not likely to be voted out, because most
IOC members were his appointees. But one of the main offenders
identified in the scandal, Jean-Claude Ganga of the Republic of
Congo, has said he plans to fight expulsion and attempt to take
Samaranch down with him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the IOC's executive board agreed Monday to set up an
ethics commission to delve into the allegations involving Salt Lake
City and most likely Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The five-person commission is expected to be in place before the
IOC's general meeting next month. The commission will include three
outsiders, described by IOC director general Francois Carrard as
''very senior, independent personalities.'' He declined to say who
is under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1852EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7610 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAVY-RECRUITING-2TAKE     02-01 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-RECRUITING-2TAKES(780)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEWEST NAVY SHIP HAS ALMOST EVERYTHING, EXCEPT ENOUGH SAILORS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By   STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD U.S.S. HARRY S. TRUMAN, off Florida _ The Navy spent $4.5
billion to build this, the nation's newest aircraft carrier. It has
two nuclear reactors, the latest electronic, computer and
navigational equipment, and, for the long ``cruises'' to come,
amenities for the crew, like televisions in almost every berth.
</P>
<P>
   What the Navy cannot put aboard the Truman is a full crew.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every department on the carrier faces a shortage of
sailors, from the engine room to the intelligence division to the
mess. The air department should have more than 600 sailors to carry
out the choreographic feat of launching and landing warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week it mustered 448.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people aren't there,'' Capt. Thomas G. Otterbein said,
sitting on the Truman's bridge as aircraft practiced takeoffs and
landings in rolling seas 100 miles out in the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The Truman, commissioned by President Clinton last July to join
the nation's 11 other aircraft carriers, is not alone. Two weeks
ago, the Navy disclosed that it has had as many as 22,000 empty
positions, or billets, in a force of 372,000. The vast majority of
those were aboard the Navy's 327 ships, rather than on shore.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's shortages have a variety of causes, not the least of
which is a thriving economy that creates more enticing
opportunities for young people than the prospect long voyages at
sea. And the Navy has responded with a variety of programs to
counter that hard reality, offering bonuses and championing
proposals now before Congress to increase pay and retirement
benefits for all military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's commanders insist that, for now at least, the
shortages have not hurt their primary mission, which is defending
the United States. But they concede that the problem is taking a
toll on ships like the Truman, where sailors and officers work
longer hours to pick up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   And that, in turn, is worsening the problems at the root of the
shortages: recruiting new sailors and keeping those who have
already joined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of feeds on itself,'' Otterbein said. ``The workload
still remains pretty high. Now you're laying it on the backs of
fewer people.''
</P>
<P>
   In Norfolk, Va., home port of the Truman and fulcrum of the
Atlantic Fleet, there are shortages on almost every warship, from
the frigates to the attack submarines. The aircraft carrier
Enterprise, whose warplanes provided much of the punch for the air
raids against Iraq in December, left port last fall nearly 400
short of a full crew of more than 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any command out there that isn't saying we're
short in one way or another,'' said Master Chief Jesse J. Elliott,
the senior noncommissioned officer for the Atlantic Fleet's
carriers and air squadrons.
</P>
<P>
   The Leyte Gulf, a guided-missile cruiser, is scheduled to deploy
to the Mediterranean Sea in March but so far has a crew of only
338. It should have 410. Its commander, Capt. Raymond P. Donahue
Jr., said he expected to fill at least some of the most important
slots before the ship steamed for six months at sea, but only at
the last minute and with junior sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of their replacements will walk up the brow a week before
they deploy,'' Donahue said, referring to the ship's gangway.
``They haven't trained with us. The continuity isn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenges with recruiting and retention have affected the
entire military, but the Navy's difficulties have become
particularly acute. The Pentagon's most recent survey on attitudes
about the military found that only 9 percent of young men between
16 and 21 were likely to consider joining the Navy, the lowest
percentage for any of the four services.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for the first time since the draft ended in 1973, the
Navy fell short of its annual recruiting goal, missing by 7,000.
Since new recruits almost always go straight to sea after boot
camp, that shortfall is now rippling through the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Navy is not retaining nearly enough
enlisted personnel, particularly those with highly technical kills.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of naval operations, Adm. Jay L. Johnson, said in an
interview that the shortage was only partly a problem of recruiting
and retention. The Navy has thousands of unassigned sailors who
could, with better management, be reassigned to fill the empty
billets, Johnson said. The answer, he said, is ``to put the right
people in the right billets at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even he conceded, however, that the Navy faces challenges far
beyond the ability of better management: a declining willingness of
young people to serve in the military and a thriving economy that
entices those who would or do serve.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer Second Class Melissa Teames, an air traffic
controller aboard the Truman, plans to leave the Navy on April 7
after five years. Only 24, she is highly trained and disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   But the Federal Aviation Administration is hiring again in the
midst of a boom in commercial travel. And, as she explained, the
FAA does not send you to sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing the same job here,'' Ms. Teames said, standing
inside the darkened control center beneath the Truman's flight
deck, ``but under more difficult conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy admits that life at sea is not for everybody _ even
aboard the big carriers. The Truman has a daily newspaper, a post
office, a barber shop, a store and even automatic teller machines.
</P>
<P>
   But as big as it is _ longer than five blocks of Manhattan and,
from the waterline to its highest point, 20 stories tall _ the
Truman is cramped and crowded. Except for the cavernous hangar bay,
its passageways are narrow.
</P>
<P>
   There is very little common space, and even less privacy.
Enlisted sailors sleep in bunks, stacked three deep, a step away
from three more. They call them ``coffin racks.'' For those who
work deep in the ship's hull, it is possible to pass days at a time
without seeing daylight.
</P>
<P>
   At a muster last week, the Truman's ``ship's crew'' totaled
2,543, more than 13 percent below a full contingent of 2,933. The
Truman does not yet have aircraft squadrons on board. Once it does,
the total crew will grow by 2,300 to 2,400.
</P>
<P>
   The Truman will not deploy overseas until next year. The ship
spent six weeks at sea late last year and has another ``cruise''
planned in March. It steamed into the Atlantic this week to allow
pilots to perform the takeoffs and landings they need to stay
proficient.
</P>
<P>
   While at sea, the shortages are felt in ways large and small.
Sailors have to work longer, usually 12-hour shifts, and spend more
days in ``duty stations,'' handling watch or otherwise being on
call. The ship's mess has half the cooks it needs, and so sailors
from other departments have to fill in.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy is scrambling, on shore and at sea, to address the
causes and effects of the personnel shortages.
</P>
<P>
   On the Truman, Otterbein has made an effort to improve the
quality of life. While the ship was under construction, he ordered
the shipbuilders to install an extra weight room to give sailors a
diversion. The ship also has more televisions than the older
carriers, showing 15 channels beamed in by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, one movie appeared especially popular: ``McHale's
Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Warrant Officer Leon A. Coles, who runs the mess, said he
held the key to keeping sailors in the Navy: better chow. The
Truman just won the Navy's award for food service, and anecdotally
at least, the sailors seconded it. ``It's going to have an impact
on whether they stay in the Navy,'' Coles said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On shore, the Navy has taken other more drastic, and
controversial, steps. It is adding 700 new recruiters to the 3,800
it had last year and sharply increased the advertising budget, to
$70 million from $45 million. But it is also going to allow in more
recruits who have failed to receive a high school diploma, despite
experience that has shown they tend to drop out of boot camp more
than high school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's commanders also hope that Clinton's proposal to raise
military salaries by as much as 9.9 percent and to improve
retirement benefits will help. Republicans in Congress have
responded by proposing even more, including raises of 10.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are also new bonuses for enlisting and bonuses for
re-enlisting. In some specialized fields, sailors can receive as
much as $30,000 to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the efforts initiated by Johnson, the chief of naval
operations, has been to cut by a quarter the number of inspections
and administrative tasks that ships face while in port, burdening
sailors with extra work during the time they should be enjoying
time off.
</P>
<P>
   A reduction in administrative work appeals to Daniel C. Appold,
a machinist mate second class on the Truman. ``You put a wrench in
my hand, and I'm happy,'' Appold said as he worked on one of the
ship's two backup diesel engines. ``Put all that paperwork in front
of me ... ,'' he started to say, then shrugged. ``I'd rather have a
wrench.''
</P>
<P>
   An 11-year veteran, he is not sure whether to stay when his
enlistment comes up next summer, though he heartily welcomed the
idea of a raise. He expressed frustration with the crew shortages,
but also seemed pleased with the Truman's efforts to improve the
amenities, especially the food, which he said far surpassed that
aboard his last ship, the carrier Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the Lincoln,'' he said, sweat on his brow, deep
inside the Truman's hull, ``this is a little slice of paradise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
