<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ADS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRACKERJACK, BUDWEISER LOBSTER SCORE DURING SUPERBOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A century from now, after the Coors Broncos have thrashed the
Coca-Cola Falcons in Super Bowl CXXXIII, anthropologists at Boeing
University will return to their study of newspaper clippings from
1999. And they will chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' they'll say. ``Look at how much was made of the
commercials during Super Bowl telecasts in those days! It seems
nobody paid attention to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the game in 2099 will command so much more attention
simply because it will be played over four days in mid-February,
kind of like a bloated Stephen King miniseries, only scarier. (A
cryogenically preserved John Madden will be defrosted once a year
to do color commentary.)
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it is right and good to celebrate the creative urge.
Especially when one of the Super Bowl teams has worse aim than the
baddies in a James Bond movie.
</P>
<P>
   Creative scorekeeping was taking place in ad agencies around the
country Sunday. It has been a popular pastime since 1984, when
Apple's classic introduction of the Macintosh computer made
marketers realize the Super Bowl can be a great launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, for example, the local office of Bozell Worldwide
was abuzz during the Super Bowl. ``We couldn't stop laughing at the
Cracker Jack ad,'' said Mary Knight, partner and creative director.
``The room was laughing so hard we couldn't hear the last half of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The spot called attention to Cracker Jack's new snack-size bags,
but also mentioned that it was testing a ``really, really big
bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the prize you might find inside a really, really big bag
of Cracker Jack. In the Super Bowl spot, a little girl finds a
pony.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to falcons, broncos and a prize pony, the Super Bowl
featured a menagerie from Anheuser-Busch, including Louie the
Lizard, who gets a tongue-lashing from the Budweiser frogs; a pair
of cute Dalmatians involved in a little one-upmanship, a mouse who
helps his owner get the girl; and a desperate lobster who escapes a
restaurant by holding a bottle of Bud hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Knight thinks this was a good year, but not a great one, for
Super Bowl ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had several favorites,'' she said, ``but nothing jumped out
on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the faves, besides the one for Cracker Jack, were the
Budweiser lobster (``great use of the product as hero''),
Monster.com (``excellent job of driving me to their Web site'') and
Apple's use of a classic computer _ HAL 9000 from ``2001: A Space
Odyssey'' _ to point out that Apple's Macs don't have a Y2K
problem. Knight said its simple execution was ``refreshing,'' and
entirely different from the big production number that made Apple
famous 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, whose agency had no clients advertising on the Super
Bowl this year, wasn't as fond of the spots for new Crispy M&AMP;M's.
(I must say I was charmed by a big orange M&AMP;M floating in a
swimming pool with Halle Berry.)
</P>
<P>
   Like Knight, I liked the ad for Monster.com, an Internet job
database. It featured stark, black-and-white images of children
saying things like, ``When I grow up, I want to be replaced on a
whim,'' `` ... claw my way up to middle management,'' ``... be paid
less for doing the same job.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's tagline: ``There's a better job out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Such as floating in a swimming pool with Halle Berry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
