<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JETS WILL BENEFIT WHEN ELWAY OPENS THE DOOR
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As a quarterback, John Elway has had to make football
decisions all his life. When and where to pass, when and where not
to pass, when to scramble, when to surrender to the sack. But now
he's about to make a quality-of-life decision: retire as a two-time
Super Bowl-winning quarterback or return next season at age 39 and
try to help the Denver Broncos win a record third straight Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice to three-peat,'' he said Monday, ``but it'd be
nice to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   And if John Elway were to depart on top, he would walk into the
same sunset that Michael Jordan did recently, that Sandy Koufax did
in 1966 as baseball's best pitcher, that Jim Brown did in 1965
after leading the National Football League in rushing, that Rocky
Marciano did in 1956 as the world heavyweight champion with a 49-0
record.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair to the Broncos' plans, Elway knows he must make up
his mind by the April draft of college talent.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike most retire-or-not decisions that affect only that
athlete's team, Elway's decision will affect every other Super Bowl
contender in the American Football Conference, especially the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   If Elway resumes his career, the Broncos again will be the AFC
team to beat to get to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But if Elway isn't wearing his No. 7 jersey next season, the
Broncos won't be the same and the AFC door to the Super Bowl will
be wide open, with the Jets first in line after their 12-4 season
that ended with their 23-10 fumble of the AFC title in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos Coach Mike Shanahan, of course, is already talking about
how ``there's no reason we can't do it again,'' even without Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan indicated that Bubby Brister, the backup who was 4-0 as
a starter this season when Elway was out with hamstring and rib
damage, would be the No. 1 quarterback on the Broncos' depth chart,
ahead of young Brian Griese and Jeff Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't come back,'' Elway said, ``Bubby can step in.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's Elway the teammate talking, just as it's Shanahan the
coach talking. You know they're going to tout Brister and the young
quarterbacks. But over Brister's checkered career with the
Steelers, the Eagles and the Jets before he joined the Broncos, he
never did anywhere near what Elway did.
</P>
<P>
   Bubby Brister is not John Elway; for all of Brister's success as
a backup, being the starter is a different deal.
</P>
<P>
   If the Broncos know Elway isn't returning, Shanahan might even
try to trade up in the April draft in order to obtain an early
first-round choice and snatch one of the touted quarterbacks coming
out of college. They might also trade for an experienced
quarterback to support, or even supplant Brister.
</P>
<P>
   If Brister is the Broncos' quarterback next season, the Broncos
might still be good enough to win the AFC West, but they won't be
anywhere near as good a team as they were with Elway at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Without Elway, the Broncos would return to the pack in the AFC,
with the Jets and the Jaguars suddenly the best of the rest, with
the Bills, the Dolphins, the Patriots, the Steelers and maybe the
Seahawks, now organized and coached by Mike Holmgren, the other
playoff contenders.
</P>
<P>
   What also makes Elway's decision different? He's the only Super
Bowl-winning quarterback to be contemplating retirement while
basking as its most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't play, it'll be hard,'' he said. ``All my life,
Saturday and Sundays in the fall are all about football. That
scares me because it's an unknown. I think football is the greatest
game in the world. I know I'll never be comfortable without being
around football.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Elway did a year ago, he will discuss his decision with
his wife, Janet, and their four children, ages 13 to 9. Last spring
their vote was 5-0 for him to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife's my hero,'' he said. ``And I'll talk to the kids, but
they've got to be home, which they never are. No absentee ballots.
I'll talk to Mike and I'll talk to Pat Bowlen, the Broncos' owner.
There's a 90 percent chance I won't play, but I don't want to close
the door.''
</P>
<P>
   If and when John Elway does close the door on his career, he
will be opening the AFC door, and the Jets will be happy to walk
through it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
