 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MARK YOUR CALENDARS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to have a baby born on New Year's Day, at the dawn
of the millennium, the day to get busy is April 9, the author of
``Making Babies'' told a New Zealand newspaper. You should know,
however, that even if the timing of conception is precise, the baby
has only a 6 percent chance of being born on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Richard Fisher &LR;  said would-be New Year's fathers should have
plenty of sex beforehand, &LR;  because ``the best sperm is fresh sperm.
... It's like ice cream and chocolate. The nearer it is to being
manufactured, the better it is.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - A granddaughter of &UR; Pablo Picasso &LR;  is furious with her uncle
 &UR; Claude &LR; , who signed a contract that will allow PSA Peugeot Citroen
to name a soon-to-be-introduced minivan after the painter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot accept that the name of my grandfather, and of my
father, be used to sell a car,''  &UR; Marina Picasso &LR;  told Le Parisien.
``We have paid heavily for rights,'' said a Citroen representative.
``Our agreement is legally binding.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Steve Waye &LR; , a patron of Manivahn Thai restaurant on 24th
Street in San Francisco, says the place doesn't encourage
overeating. The menu lists ``Fried glutton with vegetables in a red
curry sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   - MSNBC's  &UR; Jeannette Walls  &LR; reports that  &UR; Elizabeth Hurley &LR; 's
photo spread in the latest issue of Details has gotten her into
trouble with Estee Lauder cosmetics, for whom she toils. In one
typical picture, she's smoking a cigarette and grabbing her crotch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Estee Lauder has poured millions into positioning this woman
as elegant, sophisticated and sweet,'' a cosmetics business maven
told Walls. ``She's in these ads with fields of flowers and Lab
puppies. Then she goes and poses for some magazine looking like
 &UR; Courtney Love &LR; 's sluttier older sister. ... They're saying she
better clean up her act or there's talk that they might not renew
her contract.''
</P>
<P>
   - Why don't we all chip in for the Olympics? Despite recent
unfavorable publicity, a reader received a solicitation letter last
week from the U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   - Metallica drummer &UR; Lars Ulrich  &LR; told Rolling Stone that when
his band plays with the San Francisco Symphony in April, it's
possible that ``Metallica will be in black tie and the orchestra
will be in black leather.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Pierce Brosnan &LR; , 47, used a body double 16 years younger in a
rear-revealing scene he recently shot for a James Bond movie.
</P>
<P>
   - Drinks and more, as reported in Luxe: Perrier is introducing
the Source Perrier Collection, which includes furniture and table
accessories; and the new Johnnie Walker Collection for men contains
casual clothing, some of it in a signature plaid.
</P>
<P>
   - Twenty-nine percent of us, says Vogue, would like to change
our heights.
</P>
<P>
   - Time to sell those Beanie Babies, if this note from Publishers
Weekly is any indication: A first edition of ``The Bridges of
Madison County,'' valued at $225 in 1994, went for $130 this year.
</P>
<P>
   - The always-sexy Cosmopolitan magazine is launching an edition
for teenagers, says New York magazine.
</P>
<P>
   - Strange stickerfellows spotted by  &UR; Chuck Oey  &LR; on a pickup
truck in Redwood City: On the driver's side, ``Mean people produce
little mean people.'' On the passenger side, ``Bite me.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; THE FAT NECK BRIGADE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with  &UR; Tom Hanks &LR; ? Nothing at all, it seemed, until
the mean old New York Observer had its say: ``Tom Hanks has got a
fat neck. A really fat one.''
</P>
<P>
   Essayist  &UR; Andrew Goldman &LR; 's little list of fat-necked
celebrities also includes  &UR; Jay McInerney &LR; ,  &UR; Richard Simmons &LR; ,
 &UR; George Michael &LR; ,  &UR; Marilyn Manson &LR; , &UR; Neve Campbell &LR; ,  &UR; Bill Bradley &LR; ,
 &UR; David Lee Roth  &LR; and  &UR; Al Gore &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore does not have a fat neck,'' a White House official
(who seems to have protected his job by refusing to let his name be
used) told Goldman. ``He has a small head.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``You have to be able to see things from the other &LR; 
 &UR; person's shoes, and I did not do that.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
