<SLUG> BC-LIBERTY-GUARDIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY MUTUAL DEAL WITH GUARDIAN ROYAL SEALED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.H., N.Y., Ind., Ohio, Wis.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Liberty Mutual Group sealed a pact Monday to acquire
part of British insurer Guardian Royal Exchange Plc for $1.47
billion, in a transaction that expands and diversifies the
Boston-based insurer's core operations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, the latest evidence of the consolidation sweeping the
insurance industry, gives Liberty the British company's US
operations, which include eight property and casualty insurance
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition was part of a larger deal, also sealed Monday,
that saw French insurer AXA Group buy the whole of Guardian Royal,
or GRE, for $5.6 billion. AXA's British arm, known as Sun Life and
Provincial Holdings Plc, then sold GRE's US franchises to Liberty.
Both deals had been expected.
</P>
<P>
   For Liberty Mutual, the transaction is part of a strategy
launched earlier this decade to become less dependent on workers'
compensation, in which it is one of the world's biggest players.
That type of insurance is part of the property and casualty
business, in which Liberty is the nation's eighth largest
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major step in our strategy to diversify risk and
capture added market share,'' said Fred G. Marziano, Liberty's
president of commercial insurance holdings. The newly acquired
units become part of Marziano's group.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. represented Liberty Mutual in the deal,
which is expected to close in the second quarter. The purchase adds
$1.3 billion in premiums to Liberty's $61 billion in assets under
management.
</P>
<P>
   Guardian Royal's US operations include Peerless Insurance of
Keene, N.H.; Indiana Insurance Co. of Indianapolis; and other
regionally-focused companies across New York, Ohio, and Wisconsin.
The units, which will retain their names, provide property and
casualty insurance products to small companies and private
individuals, and give Liberty broader distribution channels.
</P>
<P>
   Marziano said there would be no layoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
