<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7646 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-ART-2T     02-01 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-ART-2TAKES(1,250)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS `PROGRESSIVE BUT PRUDENT' BUDGET; REPUBLICANS SEEK
TAX CUTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill., Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic, on total spending,  are being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hailing a new era of budgetary abundance, President
Clinton proposed a budget for 2000 on Monday that he called a
``progressive but prudent path to our future,'' but which
Republicans immediately attacked as a throwback to an earlier age
of liberal largesse.
</P>
<P>
   The president said his $1.766 trillion plan would insure the
solvency of Social Security and Medicare for decades while
proposing billions of dollars in paid-up programs for schools,
cities, families, the environment and the military.
</P>
<P>
   Before the black ink could dry on Clinton's budget submission,
Republican leaders in Congress complained that the president was
shortchanging taxpayers by devoting billions in surplus government
revenues to new programs rather than tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders signaled a willingness on Monday to work with
Clinton to reserve nearly two-thirds of future surpluses to
strengthen Social Security. But there the agreement ends, as the
fiscal debate in Washington shifts from a debate over how to deal
with deficits to an argument over how to allocate budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's budget ambitiously spends almost every cent of
the surplus not set aside for Social Security reform on more
Washington-based programs,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois. ``Clearly, the president sees the surplus as an
opportunity to expand the power, the influence and the size of the
federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and Republican leaders staked out their opening
positions on Monday for the budget process of public hearings and
backroom deals. In recent years, budgets have been fashioned in a
frenzy of last-minute bargaining in the fall that resulted in
spending plans that bore little relationship to the proposals
introduced nine months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   For the White House, the politicking began on Monday in a
triumphal ceremony in the East Room. Unveiling his budget for the
fiscal year beginning next Oct. 1, the president painted a rosy
vision of a future in which the American economy is insulated
against domestic recession or foreign shocks by setting aside a
large portion of $4.47 trillion in projected surpluses over the
next 15 years to reduce the federal debt from the current level of
44 percent of gross domestic product to just 7 percent in 2014, the
lowest level of public debt since 1917.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a rare opportunity that comes along once in a blue
moon to any group of Americans,'' Clinton said to an audience of
White House officials, cabinet officers and members of Congress.
``Fiscal discipline has transformed the vicious cycle of budget
deficits and high interest rates into a virtuous cycle of budget
surpluses and low interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration's spending plan is the first in more than a
generation to be written from the comfort of a year that just ended
in surplus. It projects continued low inflation and moderate
economic growth over the next five years. The unemployment rate is
projected to rise slightly in 1999 and 2000 and remain at 5.3
percent over the following four years. The current jobless rate is
4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget plan projects federal tax receipts of $1.883
trillion in 2000 and spending of $1.766 trillion, producing a
projected surplus of $117 billion. All of that surplus would be
reserved, pending a deal on saving Social Security. The president's
plan expects that deal in the next year and calls for Social
Security to receive 62 percent of the steadily growing projected
surplus for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The White House projects a surplus of $393 billion in 2009, a
remarkable turnaround from the $290 billion deficit Clinton
inherited when he took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economic house is in order and strong,'' Clinton said.
``If we manage the surplus right, we can uphold our responsibility
to future generations. We can do so by dedicating the lion's share
of the surplus to saving Social Security and Medicare and paying
down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can,'' Clinton continued, ``and because we can, we must do
it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's robust economy has brought a flood of tax revenue to
Washington, but Clinton would use none of it in the fiscal year
2000 for new programs. He finds ways to pay for dozens of programs
and tax breaks within the constraints of the 1997 Balanced Budget
Agreement by proposing to raise billions of dollars through tax
increases, mostly on business and tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The president has rejected Republican demands for an
across-the-board tax cut, proposing instead a series of narrowly
drawn tax credits for specific policy purposes. Clinton proposes
$4.1 billion in targeted tax relief for 2000 and $32.6 billion in
tax reductions in the five years 2000 to 2004. The proposed tax
incentives include new credits for long-term health care, a new
subsidy for stay-at-home parents of young children and expanded
benefits for other child care expenses, tax breaks for a variety of
environmental initiatives, incentives for school construction and
new research and development programs.
</P>
<P>
   The president also proposes significant spending increases on
education, including $1.4 billion for hiring new teachers and $965
million for job retraining and adult literacy programs. The
administration budget also calls for $1 billion to buy parkland and
reduce traffic congestion and urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for these proposals, federal budgeteers scoured the tax
code to find $33.4 billion in new revenue over the next five years
by closing corporate tax loopholes and disallowing various tax
shelters, imposing environmental charges on oil and mining
concerns, taxing certain life insurance transactions and rewriting
sales-tax rules for exporters. Many of these revenue-raising
proposals have been rejected by Congress several times.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is also counting on $54 billion in revenue
from smokers and tobacco companies: a new 55-cents-a-pack cigarette
tax that is expected to raise $34.5 billion over the next five
years and a plan to recover $18.9 billion in Medicaid
reimbursements to states that federal officials contend will be
paid by tobacco companies under legal settlements with the states
worth $246 billion.
</P>
<P>
   From 2001 onward, Clinton would devote 62 percent of future
surpluses for Social Security and 15 percent for Medicare. The rest
would be used to help middle-income taxpayers save for retirement
and to pay for increased spending on the Pentagon and social
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, said Clinton's budget squanders a
historic opportunity to reduce taxes for all Americans, rather than
for favored Democratic constituencies and special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the tax burden on the American people is at an
all-time high _ higher than during World War II,'' Armey, the House
majority leader, said. ``If we can't cut taxes now, when can we?''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials acknowledged that the president's
budget proposals _particularly the new spending and tax measures _
are unlikely to survive in anything like their current form.
</P>
<P>
   They also said that Clinton's plan to reserve 77 percent of
future surpluses to shore up Social Security and Medicare until
2055 was subject to negotiation with the Republican majority in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, the president has not said that this should be
the end of the discussion; this is the beginning of the
discussion,'' said Jack Lew, the White House budget director,
offering a pointed challenge to Congress. ``If there's an
alternative to get to 2055 that is capable of reaching bipartisan
support, we would like to see that alternative.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress were unable to agree last year on
competing tax-cut proposals, with the result that no major tax
relief was approved. But, for now at least, Republicans in both
houses appear united in their determination to pass a big tax-cut
bill and send it to Clinton for his signature.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., who chairs the Senate Budget
Committee, said he was willing to go along with Clinton's proposal
to reserve 62 percent of future surpluses for Social Security. But
while Clinton wants to use the remaining excess funds for Medicare,
a new form of retirement account for middle-income taxpayers and
additional social and military spending, Domenici wants to return
the money to the public in the form of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said he believes Congress will approve a large,
across-the-board tax cut and predicted that Clinton would sign it.
``What's changed,'' he said, ``is we have a bona fide surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, likened Clinton to Santa Claus,
bringing gifts for every constituency from the overflowing budget.
But Kasich, chairman of the House Budget Committee, warned Clinton
against surplus-generated generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to blow this by spending it on Big
Government,'' Kasich said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
