<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BUDGET02-COX     02-01 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While Monica Lewinsky testified just a few blocks
away, President Clinton reveled Monday in a White House ceremony,
rolling out a $1.8 trillion budget for the year 2000 and trumpeting
a new era of American prosperity and surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beneath the glimmering chandeliers of the ornate East
Room, Clinton challenged Congress to sweep aside populist calls for
tax cuts and spending hikes and use the fruits of good times to
shore up Social Security and Medicare, help low-income families
save and pay down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   He called on the country to devote nearly $4 trillion to those
efforts over the next 15 years, saying the country's next
generation deserves the chance to embark on a new century
''unshackled'' by the ''profligacy,'' that left the nation deeply
in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The details for those plans, expected to frame the key
legislative battles over the remainder of Clinton's term, were part
of the budget proposal Clinton sent up to Congress on Monday,
mapping out how he hopes the government raises and spends nearly
$1.8 trillion during the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's budget proposals set the stage for an epic face-off
between Clinton and his Democratic allies in Congress and their
Republican foes, many of whom have already called for
across-the-board income tax reductions of between 10 percent and 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argued, however, that the current generation of
Americans has an obligation to set aside some of its unprecedented
wealth to pour the foundations for continued growth well into the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a rare opportunity that comes along once in a blue
moon to any group of Americans,'' Clinton said, extolling the
benefits of eight years of unprecedented economic growth and the
chance to harness those blessings to solve long-term ills.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not just about saving Social Security and Medicare,''
Clinton said. ''It is also about knowing that when we leave this
century and enter the next, we have given our children 20 years or
so in which they can worry about the challenges of the future ...
unburdened by the unfinished business of the 20th century,
unshackled by our profligacy in the latter part of this century.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke, Lewinsky, the former White House intern at the
center of the sex and deception scandal that led to Clinton's
impeachment in December, was being questioned in a luxury suite at
the nearby Mayflower Hotel in connection with his Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ignored his impeachment woes and reached back instead to
the economic themes that first carried him to the presidency in
1992, declaring complete victory in his efforts to lead the country
away from three decades of deficit spending that left the country
$5.5 trillion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Seven years ago, when I ran for president, I committed to put
our fiscal house in order,'' Clinton said to an enthusiastic
roomful of cabinet members, Congressional Democrats and senior
budget staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ''America is on course for surpluses over the next quarter
century,'' Clinton declared. ''Our economic house is in order and
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government took in $70 billion more than it spent
last year, the first time since 1969 the budget wasn't in the red.
The White House estimates that the surplus will top $79 billion
this year, rise to $117 billion in fiscal 2000 and continue
spiraling upward.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 15 years, the administration estimates, the
surpluses will total more than $4.4 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Clinton's budget proposal is a plan to set aside
62 percent of the surplus, or $2.7 trillion, to shore up Social
Security, the massive federal retirement insurance program that
pays monthly benefits checks to one in every six Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Some $500 billion of that money would be invested in the stock
market, under Clinton's plan, exposing a small portion of the
Social Security program to both the risks and rewards of Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $2.2 trillion would be funneled into the Social
Security trust fund, which would, in turn, loan the money to the
Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury would then use the money to pay down part of the
publicly-held portion of the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $5.5 trillion federal debt, about $3.7 trillion is
publicly-held, meaning it is owed to individual investors and
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The interest payments on that debt are huge; they cost taxpayers
$243 billion last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Government borrowing to finance the debt also crowds out private
borrowers from capital markets, putting upward pressure on interest
rates, a dynamic that's reversed when government borrowing
declines.
</P>
<P>
   By borrowing money from the Social Security trust fund, one part
of the government is, in essence, obligated to pay back a loan to
another. Interest payments become an accounting exercise, not a
taxpayer burden, and no longer show up on the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan, as outlined, wouldn't actually reduce the gross
national debt. The money, after all, would still be owed, only it
would be obligated, in effect, to Social Security beneficiaries
instead of banks and portfolio holders.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration claims, however, that the plan would
have the effect of locking in place future surpluses and imposing
fiscal discipline upon Congress, while dramatically reducing
taxpayers' interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The appeal of this strategy of using Social Security as a
lockbox is that it scales dramatically down the burden of the debt
on the public, in terms of investment, and on the federal budget in
terms of interest,'' said Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers. ''That makes room and provides the capacity to meet, in a
much more satisfactory way, the other obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that, eventually, Democrats and Republicans would be
able to agree on long-term Social Security reform _ some
combination of raising premiums and reducing benefits _ in a way
that would free up additional money to accelerate the retirement of
the overall debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Social Security reform makes that possible,'' said Summers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget also calls for making $536 billion available
over the coming 15 years to finance subsidized savings accounts for
low-income workers, and it would channel some $660 billion into
Medicare, the government health insurance plan that helps retirees
and disabled workers pay their medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
