<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7652 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS &LR;      02-01 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIM CLUE EMERGES IN CASE OF MISSING ATHEIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Danny Fry, a Florida man who went to Texas in 1995
looking for a big score, may have played a role in one of the
century's most baffling celebrity disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   Fry may also provide the authorities with a clue to missing
atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair, who vanished from San Antonio in
September 1995 with her two adult children and $500,000 in gold
coins.
</P>
<P>
   Fry spent that month in San Antonio and he disappeared the same
weekend as the O'Hairs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the O'Hairs' fate remains an enigma, Fry's has become
chillingly clear.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic testing completed last week has determined a nude and
mutilated body that was dumped Oct. 2, 1995, in southeastern Dallas
County was the missing Florida man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly was a cocky bastard who did this. The way they
laid him out was like, `Come and find us,''' said Robert Bjorklund,
a Dallas County sheriff's detective.
</P>
<P>
   The corpse, minus crudely amputated head and hands, was found
that fall afternoon in 1995 by a man collecting aluminum cans on a
trash-strewn riverbank near Seagoville.
</P>
<P>
   The body was placed chest-up, legs neatly together and arms
splayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't they dump him in the water? It would have been a
whole lot harder to find,'' said Bjorklund, who reviewed more than
200 missing-persons cases in an effort to identify the headless
man.
</P>
<P>
   But without tattoos, scars, dental records or fingerprints, the
police were stumped.
</P>
<P>
   The search ended when DNA tests, using blood obtained from Fry's
brother, ex-wife and son, matched a genetic sample taken before the
headless corpse went to a pauper's grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is confirmed that our homicide victim is Danny Fry. The
probability ... is 99.99 percent,'' Bjorklund said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives think Fry, 42, was murdered earlier on Oct. 2, 1995.
The body held few clues, and Fry's clothing, head and hands have
not been found.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fry investigation could break loose the logjammed O'Hair
case.
</P>
<P>
   A three-year global search for the famous atheist has yielded
little more than rumors and speculation. Some believe O'Hair, her
son Jon Garth Murray and adopted daughter, Robin, were murdered for
the gold they bought in late September 1995, using money wired from
an account in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of her sudden disappearance, O'Hair, 76, was
suffering from diabetes and heart trouble. Her role in national
atheist affairs had become marginal.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long slide from her prominence decades ago during the
legal battles over Bible reading and prayer in public schools, and
the Supreme Court decisions in the early 1960s that banned them.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, who once proclaimed herself ``the most hated woman in
America,'' relished conflict with the believers of any rank or
stripe, from the local Baptist preacher to the pope.
</P>
<P>
   One link between the Fry and the O'Hair cases is an Austin man,
David Waters, an ex-convict who knew Fry and had worked as office
manager of O'Hair's atheist organizations in Austin in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, 48, has convictions for murder, forgery, battery and
theft.
</P>
<P>
   The last one came in 1995 after he admitted stealing $54,000
from the O'Hair organizations. Now on probation, Waters is making
monthly restitution payments.
</P>
<P>
   Waters thinks the O'Hairs took the money and ran, and he denies
any knowledge of their fate. He also said he had no knowledge of
Fry's disappearance and murder and recalls only a passing encounter
with him in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The two men had worked together in Florida a few years earlier,
and Waters said they became reacquainted when Fry called that
summer asking about work in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan contacted me. I did tell him if he was interested in
getting ahead, Austin was hot. I said the unemployment rate is 3.2
percent. If you want to get something going, this is the place to
be,'' Waters recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Waters said he allowed Fry to stay in his apartment sometime in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stayed here a couple of weeks,'' Waters said. ``I know he
was having some personal problems. I got the impression he was
trying to get away from things for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters said Fry stayed in Austin a little while, drinking and
gambling, and, after no job materialized, moved on, never to
surface again.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's relatives confirm the man was a heavy drinker and a big
talker when he had a few too many. And they say he wasn't too
particular about how he made his money, as long as the payoff was
good.
</P>
<P>
   But they say Fry never would have gone to Texas unless he had
work lined up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was the type where there had to be some money to be
made to go to Texas, and Waters was the only person he knew
there,'' said Fry's son, D.J.
</P>
<P>
   Family members dispute Waters' statement that his association
with Fry was brief. Phone records indicate a longer and deeper
relationship between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   When Fry failed to return to Florida in early October 1995 as he
had promised, his fiancee, children and brother say they began
calling Waters in Austin for information. But they said he was
unhelpful.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's older brother, Bob, said Waters took a more active
interest in the matter about a week after Danny Fry vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fry said the events were triggered when he called Waters
from Florida and mentioned a letter Danny had sent from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter said that if he wasn't back by a certain date, that
meant something serious had happened. I should contact the
authorities and bring in Dave Waters name, that Dave Waters planned
what we did,'' recalled Bob.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Waters and told him about the letter. I had already
destroyed it, but I just told him I had an unopened letter,'' Bob
Fry recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fry said things happened quickly after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Hold onto it. I'm sure he'll show up. I just talked
to him the night before last from a bar in Dallas. He was drunk,'''
Bob Fry said.
</P>
<P>
   By the next evening, Bob Fry said, Waters and a second man were
on his doorstep in Florida, demanding the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me they were involved with something really heavy in
Texas, and the people who planned it wanted them to get the letter
back. And if they didn't, the people would come and get it, and
they wouldn't be as nice,'' Bob Fry recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fry said the two men finally left after he convinced them
the letter was already destroyed. But, he said, their words
lingered.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing Waters said keeps haunting me. He said, `Your
brother drinks a lot. He's got a big mouth,''' Bob Fry recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Waters denied the encounter with Bob Fry took place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
