<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANAHAN TO PATRIOTS: KEEP UP THE COMMITMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The road to the Super Bowl leads through Foxborough,
Mike Shanahan and John Elway said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly, but at least it passes through Johnny
Parker's weight room.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 12 hours after Shanahan's Broncos repeated as Super
Bowl champions by destroying the dreams of Dan Reeves and the
Atlanta Falcons, the Denver coach and his quarterback were standing
at podiums in downtown Miami discussing how this had come about and
what it would take to become the first team in NFL history to
three-peat in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Their conclusion was the same, and it was simple.
</P>
<P>
   Go to work when everyone else is resting. Go to work in March
and April and May when others play golf and go to the beach and
make excuses for their absences. Go where too few Patriots went
last winter and spring.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the weight room. Go to the film room. Go to work.
</P>
<P>
   When Shanahan spoke to his players following their 34-19
annihilation of the Falcons, he congratulated them on a job well
done but immediately followed that by saying the new season would
begin Monday. He was kidding, of course, but not by much.
</P>
<P>
   While other coaches compliment half-hearted effort, Shanahan is
a hard realist. Minutes after winning the Super Bowl, he already
was demanding a deeper commitment than he had a year ago from his
Broncos. While some apologists for Pete Carroll's Patriots minimize
the importance of consistent offseason workouts, one of the best
coaches in pro football argued forcefully the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to be the best during the season,'' Shanahan
said. ``It's what you do in the offseason that makes the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't surprised at the success we had this year because of
the commitment we've had in the offseason. I'm hoping we have the
same thing again because people will pat us on the back and talk
about dynasties and I hope we don't swallow it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we talked about after the game was that we snuck up on
some people last year. We surprised some people. That's why I'm so
proud of this team this year. We knew we were not going to surprise
anybody. That's why we had the offseason we had. John has had that
commitment for 16 years.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that commitment, or at least the need for it to be truly
successful in the NFL these days, that may yet drive Elway into
retirement even though he could become the first quarterback in NFL
history to win three straight Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Normally such a challenge would be more than enough to bring a
man as competitive as Elway back to the huddle, but before he can
get there, he knows what is required in the quiet months when few
people are thinking about football.
</P>
<P>
   Elway knows what Shanahan expects of him and will demand of him,
regardless of what the NFL Players Association says about offseason
workouts being voluntary. He also knows he is not yet sure he can
do what winners must do in the NFL to maximize their abilities.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Drew Bledsoe wants to win as much as Elway does.
Carroll wants to win as much as Shanahan does. But who wants to win
in March? That is the question, Elway said Monday, that he must
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a 90 percent chance I'll be back, but you can't start
in July and expect to have a good year,'' Elway said. ``The season
starts in April. It's a nine-month job. I have to have my mind made
up by April. I don't want to just come back and go through the
motions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opinion of two champions, two people who have actually
won the Super Bowl rather than just talked about winning it, pro
football is a nine-month job. It is about commitment, the kind of
commitment last year's Patriots simply did not make in the months
when the Broncos were working.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll knows that and any honest observer of the Patriots knows
it as well. The teams that work the hardest in the NFL are the most
successful. It is the same way in most walks of life.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters who use the phone the latest get the story, the
delivery men who drive the longest hours get the promotions, the
construction workers who work the full shift get the building in on
time, the salespeople who make the last call close the deals. Those
are the winners. The ones who work the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   So there was a message for the Patriots Monday, a message that
was clear and unambiguous. If you don't want to go to work in March
and April and May, then you don't want to be playing in Atlanta
next January when the Super Bowl is held.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to the Patriots to decide what they want to do
between now and then. It will be up to Carroll to decide how hard
he wants to push them, if he wants to push them at all.
</P>
<P>
   As for Elway and Shanahan, they know what will be demanded in
Denver. There is no guarantee that if they do all that they will
reach the final game again because many things can intervene
between March and January. But this much is sure: If they don't,
it's guaranteed they won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to come back and go for a three-peat but the question
is whether you can spend the time mentally doing what you need to
do and spend the time physically,'' Elway said. ``That was tough
last year. That was a big haul for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a haul John Elway made though he didn't want to, a haul he
knows a player must make for a chance to reach the Super Bowl. If
they want to make that long haul in Foxborough, Pete Carroll's
Patriots might yet have a chance to fight the Denver Broncos for
the AFC's spot in Super Bowl XXXIV next January.
</P>
<P>
   But if they don't, they might as well make vacation plans now
because next January will be wide open for them. Just as it was
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
