<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-JORDAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERNON JORDAN TO TESTIFY ABOUT OBSTRUCTION OF JUSTICE CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On May 28, 1998, an exhausted Vernon Jordan emerged
from his fourth round of grand jury testimony at the federal
courthouse here to tell reporters: ``I have answered every question
over and over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Jordan added, he expected he would again be called upon to
answer the ``same questions over and over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   He got that right.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, it's Jordan's turn to go before House prosecutors
and White House lawyers in a closed-door deposition for the Senate
impeachment trial. He is one of three witnesses to be interviewed
under oath by the prosecutors, mainly because of their theory that
he was a key player in a conspiracy to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   For Jordan, Washington superlawyer and President Clinton's
longtime confidant and golfing buddy, the stakes are much higher
than when he made his five grand jury appearances last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the two principals of the Monica Lewinsky sex
scandal _ Lewinsky herself and President Clinton _ have appeared
before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Lewinsky's account makes it seem that Jordan knew
a lot more about her affair with Clinton than he said he did during
last year's grand jury appearances.
</P>
<P>
   For example, her testimony undercuts Jordan's contention that
his help in finding her a job was nothing out of the ordinary, and
that he was satisfied with denials by Clinton and Lewinsky that
they had a sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Some key points lawyers on both sides are likely to examine with
Jordan:
</P>
<P>
   1) WHEN HE FIRST MET MONICA LEWINSKY:
</P>
<P>
   Presidential secretary Betty Currie said she arranged Jordan's
first job-search meeting with Lewinsky in November 1998 on her own,
with no direction from Clinton. Clinton's recollection was hazy,
but the president said he didn't think he was the ``precipitating
force'' behind the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Later, around the time when he learned that Lewinsky's name was
on the list of potential witnesses in the Paula Jones civil suit,
Clinton seemed to take a more active role.
</P>
<P>
   When she complained to Clinton in a stormy White House meeting
on Dec. 6, 1998, that Jordan wasn't finding a job for her, Clinton
promised ``I'll get on it,'' according to Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   2) WHAT JORDAN WAS TOLD ABOUT THE RELATIONSHIP
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky contacted him on Dec. 19, distraught over receiving a
subpoena in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit. Lewinsky
talked about her feelings for Clinton and Jordan said he felt as
though he were ``listening to a bobby-soxer who was mesmerized by
Frank Sinatra.'' He asked Lewinsky and, later on, Clinton about
whether they had a sexual relationship. Both said no.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said he saw no need to pursue it further. ``Frankly, I
didn't want Monica Lewinsky to tell me anything about her
relationship with the president ... I was satisfied with her
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the subpoena in the Jones case changed his benign
view of why he had been enlisted in the Lewinsky job search, Jordan
replied ``Zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's account, however, suggests Jordan knew a lot more
about the relationship than he was letting on.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 22, Jordan escorted Lewinsky to the office of a criminal
lawyer, Frank Carter. Jordan's recollection of his conversation
that day with Lewinsky was that it involved her job search.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, however, recalled expressing fear that ``someone''
might be listening in on her phone calls to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan assured her that wouldn't be a problem, she told
Jordan that she and Clinton had engaged in phone sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what's phone sex?'' Lewinsky quoted Jordan as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know what phone sex is,'' Lewinsky replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't,'' Jordan said, according to Lewinsky. ``I'm just
an old man. I don't know what phone sex is.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a Dec. 31 breakfast meeting, Lewinsky asked Jordan if
Clinton and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton would always be
together. Jordan answered they would, but maybe she would have an
affair with Clinton some day.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky said she was ``shocked'' that Jordan didn't seem to
know about her relationship with Clinton. She told Jordan the two
already were having an affair, telling him that while ``we didn't
have sex,'' they ``did everything but sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan ``didn't really respond to me,'' Lewinsky said. ``So I
took that as a cue to drop the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors likely will try to exploit these varying
accounts to show Jordan knew the true nature of the relationship,
and that his job assistance was part of Clinton's calculated plan
to buy Lewinsky's silence. Lewinsky, however, has said she was
never promised a job in exchange for her silence.
</P>
<P>
   3) JORDAN AND THE NOTES FROM LEWINSKY TO CLINTON
</P>
<P>
   At the same Dec. 31 meeting, Lewinsky mentioned that she had
drafts of letters to Clinton around her apartment. Jordan urged her
to ``go home and make sure they're not there.'' Later, Lewinsky
discarded about 50 of the notes, she testified. Jordan has never
been asked about this exchange with Lewinsky. Rep. Asa Hutchinson,
R-Ark., the House prosecutor who will question Jordan, told the
Washington Post that Jordan's answers to questions about this
conversation could be ``significant to the case.''
</P>
<P>
   4) JORDAN GOES INTO HIGH GEAR
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998 as Clinton's deposition in the Paula Jones
lawsuit neared, Jordan intensified the job search for Lewinsky. On
Jan. 8, the day after Lewinsky signed an affidavit denying a sexual
relationship with Clinton, Jordan called Ronald Perelman, chairman
of McAndrews &AMP; Forbes Holdings Inc. to ask the powerful executive
to help Lewinsky. Earlier that day, Lewinsky had complained to
Jordan that an interview at Revlon _ a McAndrews &AMP; Forbes
subsidiary _ had not gone well.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Lewinsky had a second interview and was offered a
job. ``I have to assumed the Jordan magic worked,'' Jordan said.
After learning the news, he called Currie and left a message for
Clinton: ``Mission accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House legal team, however, has argued Jordan's
intervention was inconsequential because the Revlon executive who
interviewed Lewinsky the second time and offered her a job was
never told of Jordan's call to Perelman.
</P>
</TEXT>
