   BUSH-CONSERVATISM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One potential rival calls the phrase ``silly and
insulting.'' Another says Gov. George W. Bush's trademark slogan
amounts to ``weasel words.'' Whatever it is, the latest incarnation
of ``compassionate conservatism'' has caught fire, at least in
Florida and Texas, where practitioners Jeb and George W. Bush found
success in an otherwise bad election year for Republicans. Since
the election, the slogan has become a cause celebre, condemned by
some as the GOP's bane, praised by others as its salvation. Whether
it will play well in the 2000 presidential race is unclear. By JAY
ROOT. Story will move in ``p'' political category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-HISPANICS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It quickly became the stuff of political legend.
Exit polls showed Gov. George W. Bush won half of the Hispanic vote
in his November re-election, and within weeks, the figure was
spread in national and international reports about a potential
presidential bid. For Republicans, who typically get about a
quarter of the Hispanic vote, the exit poll numbers seemed
unbelievable. And they may be. By JAY ROOT. Story has moved in
``p'' political category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
