<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS CITIES SEEKING FUNDING GUARANTEES FOR OLYMPICS BIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MEDE NIX 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Even though the possibility of an Olympics in Texas is
more than a dozen years away, the state Legislature is being asked
to consider guaranteeing the costs of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio sports officials are pushing a bill by Rep. Art
Reyna, D-San Antonio, that could provide unlimited state guarantees
for funding the city's bid for the 2007 Pan American Games and for
Dallas' and Houston's bids for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can sign a blank check, but we're saying that because
the Pan American Games or the Olympics would enable the state to
have an economic windfall, they should recognize that impact with
this guarantee,'' said Susan Blackwood, executive director of the
San Antonio Sports Foundation. ``There's little risk involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood said it is crucial that the Legislature address the
issue in 1999 because San Antonio officials must provide evidence
of the guarantee by October, when the U.S. Olympic Committee will
select the U.S. host city to compete for the 2007 Pan American
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Under International Olympic Committee guidelines, the host
cities _ and their state or federal governments _ have to guarantee
the budget for putting on the two-week event. That means taxpayers
could be on the hook for any shortfall of private funds. It is
expected that the 2012 Olympics might cost as much as $3 billion to
produce.
</P>
<P>
   The funding guarantee is not yet crucial for Dallas and Houston.
The cities seeking the 2012 Olympics don't have to submit a formal
bid to the USOC until 2002. The USOC in 2003 will select a city
from among Dallas; Houston; Cincinnati; Los Angeles; New York;
Tampa, Fla.; and Washington, D.C.-Baltimore to compete against
international cities.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a hitch with Reyna's bill. The chairman of the
Dallas bid for the 2012 Olympics said he cannot support the bill
because of his bid committee's promise not to seek public financing
for the bid.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and some legislators have said they're not
keen about statewide funding for regional sports events if it
involves increasing the 8.25 percent sales tax cap. Reyna's bill
does not mention the sales tax but asks in general terms for a
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it was worded, it's not a piece of legislation we're
supporting,'' said Tom Luce, chairman of Dallas 2012, the city's
Olympic bid committee. ``It's more like an unlimited guarantee, and
we're not going to ask anybody for an unlimited guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kim Brimer, R-Arlington, said legislators are unlikely to
approve statewide help for a regional sports event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything regional the state's not going to pay for,'' Brimer
said. ``They would be barking up the wrong tree.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of guarantees is controversial. Two Dallas city
councilwomen wanted the council to reconsider its support of the
Dallas bid after learning of the guarantees. But members of the bid
cities say that although the guarantees are required, corporate
sponsorships and fees for television rights should pay for the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   If a guarantee _ like the one that Utah lawmakers approved for
the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City _ is not forthcoming,
Blackwood said, there are other possibilities that might allow the
bid committee to obtain guarantees without leaving taxpayers
liable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be able to come up with some alternatives,''
she said. ``We are looking at agreements with vendors to share some
responsibility to make sure the games are successful. And maybe San
Antonio or the state can help us find some event insurance to cover
the shortfall, using their good faith and credit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brimer said his legislation enacted in 1997 to help
communities and counties pay for sports facilities through a
variety of funding methods may provide the best vehicle for
financing the big-ticket items of the games: Olympic venues.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Brimer Bill'' is helping Dallas build a new downtown
sports arena, Round Rock construct a ballpark for Nolan Ryan's
minor-league baseball team and El Paso carry on its annual Sun Bowl
college football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the pitches we made when trying to pass the bill was
its regional concept,'' Brimer said. ``A group of five or six
counties or cities could go together and do a project. It would
allow a funding method they never had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Each county, or each city in a group of cities, would have to
conduct a separate election, but Brimer said such elections would
allow communities to gauge support for a project.
</P>
<P>
   The sports-facilities law allows voters to approve a sales tax
increase of up to a half-cent as long as it doesn't exceed the 8.25
percent cap, to increase taxes on car rentals and hotel and motel
rooms, and to add a fee to tickets and parking at the events.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket and parking fees may be most attractive to Dallas
interests because it would allow those attending the Games to help
pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas bid effort, in addition to operating costs, has
several big infrastructure needs. It would cost $250 million to put
a retractable roof on the Cotton Bowl and renovate the stadium for
track-and-field events and for opening and closing Olympic
ceremonies, according to preliminary estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The region also lacks an aquatics center and dormitory space for
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of bid committees in Dallas, Houston and San Antonio
have been meeting for several months to draft a common legislative
agenda, but the details haven't been worked out, Luce said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the cities agreed that the widening Olympic
bribery scandal that has tainted the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake
City probably won't affect the passage of any necessary legislation
because of the massive revisions expected for the bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as a really positive step,'' Blackwood said. ``We
were always going to play by the rules, and now we can assure
sponsors and even legislators that there is an even playing field
and the bid process will be highly scrutinized.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
