   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-RECRUITING (Aboard the USS HARRY S. TRUMAN) _ The Navy
spent $4.5 billion to build this, the nation's newest carrier. It
has two nuclear reactors, the latest electronic, computer and
navigational equipment and, for the long ``cruises'' to come,
amenities for the crew, like televisions in almost every berth.
What the Navy cannot put aboard the Truman is a full crew. The
ship, commissioned by Clinton last July to join the nation's other
carriers, is not alone. Two weeks ago, the Navy disclosed that it
has had as many as 22,000 empty positions, or billets, in a force
of 372,000. The vast majority of those were aboard the Navy's 327
ships, rather than on shore. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
