u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-BOS &LR;      02-01 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS, NEW HIP IN PLACE, HEADS FOR FLORIDA RECUPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They were steps taken with crutches and with far less
fanfare than his strolls up 18th fairways for parts of four
decades, but that didn't seem to bother Jack Nicklaus Monday. The
most accomplished golfer in history left New England Baptist
Hospital and headed home to North Palm Beach, Fla., for
recuperation following last Wednesday's surgery for total left hip
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   He may be years removed from his glory days as the Golden Bear,
but, at 59, Nicklaus still commands a huge presence. Thus, the
modest act of leaving a hospital meant a stage, not before a huge
gallery, but a press conference, with the national media plugged
in. The surgery, he said, was something he gave a great deal of
thought to, and it was not a decision made so that he could stalk
more glory. With 18 major professional championships, he has
cemented his place in sports history; he wants now to live
pain-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf wasn't the reason I came here; the quality of life was
the reason I came here,'' said Nicklaus. ``There are no illusions,
not at 59 or 60, of competing with the Tiger Woodses and David
Duvals. But I'm looking forward to having this stabilize my hip and
allow me to function to a quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The recovery process will involve rest, some isometrics,
stretching, then a little walking, according to Dr. Benjamin
Bierbaum, who performed the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am tired,'' said Nicklaus. ``I am a guy with pretty endless
energy, but I don't have a lot right now. I usually go to the
office, but the office will have to come to me now.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for someone to ask about his plans for
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I would love to play golf again,'' said Nicklaus.
``There's no question about that. My goal is _ I don't think I will
make it _ is the Memorial Tournament (June 3-6). But my chances are
probably 1 in 50.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus emphasized that Bierbaum is calling the shots and said
he will return to Boston in five or six weeks for a checkup. A
conservative timetable calls for competition in six or seven
months, ``simply because I won't be able to play three, four, or
five days in a row,'' said Nicklaus. ``Four months from now, I'll
be able to play a round of golf and probably do just fine.'' But it
will take time to build up his stamina.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus will miss his first Masters (April 8-11) since his
debut in 1959 and most likely he won't be at Pinehurst June 17-20
for the US Open, an event he has missed just once (1960) since he
burst upon the scene in 1957 as a teen-ager out of Columbus, Ohio,
who hit the ball with jaw-dropping length. If the end to such
remarkable streaks is making Nicklaus melancholy, he hid it
masterfully.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if a burden had been lifted from his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been struggling with this since the PGA Championship at
Bellerive (in 1992),'' he said. ``My hip was bad enough that I
remember making a statement to Barbara (his wife) that I am tired
of playing on one leg.''
</P>
<P>
   To alleviate the pain, Nicklaus embarked on a vigorous exercise
program and for a while he was able to stay competitive, but last
summer it reached a critical point. After June's US Open marked his
record 146th straight start in a major, Nicklaus looked at the
British Open the following month and knew it was a futile cause.
The pain was brutal, the leg was going numb, and the truth was too
hard to run from.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to go play, you've got to be prepared,'' he
said. ``And if you can't prepare, you can't compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus did not go over to Royal Birkdale, nor did he play in
the PGA Championship in August. He did play in the US Senior
Amateur in late July, but that was his final tournament of 1998.
There was a long stretch without golf, then in late December, after
returning from Australia, where he captained the US team in the
Presidents Cup, Nicklaus said he hit balls, starting with 30 the
first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the fifth day, I decided to play nine holes of golf and it
was a disaster,'' he said. ``That's when I said, `I need to make a
phone call.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that Nicklaus, despite encouragement from
family and friends, put surgery off for too long, but he said that
wasn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my timing was probably accurate,'' said Nicklaus. ``I
don't think I wasted a whole lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that on one good leg last April he made a dramatic run
at a seventh green jacket, only to finish fifth in the Masters,
Nicklaus flashed a little grin, as if he were about to go on a
back-nine charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to find out,'' he said. ``That would be a very
interesting thing, to find out if my legs are good and I don't
fatigue and I functionally can finish a golf swing. Having that
ability versus what I have right now, that could be a very big
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Nicklaus, seated in the audience, smiled at this sudden
burst of competitive spirit, one she has witnessed since those
campus days at Ohio State. She has a more modest goal for husband _
to dance at their youngest son Michael's wedding Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take two steps on crutches and that will be my dance,''
joked Nicklaus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
