<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MATISSE-PICASSO-1     02-01 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MATISSE-PICASSO-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT DEPICTS A VISUAL CHESS MATCH BETWEEN THE TWO TITANS OF
MODERN ART
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by KIMBELL-EXHIBIT) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Henri Matisse and Pablo Picasso were
introduced by Gertrude Stein in 1906. Previously, they were aware
of one another only by reputation. They've come together again in
an exhibit of more than 100 works that opened Sunday at the Kimbell
Art Museum in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of their first meeting, Matisse had established
himself as the leader of the fauves, the ``wild beasts,'' the
iconoclastic artists of the day. His determination to remain true
to his artistic vision _ he wasn't necessarily out to shock _
resulted in pictures whose garish colors and distortions of form
and space repelled even many of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso, 12 years younger, was the brash and brilliant young
newcomer to Paris' explosive art scene. Picasso was relentless in
his pursuit of notoriety, in his attempts to shock the bourgeoisie
and to become a true painter of modern life. By now, he had painted
his masklike portrait of Stein and was working with a geometric
vocabulary that presaged cubism.
</P>
<P>
   These are the stories of Matisse and Picasso that art lovers
know so well, the legends that were played out during the glory
years of European modern art _ such as the defection of Stein from
Matisse's camp to Picasso's and Picasso's response to Matisse's
``Joy of Life'' via his vicious ``Desmoiselles d'Avignon.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is another story _ one rich in its revelations about
human nature and artistic motivations, one of great art history
significance, one that offers tremendous insights into how so many
of the 20th century's truly important artworks came into being.
</P>
<P>
   This other story, telling of Matisse and Picasso's later years,
is recounted in the Kimbell's new, groundbreaking exhibition,
``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle Rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is the first major presentation pairing the two artists
in 50 years. It was curated by one of the world's leading art
historians. Yve-Alain Bois, of Harvard University, is a thorough
and iconoclastic scholar who has conducted important new research
on the careers of both artists.
</P>
<P>
   What he has found is that the artistic competition that abruptly
ended when Matisse moved from Paris to Nice in late 1917 was only a
foreshadowing of the protracted rivalry (which Bois variously
describes as a ``tango'' and a ``chess game'') that ensued around
1930.
</P>
<P>
   Selecting artworks well-known and also rarely, if ever,
exhibited, Bois assembled about 50 paintings, sculptures and
graphic works by Matisse and slightly more than 50 by Picasso into
an art history chronology.
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, Matisse was emerging from his years in Nice. He was
racked by doubt and bereft of inspiration. Critics had labeled him
a has-been. He was unable to paint at all.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso, on the other hand, was riding a wave of critical and
commercial success. Indeed, he was intolerably in command of the
scene. If Matisse had been immobilized by criticism, Picasso was
suffering from a lack of critical challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso looked back at Matisse's early achievements and he knew:
He needed Matisse back. And in top form.
</P>
<P>
   So he started teasing the old lion, mimicking his art. He seemed
to mock Matisse's obsession with odalisques (harem girls), leaping
dancers and views through windows. He dared Matisse to return to
the fray.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where this exhibition begins. ``Matisse and
Picasso'' shows visitors Picasso's long, looping looks back at
Matisse's work and his responses to Matisse's innovations. It puts,
right before our eyes, Matisse's immediate and deliberate responses
to Picasso's cubistic handling of space, his deployment of symbolic
shapes.
</P>
<P>
   It opens with an introductory group of potentially taunting
pictures by Picasso. From there, however, it quickly moves into
``Act One: A Fresh Start, 1930-32,'' in which we see Picasso
grappling with Matisse's tremendous gift for modeling sculpture.
Also, in response to a Matisse gallery retrospective in mid-1931,
we see his hastily produced series of ``sleeping beauties'' that
widely were recognized as a gesture toward Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   But, what of Matisse? How, if at all, would he respond?
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
