<SLUG> BC-RUN-CLARK-MILLROSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TERRIFYING ACCIDENT, CLARK TO RUN IN MILLROSE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1978, as a 15-year-old high school sophomore from
Maplewood, N.J., Joetta Clark ran in the Millrose Games. Except for
1984, when she was injured, she has run in this invitation track
meet every year and has won the women's 800 meters six times.
</P>
<P>
   She is ranked fourth in the world and can run in almost any meet
she wants. Still, she said, Friday night's Chase Millrose Games in
Madison Square Garden ``is more special than any other.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Monday luncheon meeting of the New York Track Writers
Association, she told why, a harrowing tale of a crash last Sept.
15 involving her auto and an 18-wheel semi-trailer that left her
with a battered body and initial fears that she might not walk
again, let alone run.
</P>
<P>
   That day, she said, she drove to Newark Airport to pick up
airline tickets. On the way home, on the Elizabeth ramp to the New
Jersey Turnpike, she said the truck merged into her lane when there
was no room to merge. It hit her car on the driver's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It spun the car around and jackknifed,'' she said. ``I was
pinned in the car. A 20-year-old guy from Colts Neck, N.J., named
Howard Marcus stopped and stayed with me while we were waiting for
an ambulance. He flagged down another guy, Gerry DeHaven from
Princeton, N.J., and he used my cell phone to call my mother and
father. Then he said, `Aren't you Joetta Clark?' I said yes. He
said, `Can I have an autograph?' I gave him an autograph.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark was finally pulled from her battered car. At the hospital,
she learned she had a concussion, two torn lumbar discs, a torn
abdominal muscle and an injured left eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of things wrong with me,'' she said. ``I was
bedridden for three weeks. I wasn't thinking about running
Millrose, just to be able to run again. You don't think you won't
run again. You just thank the Lord for being alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to move your arms and legs. I was in so much pain that
I wasn't thinking about running, just walking again and being my
vibrant self. I'm happy just to be able to raise my left arm over
my head and move my right leg 90 degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   That flexibility, such as it is, did not come easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body had been tossed around,'' she said. ``As an athlete,
my pain threshold is a lot higher than most people's. For me to sit
in bed all day was not something I liked to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The rehabilitation was intense: lifting her arms, moving her
legs, riding a stationary bike, stretching, massage, electrical
stimulation, running in a pool. Just before Thanksgiving, she
started running on a track. She is still getting therapy to
strengthen her arms and legs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 36, she is back for her 21st Millrose Games, a record
for this 92-year meet. She will run the 800 meters against Meredith
Rainey Valmon, Michelle DiMuro-Ave, Alisa Harvey and Zhang Jian of
China. She made it clear that she was running to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't run just to run,'' she said, ``not at this point in
my career. It would be embarrassing. Winning Millrose would
probably be the highlight of my career because this hasn't been a
typical year for me. The rehab has been tougher than training, but
I am a tough person. I am running with aggression.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
