<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7691 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MATISSE-PICASSO-2     02-01 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MATISSE-PICASSO-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
FORT WORTH, Texas: would he respond? 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Act Two: Making Partners, 1932-39'' answers those questions by
presenting works from two projects that permitted Matisse to
recover his artistic strengths. He was commissioned by Albert C.
Barnes to create a mural for his gallery/house in Merion, Pa. _
which reconnected Matisse with his powerful motifs of pagan
dancers. And he was asked to illustrate Stephane Mallarme's
``Poesies,'' in which he recapitulated his ``sleeping beauties.''
</P>
<P>
   During these years, too, each artist explored and tried to
translate into his own work that visual language of the other _ as
seen in Picasso's drawings of dancers from 1933 and Matisse's
painting of ``La Verdure (Nymph in the Forest),'' which was begun
in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Then came World War II. Many artists fled Europe _ an
immigration that led to New York's historic emergence as the center
of the art world _ while others reinvented themselves to suit
fascistic morals. Picasso and Matisse, however, remained in France
and continued their progressive, highly individualistic work.
</P>
<P>
   But Picasso was in Paris, forbidden to exhibit, and Matisse in
the south of France. Thus, their artistic exchange took the form of
works that friends transported to and fro, and memories of the
other's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Act Three: Parallel Play, 1940-44'' thus features Matisse's
``The Dream'' (1940), which reclaims the territory Picasso had
challenged with his ``Woman With Yellow Hair'' (1931). We see, as
well, Picasso painting variations on a favorite Matissean theme, a
seated woman wearing a hat.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, both artists were celebrated as national heroes.
At last, too, they lived near one another in the south of France
and could keep up with each other's work. When bad health forced
Matisse into bed, Picasso brought him recent works in order to
obtain Matisse's feedback.
</P>
<P>
   During this period _ covered in ``Act Four: Reunion, 1944-45'' _
the 80-year-old Matisse visits Picasso's 1946 show in Antibes and
makes pencil copies of several, as if he were again a young student
visiting the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso, in the meantime, returns to Matisse's 1906 masterwork,
``The Joy of Life.'' This time, instead of demonizing it, Picasso
seems to revel in the work's celebration of life.
</P>
<P>
   During this period, too, Matisse executes a commission to
decorate a chapel in Vence[ cq] and Picasso, never one to be
outdone, undertakes his own Temple of Peace in Vallauris.
</P>
<P>
   Upon Matisse's death in 1954, Picasso was plunged into mourning.
But more than ever, he reincarnated Matisse through works that
directly addressed Matissean themes or incorporated his techniques
and formal innovations. Now that Matisse was gone, Bois says, it
seemed as though Picasso could be completely open in his admiration
for his old rival.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the story ends, with Picasso once again evoking Matisse.
This time, though, there was no luring him back, and so Picasso
continued _ peerless _ until his death in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact her at vizart(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
