<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7692 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CONSERVATISM-960     02-01 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONSERVATISM-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DUSTS OFF, CASHES IN ON OLD POLITICAL SLOGAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One potential rival calls the phrase ``silly and
insulting.'' Another says Gov. George W. Bush's trademark slogan
amounts to ``weasel words.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, the latest incarnation of ``compassionate
conservatism'' has caught fire, at least in Florida and Texas,
where practitioners Jeb and George W. Bush found success in an
otherwise bad election year for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Since the election, the slogan has become a cause celebre,
condemned by some as the GOP's bane, praised by others as its
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it will play well in the 2000 presidential race is
unclear. Compassionate conservatism can be elusive, perhaps more
easily defined by what it is not rather than what it is.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the kind of divisive politics other Republicans have
used to ``bash'' Hispanics and vilify immigrants, says a
spokeswoman for the National Council of La Raza, a Hispanic
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it rely on ``code words ... that turn black people
off,'' says black political analyst Sanders Anderson of Texas
Southern University.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bush's stand against affirmative action,
while wrapped in careful language, does not sound very
compassionate to some minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is compassionate, why is he against affirmative
action?'' asked Roberto Alonzo, a former state representative and
president of the Mexican American Democrats. ``It's not just about
compassion, it's about what Bush has done for Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, while many gays were thrilled when Bush rebuked a
comment by a Republican party official comparing homosexuals to
pedophiles during the GOP state convention last year, they are
cautious of his policy on gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful,'' said Rep. Glen Maxey, D-Austin, the only openly
gay member of the Texas Legislature. ``I applauded what he said at
the Republican convention, but when it comes to real policy issues,
we don't have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush won't commit one way or another on a bill that would ban
adoptions by homosexual couples. But he said he supports the notion
that adoptions are better left to a man and a woman _ not two men
or two women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first thing we ought to do with any placement of
children, we ought to be looking for heterosexual couples,'' Bush
said. ``To have a male and a female in a household, I think it
provides the proper role models to children's futures.''
</P>
<P>
   On affirmative action, Bush says a fairer policy is
``affirmative access,'' such as ensuring that students in the top
10 percent of their class are admitted by colleges, or actively
recruiting minorities to apply for appointive jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affirmative action is quotas, where there is a group of people
sitting around saying, `All right, there is 11 percent of the
population that is so and so, therefore 11 percent of our
appointments must be this whether they are qualified or not,' ''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The best strategy is making sure ``our applicant pool reflects
Texas. Let's make sure we recruit and actively go out and seek
people and find people, and I think that's a different mentality,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush has received accolades for appointing blacks and
Hispanics to key positions. He appointed, for example, the first
black railroad commissioner, Michael Williams of Arlington, and the
first Hispanic insurance commissioner, Jose Montemayor.
</P>
<P>
   After the Williams appointment, Sen. Rodney Ellis, an
African-American Democrat from Houston, applauded Bush for his
efforts to ``make Texas' government more reflective of its
population.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the historic appointments, however, figures from Bush's
office indicate that his appointments since taking office in 1995
have been 78 percent Anglo and 64 percent male.
</P>
<P>
   Of 2,273 total appointments, 184, or 8 percent, are black; 275,
or 12 percent, are Hispanic; and 817, or 36 percent, are women. By
comparison, two-thirds of the appointments made by his predecessor,
Ann Richards, were Anglo, 18 percent were Hispanic and 13 percent
were black. But simply counting appointees might be overlooking the
broader implications of Bush's political strategy. Anderson, the
TSU political scientist, said its success derives not from policy
but rather from language and symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always what they say, it's how they say it,'' said
Anderson, citing Bush's appearance at a Martin Luther King Jr.
rally in Houston this month as an example of his successful
outreach efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What George W. Bush has done that other Republicans have not
done, is he has embraced certain symbols that are benign. It
wouldn't hurt other Republicans to embrace Martin Luther King,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   In a presidential bid, of course, Bush would first have to win a
primary contest with fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The trick there is not necessarily appealing to minorities and
independents, who might be attracted to an unorthodox Republican
message, but rather to the GOP base, which is much more
conservative and potentially more hard-edged, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   It is here that Bush has become the target of often bitter
attacks from potential rivals, including former Vice President Dan
Quayle, who has instructed his staff never to use Bush's ``silly
and insulting'' slogan, and Lamar Alexander, who has tagged
compassionate conservatism as ``weasel words.''
</P>
<P>
   But many conservative Republicans who are not in the heat of a
presidential contest say Bush's message helps the GOP by couching
its conservative philosophy in ways that are palatable to the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kent Grusendorf, R-Arlington, and Rep. Arlene Wohlgemuth,
R-Burleson, are both staunch conservatives and both like what they
see in Bush's compassionate conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lost much of the public perception debate,'' said
Wohlgemuth. ``There's more to it than just the greedy, selfish kind
of Republicans that we are stereotyped as being.''
</P>
<P>
   She said, for example, that overhauling welfare is a
compassionate way of teaching the poor how to make it on their own
instead of simply ``mailing out a check.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax cuts, a key item in Bush's legislative agenda for the past
two years, are another element of compassionate conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax cuts are compassionate,'' Bush said. ``Tax cuts give
people more money.'' He also noted that his proposed budget
demonstrated compassion by increasing funding for the agency that
investigates child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who won re-election in November with 69 percent of the
vote _ a margin that included unusually high numbers of blacks and
Hispanics for a Republican _ is not the first politician to use the
phrase ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the phrase has been used by at least one Republican now
seen as the antithesis of the slogan. Pete Wilson, a moderate on
some social issues but a hard-liner on immigration, used it with
great success in his 1988 race for California governor.
</P>
<P>
   It has also been employed by staunch conservatives such as talk
show host and presidential candidate Pat Buchanan. Former housing
secretary Jack Kemp, the 1996 GOP vice presidential nominee, also
used the term.
</P>
<P>
   While the term has been associated with figures as politically
ancient as Thomas Dewey, the former New York governor and two-time
presidential candidate, ``compassionate conservatism'' as a slogan
appears to be a Democratic invention.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest reference to the phrase located in a computer
search of major newspapers comes in connection with a drive by
former U.S. Rep. James R. Jones, D-Oklahoma, to steer the
Democratic party to the political center.
</P>
<P>
   After the party's dismal performance amid Ronald Reagan's
landslide 1984 re-election victory, Jones suggested that Democrats
use the slogan to show that being fiscally conservative and
socially moderate can go hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase never came into widespread use by Democrats, but the
notion stuck, and it became the basis of the Democratic Leadership
Council, which a young governor named Bill Clinton came to chair
and which helped forge the term ``New Democrat'' that the future
president would use over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, now a New York businessman, said Republicans like Bush
are simply using the same strategy. If Democrats can be ``tough
liberals,'' then conservatives can be compassionate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party now has the same public image on the
right-wing side of the political spectrum as the Democratic Party
had on the left wing side,'' Jones said. ``This is their way of
trying to have a code saying we want to bring the Republican Party
back to the center.''
</P>
<P>
   It works for James Dixon, an African-American preacher in
Houston who attended Bush's appearance at the Martin Luther King
Jr. celebration. Despite reports that Bush's reception there was at
times chilly, Dixon said the governor is making inroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is more middle-of-the-road than previous Republicans have
been,'' Dixon said. ``He is closer to what Bill Clinton is like, to
be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is Austin bureau chief for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (512) 476-4294, or e-mail:
jroot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
