<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: MILOSEVIC'S ADVANTAGE: IN TALKING PEACE, HE CAN WIN
BIG 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ As the deadline approaches for entering
peace talks on Kosovo province, with threats of NATO bombs and
sharp warnings from the West, Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president, has much to gain.
</P>
<P>
   The threats by the Clinton administration and its NATO allies to
bomb him into ceding effective control over the separatist province
not only make it easier for Milosevic to justify eventual
concessions but also make him indispensable to any settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as officials in Washington publicly revile Milosevic
and call him the main problem in the Balkans, he is also the
solution,'' a senior Western diplomat said. ``The West needs
Milosevic to settle Kosovo, and Milosevic needs the pressure of the
West to be able to do it. All the rest is hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Kosovo's mythic importance as the birthplace of the
Serbian nation, Serbian officials and senior diplomats here say,
Milosevic is bound to take NATO to the brink before agreeing to any
political settlement over Kosovo, where an ethnic Albanian majority
is fighting for independence.
</P>
<P>
   While the stick of NATO's bombs is a necessary condition for any
deal, Milosevic will also require some ``cake,'' as the new deputy
prime minister, Vuk Draskovic, put it _ a partial lifting of the
harsh diplomatic and economic isolation that the West imposed on
Serbia during the Bosnian war. Milosevic may also seek a quiet
promise that he not be indicted for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   There is a wide assumption here, based on the tone of the state
press, that Milosevic will send a delegation to the
Western-sponsored talks that are scheduled to start on Saturday
outside Paris. There has been no official announcement, however.
</P>
<P>
   And there is also a wide expectation that Milosevic will
eventually authorize an interim settlement that leaves Kosovo a
vague but largely self-governing entity within the formal
sovereignty of Yugoslavia, as the West is demanding.
</P>
<P>
   As he was in Bosnia, Milosevic would again become a vital
guarantor of any settlement, reinforcing his international and
domestic stature.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic will be able to argue that even the introduction of
Western troops into Kosovo will serve to repress the ``terrorism''
of the Kosovo Liberation Army, to protect Serbs and their holy
places and to keep Kosovo from becoming independent.
</P>
<P>
   Already, on state television, Milosevic is being hailed for
demanding that Kosovo must remain ``part of our country.'' While
the name of that country _ Yugoslavia or Serbia _ is left
deliberately vague, ``one can already smell the way a settlement
will be spun here,'' said Bratislav Grubacic, a well-connected
editor.
</P>
<P>
   The analytical cliche about Milosevic is that he survives by
creating crises that require national unity and justify the
stifling of dissent, and that he is a superb political tactician
who does not have a larger strategic vision. But he is also
considered a highly rational judge of his own interests, with
little emotional attachment to the kind of Serbian nationalism he
has manipulated for the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't care himself about Kosovo,'' said Aleksa Djilas, a
political scientist here who has written some of the best analyses
of Milosevic. ``His enemies are his best friends,'' said Djilas.
``He thrives when Serbs feel the world is being biased and unfair
to them. At the same time, the West comes to his aid when it treats
him respectfully, as someone who has all the cards in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has helped Milosevic, too, Djilas said. ``There
was a chance for the opposition to unite and put Milosevic and the
Socialists out of power,'' he said. ``But they never did, and now
they're joining him.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, Milosevic fired key members of his inner circle,
including the long-serving army chief of staff, Gen. Momcilo
Perisic, and the director of intelligence, Jovica Stanisic,
reportedly at the urging of his wife, Mirjana Markovic, whom many
here compare to a socialist Lady Macbeth.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Washington officials saw the purge as an indication
of Milosevic's weakness and the fragility of his regime. Some
thought the effective loss of Kosovo would mean the quick downfall
of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But Perisic has not attracted supporters and Milosevic's control
over the apparatus of both the federal and Serbian authorities
seems enhanced, said both Grubacic and Ljiljana Smajlovic, a
Serbian journalist.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Smajlovic said, ``Milosevic is in great shape,'' having
co-opted into the governing coalition both the nationalist leader
of the Radical Party, Vojislav Sesejl, and the most charismatic
leader of the former opposition coalition, Draskovic, who agreed to
enter the federal government two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic can say with some legitimacy that he has a national
unity government, and politically, he controls every institution,''
Ms. Smajlovic said. ``The only people outside his reach are those,
like students, journalists and professors, who have no
parliamentary seats or institutional authority.''
</P>
<P>
   And this more liberal group can hardly attack Milosevic from the
right, for avoiding another war and making concessions on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officials here like to say that they don't have enough money
to make everyone happy, but they have enough to bribe anyone they
need,'' Grubacic said. ``The country is poorer than before, but
passive. Milosevic is the king, untouchable, and underneath him,
the factions are fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a prominent member of the opposition Democratic Party, its
vice president, Slobodan Vuksanovic, says Milosevic's position is
unchallenged now, and that the opposition has damaged itself badly
by its own mistakes and rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, 200,000 people turned out daily in Belgrade
to demonstrate against Milosevic and in favor of democratic
spokesmen like Draskovic, Zoran Djindjic and Vesna Pesic. Their
coalition _ Zajedno, or unity _won local elections in Belgrade,
which represents almost a third of Serbia's population.
</P>
<P>
   But their own disputes destroyed the coalition, and their
decision to boycott parliamentary elections left them without any
parliamentary votes or a clear program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic didn't do this to us,'' Vuksanovic said. ``We did
this to ourselves. He's still in power because opposition leaders
missed so many opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition could have won up to 100 of the 250 seats in the
Serb parliament, Vuksanovic said. ``In the end we're left with
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Draskovic contended in an interview that he has kept his
integrity and is fighting for the same democratic goals ``from
within,'' Vuksanovic believes that Draskovic is trying to benefit
from the perks of power, including wide access to the
state-controlled media.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he notes, Draskovic's deal with Milosevic will
deeply disappoint ordinary voters. ``They will look at this
opposition leader and say, `He's just like all the rest of them.'
`'
</P>
<P>
   The ordinary voter is afraid of risk, Vuksanovic said. ``They
know Milosevic is a bad guy, but they see that he's stronger than
all the other political leaders put together.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course the end will come for Milosevic, Grubacic said, but
not now. ``The challenge will be spontaneous, caused by a stupid
mistake, like the last drop of water that overfills the glass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
