r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIMBELL-EXHIBIT-TEX     02-01 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIMBELL-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE KIMBELL ART MUSEUM LANDED THE MATISSE-PICASSO SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies ART-MATISSE-PICASSO) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Henri Matisse and Pablo Picasso are widely
considered the twin pillars of European modern art.
</P>
<P>
   So you'd think ``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle Rivalry'' would
have a number of precedents. But no. It is the first major curated
exhibition of their works ever.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring 104 works, it reveals the intensive artistic exchange
between these two giants, from the late 1920s to the time of
Matisse's death and even after, in Picasso paintings that evoke the
memory of his late peer. The paintings, sculpture and graphic works
on view come from private and public collections in Australia,
France, Germany, Russia, Switzerland and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the exhibit nearly didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   It started off on a promising note: In the process of
identifying his scholarly focus, exhibition guest curator Yve-Alain
Bois realized that about half of the loans he would want would be
readily available. But then Bois and former Kimbell curator Joachim
Pissarro _ who'd initially conceived the exhibition _ discovered
that they weren't the only ones planning to pair the two giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Tate Gallery, the Museum of Modern Art in New York and two
Paris museums had scheduled a Matisse-Picasso survey for 2002.
Would the shows overlap? Eventually, Bois and Pissarro confirmed
that their show could stand on its own.
</P>
<P>
   As to that future Matisse-Picasso pairing, well, the folks at
MoMA are rather mum. Still, MoMA curators John Elderfield and Kirk
Varnedoe told London's Art Newspaper in December: ``Giants such as
this exhibition are born in the upper ranks of the museum, not
least because they involve international museum relations. The idea
started with the British art historian John Golding, who did a
marvelous Picasso and sculpture show recently at the Tate.''
</P>
<P>
   Golding, in a recent phone interview, was a bit more helpful.
``I think the two shows will complement each other and help each
other,'' he said. ``Exhibitions can feature similar or some of the
same materials, but do so in very different ways that set them
apart. Like the Kimbell show, ours will mix masterpieces and
lesser-known works. But ours is wider in scope ... and it relies
more on curators' instinctual comparisons and contrasts between the
works than the art-historical approach Yve-Alain has taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Matisse-Picasso exhibitions of the past can't hold a candle to
either of these efforts. There have been only two of consequence,
and both reflected little curatorial vision.
</P>
<P>
   One, in 1938, was a small selection of graphic works by both
artists at the Museum of Modern Art, Boston, which no longer
exists.
</P>
<P>
   The other debuted on Dec. 5, 1945, and continued through Jan.
15, 1946, at the Victoria and Albert Museum in London. At that
time, just after World War II, the museum's collection was still
hidden for safekeeping in the slate mines in Wales. To celebrate
peace and to cover its empty walls, the museum borrowed 30 works
from Matisse and 25 pieces from Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   There was no curatorial premise. Matisse presented a
miniretrospective, with quite a few early works; Picasso showcased
recent images from the war years. Indeed, some sources refer to the
presentation as two simultaneous one-person shows.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Matisse did not welcome the London exhibition with
open arms. As he wrote in his journal on Aug. 3, 1945: ``I'm doing
this propaganda show in London with him. I can imagine the room
with my pictures on one side, and his on the other. It's as if I
were going to co-habit with an epileptic. How quiet I will look.
... ''
</P>
<P>
   Critics gave both artists equal shares of attention, but the
general public clamor focused on Picasso, and it was his work that
packed the galleries with enraged viewers.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
