<HEADER>
A7696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBINSON-COX     02-01 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBINSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robinson: 'I hope it wasn't harmful to team'
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For Falcons fans, Monday was devoted to such questions
as ``What if?'' and ``What comes next?'' and ``Why?'' However, it
was one particular player, not the entire Atlanta Falcons team,
undergoing the usual Super Bowl post-mortem here.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Eugene Robinson was charged with soliciting oral
sex from an undercover police officer, and one day after the
Falcons got squashed in the Super Bowl, questions swirled about the
veteran starting safety.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 35, will have to return to Miami for a
to-be-determined court date, but only if he wants to contest the
charge. The misdemeanor solicitation charge carries a maximum
sentence of 60 days in jail, but most first-time offenders are
offered some combination of community service, which might be
performed elsewhere, a course on the dangers of solicitation, and a
fine, according to Miami police.
</P>
<P>
   After Robinson was arrested Saturday night, initial accounts
said he would have to face the charge in person, probably within 30
days. But a court spokesman said Monday that it could take even
longer for the misdemeanor charge to work its way through the
crowded docket, and that Robinson has other options than to appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to be here,'' said Morton Luckoff,
media-relations director for the 11th Judicial Circuit, which
covers Miami-Dade County. ``His lawyer could just enter a plea on
his behalf . . . if he's not going to fight it.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear what Robinson would do. Emerging from the team
plane in Atlanta Monday with his arm around his wife, Gia, Robinson
proclaimed his innocence. But he said that, on his lawyer's advice,
he could not elaborate. The comment was somewhat less dramatic than
his declaration after the game Sunday that he would be ``found
innocent of this deal, but not righteous by the standards I set for
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Those standards were impressive enough to earn Robinson a
prestigious award from Athletes In Action, an Ohio-based Christian
sports ministry. Now in its 11th year, the Bart Starr Award winner
is decided by a vote of NFL players and is presented during Super
Bowl Week. It is intended to honor a player for ``leadership in the
home, on the field and in the community,'' a group spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson received the award in Miami on Saturday, hours before
his arrest. On Monday, Athletes In Action was negotiating through a
turn of events unprecedented in its 33-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next few days, we'll sort out where we are and what's
going to happen next,'' said Dave Bratton, pro staff liaison for
the organization. ``We're not even near talking about anything like
asking for it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect the impact that Eugene has had on the teams he's
played on over the years,'' Bratton said, adding that the
organization was praying for Robinson, who also played in Seattle
and Green Bay, and his family. ``I loved Dan Reeves' words, when he
said that `We love him unconditionally.''' Most of the Falcons
insisted that the incident had not affected their play in the Super
Bowl, although Robinson didn't sound convinced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was a distraction to my teammates,'' he
said upon arriving in Atlanta. ``I hope it wasn't. The organization
has been tremendous to me _ the fans, my teammates, everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fans, however, felt let down by Robinson's mistake on the
eve of the single biggest game in the 33-year history of the
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   At the team's welcome-home parade in downtown Atlanta, spectator
Alex Solodkin, a Georgia Tech student, watched Robinson go by on a
fire truck. ``Imagine, right before the Super Bowl,'' Solodkin said
. ``You'd think he'd have better sense than that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Callers are angry at him for disappointing his teammates,''
said Chris Dimino, co-host of Atlanta sports talk station WQXI's
``The Bottom Line'' show. ''They're not getting into the moral
aspect of it so much as what he did as a football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Larry Hartstein and Henry Farber contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
