<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERBOWL-AD-COLUMN-A     02-01 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBOWL-AD-COLUMN-ART-2TAKES(1,050)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: FEW SUPER BOWL COMMERCIALS PROVED WORTHY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an old joke about a child who is pleased to find his
bedroom filled with horse manure. As the grinning youngster wades
in with a shovel, he chortles, ``There must be a pony in here
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was only appropriate that a commercial during Super Bowl
XXXIII on Sunday featured a pony, as the prize inside an imaginary
``really big bag'' of Cracker Jack. That's because the spot was one
of a handful of gems buried deep within a morass of sludge.
</P>
<P>
   The joke's scatological image is also appropriate because many
of the 51 paid commercials that ran nationally during the game _ 48
shown one time each, plus 3 repeats _ were replete with bathroom
humor, along with other crude, common, cornball imagery. Perhaps
that's why Super Sunday turned out to be even more of a misnomer
than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a coincidence that this tasteless celebration of the
juvenile and puerile came during the first Super Bowl after the
success of the gross-out comedy ``There's Something About Mary''?
It seemed that advertisers and agencies assumed most of the 127.5
million-plus viewers of the game were either ardent fans of that
film or fraternity pledges, or both, given the number of
commercials dominated by sophomoric slapstick, toilet talk and
gratuitous sex and violence. No wonder two commercials used the
dude anthems ``Bad Boys'' and ``Bad to the Bone'' on the
soundtracks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that also accounted for all the stereotyped presentations
of women. Virtually every female face seen in a commercial belonged
to either a scantily clad sexpot, a demure mother or a dowdy
great-aunt. Except for a minority of advertisers like the AT&AMP;T
Corp., spots about business showed nearly every executive as a man
_ a white man, at that _ while others asserted that the only job a
woman was really qualified for was supermodel.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the sociological implications of such demeaning
portrayals, advertisers copied the Atlanta Falcons in squandering
valuable opportunities to score. The large audience of women
watching the Super Bowl, far bigger than for a regular-season
football game, were denied a chance to see much they could identify
with and respond to.
</P>
<P>
   How sad it was that on the biggest day of the year for
advertising _ when marketers paid an average $1.6 million for each
30 seconds of commercial time, a Super Bowl record _ Madison Avenue
was turned for the most part into a low road. What follows is an
assessment of the commercials that offended as well as some praise
for the few spots that pleased.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN EXPRESS: A spot for the American Express Co. did not
measure up to an entertaining commercial last year that paired
Jerry Seinfeld and Superman. The Seinfeldian search for real life
after ``Seinfeld'' was clever, but the punch line _ the reality was
as contrived as his sitcom _ was a self-referential letdown, as was
the end when the actors went out of character, which evoked the
close of the film ``Get Shorty.'' Agency: Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
Worldwide, owned by WPP Group P.L.C.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE COMPUTER: This salute to and parody of ``2001: A Space
Odyssey,'' depicting the HAL 9000 superbrain pitching for Apple
Computer Inc. provided an intelligent, low-key antidote to the
vulgar nonsense served up elsewhere. It was refreshing to watch a
spot that assumed the viewer's IQ was higher than XXXIII. Agency:
TBWA/Chiat/Day, part of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   BUD LIGHT: Two commercials for Bud Light, brewed by
Anheuser-Busch, disappointed in different ways. One stooped to
cheap bathroom gags when two slacker dudes chose to buy beer rather
than toilet paper. The other showed an attractive woman being
terrified by a mouse and easily impressed by a smarmy man's boasts.
Agency: DDB Needham Chicago, a unit of Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   BUDWEISER: Not since the zoo keeper visited Johnny Carson has
such a menagerie been unleashed on television. All five commercials
for Budweiser beer, another Anheuser-Busch brand, featured animals:
lizards, frogs, Dalmatians, Clydesdales and a lobster that's
boiling mad. The lobster gets two claws up. The swamp creatures
were hilarious as always, though the Three Stooges overtones were
overdone. And it was no surprise to see the dogs squabble like frat
boys. Agencies: Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners, owned by Omnicom,
and DDB Needham Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   CRACKER JACK: The pony commercial, for the snack brand sold by
the Frito-Lay unit of Pepsico Inc., was wonderful. Deft sight gags
and deadpan humor made the spot a worthy successor to clever
Cracker Jack spots by the old Doyle Dane Bernbach agency that
featured the comedian Jack Gilford. Agency: Goodby, Silverstein.
</P>
<P>
   DORITOS: An all-male university is enthralled when the model Ali
Landry sashays through the library in a slinky dress. The students
are huddled under umbrellas when she crunches a barbecue-flavored
Doritos chip, sold by Frito-Lay, and sets off ceiling sprinklers.
Do the books get soaked? Whatever. Dude, this is TV! Agency: BBDO
New York, owned by Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL EXPRESS: Another winning effort from the Federal Express
unit of the FDX Corp. Kudos to the creative talents who schemed to
warn about sending packages with fly-by-night shippers by mixing up
the Stanley Cup with a sack of donkey feed and Cobo Arena in
Detroit with a Bolivian village. Agency: BBDO New York.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL MOTORS: Rare twin successes for the General Motors Corp.
in a setting that has proved daunting in past years. Two energetic,
thoughtful commercials made compelling cases for the modernity of
two GM divisions with fuddy-duddy images, Cadillac and Oldsmobile.
``It's good to be the Cadillac'' is an inspired slogan, though Mel
Brooks (``It's good to be the king'') may demand royalties. And
Olds never looked newer than in the spot advising viewers to ``get
out of neutral and get into drive.'' Agencies: Berlin Cameron &AMP;
Partners, the Leo Burnett Co.
</P>
<P>
   HOTJOBS.COM: A security guard fantasizing about his dream job,
promoting the Internet employment service operated by Hotjobs.com,
encounters one bimbo after another ``working'' as secretaries and
actresses. He even clones them when he thinks about being a
scientist. At the end, he winds up guarding a fancier building,
only proving just how unimaginative he truly is. Agency:
McCann-Erickson Detroit, part of the McCann-Erickson World Group
unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   JUST FOR FEET: A barefoot black Kenyan runner is hunted, drugged
and forced into wearing sneakers by white-hunter types who act as
commando raiders for the Just for Feet footwear chain. Showing a
man treated like an animal is bad enough, but this is appallingly
insensitive. Agency: Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi Rochester, part of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   MASTERCARD: A sweet, charming spot for Mastercard International
uses footage from old cartoons to gently spoof the self-improvement
craze. As Olive Oyl buys a Wonderbra and Droopy Dog gets plastic
surgery, viewers are uplifted. Agency: McCann-Erickson New York.
</P>
<P>
   MONSTER.COM: The Monster.com unit of TMP Worldwide, an Internet
employment service that competes against Hotjobs.com, bested its
rival with a spot that stood out by having children talk as adults
do. ``I want to have a brown nose'' and ``I want to claw my way up
to middle management'' may someday join ``Nothing but net'' as
Super Bowl advertising catch phrases. And how nice that a girl
proclaimed many women are ``paid less for doing the same job.''
Agency: Mullen Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI ONE: A weak ripoff of the cult movie ``Reservoir Dogs''
starts with a gang (men in black suits) and ends with a bang (an
exploding car). The Pepsico spot should have ended with a whimper
because that's what viewers emitted after watching this pointless
extravaganza. Agency: BBDO New York.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPS: A commercial for Philips Electronics North America, a
unit of Royal Philips Electronics NV, demonstrates that sexy does
not have to be sexist. The spot celebrates an imaginative Romeo who
woos Juliet in his own driveway drive-in with a giant-sized Philips
high-definition TV set. Agency: Messner Vetere Berger McNamee
Schmetterer/Euro RSCG, part of Havas Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   7UP: Unfortunately for 7Up, its spot, showing men in black, ran
a quarter after Pepsi One's. Quick, call in the women in white
(i.e., nurses) to administer sedatives to the executives at the 7Up
parent, Cadbury Schweppes PLC Agency: Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA'S SECRET: The subject is objects, women as sex objects,
when tarted-up, dressed-down models parade by to promote an online
lingerie fashion show for the Victoria's Secret unit of Intimate
Brands. The spot brags: ``The Broncos won't be there. The Falcons
won't be there. You won't care.'' Maybe the Year 2000 computer
glitch can strike early. Agency: Resource Marketing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
