A7701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS02-COX     02-01 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New AIDS drugs offer more power, scientists told
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ New anti-HIV drugs that show early promise of being
more powerful, easier to tolerate and more effective against
drug-resistant forms of the virus were presented by top AIDS
researchers Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It's good news, since the 14 HIV medications available are not
capable of curing people and tend to lose effectiveness over time.
Several drugs in development were discussed at the Conference on
Retroviruses and Opportunistic Infections in Chicago, a gathering
of 3,000 AIDS researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs, named for the mechanisms they use to halt HIV's
progress, include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Two new ``protease inhibitors'' _ Agouron Pharmaceuticals'
AG1776 and Abbott Laboratories' ABT-378. Protease inhibitors are
the latest and most potent class of anti-HIV drugs, thought to be
responsible for drops in AIDS deaths since their introduction in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Three in a class of drugs known as ``non-nucleoside reverse
transcriptase inhibitors'' _ Agouron's AG1549 and DuPont
Pharmaceuticals' DMP 961 and DMP 963; and
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  One ``nucleoside analogue'' _ FTC _ created by Triangle
Pharmaceuticals. Other drugs in this class include AZT, the first
AIDS drug.
</P>
<P>
   Early test results in humans and laboratories showed these new
drugs to be effective. But the results are preliminary; the drugs
have not been tested in large numbers of patients and it could take
months or years before they gain federal approval for wider use.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS specialists also discussed new classes of HIV drugs that
will attack entirely different parts of the virus' replication
process.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, many AIDS doctors say it is critical to make the
most of the current arsenal of medication.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists agree the key to long-term HIV suppression is to
swiftly reduce the amount of virus in the blood to undetectable
levels. Because protease inhibitors do this in many patients, they
often are a standard element of drug therapy. But the drugs aren't
always effective.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Dr. Stefano Vella, president-elect of the
International AIDS Society, estimated that under the best
circumstances, a patient would have to take medication for 23 years
to eliminate the AIDS virus from the body. That's far longer than
original estimates, made just a few years ago, of three to five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence, unfortunately, that the potency of current
(drug) regimens is insufficient,'' said Vella. He noted that the
drugs eventually fail for a number of reasons, including HIV's
ability to mutate into drug-resistant forms.
</P>
<P>
   To solve this problem, new drugs not only must be more potent,
but should be easier to tolerate and less complicated to take. Side
effects and complex dosing schedules can cause some patients to
miss doses, which in turn can lead to drug resistance.
</P>
<P>
   New drugs also must dodge cross-resistance, known to affect all
three classes of HIV drugs. This is vital for the continued
treatment of people with HIV who already have undergone drug
therapy and probably have developed resistance, Vella said.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
