<HEADER>
A7702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSTAND02-COX     02-01 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsweek: Clinton, GOP, media may all be losers
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The end is near, and we're not talking about the millennium.
After what seems like a decade of investigations and testimony, the
impeachment trial of William Jefferson Clinton is all over but the
shouting. No one _ not even the GOP _ expects the president to be
removed, says Newsweek ($3.50). So why is this still going on?
Newsweek staffers Evan Thomas and Mark Hosenball contend it's all
about posturing and saving face with the right-wing base of the
Republican Party. ``The only real issue is who will come out
looking worse: the president for seducing an intern and trying to
cover it up; the Republicans for their rabid insistence on
prolonging the scandal; the media for celebrating it, or _ most
likely _ all of the above.'' In an accompanying essay, Jonathan
Alter suggests the scandal will affect everything from the legal
system (the power of prosecutors may be weakened) to the children
(young people's attitude toward politics likely will become more
cynical).
</P>
<P>
   Time ($2.95), meanwhile, makes no mention of the impeachment
trial on its cover. Instead, the magazine devotes a large chunk of
its space (12 pages) to the impact hip-hop and rap have had on
American culture. Once considered a fad, rap celebrated its 20th
anniversary by outselling country music _ America's previously
top-selling format. More than 81 million rap CDs and tapes sold in
1998, compared with 72 million for country. At the top of the heap
is Lauryn Hill, who received 10 Grammy nominations this year.
</P>
<P>
   GENDER GAP: U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.95) visits American
campuses and leaves wondering where the boys are. At the University
of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, women make up 60 percent of the
student body. Other colleges around the country report similar
figures. Apparently males are opting for fast cash in a booming
economy where air-conditioning maintenance workers earn starting
salaries of $30,000. Females are taking the long view, the magazine
says, entering colleges with better grades and a clearer sense of
goals.
</P>
<P>
   JUVENILE JUSTICE: When two Chicago boys, ages 7 and 8, were
arrested and charged with murder in the death of 11-year-old Ryan
Harris last summer, their confessions shocked the country. What is
more shocking, writes Alex Kotlowitz in The New Yorker ($3), is how
their rights were violated. The charges were later dropped after
new evidence was found, but Kotlowitz notes that the treatment of
the two Chicago youths ``shows just how deeply the special
protections for children have eroded.''
</P>
<P>
   BREASTS AND TERRORISTS: The first thing you notice about the
February Esquire ($3) is the cover. I mean really notice. Esquire,
like Maxim and Gear and Playboy and Penthouse and even Vanity Fair,
has learned that putting a sexy, sometimes semi-clad woman on the
cover boosts sales. Pamela Lee Anderson is the cover girl this
month as an example of the triumph of cleavage in our culture.
Beyond the cover story, though, is a serious interview with Osama
bin Laden, the avowed enemy of the United States who was the target
of a bombing raid in the midst of President Clinton's impeachment
woes. ABC news correspondent John Miller reports that bin Laden has
no intention of wavering in his crusade to get the United States
out of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING RICH: If you want to make lucrative investments, P.O.V.
($2.95) suggests you forget about Internet stocks and blue-chip
companies and try something creative. Some investors have reaped
financial rewards from old movie posters, vintage musical
instruments and wine. One investor sold a bottle of 1995 Bryant
Family Cabernet Sauvignon for $400 two months after he bought it
for $100. And one couple netted $600,000 after an $80,000
investment in South American llamas.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
