A7703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-COLUMN02-COX     02-01 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Something lost in era of computer keyboards
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Over the weekend a package arrived from a friend in
California, a thick manila envelope stuffed with sections from a
newspaper. At the bottom was a business card on which she had
written, ``Get e-mail and let's be pen pals.''
</P>
<P>
   An odd thought: pen pals without pens.
</P>
<P>
   The words were in black ink. Someone like Marion Hood might have
been able to guess the type of pen that was used. From the flow of
the ink I thought it looked like a Sanford, medium point. The
script was clear and uncomplicated, with no exaggerated loops or
slants and a nice ease to the way the lowercase ``L'' in ``let's''
made a rightward turn at the bottom and became a lowercase ``E.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone notices these things. Two kinds of people who do
are the hopelessly illegible like myself, trying out cursive styles
every so often like a baseball player experimenting with a new
batting stance, and a calligraphist like Marion Hood.
</P>
<P>
   She is 36 years old, with long, straight brown hair, an open,
friendly face and an informality that suggests something of the
countercultural. She came to Atlanta from Cocoa Beach, Fla., 13
years ago with her boyfriend, Richard Johnson, and they're still
together. ``I had a more radical look back then,'' she says. ``I
had spiky hair and Rich had a beard.'' After 13 years she still
calls him ``my sweetheart.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida she had been lettering signs for a surf shop, the
kind of work someone like her might find in a beach town. ``I
churned out signs like you wouldn't believe,'' she says. Then, one
night, the owner of the shop threw a party and something not
entirely clear happened and his last known whereabouts was
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Hood and Rich Johnson wanted a change, and Atlanta ``was
the biggest town outside Florida.'' For 12 years she's been selling
pens _ fountain, felt-tip, ballpoint, roller-ball _ at Binders Art
Supply in Sandy Springs (Ga.), explaining how a roller-ball pen is
different from a retractable ballpoint and why left-handers _ like
me _ are congenitally inept with fountain pens (our angle is
wrong).
</P>
<P>
   It might seem like being an expert in buggy whips at the dawn of
the auto age. Even pen pals have resorted to e-mail. But if the
police were to frisk people on the street at random, 90 would have
a pen on them and many would have several. Nothing is more taken
for granted, and nothing more relied on for expressing so many
sides of ourselves, from idle jottings to utilitarian notations to
our innermost thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't take seriously the business that didn't have its
own stationery. But there are letters that would leave you cold if
they'd been downloaded from the computer, the pixels on the screen
translated into perfectly horizontal lines of uniform lettering. I
was trying to make this obvious point in a talk at a college last
year and a young woman, 20 years old, studying computer science,
said what's the difference _ it's just the words, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   I let it go without a response. But I'd been thinking of my
father's handwriting, its distinctive ``J's'' and ``M's'' and
``S's'' imprinted on my mind at an age before I could have recited
the parts of speech. Indelible after so many years, it is somehow
his voice on paper, speaking to me across decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different medium when you use a pen,'' Hood says. ``I
think you will say things in a different way. ``
</P>
<P>
   On a computer screen you can rewrite endlessly, recasting your
motives and actions as you recast your sentences. You can paint
exactly the picture you want. But precision comes at the cost of
spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a pen you're going to more trouble,'' as Hood says.
``First you have to have the paper and then you have to write it by
hand. Then you have to fold the paper and put it in an envelope.
And you have to seal the envelope. Then you have to mail it, and
you have to put a stamp on it, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, there's something to be said for doing all that.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something to be said for writing at all, but the pen
_whether a $1,500 Montegrappa or a drugstore Uni-ball (my current
favorite) _ is a kind of high fidelity of the written word, what
the CD is to the song. Without it our words might be clear as a
bell, but the voice behind them grows faint and disembodied. Most
people know it, which is why they save certain words for pen and
paper.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that most of us are pen pals bound to computer
and keyboard, taping out words, shaping them into paragraphs and
something resembling consecutive thought. It is the quickness in
the blood that first gave rise to them that has been lost,
sometimes forever.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
