<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7707 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-PITCHERS-C     02-01 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PITCHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves pitchers armed for Camp Leo
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Atlanta mired in post-Super Bowl doldrums and
rainy Monday blues, there came some hope. Deep in the bowels of
Turner Field, Braves baseball began.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Nine pitchers congregated Monday morning, with another handful
expected to join them today, to open the eighth edition of ``Camp
Leo,'' the two-week pre-spring training program with Braves
pitching coach Leo Mazzone.
</P>
<P>
   Still more than two weeks away from the early reporting dates of
spring training, Tom Glavine was back on the mound for the first
time since the Braves season ended Oct. 14 in a 5-0 NLCS loss to
the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   This trip to the mound was indoors, thanks to the weather, and
lasted only 10 minutes, thanks to the date. But both felt good for
Glavine, who between ``appearances'' picked up another Cy Young
Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to get going again,'' Glavine said. ``This is the
time of year everybody gets itchy to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   In Glavine and Kevin Millwood, two-fifths of the starting
rotation reported to Camp Leo on Monday. Rookie Bruce Chen, who
will take a stab as the Braves fifth starter, was not in town yet
from Panama. Both he and John Smoltz are expected to arrive today.
Greg Maddux won't be joining the team until spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Among the others getting in work Monday were relievers Kerry
Ligtenberg, John Rocker and Mike Cather, recently acquired Mike
Remlinger, rookies Derrin Ebert and Micah Bowie and non-roster
invitee Kevin McGlinchy. Javy Lopez came to do some catching.
</P>
<P>
   Due shortly, along with Chen and Smoltz, are Mark Wohlers,
Odalis Perez, and Rudy Seanez.
</P>
<P>
   Former Braves starter Denny Neagle was back at Turner Field on
Monday, but he won't stick around past Wednesday. His new job is
with the Reds, compliments of the trade for Bret Boone and
Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood that Chen, 21, will move into the fifth spot,
makes Atlanta's rotation a bit younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Chen's) not a September call-up anymore,'' Glavine said.
``He's part of the team. But that's one of things about him. He
seems like he can handle (some pressure). He has a lot of poise and
control for not having very much experience. But you'll see a
difference. The first time around seeing teams, as a pitcher you
have a little bit of an edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, who takes over the fourth spot in the rotation, is 12
pounds lighter and a newlywed. He also comes in fresh off a 17-win
season in his first full year in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I belong here more, I guess,'' said Millwood, 24.
``This year a little bit more will be riding on me. I like it. I
like to have a little more pressure. It makes it exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger is another possible starter. The 32-year-old moved
into the Reds starting rotation late in the 1997 season and started
28 games in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be a big addition,'' Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
