<SLUG> BC-TEN-PRO-NOTES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INSIDE PRO TENNIS: Women's game most intriguing
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't necessarily the kind of publicity the WTA wanted, but
the Martina Hingis-Amelie Mauresmo final and feud at the Australian
Open provided the melodrama that is making women's tennis more
appealing than the men's game lately.
</P>
<P>
   The Yevgeny Kafelnikov-Thomas Enqvist final was simply a matchup
of good players. The women's final had intrigue of a different
sort, and the unfortunate rift between Mauresmo and Hingis probably
won't heal as long as Hingis denies commenting to Swiss reporters
in German, ``She's here with a woman; she's half-man.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's edition of L'Equipe, the leading sports daily in
Paris, Mauresmo says she was touched by a note of apology from
Lindsay Davenport, who said Mauresmo ``played like a man'' in their
semifinal, won by Mauresmo. The next day, Davenport blasted the
media for taking the remark out of context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, you guys love to write the worst line possible,
and unfortunately, you have hurt a very nice girl,'' Davenport
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mauresmo also told L'Equipe that Hingis' remarks were ``an
unpleasant joke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps she just said it for a laugh, without thinking, but
the next day (in the final) she wasn't very clear either in saying
that I played like a man,'' Mauresmo said. ``It was stupid of
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unwanted attention, Mauresmo said she doesn't regret
acknowledging publicly that she is a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel liberated, and it's shown in my game,'' she said.
``There are dozens of other players like me who say nothing.
They're often ill at ease and even unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov gets his due
</P>
<P>
   It always annoyed Kafelnikov that the media labeled him an
underachiever because he'd hadn't won a Grand Slam title since the
1996 French Open. Now, with the Australian title, the Russian is
one of just five active players with two major championships. The
others are Pete Sampras, Andre Agassi, Jim Courier and Patrick
Rafter. Kafelnikov's ranking is back up to a career-high No. 3.
Kafelnikov has led the ATP Tour in matches played in four of the
past five years. He played 150 last year, counting singles and
doubles. Meanwhile, Sampras played 78 and pulled out of the
Australian because of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly. . .
</P>
<P>
   Five players could have overtaken Sampras as the No. 1 player by
reaching the men's final. The list includes Marcelo Rios (withdrew
injured), Carlos Moya (first round), Alex Corretja (second), Rafter
(third) and Agassi (fourth).
</P>
<P>
   Todd Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
