<SLUG> BC-NEES-EASTERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEES TO BUY EASTERN UTILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ New England Electric System will buy Eastern Utilities
Associates for about $634 million in cash, the latest merger driven
by the deregulation of the regional power industry.
</P>
<P>
   NEES will also assume roughly $400 million in Eastern debt. By
purchasing Eastern's service territories in Brockton and Fall
River, NEES will increase its lead as the largest electric utility
in Massachusetts. It will also become the sole power-distributor in
Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also represents expansion for National Grid Group PLC,
the British Utility that is in the process of buying NEES, based in
Westborough, Mass. for about $4.6 billion in cash and debt.
</P>
<P>
   If the two purchases are completed by early 2000, as expected,
they will establish National Grid as a key player in the
Northeastern power market. They will also give National Grid
influence over New England's power-transmission network.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Sergel, NEES president and chief executive officer, said
the deal fits the expasion strategy set out when he agreed to sell
his company to National Grid last December. Sergel said the British
firm ``indicated they wanted to use the acquisition of NEES as a
beachhead for further acquisitions, and certainly this demonstrates
they have taken a further step.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Pardus, chairman and chief executive of Eastern, said a
sale was inevitable following steps to deregulate the electric
industry in New England. With just 300,000, Eastern would have been
at a disadvantage in competing with larger rivals who are now able
to sell new services in its home territory of southeastern
Massachusetts and parts of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we either had to get bigger or look for somebody'' to
partner with, Pardus said. Given Eastern's size, he said, ``It
doesn't make sense for us to stay independent.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal follows several other high-profile agreements as
deregulation enables consumers to choose electric suppliers much as
they now choose long-distance telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, BEC Energy, parent of Boston Edison, agrees to
buy Commonwealth Energy System for $1.55 billion in cash, stock and
debt. In 1997, NEES agreed to sell its power plants to a unit of
California-based PG&AMP;E Corp. BEC and NEES have also held merger
discussions, which so far have been fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Like other analysts, utilities specialist Phil Giudice of Mercer
Management Consulting in Lexington expects further consolidation as
fragmented Northeastern power companies seek economies of scale
needed for more effective marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry model is that there will be dominant distribution
companies in large regions,'' Guidice said. The latest NEES deal,
he said, ``only reinforces that projection.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, NEES will pay $31 for each of
Eastern's 20.4 million outstanding shares. That represents a 5
percent premium over their Friday closing price of $29 9/16. The
shares traded around $25 apiece in early December, before rising on
rumors that National Grid was interested in buying the company.
</P>
<P>
   NEES said it would partly finance the deal with some of the $358
million in cash on its books. The remainder of the deal will be
financed through debt, though NEES hasn't yet determined the exact
figures. NEES has about $1.1 billion in debt today.
</P>
<P>
   Following the merger, NEES said it expects to eliminate through
voluntary buyouts about 250 jobs out of a total combined workforce
of 4,100. NEES will emerge with about 1.6 million customers,
100,000 less than New England's largest distribution company,
Connecticut-based Northeast Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Pardus said he will retire following the completion of the
agreement, along with Eastern chief operating officer John Stevens.
The company's executive vice president, Robert Powderly, will
become president of a NEES support-services unit.
</P>
<P>
   Formally, NEES' purchase of Eastern isn't related to its
National Grid agreements. But in an interview Monday David Jones,
the London company's Group Chief Executive, praised the purchase
and added that ``If it weren't done through NEES, then it could be
a more complicated situation'' because of extra regulatory
approvals that would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   The purchases of NEES and Eastern, based in Boston, will give
National Grid control over a significant portion of New England's
power-transmission system. In the United Kingdom, the publicly
traded National Grid was created in 1990 to operate transmission
wires on a for-profit basis.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in NEES rose 1/16 to $49 apiece in New York Stock
Exchange trading Monday. Eastern shares fell 15/16 to close at $28
5/8 on the same exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
