<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7722 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      02-01 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE BENEFITS IN CLINTON'S BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few choices better define politicians than the two they make in
their budgets: where to get tax dollars and how to spend them.
President Clinton's budget for the coming fiscal year shows him to
be _ not surprisingly _ a crowd-pleaser who offers a little
something for everyone but not a lot of any one thing to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   For all the Repubicans' complaints that Clinton's $1.77 trillion
budget presages a return to the days of big government, it is
actually quite conservative given the boom times. It projects an
increase in gross domestic product for next year of just 2 percent
when actual increases were 3.9 percent in 1998. It increases
government spending overall by $39 billion _ 2.3 percent _ while
projecting a surplus of $117 billion even after all the program
increases are accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would get the money mostly from roaring growth in the
economy but also from a 55-cents-a-pack increase in the cigarette
tax, perhaps the only assessment that can be raised without a
special-interest outcry, since tobacco manufacturers can pass much
of the increase along to their captured market.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposes $36 billion in tax relief over five years _ not
the 10 percent across the board proposed by Republicans but small
gestures to unassailably ``deserving'' constituencies: the elderly,
stay-at-home parents, disabled workers. The budget directs 62
percent of surpluses over 15 years to shoring up Social Security.
In all, it is a spending plan aligned more with the ant than the
grasshopper.
</P>
<P>
   The budget runs to thousands of pages. But at first glance three
areas deserve special mention:
</P>
<P>
   --The administration has taken note of New England's most
troubled economic sector: its battered fishing industry. The budget
offers $92 million in direct aid and loan guarantees to cope with
declining stocks of ground fish and scallops.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is a combination of buyouts of surplus fishing
boats and scallopers ($15 million and $40 million respectively);
refitting of craft for more plentiful species like herring and
mackerel; job retraining; and scientific projects to improve
fisheries management and help replenish stocks.
</P>
<P>
   They are realistic because they require endorsement by the
industry itself and because the loan portion of the program _
totaling $44 million _ will require repayment. They are wisely
designed to cushion the effects of severe cutbacks in key areas
like the Gulf of Maine cod fishery to head off those who might
evade restrictions designed to allow stock recovery.
</P>
<P>
   --Last month Vice President Gore previewed the administration's
``liveability agenda'' _ help for communities overwhelmed by the
ravages of sprawl. The outlines of the agenda is taking shape for
New England.
</P>
<P>
   According to John Devillars, regional director of the
Environment Protection Agency, Clinton's budget includes $1.5
million to help communities set up ``Smartgrowth'' initiatives to
plan for future development, to train citizen zoning boards in
communities without professional growth planners, and to clean up
and reuse contaminated urban brownfields.
</P>
<P>
   Millions more will be available to communities competing for
grants. Given that New England is losing 1,200 acres a week to
development and that the region's ratio of land lost to population
gained is three times the national average, the smartgrowth plan
should have plenty of takers.
</P>
<P>
   --Clinton's budget also invests in stabilizing international
economies, especially in Central America, the Caribbean, and
Colombia, which have endured devastating natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch's deluge of mud, water, and death set Central
America back by decades. But even before the storm, the region was
drowning in debt. In 1998 Nicaragua owed $6.1 billion to a host of
creditors, including the United States, Germany, and the
International Monetary Fund. In 1997 Honduras spent a third of its
revenues _ some $410 million _ on debts. It owed $4.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   After Mitch, the international community rushed in with
humanitarian aid. But agencies such as Oxfam America and others
sounded the alarm that devastated countries couldn't seriously hope
to rebuild schools, houses, hospitals, and roads unless they had
debt relief.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget offers some relief, with $120 million in debt
forgiveness, $168 million for arrears payments, and $1.2 billion in
current commitments to multilateral development banks, which
provide assistance to poor countries around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
