<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVADO-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Excluding charges, Avado's income up
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Madison, Ga.-based Avado Brands Inc. said Monday
operating income rose 154 percent for the fourth quarter, propelled
by sales at its four core restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Avado owns the Don Pablo's Mexican Kitchen, Hops Restaurant Bar
and Brewery, McCormick &AMP; Schmick's and Canyon Cafe eateries.
</P>
<P>
   Including charges, however, the company reported a net loss of
$1.6 million, or 5 cents a share for the quarter ended Jan. 3,
compared with $296,000, or 1 cent, for the same quarter a year ago.
The loss included a $2.9 million one-time charge related to staff
reductions and a $5.8 million loss on the disposal of assets, both
related to the divestiture of its Applebee's business. Avado, which
last year changed its named from Apple South, is selling off its
biggest and most profitable division, Applebee's Neighborhood Grill
&AMP; Bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great business, but that's been clouded over the
last year because we're disposing of one of our businesses, which
represents about half of overall sales,'' said Tom E. DuPree Jr.,
chairman and chief executive officer of Avado. ``It's been a cloudy
story for about 14 months.''
</P>
<P>
   The company reported net operating income of $12.7 million for
the fourth quarter, up from $5 million for the same period a year
earlier. Sales were $176.7 million, compared with $218.2 million.
Lower revenue reflected decreasing contributions from Applebee's.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, the company reported revenue of $862.7 million, up
from $808.3 million a year earlier. Net income was $66.3 million,
or $1.62 a share, compared with $28.4 million, or 73 cents a share.
Operating income for the core brands was $44.6 million, compared
with pro forma operating income of $27.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Barish, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens in
San Francisco, said the company is getting all the concepts moving
in the right direction ``and that would generate operating results
in 1999 that would seem to merit a much higher stock price,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
