<HEADER>
A7725 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-MOTHER-BOS &LR;      02-01 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATMENT OF MOTHERS IN LABOR CUTS AIDS IN BABIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ On-the-spot drug treatment of AIDS virus-infected
women in labor substantially lowers the risk their babies will be
infected, according to a long-awaited, three-country African study
unveiled here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Immediate treatment of the women followed by a week of
double-drug antiviral pills for both mothers and infants cut the
risk of mother-to-child transmission by 37 percent, according to
Dr. Joseph Saba of UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS agency.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time such a brief course of antiviral drugs
has been shown to lower infant infections substantially, a finding
with large practical implications for resource-strapped African
nations where each day more than 1,400 babies are born infected
with the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In developing countries many women do not seek prenatal
care,'' Saba said at the Sixth Conference on Retroviruses here.
``We now know we can make a difference for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year a Thailand study showed that mother-child HIV
transmission could be cut in half by drug treatment before, during,
and after childbirth, a finding that was replicated by the new
African study. But that regimen requires five weeks, beginning at
the 36th week of pregnancy, and it costs about $80 for the drug
alone, not counting HIV testing, counseling, and prenatal care.
</P>
<P>
   The briefer treatment, beginning during labor, will cost perhaps
one-fifth of that, Saba indicated, bringing it within reach of
millions more women in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be cost-effective,'' Saba said. He added that Glaxo
Wellcome Pharmaceuticals, which makes the two-drug pill called
Combivir used in the study, has promised to discount its price to
meet the needs of poor nations in sub-Saharan nations where HIV
rates are the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of these short-regimen studies, pregnant women will have
access to this treatment for the first time,'' said Dr. Buis Okong
of Uganda, one of the three nations that hosted the study of 1,326
pregnant women. The others were South Africa and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers hope that the new findings will persuade South
Africa's health minister, Dr. Nkosazana Zuma, to allow pilot
projects in that country to test the economic, medical, and social
feasibility of the new regimen. Zuma last year blocked plans to
mount pilot trials of the five-week regimen, partly for reasons of
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minister Zuma was very open in listening to these results,''
said Saba, who presented them last Thursday to Zuma's deputy and
plans to return there next week. ``The dialogue with (Zuma) is not
closed.''
</P>
<P>
   One unresolved issue is the risk to infants who breastfeed in
the months after the one-week postnatal antiviral treatment has
ended, since HIV can be transmitted through breast milk. Saba noted
that a French group will present evidence here Wednesday from
African studies in Ivory Coast and Burkina Faso that a short course
of the drug zidovudine, similar to the UNAIDS study, reduces infant
infections by 31 percent, even though mothers subsequently
breast-fed.
</P>
<P>
   Okong and Saba said the new results justify the controversial
UN-sponsored study, which randomly assigned some HIV-infected women
to receive placebos, or dummy pills, in order to provide a
comparison with two groups who received antiviral regimens of
differing duration.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the studies consigned some infants to certain HIV
infection, a study design that would not be tolerated in developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a placebo group we would have been totally misled,''
Saba said. ``Now we can say with a peaceful mind that we made the
right choice.'' No more placebo trials with pregnant HIV-infected
women are under way or planned.
</P>
<P>
   The drug treatment used in the United States and Europe begins
earlier and is continued longer following delivery, but it costs
about $700 for the medication alone. Since 1994, it has reduced
infections among infants born to HIV-infected women from as high as
27 percent to as low as 3 percent in some states, Dr. Lynne
Mofenson of the National Institute of Child Health and Human
Development reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nearly 7,000 American infants born each year to
HIV-infected mothers, nearly 90 percent receive the preventive drug
regimen, resulting in a 79 percent drop in the nation's annual
number of infant AIDS cases. About 500 HIV-infected babies are born
annually in this country, a toll that Mofenson said could
``theoretically'' be reduced to zero, ``but we have a long way to
go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
