<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL IS SIXTH-MOST WATCHED TV PROGRAM IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was unspectacular.
</P>
<P>
   It lacked a cavalcade of great plays.
</P>
<P>
   It featured one great team and one overwhelmed one.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Super Bowl XXXIII lured 127.5 million viewers to Fox, making
Denver's 34-19 defeat of Atlanta the sixth-most-watched program in
TV history.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 40.2 national Nielsen rating represents a nearly 10
percent tumble from the 44.5 rating for last year's much better
game, making it the seventh-lowest-rated Super Bowl ever and the
second-lowest-rated Super Bowl of the decade, sneaking in front of
the 39.0 for San Francisco's 55-10 thrashing of Denver in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the 40s, we're the sixth-most-watched program in
history,'' said Vince Wladika, a spokesman for Fox Sports.
``Whether it's the second lowest of the 90s, we don't care.
Advertisers care about total audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox clearly got what it desired for the first Super Bowl of its
$550 million-a-year National Football League TV contract. It
commandeered the airwaves from 11 a.m. to 10:30 p.m., Eastern time,
with pre-game programming, the game and a post-game show.
</P>
<P>
   Things started off a bit puny, with a 2.1 rating for the 11 a.m.
``Kickoff Show'' and a 2.7 for the lackluster ``Hard Core
Football.'' Keith Olbermann's too cutesy, behind-the-scenes
travelogue at noon logged in with a 4.1, followed by John Madden's
90-minute All-Millennium All-Madden Team, which rated a 5.9.
</P>
<P>
   The four-hour pre-game show weighed in with a 12.3. Although the
game was far from memorable, viewers did not abandon it in droves
for other network fare, like ``Clueless'' on NBC, ``Touched by An
Angel'' on CBS, or the serial-murderer marathon of programs on The
History Channel.
</P>
<P>
   After peaking at a 41.5 between 7 and 7:30 p.m., the game's
rating slid, along with competitive interest, by 8 percent to a
38.1 by game's end, from 9:30 to 9:50. The halftime, with a 39.4,
outrated the finale. (Each national rating point equals 994,000
television households.)
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the home markets were the most rabid viewers. In
Atlanta, the game registered a 58.2 rating, in Denver, a 51.6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
