   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-BUDGET (Houston) _ The United States has dropped plans to
funnel $600 million to the Russians over the next six years to
bolster their participation in the international space station.
NASA Administrator Daniel Goldin says the space agency deems that
option a disincentive for now to a Russian role in the project. By
MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL-ADVICE (Austin, Texas) _ In what may be the strongest
action taken by a bar association group trying to stop
consumer-helpful software, U.S. District Judge Barefoot Sanders
orders sales of Quicken's ``Family Lawyer'' stopped in Texas. By
POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-ATHEIST (San Antonio) _ Texas authorities have
identified a body found more than three years ago as that of Danny
Fry, a Florida man who may have played a role in the baffling
disappearance of atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ A new granite headstone was
placed on the grave of James Byrd Jr. by a national ethnic
coalition. The mother of the slain man says she hasn't forgiven
anybody because no one has asked her forgiveness, adding that it
isn't fair murder defendant William King can hug his son in court
while she can only visit hers in the cemetery. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-SHOOTINGS (Houston) _ Several controversial police
killings have rekindled the stereotype of the trigger-happy Houston
cop. Yet despite the recent incidents, the number of police
officers involved in fatal shootings in the city is well below that
of the late 1980s and early '90s. By S.K. BARDWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ New rules that shield conversations
between accountants and their customers sound like the
attorney-client privilege, which protects certain communications
between a lawyer and client, but they're not as broad. While the
new Internal Revenue Service rules are similar, there are lots of
loopholes in the privilege. By PAMELA YIP. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLICE (Nuevo Laredo, Mexico) _ Moctezuma Rodriguez has
gone from guarding bandits in Las Vegas to riding herd over this
border city's scandal-plagued police force. Since becoming chief of
police on Jan. 1, Rodriguez has fired 120 patrol officers and six
of his commanders in a wide-ranging house-cleaning. By DANE
SCHILLER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ For months, politicians have been
publicly counting nails in the coffin of the independent counsel
law. There are now so many lid-fasteners that the law is virtually
certain to be buried without tears in June, when the statute
lapses. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BRONCOS (Miami) _ Inevitably, the Denver Broncos will talk
of a ``three-peat'' and of making NFL history next season. But all
talk is premature until John Elway decides whether he will retire
or not. In the meantime, the Broncos and Elway are savoring the
moment. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-CARR (Houston) _ He is known, not so affectionately, as
``The Big Dog.'' But Antoine Carr, a longtime nemesis of the
Houston Rockets who has joined the team this year as a backup
center, is anything but a dog on the basketball court. And the
Rockets are hoping the 15-year veteran who has been to the last two
NBA Finals can help lead Houston back to the title series. By
JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
