<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7732 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-TIMEWARNER-COX     02-01 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TIMEWARNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T, Time Warner enter cable-phone service deal
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Time Warner said Monday that long distance carrier
AT&AMP;T will provide local telephone service to its cable subscribers,
a deal that may prove a bellwether for the telecommunications
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The deal creates yet another competitor to Baby Bells such as
BellSouth Corp. and marks a breakthrough for both Time Warner and
AT&AMP;T, which have been negotiating since the fall. It may also
affect the strategies of other major cable operators, including
MediaOne and Atlanta-based Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has been trying for months to persuade MediaOne and Cox
Communications to join in a partnership to let it use their systems
to offer local telephone service. Both cable operators now offer
that service to tens of thousands of customers nationwide,
including MediaOne service in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For Cox Communications and MediaOne, AT&AMP;T's offer has been
tempting, given the recognition of its brand name. But both Cox
Communications and MediaOne have resisted AT&AMP;T's entreaties so far,
because the long distance carrier wants too much control over their
fledgling telephone operations.
</P>
<P>
   While no deal appears imminent, AT&AMP;T and Cox Communications
continue to talk. ``Cox Communications remains open-minded to
exploring a relationship with AT&AMP;T,'' said Cox Communications
president and chief executive Jim Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is controlled by Cox Enterprises Inc., which
also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Few observers, though, expect a deal between AT&AMP;T and Cox
Communications or MediaOne anytime soon, if ever. ``So far MediaOne
and Cox Communications have wanted to maintain control,'' says
Yankee Group media analyst Bruce Leichtman. ``That's neither right
nor wrong. The question is, will they rethink their position after
this deal?''
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T deal with Time Warner is yet another milestone in the
cable industry's push to capture some of the $90 billion market for
local telephone service. This partnership will eventually end up
competing against BellSouth in the northwest corner of metro
Atlanta where Time Warner owns a cable system.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, of course, wants to be able to offer long-distance
service like AT&AMP;T. So far, though, it has been blocked by
government regulators, who have supported AT&AMP;T's argument that the
Baby Bells have not opened local service up to competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (AT&AMP;T) are trying to put together something so they can
offer one-stop shopping to their customers while they (government
regulators) are blocking us from offering one-stop shopping to our
customers,'' says BellSouth spokesman Bill McCloskey. ``That
doesn't seem fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In striking a deal with AT&AMP;T, Time Warner surrendered control of
its tiny telephone service to the long-distance carrier. AT&AMP;T will
own 77.5 percent of a joint partnership set up to offer local
service to Time Warner subscribers, which number 12.6 million in 33
states. That number includes about 70,000 customers in Cobb and
Cherokee counties.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, AT&AMP;T would provide and market the
telephone service. Time Warner would provide the database of
customers and the cable lines to reach them.
</P>
<P>
   What was announced Monday was a tentative deal and now the two
companies have to hammer out the specifics. They hope to name two
pilot cities by the end of the year and then roll out AT&AMP;T-branded
telephone service across all Time Warner systems, including metro
Atlanta, by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based media conglomerate, which also owns
Atlanta-based Turner Broadcasting, has been steadily upgrading its
systems to handle the two-digital traffic necessary for local
telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   That upgrade is under way in the company's system in northwest
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents an opportunity to get a substantial return on
our (cable) plant,'' Gerald Levin, Time Warner's Chairman said last
fall when first discussing negotiations with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, AT&AMP;T has agreed to pay Time Warner $15 for every home
along its cable system ready to receive local telephone service.
Those payments, delivered in two annual installments, are expected
to total $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership is also a potential bonanza for AT&AMP;T. With the
addition of Time Warner's cable systems, AT&AMP;T will be able to offer
local telephone service to 40 percent of all U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is in the process of buying the Tele-Communications Inc.
and plans to offer its subscribers local telephone service. Time
Warner and TCI are the first and second largest cable operators,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the number of cable TV telephone customers is small,
around 100,000 nationwide. But that number is expected to reach 2.6
million within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   That still represents a tiny potion of the national market for
local telephone service but even a small slice of it could generate
a healthy return for cable operators. Says the Yankee Group's
Leichtman, ``The cable industry knows that this is a market in
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
