<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7737 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-TIME-BOS &LR;      02-01 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-TIME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T DEAL WITH TIME WARNER ENHANCES LOCAL SERVICE OPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long-distance giant AT&AMP;T Corp. accelerated its return to local
phone service Monday by announcing a joint venture with Time Warner
Inc. that will use the cable company's wires to provide local phone
service to residential and small-business customers in 33 states.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with AT&AMP;T's imminent $48 billion purchase of cable giant
Tele-Communications Inc., the Time Warner deal goes a long way
toward bringing AT&AMP;T full circle from the day 15 years ago when it
was banished from the local phone market by the break-up of the
Bell system.
</P>
<P>
   The deals with the nation's two largest cable companies would
give AT&AMP;T potential access to 40 percent of the nation's households
and company officials say that percentage will grow to more than 60
percent as more joint ventures are announced.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's return to the local phone market follows a very different
technological path from the one it used when it exited that market
on Jan. 1, 1984. AT&AMP;T this time will provide local service over
cable wires rather than telephone wires, but the goal is the same:
to give customers all the telecommunications services they want on
one bill.
</P>
<P>
   C. Michael Armstrong, chairman and chief executive officer of
AT&AMP;T, sounded almost cocky in predicting his company, within three
to four years, would sign up a fourth of the 20 million homes and
businesses that Time Warner's wires currently pass.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said the new joint venture will have a positive cash
flow and generate $4 billion in new revenues within three years,
largely because it will offer more services than Bell Atlantic and
other local phone companies at cost savings of 20 to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about offering more and costing less,''
Armstrong said. He added later: ``Why would a consumer not want an
AT&AMP;T-Time Warner offering?''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted cautiously to the joint venture. AT&AMP;T's
stock went up 2 13/16 while Time Warner's dropped 3/16. One of the
chief targets of the joint venture, Bell Atlantic, said the
announcement shows how the marketplace is outpacing a regulatory
structure that until now has barred it from offering long-distance
phone service in head-to-head competition with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are attempting to lock up customers before we can get
into long distance,'' said Jim Cullen, president and chief
operating officer of Bell Atlantic. ``It's a sensible policy for
them, but it's not a sound public policy'' to let AT&AMP;T proceed with
local service before Bell Atlantic can offer long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has criticized Bell Atlantic for failing to open its
markets to local-service competitors, but Cullen called that stance
in regulatory proceedings a farce. He said Monday's joint venture
announcement shows AT&AMP;T isn't interested in what Bell Atlantic is
doing but is busy building its own network to bypass Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wahl, a telecommunications analyst for the Yankee Group in
Boston, said AT&AMP;T's invasion of the local phone market will take
time. ``I think it's a win-win for Time Warner and AT&AMP;T and a win
for consumers as well. But I think it's a long-term win for
consumers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said the joint venture will test local phone service
in one or two cities later this year and expand the test next year.
He said it would take four to five years to roll out local phone
service systemwide.
</P>
<P>
   For a Time Warner customer, the joint venture holds the promise
of being able to receive a variety of telecommunications services,
including cable, Internet, local phone, long-distance, and wireless
phone service. The local phone service is likely to offer special
calling features like multiple lines, call forwarding, call waiting
and conference calling at heavily discounted prices. Company
officials said they also plan to develop new products, like video
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald M. Levin, Time Warner's chairman and chief executive,
said customers will be sold AT&AMP;T and Time Warner products in
bundles. Hypothetically, he said, Time Warner might give away HBO
or free Internet access to a customer who signs up for a particular
bundle of services. Consumer advocates cautioned that such freebies
are rarely free; usually higher prices for one service subsidize
giveaways of others.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T-Time Warner joint venture will have exclusive access to
Time Warner's cable network for 20 years. AT&AMP;T will own 77.5
percent of the joint venture and Time Warner 22.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for Time Warner to upgrade its cable system to be
capable of carrying telephone calls, while AT&AMP;T will pay much of
the cost of delivering those calls.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T will spend $300 million for an auxiliary power system to
run the phone system. It will pay Time Warner $15 for each home the
company's wires pass, or about $300 million in all. It will pay the
cost of hooking up a consumer, which AT&AMP;T said would cost anywhere
from $300 to $500 per home depending on whether the customer
already receives cable and has a set-top box.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, AT&AMP;T will pay a monthly fee per local phone subscriber
to Time Warner. That fee will begin at $1.50 in the first year of
the joint venture and rise to $6 after six years. Time Warner is
guaranteed payments based on AT&AMP;T signing up at least 25 percent of
the homes it passes after six years, although company officials
said that could happen in half the time.
</P>
<P>
   For Time Warner, Levin said the deal allows it to maximize the
value of its cable network with minimal risk. Levin likened the
joint venture to a movie deal where someone else shoots the film
and Time Warner gets a fee for distributing it. He also predicted
AT&AMP;T's involvement will entice more customers to sign up for Time
Warner's cable and Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner currently has 12.6 million subscribers across the
country, including parts of New York, Houston, Orlando and
Raleigh-Durham. In Massachusetts, Time Warner is the No. 2 cable
company with nearly 239,000 subscribers. It also operates cable
systems in New Hampshire and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said he did not want Time Warner to go it alone on phone
service because ``it is outside our core competence to really have
an integrated telephony offering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
