<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7738 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      02-01 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS TOP LINE IN SCORING SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On Dec. 16, Bruins center Jason Allison had a goal
against the Detroit Red Wings, giving him eight for the season
through 27 games, a pretty respectable pace but one that would have
brought him less than the 33 he scored last season.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a particularly alarming situation at the time, but it
certainly has become one. The Bruins have played 47 games _ No. 48
is Tuesday night against the Colorado Avalanche at the FleetCenter
_ and Allison has nine goals, including one in the last 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Dmitri Khristich is actually on a better clip than
last year, when he scored 29 goals. He has 20 goals but has dried
up recently. Khristich has zero points in his last four games. Even
worse is his shooting drought: five shots in the last five games,
none in his last two.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Sergei Samsonov, last year's Calder Trophy winner as
Rookie of the Year, had a fast start but he, too, has faded. In the
first 29 games, he had 28 points, 11 goals. In the last 18 games,
he has four goals and 7 points, with only two assists in the last
nine games.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't fair to blame only the top line for the Bruins' recent
fortunes (they are winless since Jan. 18), but the fact is the club
is struggling and the three leading point-getters and not doing
what they're paid to do.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, Anaheim star Paul Kariya has 268 shots this season.
The entire line of Allison, Khristich, and Samsonov has only four
more than that. You may not score on every shot you take, but you
fail to score on 100 percent of the shots you don't take.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns has tried benching two of them _
Khristich and Allison in the third period last week against the
Islanders _ but it hasn't shaken them from their doldrums. Tuesday
the coach is likely to split them up and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand that line is being checked a little bit
more,'' said Burns. ``We may break them up. I threw all kinds of
lines out there (Sunday afternoon in a scoreless tie with Carolina)
to try to change the monotony a little bit and it was all right. We
could've had a couple of goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulda, woulda, shoulda. The schedule is getting tougher, the
season is getting later, and something has to change if the Bruins
are going to make it to the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're depending too much on their skill level,''
said Burns, who has watched his top line finesse its way to
turnovers and pretty power plays that yield nothing. ``I'm not
saying they're not working or not competing but sometimes you
handle it a little bit too much. Sometimes to score goals when
you're in a slump, you've got to get your face scratched and your
wrists slashed. Those are the things that will make a difference in
the goal-scoring area.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as the penalty killing has been, that's how bad the
power play has been. The Bruins are the top man-short team in the
league. The man-advantage is another story. Boston has one
power-play goal in its last eight games and is one for its last 35
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Burns has been lying awake at night trying to figure what has
changed and what can be altered to get his club back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Khristich) has got to skate a little bit more and shoot on
stride,'' said Burns. ``He never seems to want to shoot on stride.
He wants to shoot from the stop position. He's good on the
rebounds, he's a great rebound, guy but sometimes skating and
shooting on stride can cause a lot of things. Sammy does the same
thing. He'll give you the spin-o-rama, then the spin-o-rama again.
We tend to forget that he's still learning a lot of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Dmitri's area, he's got to skate more and shoot while he's
skating. He's got to get it off on stride. Maybe you won't score
from the initial shot but maybe you'll get a rebound or it might
cause something else. We're trying to do too many things that look
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem seems to be the line's propensity for
hanging onto the puck a second too long, enabling foes to cover
them like a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've discussed it,'' said Burns. ``I've brought Sammy in, I
don't know how many times, to the video room after a period and
said, `You can't do this.' Sooner or later, you've got to cause
some kind of havoc at the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to shoot a little bit more but (his puck-handling
skills are) his bread and butter. You don't want to take that away
from him either because that's what he does best. When he does
score a goal by hanging onto it too long and does a couple of
spin-o-ramas, everyone says, `Wow, did you see that?' But when he
doesn't do it and nothing happens, it's like, `What's wrong with
him?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like (Khristich), too. When he does make those nice
little plays, or picks a loose puck up and puts it in the top of
the net, we all say, `Gee, wow.' When he doesn't . . . that's the
whole thing. Everybody panics in bad times and we shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns thinks the line is being too particular with shot
selection, which was one reason he put checking forwards P.J.
Axelsson, Rob DiMaio, and Tim Taylor out on the power play Sunday.
They keep it simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you're better just to close your eyes and let it
go,'' Burns said. ``I think a lot of the good shooting scorers do
that. They don't figure out where it's going, they just close their
eyes, put their heads down and rip it. Sometimes the puck has eyes
and it finds a way to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach has tried all kinds of things, including changing his
dress code. Now he believes he has no choice but to break up what
has been his most successful combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your first line is shut down, that's why we may have to mix
it up, nothing is happening with the second and that's where we
have to be a little bit better,'' he said. ``Maybe by moving a
couple of guys around, that might happen. The Avalanche have got
good forwards, a great goaltender, and they've got big defense.
Sometimes it brings the best out of you, we'll see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
