<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7742 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PARADE-COX     02-01 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PARADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons reign over Atlanta
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) GENERAL NEWS and (s) SPORTS categories.)
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was cold , and it was rainy _ and it was the
prettiest February day this city's pro football fans have had in
more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter to me that they lost,'' said Luther Davis,
24, hoisting a hastily scrawled banner (``We'll B Here Next Year''
), as he stood along Peachtree Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least they got to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was among the thousands who thronged downtown Atlanta
Monday for a parade to welcome the Falcons back home.
</P>
<P>
   In the 33-year-history of the franchise, the Dirty Birds had
never made it to the Big Dance.
</P>
<P>
   So who cared now if they got their toes stomped by Denver?
</P>
<P>
   Not Robbie Strickland of Powder Springs, Ga. She took the day
off, and kept her three children out of school to come down and
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But (cutting school) is good for them,'' she said, rubbing the
feet of her 7-year-old, Nicholas. ``The Falcons have never been
this far.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade, scheduled for 2 p.m., was delayed when the Falcon
charter from Miami landed at Hartsfield International Airport an
hour late. Fans and coaches, while deflated, didn't sound defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys are disappointed,'' linebacker Jessie Tuggle
told a crowd of about 100 airport workers and Delta employees
cheering the team as they deplaned about 1:45 p.m. ``At the same
time, we talked about not hanging our heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Kicker Morten Andersen vowed: ``If we stay hungry like we did
this year, we're going to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the recurrent theme among the throng downtown, carrying
placards like ``The Millennium's Our Year'' and shaking free
pom-poms distributed by a grocery store chain.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Nester, holding a pair of red, black and white jester hats
high over his head, walked down Peachtree Street before the parade
yelling ``The hat of champions!''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Bates, of Alpharetta, Ga. wore a homemade Falcons costume
with black and red feathers on her arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted (the Falcons) to know that we're still proud of
'em,'' she said. ``I think it's more important for us to be here
today because they did lose.''
</P>
<P>
   City and transit officials had anticipated crowds about the size
of the Braves' parade in '95, when the team won the World Series
and tens of thousands crowded downtown. But the weather got in the
way.
</P>
<P>
   There was no official estimate of parade-watchers, but Atlanta
Police said that 3,000 gathered in Woodruff Park. Along the route,
in front of Macy's in Peachtree Center, crowds were three to five
people deep.
</P>
<P>
   As the parade wore on, stopping and starting, and taking more
than an hour to complete, the enthusiasm of players _ wind-whipped
as they rode atop 15 firetrucks _ seemed to sag.
</P>
<P>
   At the Varsity (a famous drive-in restaurant), where the parade
began, they smiled and flapped their arms in the Dirty Bird dance.
By Woodruff Park, some looked chilled to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves, however, made good on his promise, and
performed the Dirty Bird atop a firetruck, while fans chanted,
``Dan Reeves! Dan Reeves!''
</P>
<P>
   As the parade passed, street vendors, seeing their market fast
disappearing, slashed prices on Falcons and Super Bowl
paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had won we would have jacked up the prices,'' said
vendor Gaynell Robinson, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, sweatshirts that sold for $30 at the beginning of the
parade could be had for $15 by the time the last firetruck passed.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning and end of the parade players and coaches
worked the crowd, signing autographs and fraternizing with fans.
</P>
<P>
   At the Varsity, Falcons Lester Archambeau autographed a barely
inflated football for Kirk Evans of Cumming, Ga., who handed it to
his nephew Zack.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's so cool,'' said Evans. Zack was speechless. He broke
into a nearly nonstop Dirty Bird.
</P>
<P>
   At Woodruff Park, Reeves introduced the players to the crowds to
rousing cheers, the most going to running back Jamal Anderson, who
did the Dirty Bird dance practically the duration of the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta singer Peabo Bryson sang ``I Believe I Can Fly.'' And
Mayor Bill Campbell then steered the proceedings into next season.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell showed the crowd a sign that will be placed at the
airport declaring the Falcons 1998 NFC Champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a temporary sign,'' he said. ``Next year, (it will
say) Super Bowl Champions.''
</P>
<P>
   After the parade, the Falcons rode in buses to their
headquarters in Suwanee, Ga. There, hundreds more fans greeted
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching them play this year has been a thrill,'' said Russell
Smith of Duluth, Ga. ``I just want to tell them thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   With their shoes getting soaked from the wet field, and the
temperature dropping into the 30s, fans still managed to wave
banners and pom-poms, and scream ``Thank you!'' as the players
trickled past.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players found ways to avoid the small crowd. Not
Jamal Anderson. He was greeted like a rock star when he bounded
onto the balcony and grabbed the microphone to say hello.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys being out here in the cold . . . it makes it
worthwhile,'' Anderson said. ``The Dirty Bird is alive . . . The
Dirty Bird is alive and well.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they left _ some in long stretch limousines _ some
players stopped and signed footballs, hats and shirts. Most just
got their things and left quickly and quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans wondered if they'd see the Falcons like this again.
The team has decided to move its summer training camp to Furman
University in South Carolina, and has discussed moving their
year-round facilities out as well.
</P>
<P>
   Said Emmie House of Lawrenceville, Ga., a 10-year season-ticket
holder: ``It might be the last time they're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Scott writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Ernie Suggs, Stacy Shelton, Ralph Ellis, Larry
Hartstein and Henry Farber contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
