<SLUG> BC-OMEGA-MARKETPLACE-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: A DEPLETED OMEGA ADVISORS LOSES A KEY STRATEGIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Staff turnover is nothing new at Omega Advisors, the
$3 billion New York-based hedge fund whose boss, Leon Cooperman, is
described as volatile even by friends.
</P>
<P>
   But after a tumultuous year that saw Omega drop more than 20
percent in last summer's downdraft _ prompting the quick departure
of the firm's emerging-markets managers _ Cooperman is now losing a
top lieutenant and close confidant who, according to people who
have worked at the firm, has played an important role in Omega's
success.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Leeds Jr., who joined Omega shortly after Cooperman
founded the firm in 1991, is leaving this month to spend more time
with his family and manage his own investments.
</P>
<P>
   His departure comes as Omega attempts to recover from last
year's losses. During the past year, $518 million has flowed out of
Omega Overseas Partners, Omega's largest single fund, including
investor withdrawals and distributions, according to MAR/Hedge, a
newsletter that tracks the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Omega Overseas suffered a 6.3 percent loss for the year,
according to MAR/Hedge, while George Soros' Quantum Fund and Julian
Robertson's Jaguar Fund finished last year up 12.4 percent and 2.4
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Omega's problems came in August, when the fund lost 22.3
percent as Russia's default and the near-collapse of Long-Term
Capital Management sent stocks and bonds of emerging markets
plunging. Other hedge funds lost big in August, of course, but
Omega's recovery has been hurt somewhat by hits in its domestic
stock choices even as the U.S. market rose sharply in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Omega owns 9.2 percent of Canadian funeral-home
operator Loewen Group Inc., whose shares have fallen sharply in the
wake of disappointing earnings, concerns about its $2 billion debt
load, and action by Florida regulators to suspend the licenses of
16 Loewen cemeteries and funeral homes for alleged accounting
irregularities. Loewen is appealing that action.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Omega's stake of 6.8 million shares in Loewen has
lost more than $132 million in value, or 84 percent, based on the
firm's disclosures in securities filings.
</P>
<P>
   Leeds, 46, declined to say much about his leaving, referring
questions to Cooperman. But he called his departure ``totally
amicable'' and said it would give him more time to enjoy other
aspects of life. ``I've been here for seven years. I'm basically
going to trade my own capital and play with my children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperman would not comment about Leeds, except to say: ``I'm
sorry to see Charlie go, but I'm happy that Omega has provided him
with the luxury of doing what he wanted to do. He leaves as a good
friend, and I'm wishing him well as he returns to the life of art
and enjoys his two lovely children.''
</P>
<P>
   People who have worked at the firm credit Leeds for good stock
picking during most of his time at Omega and say he developed a
close relationship with Cooperman. But they also say he lost favor
in the past year for backing Loewen and some other losing
positions, and they add that even seasoned portfolio managers can
chafe under Cooperman's intensity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``He was important right up to this last year. Charlie was a
winner every year'' before 1998, said one person who knows both
men. ``Charlie was as close as anyone could be to being an adviser
and confidant to Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Cooperman is a top stock picker in his own right.
After the Bronx native attended Hunter College and business school
at Columbia University, he joined Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., where he
rose to become the head of research as well as the firm's top
strategist. Before striking out on his own eight years ago, he was
named top portfolio strategist for nine consecutive years by
Institutional Investor magazine.
</P>
<P>
   And despite losses in Loewen and other stocks, Omega has had its
share of winners recently, including Liberty Media Group, which
doubled last year, and Lexmark International Group Inc., which
almost tripled in 1998. Cooperman's long-term success has helped
him hire six new employees recently, including veterans of
Robertson's Tiger Management and Lazard Freres &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   According to a person at the firm, Omega's total returns since
inception, net of fees, are now slightly behind the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 Index of large-capitalization companies.
</P>
<P>
   But excluding the firm's losses on emerging-markets securities
last year, Omega is still ahead of the index. In fact, the person
at the firm said, Omega's largest separately managed account _
which is run for a pension plan and thus was not invested in
Russian debt last year _ was up about 10 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest of Omega, which did have large Russian
exposure, ``it was a difficult several months, as it was for a
number of other hedge funds,'' said Steven Einhorn, a former
protege of Cooperman who resigned in December as Goldman, Sachs'
global head of research and has an agreement not to compete with
his old firm.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn said that after he announced he was leaving Goldman,
Sachs, the two men discussed the idea of Einhorn someday in the
future working at Omega, though he emphasized that both he and
Cooperman would never do anything in conflict with the agreement
not to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding his warm feelings for Cooperman _ whom he calls
``an excellent and terrific mentor'' instrumental in gaining him
partnership status at Goldman, Sachs in 1986 _ Einhorn acknowledges
that his former boss's personal style may not be for everyone. ``He
is a very demanding person. Maybe some don't appreciate the
directness of his approach,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
