<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs, Jackets gain commitments
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's recruiting class received added oomph
Monday when the Bulldogs received commitments from a pair of
high-profile prospects and Georgia Tech got a boost when it learned
it will sign one of the state's linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Kevin Breedlove of Clemson, S.C., and running
back Bruce Thornton of LaGrange, Ga. both announced their plans to
sign with Georgia on Wednesday, the first day of the national
signing period. The Yellow Jackets also landed a blue-chipper in
Early County, Ga. linebacker Recardo Wimbush.
</P>
<P>
   Breedlove is one of the Bulldogs' top commitments. The 6-foot-5,
295-pounder, who will play guard at Georgia, is rated as the No. 2
lineman in the South by Border Wars magazine. He chose the Bulldogs
over UCLA, Florida and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, a 5-11, 180-pound running back, rushed for 1,920 yards
and 28 touchdowns last fall and 4,541 yards in three years as a
starter. Thornton chose Georgia over Tennessee and Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbush, a 6-2, 210-pound linebacker, led Early County with 165
tackles and was Class AA All-State. Wimbush chose the Jackets over
Auburn, Alabama, Florida and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia did lose out on two players. Running back Cedric Cobbs
of Little Rock, Ark., chose Arkansas and Americus, Ga. defensive
lineman Alonzo Jackson chose Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Carrollton, Ga. receiver Reggie Brown has scheduled a news
conference for noon Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
