<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY REVEALS NOTHING NEW IN GRILLING BY HOUSE MANAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reliving memories of her fateful affair with
President Clinton, Monica S. Lewinsky was questioned under oath
Monday for four hours about the scandal, as House impeachment
managers sought new evidence to bolster their flagging case for
ending Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky made no explosive disclosure in the private deposition,
according to a source familiar with the session. But House
investigators were expected to spend the night examining a
videotaped recording of Lewinsky's sworn testimony in search of a
new twist in the high-stakes impeachment case.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise move, White House lawyers declined to question
Lewinsky and apologized ``on behalf of the president'' for her
troubles throughout the saga, which Lewinsky's attorney has
described as her ``long nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the opulent presidential suite of a Washington hotel
where Lewinsky was questioned, a new showdown unfolded as Clinton's
private lawyer, David E. Kendall, asked a federal judge to require
the president's chief nemesis, the independent counsel, Kenneth W.
Starr, to show why he and his staff ``should not be held in
contempt for improper violations of grand jury secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall cited a story in The New York Times on Sunday that
quoted Starr's associates as saying Starr believes he has
constitutional authority to file criminal charges against Clinton
while he is still in office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who has been roundly criticized by senators in both
parties for the timing of the story, did not refute the report. But
he said he was ``deeply troubled'' by the alleged leaks and vowed
to investigate the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This office has no desire to inject itself into the
constitutional process under way in the Senate,'' Starr said. ``We
are launching an internal investigation to determine whether anyone
in this office improperly disclosed the information.''
</P>
<P>
   An ongoing inquiry into previous allegations of leaks by Starr's
office was launched last year by US District Judge Norma Holloway
Johnson, who will consider Kendall's latest request to cite Starr
for contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, testifying under oath for the 23d time since Starr's
deputies first confronted her a year ago, was questioned only by a
House impeachment manager, Representative Ed Bryant of Tennessee,
who was accompanied by another of the 13 Republican managers,
Representative James F. Rogan of California.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said only that he ``felt it was a productive session.''
</P>
<P>
   Wary of antagonizing Lewinsky, 25, who has been generally
sympathetic to Clinton, the president's lawyers had been expected
to pose questions only if Lewinsky made an unexpected disclosure
that could damage Clinton's legal defense. Each side had up to four
hours to question Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With a senator from each party presiding, the session took place
on a cold, gray day, in the $5,000-a-night presidential suite of
the Renaissance Mayflower Hotel, five blocks from the White House.
The suite, which Clinton chose for his mother to stay in during his
first inauguration in 1992, sprawls over 2,200 square feet and
features such adornments as the presidential seal laid into the
foyer's oval-shaped marble floor.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, whose sexual liaisons in the White House with Clinton
began during the government shutdown in 1995, was not questioned
about details of their intimate encounters, under orders from the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, House managers said before the session, Bryant would
press Lewinsky on her account of Clinton's alleged role in several
key elements of the two articles of impeachment. Clinton is charged
with lying under oath to a federal grand jury and obstructing
justice to cover up his sexual affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The primary issues in dispute include a false affidavit that
Lewinsky filed in a sexual harassment suit that Paula Corbin Jones
brought against Clinton and settled last year for $850,000;
Jordan's job search for Lewinsky after she appeared on a witness
list in the Jones case; and Clinton's role, if any, in his personal
secretary, Betty Currie, hiding gifts the president had given
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by her lawyer, Plato Chaceris, Lewinsky answered
every question Bryant posed to her, in part to satisfy an immunity
agreement she struck last year with Starr to avoid possible
criminal prosecution. While Lewinsky testified, her mother, Marcia
Lewis, occasionally strolled through the Mayflower's elegant lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall, who has rarely shied from trying to score legal or
political points throughout the impeachment process, sat silently
through most of the deposition, leaving the interrogation to
Bryant. Kendall was accompanied by two other Clinton lawyers,
Cheryl Mills and Nicole Seligman.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the deposition, Seligman read a statement
expressing Clinton's regret for all the woes that Lewinsky and her
family have endured during Starr's eight-month investigation and
the nearly five-month congressional impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   The White House decision to forgo the questioning will be
apparent to senators Tuesday when they begin watching recordings of
the videotaped deposition behind closed doors in the Capitol. Four
closed-door viewings will be held, two in the morning, beginning at
8 a.m., and 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   After taking depositions from Clinton's friend, Vernon E. Jordan
Jr., Tuesday, and a White House adviser, Sidney Blumenthal,
Wednesday, the House team is expected to ask the Senate either to
call the three to testify in person or to permit their videotaped
depositions to be shown on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The final phase of the impeachment trial could follow, as
senators try to meet their goal of completing the historic
proceedings by Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over Lewinsky's deposition were Senator Mike DeWine,
an Ohio Republican, and three Democrats who took turns: Senators
Christopher J. Dodd of Connecticut, John Edwards of North Carolina,
and Patrick J. Leahy of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine told reporters afterward that the deposition lasted from
9:03 a.m. to 3:14 p.m., including a one-hour lunch break and
several other breaks. DeWine and the other senators declined to
discuss other details of the session, citing a Senate secrecy rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
