<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7759 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-PROPOSAL-BOS &LR;      02-01 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-PROPOSAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS $1.77 TRILLION IN FISCAL 2000 SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Basking in the good fortune of a robust economy and
surging tax revenues, President Clinton sent Congress a $1.77
trillion spending plan for the year 2000 Monday that seeks billions
of dollars in new spending while shoring up Social Security and
reducing the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first move in a battle with Republicans that will
likely echo through the next presidential election. Both parties
predict big budget surpluses _ $2.4 trillion over the next decade,
by Clinton's calculations _ and both want to divert some of it to
Social Security. But Clinton would spend the rest of the surplus on
Medicare and ``investments'' in education, research and other
programs, while Republicans are proposing broad tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basic fairness dictates that some of this overpayment should
go back to the taxpayers,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``They deserve it,'' said Senator Pete Domenici, the New Mexico
Republican who leads the Senate Budget Committee. ``It shouldn't be
sitting around up here to be spent.''
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma of how to use the surplus was unimagined only a few
years ago, as lawmakers seemed unable to do anything to rein in
rising annual deficits. Now, both Congress and the White House
foresee a booming economy that keeps people working, shopping and
investing _ and paying taxes on all those activities. In 2000,
Clinton says, the government will take in $117 billion more than it
needs under current law, and the surpluses will rise from then on.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting the political nature of the budget debate, Clinton
released his spending plan at a White House event while, only five
blocks away, prosecutors from the House furthered the impeachment
process by taking a deposition from Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the budget as an effective political tool for last
fall's elections, when the House Judiciary Committee first approved
impeachment charges. As the fiscal year expired and government
agencies lost authority to spend money, Clinton refused to sign the
budget bills unless Republicans offered more money for school
construction and for 100,000 new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Clinton is proposing a variety of tax cuts and new
spending, much of it aimed at parents and middle-class voters. He
is asking for $1.4 billion to move the nation closer to the goal of
hiring 100,000 new teachers, and he has revived a plan for $22
billion in bonds for school construction, which failed last year.
Clinton would also give stay-at-home parents of infants an annual
$500 tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   People caring for those with long-term illnesses would get a
$1,000 tax credit, and new tax credits would go to disabled workers
and to small businesses that offer health insurance to employees.
</P>
<P>
   In all, spending for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1 would
rise by $39 billion over this year, or 2.3 percent. Clinton's tax
credits would cost $36 billion over five years, with the expense
nearly offset with new money to be raised by eliminating corporate
``tax shelters.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton finances some of the new spending with changes in
investment rules and tax laws that Congress might not accept. For
example, he is counting on $8 billion next year from a cigarette
tax increase of 55 cents per pack. Congress turned down a similar
proposal last year.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 2001, Clinton's budget includes a claim on nearly
$19 billion from a settlement between states and tobacco companies,
which aims to reimburse the states for the cost of treating
smoking-related illnesses. However, there is no guarantee that the
settlement will funnel money to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking feature in Clinton's spending plan is that the
nation would pay down the federal debt, which now tops $5 trillion.
Clinton's aides say this is the true goal of diverting 62 percent
of future surpluses to Social Security, the federal pension
program, and 15 percent to Medicare, the health insurance program
for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The nation owes money to future beneficiaries of both programs _
obligations that are part of the federal debt. By reducing the
nation's IOUs to those programs, the White House says, the budget
within six years would cut federal debt to levels seen before
President Reagan took office, as a fraction of the total economy.
If followed through 2014, the Clinton plan would cut debt to its
lowest level since before World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting federal debt, Clinton said Monday, is ``a rare
opportunity that comes along once in a blue moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders say they agreed with the amount of the
surplus that should be spent on Social Security, but they would use
the money to transform the program into a series of private savings
accounts, owned by each worker. Clinton opposes that idea and says
it would increase the costs of the Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit it's a little melodramatic, but this ought to be
viewed as one of the greatest and most important debates on
economic policy since I can't remember when,'' said Henry Aaron, an
economist at the Brookings Institution, whose thinking on economic
policy is often in line with Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cornucopia of surpluses is unprecedented,'' Aaron
continued. The great debate is whether we consume them today with
tax cuts, or save them for the future and allocate them to shore up
our two most important domestic programs _ Social Security and
Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Other economists said Clinton could not fairly claim the high
ground of frugality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one Christmas present in here after another,'' said
Diana Furchtgott-Roth, a tax economist with the American Enterprise
Institute, a conservative think tank in Washington. ``Free
pharmaceutical drugs under Medicare. More child care spending. More
money to enforce equal-pay laws for women. He's basically paying
off every single group.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Schick, a professor of public affairs at the University of
Maryland, said, ``Clinton's legacy will be that he enlarged
government but concealed that by the growth of the surplus, the
growth hidden by the expansion of revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Schick said Clinton's plan reduces federal debt but doesn't make
structural changes in the Social Security and Medicare programs
needed to set their finances right permanently. Those programs
still offer more money in benefits than they are projected to
receive in taxes, though Clinton's plan delays the day that they
have a shortfall and cannot make good on their promises.
</P>
<P>
   Proposing another form of savings, Clinton would commit 12
percent of future surpluses to tax incentives to encourage workers
to open new ``Universal Savings Accounts'' for retirement. But Gene
Sperling, a senior White House economic adviser, said the president
was not ready yet to say whether all workers would qualify, or only
those below certain income caps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
