<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL PUSHES TO RESTORE FINANCIAL CREDIBILITY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Monday, a bank holiday was not
declared. Bank accounts were not frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the rumors that swept Brazil on Friday that the
government would curtail access to bank accounts, the government
instead acted to build credibility. Finance Minister Pedro Malan
told Brazilians not to expect an about-face in policy from one day
to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not have a bank holiday,'' Malan said in a lengthy
television interview. ``We will not have confiscations, blocking or
holding back of accounts, or any kind of surprise of that nature.''
As he spoke, Stanley Fischer, first deputy managing director of the
International Monetary Fund, flew to Brazil for negotiations on
releasing the second installment of a $41.5 billion loan.
</P>
<P>
   The credibility of President Fernando Henrique Cardoso's
administration hit a new low after the recently re-elected
government reneged last month on its pledge not to devalue the
currency under any circumstances. After that, the currency lost 40
percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil's economic plunge this year will prompt the sharpest
Latin American downturn since 1982,'' Salomon Smith Barney
predicted in a note to investors on Monday. The Brazilian economy
will contract 6 percent this year, the Wall Street firm said.
</P>
<P>
   For some Brazilians, like Guilherme Marques, 29, a professional
player of beach volleyball here, rumors that accounts might be
frozen were little more than the work of speculators looking for a
fast buck. ``We have to believe in the government's policies,'' he
said. ``I know Brazil is a very rich country.''
</P>
<P>
   But others were hardly reassured. Marcos A. Solto, 57, a retired
Central Bank employee, blamed the government for the devaluation.
Two weeks ago, the government won a congressional vote forcing
retired public servants like Solto, who collect lifetime pensions
equal to their highest salaries, to contribute to the pension
system for the first time. Monday, he was in no mood to give
Cardoso the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government is a farce,'' said Solto. Since Friday, he has
been transferring savings certificates into checking accounts,
which he heard would be exempt from confiscation. ``The country
does have a way out, but only in the hands of a worthy person,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With Fischer of the monetary fund and George Soros, the
international financier, both saying publicly that the Brazilian
currency had sunk too far at more than 2 reals to the dollar
Friday, the real appeared fortified Monday, closing at 1.89 to the
dollar. The Sao Paulo Bovespa index jumped 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the World Economic Forum's annual meeting in Davos,
Switzerland, Soros criticized Brazil's policy of increasing
interest rates to keep capital in the country and discourage
inflation. Monday, the Central Bank raised interest rates for the
fourth time this year, to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a disastrous move,'' he said. Each increase in
interest rates creates higher debt payments, fueling fears about
the country's ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Soros also encouraged the IMF to continue backing Brazil, saying
the risk was far lower than in Russia, which defaulted on some
loans last August. ``Right at this minute, Brazil has arrived at
the point where interposing a wall of money would stabilize the
situation,'' Soros said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Brazilian Congress has passed many of the spending
cuts and tax increases the government promised three months ago,
approval came late, eroding investor confidence to disastrous
effect. Now, the monetary fund and the government must rewrite
parts of the loan agreement, in the midst of a crisis the aid was
meant to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
