<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7764 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-TEXAS-ARLINGTON-P     02-01 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-TEXAS-ARLINGTON-PITCHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS-ARLINGTON PITCHER MOVES INTO STARTING ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ A lull had fallen over the crowd at Allan
Saxe Stadium. It was only another game, after all. Nothing unusual.
Nothing spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a loud pop issued from the catcher's mitt and the fans
began to buzz. Then there was another. From out of nowhere, four
men armed with radar guns _ Major League Baseball scouts _ appeared
behind home plate, reading the display approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the wake-up call, Cade Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely has big-league arm strength,'' Texas-Arlington
pitching coach Ron Liggett said of Sanchez, his prize pupil. ``He
could be a very high draft choice next year, depending on how he
throws. There are a lot of scouts showing a lot of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll get their first chance to see Sanchez pitch at 2:30 p.m.
today in Austin, where the junior right-hander will start for the
Mavericks in their season opener against Texas. It marks his first
outing in his new role as Texas-Arlington's No. 1 starter after
spending most of last year in relief.
</P>
<P>
   The move was made because, after a summer spent in the
prestigious Cape Cod League developing a curve ball and a
change-up, Sanchez was deemed reliable enough to join the rotation.
And as an added bonus, becoming a starter should enhance Sanchez'
draft stock, not only providing versatility to his resume but also
giving scouts more of a chance to see him throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many times scouts called last year and
asked, `Are you going to use Sanchez today?' '' Liggett said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Texas-Arlington coach Butch McBroom found himself
wondering the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get a chance to use him enough,'' McBroom said.
``With an arm as good as his, we want him out there pitching as
much as he can.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because when he was on the mound, Sanchez was close to
unhittable, allowing opposing batters a mere .162 average in 30
innings of work, using only a fastball that consistently clocks in
the 92-93 mph range and has reached 96 mph on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws almost effortlessly,'' Liggett said. ``He's so
strong that it doesn't look like he's airing it out, but the ball's
just popping in there. Some of the other pitchers don't like to
warm up with him because he throws so easy but throws so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, his limited repertoire was a concern, as was
his often alarming lack of control. Last season, he struck out 29
batters but walked 30 and hit 13 more.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Sanchez was selected in the 31st round of last year's
draft by San Francisco, which was willing to overlook the control
problem because last season was his first as a full-time pitcher.
Sanchez had played third base at Barton County (Kan.) Community
College in 1996 before transferring to Mesa (Colo.) State College
and giving up baseball to play outside linebacker for the football
team.
</P>
<P>
   He got his shot at Texas-Arlington after assistant coach Clay
Gould saw him throwing 90 mph in a summer league. Last season,
Sanchez showed potentially dominating stuff from the bullpen and
earned two late-season starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, it was just the fastball,'' said Sanchez, who at
6-foot, 200 pounds has lost 15 pounds from his football days.
``That was all I had. Now I have more pitches and more endurance. I
can go out there five or six or seven innings and still be sharp.
By the end of the season, I'll be able to go nine innings and have
my stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point last summer, Sanchez thought he'd be building his
endurance in the Giants' minor-league system. After receiving word
he had been drafted, the native of Salina, Kan., wrestled with the
idea of turning professional before deciding that another strong
year at Texas-Arlington would likely improve his draft position and
his bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I thought hard about all summer,'' Sanchez
said. ``The Giants had a scout up at the Cape, watching me, and
part of me kept saying, `This is it. I can be playing pro ball.
This is what I've always wanted.' But I think coming back,
especially as a starter, I'll be better prepared for the pros.
Working as a starter and developing more pitches will prepare me to
take on any role they throw at me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Andy Friedlander writes about the college sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
sportszone(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
