<HEADLINE>
TOURING WALES 
CONFISCATED SALAMIS 
TEXAS BEACHES
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Feb. 7)  
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We are four people who want to tour Wales for 10 to 14 days
without having to drive, and we are interested in forts, castles,
Celtic and Roman history and choral groups. Do you know any tour
operators who can arrange the trip we want? _ Elizabeth Offutt,
Atherton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. You have a choice of custom-tailored tours or packaged ones.
Let's start with the former.
</P>
<P>
   Leisurelink Visitor Services, 1-3 Castle St., Cardiff, Wales,
CF1 2BS, (44-1222) 522202, fax (44-1222) 529310, uses
four-passenger vehicles that are ideal for Wales' rural roads.
Leisurelink says it will draw up a sample itinerary for you at no
charge. The daily 24-hour rate for a four-passenger vehicle with
driver-guide is $273, including fuel (at $1.65 to a pound).
Leisurelink will arrange transfers from, for example, Heathrow
Airport near London and return. If guides are far from their home,
there will be a $41 accommodation fee. But you can avoid this by
using one town as a base for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Eurowales, Prince's Square, Montgomery, Powys, SY15 6PZ, Wales,
telephone (44-1686) 668030, fax (44-1686) 668029, specializes in
tailor-made tours in eight-seat vehicles. It was established in
1985 by Emyr Griffith, a former executive of the Wales Tourist
Board. It provided a sample seven-day tour for four at a price of
either $1,240 a person, double occupancy, with accommodations at
historic inns, or $1,373 at country house hotels. It includes
breakfasts, guide services and guide accommodations, admission
fees, fuel and taxes. Prices will vary based on your tastes.
Remember, too, that air fare and a tip for your driver-guide are
not included in these prices.
</P>
<P>
   Because Wales is compact (180 miles from north to south and 60
miles at its shortest from east to west), most packaged tours are
shorter than the 10 to 14 days you requested. For example, Unique
British Tours, (888) 277-1722, has a seven-day Grand Tour of Wales
with a guide and minibus that includes airport pickup, all meals
and superior-class accommodations and entrance fees. It stops at
castles and you will hear a performance by one of Wales' many male
choirs. Price: $1,900 a person, double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Trafalgar Tours, (800) 854-0103, offers Best of Wales, a fully
escorted nine-day motorcoach tour visiting London, Caernarvon,
Snowdonia, St. David's, Cardiff and Bath. It costs $890 a person,
double occupancy, for June departure and includes some meals but
not the air fare. A similar nine-day tour is offered by Globus,
(800) 851-0728, for $849 a person, double occupancy and can be
arranged through a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   For more on Wales, call the British Tourist Authority at (800)
462-2748.
</P>
<P>
   Puzzling Customs
</P>
<P>
   Q. In December, we returned from Rome to Philadelphia's airport,
the first time we had ever returned through that airport. The
Customs officials confiscated our Italian salamis, which were
vacuum wrapped, and did the same when another couple tried to bring
in German sausages and canned meats. But we were allowed to keep
cheeses. In the last four years, we have been to France six times,
and the sausages we brought back were never confiscated. These
inconsistencies make me wonder: What exactly are the rules? _
Bullets Gillespie, Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   A. Customs inspectors are responsible for enforcing about 400
regulations from 40 federal agencies. The rules in this case are
those of the Animal Plant Health Inspection Service, part of the
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Customs Service Web site,
www.customs.ustreas.com, any cured cheeses can be brought into this
country. It goes on to say: ``Meats, livestock, poultry, and their
byproducts (such as ham, frankfurters, sausage, pate), are either
prohibited or restricted from entering the United States, depending
on the animal disease condition in country of origin. Fresh meat is
generally prohibited from most countries. Canned meat is permitted
if the inspector can determine that it is commercially canned,
cooked in the container, hermetically sealed, and can be kept
without refrigeration. Other canned, cured, or dried meat is
severely restricted from most countries.''
</P>
<P>
   If there appear to be inconsistencies based on your experiences,
it is because inspectors can exercise discretion, based on
livestock health conditions around the world. And, alas, your
sopressata was probably barred from entry because of two separate
hog-cholera outbreaks. Neither were in countries anywhere near
Italy, but in protecting American livestock from this blight and
others, such as Mad Cow Disease, Customs likes to play it safe.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, either contact USDA-APHIS-VS, Federal Building,
6506 Belcrest Rd., Hyattsville, Md. 20782 or call (301) 734-7830
for detailed requirements before you go, or buy a loaf of bread
with those salamis and stop for a picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting Halfway
</P>
<P>
   Q. My adult son and I plan a trip together in May or June, to a
place where the climate would allow some ocean swimming and other
outdoor activities. He lives in Walnut Creek, just outside Oakland,
Calif., and we'd like to pick a spot roughly in between our homes.
Any suggestions? _ Allan Weitzenhoffer, White Plains, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you and your son want to split the flight time and air
fares somewhat evenly, and you're looking for good beaches,
someplace along the Gulf Coast is the best idea. To help you
compare, we chose an arbitrary departure date, May 15 (a Saturday),
with return a week later, and shopped for air fares on the Web.
These fares were available as of Feb. 1, and could change by the
time you reserve, but they give an idea of what you and your son
can expect to pay, and the differences between the fares.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston, a short drive from Houston, has beaches along its
famous Strand, and is bustling with perhaps the widest range of
activities among Texas coast cities. The round-trip fare for May 15
from New York to Houston is $257; from San Francisco, it's $202.
</P>
<P>
   Corpus Christi has nicer beaches, and is much more low key, with
fewer activities. The fares are higher: $306 to $348 round trip
from New York to Corpus Christi and $287 from San Francisco. You
and your son will each have to change planes in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, the tourist amenities are scarce along the gulf until
you reach the Yucatan Peninsula. Cancun is popular, with beaches,
resorts and archeological sites. Air fares: $388 for you, $434 for
your son.
</P>
</TEXT>
