<HEADLINE>
COURT, REJECTING RACIAL ARGUMENT, UPHOLDS N.J. DEATH PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Rejecting the argument that New Jersey's death
penalty is imposed disproportionately on blacks, the state's
Supreme Court upheld New Jersey's capital punishment law Monday and
affirmed the death sentence for a black man convicted of a 1992
murder during a gas station robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-1 vote by the justices followed nearly two years of
deliberation and a court-ordered study that found that blacks and
whites convicted of capital crimes in New Jersey had been sentenced
to death in nearly equal percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Deborah Poritz, who wrote the majority decision,
rejected the contention of a death row inmate, Donald Loftin, that
he had received a disproportionately harsh sentence or that race
``operated as an impermissible factor in the imposition of the
death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also discounted the assertion by the New Jersey public
defender's office that the blacks convicted of capital crimes
against whites were 20 percent more likely to be sentenced to die
than other defendants.
</P>
<P>
   But despite its support for the law, the court did not seem
supportive of the efforts of Gov. Christie Whitman and other
politicians who have sought to speed the pace of the death penalty
process by limiting condemned defendants' right to appeal. The
decision, in fact, staunchly proclaimed the court's right to hear
appeals without ``legislative interference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
