</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANT-EXPLOSION-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE EXPLOSION KILLS 1, INJURES 16 AT FORD'S RIVER ROUGE COMPLEX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.) (sw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ A thunderous explosion, followed by a fire
that burned for several hours, killed one worker and seriously
injured at least 16 on Monday at the Ford Motor Co.'s River Rouge
complex, long a symbol of American industrial strength that put the
nation on wheels by building the Model T.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion and fire heavily damaged the complex's power
plant, which normally produces enough electricity to supply the
residential needs of a city the size of Boston. Ford and Rouge
Steel, a subsidiary that Ford spun off in 1989, were forced to
close all six factories in the Rouge complex and send home
virtually all of the factories' 10,000 workers until further
notice.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the explosion, which occurred in a boiler at about
1 p.m., was not known.
</P>
<P>
   Charles N. Jeffress, the assistant secretary of labor for
occupational safety and health in Washington, said that although
industrial accidents involving similar numbers of injuries were
fairly common, it was extremely rare to have such a broad and
immediate economic effect from an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan is one of 23 states in which state officials, instead
of federal ones, investigate workplace mishaps, and these state
investigators will start as soon as firefighters declare the site
safe, Jeffress said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the dead and injured, three workers were missing
on Monday night. Ford officials said that they hoped these workers
had left their posts before the accident. Many of the injured were
severely burned and three were in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry workers have a rate of injuries and work-related
illnesses that is two-and-a-half times that of the average for all
workers in the private sector, according to the federal Bureau of
Labor Statistics. But Ford has had a fairly good record until now,
maintaining a large staff to investigate ways to improve workplace
safety, Jeffress said.
</P>
<P>
   William Clay Ford Jr., the Ford Motor Co.'s chairman, arrived at
the factory less than two hours after the explosion, as
firefighters were still trying to put out the blaze, and said that
the loss of life and injuries made Monday ``the worst day of my
life.'' A great-grandson of Henry Ford, Ford emphasized safety and
environmental issues as a member of Ford's board before reasserting
the Ford family's control of the company last fall and becoming the
chairman at the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor's headquarters is still located about two miles from
the Rouge complex here in this southwestern suburb of Detroit.
Started in 1918, the factory complex employed nearly 100,000
workers at its peak in the late 1940s. The complex took raw iron
ore, timber, rubber and other raw materials and turned them into
cars. While Henry Ford perfected assembly-line production and built
the first Model T's at another, smaller factory in nearby Highland
Park, Mich., it was the Rouge complex that became a symbol of
American mass production after World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent factory complexes were less ambitious, buying more of
their parts from outside suppliers. Ford now builds the Mustang and
many auto parts here.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials refused to speculate on Monday night on when the
aging factories here would reopen, saying that their first concern
was for their workers' safety. The unionized workers here will
continue to be paid.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the official cause of explosion was still a mystery on
Monday night, a man identifying himself as a power plant foreman
called a local radio station and said that sensors had alerted to
him a problem with a ``pressure relief valve'' on a boiler.
</P>
<P>
   After the explosion, flames leaped from the top floor of the
factory for several hours. The factory building is the equivalent
of 20 stories and covers most of a city block; its eight
smokestacks are 600 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   George McPartlin, a Ford employee who used to work inside the
plant and stood outside it on Monday afternoon, said that the top
floor was where coal dust was blown by powerful fans as fuel into
the boilers. He raced to the factory on Monday afternoon to make
sure that his brother, Larry, a power plant electrician, was safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had soot all over his clothes and he was shaking'' but was
not injured, McPartlin said, adding that his brother had told him
that the explosion occurred in a boiler that had just been repaired
and only turned on again on Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
