u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSICO-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      02-01 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSICO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPSICO SAYS ITS EARNINGS WERE HIGHER THAN PREDICTED
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pepsico Inc. announced its fourth-quarter earnings after the
market closed on Monday, painting a picture that was largely
positive for its soft drink, snack food and orange juice
businesses. Earnings per diluted share came in at 24 cents for the
quarter, a penny higher than analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   The company credited momentum in its soft-drink business for
much of its success, noting that its North American sales volume
had grown 10 percent in the quarter and 6 percent for all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pepsi One, our new one-calorie cola, led the growth in the
fourth quarter,'' the chairman and chief executive of Pepsico,
Roger A. Enrico, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that growth may have come at a steep price. Pepsi-Cola's
profits in North America fell 21 percent in the quarter, which was
the result of intensive advertising and promotional spending, as
well as ``a very competitive pricing environment,'' said Richard M.
Detwiler Jr., a Pepsico spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi and its chief rival, the Coca-Cola &UR;  &LR; Co., have been engaged
in a price battle at the supermarket and other retail outlets for
most of the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico had announced last week that it was taking 17 cents in
various one-time charges against earnings to cover losses in
business areas like Russia, where the company had an unusual charge
of $218 million, and to cover the costs of certain Frito-Lay plant
closings in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of Russia, though Asia also played a role,
international Pepsi-Cola sales fell 12 percent compared with the
fourth quarter a year ago. Worldwide operating profits in the
soft-drink division were down 33 percent, the company said,
attributing that to competitive pricing, higher advertising and
marketing expenses, and the unraveling of the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Other areas of concern include Brazil, where sales of Frito-Lay
products fell 3 percent, according to the earnings statement.
``That's a little disappointing,'' said Jennifer Solomon, an
analyst for Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, international profits from Frito-Lay, which makes up
half of Pepsico's earnings, fell 6 percent in the quarter, while
North American profits rose 3 percent. Worldwide, Frito-Lay posted
a 1 percent gain in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi reported fourth-quarter sales of $7.19 billion, up 15
percent from $6.26 billion in the fourth quarter of 1997. Net
income declined 10 percent, to $361 million from $401 million in
the period a year earlier. The earnings announcement was made after
the stock market closed. Earlier, shares of Pepsi fell 87.5 cents,
to $38.125.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the critical drivers in 1999 will be the strength in
profit growth of the Frito-Lay business,'' said Andrew M. Conway,
an analyst for Morgan Stanley, who estimates that growth at 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide Pepsi-Cola volume grew 7 percent in the quarter,
mostly driven by the 10 percent gain in North American volume, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Pepsi One, the leading brands were Mountain Dew,
Pepsi, Lipton Brisk iced tea and Pepsi's bottled water brand,
Aquafina.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
