A7779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-GAMBLING-BOS &LR;      02-01 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GAMBLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS. SPEAKER SOFTENS POSITION ON CASINO GAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Softening his position on legalized gambling, House
Speaker Thomas M. Finneran said Monday building a casino in Boston
might be a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions about New Hampshire's plan to legalize
slot machines to help pay for education programs, Finneran said
Massachusetts can not afford to reject expanded gaming if that
happens.
</P>
<P>
   And in a move that will put him at odds with the Wampanoag
Tribe, which is trying to build a casino in Southeastern
Massachusetts, Finneran said the casino should be located in Boston
_ where a new convention center and several hotels are now being
built.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're getting into this for purposes of revenue, rather
than dilute it all over the place in two or three or four locations
in Massachusetts, you want to make it a destination point as
Foxwoods has become a destination point,'' Finneran said. ``I don't
think it's really too much of an arguable position to say that the
destination point of greatest attraction in Massachusetts remains
Boston and that is likely to remain the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino, who favored the idea of a casino in
Boston during the Megaplex debate, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran's remarks follow those of Attorney General Thomas F.
Reilly, who, unlike his predecessor Scott Harshbarger, said he is
not morally opposed to gaming and would not challenge in court a
move to legalized casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the House and Senate would need to approve
legislation authorizing expanded gambling in the state. The last
time the issue was before the Legislature two years ago, it was
overwhelmingly voted down, with Finneran arguing against it.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's recent comments on the subject, especially
Monday's, signal a change of heart that is perplexing to many,
including Representative Daniel E. Bosley, chairman of the
Government Regulations Committee and a key player in the gambling
debate on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran said he would wait to see what that panel recommends
before determining whether to limit gambling to one casino in
Boston or whether to allow racetracks to add slot machines or
scatter gaming throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the appropriate solution is,'' Finneran
said.
</P>
<P>
   A key sign on how far Finneran is willing to push the gambling
issue may come Tuesday when he announces his committee
chairmanships. Bosely, who authored an in-depth report two years
ago opposing casino gambling, could be replaced with someone more
amenable to the speaker's softened position on gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran would not disclose his committee choices.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the Boston delegation on Beacon Hill could
not be reached for comment.But Representative Paul C. Demakis, a
Back Bay Democrat, said he remains opposed to casino gambling,
especially in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say whether I'm surprised or not,'' Demakis
said of Finneran's remarks. ``We don't need casino gambling in
Boston for our economy or to attract visitors and tourists here. It
would invite all the things associated with it, including higher
crime and compulsive gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he has changed his mind about legalized gambling,
Finneran said he would characterize himself as a ``skeptic
regarding many of the claims (surrounding the issue) but at the
same time I'm not taking any kind of a moral position that somehow
or another this would be sinful for the Massachusetts government to
sanction or authorize.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, Massachusetts already has legalized gambling
in the form of the Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a little bit inconsistent for anybody in the State
House to talk about trying to take a moral tone, strike a moral
position on it,'' Finneran said.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks surprised Bosley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that interesting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to remember that Foxwoods is in the middle of
nowhere,'' Bosley said of the Ledyard, Conn., casino. ``Not in the
middle of our biggest city. To put that here means a
disproportionate share of revenue would come from the poorest
people in Massachusetts. So you're not going to get the revenue
bump that you think you will.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosley also said opening the door to one casino would open up
the entire state to gambling, enabling Indian tribes, including the
Wampanoags, to push forward with their plans for high-stakes
gambling. It could also allow racetracks to argue for slot machines
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have a very, very negative impact on your Lottery,
which goes directly back to cities and towns,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
