r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-RECRUITING-TEX     02-01 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-RECRUITING-TEX </SLUG>
 
COMMENTARY: THE STATE OF RECRUITING HYPOCRISY (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arlington (Texas) Lamar High School defensive lineman Cedric
Hilliard had never traveled to the Midwest before a summer
recruiting trip to South Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   He noticed that the skies were different, sometimes more hazy
than the skies are in Texas. He liked the people around town
because they were similar to folks in the Fort Worth-Dallas area,
down to earth and friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard went back in the winter and experienced some snow and
bitter cold temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   That might take some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard plans to spend more time in Indiana, and he will sign a
national letter-of-intent Wednesday to play football for Notre
Dame.
</P>
<P>
   For the next four years, he will meet high school football
players from all over the country, and he will live in a place he's
never been. He will get to know the Midwest. Hilliard will learn
that people who live in small, farming communities actually enjoy
every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, Hilliard is considered a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, my God. It can't be. He's about to leave Texas to play
football.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no yee-haws for Hilliard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking so forward to it,'' Hilliard said. ``I'm going
someplace completely different, and I enjoy experiencing places
I've never been before. I'd like to go to California and see things
out there, too. I've never been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard is bringing down the percentages, and it's nice to see
he doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   He is well aware that the big story in every Texas newspaper
this recruiting season is that a huge percentage of the state's
best football players are staying in Texas to play.
</P>
<P>
   The big story last year was that Texas players did not stay in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   All people cheer for are jerseys anyway, and it really doesn't
matter who is wearing them. Texas running back Ricky Williams is
from California. Those who follow the Longhorns don't like Williams
any less because he didn't grow up in Texas. Let me know the next
time you hear a fan yell: ``Hurray. We're national champions. Too
bad our players are from someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   The hypocrisy of it would make for a good comedy skit.
</P>
<P>
   High school students are encouraged all through school to
experience different things. Go places and see the world. Football
players are urged to take all five of their recruiting visits so
they can see the country for free.
</P>
<P>
   Then, signing day comes.
</P>
<P>
   The ones who stay in Texas are heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The ones who don't are making a horrible decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``People never say things to your face, but you read stuff in
the papers about players leaving the state and how bad that is,''
Hilliard said. ``I look at it like this; those people don't know my
situation. I didn't want to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard brings up an even more interesting point. Look down the
Texas Longhorns roster, and almost everybody is from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   How fun is that? You go off to college, and all your new friends
are exactly like you and all the friends you already had back
atLamar High School. Where Hilliard is going, there will be players
from everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me who learns more _ Hilliard, or the guy who spends four
years in College Station?
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard should be applauded for leaving Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The skies might be a little more gray where he is going.
</P>
<P>
   But at least they're different.
</P>
<P>
   (Darrin Scheid writes about the college sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 548-5451. E-mail:
sportszone(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
