u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENVER-MOOD-NYT     02-01 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENVER-MOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER HAILS THE BRONCOS AND SETS SIGHTS ON A THREE-PEAT
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Mass.) (Duplication notice: Also moving in `s' category . ) 
 (ms) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ In a celebration of two straight Super Bowl victories,
orange and blue plastic horse heads bobbed in a massive parade here
Monday, confirming that the Broncos, the sporty stallions of the
National Football League, have trampled Denver's fusty old image as
a cow town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the champions, we are the champions,'' sang a joyous
crowd, estimated at 375,000 people, that overflowed Civic Center
Park. Hoping to persuade the team's quarterback, John Elway, to
postpone retirement, some held up signs calling for a
``Three-peat'' and chanted, ``One more year, one more year.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback teased the crowd, ``That three-peat does sound
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people had come from across the state for a glimpse of
their hero. ``God is coming,'' said Holly Smith, 38, who had driven
almost two hours from Colorado Springs to see the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's festive scene contrasted with the hooliganism that
broke out Sunday night after Denver's 34-19 victory over the
Atlanta Falcons in Super Bowl XXXIII. Repeating vandalism that was
seen after the Broncos' 1998 championship and after Denver's hockey
team, the Avalanche, won the Stanley Cup in 1996, bands of young
men ran through downtown, breaking windows, setting small fires,
throwing bottles at police, and fleeing tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like being behind the path of a tornado,'' Andrew
Hudson, spokesman for Mayor Wellington E. Webb, recalled Monday of
watching people run through the city's financial heart, 17th
Street. As part of an estimated $100,000 in damage, the vandals
broke windows on the street, sometimes called ``The Wall Street of
the Rockies.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory celebrations boiled over into minor vandalism in other
cities around the state: Boulder, Grand Junction, Greeley and Fort
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, few Denverites interviewed had sympathy for the vandals.
``It's terrible, a lot of young kids out drinking too much,'' fumed
Daniel Munoz, a barber.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's parade went on without incident. But it came after many
Denverites felt jilted by the team's owner, Pat Bowlen. Last week,
the team announced that the Broncos would be too busy to have a
parade after a victory. Instead, fans would have to content
themselves with a rally. Only three months earlier, Denver area
voters had approved a pet proposal of Bowlen's: using sales tax
money to pay for three quarters of the $360 million cost of a new
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos officials said nine members of the team were required to
be in Hawaii for practice and publicity for next Sunday's Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Bowlen reversed himself and authorized a parade
featuring the entire team.
</P>
<P>
   The new stadium, which is to open in August 2001, is part of $1
billion in downtown investments, including a baseball stadium that
opened in 1995, and an aquarium that is to open in May.
</P>
<P>
   In this sports-oriented city, the Super Bowl victory carries
political weight, giving a lift to Webb, who plans to announce in
coming days that he will run for re-election. Without any strong
opponent in this heavily Democratic city, the mayor is favored to
win a third, four-year term in May.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl victory also comes as the Democratic National
Committee weighs Denver against Boston and Los Angeles for the 2000
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is $130 million in spending by 50,000 delegates and
news people, as well as an enormous amount of news media exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the high road, Denver advocates say that by having their
convention here, Democrats would plant their flag in the Republican
Rockies and would link the Democratic Party with Denver's image of
high technology, efficiency and high living standards. Taking the
low road, advocates warn against holding the convention in Monica
S. Lewinsky's hometown (Los Angeles), and say that if the Democrats
cannot win Massachusetts next year, they are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   With a decision expected within a few days, committee members
have said that they are impressed with Denver's smooth handling of
large events in the last five years: a papal visit, the Oklahoma
City bombing trials and a summit meeting of leaders of Russia and
the seven largest industrial nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENVER-MOOD-NYT     02-01 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENVER-MOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER HAILS THE BRONCOS AND SETS SIGHTS ON A THREE-PEAT
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Mass.) (Duplication notice: Also moving in ` a ' category . ) 
 (ms) 
