<P>
   At stake is $130 million in spending by 50,000 delegates and
news people, as well as an enormous amount of news media exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the high road, Denver advocates say that by having their
convention here, Democrats would plant their flag in the Republican
Rockies and would link the Democratic Party with Denver's image of
high technology, efficiency and high living standards. Taking the
low road, advocates warn against holding the convention in Monica
S. Lewinsky's hometown (Los Angeles), and say that if the Democrats
cannot win Massachusetts next year, they are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   With a decision expected within a few days, committee members
have said that they are impressed with Denver's smooth handling of
large events in the last five years: a papal visit, the Oklahoma
City bombing trials and a summit meeting of leaders of Russia and
the seven largest industrial nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7786 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ELWAY-BOS &LR;      02-01 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY LEANING TOWARD ANOTHER SEASON? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The door, open just a sliver last week, is now wide
open. John Elway is considering whether to come back next season
and, his closest friends say, it is more a likelihood than a mere
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Elway did not sleep Sunday night after Denver's 34-19 Super Bowl
victory over Atlanta when, once again, he displayed the intangibles
that those few athletes who are great have, that gossamer that can
never be explained by words, when his 38-year-old body threw for
336 yards and one touchdown and ran for one more.
</P>
<P>
   He celebrated with his teammates and then with his coach, Mike
Shanahan, and when he arrived to accept his MVP trophy Monday at
8:30 in the morning, he said, ``I still haven't been able to lay
down and change the days yet; it's still Sunday to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And the memory of that Sunday just may be the deciding factor,
because Elway's arm seemed to have a magical revival Sunday night.
His passing in a playoff game hadn't been as crisp and sharp since
the famous game against Cleveland 12 years ago, the game of ``The
Drive'' that made Elway's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt as comfortable before a playoff or Super Bowl
game,'' Elway told friends before Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Even more significantly, Elway told intimates that the family
vote on his returning _ 4-1 against this time last year _ is now
3-2 against as one of his children apparently has switched sides.
But the deciding vote always is Elway's, and he has a chance to do
what no quarterback ever has done: win three Super Bowls in a row.
The enticement of that bid for immortality is compelling to Elway's
competitive nature, friends say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping he gives me one or two more years,'' Shanahan said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Elway would not rule out that possibility in his public comments
after accepting the MVP award. Indeed, those words hinted that his
mind is tilting toward returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 38 years old and in the twilight of my career, I really
have the tendency to focus on the `now' and not the `tomorrow,' ''
Elway began, using a variation of the stock reply he had given all
week. ``I really want to enjoy the win tonight. There'll be times
when I think about it down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, though, Elway said more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great to come back and `three-peat,' '' he said,
``but also it would be nice to walk away with the way I'm playing
right now. It's a fine line because, as a football player, I'll
never want to never play football. It's such a fine line. I'm one
of those guys who doesn't want to walk away too late.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he went on, ``If I can play like I played tonight, then I
can play a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why his arm seemed so much stronger and surer Sunday
night than it had earlier this season, Elway joked, ``I was talking
to Dan Marino the other night, and I said to Dan, `No wonder you
talk about playing three more years. You get down here in the sun
and practice and run around.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I enjoy practicing down here. It's tough to practice
in Denver when it's cold, but you get down here and the warmth kind
of seeps all the way down into your bones.''
</P>
<P>
   But the sheer artistry of Elway's performance against the
Falcons was due to more than the warmth of Florida. Elway earned
MVP honors in the ultimate game that leveled him three times in the
past, calling upon the intangibles that for so long have made him
great and have given him a new enticement to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to talk to my wife, who is my hero, and I'm going to
give my kids a vote, if they're in the house long enough,'' said
Elway. ``As I said earlier in the year, there's going to be no
absentee ballots this year. They're going to have to be home to
vote, and they never are. But there'll be no absentee ballots. I'll
talk to them and I talk to my dad and my mom and I'll talk to Mike
and I'll talk to (Broncos owner Pat Bowlen).''
</P>
<P>
   What Elway most fears is the unknown: how he'll react once he
decides to leave football. He also worries about what happens if
``I say I'm done and then get into April or May and say, `You know
what? I can play one more year.' So I just want to take the time
and not close the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The game itself Sunday night displayed the dilemma Elway is in.
Shanahan joked that Elway's TD on his trademark quarterback draw
play was a more difficult score than it had been in the past. And
there was another play on a keeper around the right side when Elway
and Atlanta linebacker Cornelius Bennett were in a foot race, a
race Elway easily would have won years ago for a huge gain, but
this time resulted in no gain. Elway clearly is 38 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But Elway's passing was magnificent. The Falcons dared him to
beat them with his arm and his leadership, and Elway was immense.
He still has that intangible gift that few QBs have. As he put it
last week when talking about all-time great QBs, ``They find a way
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If he were to take out a yellow legal pad and draw a line down
the middle, the ``pros'' for his return on one side would be these,
he said: ``No. 1 would be talking about `three-peat,' and No. 2
would be my need to compete. And then on the other side, it would
be whether physically I can still do it. And whether you can still
spend the time to prepare, especially what we do in Denver
offensively, spend the time mentally each week to get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Elway tapped his chest and said, ``It'll
depend on what I feel here. The bottom line is my heart is going to
tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   And his heart, his friends say, is leaning toward returning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
