<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CREDITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BUDGET OFFERS TAX BREAKS FOR MANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the second year running, President Clinton is
trying to block Republicans from enacting a broad tax cut. And yet
the budget Clinton released Monday includes a variety of ``targeted
tax relief'' for certain groups, ranging from parents of infants to
parkland advocates to the steel industry.
</P>
<P>
   While closing ``tax shelters'' for corporations, Clinton would
create at least a dozen new tax breaks for families, for certain
businesses, and for state and local taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The large number of tax breaks _ the White House leaked word of
them earlier this month at a rate of one a day _ has raised a
debate about whether the nation is better off giving everyone a tax
cut, or funneling the benefit to certain groups who might deserve
an extra hand.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say a rollback in income tax rates of 10 percent or
15 percent is fairest to the most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, ``we did a lot of targeted tax cuts, and if you
weren't a left-handed cab driver in New York, you didn't get
anything,'' Representative John Kasich, an Ohio Republican who
leads the House Budget Committee, said Monday. ``You know, there
were a lot of Americans left out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, a senior White House economic adviser, counters
that narrow tax credits are the most fair. A family earning
$40,000, he said, might save only $100 or $200 under the Republican
income tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Clinton foresees a benefit of several times that
amount for the same family through the ``United Savings Accounts''
he proposed this month. The so-called USA accounts would give
families an annual payment and matching grants to help them save
for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're proposing is far more progressive, more targeted to
middle-income families,'' Sperling said. The White House has not
released details of the savings account proposal yet and has not
said what income caps would apply.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and its critics also differ on
whether broad tax cuts or narrow tax breaks are more beneficial to
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has long argued that the nation needs to cut its debts
while making selective ``investments'' in programs that make people
more productive. The administration uses that argument when arguing
for higher spending on education and worker training.
</P>
<P>
   But conservative economists say that Clinton's tax credits make
the economy less efficient by using the tax code to change people's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Even something like Clinton's ``Hope credit'' for college
tuition, which is now law, makes the economy less efficient, argues
Diana Furchtgott-Roth, a tax economist with the American Enterprise
Institute, a conservative think tank. ``Some people might not want
education,'' she said. ``They might want to do something else that
is equally productive, like start a small business. But the tax
code says, `Go to school.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she said, conservative philosophy calls for the
government, when faced with surplus tax money, to return it to
taxpayers with no strings attached. ``They shouldn't say, `We'll
give money back if you jump through this hoop. You can't take your
money and go fishing. You have to go to school or have children.
Plus, you can't earn more than a certain income to get it back,''
Furchtgott-Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's USA plan would cost $536 billion over 15 years. Other
tax credits in his budget include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A $1,000 credit for services for people who need long-term
health care, at a cost of $5.6 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   _ A $1,000 credit to help the disabled pay for transportation,
special technology and other on-the-job costs. The price is $700
million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tax credits to help local governments issue nearly $25 billion
in bonds to build or renovate public schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tax credits to help state and local governments issue $9.5
billion in bonds to preserve green space, create urban parks or
protect water quality.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tax credits for stay-at-home parents with a child under age 1,
for small employers who offer health insurance and for the US steel
industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
