A7799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      02-01 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CONSENSUS ON SAVING SOCIAL SECURITY BUT NOT ON HOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Minn., N.J., N.M.)  (See related BUDGET-CLINTON, BUDGET-SPEND, BUDGET-REVENUE) 
 (sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It says ``Budget of the United States Government''
on the cover, but the document that President Clinton sent to
Congress on Monday is really a political agenda, in spreadsheet
form, for a new fiscal era.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents always use their budget proposals to lay out their
wish lists, and Clinton has been particularly adept at using the
annual budget cycle not just to win attention for new and recycled
programs but, this year especially, to portray himself as active
and engaged.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton also has a more sweeping goal. With Washington still
in shock at the speed with which the federal government has left
behind an era of huge budget deficits and diminished expectations,
Clinton is trying to seize the high ground in a fast-developing and
fundamental debate over how the nation should capitalize on its
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Should the country invest its anticipated fiscal windfall in
preparing for the aging of the baby boom generation and the strains
that will create on the foundations of the social welfare system,
Social Security and Medicare? In Clinton's view, that is the
prudent course and one that, after accounting for new spending for
the Pentagon and domestic priorities, leaves no money for the
sweeping tax cuts that frustrated Republicans have been demanding
for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just about saving Social Security and Medicare,
although that is terribly important,'' Clinton said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscal prudence now, he said, will allow succeeding generations
to deal with the unforeseen and unknowable challenges of the next
century ``unburdened by the unfinished business of the 20th
century, unshackled by our profligacy in the latter part of this
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's implications to the contrary, Republicans say,
they are equally dedicated to shoring up Social Security, and they
also believe there should be more money for education and the
military. Showing remarkable unanimity for a party that has been
riven for the last few years by internal dissent, Republicans are
arguing that there is enough money to slash taxes as well, although
the budgetary math that leads to such a conclusion is a bit murky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have it all,'' said Rep. John R. Kasich, R-Ohio, who is
chairman of the House Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties are in at least tacit agreement on a few points.
One is not to question too aggressively the assumption that the
trillions of dollars in anticipated surpluses will actually
materialize. Reaping the windfall requires that the economy and the
stock market remain relatively healthy for years. And Republicans
and Democrats alike are considering detailed policy proposals that
presume long-term budget forecasts from the White House and
Congress prove uncharacteristically accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the two parties are not far apart on the biggest
question before them. Facing the insolvency of what is arguably the
most popular and enduring of all government programs, they agree in
general terms that nearly two-thirds of the anticipated budget
surpluses should go to dealing with Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   There is little agreement, however, on the best way of using the
surplus to shore up the retirement system. And even putting aside
Social Security, there is a heated battle shaping up over how to
use the money left over once Social Security's future is assured.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership in Congress and Clinton have powerful
reasons to find some accommodation this year and enact legislation
on Social Security and dividing up the surplus. But the stakes are
so big and the atmosphere so poisonous that resolution of the big
questions may have to wait for the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   And even as they debate each other, the two parties are being
forced to rethink their own approaches to tax and spending policy
as the old rules forged in the austerity of deficit politics give
way to a presumed age of fiscal plenty. They even need a new
language.
</P>
<P>
   So murky are some of the concepts for using the surplus to shore
up Social Security that neither side can fully understand what the
other is proposing, leaving budget analysts from both parties
scratching their heads. And what, after all, has happened to the
deficit hawk now that the deficit is no more?
</P>
<P>
   No longer able to use the specter of endless deficits to impose
limits on the growth and power of the federal government,
Republicans are returning to the approach championed by Ronald
Reagan two decades ago: stimulate the economy through big tax cuts,
an approach that has the corollary benefit of starving the
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We count on the American people to handle their own money and
solve many of their own problems around their kitchen tables and
their front rooms and their businesses,'' said Sen. Pete V.
Domenici, R-N.M., who is the chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee. ``We don't want to invent programs to use the surplus
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Having tried hard to refashion themselves as the party of fiscal
responsibility, the Democrats now have to find a way to promote
what Clinton called on Monday a ``prudent but progressive''
approach to governing. In other words, can they use government to
address the country's problems without opening the floodgates to
new spending?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a budget and an agenda that will not do nearly enough
to bridge the broad and growing chasm that divides the wealthy and
prosperous from the majority of Americans,'' said Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., who added that the country has ``a great number
of critical domestic programs that desperately require real
budgetary commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a sign of the Democratic Party's move to center on
fiscal issues that his critique was an isolated one and that the
official party line of the day was that Democrats stood for a
smaller, smarter government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cry has gone out across this country, `The Democrats are
at it again, the era of big government,''' said Sen. Frank
Lautenberg of New Jersey, the senior Democrat on the Senate Budget
Committee. ``The fact of the matter is that we will be spending
less as a percentage of the American economy on government than we
have at any time since 1973, and that public debt, looking out 15
years from now, will be at its lowest point since 1917.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
