<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-REASSIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON GLOBE REASSIGNS 12 EDITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KINDLEBERGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Globe editor Matthew V. Storin announced Monday the
reassignment of 12 editors in a broad reshuffling of the newsroom's
middle-management ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Acting city editor Peter Canellos will become assistant managing
editor for metropolitan news, leading a list of reassignments that
Storin said was aimed at introducing ``fresh blood and fresh
ideas'' to the newspaper. The changes take effect March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to reinvigorate the place,'' Storin told a crowded
staff meeting. ``No one was taken out of a job because they were
doing a bad job.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin said the news staff was performing well but needed to
prepare for new challenges, especially the Globe's efforts to
reverse a decline in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The other changes are as follows:
</P>
<P>
   Assistant city editor Joe Williams, 36, will move up to city
editor, filling the job left open by the promotion of Canellos,
also 36. Teresa Hanafin, 43, currently assistant managing editor
for metro news, will become assistant managing editor for
technology, a newly created position.
</P>
<P>
   Political editor Doug Bailey, 45, was named senior assistant
metropolitan editor for health and science. He will succeed Nils
Bruzelius, 52, who will become foreign editor. The current foreign
editor, Sam Allis, 52, will move to a reporting job.
</P>
<P>
   Business editor Larry Edelman, 37, will replace Bailey as
political editor. Peter Mancusi, 44, senior assistant business
editor, takes over as business editor; Bennie DiNardo, 41, an
assistant magazine editor, becomes senior assistant business
editor.
</P>
<P>
   Living editor Nick King, 52, was appointed editor of the Sunday
magazine. Fiona Luis, 34, an assistant living editor, will assume
King's position. Evelynne Kramer, 55, the magazine editor, will
take a senior editing job still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Storin said two of his immediate lieutenants,
managing editor Gregory Moore and executive editor Helen Donovan,
will shift responsibilities. Donovan, 51, now in charge of the
daily Globe, will oversee the Sunday paper. In the case of Moore,
44, Storin said the change would provide ``a great opportunity for
Greg to operate more on his own day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   While the moves appeared to be steps down for some of the
affected editors, Storin said he did not believe that ``anybody
involved with these changes is unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin, a Globe veteran who has been editor for six years, said
in response to a question that he could not recall a reshuffling of
management jobs in the newsroom involving more people.
</P>
<P>
   Also in response to a question, Storin said the impetus for the
changes did not come from the resignations of former Globe
columnists Patricia Smith or Mike Barnicle, at least not directly.
He said the only possible link was that last summer's turmoil may
have left a ``subliminal'' sense that it was ``time to move
forward.'' The Globe asked for Smith's resignation last June after
she admitted fabricating parts of columns. Two months later,
Barnicle resigned after he was unable to substantiate facts in a
column.
</P>
<P>
   Erosion in the Globe's Sunday circulation, which dropped 1
percent over the six months that ended last Sept. 30, is an
industry-wide problem related to changing lifestyles, according to
Storin. In the Globe's case, a price increase also contributed to
the falloff, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Summarizing the reason for the changes, Storin said: ``If you
put good people in good positions, good things are going to happen.
That's the underlying philosophy here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
