<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC TO ALLOW OUTSIDERS TO OVERSEE ACTIVITIES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By PAUL MONTGOMERY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The International Olympic Committee is
near completion of an ethics panel that for the first time will
allow outsiders a role in overseeing its activities.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Carrard, a Swiss lawyer who serves as the committee's
executive director, said Monday that the concept of an independent
panel composed of two IOC members and three outsiders had won
approval from the IOC's 11-member executive board after a meeting
Monday morning. He would say nothing about the proposed non-IOC
members except to describe them as ``very senior independent
personalities'' of worldwide renown and with ``impeccable
credentials.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrard, who has frequently been brought forward for damage
control in the IOC's burgeoning ethics crisis, spoke at a news
conference on the eve of a three-day international meeting here on
doping in sports. The meeting was planned before the outbreak in
November of the bribery scandal involving the 2002 Winter Olympics
in Salt Lake City, a scandal that has since spread to include other
cities that allegedly paid bribes or gave favors to IOC members in
an effort to attract the Olympics. In the last months, ethics
questions have overshadowed doping questions at the lakeside
quarters of the IOC here.
</P>
<P>
   Carrard said the ethics panel and its proposed members would be
submitted for approval to the full IOC, now down to 106 voting
members from 118 a year ago. Three members have died, four have
resigned as a result of accusations of corruption and five have
been suspended pending expulsion by a plenary session next month.
</P>
<P>
   The doping congress, which brings together 650 delegates from
government and sports, is intended to forge new enforcement
mechanisms for world athletics. Spurred by a series of doping
scandals that enveloped the Tour de France cycling race last
summer, the congress is the largest held so far. The doping problem
in sports has, by wide agreement, so far defeated efforts at
control, but in advance statements, participants here still hold
out hope.
</P>
<P>
   One major proposal involves the creation of a worldwide
independent doping control agency that would establish enforcement
standards to keep pace with the inventions of new drugs. Juan
Antonio Samaranch, the 78-year-old president of the IOC, has said
he would like an agency headed by an IOC executive, possibly Prince
Alexandre de Merode, a Belgian who has led the IOC medical
commission since its inception 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Barry R. McCaffrey, director of the White
House Office of National Drug Control Policy, say the IOC lacks the
credibility to effectively run the agency. They say it should be
completely separate, with open books, open finances and democratic
votes.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey will attend the conference as part of the U.S.
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal under consideration is for urine and blood
samples taken from athletes in competition to be frozen for future
testing when detection techniques are more advanced. That, too, is
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC is also at odds with the international federations for
soccer, cycling and tennis about suspension of athletes detected
taking drugs. The IOC has proposed suspension from competition for
two years for the first offense, and for life for the second.
Soccer and cycling say that two years is too much for participants
in their sports, since a professional's career is 15 years or so,
whereas other Olympic sports allow more time to recoup lost years.
</P>
<P>
   In all the debate, which goes on until the adoption of a final
declaration on Thursday, the shaky position of the IOC at the
center of world sports is likely to be the main issue. When the
conference was planned last year, the IOC was alone in the field,
but the bribery scandals have undermined its position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-NYT     02-01 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ELWAY AND SHANAHAN, A VICTORY MADE IN PICTURES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was a blue loose-leaf notebook in the hands of Mike
Shanahan early in Super Bowl XXXIII that, in part, became the key
to unlocking the Atlanta defense in Denver's 34-19 championship
victory here on Sunday. It was a book of pictures, snapshots of the
Atlanta defensive sets early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   There on the Broncos bench after Denver's initial offensive
drives sat Shanahan, the Denver head coach, and to his right,
quarterback John Elway. Huddling. Studying. Both flipping the pages
back and forth. Elway would point in the book and Shanahan would,
too, and there was give and take between them and nodding and
nudging.
</P>
<P>
   These two guys were in school, in their own karma, in sync,
privately but so publicly working and relating smack in the middle
of Super Bowl XXXIII. There was clamoring in the stands surrounding
them and clashing on the field in front of them, but little
appeared to matter to both on the Broncos bench as they intensely
brainstormed during the game while the Denver defense performed on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Every team reviews photos of opposing defense during games, but
this scene represented something special. There was more than a
decade of familiarity between Shanahan and Elway at work, a span
that has born mutual respect and sharpened talents and genuine
growth. The kind of relationship where one man can look the other
squarely in the eye and see his own reflection.
</P>
<P>
   Get the picture?
</P>
<P>
   ``That book had our first 15 or so plays in it and a look at
their defensive sets in response,'' Shanahan explained. ``On the
left side were pictures of a play before the snap; on the right
side were pictures of the same play one-and-a-half seconds after
the snap. So, add it up and you've got 30 or so pictures. We called
two or three plays early with some very unusual formations to see
how Atlanta would react. From that we could tell in the pictures
that the safeties were really biting on the run and on action in
front of them. That told us enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, the 80-yard touchdown pass to Rod Smith was not in the
game plan. We put that pattern in where he would run at and then by
the safety after we read the pictures. You never know the way the
game is going to go. But it's nice to have a quarterback like John
where you expect him to pick things up, that little has to be
repeated. In our conversation over there on the bench during that
time, I didn't ask him what does he think about this or that.
That's my job. My job is to think, to come up with the adjustments
and not to overload him. His job is to play quarterback and I try
and keep his mind free to do that. But he knows what is going on in
the book and on the field. He knows how to look people off with his
passes and play with a commanding presence. I really thought that
John or Shannon Sharpe would be the MVP in the game. John earned
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach and quarterback. A signature duo on any Super Bowl
champion team. We have seen Lombardi and Starr. Namath and Eubanks.
Shula and Griese. Knoll and Bradshaw. Gibbs and Williams. Walsh and
Montana. All Super Bowl-winning head coach/quarterback duos. Maybe
only Walsh and Montana of the San Francisco 49ers match the
chemistry, respect and modern-day offensive artistry of Shanahan
and Elway.
</P>
<P>
   In other ways, this is a duo whose personal relationship stands
alone in Super Bowl history.
</P>
<P>
   Get the picture?
</P>
<P>
   ``You never really know what is behind some of those
relationships in past Super Bowls and what the people involved
really think about each other,'' Shanahan said. ``It can be
personal or it can be strictly business; the people involved are
really the only ones who know.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met John I was 31 and he was 24. I was the new
assistant coach in Denver and he was the new quarterback and we
sort of started our careers together. We studied film and grew
together. Now, I was in San Francisco for three years later in my
career and Steve Young is one of the classiest people you will ever
meet, but we didn't bond like that. John was hungry and wanted to
be the best and he was not happy because he wanted to win the Super
Bowl. The tag had already been put on him that he was the best and
he should win at least one. But the biggest problem was he never
had a run game and nor a power running game and nor a defense that
could stop the run. That means everything to winning a Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   So does the supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years Elway has been complemented by running
back Terrell Davis; by big, tall dangerous receivers who are easy
targets with sure hands; by an offensive line that has been
exacting, and by a defense that is unsung but, in every way, has
proved its mettle as special, tough and impacting. Elway has been
complemented by an owner in Pat Bowlen who has stroked him, who
understood Elway's ability and stature and cultivated it, creating
an environment where the Broncos would always look forward,
stretching for new heights rather than leveling at a common
plateau.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, Elway gained Shanahan. He coached Elway as an
assistant from 1984 through 1987 and then again from 1989 through
1991. And then in 1995 Shanahan returned to Denver as head coach,
and put himself in charge of nearly every Bronco detail ranging
from personnel to plays and beyond. He picked the Denver roster
apart, pulling here, tugging there. He set new standards. He
created new, imaginative offensive designs and placed a supporting
staff of coaches around himself and of players around Elway that
would boost Denver to a record of 55-18 in all games under Shanahan
in the last three seasons. That would boost Denver to consecutive
Super Bowl titles.
</P>
<P>
   They have done it together, Shanahan and Elway, with their
families involved and with their egos between them in check and
with love abounding between them. And now it may be over. Elway has
hinted that he will retire after 16 pro seasons, though he said
here on Monday that he has not closed the door, that he could,
indeed, return for another season.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan was asked if he could entice Elway into coming back by
promising him that he could sit out five or so games and simply
rest, or by promising he could sit out more practices, more routine
drills?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I couldn't do that to the team and John wouldn't,
either,'' Shanahan said. ``He's too smart for that. He knows and I
know that is not the way to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Get the picture?
</P>
<P>
   The kind of relationship where one man can look the other
squarely in the eye and see his own reflection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
