<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-INVEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ARE URGED TO `TAKE CARE OF YOUR OWN BUSINESS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Many women don't know enough about financial matters
to trust their own judgments, unfairly blame men for their own
money woes and spend a lot more time on their appearances than
their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's how some female financial experts see it.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that stereotypes don't die easily, even in a politically
correct age, female financial experts continue to play up what they
describe as noticeable differences between the sexes when it comes
to money matters _ all in the hopes of inspiring their sisters to a
greater degree of confidence and control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men grow up figuring they'll have a wife and kids that they'll
have to take care of,'' said Tessa Albert Warschaw, a
psychotherapist and financial author. ``With women, there's still
an expectation that someone will give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The objectives of men and women may be pretty much the same _
save sufficiently and generate enough investment profits to live
comfortably and enjoy security heading into old age.
</P>
<P>
   Yet women apparently use different means _ and not altogether
successful ones _ to achieve those ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference comes in the fact that women, more than men,
have not been socialized to talk about money,'' said Laura Wolf,
managing director at Smith Barney Asset Management in New York.
``Women want to be educated about investing, but too often we're
afraid even to ask the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Warschaw, Wolf and other female money experts drove home the
message of self-reliance during a talk last week in Phoenix that
drew more than 250 people, mostly women.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times do you sign a paper without reading it?''
Warschaw asked the crowd. ``Don't blame him if you don't take care
of your own business.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than challenge such statements, many spectators agreed
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel women have been left out (of family financial
decisions) by men who want to protect them,'' said Marge Lazarus of
Scottsdale. ``But I also think some women want to be left out.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny Wolford of Scottsdale said she regularly sees friends
facing financial disruptions when they divorce or separate because
they didn't take the time to educate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not prepared when the time comes, it can be a
shock,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Money as a source of security was a dominant theme at the
seminar, which was sponsored by brokerage Salomon Smith Barney and
focused on divorce and widowhood. Almost everyone in the audience
who posed a question asked about such things as estate planning,
insurance or starting an investment plan. Nobody asked about
options, gold, hot mutual funds, day trading or Internet stocks _
likely fodder for a male-dominated crowd.
</P>
<P>
   To Wolford, that was an indication women can make better
investors than men _ a contention with which many financial experts
agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men have a greater tendency to trade, they're too impatient
and they don't do as much research as they should,'' said Wolford,
who belongs to a Valley investment club. ``I know my husband and I
don't see eye to eye on investing.''
</P>
<P>
   The panelists, who also included attorney Jacalyn Barnett and
Michele Williams, a vice president in Citibank's estate-planning
and trust division, steered the audience toward a fairly banal list
of financial recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure you know what you own and what you owe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Find out who's managing your investments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Size up your spouse's Social Security and retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Develop a habit of saving.
</P>
<P>
   _ Draw up an estate plan and amend it periodically.
</P>
<P>
   _ Invest small amounts on a regular basis _ an approach known as
dollar-cost averaging.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider prenuptial agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Although many perceived differences between men and women are
hard to prove, one gender distinction is a fact: Women live longer
than men on average, which means they have a greater need to make
their money last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are usually the ones left behind,'' said Lauri Lazarus,
who owns a Phoenix physical-therapy practice. ``They have a
responsibility to protect their money, regardless of which spouse
earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Longer life expectancy is a doubled-edged sword that partially
negates the gains women have made in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that women are better educated and making
more money, but the bad news is that they'll outlive it,'' Warschaw
said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial responsibility for women was the theme of the seminar,
and the speakers clearly indicated that there remains plenty of
work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the amount of time that young women spend on
their bodies compared to their portfolios,'' Warschaw said, ``you
can tell what they think is more important.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russ Wiles can be reached at 444-8616 or at
russ.wiles(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
