<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL NOTEBOOK: SHANAHAN GIVES ELWAY A DEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Fresh from his second consecutive Super Bowl victory,
John Elway stood before a crowd of reporters Monday morning and
left open the possibility, however slight, that he would return
next season to go for three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice to come back and three-peat,'' he said, quite
aware that it has never been done in the National Football League.
``But it'd be nice to walk away at the level that I'm playing right
now. I don't want to walk away too late, but I also know that if I
play like I played last night that I can play a little bit longer.
There will be a bunch of things that go into the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all week and I said this last year that it's a 90
percent chance I'm going to quit,'' Elway said. ``But the last
thing I want to do is shut the door. I don't want to say that I'm
done, then get into March or April and say that I can play one more
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway said he would talk to his wife and children, his parents
and Coach Mike Shanahan as he ponders whether at age 38, coming off
a season in which he missed four starts with hamstring and back
injuries, he wants to do this one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said Monday that he would give Elway about two months
to decide whether he wanted to return. But the truth is, Shanahan
would probably like to know right now what Elway wants to do.
That's because the free-agency signing period in the NFL begins
Feb. 13, and if Elway is not coming back, the Broncos might want to
act quickly to bolster their quarterback situation, where the
veteran Bubby Brister is now No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Shanahan expressed patience Monday when asked
how long he would wait for Elway to give him an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can tell us by the draft, that would help us out,''
Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   The college draft will take place April 17. But since the
Broncos may already have a quarterback-in-waiting in Brian Griese,
a rookie out of Michigan this season, it is conceivable that Denver
will be less interested in drafting a top prospect and more intent
on acquiring a veteran through free agency or a trade.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, Shanahan nominated the 36-year-old Brister
as the incumbent if Elway did retire. And Brister did have a good
season in 1998, going 4-0 as Elway's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Brister completed almost 60 percent of his passes and threw for
10 touchdowns and only 3 interceptions. He has not been the No. 1
quarterback for an NFL team since 1990, however, when he started
for the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   STINGY DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   The usually overlooked, and sometimes maligned, Broncos defense
roared through three playoff games yielding all of two touchdowns.
And the last one it allowed came in the closing minutes Sunday
night, when the game had already been decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty special,'' the defensive coordinator Greg
Robinson said. ``It really is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins did not score a touchdown in the divisional
playoff. The Jets produced only one, on a Curtis Martin run, and
that was set up by a blocked punt that gave the Jets the ball on
Denver's 1-yard line. The only other touchdown was Terance Mathis'
3-yard reception from Chris Chandler on Sunday night with the
Falcons trailing, 34-13, and 2 minutes 4 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   REEVES GOES 0 FOR 4
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves has been to the Super Bowl nine times as a player,
assistant coach and head coach. But with the Falcons' loss on
Sunday night he joined Minnesota's Bud Grant, Buffalo's Marv Levy
and Don Shula of Baltimore and Miami as the only head coaches whose
teams lost four games. Reeves' previous three came with Denver.
</P>
<P>
   AN UNEASY FEELING
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan looked around Pro Player Stadium before the Super
Bowl and felt uneasy. The last time the Broncos were there, for a
Monday night game on Dec. 21, they lost to the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   He spotted Jerry Seeman, the league's senior director of
officiating, and told him: ``The last time I was in this stadium I
went against a team that had no penalties. What is the chance of
that happening again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Zero,'' Seeman said.
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong. The Falcons were called for no penalties while the
Broncos had four, not that it ultimately mattered.
</P>
<P>
   The usually tight-lipped Shanahan did not seem concerned Monday,
and said, with feigned annoyance, ``Jerry Seeman, where are you
now?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
