<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-REEVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7 WEEKS AFTER HEART SURGERY, REEVES SEEKS REST FROM FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Dan Reeves was up before daybreak Monday, packing his
bags for the trip home. Only 49 days removed from heart-bypass
surgery, the Atlanta Falcons' coach talked of sleep deprivation and
the effects of his team's emotional playoff roller-coaster ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, I've got to take some time off, strictly because
I need some rest,'' Reeves said, sitting in a chair near the
Airport Hilton lobby. ``I need to get away where football doesn't
mean anything _ not even mentioned.''
</P>
<P>
   During the rest of this week, Reeves plans to attend to the
final details of this season, which ended painfully for him on
Sunday night with the Falcons' 34-19 loss to the Denver Broncos in
Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next week, he will begin a vacation with his wife, Pam,
lasting up to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old native of Americus, Ga., is reasonably sure of
one thing: He wants to fulfill the remaining three years of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't feel any inclination whatsoever not to do what my
contract calls for,'' Reeves said. ``As long as it's fun. We've got
things going. I'm back home and among family and friends. Very few
people have a chance to be a head coach, and to do it where you're
born and raised has really been special.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves acknowledged, however, that there might be a health
factor in his desire to continue coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not something that's come to my mind; now all of a
sudden you're questioning it,'' he said. ``I think you have to
evaluate everything. But hopefully it'll work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves did not particularly second-guess his cornerback Ray
Buchanan for guaranteeing an Atlanta victory, or himself for the
Falcons' failed fourth-down attempt from the Denver 26-yard line
early in the second quarter. Atlanta was trailing at the time, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like we had to score a lot of points,'' Reeves said.
``They're a powerful offensive football team, and they were doing
exactly what we thought they were going to do in short yardage. Had
a play that we really loved _ in fact the Giants ran it in their
game against them. I thought they would jam it up thinking it was
short yardage. We tossed it outside and we just didn't execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Anderson was stopped for a loss of 2 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds after the game ended Sunday, Reeves sought out Denver
quarterback John Elway in an effort to congratulate him despite the
fact that Elway has been critical of Reeves, his former coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to do it and there was no way,'' Reeves said. ``And
really the only way you could do it was to find out where he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's a big reason I'm where I am today. When you're
competing against him, you're not happy for him as far as winning.
But when the game's over, it's over. There wasn't any problem there
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his 16-3 Falcons, Reeves called them overachievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel like when we walk on the field we can beat
anybody,'' he said. ``But we also can get beat by anybody if we
don't play well. I don't think anybody walks on the field and all
of sudden fears the Atlanta Falcons. I think they respect us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
