<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S POLITICAL INSIDERS SHARE WISDOM ON IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ They've sat in the inner sanctum, like Washington
power attorney Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   They are the consummate behind-the-scenes movers and shakers.
They are the right-hand advisers. As Jordan takes his turn today
with the deposition squad in President Clinton's impeachment trial,
I seek out the wisdom of Arizona's most trusted political insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, I find only one who will talk on the record.
</P>
<P>
   Others, declining to be identified, note what happened to Jordan
when HE &UR; opened his mouth. &QL; 
Jordan, perhaps the most intimate confidant of Bill Clinton's
kitchen cabinet, is expected to be grilled - again - about the
advice he gave the president regarding his sexual fling with Monica
Lewinsky and his role in helping the former White House intern find
a job.
</P>
<P>
   One guru of Arizona's business and political world declines to
be identified at all, pointing to the trouble Jordan has gotten
himself into. ``Nothing good comes out of being too public,''
explains this powerhouse, who has counseled many Hispanic
lawmakers. ``I hope you understand.''
</P>
<P>
   I turn to the governor's office to see what insights can be
found there.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jordan, Rick Collins is skilled at skirting questions about
the impeachment trial that could be viewed as controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the one to ask. I'm too busy focusing on naughty
legislators right now,'' says Collins, the chief of staff for Gov.
Jane Hull, referring to lawmakers who weren't budging on
legislation important to the administration. ``I'll pass on it, if
that's all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to other political insiders aren't returned.
</P>
<P>
   But Jay Heiler has plenty to say. He was the right-hand man for
Gov. Fife Symington, who resigned from office after being indicted
for fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like to be standing by someone who is under
fire,'' says the former chief of staff. ``But you can't let
yourself become divorced from the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Now practicing law and cultivating his public affairs consulting
business, Heiler says if he could advise Jordan, he'd give him this
message: ``The duty to tell the truth is more important than his
duties of loyalty to his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, Heiler then offers a more personal view of the
affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want my peanut gallery view, Washington and everything
happening there has become so irrelevant and distasteful to the
average citizen,'' says Heiler. ``That's why no one cares.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
As President Clinton's impeachment trial progresses, Julie Amparano
will be taking the pulse of people in the Valley. Do they care
about President Clinton's trial? Do they want him removed from
office? What does captivate Americans? She looks for the answers.
Amparano can be reached at 444-8394, or at
julie.amparano(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
