<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-TIME-760(2TAKES)     02-01 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TIME-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER JOINS FORCES WITH AT&AMP;T 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Texas, Calif.)  (lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ AT&AMP;T Corp. and Time Warner Inc. joined forces on
Monday to sell local telephone service over Time Warner's millions
of cable television lines, a venture that could provide consumers
with a major alternative to the Baby Bells and GTE Corp., which now
dominate that $100 billion business.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, the leading long-distance company, and Time Warner, the
entertainment giant that serves 12.6 million cable television
customers in 33 states, said they would sell local phone service in
one or two undisclosed Time Warner markets this year, with a goal
of expanding the offering in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also aimed for savings of at least 20 percent over
the competition. A customer's telephone would function normally,
but the wall connection would connect to the same outside cable
that provides TV service.
</P>
<P>
   After it finishes acquiring Tele-Communications Inc., the No. 2
cable company, later this year, AT&AMP;T also plans to offer local
phone service using cable lines in 10 of TCI's markets, including
Chicago, Dallas and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   For Time Warner's 1.1 million subscribers in New York City, the
deal could bring a widespread local phone alternative to Bell
Atlantic Corp. within a few years. Time Warner is the main cable
television company in Manhattan and in parts of Brooklyn, Queens
and Staten Island. The Bronx is served almost entirely by
Cablevision Systems Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Coming seven months after the announcement of the TCI deal,
Monday's agreement put AT&AMP;T in position to pose a serious threat in
coming years to the Baby Bells and GTE.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has about half of the $80 billion long-distance market. It
stopped providing local phone service to settle a federal antitrust
suit in 1984, but the Telecommunications Act of 1996 removed many
regulatory barriers and it allows AT&AMP;T to re-enter that business.
</P>
<P>
   Were it to fully exploit the agreements it now has with cable
carriers, AT&AMP;T could offer local phone service to more than 40
percent of the United States' homes.
</P>
<P>
   For Time Warner, Monday's agreement largely answered years of
questions about how the media titan would use advances in digital
technology to expand its cable television business to provide much
more than TV programming. While the initial agreement between AT&AMP;T
and Time Warner covers only telephone service, the two companies
said Monday that they would try to enlarge its scope to include
high-speed links to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a significant step in our strategy of offering
broadband communications in our consumer business,'' said Michael
Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's chairman, using communications jargon for
advanced, high-speed services. He said that AT&AMP;T's goal was to be
able to offer local service to as many as 65 percent of U.S. homes.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, before Armstrong took over as AT&AMP;T's chairman,
the company was struggling to break into local communications
markets using the copper telephone wires owned by the Bell
companies. But when AT&AMP;T agreed to buy TCI, it became clear that
AT&AMP;T saw television cables as its lines to the future. It was the
apparent depth of AT&AMP;T's commitment that brought Time Warner to the
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, there have been discussions and we have looked at
this capacity of our plant for some time,'' said Gerald Levin, Time
Warner's chairman. ``But we never could have made the arrangement
with an AT&AMP;T that hadn't already committed itself to cable. It
built a form of trust and compatibility that wouldn't otherwise be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said AT&AMP;T was already negotiating to form joint
ventures with other big cable companies, though he would not
identify them. The other cable giants _ including Comcast, Cox and
Cablevision _ seem likely. Leo Hindery Jr., TCI's president, who is
set to run the cable operations of the combined AT&AMP;T-TCI, said he
expected AT&AMP;T to announce deals with additional cable carriers by
late spring.
</P>
<P>
   Media One Group Inc. owns 25 percent of Time Warner
Entertainment, a partnership that owns many of Time Warner's cable
operations, so Media One must approve Monday's deal. Steve Lang, a
Media One spokesman, said that his company had not yet seen details
but that Media One was itself considering a similar deal with AT&AMP;T,
as well as with other partners.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and Time Warner said their deal would not require approval
from federal or state regulators. A Time Warner spokesman, however,
ventured that the agreement could require approval from some local
authorities. It was unclear Monday whether New York City would have
to approve the deal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In any case, some analysts said Monday it was unlikely that AT&AMP;T
and Time Warner would make New York City a priority for introducing
the local phone service. Communications companies are often slow to
bring new services to New York City because the sheer scale of the
city can pose unique technical challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Communications executives also sometimes want to work kinks out
of their new products before they subject them to hard-to-please
New York City consumers.
</P>
<P>
   For Time Warner's shareholders, perhaps the critical element of
the agreement is that it does not require Time Warner to make any
new investments. Time Warner is already in the middle of a $4
billion project to make its cable systems ready to offer advanced
digital services generally, but AT&AMP;T has agreed to carry the
financial load of providing local telephone capability.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, AT&AMP;T would pay Time Warner $15 for each of the
homes passed by Time Warner's cable lines as Time Warner makes the
basic upgrades in those lines. Because Time Warner's systems pass
about 20 million homes (though only 12.6 million homes subscribe),
those payments could total $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T also agreed to spend about $300 million to provide backup
power systems for Time Warner's cable hubs. The additional power
units are meant to help ensure that telephones linked to the cable
network continue to function even if the television part of the
system malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   Each new subscriber would result in an additional AT&AMP;T
investment of between $300 and $500 for switching equipment and for
a unit that would sit on the side of each house that would connect
the house's standard telephones to the cable system.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T guaranteed that 25 percent of homes passed by Time Warner's
lines would subscribe to the new phone service within six years,
and said that Time Warner would get up to $6 every month for each
of those customers. In addition, AT&AMP;T said it would give Time
Warner 15 percent of customer revenue exceeding $100 a month if the
average per-home bill in a given market came to more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   In return, AT&AMP;T owns 77.5 percent of the new joint venture,
which is meant to last at least 20 years, while Time Warner owns
the rest. The companies expect the new venture to become profitable
after three years.
</P>
<P>
   Investors appeared to view the deal as better for AT&AMP;T than for
Time Warner. AT&AMP;T's shares gained $2.8125 to close at $93.5625 on
the New York Stock Exchange, while Time Warner's shares lost 18.75
cents to close at $62.3125. Shares of GTE and of each of the Baby
Bells except BellSouth Corp. also lost value.
</P>
<P>
   But demonstrating that the Bells are not standing still,
executives close to Bell Atlantic Corp., the No. 1 local phone
company, said that company would announce a deal on Tuesday with
IBM to sell an IBM product that links home computers with one
another using either the standard phone lines or cable television
wires within a home. The product would cost about $1,000, the
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatives to the Bells continue to emerge, however.
Executives close to Psinet Inc., a big provider of Internet service
for business customers, said Psinet would announce Tuesday that it
planned to offer Internet links using advanced wireless systems in
50 markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
