<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-LOTTO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida lottery rolls over to $64 million
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Florida's lottery jackpot has rolled over to
$64 million, the largest in the nation at the moment and fourth
largest in state history.
</P>
<P>
   The pot grows as Gov. Jeb Bush nears a decision on whether to
let Florida join the 20-state Powerball lottery after two years of
declining Lotto sales.
</P>
<P>
   With five days of ticket sales left until the next drawing
Saturday night, the jackpot is already the largest in Florida since
$81.2 milllion in April 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 4 p.m. (Monday), sales were $4,020 per minute, about four
times what they were a week ago,'' said lottery spokesman Dave
Rhea, referring to sales of the $1 tickets. ``On Saturday about 7
p.m. (shortly before the drawing produced no winner), they peaked
at $27,600 per minute. So yes, it's busy.''
</P>
<P>
   The question for Bush is whether the presumed benefits of
Powerball _ such as sales generated by occasional huge jackpots
including a world-record $161.5 million _ outweigh an expected
decrease in Lotto sales. Sales contribute hundreds of millions of
dollars annually to state schools and scholarships. Bush aides and
Powerball officials didn't return calls Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A $64 million jackpot could be taken in annual payments spread
over 30 years or an immediate lump sum of about half the value, $32
million. Lottery officials conservatively expect the jackpot to
grow above $70 million this week, though if sales remain brisk it
could well go higher.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
