<SLUG> BC-AIR-SLOWDOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AIRLINES PILOTS THREATEN A WORK SLOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev.)  (ms) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pilots at American Airlines are threatening a work slowdown if a
dispute over the nation's second-largest carrier's recent
acquisition of a small airline that flies in the western states is
not resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots contend that the Dec. 23 purchase of Reno Air, which
is based in Nevada and flies to 16 cities mostly in the West,
violates the so-called scope clause in their contract. That clause
guarantees that any planes owned by American will be flown by
members of the Allied Pilots Association, the independent union
that represents its 9,200 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   American said that it fully intends to integrate Reno's 25 jets
and 300 pilots into its much larger network but that it would take
12 to 18 months because Reno's airplanes need to be upgraded and
pilots from both carriers need to be retrained.
</P>
<P>
   Reno pilots earn roughly half what their counterparts at
American are paid, about $150,000 a year on average plus a generous
retirement payout.
</P>
<P>
   The union fears that American's real agenda is to maintain Reno
as a separate low-cost carrier, something the American pilots have
not agreed to in past contract negotiations with the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line pilots are about as angry about this as I have seen
them in my eight years at the company,'' said Drew Engelke, a pilot
and spokesman for the union. ``They believe that scope is the heart
of the contract and they hold it very dear.''
</P>
<P>
   American executives were also steamed. Don Carty, chief
executive of the AMR &UR;  &LR; Corp., American's parent, blew up at a Jan. 8
meeting with union leaders and stormed out, according to Engelke
and others. American confirmed that the meeting took place but
declined to comment on what happened. On Saturday, Rich LaVoy, the
pilot union's president, told members in a telephone message that
he had sent a letter to Carty telling him that if the airline went
ahead with plans to sell seats on Reno flights as if they were part
of the American network it ``would create a major dispute between
us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the parlance of the Railway Labor Act, the arcane law that
governs labor relations in the airline industry, a ``major
dispute'' allows the union to strike or take other, less
disruptive, actions.
</P>
<P>
   Many pilots were urging the union to move this week after a
Sunday deadline passed without an agreement. But union leaders
convinced members to give negotiators an extra week to try to
resolve the dispute. They have proposed that American commit to
completing the integration of Reno by June 23. Talks between the
union and the airline are scheduled to resume Tuesday. The union's
negotiators will brief the board of directors in a conference call
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a week that doesn't produce much of anything, there
will be a sense that we need to increase the pressure on
management,'' said Gregg Overman, another union spokesman. ``What
form that takes I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The union's most likely action, according to members and
analysts, would be to encourage pilots to refuse to do
discretionary flying. That is what the pilots did last summer, when
the union accused American of putting too many of its passengers on
Canadian Airlines, one of American's international partners.
American was forced to cancel 500 of its 6,300 flights in both July
and August and to reduce its schedule 2 percent to 4 percent in
September and October before it agreed to reduce the number of
Canadian flights also sold as American.
</P>
<P>
   If the pilots decided to decline discretionary flying, American
flights would not be affected until the end of the month, though
the airline might cancel some flights in advance and book
passengers on others.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
