u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGOLA-WAR-ART-NYT &LR;      02-01 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGOLA-WAR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIDE OF REFUGEES WASHES THROUGH TOWN IN ANGOLA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   N'DALATANDO, Angola _ ``Unita was coming in, and I was afraid I
would have my head cut off, so I took my family and ran,'' said
Sebastian Domingos, 34, a war refugee in a tattered shirt and a
baseball cap with a very faded Calvin Klein logo on it. ``They
would find out I don't support them, and that's what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The thatched hut in which he has lived for six weeks in a
refugee camp in this provincial capital is no temporary shelter.
The mud-brick camp was built in the 1960s when N'dalatando was full
of refugees from Zaire, and like a hermit crab's shell, it gets
different owners as the tides of displaced people shift with the
ebb and flow of war.
</P>
<P>
   Now it houses people fleeing south from the towns of Bula Atumba
and Banga, where the rebel Unita movement and the Angolan
government are fighting. As Domingos spoke, there were two busloads
of people fleeing west from Malanje only a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the capital, Luanda, is acting nonchalant, the
rebels are seizing towns relatively close by.
</P>
<P>
   N'dalatando, 120 miles southeast of Luanda, is in government
hands, and the local police said there had been no fighting nearby.
But it is a touchy place, a hive of police officers and
citizen-soldiers toting AK-47s, because it has an airport and
controls the main east-west paved road.
</P>
<P>
   Bula Atumba and two nearby towns that Unita has seized are only
100 miles from Luanda, and there are reliable reports that armed
rebels are patrolling Caxito, which is only 50 miles from Luanda.
</P>
<P>
   Malanje, Cuito and Huambo, the chief cities of the central
plateau, have been under artillery attack. And the eastern
two-thirds of the country is still considered Unita territory even
where the government controls cities.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 25 the government conceded that it had lost Mbanza
Congo, capital of the northernmost province. The town sits on the
road to Soyo on the coast, where Texaco has offshore drilling
operations, an important source of government income.
</P>
<P>
   The fall of nearby towns does not mean that the capital is
doomed. Historically, this has been a guerrilla war, with the
government holding cities and the rebels terrorizing the
countryside, overrunning some urban garrisons, and eventually
melting back into the bush.
</P>
<P>
   What is crucial to the government are the coastal towns: Luanda,
which is near the country's only oil refinery; Lobito and Benguela
with their big military bases; Soyo with its oil, and the whole
oil-rich province of Cabinda, separated from Angola proper by a
strip of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   But the speed with which Unita has struck back since the
government tried to smash it in early December has surprised
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Since Luanda has more than a third of the country's 11 million
people, it presumably can defend itself if militias are raised and
stay loyal. The oil enclaves have employed heavily armed private
security in the past, although that did not save two eastern
diamond mines attacked by Unita in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, there are rumors of mercenaries everywhere. A
Portuguese newspaper reported that at least 300 Cuban advisers had
arrived. Its correspondents were promptly deported. The government
admits to only a few ``medical and agricultural advisers'' from
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Jakkie Potgeiter, a military analyst with the Institute for
Security Studies, a South African defense research organization,
said he had heard credible reports that Ukrainians who had sold
artillery and anti-aircraft guns to Unita were helping to operate
them, and sketchier reports that former South African infantry
officers were training Unita troops.
</P>
<P>
   Alcides Sakala, Unita's foreign secretary, suggested that ``for
security reasons'' all foreigners should leave the contested
interior. ``The worst is to come,'' he warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
