<HEADER>
A7831 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-PARENTING-HNS &LR;      02-01 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-PARENTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR WRITES BOOK ON PARENTING FOR AFRICAN-AMERICANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (resend to fix garble) 
 
By BARBARA KARKABI 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) All new parents have the same questions and worries
about their babies, toddlers and preschoolers. Are they healthy?
How can I find the best child care? How do I discipline without
spanking?
</P>
<P>
   But for African-American parents the questions can be even more
challenging. Black mothers and fathers wonder about locating a
pediatrician with the same values or question whether their child
should go to an all-black preschool. They want suggestions about
books with strong black characters and advice on talking to their
children about race and racism.
</P>
<P>
   It was concerns like these, plus her own experiences as a
mother, that compelled Dr. Anne C. Beal to write ``The Black
Parenting Book'' (Broadway Books, $20) with co-authors Linda
Villarosa and Allison Abner. The comprehensive work focuses on the
first five years of a child's life.
</P>
<P>
   So many baby books, for instance, said Beal, talk about newborn
rashes, but don't touch on the rashes and illnesses that are more
common in African-American children, who tend to have dry skin.
Beal discusses those, but she also addresses broader issues like
spirituality, racism, stress and the challenges facing single
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Several other books have been written specifically for black
parents _ perhaps the best-known being ``Raising Black Children``
by Dr. Alvin F. Poussaint. But Beal's book has garnered praise from
parents and pediatricians as a practical book that will help the
parents of America's 3.6 million black children under age 6 deal
with questions for the '90s and into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any combination of this information all in one
source,'' said Binta Chui, a teacher and parent who attended Beal's
book-signing in Houston last month. ``I've seen bits and pieces
here and there. We talked about why we thought black parents need
that kind of book. Most blacks, if they have problems, call their
mother or aunt; we don't turn to books because we feel there is
nothing we can trust. But we need a resource like that to help us
know we are going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   In talking to parents, Beal said, she found the biggest concerns
revolving around racial pride and self-esteem, as well as when to
talk to children about race and racism. For some of the answers,
Beal, a specialist in medicine at Massachusetts General Hospital
and Harvard Medical School, gives examples from her experiences
with her own daughters, now 6 and 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question that seems to present itself at an earlier
time for African-American children,'' she said. ``Children at 3 and
4 are very aware of their environment, and descriptive _ this is
blue, this is green, this is white. But then they will notice that
they look different from other people they see around them, and
they say, `How come I look like this and my day-care teacher looks
like that?' That starts the explanation: `You are African-American
and you have brown skin ... but we come in a range of colors.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beal, who also writes a parenting columnist for Essence
magazine, stressed that the issues are complicated and complex and
must be addressed at appropriate developmental levels. Recognize,
she said, that these questions will come up over and over again and
must be handled in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that we should always teach our children the
truth and never be in the position where they learn one thing and
have to relearn another,'' she said. ``You need to peel it like an
onion and then give them pieces they understand. After they
understand there are differences, then go on to explain that
because there are different races and groupings of people,
sometimes people don't like each other based on the way they look _
whether it's hair, skin or crooked teeth or that they are in a
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later on they can understand that there is a direction that
historically has occurred in this country over these types of
issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Skin-care issues are common early on, when parents ask why their
children are born with a light complexion and wonder if they will
get darker. The answer, Beal said, is yes.
</P>
<P>
   Parents worry about ``cradle cap,'' a type of dermatitis that,
when it heals, often leaves African-American infants with splotches
or ``hyper-pigmented'' areas. Beal assures parents that it's
natural and the normal skin color will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children tend to have more dry skin and are sensitive to a
lot of these beautiful lotions that smell great but have perfumes
which irritate the skin,'' Beal said.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues addressed in the book include asthma, a chronic
disease that is becoming increasingly common in African-American
children, and questions about discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Parents want to know whether they should spank. Beal said that
respect for elders is important in the African-American community,
as is acting in an appropriate fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Af%~
</P>
</TEXT>
