<SLUG> BC-AD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 2 S.F. Ad Agencies Bought by Boston Firm  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ingalls Moranville Advertising and Rockpile Interactive, two San
Francisco ad agencies that focus on technology, have been acquired
by Boston's Arnold Communications, Arnold said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls Moranville's annual billings totaled about $40 million,
and Rockpile's were about $20 million, said Ed Dilworth, Rockpile's
founder and chief executive of the new unit, to be called Arnold
Ingalls Moranville.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the sale were not disclosed, but a knowledgeable source
said the combined price tag was under $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dilworth said he approached Arnold about buying Rockpile after
working with the Boston company on some West Coast account pitches.
But before a sale could be completed, Rockpile, which specialized
in Internet advertising, needed a partner to handle traditional
media. Dilworth then approached Ingalls Moranville, which was
amenable to a combination.
</P>
<P>
   This type of arrangement is becoming more common, said Fred
Schwartz, a partner in the San Francisco interactive agency Left
Field. ``Interactive shops are looking for their other half because
clients are looking for one-stop shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls Moranville, which lost its Infoseek account last year
after Infoseek was bought by Disney, had been owned by the Los
Angeles agency DavisElen Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Ingalls and David Moranville will be co-creative directors
at the new agency.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold is a division of Snyder Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls Moranville's clients included Ascend, Qualcomm and Bally
Gaming. Rockpile's include Digital Chef and Berkeley Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Separately yesterday, CMGI Inc. of Andover, Mass., announced the
acquisition of 2Can Media, a Los Angeles Internet ad agency that
has a San Francisco office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
