<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS TRADE TOP PROSPECT FOR MINOR LEAGUE PITCHERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees traded one of their top infield
prospects, Mike Lowell, to the Florida Marlins on Monday for three
minor league pitchers in the latest effort by General Manager Brian
Cashman to restock the organization's pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, a third baseman who turns 25 this month, had been
regarded as a marginal prospect before the 1997 season, when he
slugged 30 homers in 135 games. Then, last year, after a terrific
spring-training performance, he batted .304 with 26 homers and 99
RBIs for Class AAA Columbus, and went 4 for 15 in eight games with
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1998 season, the Yankees had acquired Scott Brosius
from the Oakland A's, and it was widely assumed within the Yankees'
hierarchy that Lowell would be given a chance to replace Brosius in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Brosius was a stunning success last year, hitting .300,
driving in 98 runs and playing exceptional defense during the
regular season, before winning the most valuable player award in
the World Series. The Yankees re-signed Brosius to a three-year,
$15.75 million deal in November, making Lowell expendable. He will
likely become the Marlins' regular third baseman this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for him,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager,
``because he was going to have to wait a couple of years to play
for us, and he's probably ready to play in the big leagues right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   In return for Lowell, the Yankees received three highly rated
young pitchers, each of whom was involved in a previous trade that
involved a big name. Ed Yarnall, a 23-year-old left-hander, was a
part of the Mets organization until he was shipped to the Marlins
in the package for Mike Piazza. Mark Johnson is a former
first-round pick of the Houston Astros who was sent to Florida in a
trade for outfielder Moises Alou. And Todd Noel is a 20-year-old
right-hander who was a first-round pick of the Chicago Cubs in
1996, then was traded to Florida last season for the reliever Felix
Heredia.
</P>
<P>
   Executives with other teams gave the Yankees high marks for this
trade, saying all three pitchers possess excellent potential and
could develop into major league pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman has been trying to replenish the organization's pitching
in recent months, after the Yankees became somewhat thin in this
area last year. Last February, the Yankees traded their top minor
league pitcher, Eric Milton, to Minnesota as part of the deal for
the second baseman Chuck Knoblauch. During the summer, another
prospect prized by the Yankees, Luis Delos Santos, struggled and
was demoted to Class A, and Ricardo Aramboles, a hard-throwing
right-hander, suffered a major elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are loaded in the big leagues _ with the 20-game
winner David Cone, the left-handers David Wells and Andy Pettitte,
and the right-handers Orlando Hernandez, Hideki Irabu and Ramiro
Mendoza _ but have little in reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never have enough pitching,'' Cashman said. ``Pitching is
the name of the game. If we could utilize Lowell by trading him and
bringing three legitimate prospects into the organization, we were
going to do it.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
