<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Sizing Up Online Brokers  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. charges twice as much as E-Trade Group _
$29.95 versus $14.95 _ for each online brokerage trade it
processes, so it must be twice as good, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gomez Advisors, an independent consulting firm that
compiles a widely followed quarterly report card on 55 Internet
brokers, E-Trade provides generally better online service than
Schwab and has superior research tools on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Another online broker that charges markedly less than Schwab _
DLJ Direct, at $20 per trade _ outranks Schwab in all six of the
performance measures on the Gomez report card.
</P>
<P>
   The old saw that price reflects quality _ that you get what you
pay for _ is becoming less and less reliable in the online
brokerage industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the fierce competition to lure and retain customers in this
rapidly burgeoning industry, online brokers are becoming more and
more similar to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Even bargain-basement firms such as Suretrade ($7.95 per trade)
and Ameritrade ($8) have been adding research, stock charting, news
updates, stock-screening tools and other Web site features that
compare favorably with the offerings long available from industry
leaders such as Schwab and Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade, which a year ago &LR;   &LR; provided little more than a
bare-bones transaction service, now offers its customers research
reports and a stock-screening tool from Market Guide, covering
10,000 public companies. Ameritrade customers also can pull up
earnings estimates from First Call and news updates from Dow Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time one of us comes out with something new and
interesting, the others seek to match it,'' observes Matt Sadler,
Fidelity's senior vice president for brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade, which pioneered online brokerage a scant seven years
ago, has lately embarked on a binge of service-enhancing moves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  It has done so at a steep price, spending more than $100
million in the past year to improve the technology and content of
its Web site. As a result, it reported losses totaling nearly $30
million in the six months ended December 31.
</P>
<P>
   At present, E-Trade has 544,000 customers, according to Piper
Jaffray, or a bit more than one-fourth of industry leader Schwab's
online total.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month alone, E-Trade:
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ONLINE02 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  _Created an online tax-preparation service, allowing customers to
prepare and file federal and state taxes through its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   _Gave its customers direct access to TheStreet.com, a leading
Internet provider of financial news and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   _Struck a deal with United Airlines to provide frequent-flier
miles to people who do business with E-Trade.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade previously made a big splash by adding analyst
recommendations from BancBoston Robertson Stephens and access to
initial public offerings from that firm.
</P>
<P>
   It also maintains its own investor chat room _ evidently the
only one on a brokerage Web site _ where customers can trade rumors
and opinions about stocks and industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focused on creating a one-stop financial-services
center,'' says Lisa Nash, E-Trade's vice president for corporation
communications and customer management.
</P>
<P>
   Its efforts have rocketed E-Trade to the highest rating overall
among the brokers surveyed by Gomez, with an overall score of 7.32
(on a scale from 0 to 10). E-Trade is tied with DLJ Direct in the
quality of its on-site resources _ the tools that customers use to
make investment decisions _ with a score of 8.82.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez bases its ratings on customer questionnaires, its own
observations of the Web sites and interviews with the brokerage
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, despite its top-of-the-line commission, remains the
largest online broker measured both by number of customers _ 2
million _ and share of online trading volume (27.4 percent last
quarter).
</P>
<P>
   Most of those online customers have moved over to Schwab's
Internet site from conventional brokerage accounts. Schwab still
has more than 3 million customers who only trade the old-fashioned
way _ by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the majority of our business, the first point of contact
continues to be the branch'' rather than the Web, says Schwab
spokeswoman Tracey Gordon. ``People want to kick the tires.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the firm's online traders are far more active than
their conventional counterparts. Online trades now account for 61
percent of Schwab's total _ up from 41 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   While the $29.95 that Schwab's online customers pay for each
trade is high by online standards, it is substantially lower than
the $55 minimum Schwab charges for conventional trades.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab has been able to maintain both market leadership and a
high commission because of what might be called the Tiffany factor.
People who shop at Tiffany's pay more for jewelry than they do
elsewhere because of the firm's venerable name and stately
emporiums, and the confidence they inspire.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, Schwab boasts a time-honored name dating back
a quarter-century and a reassuring, tangible presence at nearly 300
branches.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of ONLINE02 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``People want to know that they are buying quality _ a
respectable brand,'' says Alex Stein, a principal with Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   But Schwab's Tiffany-like reputation appears to be losing some
of its luster. Its customer confidence rating, as measured by
Gomez, slipped from 9.05 a year ago to 8.21 in December, ranking it
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The customer confidence rating is based on such factors as
well-trained customer service staffs, easy accessibility to a
firm's Web site and fast response time when customers try to reach
a broker by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab ranks eighth on the Gomez list in overall quality and
fifth in the quality of its on-site resources.
</P>
<P>
   Like other leading online brokers, Schwab has had trouble
maintaining its service standards lately because of the tremendous
surge in online trading volume.
</P>
<P>
   Last quarter, total industry volume surged 34 percent, according
to Credit Suisse First Boston, spurred largely by wild speculation
in Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of Schwab and other firms have found themselves
waiting longer to gain access to broker Web sites, move from page
to page and execute trades. They also are finding it harder to
reach customer-service representatives by telephone when they have
questions or problems.
</P>
<P>
   Teri Felix, Schwab's vice president for electronic brokerage
marketing, acknowledges that the firm's customers have been waiting
longer lately to get their telephone queries answered.
</P>
<P>
   Felix claims that ``less than 20 seconds'' is the Schwab norm,
but that some customers have lately been forced to wait up to seven
minutes to talk to service representatives. However, some Schwab
customers say they have encountered delays as long as 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That could prove a significant setback for Schwab, because in
the past one of the firm's great selling points has been its quick
response to phone calls. If Schwab comes to be perceived as just
another online firm that keeps its phone-in customers eternally on
hold, it could have trouble keeping customers and maintaining its
fees.
</P>
<P>
   As other firms begin to look more and more like Schwab, ``savvy
consumers will take a closer look at the price differential,''
predicts John Payne, an analyst with the Cerulli Associates
consulting firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Novice investors looking for an online broker _ or experienced
investors looking to change their brokers _ can view the complete
Gomez ratings at  &LR; www.gomez.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Another useful resource is the annual report on discount brokers
published by the American Association of Individual Investors. It
includes a section comparing 72 online firms.
</P>
<P>
   The AAII doesn't provide quality rankings. But it does give a
thumbnail listing of each broker's research resources, outlines the
commission structures, and provides other point-by-point
comparisons to help you narrow your choice.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of ONLINE02 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  You can get a copy of the latest report, which was issued last
month, by writing the AAII at 625 N. Michigan Ave., Suite 1900,
Chicago, Ill. 60611-3110, or by calling (312) 280-0170.
</P>
<P>
   While the Gomez and AAII reports will help you sort the wheat
from the chaff, you also ought to explore the broker Web sites
yourself. Most of them let noncustomers take a demonstration tour
that offers a good feel for the online resources.
</P>
<P>
   Only you can decide how many and what kinds of resources you
need. Check out the brokers that offer those resources, then choose
the one that offers them for the lowest commission per trade.
</P>
<P>
   You may decide that you don't need any research help at all _
that a low price is everything. In that case, your logical choice
probably would be Brown &AMP; Co., the lowest-priced online broker at
$5 per trade, and one of the very few that still maintains only a
bare-bones site.
</P>
<P>
   Brown lets you trade securities, of course, and it will display
a history of your transactions, show your current holdings and
balance, and respond to requests for cash from your account. But
that's it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of ONLINE02 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
