<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Charitable Remainder Trust Primer  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Please explain the advantages and disadvantages of a
charitable remainder trust.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Setting up a charitable remainder trust might be worth
your while if you want to liquidate stocks or other assets that
have appreciated greatly, and you have a favorite charity to which
you would like to make a substantial gift.
</P>
<P>
   You can put your assets into a trust, sell them and reinvest the
funds without incurring a capital-gains tax. You get an immediate
charitable deduction for the tax year in which you set up the
trust, and you can withdraw a prearranged portion of the assets
annually for the rest of your life, to help with living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   When you die, the money that remains in the trust will go to the
charity of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   One disadvantage is that your gift to the trust is irrevocable.
If you get into financial trouble later, you can't take the money
back. Nor can you bring the money back into your estate for the
benefit of your heirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never recommend that anyone put more than one-third of
their net worth into one of these trusts,'' says San Francisco
financial planner Norm Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Charitable remainder trusts are a lot more complicated than this
necessarily brief description indicates. For example, the size of
your charitable deduction will depend on your age; in general, the
younger you are, the smaller it will be. And the money you withdraw
from the trust during your lifetime may be taxable as ordinary
income, capital gains or both.
</P>
<P>
   If you are thinking of setting up a charitable remainder trust,
you should first talk out the details with a good financial planner
or tax lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Down Payment Safety
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am planning to buy a house in about three months, using
$50,000 I have saved for a down payment. Where can I put the money
in the meantime to maximize my funds?
</P>
<P>
   A: Whoa! Don't gamble with the money _ not if you really want
that house. If you buy stocks, options, futures or any other risky
investment, you might very well ``maximize'' your funds. But then
again, you might suffer a substantial loss instead.
</P>
<P>
   Because you will need the money soon, you had better keep it in
an insured, interest-bearing account such as a CD. In three months,
your money will have earned several hundred dollars of interest _
enough to buy a nice armchair or appliance to spruce up your new
digs.
</P>
<P>
   Roth IRA Limits
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am currently contributing to a Roth Individual Retirement
Account and would like to continue doing so after I retire. My
retirement income will consist of Social Security, a pension and
interest from bank certificates of deposit. Will I be permitted to
go on contributing to my Roth?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Alas, no _ not with that mix of income. The tax law says
that you can make annual contributions to your Roth IRA equal to
the sum of your ``earned income'' or $2,000, whichever is less. But
Social Security, pensions and bank interest normally don't qualify
as earned income.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MONEYBAG () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Most people might think that a pension or Social Security is
earned income, because you get it in recognition of work you did,''
says Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller. ``But it is
treated as unearned income for tax purposes, because you aren't
working for it at the time you get it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one exception to that rule. If you are forced to retire
early on a disability pension, the money you get from the pension
counts as earned income. However, once you reach normal retirement
age _ as defined by your former employer _ your pension no longer
will be considered earned income.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to continuing qualifying for Roth contributions _ a
laudable goal _ you might find it worthwhile to take a part-time
job. Or, if you have the skills to earn money as a free-lancer or
independent contractor, that money, too, will count as earned
income.
</P>
<P>
   However, bear in mind that if you get carried away and earn a
substantial amount of money after retirement, you can lose part of
your Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   If you are less than 65 years old and drawing Social Security,
you can generate up to $9,600 of earned income per year without
affecting your benefits. But for every $2 you earn beyond that, you
will lose $1 in benefits, says Social Security Administration
spokeswoman Leslie Walker.
</P>
<P>
   If you are at least 65 years old but less than 70, you can earn
up to $15,500 on the side without reducing your Social Security
benefits. Beyond that, you lose $1 for every $3 you earn.
</P>
<P>
   Once you reach age 70, you can earn an unlimited amount without
suffering a Social Security penalty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
