<SLUG> BC-BLADDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Alza Introduces New Bladder-Control Drug  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
A biotech firm has launched a new bladder-control drug, setting up
a marketing battle against another new remedy that also targets
incontinence.
</P>
<P>
   Alza Corp. of Palo Alto said yesterday it has started selling
Ditropan XL, a new one-a-day formula to control weak bladders.
Ditropan XL will compete with Detrol, the incontinence remedy
released last spring by Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For the one in 10 people over 65, mainly women, who suffer from
this embarrassing affliction, yesterday's news means there now are
two pills that claim to restore bladder control with fewer side
effects than previous remedies.
</P>
<P>
   For Alza shareholders, the marketing of Ditropan XL marks a
first. Alza is a 30-year-old firm that has made its living by
developing drug-delivery technologies _ like the NicoDerm patch _
and living off royalties from the firms that sold the actual drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first major product they've taken from start to
finish under their own name,'' said Alex Zisson with the New York
office of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. ``We're betting it won't be the
last.''
</P>
<P>
   Urologist Tim Boone with Baylor College of Medicine in Houston
said Ditropan XL is a new version of the Ditropan drug, which has
been around for 20 years. Ditropan calms the involuntary bladder
muscle contractions that cause frequent or unintentional urination.
</P>
<P>
   But regular Ditropan, taken three times a day, has enough side
effects _ dry mouth, constipation and blurry vision _ that four out
of five people quit using it, Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   Ditropan XL uses Alza's time-release formula to put a day's dose
into a single pill, releasing the drug slowly. In clinical trials,
this timed release relaxed the bladder with fewer side effects,
Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   Detrol, the competing incontinence medicine from Pharmacia, was
the first new drug in a decade to relax the bladder with fewer side
effects than conventional Ditropan. It is taken twice a day. Detrol
has generated more than $55 million in sales since Pharmacia of New
Jersey launched it in April.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Szabo, a urologist with Kaiser Permanente in San
Francisco said neither Alza nor Pharmacia has done the study that
would most benefit consumers _ a head-to-head comparison of
Ditropan XL against Detrol to see which drug offers the most
bladder control with the fewest side effects.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, according to Jeanette Brown, an incontinence
researcher at the University of California at San Francisco Medical
Center, is that other companies are developing even newer drugs for
this bladder ailment.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BLADDER0 (63441 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``The private market has realized that incontinence will only
grow as the population ages,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Zisson, the H&AMP;Q analyst, said Detrol and Ditropan XL both should
do well because doctors have nearly doubled the number of
prescriptions they are writing for incontinence remedies since the
new drugs appeared. He expects Ditropan XL to add upward of $50
million to Alza's revenues in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Alza gained 88 cents yesterday to close at $51.44. Last week,
the company reported year-end net income of $112 million ($1.26 per
share) on revenues of $584 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
