<TEXT>
<P>
   Black and white churches merge
</P>
<P>
   By Glenn Evans
</P>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ A Longview congregation ignored centuries of
Christian division Sunday and agreed with a sister church that the
two assemblies should unite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote is done in both churches, and that means there will
be a new church in Longview by the name of Wesley-McCabe United
Methodist Church,'' Don Meador said to applause and amens from the
members of McCabe United Methodist Church who had just voted to
merge with Wesley United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Meador, district superintendent of the United Methodist Church,
said the merging of the predominantly black McCabe with the mostly
white Wesley would show the community the groups care more for
their religion than their race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we're poised to make a strong witness to our region
about what the church is and what the church must be,'' Meador
said, noting Sunday's Longview News-Journal editorial that included
the anticipated McCabe vote amid praise focused on the recent
hiring of the first blacks as Longview city manager and Longview
Independent School District superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are glad the community celebrates what is happening around
McCabe United Methodist Church, and especially at the start of
Black History Month,'' Meador said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Byron Boyett, pastor of Wesley United Methodist Church,
said last week a significant majority of his flock had approved the
measure the previous Sunday. That congregation, at 1115 S. Mobberly
Ave., had extended the invitation to unite as the McCabe church was
dealing with a crisis with its 102-year-old building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fixing to have to move out of this building,'' said
the Rev. Mary High, pastor of McCabe. ``When they sent the
proposal, we answered it. Hopefully, we're going to have a joint
service next Sunday. That's Communion day, and we couldn't have a
better way to start it.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Meador said the new church will meet at the Wesley site.
Property of both churches becomes the property of the new entity,
Meador told the group of 10 before they filled in secret ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is the third such recent action by predominantly
black and white congregations in the denomination's Texas
Conference, the others being in Beaumont and near Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, writes for the Longview News-Journal, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
