<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD STRENGTHEN RIGHTS OF AIR PASSENGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Ariz.)  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Airlines would have to tell passengers when a
flight had been oversold, why a plane was late or a flight had been
canceled, and how many seats were available for passengers to buy
with frequent-flier miles, under a bill that two senators said they
planned to introduce this week.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also let consumers return tickets within 48 hours
of purchase, even ``nonrefundable'' ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airline profits are soaring, but often respect for basic
rights for the passengers is sinking,'' Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., one
of the bill's sponsors, said Monday in a telephone interview.
``These are the kinds of rules that the corner grocery store has to
comply with. The corner grocery store can't lure people in with
promise of a particular thing at a particular price, and then not
offer it.''
</P>
<P>
   The other sponsor is Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the
Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would define a variety of common airline practices as
anti-competitive, which the Transportation Department has the
authority to stop.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the department could find airlines to be
anticompetitive and then fine them if they failed to ``disclose to
consumers information that would enable them to make informed
decisions about the comparative value of frequent-flier programs
among airlines, including the number of seats redeemable on each
flight.''
</P>
<P>
   David Fuscus, a spokesman for the Air Transport Association, the
trade group of the major airlines, said he could not comment
because he had not seen the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines would also have to disclose all of their fares at a
consumer's request. If a flight did not take off as planned,
airlines would have to ``inform passengers of the factual reason
for the delay, cancellation or diversion of the flight to an
airport other than the scheduled stopover or destination.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also make legal a practice that the airlines call
``back-to-back ticketing,'' and have tried to block, in which a
passenger buys two round-trip tickets and throws away half of each,
because it is cheaper than buying a round-trip ticket for the days
the traveler wants to fly. It will also legalize what the industry
calls ``hidden cities,'' where a traveler buys a ticket to a
distant city but leaves the plane at an intermediate one, because
it is cheaper than buying a ticket to the real destination.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines contend that consumers have benefited from
deregulation and that any intervention by the government would mean
re-regulating them. They have also argued that under ``yield
management'' practices, they change the ticket prices for each
flight dozens of times in the months before the flight date. As a
result, the airlines say, answers about fares, or the number of
frequent-flier seats available, are accurate only temporarily.
</P>
</TEXT>
