<HEADLINE>
UCLA GETS MONROVIA RUNNING BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROVIA, Calif. Monrovia High School running back Akil Harris
said Sunday that UCLA has been interested in his football talents
since ``early in my junior year.''
</P>
<P>
   That consistent persistence looks like it will pay off
Wednesday, as Harris said he will sign a national letter of intent
with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who gave the University of Colorado an oral commitment
in late December, had a change of heart after Colorado coach Rick
Neuheisel and running backs coach Kennedy Pola left the school for
the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaching change changed things,'' Harris said. ``But I can
tell you, if coach Pola was still there (in Colorado), I'd be a
Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said his decision to give UCLA a late oral commitment was
after much thought and discussion with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really needed to sit back and kind of check myself,'' Harris
said. ``My family and I talked about it and we weighed everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think what it came down to was that I like UCLA, and the
fact that my parents and grandmother can come see me play.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who looked like a possible first-year starter if he
attended Colorado, is aware that the Bruins have a crowded
backfield returning. DeShaun Foster, Jermaine Lewis and Keith Brown
all saw significant playing time last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was being kind of selfish,'' Harris said. ``I guess I wanted
to go somewhere where I would, for sure, have an impact right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can do the same at UCLA. I really think I'm going to be
on the field next year. I think I can contribute, even as a
tandem.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris took his fifth and final trip to UCLA last weekend, a
trip he said he wouldn't have taken if the Colorado coaching change
hadn't occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA has liked me all along and they've been very
understanding,'' Harris said. ``They haven't given me that
full-court press approach, where they back you into a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my trip, UCLA sent me (via overnight delivery) a letter
of intent. They were the only school to do that. They told me,
`Take this and, if you change your mind on signing day (from
Colorado to UCLA), we'd love to have you.' Apparently, I'm the only
running back that they're recruiting.'' &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
