<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7848 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIEDE-MURDERTRIAL-COX     02-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIEDE-MURDERTRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury seated in East Texas murder case
 &HT;    By Janet Jacobs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN AUGUSTINE, Texas _ After a full day of questions and
instruction, a jury was finally chosen Monday in the trial of
Berhardt Tiede II in San Augustine County. A jury and two
alternates was seated consisting of eight black women and six white
men.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the jury panel, nearly 100 people, were dismissed
just before 7 p.m., with the thanks of 123rd District Judge Guy
Griffin. Selection took so long, he said, because the panel had
been so honest in their answers to attorney's questions.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Tiede sat with a serious expression, taking
notes and seldom making eye contact with the members of the jury
panel. He wore a dark blue suit and conservative striped tie.
</P>
<P>
   In the audience were his aunt and uncle, Millie and John Compton
of Lake Charles, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to come,'' Millie Compton said, tearing up, adding that
the family was still confused over the charges against Tiede.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always such a well-disciplined boy and easy to
discipline,'' she said. ``We just can't believe any of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody can't just go completely wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiede, 40, is charged with murdering his elderly companion,
Marjorie Nugent, 81, and hiding her body in the freezer in her home
for nine months. He also is charged with theft over $200,000.
Prosecutors hope to prove that he stole hundreds of thousands of
dollars from her estate after her death and before his arrest in
August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In his confession, Tiede said he killed Nugent because she had
``become very possessive over my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The crime is alleged to have happened in Carthage, but an effort
to seat a Panola County jury failed last November, and the trial
was moved to San Augustine. The trial is expected to take three
weeks to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecuting attorney, Panola County Criminal District
Attorney Danny Buck Davidson, was assisted in his choices of local
jurors by San Augustine District Attorney Charles Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   During jury selection, Davidson read aloud his list of 104
subpoenaed witnesses to see if potential jurors knew or were
related to them. Among the witnesses to be called in the trial are
several officers and employees of Longview Bank &AMP; Trust, where
Nugent had some accounts. Tiede and Nugent also traveled
extensively with the bank's Omni Club, which arranges tours and
trips both abroad and in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In his questioning of jurors, defense attorney Clifton
``Scrappy'' Holmes of Longview, suggested he would attempt to prove
Tiede's confession, given to a Panola County deputy and a Texas
Ranger, was taken improperly.
</P>
<P>
   Tiede was arrested after Nugent's son came to take possession of
his mother's Carthage home. Deputies discovered the body, with four
bullet holes in the back, in the freezer beneath some frozen
vegetables, wrapped in a sheet.
</P>
<P>
   The case has caused an uproar in Carthage because Tiede was
known as a popular and generous local businessman who was involved
in volunteer activities with Panola College, the Panola Chamber of
Commerce and the First United Methodist Church of Carthage, where
both he and Nugent were members.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs writes for the Longview News-Journal, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
