<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7850 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FRANCIS-TEX     02-01 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FRANCIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LONG JOURNEY, FRANCIS FINDS HOME, SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE PARK, Md. _ Reality and absurdity double-teamed Steve
Francis soon after he started classes at the University of
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   He was walking across campus, Walkman headphones in place,
trying to be a ``regular student'' when another student, high-beam
smile in place, stepped in front of Francis. Before they could
shake hands, the worshipful stranger dropped to his knees to praise
the human shrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too much, I was overwhelmed by what people were
expecting,'' said Francis, a 6-3, 190-pound guard. ``The pressure
has been here since I decided to come here. I just expected myself
to play like I can play. I wanted to fit in with the team. I was
worried about how the guys would accept me.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis has a better grasp of reality than most 20-year-old
basketball players who are regarded as saviors of a program. His
presence on Maryland's team has fans thinking Final Four and has
NBA scouts thinking No. 1 draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, bombastic coach Lefty Driesell said he wanted
to make Maryland the ``UCLA of the East.'' But before or since,
Maryland has never reached a Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   With Francis joining a veteran team that reached the Sweet 16
last season, Terrapins fans began thinking this could be their
year.
</P>
<P>
   His pre-Maryland reputation was hearsay because of a limited
high school career and two different junior-college stops. Francis'
frequent moves could indicate a checkered past; instead, it's one
of tragic circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   On his right bicep is a tattoo that Francis rubs before he
shoots a free throw. It's a cross with the name ``Brenda'' and the
words ``In memory.'' Brenda Francis, Steve's mother, died of cancer
in 1995. A senior in high school, Francis said he was ``paralyzed''
for five or six months after her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always thinking about what it would be like if she could
come watch me play,'' said Francis, whose father left when Steve
was 6. ``Maybe the story wouldn't be as dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis has posted modest numbers for the No. 7 Terrapins. He is
averaging 16.6 points, 4.2 rebounds and 4.7 assists per game for
19-3 Maryland, which plays at No. 2 Duke tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   He has blended himself into the lineup in his first season as a
shooting guard, not a point guard, although he's averaging just
over 11 shots per game and is second on the team in assists.
</P>
<P>
   And his ability to make plays _ in coaching parlance, break down
the defense _ is why Francis' reputation preceded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what defense the other team is playing, a guard who
can penetrate is going to cause you problems,'' Maryland coach Gary
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people expected him to take 30 shots a game and do
crazy things. But his game is fundamentally sound. He's just a
great player. You want him to play a team game and he does that
more than anyone expected. But when he can, we want him to
explode.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season at Maryland games, before he had even stepped on
campus, Terrapins fans chanted ``We want Francis.'' They got him
when Francis chose Maryland over Clemson. It was an easy choice;
Francis is a home boy. His Takoma Park home is about three miles
from Cole Field House.
</P>
<P>
   Renowned for his athletic play and 43-inch vertical leap,
Francis could have become an ``urban playground legend''
(translation: basketball talent wasted by circumstances). After his
mother's death, he left a Connecticut prep school and his
basketball career nearly ended. Dale Lamberth, his high school
coach, thought Francis was going to be ``a superstar in the
ghetto.'' Though he never got in any serious trouble, he admits he
was hanging with the wrong people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad at the world for awhile,'' said Francis, who turns
21 Feb. 21. ``I've learned a lot of things guys my age won't learn.
But I've always kept my faith alive. And on the court, I think it's
made me more patient. When I get on the court, it's my chance to
get away and relax.''
</P>
<P>
   A spectacular showing in 1996 at a national AAU tournament led
Francis to San Jacinto Junior College, which he led to the national
championship game. Homesick, Francis transferred to Allegany
Community College in Western Maryland. He led the Trojans to the
national title game and was a JUCO All-American.
</P>
<P>
   The praise has stacked up like Bill Gates' money. Teammate
Obinna Ekezie says Francis is the best one-on-one player in the
country. Maryland point guard Terrell Stokes says Francis always
plays his ``A'' game. NBA player Chris Webber says Francis' game
has ``spice and brains.'' NBA scouts have said Francis is Allen
Iverson with discipline.
</P>
<P>
   And, especially considering his Marco Polo past, there has been
much speculation that Francis will leave for the NBA after this
season. Recently, ESPN aired, but later retracted, a report that
Francis had said this will be his last season here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It upset me a lot,'' Francis said. ``My friends were saying,
`Wow, are you outta here?' That decision has to come from me and it
didn't. It was something somebody wanted to say. People can do
anything to try to take you down. It makes you want to get into a
shell.''
</P>
<P>
   March 21 will be the four-year anniversary of Brenda Francis's
death. It will also be the day this year's Final Four will be set
after finals at the East and Midwest regions. If Francis and his
teammates are then headed for Tropicana Field in St. Petersburg,
Fla., well. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that in order to be considered a good player, you
have to win,'' Francis said. ``That's what it all comes down to. I
know the Final Four is what a lot of people around here are
thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about my mom every day. I'm trying to make her proud
of me, on and off the court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
