<HEADER>
A7851 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     02-01 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD VOTE, BAD OFFER TARNISH SUPER SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Monday-morning-after-Super-Bowl blues
and views:
</P>
<P>
   Those ultra-provincial New York football writers and columnists
who were fighting mad that anyone would dare question the right of
Lawrence Taylor to be a first-ballot inductee into the Pro Football
Hall of Fame must be very proud of their man after he maliciously
ripped into those who didn't make him a unanimous selection
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor did a rambling, mumbling, scowl-filled TV interview that
again showed no remorse for his litany of drug arrests and
post-career misbehavior and accused the writers who voted against
him of ``getting high on their third or fourth highball ... and
they'll go here to South Beach, get totally trashed and chase some
little 13-year-old up and down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, a real Hall of Famer, that L.T. He was great on Sundays
but what, the other six days of the week don't count? If he had
played anywhere but New York, he'd have to buy a ticket to get into
the Hall of Fame, just like you and me. ...
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I know those ``old phonies'' who voted against him, and
they don't have either the energy or the inclination to chase an
ice-cream cart up and down the street, much less a teen-ager. ...
</P>
<P>
   Taylor says he didn't like it that anyone would feel that his
name should have an asterisk by it in the Hall of Fame. The only
asterisk there is the one he has attached himself, but it is a
doozy. ...
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, Taylor's diatribe also embarrassed NFL commissioner
Paul Tagliabue, who openly stumped for Taylor's admission. The
commissioner has no business campaigning for anyone unless he
intends to do so for every legitimate candidate on the ballot.
Where were you when Bob Hayes needed you, Mr. Commish? If Hayes had
played in New York, would he be in the Hall right now? ...
</P>
<P>
   Poor Dan Reeves. He must have known on the spot that it wasn't
going to be his day Sunday when he received word that starting
safety Eugene Robinson had been arrested for soliciting oral sex
from an undercover police officer. That Robinson's wife, kids and
father were in town for the game gives a whole new meaning to the
``Dirty Bird.''...
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between righteous and innocent,''
Robinson said afterward. ``And I wasn't righteous.'' Say what? ...
</P>
<P>
   Best line on Robinson came from WFAA/Channel 8's Dale Hansen on
Sunday night as he showed highlights of John Elway's 80-yard
touchdown pass to Rod Smith, who ran by Robinson on the play.
``Maybe,'' Hansen smirked, ``he should have offered \RSmith\S $40
to stop.'' Ouch. ...
</P>
<P>
   It's lines like that _ I guess _ that just helped Hansen be
elected Texas broadcaster of the year by the National Association
of Broadcasters and Sports Writers. ...
</P>
<P>
   What do you suppose hurt Reeves most, that quadruple-bypass
surgery he had less than two months ago or the collective pain of
losing his fourth Super Bowl? Having been through the former, I'm
still betting on the latter. Hey, not many coaches have even had a
chance to lose four Super Bowls. ...
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. Would somebody remind me again what a great season Chris
Chandler had? ...
</P>
<P>
   John Elway's postgame comments about the victory ``throwing a
kink'' into things makes it sound like he was leaning toward
retirement. Suggestion to Elway: Take some time, think things
through, then go ahead and hang 'em up. Coming back to try to
become the first to win three in a row may sound enticing, but as
we know from experience around here, it's a lot easier said than
done.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to keep players who already own two rings, with
all the glory and money that goes along with that, hungry enough to
make the sacrifices necessary to win a third. Elway deserves to
ride the glory into the sunset rather than risk walking off the
field a loser in his last game. ...
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of stars on the field Sunday, but one player
sticks out in my mind and surprisingly, it's not Elway, Terrell
Davis or Jamal Anderson. It's Falcons' kick returner and wideout
Tim Dwight, who returned one kick 94-yards for a touchdown and
almost broke a couple of others. He can fly. ...
</P>
<P>
   Updating note to Norm Hitzges: Teams with animal nicknames _
Colts, Dolphins, Broncos, Rams, Eagles, Bengals, Bears, Falcons _
making their first Super Bowl appearances now 1-7. A trend to
watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
