<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY'S DECISION WILL TAKE SOME TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The first time is always special.
</P>
<P>
   But the Denver Broncos submit that it can be sweeter the second
time around.
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly their take in the aftermath of Sunday's 34-19
blasting of the Atlanta Falcons in Super Bowl XXXIII at Pro Player
Stadium, marking only the seventh time in NFL history that a team
has won back-to-back titles.
</P>
<P>
   This one might have meant more than their 31-24 upset victory
against the Packers in Super Bowl XXXII, partly because the blowout
gave the Broncos a chance to relish their accomplishment during the
game. And it might have meant more because the Broncos said the
road to the title was tougher because they expected to do it, and
as defending champion they were targets of hungry opponents all
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``After winning last year, we were going to get everyone's best
shot,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said. ``Throughout the whole
year, that's how our team played.''
</P>
<P>
   And they seemed to play that way Sunday night, especially
38-year old quarterback John Elway, whose 336 yards passing were
the third-highest total in Super Bowl history. He walked off the
field _ and maybe out of the game forever _ with 50 seconds left in
the fourth quarter to a sea of flashing bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Elway will consult his family, Shanahan and Broncos owner Pat
Bowlen about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all week, and I said this year, that it's a 90
percent chance I'm going to quit,'' he said yesterday. ``But the
last thing I want to do is shut the door. I don't want to say that
I'm done, then get into March or April and say that I can play one
more year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to walk away too late. But I also know by the way
I played last night that I can still play.''
</P>
<P>
   If Elway comes back, the Broncos could become the first team in
NFL history to win three in a row. Elway, who likes the idea of
going out on top, said the challenge of doing something
unprecedented makes for an intriguing decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things that I'm going to have to sit down and think
about,'' Elway said. ``It would be great to come back and
three-peat. But also it would be nice to walk away at the level I'm
playing at right now. There will be a bunch of things that go into
the decision, but at 38 years old and in the twilight of my career,
I want to focus on the now and not tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Broncos coach Mike Shanahan became the sixth coach in NFL
history to coach teams to back-to-back titles, joining Vince
Lombardi (Packers), Don Shula (Dolphins), Chuck Knoll (Steelers),
Jimmy Johnson (Cowboys) and Bill Walsh (49ers). He said he would
prefer for Elway to come back for the ``three-peat,'' but said he
would not pressure his quarterback, believing that Elway has had a
great career and deserves to go out on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said before the game that my gut feeling is that John would
retire,'' Shanahan said. ``If he does retire, what a way to go out
_ the MVP, what he did last year and this year and what he did
throughout his career. But I'm hoping he will sit back and say `I'm
going to give it one more shot.' If he does come back, there won't
be a person with the team who won't be excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan, who joked to his team that off-season workouts will
start this week, believes the Broncos will do what it takes to put
themselves in position to win a third with or without Elway. He
said he would like a decision from Elway before the draft in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got a good shot,'' he said. ``We have our
nucleus coming back next season. That certainly can't hurt us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
