u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-SYRACUSE-NY     02-01 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-SYRACUSE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 1 CONNECTICUT IS UPSET AT HOME BY SYRACUSE, 59-42 
 ( ms ) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Get well soon. Real soon. That is the message
the University of Connecticut basketball team should scream outside
the dormitory rooms of Richard Hamilton and Jake Voskuhl after the
Huskies tumbled and stumbled to Syracuse, 59-42, without their two
injured starters Monday night. As Hamilton and Voskuhl watched from
the bench, UConn's chance for an undefeated season fizzled away in
emphatic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies had been ranked first in the country over the last
10 weeks, but they looked bewildered without Hamilton and Voskuhl
and saw their chance for an undefeated season squashed by the
16th-ranked Orangemen. In addition to pinning the first defeat on
the Huskies (19-1 overall, 11-1 in the Big East), Syracuse (16-6,
7-5) also ended UConn's 31-game home winning streak by humiliating
the cold-shooting, poor-passing Huskies. The paltry point total
matched UConn's lowest ever in a Big East game, equaling its total
against Georgetown in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange did it behind Damone Brown, a player who took one
shot in the first half and then erupted for 14 in the second half
as Syracuse played under control and then cruised. The normally
raucous Connecticut fans were stunned. Simple tasks like running a
half court offense, boxing out and draining eight-foot jumpers were
serious obstacles for UConn, obstacles that the Huskies never
overcame at the Hartford Civic Center. If this had been a
Connecticut practice, Coach Jim Calhoun would have blown a whistle
and forced his team to run sprints. It was that bad. The Huskies
missed 29 of 45 shots from the field and made 18 turnovers, but
Calhoun could not stop it. It continued on and on for 40 ugly
minutes. So, even before the Huskies travel to the West Coast for a
matchup against third-ranked Stanford next Saturday, they will
almost definitely relinquish their top-ranking in the next poll.
Without the smooth Hamilton as a weapon from the outside or the
6-foot-11-inch Voskuhl clogging the middle, the Huskies looked and
played like a very mortal team.
</P>
<P>
   After Kevin Freeman muscled inside to give the Huskies a 27-25
lead early in the second half, their first since the score was 2-0,
the Orange methodically scored 10 points in a row to snatch an
eight-point lead and silence the fans. Brown had four points during
the streak and UConn, which had to rely too heavily on either the
erratic Khalid El-Amin or players who are not accustomed to being
so involved in the offense for points, wilted, never getting closer
than seven points for the rest of the game. El-Amin was 2 for 12
from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game even started, fans of the Huskies spotted an odd
and potentially troubling sight on Connecticut's bench because
Hamilton and Voskuhl were not in their familiar red, white and blue
home uniforms. The two juniors have been mainstays for the Huskies
for three seasons so it was strange to see them slumped in chairs
while wearing sport coats. Freeman, another starter, played with a
bruised left thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who is Connecticut's leading scorer with an average of
22.1 points a game, missed the second game of his career, while
Voskuhl, the team's leading rebounder with 7.2 a game, missed his
first game ever. Both players injured themselves in UConn's 78-74
victory over St. John's last Saturday, but the extent of the
injuries was not realized until Monday. Voskuhl did not practice on
Sunday and Hamilton was unable to run.
</P>
<P>
   While Hamilton is described as day to day with a contusion on
his right thigh, the possible return date for Voskuhl is more
confusing. Voskuhl had a bone scan performed Monday at the UConn
Medical Center in Farmington and it showed a stress fracture of his
left foot, which is a recurrence of an injury he had in high
school. Coach Jim Calhoun spoke ominously about his 6-foot-11-inch
center's status.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be very, very cautious,'' said Calhoun. ``I don't
like the signs. He has had foot problems before. If this is a
long-term thing, it's certainly not the news we wanted to get.''
</P>
<P>
   The lineup of Hamilton, Voskuhl, Freeman, Khalid El-Amin and
Ricky Moore had not been disrupted since Jan. 24, 1998, a streak of
36 games. During that stretch, the Huskies were 34-2. Without
Hamilton and Voskuhl, the Huskies started Souleymane Wane at center
and Rashamel Jones at forward. But Calhoun frantically looked for a
unit that could play cohesively by making four substitutions in the
first four minutes. The coach kept looking all night.
</P>
<P>
   Other than a frenetic spurt in which the Huskies scored six
points in the final 47 seconds to even the score 25-25, the first
half was a brutal display. The teams combined for 20 turnovers and
18 field goals, a revealing statistic. UConn shot 32 percent from
the field and made five of 10 free throws while Syracuse sank 39
percent of its shots and was also five of 10 from the line. It was
supposed to be a marquee matchup, but it was hardly gaudy for the
first 20 minutes and then it was only glorious in the end for
Syracuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
