<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0474 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-JORDAN-590&AMP;AD     02-01 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-JORDAN-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOCUS TURNS TO VERNON JORDAN AND DIFFERING ACCOUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH) 
(lb) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After questioning Monica Lewinsky for several
hours, the House managers will turn their attention on Tuesday to
Vernon Jordan and how his account differs from hers over a sworn
affidavit in which she denied a sexual relationship with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who will be the second witness deposed by the House
managers, will be questioned largely about his role in getting Ms.
Lewinsky to file the affidavit in January 1998 in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment case, and about his efforts to help Ms. Lewinsky
get a job around the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers have said they wanted to have Jordan as a
witness to bolster the second article of impeachment against the
president, which charges a wide-ranging scheme of obstruction of
justice. Under their theory, Jordan helped orchestrate an effort to
have Ms. Lewinsky file the affidavit, which they say Jordan knew
was false. Jordan has denied that he tried to influence her
affidavit or helped her in the job search to buy her cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky testified before the grand jury in detail last year
about conversations she said she had with Jordan in which she made
it clear that she had an intimate relationship with Clinton. She
provided a host of details about their conversations, which the
House managers believe reinforce her version of events.
</P>
<P>
   But in his grand jury appearances, Jordan testified that he
could not recall that she ever told him of her affair with the
president before it became known publicly, and, in some instances,
could not even recall some of the meetings about which she
testified. His grand jury testimony is replete with assertions that
he was unable to remember the content of conversations, not only
with Ms. Lewinsky but also with Clinton and Betty Currie, the
president's secretary.
</P>
<P>
   One incident Jordan is likely to be asked about is Ms.
Lewinsky's account of a conversation in which he suggested to her
that she destroy any notes she had written to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   By Ms. Lewinsky's account, that conversation occurred over
breakfast at the Park Hyatt Hotel in Washington on Dec. 31, 1997.
Until then, she said she had concealed from Jordan and Clinton her
fear that her one-time friend Linda Tripp was disclosing her
confidences about her relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky testified that she told Jordan over a breakfast of
an egg-white omelet that Mrs. Tripp had been at her apartment and
might have seen notes she had written to Clinton. She testified
that Jordan told her, ``Go home and make sure they're not there.''
She then said that she went home and discarded a handful of drafts
and copies of notes she had written to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., the House manager who will be
Jordan's principal questioner, said over the weekend, ``I think
that's an area that needs to be explored with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has testified that he cannot recall ever having breakfast
with Ms. Lewinsky in the Park Hyatt. But the independent counsel
Kenneth Starr has said that circumstantial evidence, including a
restaurant receipt for Ms. Lewinsky's omelet, led him to believe
that the meeting occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has depicted his efforts to help Ms. Lewinsky file an
affidavit as minimal and his role in doing so as that of a
disinterested and distant acquaintance. He has portrayed his help
in her job search as based on a generalized inclination to help a
talented young woman and not as an effort to prevent her from
disclosing her intimate relationship with the president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the White House lawyers, one statement of Ms. Lewinsky's has
served as an all-purpose shield: She has said that no one asked to
her lie and that she was not promised a job in return for anything.
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Lewinsky's version, she first unmistakably informed
Jordan that her relationship with Clinton was intimate on Dec. 22
when they were conferring about getting her a job. In that
conversation, she said she told Jordan that she and the president
engaged in phone sex, which she defined for him as having a
telephone conversation in which each aroused the other.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers assert that the job search ``intensified''
after Ms. Lewinsky appeared on a list of possible witnesses in the
Jones case on Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 8, she had a job interview that was set up by Jordan.
When she reported to him that it did not go well, Jordan called
Ronald Perelman, the chairman of MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes Holding, the
company that controls Revlon Inc., and arranged for her to be
reinterviewed, after which she was offered a job at Revlon in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers have attacked the theory that the job help
was a reward to buy Ms. Lewinsky's silence. They have noted that
her efforts to find a job in New York began months earlier. They
say she had even met with Jordan in November, before her name
turned up on the Jones witness list.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts of Ms. Lewinsky and Jordan are also at odds over
whether he took a detailed interest in the affidavit's contents.
Jordan said he helped her find a lawyer and then said he had little
role in the affidavit. Ms. Lewinsky said Jordan helped her fashion
the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   While the House managers have said everyone knew that any
affidavit denying a sexual relationship had to be false, White
House lawyers have argued that Ms. Lewinsky could have believed it
to be true. They point to her taped conversation with Mrs. Tripp in
which she said that oral sex did not constitute sexual relations,
which she said she believed could only be defined by intercourse. l
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
