<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7877 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AXA-GUARDIAN-525&AMP;ADD-     02-01 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AXA-GUARDIAN-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AXA OF FRANCE TO BUY GUARDIAN OF BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AXA Group of France, one of the world's largest insurance and
financial-services companies, said Monday that it had agreed to buy
Guardian Royal Exchange PLC for $5.68 billion, greatly expanding
its auto and homeowner business in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, through its Sun Life and Provincial Holdings
subsidiary, will make AXA No. 3 in Britain's property and casualty
insurance business, up from 10th. It will also fortify its No. 3
ranking in life insurance and give it the No. 2 position in health
insurance, a new field for AXA in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the deal gives the French giant a corporate insurance
unit in Germany to bolster its subsidiary there, AXA Colonia,
Gerard de la Martiniere, AXA's chief financial officer, said in an
interview from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, de la Martiniere said, fills several important gaps in
AXA's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for us to have a strong position in the
main markets of Europe _ the U.K., Germany and France,'' he said.
``To be efficient and profitable, you have to be among the leaders
in every market. If you are a follower, you can't really make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that AXA, with revenue of $62 billion last year, was
considering more acquisitions, possibly in Latin America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Guardian Royal's profits have been declining for several years,
and its share price is down considerably from a year ago. But in
paying about 5 percent more than Guardian Royal's market value, de
la Martiniere said he thought AXA had gotten a bargain. And that,
he said, is what AXA seeks in acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, we try to avoid situations where everybody
is bidding,'' he said. ``It leads to huge prices. We prefer shaken
companies with potential for recovery. It is more in line with our
track record to get quick and sharp improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal on Monday, AXA will sell Guardian Royal's
property-casualty business in the United States to Liberty Mutual
Group in Boston for $1.47 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty, the leading provider of workers' compensation coverage,
will add 20 companies, from Albany Insurance Co. of New York to
Tower Insurance Co. in Pewaukee, Wis., increasing its regional
corporate as well auto and homeowner businesses. Besides its
domestic operations, Liberty, which had sales of $5.9 billion last
year, does business in 13 countries in Latin America, Britain and
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``AXA is becoming the major consolidator in Europe,'' said
Martin Mills, a senior analyst at Moody's Investors Service in
London, citing AXA's acquisition of its French rival UAP in 1996
and its purchase last year of the stake in Royale Belge Insurance
in Belgium that it did not already own. AXA has owned 60 percent of
Equitable Cos., the New York life insurance and financial-services
company, for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   AXA agreed to pay 389 pence, or about $6.40, a share for
Guardian Royal, a 5 percent premium over the company's closing
price on Friday and 41 percent more than its closing price in
mid-November, when Guardian Royal said it was looking for a buyer.
The deal will be mainly in cash, with AXA paying 249 pence plus
0.243 share for each share of Guardian Royal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Analysts said there were several reasons that Guardian Royal
sold for close to its market value. Not only have profits in the
property-casualty business generally been depressed but the pool of
potential buyers has shrunk as several other large insurers have
recently merged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the other large players are busy digesting recent
mergers,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   AXA outbid two other companies that had been negotiating for
Guardian Royal: Royal and Sun Life Insurance Group in Britain, and
Eureko, a company formed by seven European insurers.
</P>
<P>
   AXA executives said that part of their plan for Guardian Royal
was to save millions of dollars in costs. But some analysts were
skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guardian has already been doing a lot of things to improve
efficiency and reduce costs,'' said Rafael Villarreal, another
analyst at Moody's in London.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor inhibiting cost-cutting in Britain, Villarreal
said, is that the property-casualty business AXA is buying is much
larger than its holdings in Sun Life. It thus does not have a
structure into which it can fold the new business, but instead will
need to fit the Sun Life property and casualty business into the
larger operation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One likely cost reduction, de la Martiniere said, will come at
the headquarters of Guardian Royal. The running of Guardian Royal's
units in South Africa, Asia, Latin America and Germany will be
shifted to other AXA units. ``As soon as we free the U.K. business
from these costs, we will have significant savings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guardian Royal has been losing money through its calculation of
risk and pricing, de la Martiniere said. And AXA hopes to reverse
that. ``We have some skill in running property-casualty insurance
companies in competitive markets, especially France,'' he said.
``And we have been making money even when market cycles are
relatively poor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
