<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL BRIEFS: PICASSO AND MATISSE, SIDE BY SIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the time they met in 1906, Picasso and Matisse were
fiercely competitive, and ``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle
Rivalry,'' which opened last Sunday at the Kimbell Art Museum in
Fort Worth, Texas, is the first major exhibition to examine their
sparring. It brings together more than 100 paintings, drawings and
sculptures from around the world, juxtaposing many for the first
time. The show, which runs through May 2, will not travel.
</P>
<P>
   Arranged chronologically, the exhibit picks up the rivalry
around 1930, with Matisse recovering from a bout of artist's block,
while Picasso was enjoying a highly productive period, even teasing
his rival with parodies of his odalisques, dancers, studio scenes
and other paintings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, Matisse began working again, and Picasso, apparently
fascinated by a Matisse retrospective and an exhibition of his
sculptures, represented in this show by works like ``Jeannette
III,'' responded with sculptures of heads and bathers and his
``sleeping beauty'' canvases, like ``Woman with Yellow Hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Matisse then rose to the challenge with such paintings as ``The
Dream'' from 1935, prompting Picasso's gradual mellowing toward the
decorative aspects of Matisse's work. By the end of the 1930s, the
two observed a truce, with each exploring the other's pictorial
language in his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   During the war years, they exchanged some paintings and
drawings, most of which will be on view. In peace, the two began to
meet often and exhibit together, producing works like Matisse's
``Blue Nude II'' (1952) and ``Seated Woman'' by Picasso (1953).
Finally, following Matisse's death in 1954, Picasso began to
reinvent his colleague, painting elegies _ first, thematic works
like ``Women of Algiers'' and then a series of empty studios
reminiscent of Matisse's Vence interiors.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell, at 3333 Camp Bowie Blvd., Fort Worth, is open daily
except Monday. Timed advance-purchase tickets for $8 are
recommended. Call: (800) 654-9545. Same-day tickets, also $8, are
available at the museum on a first-come, first-served basis.
Information: (817) 332-8451.
</P>
<P>
   A SPANISH PEAK JOINS A NATIONAL PARK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the fabled Alhambra in Granada have always been able
to gaze at the distant snowcapped Veleta Peak, which at 11,129 feet
rises as a breathtaking backdrop to the medieval Moorish complex.
Now, Veleta has become part of the new Sierra Nevada National Park,
a 213,790-acre nature preserve whose main western entrance is a
30-minute drive from Granada. The park contains 14 peaks above
9,600 feet, the tallest being Mulhacen, at 11,421 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Nevada is a Mediterranean mountainous zone that
already enjoyed some official environmental protection and now will
get more after Parliament approved it last month as the 12th, and
largest, national park in Spain. It has 2,100 species of fauna and
flora, including vast forests of pine, oak, chestnut and maple, and
rare plants such as an indigenous narcissus. Some 100 miles of
marked trails are open daily during daylight. Admission is free,
but the park management recommends that visits deep inside the park
be led by local guides (about $71 to $106 a day, at 141 pesetas to
the dollar).
</P>
<P>
   The easiest access from Granada is on Highway 395 toward the
Sierra Nevada ski resort at Prado Llano. The park's Dornajo
information center is on this road at kilometer 23. One can enter
the park there, or drive 30 minutes more along the same road to the
Hoya de la Mora parking area, closer to the base of Veleta Peak.
The Dornajo center is open daily from 10 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. and 4:30
to 7 p.m. (until 8 in summer). Information: (34) 958-340-625.
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL RIGHTS SITES MAPPED ON THE WEB &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new historical itinerary with maps and photos tracing events
in the civil rights movement has been introduced on the Web. From
photos of Sammy Davis Jr. and the Moulin Rouge, an integrated hotel
and theater opened in Las Vegas in 1955, to the home in Daytona
Beach, Fla., of the Rev. Howard Thurman, whose book was a mainstay
for the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., the site describes and
shows 42 places in 21 states.
</P>
<P>
   The itinerary, ``We Shall Overcome: Historic Places of the Civil
Rights Movement,'' is found at www.cr.nps.gov/nr. It was prepared
by the National Park Service, the Federal Highway Administration
and the National Conference of State Historic Preservation
Officers. Many of the buildings on the itinerary are on the
National Register of Historic Places, but some are gone, and some
that remain are not open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Printed out, the text and pictures become a guidebook for
exploration of a turbulent period and its antecedents.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K MAY BE BUMPY ABROAD, U.S. SAYS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has issued an announcement about possible
malfunctions of computer-based systems outside the United States as
of Jan. 1, 2000. Financial services, including ATM machines, credit
cards and banking transfers, may be affected, the notice on Jan. 29
said, along with transportation, medical facilities and
communications. The department said it would publish details as
they became available and by Oct. 1, the Consular Information Sheet
on each country would note what was known about that country's
preparations. These may be seen on the Internet at
travel.state.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
