<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Kenya: Students Protest Again
</P>
<P>
   Clashes between the police and university students continued for
a third day in Nairobi over a plan to build luxury housing in a
large forest at the edge of the city. The police fired tear gas at
the students, who blocked traffic and harassed motorists. Dozens of
students and several officers have been injured in the protests.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: 10 Officers Charged With Murder
</P>
<P>
   Ten Mexico City police officers have been charged with murdering
a New York University student, Frederick McPhail, in November. The
officers are accused of having seized McPhail, 27, as he withdrew
money with his bank card and forcing him to drink large amounts of
liquor before letting him go. McPhail died of alcohol poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Canada: Chinese Smuggling Case
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese man who tried to take four Chinese women from Canada
to the United States in a false compartment under a truck was
arraigned in Buffalo, N.Y., and charged with smuggling. Immigration
officials say that as part of a growing trend in which Canada has
become a major illegal entry point into the United States, Khung
Chang Kang, 54, of Rochester, N.Y., was paid $500 a person to
transport the four women from Ontario to New York.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Netherlands, Greece: Kurd Seeks Haven
</P>
<P>
   The Kurdish guerrilla leader, Abdullah Ocalan, whose whereabouts
have been a mystery since he disappeared last month from Rome,
tried to enter the Netherlands, but his private plane was not
allowed to land at Rotterdam. Later, Turkish officials said Ocalan
had landed in Greece. Greece denied that. He is Turkey's most
wanted fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Hardliner Sworn In
</P>
<P>
   Narayan Rane, a leader of the hardline Hindu party, Shiv Sena,
was sworn in as chief minister of the state of Maharashtra, whose
capital, Bombay, is India's financial center. He took over two days
after the head of Shiv Sena, Bal Thackeray, asked Monohar Joshi to
resign. Thackeray, who holds no public office, gave no reason for
Joshi's dismissal.
</P>
</TEXT>
