<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOND PRICES TUMBLE AS STOCKS END MIXED
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices finished mixed after investors chose to take some
profits in late trading, but bond prices posted the biggest drop in
almost three months as several economic reports pointed to
resilience in the U.S. economy, leaving investors little incentive
to buy Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 13.13 points, or 0.1
percent, to 9,345.70. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slipped
6.64 points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,273.00, and the Nasdaq composite
index closed at 2,510.09, up 4.20, or 0.2 percent. In the bond
market, the yield on the 30-year issue shot up to 5.18 percent from
5.08 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Factory production rebounded last month after a four-month
slump, and consumer spending and home building accelerated in
December, the latest economic reports showed.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT APPEARS TO STUMBLE
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft set out in federal court to demonstrate that computer
users gain numerous benefits from the company's decision to
integrate a Web browser with the Windows operating system. But that
demonstration appeared to have backfired during cross-examination
of a senior Microsoft executive in the government's antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH INSURER EXPANDS IN BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   AXA Group of France, one of the world's largest insurance and
financial services companies, said it had agreed to buy Guardian
Royal Exchange for $5.68 billion, expanding its auto and homeowner
business in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   PILOTS THREATEN WORK SLOWDOWN
</P>
<P>
   Pilots at American Airlines are threatening a work slowdown if a
dispute over American's recent acquisition of Reno Air is not
resolved. The pilots contend that the purchase of the carrier
violates an agreement that any planes owned by American will be
flown by members of the Allied Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL SEEKS TO BOLSTER CREDIBILITY
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the rumors in Brazil that the government would
curtail access to bank accounts, the government instead sought to
reassure its citizens and investors.
</P>
<P>
   ROHM &AMP; HAAS AGREES TO BUY MORTON
</P>
<P>
   Rohm &AMP; Haas agreed Monday to buy Morton International, which is
best known for its Morton Salt girl trademark, for $4.5 billion, a
deal that would make the combined business the No. 2 maker of
specialty chemicals. Rohm &AMP; Haas shares rose 75 cents, to $31.75,
while Morton jumped $9.75, to $35.625.
</P>
<P>
   MAXIM EDITOR TO TAKE OVER DETAILS
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast has appointed Mark Golin, the editor in chief in the
United States of Maxim magazine, a testosterone-rich, off-color
bible of sports, sex and humor for young men, to be editor in chief
of Details magazine, replacing Michael Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA ONLINE ADDING MOVIEFONE
</P>
<P>
   America Online has agreed to buy Moviefone, which provides movie
show times and sells tickets through the 777-FILM telephone service
and the Moviefone.com Internet site, for stock valued at $388
million.
</P>
<P>
   ANYTHING BUT SUPER FOR COMMERCIALS
</P>
<P>
   Super Sunday was more of a misnomer than usual. Many of the
commercials broadcast nationally were dominated by sophomoric
slapstick, toilet talk and gratuitous sex and violence.
</P>
