A7882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN02-COX     02-01 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Legislature: '99 session looking for an identity
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To define itself, a legislative session needs face
books and a good fight. Neither having arrived yet, this session
remains pretty much a blank sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Face books are those little booklets made available by the House
and Senate information offices that put a face beside the name of
every legislator along with some basic facts. Without the face
books, which are expected any day now, the first-term lawmakers are
hard to keep up with. More detailed information is nowadays
available on the Web, but you can't tuck that in your coat pocket
or purse.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to thumb through a decade or so of face books
to get a sense of how not only race and gender but occupations have
changed over time.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1987-88 face book, 11 of the 56 state senators _ all but
one of them Democrats _ listed their occupation as attorney. There
were two funeral home directors and a retired veterinarian, but no
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   This year, eight senators listed lawyering as their trade,
including four Republicans and three first-term Democrats. That
there is only one Democratic lawyer with experience in the chamber,
Sen. Rene Kemp of Hinesville, marks a huge change from the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   What has been given up by the legal profession has been taken up
by the medical field. This year the Senate has three Republican
doctors _ Minority Whip Tom Price of Roswell, Sen. Don Thomas of
Dalton and first-term Sen. Phil Gingrey of Cobb _ as well as a
Democratic nurse, Nadine Thomas. (With his change of status, the
Republicans have also acquired a veterinarian in Sen. Sonny Perdue
of Bonaire, although he lists his calling as ``agri-business.'')
</P>
<P>
   The way these professional-political shifts over time can change
the way legislation is approached was evidenced by Monday's debate
over Senate Bill 16, which would give optometrists the right to
prescribe certain kinds of topical drugs as well as give samples to
patients.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason this session has been slow in defining itself
is that Gov. Roy Barnes' mandate to get something done about the
metro area's transportation woes has tended to blur the usual
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democrat, developer and environmentalist,
bureaucrat and industry rep all sing from the same page, dutifully
observing, for the time being, the Pax trafficus.
</P>
<P>
   So there was a little extra interest in the optometrists' bill,
an evergreen issue over which there are at least clearly defined
lines, if not a full-fledged fight.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago the medical merits of this bill would have been
debated entirely secondhand. But on Monday, Don Thomas, an opponent
of the bill, regaled his fellow senators with med school stories of
working on cadavers until he reeked of formaldehyde and learning
how to revive guinea pigs from anaphylactic shock. His point being
that the ability to prescribe drugs should not be casually granted
to those who have not undergone such rigorous training.
</P>
<P>
   It was a vivid argument, and it carried the day, although maybe
not more than that. The bill fell a vote shy of a majority, but
will be reconsidered today.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-DEATH-PENALTY-2NDT     02-01 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DEATH-PENALTY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TRENTON, N.J.: ``legislative interference.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey reinstated capital punishment in 1982, and since then
14 convicts have been sentenced to death. But because of the
appeals process and the insistence by the courts that a sentence
for a given crime be proportional to those imposed on other
inmates, the state has yet to carry out an execution, and a
succession of state leaders have tried to streamline the process.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Gov. Jim Florio signed legislation intended to restrict
``proportionality review.'' Last year, Whitman impaneled a
Commission on the Death Penalty, which also criticized the length
of the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the death penalty expressed disappointment Monday
that the state's highest court did not overturn the capital
punishment law, but said they took comfort in the fact that the
court was eager to get more information on the question of racial
disparities.
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling, Poritz acknowledged that the small number of
death penalty cases left the statistical conclusions open to
question, and she appointed a judge to study the issue and search
for a ``sound methodology capable of producing reliable results.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Waldor, one of the few members of the Commission on the
Death Penalty to oppose capital punishment, expressed relief that
the court did not strike down the proportionality issue. ``What
they are saying here is that it be administered with some semblance
of equality,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the death penalty also hailed the decision as
a step toward speedy justice and a more reasonable appeals process
for convicts condemned to death. Dick Zimmer, the former U.S.
representative who was chairman of Whitman's death penalty
commission, predicted that a review of the proportionality policy
would lead to its restriction, or even its abolition, because it is
too muddled for even judges to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The justices have taken nearly two years to decide that they
can't answer basic questions about their statistical analysis and
have had to ask a special master to sort out the mess,'' Zimmer
said. ``The time has come to abolish proportionality review.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the 39 states that now impose capital
punishment have enacted measures to limit the appeals process,
according to experts, and the average time that elapses between
sentence and execution is now nine years. Some states, like
Virginia, have streamlined the appeals process to a point where
some inmates are executed five years after being sentenced, said
Richard Dieter, executive director of the Death Penalty Information
Center, a nonprofit research organization based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's court ruling leaves New Jersey among a handful of
states in which the legislative and judicial wrestling over the
appeals process has prevented any executions from taking place.
</P>
<P>
   ``There haven't been any inmates whose death penalty conviction
has been overturned on the basis of race discrimination studies in
state or federal court,'' Dieter said. ``It's been a pretty blanket
lockout. But studies showing bias are still out there and still
disturbing to the courts, the legislators and the public in
general.''
</P>
<P>
   Loftin, the Death Row inmate, was convicted of shooting a gas
station clerk in Lawrenceville in 1992 and was sentenced to death
despite testimony from psychiatrists who said he suffered from a
borderline personality disorder.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for the reversal of Loftin's conviction, the public
defender's office said his punishment was unduly harsh when
compared with those of other defendants convicted of similar
crimes. The public defender also offered a statistical analysis of
capital cases in New Jersey as evidence that blacks convicted of
capital crimes against whites were more likely than other
defendants to receive a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at what factors really influence juries in
deciding who lives and who dies, the race of a defendant is just as
important and has just as much impact as the list of factors
permitted in the statute,'' said Claudia Van Wyck, a deputy public
defender. ``There is no other rational explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the court said the claim of racial bias was unconvincing and
pointed to its own study, conducted by a retired Superior Court
judge, Richard Cohen, which found that blacks had been sentenced to
death in 13.79 percent of all death-eligible cases in the state
since 1982, as opposed to 13.84 percent in the case of whites.
</P>
<P>
   Associate Justice Alan Handler was the lone dissenter from the
majority opinion. Handler, who has a long history of voting to
strike down the death penalty, said the Legislature's attempt to
limit death penalty appeals was unconstitutional and that the
public defender's statistical findings raised troubling questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``An unconstitutional risk of racial discrimination in the
imposition of the death penalty has, in my opinion, been laid bare
and exposed,'' he wrote in his dissent.
</P>
</TEXT>
