<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SHOOTINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON POLICE TRYING TO CURB USE OF DEADLY FORCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By S.K. BARDWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Houston Police Chief C.O. Bradford has instituted
additional training, more deployment of specialized weapons such as
tasers and a new review process in the wake of some controversial
police shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them to do what they have to do to survive,'' Bradford
said of the more than 5,000 officers under his command. But, he
added, officers must understand that ``for each round they
discharge, there is accountability required.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said he formed a Critical Incident Review Group,
composed of officers and chaired by an assistant chief, to study
some of the shootings and recommend training changes or additions
that could better the department's response to similar calls.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford recently began the process to train some patrol
officers from each patrol district in the use of tasers, hand-held
devices that deliver an electrical shock.
</P>
<P>
   For years, only Houston police sergeants received the training
on using tasers.
</P>
<P>
   The department has been criticized for not using such a device
on Sheryl Seymour, who called paramedics Jan. 20 and demanded to be
taken to a psychiatric facility, then attacked them and arriving
police with a large knife.
</P>
<P>
   Before a sergeant could arrive with a taser, Seymour, 40,
charged at police and paramedics with her knife and was shot and
killed.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Mental Health Association of Greater Houston will
begin a pilot program in which 60 Houston officers will receive
intensive training in dealing with the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said a traditional police response to a psychologically
ill person with a weapon may not be the best way to handle such an
instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to train officers differently and not put ourselves in
a position where we have to use deadly force,'' Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston department is often criticized for shooting
suspects, impaired or not, when armed with anything other than a
gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have different experiences,'' Bradford said. ``There's
a lack of understanding ... when (police) are not confronted with
what citizens believe is a deadly weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bats, ice picks, machetes, they're all deadly weapons. We do
not expect our officers to go up against someone with a deadly
weapon. They don't get a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said he is also concerned over the number of shots
fired in some incidents. The number has gone up greatly over the
past two decades as more officers began carrying semiautomatic
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Houston police were widely criticized in October after seven
officers fired 59 shots at Derek Kaeseman after a chase from
downtown Houston into suburban Fort Bend County.
</P>
<P>
   Kaeseman, 24, was shot 14 times as he climbed from his wrecked
vehicle holding a shiny object that turned out to be a can opener.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford could not comment on the Kaeseman incident specifically
because it remains under investigation by his internal affairs
division, but said, ``In some instances, I'm concerned the total
environment is not being considered _ what's around that suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   In another shooting, six Houston officers, without a search or
arrest warrant, burst into an apartment July 12 and killed Pedro
Oregon Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, who said they had a tip that drugs were being sold
in the apartment, fired about 33 shots, hitting Oregon 12 times.
The officers said Oregon pointed a gun at them, and believed he had
shot one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford fired all six officers, although only one was charged,
with misdemeanor criminal trespass. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bradford said it also concerns him when a large number of
officers fire on a suspect, because ``I don't know if those
officers are firing in fear for their lives, or because another
officer shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to make sure that when each officer fires, it is
because he perceives an imminent threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the number of police shootings in the city is well
below that of five years ago, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Houston officers fired their weapons in 70 incidents,
the same number as in 1993, but killed or wounded significantly
fewer civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Police shot 19 people, nine fatally, last year, and five
officers were wounded. In 1993, police shot 29 people, killing 14,
and two officers were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Narcotics operations accounted for several of 1998's shootings,
which included two citizen fatalities and two wounded officers. But
narcotics-related shootings were down in relation to the amount of
drugs seized and narcotics arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic violence calls accounted for two fatal police shootings
last year and an officer being badly cut. Nearly 50 of the 254
slayings in Houston in 1998 involved domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
