<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA LEWINSKY AGAIN TESTIFIES UNDER OATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky testified under oath Monday as
House prosecutors and White House lawyers began a series of
close-door depositions in the Senate impeachment trial of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's interrogation, her 23rd session with officials
investigating her affair with the president, ended with Clinton's
lawyers passing on a chance to question Lewinsky, instead
apologizing to her ``on behalf of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The session, which was videotaped for senators to view privately
beginning early today, reportedly turned up nothing at odds with
Lewinsky's earlier testimony or, in the opinion of one of the
participants, helpful to the Republican drive to terminate
Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton lawyer David Kendall said he was asking a
federal judge to sanction independent counsel Kenneth Starr over a
published report that the special prosecutor was considering
whether to indict Clinton on criminal charges before he leaves
office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, whose office already is under investigation for illegally
leaking grand jury information, denied that he was the source for
the weekend report and launched an internal investigation to
determine the source of the New York Times story.
</P>
<P>
   ``This office has no desire to inject itself into the
constitutional process under way in the Senate,'' said Starr, whose
report to Congress in early September prompted the House, in a
party-line vote, to impeach Clinton and send his case to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, only the second president tried by the Senate, is
charged with perjury and obstruction of justice, allegations that
grew out of his effort to conceal his adulterous relationship with
Lewinsky. The impeachment trial, which formally opened on Jan. 7,
could end with Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   In calling Lewinsky, senators are seeking any new information
she might provide regarding her decision to lie in an affidavit in
the Paula Jones lawsuit. They also want information on the
president's effort to find her a job and whether that campaign
intensified when her name appeared on the witness list in the Jones
case. Also in question is the president's role, if any, in her
decision to hide gifts received from him.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Washington power broker Vernon Jordan, a close friend and
confidant of the president's, is to be questioned in a room at the
Capitol used mostly to discuss secret national security issues. On
Wednesday, White House aide Sidney Blumenthal is to testify, also
in secret.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors want to quiz Jordan about his drive, initiated
by presidential secretary Betty Currie and endorsed by Clinton, to
find Lewinsky a job in New York. Prosecutors also want him to
explain inconsistencies between his testimony before Starr's grand
jury and the version Lewinsky provided during 22 sessions with
grand jurors and Starr's investigators
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, prosecutors plan to question Blumenthal about
conversations he had with the president in which Clinton denied
engaging in sex with Lewinsky, claimed that she ``threatened'' him
and described her as a stalker.
</P>
<P>
   In her five-hour deposition Monday in the presidential suite of
Washington's Mayflower Hotel, Lewinsky responded to questions from
Rep. Ed Bryant, a Tennessee Republican and House prosecutor
assigned to interview the former White House intern as four
senators and members of Clinton's legal team listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with today's events and felt it was a productive
session,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   When he was finished, the president's lawyers -- private
attorney Nicole Seligman and Deputy White House Counsel Cheryl
Mills -- passed on the chance to pose their own questions. Seligman
read a statement apologizing to Lewinsky ``on behalf of the
president for all the trouble the investigation and impeachment
trial had caused her,'' according to published reports.
</P>
<P>
   Absent some startling revelations from the three depositions, or
from live testimony if the Senate demands the witnesses' appearance
during the trial, senators have agreed to vote by Feb. 12 on the
two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Votes on procedural matters have shown all but one of the 45
Senate Democrats opposing the Republican-led effort to oust
Clinton. If they remain unified when the final impeachment votes
are held, Democrats could block his conviction and removal, which
would take a two-thirds vote.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, Kendall said he was asking U.S. District Judge
Norma Holloway Johnson to require Starr to show why he ``and
members of his staff should not be held in contempt for improper
violations of grand jury secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Kendall's complaint is a New York Times story
quoting unidentified Starr ``associates'' saying that the
independent counsel, which has investigated Clinton's private
business dealings, misuse of FBI files, missing billing records and
the suicide of deputy White House counsel Vincent Foster, has
determined that he has the authority to indict Clinton before he
leaves office in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, Clinton's legal team has accused Starr's
office several times of leaking sensitive information embarrassing
to the president. Johnson ordered an investigation of earlier
allegations of Starr leaks, but that inquiry has not been
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal rules prohibit prosecutors from disclosing information
about grand jury proceedings. Johnson, who oversees the Starr
probe, has said the rules prohibit disclosing the strategy or
direction of an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bakaly III, a spokesman for Starr, said the independent
counsel had ``not made a formal decision or final decision'' on
whether he has the constitutional authority to indict a sitting
president.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
