<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CLINTON UNVEILS $1.77 TRILLION BUDGET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
WASHINGTON _ Urging America to grasp a rare opportunity, President
Clinton officially unveiled Monday a $1.77 trillion budget to open
the 21st century with plans to save Social Security, bolster the
Pentagon and social programs and pay down the national debt.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The five-volume budget packet, symbolically printed in black
instead of the varying colors of past years for its record $117
billion surplus of black ink, would create a series of tax credits
for working families with children, families who care for a parent
and families who want to create a retirement fund.
</P>
<P>
   However, it avoids any across-the-board tax cut that Republicans
have made a centerpiece of their legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget sets the stage for a showdown between the White
House and Congress over how to spend the surpluses projected for
decades to come, providing a new political drama to replace past
battles over red ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a rare opportunity that comes along once in a blue
moon to any group of Americans,'' Clinton said. ``But with our
economy expanding and our surplus rising, we have confidence that
we can now look to the long-term challenges of our country, to
fulfill our obligations to 21st century Americans, both young and
old.''
</P>
<P>
   The fiscal year 2000 budget, which begins Oct. 1, lays out in
cold numbers the warm poll-tested rhetoric that Clinton offered in
his State of the Union.
</P>
<P>
   It calls for setting aside 62 percent, or $2.8 trillion, of the
projected $4 trillion budget over 15 years to save Social Security.
It also calls for using 15 percent to save Medicare from
bankruptcy, 12 percent to fund retirement savings accounts (or USA
Accounts) for working families, and 11 percent to provide more
money for defense and education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Setting aside the surplus for Social Security and Medicare,
whose trust funds are invested in government bonds, also would help
trim the nearly $4 trillion national debt, reducing it to its
lowest percentage levels since 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget also proposes raising taxes by $82 billion over
five years, including $53.4 billion from a 55-cent-per-pack tax
increase on cigarettes and closing corporate tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
   It also would allocate billions of dollars more on education to
pay for 100,000 new teachers, new school funds to help improve
student achievement, more police officers, pay raises for military
personnel and to bolster defense spending again after years of
decline.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton, whose impeachment trial may draw to a close this
month without his removal, called for bipartisanship as the
administration and Congress confront the long-term challenges
facing the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, several Republican leaders embraced Clinton's idea
to set aside the surplus for Social Security. But they wasted
little time in blasting Clinton's budget plan for taxing and
spending too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big government has been reborn and reinvented with this
budget,'' said Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., Senate Budget Committee
chairman. ``It's clear that the president has initiated scores of
new programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said, ``In all my years in Congress, I've never seen
such a kitchen-sink approach to government. The budget contains
something for everyone and that's what's troubling. It's a
throwback to the days when the government tried to solve problems
by raising taxes and throwing money at problems.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, complained, ``Out of
$4 trillion in projected budget surpluses over the next 15 years,
the president can't find one penny for tax cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials pointed to several tax credit
proposals targeted to lower- and middle-income families.
</P>
<P>
   The USA Account would create a 401(k) savings plan for
low-income Americans by creating a tax incentive that would provide
a matching contribution by the government to the taxpayers'
savings. It would cost $536 billion over 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The budget would create a $1,000 tax credit to elderly Americans
or to their families that provide long-term care, a $1,000 tax
credit to cover special transportation costs and technology needs
of disabled workers and expand by $345 a child-care tax credit for
families earning up to $59,000.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, the East Room ceremony unveiling the budget
provided a measure of vindication. In 1993, Democrats, then
controlling Congress, passed a $500 billion package that raised
taxes and cut spending, without any support from Republicans. The
next year, many of them were defeated and Republicans assumed
control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what the president did today was demonstrate how long
it takes for this country to pull itself out of a hole when we have
made a major public policy mistake, one rooted in irresponsibility,
as we did in 1981,'' said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., senior Democrat
on the House Appropriations Committee. Obey referred to the budget
passed by Congress and the Reagan administration that began the
country down the road of massive deficit spending and quadrupling
of the national debt within eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget is not perfect, but it is certainly a vindication
of every action that has been taken in the last six years to try to
put us back in the world of black ink,'' Obey said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
