<HEADLINE>
VICTIM'S MOTHER ISN'T FORGIVING ACCUSED IN JASPER CASE &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Viewing a new black granite tombstone on her
son's grave, the mother of James Byrd Jr. said Monday that she
hasn't forgiven the men accused of dragging the black man to death
behind a pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want justice done,'' said Stella Byrd, who added that
none of the three white men charged with the June 7 murder of her
son have expressed regret for his slaying.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that defendant John William ``Bill'' King, 24, got to
hug his 6-month-old son for the first time last week during a break
in jury selection for his capital murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I get to hug my son is to come out here and visit
his grave,'' she said. ``The last time I got to hug him was the
night before he was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Stella Byrd said James Byrd's granddaughter can never hug her
grandfather again. ``She points at his picture and asks where he
is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by the family Monday said ``each individual
Byrd family member is going through this process at his or her own
pace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have forgiven in the sense that they are now able to go
beyond the horrible day of June 7, and are trying to regain some
normalcy in their lives, as they wait until justice is finally
served on the men responsible for James Jr.'s death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe in destructive hate, but we are righteously
angry about the senseless murder of James.''
</P>
<P>
   James Byrd Sr. attended the opening day of jury selection last
week, but became so upset that he later had to undergo medical
tests in Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sister, Clara Taylor, said the family hopes for justice
through the court system.
</P>
<P>
   The new tombstone was bought by the New York-based National
Ethnic Coalition of Organizations to replace a nameplate that was
stolen from the grave's vault cover last November. A spokesman for
the coalition said that if vandals do anything to the new marker,
the organization will replace it and provide guards to make sure it
isn't defaced again.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Verrett, another of Byrd's sisters, said the family had
first sought solace in the thought that Byrd was unconscious when
he was chained behind a pickup truck and dragged almost three miles
along back country roads. But when King's trial opened last week,
prosecutors said evidence would show that the victim was conscious
and tried to lift himself from the pavement when the dragging
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was hard to hear,'' Verrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Verrett and Taylor were in the courtroom Monday, as was King's
father, Ronald King, as lawyers questioned possible jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers approved five more jurors, bringing to 27 the number who
have qualified for the trial. Five are black.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys hope to qualify about 50 for a pool that will be used
to pick 12 jurors and two alternates. Testimony is expected to
begin Feb. 16.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, King will face life in prison or death by
injection.
</P>
<P>
   Trials for his co-defendants, Shawn Allen Berry, 23, and
Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, have not been set.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2215EST &QL; 
