<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGAL-ADVICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE TO BAN TEXAS SALES OF SELF-HELP LEGAL SOFTWARE &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a precedent-setting opinion, a federal judge
in Dallas says he plans to ban the sale of self-help legal software
in Texas as the unauthorized practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Barefoot Sanders released a summary judgment
Jan. 22 to prevent Parsons Technology Inc. from distributing future
copies of Quicken Family Lawyer and Quicken Family Lawyer '99 in
Texas. Products already in stores apparently are unaffected by the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   An injunction to enforce the ruling could be issued within the
next two weeks, lawyers involved in the case said. Attorneys for
Parsons said they are planning to challenge the ruling and will ask
the judge to place the ban on hold, pending a decision from the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The new legal muzzle on the popular self-help products drew
rebukes from consumer groups and industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can quote me: This is sick. This reeks of greed,'' said
Ann Stephens, president of PC Data, a company that tracks the sale
of software for personal computers. ``Boy, these lawyers are
sticking up for their own, aren't they? I don't think they're
representing you or me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight states that have considered cases against self-help
legal publishers, Texas is the first to opt for a ban, said David
Schenck, an appellate lawyer representing Parsons Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is apparently alone in banning books and software
according to the judge's ruling,'' Schenck said. ``Our opinion is
the Texas statute doesn't reach that far and if it did it would
violate the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The do-it-yourself products sell for under $30, and the latest
version offers more than 100 legal forms and instructions on how to
file your own will, prenuptial agreement, employment contract, real
estate lease and similar documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it means, really to be honest, not that much to the
company, but what it does to the common people is sad,'' Stephens
said of the court decision.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling marked a major victory for the Unauthorized
Practice of Law Committee, an arm of the Texas Supreme Court that
is fully funded by the State Bar of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups and lawyers representing self-help publishers
complain that the operations of the committee's investigative arm
are cloaked in secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ticer, a Dallas attorney who chairs the investigative
subcommittee, praised Sanders' decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think overall it is probably the most comprehensive,
well-reasoned, authoritative judicial opinion in the United States
on this subject,'' Ticer said. ``It becomes a benchmark or a
measuring stick as to what constitutes unauthorized practice of law
for some self-help materials.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticer said the committee argued that the Quicken Family Lawyer
products go beyond generic information because they are
interactive. Users wishing to draft their own wills, for instance,
would answer questions about whether they are married or single,
how many children they have, and so on. The program would then
chose a form that fits the individual's characteristics and provide
instructions for filling it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, what you had was a cyber-lawyer. They were doing
the drafting, everything for you,'' Ticer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ticer said some of these Quicken-produced documents might be
unenforceable in Texas if an individual needed to take certain
actions before filing the document. He acknowledged, however, that
no one has shown evidence of such harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't wait around till the damage is done, if somebody
raises a red flag. Then the person complaining would say, `Why
didn't you do something about this? You knew it was wrong to begin
with,''' Ticer said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the source of the complaint leading to the
federal court action was an average consumer, a judge or a lawyer,
and Ticer said he's not at liberty to reveal that information, even
generically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot reveal the sources of complaints. If I do that I'm
in big trouble,'' Ticer said. ``In this case it's totally
irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Borges, who follows legal issues for the consumer advocacy
group Texas Watch, does not share that opinion and sharply
criticized the committee's secretive investigative practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an absurd situation. Basically we've got a bunch of
lawyers on this thing who are secretive. How can a bunch of lawyers
run a kangaroo court like this and not give us any of the rights
they would demand if they were being dragged in?'' Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ought to be called the Authorized Monopoly of Law Committee
as opposed to the Unauthorized Practice of Law Committee,'' he
said. The ruling is especially troubling, he added,because 60
percent of Texans who responded to a recent poll said that they
were unable to afford lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Nolo Press, another legal publisher under investigation by the
committee, is awaiting a Texas Supreme Court decision in a freedom
of information lawsuit it filed challenging the committee's
secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a government agency out there that is taking the
position that a number of its investigative meetings are secret,''
said Peter Kennedy, a Nolo Press lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now obvious that the committee has significant power to
be a censor over legal publications, file lawsuits to ban books.
It's not hyperbole, either.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, about $500,000 worth of the Quicken Family Lawyer
software was sold last year, resulting in profits of $100,000,
according to Schenck, Parsons Technology's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
