u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETH     02-01 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(925)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA LEWINSKY IS QUESTIONED BY HOUSE PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: SUBS grafs 1-3 to CORRECT spelling of `prosecutor,' ADDS
attribution, that six senators questioned her, Lewinsky's age; SUBS
grafs 7-10 bgng, As the senators ..., to clarify on who was present
at session, identify programs as CNN, raise material about White
House position that had been lower in story; SUBS grafs 16-17, A
battery ..., to ADD names of senators who monitored proceedings,
details about who paid for expenses; story now in 2 takes.) (HLW)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to bolster an obstruction-of-justice charge
against President Clinton, a House Republican prosecutor
interviewed Monica Lewinsky under oath and on videotape for nearly
four hours on Monday. White House lawyers offered only an apology
to the young woman and made no inquiries of their own, several
officials familiar with the session said.
</P>
<P>
   The questioning of Ms. Lewinsky in the 10th floor Presidential
Suite of the Mayflower Hotel marked a new and possibly final phase
in the Senate's impeachment trial, which stemmed from Clinton's
efforts to cover up his sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, a
former White House intern. At various points in the day, six
senators sat in.
</P>
<P>
   One year after the scandal seized Washington, Ms. Lewinsky, 25,
once again received a statement of regret for the disruption to her
life and apologies to her family. Several officials familiar with
the session said that the lawyers representing the president asked
her no questions. Instead, one of them, Nicole K. Seligman, read
her an apology on behalf of the president for her ordeal across a
year of investigations. The president first apologized to Ms.
Lewinsky shortly after he publicly admitted to the relationship
last August.
</P>
<P>
   The proceedings began at 9:03 a.m. and ended at 3:14, with
several breaks, including an hour for lunch. The actual questioning
took far less time than the eight hours that had been allotted by
the Senate. Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., who conducted the interview
for the House prosecutors, said in a written statement, ``I was
pleased with today's events and felt it was a productive session.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House's decision not to use its four hours for
questioning suggested that the lawyers felt no startling new
information had emerged. The House focused on her affidavit in the
Paula Jones lawsuit, denying a sexual relationship with Clinton; on
the help Vernon Jordan gave her in seeking a job, and on the
retrieval of gifts from the president by Clinton's secretary, Betty
Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Plato Cacheris, Ms. Lewinsky's lawyer, said Monday night, ``She
was excused as a witness, and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the senators emerged from the hotel, they emphasized their
chamber's efforts to keep the deposition process secret. ``We are
under a prohibition from the United States Senate not to talk any
further about this,'' Sen. Mike DeWine, R &UR; - &LR; Ohio, said. DeWine
presided over the proceedings for the Republicans; Democrats began
the day with Sen. Patrick J. Leahy of Vermont presiding but took
turns at the job as the session wore on.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant canceled appearances he had scheduled for Monday night on
the CNN programs ``Larry King Live'' and ``Crossfire.'' ``We set
them up because it seemed like he could possibly talk about the
deposition afterwards,'' said Steve Susens, his spokesman.
``Somewhere down the line he decided against it.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been considered unlikely that Ms. Lewinsky would break
substantial new ground because under her immunity agreement with
the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, she could be prosecuted for
changing her story.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the White House went into the session with some
assurances that explosive new information was unlikely to emerge
and it could take the magnanimous route of simply making an
apology.
</P>
<P>
   Senators will be allowed to view the videotape of the
questioning on Tuesday, even as the House and White House lawyers
question a second witness, Jordan, about his efforts to help Ms.
Lewinsky find a job. A less sensational presence than Ms. Lewinsky,
Jordan, a Washington lawyer close to Clinton, is to be questioned
on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was arranging for three group showings of Ms.
Lewinsky's videotaped deposition in three large rooms in the
Capitol, and individual senators can see the tape in a separate
recording room. Senators will also be able to read her deposition.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday a third witness, Sidney Blumenthal, a senior White
House aide, is to be questioned about the president's remarks to
him that he had been stalked by Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the Senate trial is to resume. Senators will then
vote on whether to allow the videotaped depositions to be shown as
part of the trial and on whether to call the witnesses themselves
for questioning before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Although House prosecutors once wanted to call as many as 15
witnesses, they narrowed their list to three under pressure from
Senate Republicans, who were eager to bring the case to a close.
The House prosecutors want to use Ms. Lewinsky, Jordan and
Blumenthal to bolster one article of impeachment in particular;
that article charges Clinton with obstructing justice in his
efforts to hide the affair. A number of senators have said they
take this charge more seriously than a second one, which charges
Clinton with perjury.
</P>
<P>
   A battery of lawyers, lawmakers and aides attended the
questioning of Ms. Lewinsky on Monday. Besides DeWine, other
senators were also deputized to monitor the proceedings: for the
Republicans, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and Fred Thompson of
Tennessee; for the Democrats, Leahy, Christopher J. Dodd of
Connecticut and John Edwards of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   As a witness subpoenaed by the Senate, Ms. Lewinsky had her
coach air fare from California and her hotel expenses paid for by
the Senate. With scores of photographers and camera crews staking
out the sidewalks, the hotel made the Presidential Suite available
free for the questioning.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials familiar with the session, who spoke on condition that
they not be identified, described Ms. Lewinsky as poised, even
occasionally humorous, throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said Bryant, a former prosecutor, covered several
areas that have been of interest to the team of House managers.
They said that he asked Ms. Lewinsky to run through the events
leading to her delivery of some of the president's gifts to Mrs.
Currie and that Ms. Lewinsky stuck to her prior testimony that it
was Mrs. Currie who had initiated the collection of the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, the officials said, also quizzed her about the time Mrs.
Currie picked up the gifts and about a cell phone call by Mrs.
Currie to Ms. Lewinsky's apartment that the White House has argued
undercuts Ms. Lewinsky because it came an hour and a half after Ms.
Lewinsky said Mrs. Currie had picked up the gifts. Ms. Lewinsky,
officials said, said her memory had become more hazy over time.
</P>
<P>
   At other moments in the questioning, Ms. Lewinsky pointed the
House prosecutor back to her statements before the grand jury,
officials said. She did so, they said, when Bryant asked whether
Jordan had ever said he was acting on behalf of the president as he
was helping her seek a job in New York. Ms. Lewinsky had told the
grand jury that Jordan never made such a claim.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant asked her why she had filed a false affidavit in the
sexual harassment suit brought by Ms. Jones against Clinton. One
person familiar with the testimony said Ms. Lewinsky repeated her
statement that the president never instructed her to lie.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate worried about a spectacle in the chamber, Bryant
last week assured senators that he would stay away from the sexual
detail of Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with the president and ask
her to ``simply affirm those provisions'' of her prior testimony in
this realm.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that on Monday when Bryant started to ask a
question getting into sexual detail, Cacheris, her lawyer,
objected. DeWine and Leahy quickly held the question to be out of
line.
</P>
<P>
   Before the questioning began Monday morning, the White House
also went on the offensive against Starr because of a story in The
New York Times on Sunday. Citing associates of Starr, the article
said the independent counsel had decided he had the constitutional
authority to seek an indictment of Clinton while he is in office.
It said he had not decided if he would do so.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's private attorney, said he was asking a
federal court to require the independent counsel to show why he and
his staff ``should not be held in contempt for improper violations
of grand jury secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said in a statement that he was ``deeply troubled'' by the
story and that his office ``has no desire to inject itself into the
constitutional process under way in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was ``launching an internal investigation to
determine whether anyone in this office improperly disclosed the
information.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
