<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GODWIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLS GODWIN JR., 84; RULED VIRGINIA AS DEMOCRAT AND REPUBLICAN
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Gov. Mills Edwin Godwin Jr. of Virginia, who rose above
his segregationist past to become one of his state's most effective
chief executives, died Jan. 30 in Newport News, Va. He was 84 and
lived in Suffolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Godwin had just been released from Riverside Hospital in Newport
News, where he was treated for pneumonia, said the office of Gov.
James S. Gilmore III in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Godwin was the only two-term governor for the Commonwealth of
Virginia since the Civil War, and he served his terms eight years
apart _ elected in 1965 as a Democrat and in 1973 as a Republican.
He epitomized the end of an era dominated by the Democratic machine
of Harry F. Byrd Sr., whose organization ran Virginia politics from
the 1920s to the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In his first term, Godwin broke with the policies of the Byrd
machine and was able to piece together a mainline conservative
coalition that attracted labor leaders and the rank and file,
African-Americans and whites, liberals as well as conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   With such broad support he was able to build roads, overhaul the
state Constitution and tap a new source of revenue in the form of
sales taxes. His legacy was a community college system that gave
Virginia an educational basis for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Born a farm boy in Chuckatuck, Va., Mills Godwin was a 1938 law
graduate of the University of Virginia and practiced law in his
home county, Nansemond, until 1960. He was elected to the Virginia
House of Delegates in 1947 and to the state Senate in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the Senate that he became a pillar of his state's
policy of ``massive resistance'' to the racial integration of
schools. He vowed that there would be no compromise on the issue.
But that intransigence shattered in the late 1950s, and he
eventually argued that Virginia just needed time to adjust to the
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected lieutenant governor in 1961 and governor four
years later. He later left the splintering Democratic Party and was
elected to a second four-year term as a Republican in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   After his second term, he worked as a business consultant and
corporate director.
</P>
<P>
   Godwin is survived by his wife of 58 years, Katherine Beale
Godwin, and a sister, Leah G. Keith of Chesapeake, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0492 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7902 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      02-01 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Why Las Vegas' Purchase Pro May Be One Firm Worth Watching  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
If Web stocks are turning the stock market into one big casino,
it's only fitting that Las Vegas is spawning an Internet company
poised to go public.
</P>
<P>
   Those high-octane Net stocks, which conservative fund managers
liken to playing roulette, tend to be consumer-driven and fueled by
their brand names.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate financial potential of the Internet is supposed
to be manifested in whatever benefit it brings to business. In
fact, Wall Street visionaries have proclaimed that 1999 could be
the year that investors finally pay attention to the potential of
business-to-business applications on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Purchase Pro may be one company worth watching. The
2-year-old Las Vegas startup was custom built to help hotels,
resorts and casinos perform most of their purchasing via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mirage Resort Chairman Steve Winn was an early stage
investor (word is that he no longer holds any stake), and Mirage
Resorts is one of Purchase Pro's biggest customers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Because the hospitality industry is under intense pressure to
lower its costs, Purchase Pro was formed to develop networks that
allow resort and hotel chains to privately negotiate their supplier
contracts, such as those for linens, over the Internet, notes
Purchase Pro President Chris Carton.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mirage Resorts seeks bids for nearly all of the
stuff in its warehouse every six months. And ``in the past, it had
taken three people, three and a half weeks (to accomplish the
task). With Purchase Pro, it took two people just two days,'' says
Dennis Macready, director of purchasing at Mirage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to large corporatewide purchasing deals, Purchase
Pro also provides a function where individual restaurants or hotels
can ask hundreds of suppliers to bid for spot contracts, such as
orders of produce, Carton says.
</P>
<P>
   The general idea is to cut time and save money. Clients such as
Mirage, MGM Grand and Caesar's Palace have seen the prices they pay
for goods and services slashed anywhere from 15 percent to 20
percent, Carton says.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, that model can be applied to industries other than
the hotel and resort business, such as construction and
manufacturing. Of course, the company is still privately held, but
it is already conducting its ``bake-off'' to determine which
underwriters might take them public, Carton says. ``We're very
close to making a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET02 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Purchase Pro, which employs 100 people, has raised about $8
million and has almost completed its second round of financing.
Flynn-Gallagher, a Las Vegas venture capital firm, is one of its
key stakeholders.
</P>
<P>
   The company isn't out of the red yet, but it ``has a burn-rate
that is very palatable when you compare it to other Internet
startups,'' Carton says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AMAZON CONSTRUCTION INC.: Amazon.com expounded a tad yesterday on
the company's ambition to build an internal real estate department.
The online bookseller's chief financial officer, Joy Covey, told
fund managers and other buy-siders that the company's plans to open
new shipping warehouses will hit the expense line during the first
quarter, according to attendees at the NationsBanc Montgomery
technology stock conference being held this week at the Ritz
Carlton on Nob Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Covey said that at least one more, or maybe two,
distribution-related announcements will come this year, attendees
and wire services reported.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as reported in Street Smarts, Amazon revealed in a
quarterly earnings filing that it wanted to grow distribution
capability in order to keep pace with swelling customer demand.
What was more interesting, however, was that the filing alluded to
``data centers'' and ``office'' developments. In addition, Amazon's
own Web site indicated that it was adding three new key positions
to its fledgling real estate department.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who favor electronic commerce stocks generally like
the notion that the companies have little exposure to traditional
operating risks, such as real estate leases or development costs.
Amazon's shares closed down about a buck yesterday at $115.88,
which was down about 10 bucks from $125.63 on Wednesday _ last
week's peak.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Amazon raised nearly $1.25 billion last week in a
monster convertible stock offering, which will more than adequately
fortify the Internet company's acquisition war chest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO RAIDERS: Thomas Weisel Partners has been beefing up
its institutional sales force at the expense of some of its rivals.
Chief executive and founder Weisel says he has hired three of
BancBoston Robertson Stephens's top salespeople: Bill Hazen, Greg
Cote and Paul Slivon.
</P>
<P>
   And while that might put a dent into the roster at Beantown
Robbie, that doesn't mean that other regional investment banks are
raid-proof. Weisel has also hired away sales executive Chris Henkel
from BT Alex. Brown and international sales specialist Otto Tschudi
from his former firm NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. Given
Weisel's passion for competitive skiing, it should be noted that
Tschudi once strapped on boards in the Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
