<HEADLINE>
HEMS AT THE KNEES (FOR NOW)  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Skirt lengths have been moving up and down faster
than the stock market. But except for the ankle-brushing lengths
favored by trendy fashion folk, hems seem to have settled for now
just at the bottom of the knee. Straight or in a slight A-line,
these skirts look best with bare-looking legs and medium or high
heels.
</P>
<P>
   In the Barneys New York Collection, you'll find a slim skirt in
yellow, light blue, tan or black, all with rows of contrasting
stitching at the hem ($135); an A-line skirt in beige, khaki or
black ($125); a wrap in blue or pink silk ($295); and a
cream-colored skirt in a wool-and-silk blend with an inverted front
pleat ($395). The store also has a button-front hip-hugger in gray
by Wang ($185) and a back-wrap cream-colored organza by Wayne
Cooper ($185).
</P>
<P>
   Henri Bendel has an apron skirt in pale yellow by P.A.K. ($158)
and African prints in pink, orange, green or blue by Dona Jean
($178).
</P>
</TEXT>
