<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7905 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-RAFAEL-LADN     02-01 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-RAFAEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEXICO ANXIOUSY AWAITS BERUMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ Terry Berumen wondered if there was some
sort of setup.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the University of New Mexico, which was recruiting her son
Rafael to play basketball, had put these people up to this.
</P>
<P>
   All these well-wishers and autograph seekers greeted Berumen
throughout his visit to Albuquerque. In fact, the moment the
6-foot-9 center from Simi Valley High stepped off the plane, a
television crew began shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for sure the university was behind it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Which causes Ron Garcia, the New Mexico assistant who hosted the
Berumen family during their stay last September, to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia grew up in New Mexico and he knows well the intensity
fans have for their Lobos. He also knows that the Latino community
in Albuquerque is eager to embrace a player of Latino heritage.
</P>
<P>
   When Garcia took the Berumens, who are Mexican-Americans, to the
heavily Latino-populated Old Town for lunch, fans engulfed Rafael.
Storekeepers and shoppers shook Rafael's hand and told him they
hoped he'd play for the Lobos.
</P>
<P>
   This was no setup. This was New Mexico showing Berumen how much
it cared.
</P>
<P>
   The reception touched Berumen, and he immediately decided to
spurn offers from Florida State, Washington State, Oregon State and
Duquesne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew right away that New Mexico was the place for me,''
Berumen said. ``Those people are crazy about basketball and there
aren't many places like the Pit. I can't wait to play there.''
</P>
<P>
   And New Mexico can't wait to have him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an outstanding player and he's a Latino that is
bilingual,'' Garcia said. ``I don't want to put any pressure on
him, but with all of that going for him, there is no doubt that
Rafael can be a big hit out here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; He doesn't play above the rim, or excite anyone with athletic
ability. Rafael Berumen is a thinking man's player. He finds a way
to get it done, beating people with passing and clever moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a knack,'' said his father, Rafael Sr. ``And it's been
that way since he was a little kid. He's always been able to
score.''
</P>
<P>
   Berumen is doing plenty of scoring, among other things, this
year for Simi Valley. He's averaging 23.5 points and 11.3 rebounds
but also shows considerable poise and court vision.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite part of the game is passing, and with the Pioneers,
his unselfishness is appreciated since Simi Valley is loaded with
scorers. And Berumen, who grew up idolizing Magic Johnson, doesn't
mind feeding them the ball.
</P>
<P>
   At New Mexico, where Berumen will play small forward, Garcia
expects he'll make an immediate impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's smart enough to make up for any lack of quickness or some
of what others may deem as athletic ability,'' Garcia said. ``He's
a hard worker who knows the game. Utah and Duke make a living off
those kind of players.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Pomona, Calif., where Rafael Berumen grew up, seems like a
lifetime away from his home in middle-class Simi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, even though Berumen was always the biggest kid in
the neighborhood, he was also the most protected. As a youngster,
his parents never let him spend the night at a friend's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he noticed what we were doing because all his
friends were always at our house hanging out or spending the
night,'' Terry Berumen said. ``He was having fun, regardless. But
we were definitely concerned about the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety over his safety extended to Berumen's growing love
of sports. Originally, he wanted to be a football player, even
starring at quarterback on his youth teams. But the tall,
strong-armed Berumen quickly became the target for some overzealous
parents. From across the field, Rafael Sr. and Terry could hear
them screaming to take shots at the big kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like all they wanted to do was hurt Rafael,'' his
father said. ``And we weren't going to let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to pull Berumen off the football field was made
easier by his increasing success in basketball, a popular sport in
the Berumen home. Rafael Sr., who left Mexico 20 years ago, played
basketball as a youngster. Older brother Philip played at Damien
High before becoming Rafael's personal coach.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, Rafael was beginning to take basketball a step
beyond. He was becoming a force on youth teams, playing throughout
California in travel leagues and all-star tournaments. By the time
he enrolled at Pomona High as a freshman, Berumen was being
recognized as an emerging big man on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   He played at Pomona that year as a ninth-grader, but a dispute
over the school's academics and the family's increasing uneasiness
concerning the threatening surroundings prompted the Berumens to
look for a new, safer home.
</P>
<P>
   After first considering Sylmar and San Fernando, they settled on
Simi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Berumen's arrival in Ventura County caused an immediate stir, as
did Branduinn Fullove's transfer that same year. The Pioneers have
been accused in the past of recruiting basketball players, so when
two standouts arrived from out of the area, eyebrows raised.
</P>
<P>
   Simi Valley coach Dean Bradshaw is quick to point out that
thorough investigations have proven no wrongdoing, and insists
there is nothing he can do if talented basketball players wish to
play at Simi Valley based on past success. In other words, some
schools are magnets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Part of the reason Latinos haven't been well represented in
basketball is cultural. Many Hispanics grow up playing soccer and
baseball, two sports with many role models. That hasn't been the
case in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who coached high school basketball in New Mexico for
many years, believes Latinos' generally smaller stature also is a
factor but thinks exposure plays out more prominently. He's coached
enough 6-foot-8, 6-foot-9 Latinos over the years to know that size
isn't the biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys went on to play at Division II or Division III
colleges, but maybe they would have been recruited more heavily had
they played in a bigger city.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, things are changing. Players like Berumen, and Eduardo
Najera and Victor Avila, two Hispanics now at the University of
Oklahoma, show that Latinos can be successful on the college level.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is going to lead another and then another and another,''
Garcia said. ``That's the way life works.''
</P>
<P>
   The last basketball player at New Mexico with a Latino surname
was J.J. Griego, a small forward from Socorro, a little town in New
Mexico. Latinos throughout the state followed Griego's success and
he became a hero in the community. Now a successful businessman in
Albuquerque, Griego was preceded by Nick Pinos, a star for the
Lobos in the 1970s who was later killed during a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, Griego and Pinos were idolized in the largely
Hispanic population, in which anyone who plays for the Lobos
already has celebrity status.
</P>
<P>
   Many predict that Berumen will have a similar affect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to make a positive
impact within the Hispanic community _ along with all the other
communities,'' said Vince Garcia, a local businessmen who hosted
the Berumens last September. ``The time I spent with Rafael and his
family, he seemed to be an exemplary citizen who is acutely aware
of his position. Certainly, he brings so much to the table. He can
truly serve as a role model for this community and the whole state.
We can't wait until he gets here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
