<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ROBINSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS SAY ROBINSON ARREST WAS A DISTRACTION ON GAME DAY
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Some members of the Atlanta Falcons said Monday they
were not surprised when their teammate, Eugene Robinson, was
arrested for soliciting an undercover police officer for sex in a
seedy section of Miami the night before Super Bowl XXXIII. After
all, some of them said, other Falcons players had been there
several times for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys had been going there all week,'' said one Falcon starter.
``It's just that Eugene was the only one who got caught.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews after the game and on Monday morning, several
Falcon starters spoke about Robinson's arrest and its affect on the
team. They insisted on anonymity because of their concern that
their comments could be divisive to a team that hopes to return to
the Super Bowl next season.
</P>
<P>
   While they said they were unsure how many players went to the
area north of downtown frequented by prostitutes, they estimated it
was at least five, some of them starters.
</P>
<P>
   The players said Robinson heard from teammates about the area
and, the players added, ``he wanted to see it for himself.'' Miami
police said Robinson offered an undercover officer $40 for oral sex
on Saturday night. Robinson said he is innocent of the charge, but
he apologized to his teammates and his family, saying he did not
``maintain the high standards for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   While publicly the Falcons players maintained Robinson's arrest
was not a distraction, privately they said differently. Those
interviewed said the morning of the game was extremely tense, and
all the talk was about Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of getting mentally ready for the Broncos,'' said
another Falcons player, ``we were talking about Eugene. The Broncos
beat us, but anyone who says what happened to Eugene was not a
factor is lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons players said the team did not play its normally sharp
game, and that there were numerous blown blocking assignments and
botched secondary coverages.
</P>
<P>
   The comments from Atlanta players were part of an extensive
postmortem following Atlanta's 34-19 loss. The Falcons had entered
the game as one of the hottest teams in the National Football
League, after upsetting the heavily favored Minnesota Vikings on
the road. They had a potent offense led by quarterback Chris
Chandler and running back Jamal Anderson, and a solid defense as
well.
</P>
<P>
   They figured to give the Broncos a much better game, especially
considering running back Terrell Davis was playing with a sore
groin and tight end Shannon Sharpe tore a ligament in his knee in
the opening quarter and did not return. The Falcons could not have
asked for a better situation.
</P>
<P>
   But something happened. The team that became one of the best
stories in the league, one that had shown the cool, killer
instincts of a champion against the San Francisco 49ers and the
Vikings in the playoffs, did not have its mental edge against
Denver. The Falcons got inside Denver's 30-yard line seven times
but managed only two field goals and a touchdown. During the
regular season, Atlanta scored 27 touchdowns and 14 field goals in
46 chances inside the red zone. Of the five missed opportunities,
four were the Falcons quarterback taking a knee to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Atlanta's problems had to do with the Broncos, of
course. Coach Mike Shanahan threw things at the Falcons they were
not expecting and quarterback John Elway was a dazzling 18 of 29
for 336 yards. Denver's defense sacked Chandler twice and
intercepted him three times. No doubt, the Broncos were the better
team.
</P>
<P>
   But were they over two touchdowns better? The Falcons say no and
privately they pointed to several things during the week that were
distractions in addition to Robinson's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons players interviewed said the fact that families were
allowed to travel and stay with the team _ something few teams
allow _ was a novel idea, but proved to be a major distraction in
some cases. Some Falcons players were inundated with requests from
family members for things like tickets and hotel rooms for
relatives. By comparison, the families of Broncos players were not
allowed to stay with the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your family is going to become really important,'' said
Robinson before the game. ``Everybody in your family is going to
want your time. They're going to bug you for everything, and you
have to realize the distraction and make sure you get your work
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson bluntly stated after the game, ``Having families in the
hotel became a hassle to some guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Falcons players also said that their living situation
reminded them more of a compound than a hotel. Players could not
receive phone calls directly in their rooms. Instead, all calls
were routed to a receptionist, who took a message. Security at the
hotel was extremely tight, and several friends of players, who
tried to visit _ including some agents _ were turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Some Falcons players think all of these things are just excuses.
``There is no way we're going to turn our backs on our teammate in
an adverse situation,'' said linebacker Jessie Tuggle, speaking of
Robinson. ``As a team, this wasn't a distraction. I think it made
us stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has taken the loss harder than Reeves, who is now only
the third coach in league history to go winless in four Super
Bowls. His teams have been outscored, 170-59, in Super Bowl games.
The Falcons were a wonderful story this season, especially for
Reeves, who had heart surgery but returned to the sideline after
five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Robinson arrest followed by the loss have put a
damper on the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't get any easier,'' Reeves said of the Super Bowl
losses. ``I think the more you have, of those losses, the more you
hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
