<SLUG> BC-KOO-DELIST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOO KOO ROO STOCK DELISTED BY NASDAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: Today in 2nd graf refers to Tuesday.) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ Koo Koo Roo Enterprises Inc., the operator of a
far-flung restaurant chain, said Monday its stock is being delisted
by the Nasdaq exchange after a panel overturned a waiver to the $5
minimum bid requirement.
</P>
<P>
   The company, whose holdings include the Koo Koo Roo, Hamburger
Hamlet, Chi Chi's and El Torito chains, will start trading today on
the OTC exchange under the ticker symbol KKRE.
</P>
<P>
   Koo Koo Roo was first listed on the Nasdaq in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin S. Relyea, the company's chairman, chief executive officer
and president, said the ruling will not impact ongoing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Koo Koo Roo bought the Hamburger Hamlet chain in 1997 and 13
weeks ago merged with privately held Family Restaurants Inc., owner
of the Mexican-themed restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last several months have been involved in getting the two
companies together and understanding the operations down to the
nitty-gritty detail,'' said Robert L. Carl, Koo Koo Roo's vice
president for investor relations. ``I think we pretty much
inherited an excellent opportunity for growth.''
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas J. Burke, director of private placements for
investment house Sutro &AMP; Co., said that ``micro-cap'' restaurant
companies like Koo Koo Roo, those with a market capitalization of
less than $150 million, are finding themselves in a tight financial
spot these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is flowing rapidly out of mutual funds that specialize
in stocks with a market cap of less than $150 million,'' he said.
``Other large investors are also turning away from these micro-cap
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Koo Koo Roo operates 58 restaurants in Los Angeles and Ventura
County. The Irvine-based company has more than 20,000 employees at
300 restaurants scattered across 28 states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0497 </DOCNO>
