<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRUPO-TELEVISA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN AIRED TO RESTRUCTURE GRUPO TELEVISA DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The owners of Grupo Televisa SA, the largest
television conglomerate in the Spanish-speaking world, announced a
plan on Monday to restructure their debt.
</P>
<P>
   Televisa will put up $230 million in cash to buy some of its
stock from its holding company, Grupo Televicentro SA de CV, along
with other notes that will bring Televisa substantial tax breaks.
Televisa is also undertaking a separate $50 million stock
repurchase program.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the measures, if they are approved by Mexican
regulators, will reduce Televicentro's debts by $733 million, to
$533 million. The remaining debt has been extended to three to five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Grupo Televisa has been as packed with intrigue as
the nighttime soap operas it is famous for producing and
broadcasting to countries worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The company's young chairman, Emilio Azcarraga Jean, who is 30,
has campaigned to modernize the company, which created the
television shows that most Mexicans grew up with. But he had to
scramble to hang on to Televisa after the death in April 1997 of
his father, Emilio Azcarraga Milmo, who had built Televisa by
extravagant methods.
</P>
<P>
   Azcarraga Jean, who had little financial experience, took out
large bank loans through Grupo Televicentro to buy stock from
relatives and large shareholders who had been close to his father.
But the decline of the Latin American markets in 1998 sank the
stock price and left his holding company with more than $1.3
billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Delays by Azcarraga Jean in confronting the debt gave rise to
worries on Wall Street that he might lose control of Televisa.
There were also fears that he might shore up Televisa in ways that
would help the Azcarraga family but hurt the public shareholders,
who are in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts were satisfied on Monday that Azcarraga Jean had
found a plan to reduce Televicentro's debts, assuage bankers and
assure other stockholders that his plan was also fair to them.
Televisa shares rose by 6 pesos, or 4.7 percent, to 134 pesos,
here. Its American depository receipts rose 43.75 cents, to
$26.0625, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Azcarraga Jean said in an interview that he hoped the measures
would help bolster the sagging price of Televisa stock.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Grupo Televisa said Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
had been brought in to certify that all shares would be sold
between the two companies at market price. ``Nothing was done that
was not at fair value,'' said Matthew Harrigan, who follows
Televisa for J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   The company's problems are by no means solved, and executives
said they continue to weigh a number of options, such as taking on
a strategic partner. But Azcarraga Jean, who retains 50.3 percent
of the voting control of Televicentro, sounded on Monday like a man
who was at least beginning to master the intricacies of the world
into which he was thrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a huge effort to cut costs and expenses last year, and
it is working well for us,'' he said. ``We are creating more value
for our shareholders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREASURE-SALE-COX     02-01 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREASURE-SALE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fundraiser for Florida aquarium turns into eyebrow-raiser
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Muffy Matthews leaned close to the glass case
enclosing 400-year-old treasure salvaged off a sunken Spanish
galleon, eyeballed a $1.2 million gold and diamond suite of jewels,
elbowed her friend and announced:
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the saber toothpick and I`ll take the Neptune
doubloon.''
</P>
<P>
   And so began the first day of a rather unusual sale to raise
money for a proposed aquarium in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 invitation-only guests squeezed into Mary Mahoney's
Worth Avenue boutique Monday to view jewelry, bowls, a rosary, and
several painful looking grooming devices rescued from the bottom of
the sea by treasure hunter Mel Fisher. What a long way for the
former chicken farmer, who gazed upon the Pellegrino-drinking,
canape-eating throng from a 1980 photograph of him draped in gold
from the Atocha, and displayed in a case with the artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   For the crusty Fisher, home was more frequently a Key West bar
stool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his idea,'' said Fisher's son, Kim, who took over
family businesses after Fisher died in December.
</P>
<P>
   Before his death, Fisher gave $1.4 million in treasure to
aquarium developer Duane Boise to help get the project off the
ground. Since then, the family has pledged another $19 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the ocean and we think it's very important to educate
people about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boise organized the sale with Mahoney's brother, Tom Ryan, a
salvor enthusiast who befriended Fisher before his death and
introduced him to Boise. The treasures _ including a $120,000
boatswain whistle Fisher once blew in federal court after Judge
James Lawrence King awarded him title _ and a $1.2 million gold
spoon, will be displayed through Thursday. Five percent of the
proceeds will go to the aquarium, Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   The family's contribution could mark the first step in what
would be a complicated effort to raise enough money to build the
4.8-acre project in CityPlace.
</P>
<P>
   Boise first proposed the Gulf Stream-themed aquarium for Riviera
Beach, but the city pulled his contract for land after he failed to
raise enough money. Boise has sued. About eight months ago, he
began talking with CityPlace builders and Monday released an
overview of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the $52 million aquarium will depend upon tax-exempt
revenue bonds to pay its way, said Robert T. O'Connor, the
aquarium's director of development and finance.
</P>
<P>
   Boise won't say who would issue the revenue bonds, but Monday
Palm Beach County officials suggested it won't be the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``The county commission, I think, will look at this no
differently than the arena downtown,'' said Commissioner Mary
McCarty.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, county officials refused to support a $55 million
bond issue unless the aquarium developers raised $15 million
privately.
</P>
<P>
   In August they pledged to support a $55 million arena on
Clematis Street if, among other conditions, the developer finds
private investors and provides a letter of credit to guarantee the
county's $1 million a year donation from parking and sales tax
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big challenge, and it's a nice dream,'' McCarty said.
</P>
<P>
   Kajima International, a Los Angeles company that built the
money-losing Tampa aquarium, is developing the project, according
to Boise. More recently, Kajima completed a more successful
attraction in Long Beach, Calif., that boosted that city's
revitalization efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Mel Fisher always liked to say, ``Today's the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who in his last days engaged in a legal battle over the
authenticity of his treasure, fell in love with the aquarium
project when told about plans for an exhibit on treasure salvors,
said family attorney Gene Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What attracted the Fishers to the aquarium project was the
fact that what the aquarium proposes to do is something I don't
believe another aquarium in the U.S. does: They're going to set up
an actual working laboratory, a conservation laboratory within the
aquarium itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The developer and family have talked to state officials about
money to create a center for artifacts found in state waters that
would include a mini-recreation of the Atocha's mother lode, Lewis
said. Visitors would watch as divers re-enact the salvage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Fisher believes the exhibit would be a fitting memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Before he died, Fisher was plagued with challenges to his finds
after he sold several coins purchased from a subcontractor claiming
they were from a 1733 wreck. After one customer complained, others
stepped forward. The Monroe County State Attorney's Office began an
investigation that led to fraud charges and ultimately a
settlement. Fisher pleaded no contest to the charges and promised
to pay back dissatisfied customers. So far, $100,000 has been
repaid to 15 customers and seven more have filed complaints, said
investigator Paul Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   All the items of treasure being sold to help the aquarium _ and
the other $1.4 million donated by Fisher in November _ are from the
Atocha and a 1715 wreck off Sebastian, which have been
authenticated in federal court, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the treasure exhibit, Boise said the aquarium
will feature a 1.5 million gallon tank, a West Africa exhibit with
a pair of hippopotamuses and spider monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when we have the aquarium,'' Fisher's daughter, Taffi,
said as she set up a display case Monday, ``next time we catch a
pirate we're going to throw him in the shark tank.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. Marcia Gelbart and staff researcher Sammie Alfozon
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
