<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-GATLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS' GATLING HAS AN ASSIGNMENT TO SCORE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the job description from heaven. Whether Chris Gatling is
open, in the flow of the game or fresh off the bench, he has Coach
John Calipari's permission to try to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing he does is score,'' Calipari said of the Nets'
6-foot-10-inch forward from Elizabeth, N.J. ``If he plays 25
minutes, he's getting 15 to 18 to 20 points.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatling, a sixth man, scored 18 points in 28 minutes of the
Nets' 92-90 exhibition victory over the Knicks on Friday. And
although he scored the game-winning points on a baby hook and free
throw with 21 seconds remaining, the most impressive part of his
game was his outside shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The new range is a result of Gatling's determination in the
off-season to increase his versatility. Like most big scorers, he
was looking for another path to the points column. Already adept at
driving, hitting hooks and turnarounds, Gatling decided to move to
the perimeter. He continues to hone his touch by working with some
of the Nets' most reliable shooters at practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be a great shooter, you have to shoot with the
best shooters,'' said Gatling, who averaged 11.5 points a game last
season as Keith Van Horn's backup. ``I try to shoot with Brian
Evans. I try to shoot with Keith. I try to shoot with Lucious
Harris, Kerry Kittles. What better way to learn than to learn with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gatling's coaches and teammates are raving about more than
his ability to step outside. The Nets were pleasantly surprised
when Gatling, 31, arrived at training camp in the best shape of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Gatling's sense of urgency came during the summer, when he had
bone spurs removed from his left ankle. The surgery was in
September, and Gatling, assuming the season would start on time,
was afraid of missing the beginning of the year. Motivated by his
fear, he underwent rehabilitation with his personal trainer, George
Abrams, in hopes of playing 82 games.
</P>
<P>
   When the lockout delayed the season, Gatling continued his
varied regimen of lifting weights, riding bikes, working on a
treadmill, sprinting up hills and playing tennis, racquetball and
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the year and a half he's been with me, he's never been in
this type of shape,'' Calipari said.
</P>
<P>
   Calipari is now asking Gatling to extend his responsibilities.
In addition to putting the ball up, Calipari wants Gatling to shut
his opponent down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I'm saying to him is you have to do two things _
guard and rebound,'' Calipari said. ``Then do what you always do.
But if you don't guard and rebound, if you don't block out, it
negates what you're doing offensively.''
</P>
</TEXT>
