<SLUG> BC-HKC-BEANPOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHEASTERN TOPS HARVARD IN OVERTIME AND GAINS BEANPOT FINAL
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Will be led with results of second game.) 
 (ms) 
 By WILLIAM N. WALLACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Northeastern defeated Harvard, 4-3, in overtime Monday
night in the first game of the Beanpot Tournament, Boston's
midwinter salute to college hockey. Brian Cummings, a sophomore
right wing, scored the winning goal 4 minutes 35 seconds into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern advanced to the tournament final, to be played at
the Fleet Center next Monday night, for the first time since 1996.
The Huskies last won the Beanpot in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied after one period and Northeastern led, 3-2,
after two. Then Matt Scorsune, a Harvard defenseman, tied the score
at 3-3 with five seconds left in regulation time.
</P>
<P>
   Scorsune's 20-foot slap shot went through a screen and past
Jason Braun, Northeastern's goalie. The Crimson had six skaters on
the ice and an empty goal in the final minute, and Braun had made
two stops before the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard continued to press in the overtime until Cummings
punched a shot past J.R. Prestifilippo, the Crimson goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College and Boston University met in the second contest.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College (16-8-2) is the only one of the four teams with a
winning record. Boston University (8-14-2), which has won the last
four Beanpot Tournaments, is in the middle of a rare losing season,
and Northeastern (9-13-2), a young team with no seniors and only
four juniors, is struggling as well.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Monday night's loss, Harvard (8-10-1) had bounced back
from a horrendous beginning and won six of its last eight games.
The Crimson, tied for 10th place in the ECAC standings, has won all
five of its nonleague contests and two were victories over
competitors here _ Boston University by 5-3 last Nov. 24 and Boston
College by 3-1, on Jan. 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
