<HEADER>
A7914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPERM-WHALE-COX     02-01 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPERM-WHALE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beached whale clinging to life
 &HT;    By Sally D. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ A pygmy sperm whale that washed ashore at
Melbourne Beach clung to life Monday as volunteers held his head
above water in an above-ground pool at Harbor Branch Oceanographic
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first whale rescue for Harbor Branch, which just
opened a marine mammal emergency care center north of Fort Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-foot whale beached himself about 6 p.m. Sunday and
Department of Environmental Protection staff stayed with him until
about 11 p.m. A Sea World truck took the whale to Harbor Branch.
</P>
<P>
   The whale is very thin, said Steve Lang, a former Sea World and
Marineland employee who came from Orlando to help care for the
animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Healthy whales don't beach themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers tube-fed the whale and gave it antibiotics, but Lang
held out little hope it will survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we let go of him, he sinks to the bottom and doesn't want
to come up,'' said Suzanne Leffew, director of institutional
relations. Leffew is one of more than a dozen Harbor Branch
employees who took two-hour shifts in the pool or did other work to
help the whale.
</P>
<P>
   The animal may be moved to a Florida International University
pool in Miami, the only other emergency care facility on the east
coast, if it is alive today, Leffew said.
</P>
<P>
   Harbor Branch's Dolphin Research Center staff organized the
primitive emergency care center after Orlando's Sea World stopped
taking beached whales and dolphins and St. Augustine's Marineland
closed down.
</P>
<P>
   Sea World has stopped caring for wild marine mammals, fearing
they might have a virus that attacks the immune systems of whales
and dolphins, said Craig Pelton, who is with the Marine Animal
Rescue Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't compromise their captive populations,'' Pelton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Fisheries Service helped Harbor Branch set
up the small pool, which is about 20 feet wide and 4 feet deep,
said Steve McCulloch, Harbor Branch's dolphin program director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing this on a shoestring,'' McCulloch said.
</P>
<P>
   Money from a new ``Protect Wild Dolphin'' specialty auto license
tag, which goes on sale in April, could help pay for a new
facility. But private donations also are needed, McCulloch said.
</P>
<P>
   Harbor Branch will be in charge of distributing money raised
through tag sales for marine mammal research and rescue projects
throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a state-of-the-art pool to care for sick marine
mammals could cost $5 million initially and $1 million annually to
operate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Harbor Branch experts rigged the small pool with a pump
to draw water from a salt water well, heat it and filter it. Others
padded the outside of the pool with foam rubber to buffer the noise
of a heater blower. The sound, magnified by the water, could
further stress the animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harbor Branch has tremendous technical resources,'' McCulloch
said, ``and everyone has been great about helping out. It has been
a real team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally D. Swartz writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
