<SLUG> BC-TEKELEC-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS EXPECT TEKELEC GAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in 1st, 4th grafs refers to Tuesday.) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. _ After a year that saw its sales increase by
nearly 50 percent, telecommunications network equipment maker
Tekelec is expected to report a healthy gain in fourth-quarter and
year-end earnings today.
</P>
<P>
   A consensus of five analysts surveyed by First Call project the
company will report fourth quarter earnings of 19 cents per share,
a 19 percent gain over the same period a year ago. For the year,
analysts expect earnings of 60 cents per share, a 71 percent gain
over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth quarter (increase) might not be as explosive (as
the annual gain), but still they've had a big uptick,'' said
analyst Tim Savageaux at Volpe Brown Whelan in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec said it will announce results after the close of U.S.
stock markets today.
</P>
<P>
   Having struggled for market share throughout the 1990s,
supplying mostly smaller and newcomer telecom operators, Tekelec
emerged in 1998 as a recognized if still relatively minor supplier
to blue chip firms. That was highlighted in October when the
company, northwest of downtown Los Angeles, landed a contract to
sell Sprint between $4 million and $5 million worth of switching
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Together, gains in the two ends of the market pushed Tekelec's
sales up markedly. In the first three quarters, for example, the
company had revenues of $127.5 million, compared to $81.76 million
in the same period a year earlier and to $125 million for all of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its success in growing the business, Tekelec saw its
share price battered around in 1998, dipping to a low of just over
$10 in late summer from a high of more than $25 in April. The
company closed Monday at $21.4375, up $1.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts ascribed the dips in large part to collateral damage
from other telecom equipment makers missing their earnings
estimates. Savageaux has a 12-month target price on Tekelec shares
of $30.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an extremely significant year for them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
