<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MOVIEFONE-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE TO BUY MOVIEFONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif., Ill., Mass.) (lb) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moviefone is hooking up with the ``You've got mail'' man.
</P>
<P>
   America Online said Monday that it had agreed to buy Moviefone
Inc. for stock valued at $388 million, linking two companies
notable for their sonorous spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Moviefone provides movie show times and sells tickets through
the 777-FILM telephone service and the Moviefone.com Internet site.
Most of its $20 million in annual revenue represents advertising
from movie studios promoting films. But about 20 percent of its
sales come from commissions on tickets bought through the service.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest in an aggressive expansion effort by
America Online, which has agreed to buy a range of Internet-related
companies, most recently Netscape Communication Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Moviefone acquisition is a departure of sorts for
America Online, which has mainly served as an advertising medium
for other companies that do business online.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that America Online has bought
something that can be considered a commerce company,'' said Keith
Benjamin, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Schuler, the president of America Online's flagship
service, said that the company wants to make acquisitions in areas
in which electronic commerce will be important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really like businesses where the online medium will
transform them in the future,'' he said. ``And we think that movies
are the sort of thing that people will be doing online more and
more.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online said it would promote Moviefone prominently on
its various online services, especially Digital Cities, its network
of local guides. The Moviefone.com site will be expanded to include
more information about films, creating more positions for
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, which is based in Dulles, Va., also wants to
expand the service to offer ticketing for live events as well as
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that electronic ticketing has a lot of upside and is
at its very early stages,'' Schuler said.
</P>
<P>
   That would open another front of competition with Ticketmaster
Online-Citysearch Inc., the company that recently combined
operations of the United States' leading live-event ticketing
service with a local-information Internet service. The company is
controlled by USA Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Schuler said America Online saw an opportunity to
use Moviefone's phone line and links to theaters as a way to
promote the America Online brand. The service will be renamed AOL
Moviefone.
</P>
<P>
   Moviefone, which is based in New York, sells tickets for about
4,000 of the nation's 27,000 movie screens, though it represents
about 60 percent of the screens in the five biggest markets: New
York, Los Angeles, Boston, Chicago and San Francisco. In New York,
it has a reciprocal promotion arrangement with The New York Times,
among others.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Andrew Jarecki, Moviefone's chief executive, said he had been
looking to sell the business to an Internet company for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought that the Internet would be an important
part of our business, but I've been surprised by how tremendously
fast it has grown,'' he said, adding that 25 percent of the 3
million Moviefone users each week already use the company's World
Wide Web site rather than its phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Moviefone shares trade on the Nasdaq market, but the Jarecki
family controls 73 percent of the company's equity and 92 percent
of its votes. For the quarter ended Sept. 30, 1998, the company
showed a loss of $920,000 on revenue of $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal values Moviefone at $29.25 a share. With rumors of a
deal swirling on Monday, the company's shares closed up $1.50, to
$26.50, after trading as high as $33. America Online's shares fell
$4.5625, to $171.1875, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   For America Online, analysts said, the high price of its stock
allows acquisitions on advantageous terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see even more consolidation like this,'' said David
Readerman, an analyst with Thomas Weisel Partners in San Francisco.
``The leaders want to bulk up so the strong will get stronger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
