<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7917 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-DEATH-SPI &LR;      02-01 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-DEATH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER CHARGE DISMISSED IN INFANT DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GORDY HOLT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ANGELES, Wash. _ Prosecutors Monday dismissed a
second-degree murder charge against Dr. Eugene Turner in the death
of an infant under his care, but troubles still lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Turner still faces possible disciplinary action _ which could
include the loss of his license _ and the parents of the
three-day-old infant say they will file a civil lawsuit against
him.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by an outside prosecutor to drop the charges
against the popular doctor prompted a burst of cheers from his
supporters in the crowded Clallam County courthouse. Turner and
friends later poured champagne to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved,'' he said between hugs.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he never gave up hope that the charge, filed in
October by Clallam County's former prosecutor, David Bruneau, would
be dropped ``once people saw the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the infant's parents, Michelle and Martin McInnerney,
said in a statement through their attorney that they were
disheartened by the decision and ``will continue to do everything
we can to see justice for Conor ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Turner had been accused of stopping Conor's breathing with his
hand on Jan. 12, 1998. The infant was declared dead twice after he
stopped breathing at home and was brought to the Olympic Memorial
Hospital emergency room by ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said the breathing he stopped was reflexive ``agonal
breathing'' that is a sign of imminent death _ that the infant was
already brain-dead.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Knopp, the attorney for the McInnerneys, said Turner's
conduct ``was simply wrong. Marty and Michelle will always be
haunted by the image of what Dr. Turner did while he was alone with
Conor that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Knopp said the couple will file a civil action against Turner. A
$1.5 million civil claim was filed last summer against Olympic
Memorial Hospital where 3-day-old Conor was rushed by emergency
medics on a dark and snowy January night more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Turner, 62, will continue to practice medicine at the
children's clinic he founded here nearly 30 years ago, his wife,
Norma, acknowledged that her husband still faces a review by the
state Medical Quality Assurance Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, the commission charged Turner with unprofessional
conduct, accusing him of lowering the esteem of his profession. He
also is accused of incompetence that resulted in an injury and
abuse of a client. A hearing is set for May 26.
</P>
<P>
   The panel could clear Turner or impose sanctions, ranging from
remedial steps _ such as working with another doctor to improve his
work _ to revocation of his physician's license.
</P>
<P>
   The commission already has ordered Turner not to recuscitate a
patient without another physician present, and that ruling is still
in force.
</P>
<P>
   Commission spokesman Matt Ashworth said the dismissal of the
criminal charge will be taken into account by the panel, but that
its review is a separate proceeding in which protecting the public
is paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said Monday that he believes evidence gathered for the
trial will help before the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can have some evidence to bring forth to the state
board to indicate that things were maybe not as bad as they
originally thought they were,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   With that evidence, ``it will be easier for us and them to come
up with a conclusion which I think will allow everybody to get back
to the business at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unknown when, or if, Turner will reclaim his privilege to
practice medicine at Olympic Memorial Hospital _ a privilege he
voluntarily gave up last year.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for her husband Monday afternoon, Norma Turner said
they intend to continue ``taking it one day at a time as we have
for the last year. This is all new territory for us.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Monday that family and friends ``are celebrating today,
but he's going back to work tomorrow, as he has all year.''
</P>
<P>
   One sentence told it all Monday in Clallam County Superior
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time,'' said Snohomish County's Chief Criminal
Prosecutor Jim Townsend, ``the state moves toward dismissal without
prejudice.'' The phrase means the murder charge against the doctor
is dismissed, but could be brought again should new evidence come
to light.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend's words brought tears and flushed grins to the faces of
the Turners.
</P>
<P>
   Cloaked in controversy and widely publicized, Turner's troubles
began on a snowy night a little more than a year ago. Conor stopped
breathing while nursing at home and was rushed to the emergency
room of Olympic Memorial Hospital. Attending physicians failed to
revive him and neither could Turner.
</P>
<P>
   The child eventually was pronounced dead and placed on a warming
tray to await the coroner. But he later showed signs of life.
Turner again was called to revive the boy, but failed again even as
the infant showed fleeting signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Finally _ and this became the issue that would crystalize the
case for the Clallam County prosecutor _ Turner placed a hand over
the infant's nose and mouth to stop what he later would describe as
the last ``agonal'' gasps of an already brain dead infant.
</P>
<P>
   In his review of the special prosecutors' finding Monday,
visiting Judge Michael Rickert of Skagit County said Turner did
what any other reasonable person in his position might be expected
to do. But he added that ``Turner's choice was not the usual
option.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's trial was set to begin here Jan. 25, but was delayed a
week while the Snohomish County prosecutor's office continued a
review of the case. Snohomish County Prosecutor Jim Krider was
given full charge of the case after the defeat in November's
election of then prosecutor Bruneau, who filed the murder charge in
October.
</P>
<P>
   At a special hearing after the election, the newly elected
prosecutor, Christopher Shea, said he would not have time to review
the case after taking office on Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting Townsend's motion Monday, Rickert said the evidence
against the doctor was not strong enough to merit either murder or
manslaughter charges. Moreover, medical experts cited by both the
prosecution and defense disagreed to such an extent that a trial
would not resolve the differences. Further, there was no evidence
of criminality ``or even negligence,'' Rickert said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference later, Snohomish Prosecutor Krider said
Conor was not dead as defined by state law because his brain stem
was still directing a breathing response.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that wasn't breathing as you or I know it,'' Krider said,
declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   When Rickert signed Townsend's dismissal motion, the courtroom
erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real happy for Dr. Turner, that's for sure,'' said Ken
Simpson, a Port Angeles electrician. He had come to the courthouse
with his wife, Heidi. The couple have two boys, ages 5 and 7. At
age 18 months, the youngest nearly died of pneumonia, but Turner
pulled him through, Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a special place in our hearts for Dr. Turner,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2246EST &QL; 
