<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-CHILDS-NYT     02-01 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CHILDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' COACH TELLS CHILDS TO IGNORE TRADE RUMORS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Jeff Van Gundy calls it clutter: the
thoughts and distractions that have occupied the mind of Chris
Childs since he came to the Knicks two years ago from across the
river. To succeed, the Knick coach tells Childs that he must rid
his mind of the clutter.
</P>
<P>
   But it is easy to understand how Childs could be preoccupied.
Almost from the moment he left the Nets and signed as a free agent
with the Knicks for six years and nearly $24 million, he has been
the subject of trade rumors. And Childs has absorbed more blame
than any player outside of Patrick Ewing for the Knicks' failure to
catch Michael Jordan and the Bulls and win a National Basketball
Association title.
</P>
<P>
   Childs was demoted from the starting lineup last season in favor
of Charlie Ward, which helped Ward gain a big contract this year,
but did little to justify his own contract. And neither Ward nor
Childs has been able to perform to the level of guards such as Rod
Strickland, Tim Hardaway, Mark Jackson or Stephon Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   When Childs' season ended last spring against the Indiana Pacers
as the scapegoat for Reggie Miller's last-second heroics, he went
home to California and could not shield himself from the rumors
that that was his last series as a Knick.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to simply concentrate on basketball, but not with a
particular idea of where he would be playing.
</P>
<P>
   No clutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a stance of whatever happens, happens,'' Childs said
after the first of two practices Monday. ``There is going to be a
time in everybody's career that they're put out there as trade
bait. This was the second year in a row for me. You get used to it
by now. I worked out, ran a lot. I wasn't worried about anything
management was doing. I was just worried about getting myself
mentally back into the game of basketball like I need to.''
</P>
<P>
   With the players locked out, Childs knew that his status with
the Knicks would be in limbo. But if the uncertainty might have
bothered some players, Childs has endured shakier moments in his
life and career, spending five years in the Continental Basketball
Association before he finally stuck in the NBA, and enduring a bout
with alcoholism that nearly cost him his chance.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy said: ``The trade rumors, 99 percent of them are
false, and if you're any good in this league, like Chris obviously
is, people want you so there is always going to be rumors. But also
even if it is true, there is nothing you can do about it, so why
worry?''
</P>
<P>
   When the lockout ended, John Starks, Chris Mills, and Terry
Cummings were dealt to Golden State. Childs was rumored to be gone,
but the Warriors passed on him. And now Childs not only has
returned, but with an increased role. In Starks' absence, Childs
will not only be the backup point guard, but will play alongside
Ward at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our point guards have been much maligned because
they're not your new-wave NBA point guards that think shot first,
pass second,'' Van Gundy said. ``If you look at them statistically
as a combination, what they bring to 48 minutes of the game and not
individually, they're very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Starks, Childs has his share of flaws. Coming from the Nets
where he was the first offensive option after displacing Kenny
Anderson as the starter, he never was as ready as Ward to serve as
a caddie to Ewing. He missed 17 games his first year in New York
and 14 last season with an assortment of injuries. Whatever the
role now, he said he is more mature and ready to be a piece of the
puzzle, and has played through a strained groin during the last two
days of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I've always respected about Chris, I say this to
him all the time, there is not one time I've ever had to get on
Chris about more effort,'' Van Gundy said. ``He plays hard. He
practices hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0507 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-PARADE-CO     02-01 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-PARADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thousands jam streets to greet champions
 &HT;    (MOVING ON (a) GENERAL NEWS AND (s) SPORTS CATEGORIES)
 &HT;    By Ted Taylor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ ``Three-peat'' was the word of the day as more than
300,000 fans gathered in downtown Denver Monday to greet the
Broncos, two-time winners of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd packed sidewalks for a parade that, like Atlanta's,
brought the team through downtown streets aboard fire trucks to a
rally at a park in the heart of the city. As the players were
introduced, fans chanted ``three-peat, three-peat.''
</P>
<P>
   They also reveled in the chance to get in a few more digs at the
defeated Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``How sweet it is,'' Colorado Gov. Bill Owens told the team.
``Thank you for putting those Dirty Birds to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   As clouds parted to let the sun shine on the parade and rally,
the emcees for the event told the fans that it was ``raining
tears'' on Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour parade and rally was about half the length of last
year's, when the Broncos got their first Super Bowl title, and it
almost didn't happen. City officials last week had rejected the
idea, only to change their minds after a public outcry fueled in
part by Atlanta's announcement that it planned a parade and rally
for the Falcons, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl MVP Dan Elway, who is contemplating retirement,
teased the crowd by acknowledging he is tempted by the thought of
winning three Super Bowls in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``That three-peat does sound interesting,'' Elway said with a
grin. ``We'll talk about it later.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie White, in Hawaii for his record 11th Pro Bowl appearance,
is preparing to strap on the shoulder pads one last time.
</P>
<P>
   Or is he?
</P>
<P>
   White insisted all year that this was his final season, and at
37, he had a great farewell, garnering 16 sacks and the NFL
Defensive Player of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   Like Michael Jordan, he went out on the top of his considerable
game.
</P>
<P>
   But White, who changed his mind 48 hours after announcing his
retirement last April, gave Green Bay Packers fans another glimmer
of hope Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Fox network show before the Super Bowl, White, who was
due to make $3.9 million in 1999, said he was ``intrigued'' about
the idea of returning to play under new coach Ray Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ray got the job, if anyone else had gotten the job I
wouldn't have been intrigued,'' White told Fox. ``I've really been
praying about it and thinking about it. Right now I'm retired.''
</P>
<P>
   White's agent, Jimmy Sexton, said he doesn't think White will
change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Taylor writes for the Daily Sentinel, Grand Junction, Colo.
The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
