 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BLAIR (London) _ Twenty months after Tony Blair led
Britain's ``new'' Labor party to power, there are two images of
him: the first is that he is youthful, articulate, and a visionary,
a leader of a nation in dramatic transition. The other is that he
is all style and fluff, with little substance. A look at what is
actually inside the enticingly wrapped package he is offering
Britain for its future. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT14) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ News analysis: as the
deadline approaches for entering peace talks on Kosovo province,
with threats of NATO bombs and sharp warnings from the West,
Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, has much to gain. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WATCHES (Shenzhen, China) _ Every day, an estimated 90,000
people travel by train or bus from Hong Kong across the border to
Shenzhen, a raucous boom town of thrusting skyscrapers and
bottom-feeding nightclubs. Many head straight for Lo Wu Commercial
City, a giant shopping mall devoted almost entirely to imitation
luxury goods. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT grpahics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-RECRUITING (Aboard the USS HARRY S. TRUMAN) _ The Navy
spent $4.5 billion to build this, the nation's newest carrier. It
has two nuclear reactors, the latest electronic, computer and
navigational equipment and, for the long ``cruises'' to come,
amenities for the crew, like televisions in almost every berth.
What the Navy cannot put aboard the Truman is a full crew. The
ship, commissioned by Clinton last July to join the nation's other
carriers, is not alone. Two weeks ago, the Navy disclosed that it
has had as many as 22,000 empty positions, or billets, in a force
of 372,000. The vast majority of those were aboard the Navy's 327
ships, rather than on shore. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
