<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAEMMLE-OPENING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAEMMLE TO OPEN REGION'S BIGGEST MEGAPLEX FOR ART FILMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Laemmle Theaters, hoping to cash in on the
increased taste for offbeat fare from American moviegoers, has
stepped up its pursuit of box-office dollars by launching the
region's largest art-house theater.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the Playhouse 7 means Laemmle, often the first
chain to show quirky films like ``Affliction'' and ``Central
Station,'' will be battling on similar megaplex turf as chains like
AMC, Edwards and Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the 1,200-seat facility is half the size of many
megaplexes, it offers the hot concepts _ stadium seating, massive
concession stands, big screens even in small auditoriums, staggered
start times _ now expected by customers at the mainstream chains.
</P>
<P>
   The mission-style complex, due to open Friday, has been under
consideration by privately-held Laemmle for most of the decade as
the competition for moviegoers heated up. ``The economics of the
business are such that single screens are disappearing,'' said
owner Robert Laemmle. ``The same conditions apply to the
specialized film area.''
</P>
<P>
   Laemmle did not disclose how much the Playhouse 7 costs but
state-of-the-art movie houses currently cost about $1 million per
screen.
</P>
<P>
   The Laemmle name goes back more than eight decades in Hollywood
history from when film distributor Carl Laemmle bought a 230-acre
ranch in the Cahuenga Pass that became Universal Studios. The
family cut ties with the studio in 1936 and started opening its own
theaters, coming to the San Fernando Valley Valley in 1979 when it
took over the Town Center complex in suburban Encino.
</P>
<P>
   The Playhouse 7 will boost the number of screens operated by Los
Angeles-based Laemmle by 20 percent from 27 to 34. It gives the
chain a far better chance of making money from obscure films like
``Clerks'' or ``Ulee's Gold'' that might have otherwise gone
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago, foreign films were a big staple of the
art-house market so it's primarily expanded from American indie
films achieving greater popularity,'' Laemmle said, citing the
near-sweep of Academy Awards by ``The English Patient,'' ``Fargo,''
``Sling Blade'' and ``Shine'' in 1997. ``The popularity of the
indies has taken on a whole new dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   Visibility for indie product, produced outside the direct
control of the seven major studios, is crucial nowadays. That's
because the number of independent movies, inspired by the break-out
successes of ``Pulp Fiction'' and ``The Full Monty,'' has exploded.
While majors have cut back the number of films released in recent
years, indies have gone from 121 movies in 1993 to 287 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The art-house market is the largest and most well-established
niche in moviegoing,'' said Chris Lanier, head of the Motion
Picture Intelligencer analysis firm. ``It is playing to a different
audience universe than a mass entertainment film, so you can do
different things because that's what that audience responds to.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate art houses take in about 5 percent of the
nation's gross but the number of art-house screens has not expanded
as quickly as the rest of the business. ACNielsen EDI estimates
that more than half of the 3,086 U.S. screens that opened last year
came from just 80 megaplexes.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of new art-house screens and the plethora of indie
product means that distributors often can't find specialized
locations and have to settle for megaplexes or discount houses. In
either case, the grosses won't be as high as they would at an art
house.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles-based Laemmle, which operates nine theaters, is
gambling on being able to invigorate a relatively quiet stretch of
Colorado Boulevard about a mile to the east of the red-hot Old Town
retail district of Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Experts contend it's become crucial to cluster like this. ``I
think the public is getting used to the idea that if they go see a
movie, they'll be other opportunities before and after to do things
like eating and shopping,'' said Grubb &AMP; Ellis commercial real
estate broker Bill Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The introduction of live theater or additional movie screens
extends the hours of a retail environment, which enhances retail
sales,'' he added. ``They're joined at the hip because they enhance
the longevity of the customer staying in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the first new theater for Laemmle since 1993, when it
opened the 1,000-seat Sunset 5 in West Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Playhouse 7's opening may lead to Laemmle
closing its other two theaters in Pasadena, the Colorado and the
Esquire. ``We've been frustrated with operating two single screens
in Pasadena that we could not show all the product we wanted,''
said Laemmle, who would only say he plans to keep the other venues
open for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   The executive argues that the line between art-house movies and
major studio releases has gotten blurry in recent years as the Big
Seven become more inclined to search for low-budget high-prestige
hits rather than farming them out to their indie subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Laemmle is pleased that the Playhouse 7 will show ``Rushmore,''
a critical favorite moving into nationwide release, on two screens
at the Playhouse 7 even though it is being released by Disney, one
of Hollywood's largest studios. ``I think of it as a well-done
specialty film even though it's from Disney and stars Bill
Murray,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also playing will be five other films with some chance of
recognition when Academy Award nominations are announced Feb. 9:
``Affliction,'' ``The General,'' ``Little Voice,'' ``Playing by
Heart'' and ``Still Crazy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
