<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS GET GUIDED TOUR OF GREED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The guy from the county and the guy from the Arizona
Diamondbacks tell me that ripping off schoolchildren is not what
they had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, that's what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   The guy from the county and the guy from the Arizona
Diamondbacks tell me that we're not talking about a lot of money,
particularly when you look at the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, they continue putting the squeeze on kids.
</P>
<P>
   The guy from the county and the guy from the Arizona
Diamondbacks tell me that everything associated with Bank One
Ballpark is new and constantly being re-evaluated and that the
program being discussed could change.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it hasn't. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, a group of schoolchildren from Phoenix will
take a guided tour of Bank One Ballpark. It's part of an all-day
program in which the kids also will visit the Phoenix Public
Library.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of one of the children, Kathy Errigo, was surprised
to discover the ballpark tour would cost each student $4.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 60 children from my daughter's school going on the
tour,'' Errigo said. ``That's $240 to take kids around a ballpark
that myself and my husband and everybody else who lives here
chipped in a lot of money to build.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-hundred and thirty-eight million, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now they want to charge children to see the place?''
Errigo said. ``That doesn't make any sense. Taxpayers paid to build
the library, too. They're not charging the kids for THAT tour.'' &QL; 
AN ARRANGEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Bill Scalzo, a spokesman for Maricopa County, said the ballpark
tours were part of an arrangement worked out with the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention was never to make money off kids,'' he said.
``It's really something aimed more at winter visitors and tourists,
those who didn't pay taxes to build it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine.
</P>
<P>
   So why charge schoolchildren?
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks spokesman Craig Pletenik emphasized that the
proceeds from ballpark tours are split between the county and
Diamondbacks charities. He said ticket pricing is based on what is
charged at other ballparks with tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get right down to it,'' he said, ``the proceeds are
going to charity, so in an indirect way it's going back to help
some of those same kids who have been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, when you get right down to it, they could treat kids
like future patrons who might think more fondly of an operation
that didn't once covet their milk money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem smart to me,'' Kathy Errigo said. ``I don't
believe the money is worth the bad feelings.'' &QL; 
`VERY FEW' COMPLAINTS
</P>
<P>
   Scalzo said the price of tours hasn't created any ill will,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had very few, if any, calls with that type of
complaint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are $6 for adults, $4 for children ages 7 to 12, $2 for
those 4 to 6 and free for those 3 and younger. There's also a group
rate of $4 a head.
</P>
<P>
   Both Scalzo and Pletenik said money needs to be raised to pay
for guides and scheduling. Although I'd guess there are hundreds of
retired baseball fans in the area who'd do it for no pay.
</P>
<P>
   Pletenik said Diamondbacks charities handed out almost a
half-million dollars to programs for the homeless and health care
for the poor. Tour proceeds played a tiny part in that, he added.
</P>
<P>
   He and Scalzo also said the Diamondbacks and the county are
working on programs to get more kids to ballgames _ free _ in the
coming season, and that there may be more ``open house''
opportunities for the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the paid tours remain popular. They last a little over
an hour, and include stops at the visitors' clubhouse, the
Diamondbacks' dugout, the swimming pool behind the center-field
fence and even a luxury suite.
</P>
<P>
   It's a very educational experience for boys and girls, teaching
them nothing about baseball but all they need to know about
government and big business.
</P>
<P>
   E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
