<HEADER>
A8036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT &LR;      02-01 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE FANS 
TORRE ALOFT 
CROSS-COUNTRY COLLABORATION 
GUN CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 BY JAMES BARRON WITH BENJAMIN WEISER AND BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``There's no bigger fan than the mayor himself,''
Michael Hess, the city's corporation counsel, declared last week
after federal prosecutors accused New York City and the New York
Yankees of discriminating against fans with disabilities at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that the top federal prosecutor in Manhattan
_ who signed the papers the government filed in U.S. District Court
_ is a Yankee fan too.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney for the Southern District, is a
fan from childhood and knows her way around Yankee Stadium. ``My
husband has been in a ticket group for about 10 years and has
tickets to about 20 home games a year,'' she said through a
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   So how many Yankees games does Mayor Rudolph Giuliani attend?
</P>
<P>
   ``As many as he can get to,'' said a spokeswoman, Colleen Roche.
She said Giuliani sits in a box on the first base side, right next
to the Yankees' dugout. Ms. White's spokesman, Herbert Hadad, would
not elaborate on where her seats are.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Shira Scheindlin, who has scheduled a hearing for a week
from Tuesday in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, is maintaining
absolute impartiality. An aide said Monday that she had no comment
as to whether she was a Yankees fan or not. Maybe the Mets?
</P>
<P>
   Air Time
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees manager, has said that winning the 1996
World Series was like having an out-of-body experience.
</P>
<P>
   He had the same feeling Monday, when he rode in (and briefly
piloted) an F-18 Hornet at the Naval Air station in El Centro,
Calif. The jet is standard equipment for the Blue Angels team that
performs internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a rush,'' Torre said once he was back on the ground,
talking about ``the whole G-force thing'' and about taking a fast,
low pass over the California landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like going over another planet,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Lt. Keith Hoskins, turned the controls over to Torre
at 10,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did great,'' Hoskins said. ``He did some right-handed turns
and left-handed turns, and a 360-degree roll. He did it perfect,
and we told him we were going to have to get him a job during the
off-season.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Torre put it: ``My wife said this is the most I've smiled
in the off-season, even after winning the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   A Few Bars
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First Michael Amante, a graphic artist and cabaret
performer, wrote a song about Mary Kay Letourneau, the Seattle
teacher who had two children by a boy she started having sex with
when he was in her sixth-grade class.
</P>
<P>
   Then Amante sang the song (``I Never Meant to Fall in Love With
You'') for her over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   She was in prison. Amante, who is scheduled to appear in the Oak
Room at the Algonquin Hotel in New York next month, was standing in
the office of Sonny Grosso, a former New York City detective turned
producer whose show business career grew out of the ``French
Connection'' drug case (Roy Scheider played Grosso in the Academy
Award-winning thriller). Grosso bought the film rights to Ms.
Letourneau's story and commissioned a script.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Letourneau was tinkering with the song's lyrics by long
distance ``like they were schoolwork'' when Amante walked in. ``I
said, `Why don't you let Michael sing this?''' Grosso recalled.
``After, she said, `Forget whatever I said.'''
</P>
<P>
   `Fire' Insurance
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernadette Peters, who plays the pistol-packin' Annie
Oakley in the revived, rewritten version of ``Annie Get Your Gun''
that goes into previews at the Marquis Theater Tuesday night, will
not be packing real pistols. The bang-bang _ the sharp report of a
six-shooter or the crack of a rifle _ comes from the drum section.
</P>
<P>
   This is not because Miss Peters wanted ``Annie Get Your Gun'' to
make a statement about gun control. ``She has no stance on gun
control,'' her spokeswoman, Judy Katz, said.
</P>
<P>
   No, the decision came from the show's choreographer, Graciela
Daniele. ``I hate firearms,'' she said. ``They were absolutely
needed 200 years ago when people had to kill to eat, but not
today.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the issue of authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did research on Annie Oakley,'' she said. ``They never used
bullets. They used pellets, or they would have killed the
spectators.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
