</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEZE ON MEDICARE MONEY TO HOSPITALS WOULD PAY FOR HEALTH CARE
INITIATIVES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Fla.)   (See related BUDGET-CLINTON, BUDGET-ASSESS, BUDGET-REVENUE) 
 (Eds: SUBS for story slugged BUDGET-SPEND on digest; accompanied by
BUDGET-MILITARY, BUDGET-ENERGY and BUDGET-ENVIRONMENT.)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the budget blueprint he offered Monday,
President Clinton proposes keeping Medicare payments to hospitals
at current levels next year to help pay for new health care
initiatives, including assistance to people who need long-term care
and the expansion of Medicare to people from 55 to 64.
</P>
<P>
   The freeze, which would save $3.9 billion over five years, comes
on top of cutbacks made by Congress in the Balanced Budget Act of
1997, which squeezed $112 billion from Medicare over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, administrator of the federal Health Care
Financing Administration, which runs Medicare, said the proposed
freeze in hospital payment rates was justified because hospitals
were being overpaid.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Pollack, executive vice president of the American
Hospital Association, said: ``We don't understand the logic behind
the president's proposal. It makes no sense to us.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should wait to see how hospitals and other health care
providers cope with the cuts already enacted'' in 1997, Schumer
said in a letter to the president. Moreover, he said, the proposed
cutbacks would ``fall heavily on New York hospitals'' and, because
the savings would be used to finance new initiatives, would not
improve the shaky financial condition of the Medicare trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposes a relatively modest increase in the budget of
the National Institutes of Health, the pre-eminent sponsor of
biomedical research in the United States. In 1998, Congress
approved an increase of $2 billion, or 15 percent, so the
institutes would have a total of $15.6 billion in the current
fiscal year. Clinton proposes a further increase of $320 million,
or 2.1 percent, for a total of $15.9 billion in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Even Donna Shalala, the secretary of Health and Human Services,
said such abrupt changes in the growth of federal support for
scientific research were unwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer that it was larger,'' Shalala said. ``I don't
think that the roller-coaster effect, going up and going down, is
an effective way to invest in the nation's scientific
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his proposal was consistent with his commitment,
made before the 1999 budget was adopted last year, to increase the
NIH budget by 50 percent over five years. In contrast, members of
Congress from both parties are determined to double the institutes'
budget over five years, and administration officials said Clinton
could propose small increases in the knowledge that Congress would
add to them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sens. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, and Connie Mack, R-Fla., said
they were disappointed with the president's proposal for biomedical
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents a regrettable retreat in the search for
medical breakthroughs,'' Harkin said. Mack said: ``The president's
proposed budget means a cease-fire in the war against cancer,
Parkinson's, Alzheimer's and other diseases. It is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton proposed a big increase for the Food and Drug
Administration. Its budget would rise by 19 percent, to $1.35
billion. Shalala said this would be the biggest increase for the
agency in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The president would double the budget for FDA enforcement of
tobacco rules, providing $68 million to curb cigarette sales to
people under the age of 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
