<HEADER>
A8044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-STARR-LEAKS-N     02-01 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-STARR-LEAKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR SAYS HE WILL INVESTIGATE HIS OFFICE FOR LEAKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-JORDAN) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, said Monday
that he would investigate his own office for leaks, after President
Clinton's lawyer accused it of disclosing that Starr might seek an
indictment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In making his accusation Monday morning, David Kendall, the
president's private lawyer, cited an account in The New York Times
on Sunday, attributed to associates of Starr, that said he had
concluded he had the authority to seek the indictment of an
incumbent president. White House aides complained that Starr was
spreading that news in hopes of influencing the Senate impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bakaly, a spokesman for Starr, denied that his office
was the source for the article.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not leak this information, and that's all I can say
about that,'' Bakaly said on the ABC News television program ``Good
Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost a year, Kendall has accused Starr of violating
federal rules forbidding the disclosure of grand jury testimony.
Starr has repeatedly denied such disclosure, and critics of the
White House have accused it of spreading protected information
itself, in hopes of tarring the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said on Monday that he would file a motion in federal
court over the latest episode, seeking to have Starr and his staff
held in contempt for ``improper violations of grand jury secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The office of independent counsel,'' Kendall said, ``has once
again engaged in illegal and partisan leaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Late on Monday afternoon, Starr issued a statement that said:
``We are deeply troubled by yesterday's New York Times report. This
office has no desire to inject itself into the constitutional
process under way in the Senate. We are launching an internal
investigation to determine whether anyone in this office improperly
disclosed the information to The Times. The announcement of this
investigation should not be taken as confirmation of anything in
the article.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Clymer, Washington editor of The Times, said, ``We do not
discuss our sources.''
</P>
<P>
   James Kennedy, a White House spokesman, noted that Starr
announced another internal leaks investigation last Feb. 6.
``Here's hoping this February's investigation doesn't disappear
into the same black hole as last February's investigation,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   In making his accusation, Kendall is relying on a broad
interpretation of the rules governing grand jury secrecy. But the
federal judge who has heard his previous complaints, Norma Holloway
Johnson, has upheld a broad interpretation in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall believes that prosecutors are forbidden to reveal not
only the content of grand jury testimony but also subjects of
potential indictments and the timing of indictments, Clinton
advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Judge Johnson ruled that prosecutors were
prohibited from talking publicly about matters like the ``strategy
and direction of the investigation'' as well as ``what is likely to
occur'' before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   She found that 24 news accounts last year appeared on their face
to show that prosecutors from Starr's office had violated federal
rules by disclosing details of their investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The judge appointed a special master, John Kern III, a former
judge here, to investigate the matter. His progress is unclear,
though he was expected to report to Judge Johnson by the end of
1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0519 </DOCNO>
