A8046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      02-01 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES LARGEST INCREASE IN MILITARY SPENDING SINCE
REAGAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)   (See related BUDGET-CLINTON, BUDGET-ASSESS, BUDGET-REVENUE) 
 (Eds: SUBS for story slugged BUDGET-SPEND on digest; accompanied by
BUDGET-HEALTH, BUDGET-ENERGY and BUDGET-ENVIRONMENT.)  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The budget proposed by President Clinton on Monday
includes the largest increase in military spending since the Cold
War buildup under President Reagan and would give members of the
military their biggest raise in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The president's budget of $267.2 billion includes a $12 billion
increase, $4 billion of which is a straight increase and $8 billion
of which is to be financed by savings earned from
lower-than-budgeted fuel prices and inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The president is also asking for the authority to initiate two
more rounds of base closings, which would eventually produce $2
billion in annual savings, although that is not reflected in this
year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton appears to have included all the money requested
by the military to improve pay, benefits and readiness _ including
spare parts and training _ he held back on any sharp increase for
modernizing the military's weaponry and equipment. He asked for $53
billion for procurements, only $1 billion less than in the earlier
budget review. But it was not the larger increase requested by the
Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   That modernization includes money for a new Virginia-class
attack submarine, Navy ships, aircraft for the Air Force and a
national missile defense system that the Pentagon is trying to
develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``This highlights the looming debate over modernization that
will probably become part of next year's presidential campaign,''
said Michael O'Hanlon of the Brookings Institution. ``The question
will be whether the Cold War-like agenda for modernization should
be reassessed before all that money is spent.``
</P>
<P>
   In presenting the budget, Defense Secretary William Cohen
emphasized the 4.4 percent increase in pay for the troops, the
reinstatement of military retirement benefits to 50 percent of base
pay after 20 years in service, from 40 percent, as well as special
programs to encourage members of the military to stay in the
service.
</P>
<P>
   Congress agrees that the military deserves higher pay and, in
what may become a bidding war, a Senate committee last week
approved a bill that would give the military an even larger raise,
4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Monday that while the Pentagon welcomed as much money
as it could get ``for our men and women in uniform,'' he was
worried that the Senate would not be able to come up with the
additional $7 billion that its pay proposal would require.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to raise expectations and not be able to pay
for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, Senate Republicans, who plan to make increasing
military pay a major theme of this congressional session,
complained that the Clinton budget for the military was not large
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed that the president did not fully heed the
requests of his secretary of defense and the Joint Chiefs of Staff
for a significant defense budget increase,'' said Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The military budget is apart from $13 billion for the nuclear
weapons programs of the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   About $29 billion of the Pentagon's budget is for the nation's
13 intelligence services, including the CIA. The precise amount is
classified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
