<HEADER>
A8048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ELWAY-NYT &LR;      02-01 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ELWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PLAY IT AGAIN, JOHN 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, Feb. 2: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Was Sunday's Super Bowl John Elway's last game? He has talked
about retiring, but has made no final decision. Denver obviously
needs him next year if it hopes to become the first team in history
to win a third straight Super Bowl. The game of professional
football may need him even more to revive sagging ratings.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, it is best for an athlete to leave at the top of his
game, before the reflexes erode and the muscles tire and the fans
grow fickle. Elway is clearly at the top, but if Sunday's
performance is any guide, he has at least one and maybe several
more years of excellence left in him. His arm is the same cannon it
always was, his competitiveness is undiminished. Near the end of a
game that Denver was in no danger of losing, he even chewed out a
receiver who had run the wrong pattern, possibly costing Denver a
final touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   It may be tempting to take his most-valuable-player trophy and
his 38-year-old body and retire to his den and the golf course. But
his teammates hope this second straight Super Bowl victory may spur
him to go for three _ a tasty prospect that, Elway concedes,
``throws a kink into my thinking.'' The people who run the National
Football League have an equal interest in his continued presence.
Attendance has been flat during the 1990s, while television ratings
have actually declined.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend, with some justification, that professional
football has become boring, with excessive timeouts and too many
coaches who prefer conservative running games to razzle-dazzle.
Students of the game also lament that free agency has made it
impossible to build and maintain the kind of marquee teams, like
the old Dallas Cowboys or San Francisco 49ers, that some people
love and others love to hate but nearly everyone wants to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Elway can help fix all that. There is nothing conservative about
a quarterback who has produced a record 47 game-saving drives over
his career. This man was born to take risks. And with Elway at the
helm, Denver surely has marquee status. Elway may feel that 16 hard
years is enough. But he should consider at least one more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0521 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT &LR;      02-01 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: KEN STARR'S MEDDLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, Feb. 2: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising aspect of the Senate impeachment trial is
the persistent challenges to the senators' constitutional right to
run it. First came the House managers' attempt to call a parade of
unnecessary witnesses. Now we have an apparent effort from the
office of Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, to spark a debate
over criminal prosecution of the president at a time when the
Senate deserves a calm decision-making atmosphere and an open field
for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is already regarded by his critics as an obsessive
personality. Now he seems determined to write himself into the
history books as a narcissistic legal crank. Once the Senate
started the second presidential impeachment trial in American
history, that was Starr's cue not only to shut up but to stop any
activity by his office that would direct attention away from the
Senate or reduce its bargaining room. The issue of who leaked news
of Starr's indictment research to The New York Times is a phony
one. What is needed here is not an investigation of journalistic
sources, but attention to the substance of Starr's legal mischief.
It seems designed to disrupt these solemn deliberations into
presidential misconduct of a serious if undeniably sordid kind.
</P>
<P>
   The news article highlighted an underlying problem. Starr keeps
flapping around _ with deliberations over indictments and by
meddling in the House managers' contacts with Monica Lewinsky _ in
ways that complicate Senate work that is more important than he is.
The Senate should rebuke Starr and also appeal to the federal
judges who supervise him to restrain him from further disturbance
of the constitutional process.
</P>
<P>
   This incident is more serious than Starr's customary blundering.
The Constitution clearly allows the indictment and prosecution of
officials who have been impeached by the House and removed from
office by the Senate. But whether such a trial should go forward in
this case is a complex constitutional and civic question that needs
to be shaped by the wisdom of the Senate rather than by Starr's
personal inclinations and his idea of prosecutorial duty. If the
three witnesses being deposed this week do not dramatically change
the evidence, then the Senate is clearly the right place to make
the final disposition of President Clinton's case.
</P>
<P>
   For Starr's office to be talking about a trial inhibits the
Senate's freedom to draft a censure resolution that might include
some kind of presidential admission. Indeed, virtually everyone in
the capital except Starr seems to know that censure-plus-admission,
speedily arrived at, would be a far better outcome for the country
than a trial for either a sitting or former president.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, if the charges were of greater criminal magnitude or
threatened orderly government, such a trial could be fitting and
constitutional once a president was removed. While removal is not
appropriate in this case, the Senate is clearly the appropriate
venue for condemning and finding a proportional punishment to
offenses like those committed by Clinton. The Senate, which is
always talking about its potent collective probity, needs to find a
way to slap Starr back into line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
