<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-ENERGY-NYT     02-01 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-ENERGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: TENN.) 
ENERGY SPENDING WOULD RISE 4 PERCENT IN 2000 UNDER CLINTON'S
PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (See related BUDGET-CLINTON, BUDGET-ASSESS, BUDGET-REVENUE) 
 (Eds: SUBS for story slugged BUDGET-SPEND on digest; accompanied by
BUDGET-HEALTH, BUDGET-MILITARY and BUDGET-ENVIRONMENT.)  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under President Clinton's proposed budget, the
Energy Department's operating budget for the 2000 fiscal year would
rise $717 million, or 4.1 percent above the 1999 figure, not
counting one-time expenditures this year like buying enriched
uranium from Russia and helping that country safeguard plutonium.
Spending in 2000 would be $17.8 billion, about the same as what the
department is spending this year, including those one-time
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The administration wants to spend $208 million more on renewable
energy and energy efficiency, and $138 million for science
projects, including supercomputers and a new nuclear laboratory at
Oak Ridge, Tenn., that would use neutrons to investigate the
properties of matter. The proposal also includes $109 million for
``threats of nuclear, biological and chemical proliferation,'' and
for doubling the counterintelligence effort, because of penetration
of the department's laboratories by foreign spies.
</P>
<P>
   Other areas that would get big increases include a testing
program for nuclear weapons that substitutes for explosions, and
environmental clean-up of former weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also proposes to pay for maintenance of the Strategic
Petroleum Reserve out of tax revenues, rather than sales from the
reserve, and Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said he would soon
propose some way to add oil. He said this would not be a
``budgetary initiative'' but did not say how he planned to pay for
increasing the reserve, which is at 561 million barrels, roughly
two months' worth of imports.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also calls for $86.5 million, up from $78.5 million,
for health studies of workers and people who live near weapons
plants. The department is trying to determine, with the Department
of Health and Human Services, which sites most merit study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0523 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-ENVIRONMENT-NY     02-01 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-ENVIRONMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE SEEKING RECORD $34 BILLION FOR ENVIRONMENTAL PROGRAMS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla.)  (See related BUDGET-CLINTON, BUDGET-ASSESS, BUDGET-REVENUE) 
 (Eds: SUBS for story slugged BUDGET-SPEND on digest; accompanied by
BUDGET-HEALTH, BUDGET-MILITARY and BUDGET-ENERGY.)  (mk) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN JR. 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The administration is seeking a record $33.9
billion for environmental programs next year, an increase of 5
percent over this year's spending.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the hardest part of the budget to sell in Congress will
be the $4 billion for fighting the risk of global warming, mainly
by spurring research and investments in energy efficiency. But even
industry lobbyists who have opposed a proposed international treaty
to reduce emissions of heat-trapping gases welcomed some of the
proposals, saying they would help companies take voluntary steps.
</P>
<P>
   Along with hefty increases in federal energy research, the
budget for 2000 proposed by President Clinton on Monday seeks $3.6
billion in tax breaks over the next five years for renewable energy
investments and for purchases of energy-efficient homes, cars and
appliances. Congress has turned down similar ideas before.
</P>
<P>
   Another major initiative calls for spending $1 billion next year
to buy land for conservation, a record amount. Like several other
environmental proposals, this one had already been announced by the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights include $312 million for restoring the
Everglades, $2.3 billion for programs to clean up polluted waters,
$1.5 billion for cleaning up Superfund toxic waste dumps, and $1.8
billion for transportation programs intended to ease traffic
congestion to help cut air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental proposals emphasize aid to states and cities,
including matching grants for air pollution programs and $700
million in tax credits over five years to subsidize the issuance of
$9.5 billion in conservation bonds. Of the Environmental Protection
Agency's request for $7.2 billion next year, 40 percent would be
funneled to state and local governments, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
