<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0525 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENIM-FASHION-ART-NYT     02-01 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENIM-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENIM TURNED EVERY WHICH WAY BUT LOOSE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blue is supposed to be the color for the millennium. Could that
be why denim seems to be more popular now than at any time in the
last 10 years? Its current appeal extends to all ages and
socioeconomic groups, to the young and to the sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   While teen-agers live in jeans, wearing them for school, on
dates, for just about every activity, adults generally reserve them
for casual times. But there are signs that designers would like to
change that. And not just designers with jeans lines like Tommy
Hilfiger, Helmut Lang, Calvin Klein and Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   In her spring-summer report to Saks Fifth Avenue's buyers,
Nicole Fischelis, the store's fashion director, listed all the
variations on denim seen on the runways. These included Martin
Margiela's recycled-denim pinafore, Chanel's simple denim skirts
paired with organza tops, Gucci's elaborately decorated jeans, Anna
Sui's hippie revival, Hussein Chalayan's denim suits with
asymmetric trimming, and Thierry Mugler's glamour dresses in denim.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the feather-trimmed denim strapless ball gown in Jean
Paul Gaultier's haute-couture show last month, and 10 pages in the
February Harper's Bazaar of denim that was studded, painted and
distressed by designers like Lang, Stephen Sprouse and Tom Ford
(whose feather-trimmed and embroidered jeans for Gucci are priced
at more than $3,000).
</P>
<P>
   Denim has come a long way since a Bavarian immigrant named Levi
Strauss first used it in 1850 to sew sturdy trousers for California
miners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it denim deluxe,'' Ms. Fischelis said. ``There are new
ways to take this fabric. I see a return of denim done in very
fashion ways. Our March catalog has a spread on different items of
denim. There are shoes, slides, hair accessories, and bags from
Chanel and Fendi.''
</P>
<P>
   Kal Ruttenstein, Bloomingdale's senior vice president for
fashion direction, also sees a revival of interest in denim as a
fashion fabric. ``That Gaultier couture dress will give a
tremendous resurgence to ready-to-wear in denim,'' he said. ``We
think it will put the idea of making things other than jeans into
more designers' heads.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that, while the darkest denim is selling now,
Bloomingdale's is betting on distressed looks and white for spring.
``And we think gray and pewter denim will be strong for fall,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else in fashion, the interest in denim and jeans
is cyclical. In the 1950s, movie stars like Marilyn Monroe and
James Dean made wearing jeans look glamorous and sexy. In the '60s,
jeans became a symbol of social rebellion. In the late '70s, Calvin
Klein and Ralph Lauren got into the act and sparked a craze for
designer jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Jeans sales reached 502 million pairs in 1981. By 1998, that
figure had dropped to 412 million. Sales last year totaled $8.29
billion, according to the NPD Group, which tracks sales of apparel
and accessories. That represents an increase of more than $2
billion in the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The jeans business appears to be growing, thanks to the
teen-agers who have adopted jeans as a school uniform. And it has
become fashion-driven. Style, fit and label are all important to
teen-agers, and the criteria can change with astonishing speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a fashion cycle, and when you're in a fashion cycle
it can shift so fast,'' said Bonnie Junell, a Nordstrom vice
president and merchandise manager for junior girls. ``Fit-and-flare
is the new basic. We used to display jeans folded on shelves on the
back wall. Now you have to hang them so they see the style.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Bufano, an executive vice president of Macy's East,
agreed. ``The status explosion has been going on for three or four
years with labels like DKNY, Polo, Tommy Jeans, Guess and CK Calvin
Klein,'' she said. ``In the junior area, the explosion has reached
the second-tier jeans resources, the California-based entrepreneurs
that have tremendous newness, that change the silhouette and body
every six weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   She mentioned labels like Mudd, LEI, Paris Blues and Union Bay
that have been keeping up with changing tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers who a few years ago were wearing oversize
rave-inspired jeans with elephant legs so wide they looked like
skirts are now into a smaller silhouette. Favored styles are either
hip-huggers that fit tight across the hips and thighs and flare out
toward the ankle or slim, straight-legged styles with turned-up
cuffs. There are, of course, regional differences.
</P>
<P>
   One of the people who track fashion preferences among teen-agers
is Irma Zandl, the president of the Zandl Group in New York, a
trend-spotting company that does nationwide surveys. She says that,
as might be expected, jeans are the single most popular item in
teen-agers' wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, we've been seeing dark denims with a tighter fit
for the last two or three years,'' Ms. Zandl said. ``In the
Midwest, we're not seeing that. We're still seeing the bigger jeans
of Jnco, which cornered the market on Raver. But I think that's
peaked. In California, super bell-bottoms are hot. But over all,
the silhouette is smaller and cleaner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are influenced by what the cool people in school are
wearing,'' she said. ``The right clothes and the right brands have
become so important. Pity the kid who saves up to buy the brand
that's in and cool and by the time he has it, people go, `That's so
out.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of the labels that has been out with the young is old
reliable Levi's, which they consider their ``father's jeans.''
Although Levi's is still the best-selling jeans brand, its market
share dropped 30 percent between 1997 and 1998 among males 13 to 24
years old and 38 percent among girls in the same age group,
according to the Zandl Group's latest survey.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's sales fell 4 percent, to $6.9 billion, in 1997, the
latest year for which earnings have been reported. Last month,
Peter Jacobi, the company's No. 2 executive, retired as analysts
predicted an even steeper drop in sales for 1998. Levi's was ``slow
to react to the trends young people were into,'' Ms. Zandl said,
adding, ``Their challenge is getting that back.''
</P>
<P>
   Devon Burt, the creative director of the Levi's brand for the
last six months, is working to reconnect with the youth market.
``We've been around a long time,'' he said, ``and kids are always
looking for something new, something to identify their own
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so into the classic five-pocket jean. We still own
that classic. No one can do it better. But what we want to do is
get more in the center and be able to react quicker. By no means
are we going to go out and chase trends, but we have to redefine
what we stand for and let the new generation understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the ways Levi's is reaching out to the youth market is by
sponsoring music tours and by bringing out the Mod Squad
Collection, a line of clothing inspired by the ``Mod Squad'' movie
coming out next month starring Claire Danes, Omar Epps and Giovanni
Ribisi.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's may be taking a cue from Tommy Hilfiger, who has been
successful in connecting with the youth market for all the products
he sells. To promote his 3-year-old men's jeans line and the Tommy
Jeans for the junior women's market introduced last fall, he is
using hip young musicians in print ads and is currently sponsoring
the Rolling Stones ``No Security'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be in touch with the customer,'' he said. ``The
young consumer today is so advanced, so on top of what's happening,
you have to feed new ideas into the pipeline. If you have a great
name and don't have the product, they won't buy. But you can have a
marginal name and a great product, and they'll find you.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0526 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EDUCATION-BOS     02-01 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT TO OUTLINE EDUCATIONAL OBJECTIVES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
