<HEADLINE>
BRODEUR AND THE PENALTY KILLERS EARN A POINT FOR DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils were looking to redeem
themselves Monday night after their lackadaisical approach led to a
loss two days ago to Nashville, one of the lowly teams in the
league. This time they started just as well as they did against the
expansion Predators, but they maintained their intensity for the
entire game and earned a 2-2 tie against the Detroit Red Wings, one
of the league's elite teams.
</P>
<P>
   That Detroit has won the last two Stanley Cups provided more
than enough motivation for the Devils to play well and sustain it.
But the Devils will have to do better against the Nashvilles of the
league if their aim is to finish high in the conference ranking and
play one of the weaker teams in the playoffs' first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils earned a tie at Continental Arena thanks primarily to
the efficiency of their penalty killers. They kept the Red Wings
scoreless in five power-play attempts and they have now kept the
opposition at bay in the last 25 power plays spanning six games.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur made 30 saves in the New Jersey net and was
particularly sharp during the five manpower advantages for the Red
Wings, who got goals from Aaron Ward and Slava Kozlov. Petr Sykora
and Lyle Odelein scored for the Devils, who failed on five manpower
advantages of their own, including one in the five-minute overtime.
</P>
<P>
   For Coach Robbie Ftorek of New Jersey, there were several
agonizing moments, especially in the first period, as his Devils
were caught in odd-man rushes. Were it not for Brodeur's
goaltending, Detroit would have had more than two goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils started with enthusiasm and Sykora opened the scoring
just 3 minutes 1 second into the game, when his blistering shot
from the right circle hit Chris Osgood's left post and landed in
the net. It was Sykora's 14th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ward tied it for Detroit with his third of the season, at 8:01,
when his shot from near the Devils' blue line found its way past
Brodeur through a crowd in front of the goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit took the lead just under two minutes later when Martin
Lapointe intercepted Bobby Holik's pass in the Devils' zone. His
shot was knocked away by Brodeur, but Kozlov was there for the
rebound and his 11th goal of the season from close range on the
left.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Yzerman had a marvelous opportunity to extend the lead
with six minutes left in the period during a Devils power play.
Brian Rolston of the Devils lost the puck at Detroit's blue line
and Yzerman broke in alone on Brodeur, but his shot hit the
goalie's left skate.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were the better team in the second period and tied
the game on Odelein's second goal in two games, his second of the
season as well. games. It came with 2:39 left in the period from
close range on the right after a precision cross-ice pass by
Brendan Morrison.
</P>
</TEXT>
