<HEADER>
A8064 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-REVENUE-1STLD-     02-01 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-REVENUE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES 81 TAX INCREASES AND 37 CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 4th graf to insert administration figures) (See also BUDGET-CLINTON, BUDGET-ASSESS, BUDGET-SPEND) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's budget includes a grab bag of
small tax cuts for some Americans and small tax increases for
others. Many of these tax proposals seem unlikely to get far in the
Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen such a kitchen-sink approach to government,''
said Rep. Bill Archer of Texas, the chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, which takes first crack at tax legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans like Archer prefer an across-the-board reduction in
income-tax rates for all taxpayers, but it is far from clear that
such an approach can be enacted in the face of a likely
presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   As tallied by congressional committee staff members, who added
all the pluses and minuses in the budget's revenue tables, Clinton
proposed 81 separate tax increases totaling $82 billion over the
next five years and 37 tax cuts totaling $36 billion over the same
period. By the administration's calculations, the comparable
figures are $87.4 billion in new revenue and $32.6 billion in tax
reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The largest amount of new revenue anticipated in the budget
would be generated by the president's tobacco policy. Clinton would
raise nearly $35 billion over five years by increasing the federal
tax on cigarettes, now 24 cents a pack, by an additional 55 cents.
And he would raise an additional $19 billion by insisting that the
federal government get a share of the money that states will
receive from their lawsuits against the cigarette manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   This revenue may not materialize. Last year, the Senate rejected
a proposed increase in cigarette taxes, and the measure never got
off the ground in the House. Furthermore, the states have resisted
sharing with Washington the proceeds from their lawsuits, and
measures are pending in Congress that would block attempts to
recoup the money.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the president's tax proposals do stand a fair chance of
enactment. For example, Clinton proposed a tax cut of up to $1,000
to defray some of the cost of long-term care for elderly or
disabled dependents. A similar proposal was part of the Contract
With America, the platform on which Republicans ran when they won
control of the House in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Clinton proposal, taxpayers could claim this credit if
they provided more than half the support of someone who was in a
nursing home or required other long-term care. The credit would be
reduced for taxpayers with incomes above $75,000, or $110,000 for a
couple filing a joint return.
</P>
<P>
   The president's proposal for a tax credit to offset some of the
cost of child care might stand a slightly better chance this year
because, to appeal to Republicans, the administration added a
modest new benefit for parents who stay home to take care of their
own children.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recommended increasing to 50 percent from 30 percent the
proportion of child-care costs that could be written off by
families with annual incomes below $30,000. The credit would be
gradually reduced for families with incomes between $30,000 and
$59,000 and would be 20 percent of allowable expenses for those
with incomes above $59,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the president proposed an extra tax cut of up to
$250 for families with infants who have not reached their first
birthday. This credit would be available even if the family had no
child-care expenses because a stay-at-home parent or unpaid
relative watched the infant.
</P>
<P>
   The tax credit for long-term care expenses would cost $5 billion
over five years. The expanded child-care credit would cost slightly
more than $6 billion over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the cigarette-tax increase, these are among the
largest of the president's tax proposals. In a budget with total
five-year revenues of about $10 trillion, they are hardly more than
asterisks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many of the president's tax proposals have been offered in the
past and have been rejected out of hand by Congress. Among these
are arcane proposals to change the way airline tickets are taxed,
to alter the tax rules on exports by manufacturers and to raise
taxes on certain life-insurance transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The House Ways and Means Committee staff experts calculated on
Monday that 35 of the 81 revenue increases in the budget are
essentially repeats of measures that were rejected last year. Of
the $82 billion in additional revenue proposed, more than $60
billion would be accounted for by these reprised offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The budget describes many of these proposals as attempts to
``eliminate unwarranted benefits.'' But the beneficiaries obviously
do not view them that way, and the Republican Congress has been
reluctant to end any but the most indefensible tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   As a political matter, the battle over taxes this year is not
likely to be over whether these small tax breaks are justified, but
rather over the broader question of whether part of the budget
surplus should be used for an across-the-board tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argue that it is much more efficient economically to
give everyone a tax reduction than to follow Clinton's course and
give small tax cuts for particular purposes like school
construction or promotion of energy efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The president has threatened to veto an overall tax cut, saying
wealthy people would be the big winners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
