<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ermenegildo Zegna, the venerable Italian suit maker,
is hoping that the most valuable player in the Super Bowl will be
just as valuable as a pitchman for its new athletic line, to be
introduced next fall.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway, the quarterback of the Denver Broncos, has been
signed to be one of the stars of the marketing campaign for the
line, Zegna Sport, said Tom Mastronardi, a partner in
Beauchamp/Mastronardi &AMP; Associates, a New York company, which is
developing the campaign. It will also feature the quarterbacks Dan
Marino and Troy Aiken.
</P>
<P>
   Zegna, a private company, is a powerful but sleepier version of
Italian glamour labels like Giorgio Armani and Nino Cerruti. Zegna
is the safe bread and butter of luxury menswear in stores like
Neiman Marcus and Saks Fifth Avenue. Sales for Zegna were $125
million in the United States in 1998, said Richard Cohen, the chief
executive of Ermenegildo Zegna USA.
</P>
<P>
   Armani, Prada and Tommy Hilfiger have all spun off designer
sports and sneaker lines. Zegna Sport will include functional
athletic clothes with an average price of $75 for a polo shirt or
sweat pants. Since men, no matter their income, tend to buy less
expensive sports brands like Adidas or Champion, Zegna Sport will
have to compete with this segment of the market, as well as with
high-priced labels.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes are being pitched to customers over 35. ``On their
weekends, apart from responsibilities of family and children, they
like to get out there and do something _ golf, tennis,'' Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Zegna Sport store is planned for fall at 305 North Rodeo Drive
in Beverly Hills, Calif., next to an existing Zegna store. The line
will also be in Zegna's six other American stores and in department
stores.
</P>
<P>
   From Street Wear to Suits
</P>
<P>
   The success of Fubu, a hip street-wear company, has meant that
its four owners find themselves invited to evening events a lot
more often. But the casual garb that has made Fubu a $350 million
company is rarely appropriate. So, the company has signed a deal to
start its own tailored suit and sportswear line this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to start purchasing suits and so on for ourselves,''
said Daymond John, who started the company a few years ago in the
basement of his Queens home. ``We saw what we wanted, but at
exorbitant prices.''
</P>
<P>
   But can Fubu, whose name is an acronym for ``For us, by us,''
parlay its street credibility to the office? Richard Pietrafesa,
the president of the Pietrafesa Corp. in Syracuse, which has made
menswear for Brooks Brothers and Ralph Lauren, believes it will
work. Pietrafesa has signed a licensing deal with Fubu to produce
three collections. ``The name has tremendous appeal across a wide
range of constituents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John, whose partners are Keith Perrin, Carl Brown and J.
Alexander Martin, said he expected Fubu's current fans to buy the
new line. ``My present customers are a lot of Wall Street guys who
dress down in Fubu on the weekends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom of Finland in Chelsea
</P>
<P>
   Attracted by the galleries, the affluent gay population and a
hunch that Chelsea may be the next high-fashion mecca, Tom of
Finland menswear will open its first store in the neighborhood next
week.
</P>
<P>
   The store will be at 261 West 19th St. Instead of showing during
the menswear collections, which begin next week, Tom of Finland's
designers, David Johnson and Gary Robinson, plan to have a party
with informal modeling on Feb. 11 in the shop. Coincidentally, a
Comme des Garcons boutique, which moved from SoHo, is scheduled to
open the day before at 520 West 22d St.
</P>
<P>
   The Tom of Finland boutique will carry jeans, biker jackets,
outerwear and special leather pieces, with prices from about $45 to
more than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the neighborhood's influx of galleries, the
boutique Tom of Finland, which is named for the illustrator of
erotic, muscle-bound gay men, is designed to house small art
exhibitions. ``Most important is the whole gay angle,'' Johnson
said. But he added, ``The nongay people in that area, people who
are interested in artwork, all that foot traffic will come into the
store.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
