<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0531 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SPORTS-CITY-NYT &LR;      02-01 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPORTS-CITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ONE NATION, DEVOURED BY SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the time Super Bowl XXXIII gasped to an end on
Sunday night, there could not be a soul left in this city to doubt
the dominance of sports in our social, political and, yes, moral
universe. Let's not even discuss the XI hours of Sunday football
programming on Fox television or the numbing M's of words inspired
by this rather dull game.
</P>
<P>
   New York, which likes to think of itself as impervious to any
outside force short of a nuclear attack, was transformed on Super
Sunday. Streets were fairly empty, restaurants uncrowded and
theater lines short _ all because gargantuan men from Denver and
Atlanta were smashing into one another on the tube.
</P>
<P>
   With so many people eating in, the police decided to crack down
on the scourge of many New Yorkers: deliverymen on bicycles. These
are mostly sympathetic fellows, low-paid and hard-working. But if
you have ever been clipped or scared half to death by one of them
riding on the sidewalk or going the wrong way on a one-way street,
you know the problem.
</P>
<P>
   While the game was on, officers from the XX Precinct _ OK, no
more; that's the 20th Precinct _ set up in a spread formation on
the Upper West Side, flagging down restaurant deliverers flouting
the law. ``Operation Halftime,'' they jauntily called it.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 62 summonses were issued. Many food pedalers had their
bikes confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the dinners they were carrying remains a
mystery. A police spokeswoman and officers at the precinct said
they had no idea. For all anyone knows, some West Siders are still
waiting for their pizzas and steamed dumplings.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where the food wound up, many in Manhattan were no
doubt thrilled by this crackdown. The recklessness of some cyclists
is alarming.
</P>
<P>
   But a closer look suggests that the summonses may not have
struck at the heart of the problem. Of the 62 handed out, 55 were
for not displaying proper identification or for lacking required
bike equipment like lights or horns. Only five were for riding the
wrong way, along with one for bicycling on the sidewalk and one for
going through a red light.
</P>
<P>
   That's not terribly many, when you think about it. Those last
violations are what set New Yorkers' teeth to gnashing, not
handlebars without bells.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe takeout restaurants saw the light and ordered their
deliverers to shape up. Or maybe the police are still fine-tuning
their search and seizure techniques. Oscar night in late March
offers them another opportunity. They could get in the Hollywood
spirit by dubbing the operation ``Saving General Tso.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the social aspects of professional athletics.
</P>
<P>
   For the political effects, look at the latest budget proposal
from the sports-minded mayor, Rudolph Giuliani. He has talked about
building no fewer than six stadiums and arenas that could
eventually cost a billion dollars or two: ball parks for the
Yankees and the Mets; a football stadium on the West Side, next to
a new Madison Square Garden, and new ball parks on Staten Island
and in Brooklyn for minor-league teams.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the mayor likes sports so much that his administration
has given the Yankees and the Mets grants of $3 million each to
help them figure out what kinds of stadiums they would like, and
where. Good thing he has shrunk the welfare rolls so that money is
available to assist such needy enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   As for moral import, it is hard to beat the stir caused by the
Knicks' hiring of Latrell Sprewell, a talented basketball player
best known for having choked his coach. And just before the Super
Bowl, the great former Giant, Lawrence Taylor, was voted into the
Pro Football Hall of Fame. There was a lot of hand-wringing over
whether this was the right thing to do. Taylor has had trouble
staying away from crack cocaine and from the back seats of police
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Expect such morality debates to be repeated, Jeff Benedict said
Monday. ``People get pretty emotional over issues like this,'' said
Benedict, co-author of ``Pros and Cons: The Criminals Who Play in
the NFL'' (Warner Books). This recent study discovered that one of
five pro football players had been charged with serious crimes,
with roughly half found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict also noted that what counts to football's mandarins is
a person's performance on the field, not off it. He made no
reference, in this context, to the Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
