A8072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATCHMAKER-PROFILE-NY     02-01 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATCHMAKER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-FASHIONED ARRANGER FOR A LONELY CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Interviewing Dan Field is not hard work. ``Relax,''
he says, grabbing a reporter's tape recorder. ``I'll take over.''
</P>
<P>
   He turns to a photographer. ``Let me tell you how to make a good
picture,'' he says. ``Number one, like this, like a businessman.''
He strikes a pose against the desk in his tiny office near Grand
Central Terminal, jutting out his chest. Then he goes to a filing
cabinet, grinning as he opens a drawer stuffed with thousands of
smudged index ards.
</P>
<P>
   If this seems only a little pushy, it is because arranging
things is what Field has done for more than 40 years, and what his
uncle did before him and his grandfather, Rabbi Joseph Field,
before that, in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Field is a professional matchmaker. And February for him is like
November for a turkey farmer. ``Business is good,'' he says.
``People are lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly oblivious to every upheaval in the world of love
during the last four decades _ the sexual revolution, casual
cohabitation, personal ads, the Internet and even _ perish the
thought _ women asking out men, Field bristles at the words
``dating service.'' He once called himself a marriage broker, like
his uncle, Irving Field, but that is now illegal under federal law.
Whatever it is called, Field, owner of Field's Exclusive Service,
does it the same way he always has.
</P>
<P>
   His office has no computers. The walls are carpeted and
decorated with thousands of pictures, including one of Field as a
guest on ``The Mike Douglas Show'' in the 1970s with Joan Rivers
and Jack Klugman.
</P>
<P>
   The lovelorn _ once mostly Jewish, but now from all backgrounds,
he says _ drop by and describe themselves and the kind of mates
they are looking for. Field and his 32-year-old grandson, Joseph
Speyer, fill out index cards. Later, the two thumb through hundreds
of other cards in the big gray filing cabinet, and mail clients the
names and numbers of possible matches.
</P>
<P>
   They still encourage the women to wait to be called. And to the
men, they still send letters with guidelines straight out of Emily
Post: ``In order to make a good appearance to the ladies, always be
dressed up.'' The rest, Field says, is up to fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No gimmicks,'' he says. ``I see the person. A computer, you
only press buttons.'' He adds: ``On the Internet or whatever you
want to call it, how do you know who's this person? You know how
many killings there were already from the Internet? They met each
other and they killed each other? I have papers.'' He begins to
rummage in a stack of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, though, Field has begun to generate a
few bad headlines of his own. Two city councilmen held a news
conference in front of his office last year, saying that clients
had complained that they were pressured to pay for extra services,
like haircuts and makeovers, after already paying up to $1,000 in
fees. The Better Business Bureau sent him a letter in January 1998,
saying it had received 16 complaints about his service in 36
months, earning him an unsatisfactory rating with the consumer
group.
</P>
<P>
   Field insists that he has never pressured anyone to do anything,
although he does urge people to look nice for dates. He adds that
complaints are inevitable in a business that deals in hope and
fragile emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can write into the Better Business Bureau,'' he says.
``I call them the Better Baloney Business.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a theory about what makes clients generally less
satisfied than clients were back when he began matchmaking with his
uncle. ``Today, the more educated they are, the better looking they
are, the bigger problem they have,'' he says. ``They don't know
what they want. They pass 30, already there is a little problem.
They get set in their ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in his day, he added, people came in, they got married and
``they stayed married, like concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with Field's reminiscences _ and many other
things he says _is that they tend to change a little with the
telling. At one point, he says his father came from Poland to the
United States, and kept his grandfather's matchmaking tradition
alive. Later, he says that all of his immediate family disappeared
in the Holocaust and that he alone was saved, a boy of 11 sent out
on a ship ``with a label around my neck, like I was a package.''
</P>
<P>
   He will spell his name for you: ``F-I-E-L-D-S.'' His grandson,
who has been working with him for a dozen years, corrects: ``No
S.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever,'' Field says, brushing him away.
</P>
<P>
   Asked his age, he says: ``Nobody knows how old they are from
Europe. It's how old you feel.'' Asks how old he feels, he says,
his eyes sparkling: ``The middle 60s.'' (His grandson says he is
probably somewhere in his 70s.)
</P>
<P>
   He says he has worked hard in the matchmaking business, and that
it has treated him well. He estimates he has served about 120,000
clients. He has no idea how many ended up with lasting
relationships, but one of those who did was a young woman named
Lillian Horowitz, whom Field married. ``Uncle Irving told me, `Dan,
it's time for you to get married. Call this girl.''' They were
married for 53 years and lived in Scarsdale, N.Y. Mrs. Field died
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Field says he has always worked seven days a week, and he will
keep it up until he loses his knack: ``Right now, I still have it.
Sometimes a man says, `Give me this, give me that,' and I send him
altogether the opposite. `That's what I was looking for!' he
says.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
