<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BRUTALITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BRUTALITY INQUIRY AT THE NASSAU JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, Feb. 2: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By its own admission, the Nassau County district attorney's
office has bungled the job of investigating and prosecuting
brutality charges lodged by inmates against guards at the Nassau
County jail. But beyond failing to surmount some of the usual
obstacles _ guards unwilling to testify against their brethren and
reliance on overworked investigators _ this office seems paralyzed
by a debilitating mindset articulated by Frank Quigley, chief of
special investigations for District Attorney Denis Dillon. ``Does
society tolerate this kind of abuse?'' Quigley told The Times'
David Halbfinger. ``In the cold light of day, no. But in their
secret heart of hearts, the answer may be different.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude and the office's lackluster record in pursuing
charges of prisoner abuse are profoundly disturbing. That makes
Dillon's decision, reached Monday, to defer his own inquiry a
welcome development. Zachary Carter, U.S. Attorney for New York's
Eastern District, and the FBI will now take charge of what should
become a wide-ranging look into a raft of allegations of brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Pizzuto's death last month has heightened concern. A
recovering heroin addict serving a 90-day sentence for traffic
violations, Pizzuto died Jan. 13 from injuries sustained while he
was in the custody of guards, which the county Medical Examiner and
investigators say are consistent with assault. His death has been
ruled a homicide.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights prosecution Carter promises should help
determine what new policies and procedures the county jail needs.
Dillon's call for the use of video cameras to document inmate
treatment is a long-overdue reform. It should be combined with
strict policies that can prevent a recurrence of the kind of
lawlessness Americans generally associate with rogue regimes, not
local agencies they pay taxes to support.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon and Carter also agreed Monday that federal grand jury
procedures, evidentiary requirements and penalties were superior to
those available under state law. Only a thorough federal inquiry
and reform can reassure New Yorkers that every agency of their
criminal justice system has the safeguards necessary to prevent
brutality and to uphold the Constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
