<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MONMOUTH-WAGNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST NCAA TEAM WITHOUT A VICTORY, MONMOUTH ENDS 0-22 FAMINE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST LONG BRANCH, N.J. _ Monmouth University forward Alpha
Bangura flung the basketball to the ceiling as the buzzer sounded
Monday night, ending the game and a drought. Students of this
school less than a mile from the Jersey Shore emptied from the
gymnasium bleachers, storming the court wave upon wave.
</P>
<P>
   As the public address system played the song ``Celebration'' and
players and fans united in a group hug at center court, the crowd
of 1,117 did not chant, ``We're No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   They could have chanted, ``That's one.''
</P>
<P>
   With a dramatic second-half comeback, Monmouth, which had been
the only Division I team in the nation without a victory this
season, defeated Wagner, 66-61, at Boylan Gymnasium. Monmouth,
which qualified for the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament only three years ago, improved its season record to
1-19.
</P>
<P>
   The victory also ended Monmouth's 22-game losing streak, which
was the longest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt a little like we were going to the NCAAs,'' said guard
Maurice Williams, the lone holdover from Monmouth's 1996 NCAA team.
``It was kind of reminiscent.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bangura, the end of the game was a release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was four months of frustration,'' Bangura said. ``That's 20
games and a lot of practices to get one win. It shouldn't take that
long, but when we got it, it was exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dave Calloway, who starts three freshman and has lost six
players from his program for various reasons in the past year,
spent the past week answering questions about the streak in part
because it was assumed that Monmouth's game with Wagner (5-15)
might be its best _ or last _ chance to win a game this season.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Calloway's first reaction following Monday
night's victory was one of relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt relief for me but even more relief for the guys,'' said
Calloway, who took over the program when long-time coach Wayne
Szoke resigned a year ago with Monmouth's record at 1-13. ``For
them, it's hard to keep working. It's been tough. In yesterday's
practice, I questioned their toughness. But by this response, they
proved me wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Division I basketball record for successive losses is 37
games, by the Citadel in the 1954-55 season.
</P>
<P>
   If the crowd Monday night was stirred up by the game's end, it
could have been because of Monmouth's rousing rally to win its
first game since last Feb. 16, also against Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   With 7 minutes 35 seconds to play in the second half, Wagner led
by 53-47. Behind Williams, Monmouth went on an 11-2 run, taking a
3-point lead with three minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Williams scored 9 of his game-high 19 points in that span. In
the final minute, as Wagner fouled in an attempt to get back in the
game, Bangura sank four consecutive free throws to extend
Monmouth's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practice every day, the coaches have been putting 10
minutes on the clock to get us to concentrate on playing the last
10 minutes with good focus and execution,'' Williams said. ``It's
been a drill so we won't let down. And tonight it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner Coach Tim Capstraw noticed the same thing. Of Monmouth,
Capstraw said: ``Their team has had a lot of good 35 minute games.
This time, they had a good last five minutes, too.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if it was especially difficult to be the first team
to lose to Monmouth this season, Capstraw said: ``I'll be honest
with you, I have my own problems. We had respect for them. We're
not that strong a team to have looked at it any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory seemed to put a charge into the Monmouth campus with
a large crowd remaining in the gymnasium even after the players
headed to their locker room. ``We've gotten overwhelming support,''
Calloway said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Williams: ``No one on campus has said anything cruel to
me. It's tough because I've seen this place when we really were
heading to the NCAAs. I want to get that back.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're here because we love playing basketball and we loved
it even with all the losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bangura felt Monday night's victory might spark a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving up yet,'' Bangura, a freshman, said. ``Monmouth
has a lot of plans. I've got a lot of plans.''
</P>
<P>
   And now it will even be a little easier for the Monmouth
cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard sometimes to raise spirit in the gym when you're
0-19,'' said Gail Chance, a junior from East Brunswick. ``But we
always came here each game thinking that this time we had a
chance.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
