</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: IN `SPIN CITY,' MASTERS OF THEIR NON-NEW YORK
DOMAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All right, we all knew ``Seinfeld,'' and ``Spin
City'' is no ``Seinfeld.'' But the resemblances are there,
conspicuously the New York setting if not its ambience and the
dependable shticks of its residents. Comfortably into its third
season, ``Spin City'' is holding its own, a tribute to its quirky
characters and their comical collisions. There are many nights when
the ensemble at an improbable City Hall is at least as funny as the
gang at the relatively realistic Upper West Side diner used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody can ignore the differences. Seinfeld and his
pals, even those operating under different ethnic disguises,
kvetched in television's copyright New York Jewish manner.
Curiously for New York by contrast, the mayor's office spinning at
the center of ``Spin City,'' otherwise a weekly buffet of mockable
diversity by sex, race and so forth, does not include that
particular stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   Even Indian cab drivers, equipped with truculent accents of some
sort, got a jolly going-over recently in an episode about a taxi
strike: ``We've had a number of complaints from pedestrians.''
``About what?'' ``Apparently you keep running into them.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is only by way of observing that although decorated with
familiar places, this really isn't a New York show. Instead, it's
about a clubby batch of outsiders who have somehow found jobs in
what is labeled City Hall, as if to demonstrate that they can make
it anywhere. In the amiable array of made-for-television eccentrics
you will not spot one who might be classified as a Manhattan type.
Yet all are Seinfeldish in their self-absorption and their
merciless scrutiny of everyone else's weaknesses and compulsions,
the amusing tics of a smartly scripted series that only
occasionally dips into sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Fox, the ever-in-motion star who won a Golden Globe
last week playing a brogueless Deputy Mayor Michael Flaherty, is
frenetically at work getting his boss into or out of hot water
(which his honor rarely notices he is in) and pursuing romance
while racing away from it like any certified neurotic. When our
Michael gets too close to commitment, he has breathing problems. He
and Connie Britton, whose last name is supposed to be Faber, have
something for each other, which you can bet will remain shakily
unresolved as long as they keep meeting around the candy machine
with a mind of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those endearingly odd roommates _ Michael
Boatman, the black representative of middle-class homosexual
gentility, and Alan Ruck, the determinedly vulgar white
heterosexual trapped forever in his teens _ who are equipped with
vaudeville cracks at the expense of each other's sexual
proclivities. There's Paul (Richard Kind), the ingenuously devious,
implacably maladroit press spokesman, and young James (Alexander
Chaplin), adrift from some Gothic all-American town and without a
place to park. And there's an outer-borough sexpot (Jennifer
Esposito) with an uncurable yet wholesome lech. And there's a
suicidal dog.
</P>
<P>
   They and others all have their moments, but the truly brilliant
``Spin City'' invention is Mayor Randall Winston, a WASP of eerie
calm in the midst of the bustle. Played with finely tuned vagueness
by Barry Bostick, he is the ultimate outsider (as well as the one
cast regular of a certain age), oblivious to distraction as he
tries to figure out whither his unflappable muse calls. While Mike
is conspiring to fix a dam that has more leaks than he has fingers,
the mayor resides Zen-like high above the flood, as well as several
heads above his diminutive troubleshooter.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Seinfeld'' was topical in a social-comment way, as an
exercise in over-the-edge Upper West Side angst, ``Spin City'' is
often smack on the news. As I write this, a trash war is again
going on between New York and one of its selected garbage
depository towns far away. Fans will remember that very early in
the series in 1996, Michael, informed that his city contributes
more than its share to the nation's garbage dump, announced
triumphantly, ``We're No. 1!''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of one-liners to pep up the action, plenty of
peculiarities of personality to grease an antic 22 minutes a week.
And even if a touch of desperation shows in an occasional plot that
flies out of control or in gags that do not bear yet another
go-round, the collective spirit generally prevails.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty part of sitcoms is that recycled jokes, shrewdly set
up, often provide heartier laughs than new ones. But then you don't
have to look and act like a New Yorker to figure that out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
