<HEADER>
A8094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-CAMEOS-NYT &LR;      02-01 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CAMEOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANT TO BE IN PICTURES? ALMOST ANYONE CAN, FOR FIVE SECONDS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fate of ``At First Sight,'' the Irwin Winkler
film that opened to tepid reviews a few weeks ago, probably won't
depend on the publishing and real estate magnate Mort Zuckerman's
seconds-long performance as a surly, tattered homeless man.
</P>
<P>
   But Zuckerman's screen debut is a reminder that it may be time
to update Andy Warhol's dictum about everyone's getting 15 minutes
of fame. Now almost everyone seems to get at least five seconds of
it on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Cameo appearances seem to be more a creature of New York
filmmakers than Hollywood ones, and cameos hardly began in the 90s.
But vanity film roles seem to be one of the status symbols of the
90s. What they have to do with the business of making movies is
less clear.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably three main kinds of cameos. There is the
classic cameo performance, in which Hollywood actors show up in
small parts, like the actors who appear in Robert Altman movies
because of their admiration for his work. Then there are
recognizable people playing themselves or similar characters, like
the CNN reporters who showed up in ``Contact'' or Ivana Trump in
``The First Wives Club.'' Last, there are people not known as
actors who often are recognizable only to their friends, like
Zuckerman in his recent role.
</P>
<P>
   The Category 3 cameos are often byproducts of friendships, like
Zuckerman's with Winkler, rather than career moves, though some of
the actors tend to take them pretty seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The writer Calvin Trillin keeps a photograph of the marquee of
the Varsity Theater in Seattle prominently displayed on the
mantelpiece of his bedroom. It reads: ``Meg Ryan Calvin Trillin in
Sleepless in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   The usual billing for the film went to Ms. Ryan and Tom Hanks,
who played a somewhat bigger role in the film than Trillin's brief
appearance at a Christmas dinner. In addition, Trillin played a
sheriff in ``Michael,'' a 1996 movie starring John Travolta that
was also directed by Trillin's friend Nora Ephron.
</P>
<P>
   Trillin concedes that his acting career at the moment seems
bound by the whims of Ms. Ephron, who regularly casts friends in
small roles in her movies and gives the characters in her films
names from her real life. But he maintains that his cinematic
oeuvre, particularly his sheriff's role, remains underappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fantastic,'' reported Trillin, who said he prepared for
his role by reading and rereading the Texas Ranger creed every
morning: ``No man in the wrong can stand up against a fellow that's
in the right and keeps on a'comin'.'' Trillin added: ``When I got
into my sheriff's costume and walked onto the set, Nora, whom I've
known for 35 years, actually thought one of the law enforcement
officers had illegally parked his van outside and walked onto the
set. I was the sheriff.''
</P>
<P>
   The king of the cameos may be the author George Plimpton, whose
acting career dates back to his performance as one of 6,000
Bedouins in ``Lawrence of Arabia.'' Plimpton said he was there to
write about the film and ended up also appearing in it when its
director, David Lean, banished him to a Bedouin encampment.
</P>
<P>
   Since then his appearances have included ``The Detective'' with
Frank Sinatra, ``Rio Lobo'' with John Wayne, ``Reds,'' ``Religion
Inc.'' (an early Sandra Bullock film), ``Little Man Tate,''
``Bonfire of the Vanities,'' ``Nixon'' and ``L.A. Story,'' in which
he played a weatherman whose line was ``Sunny, 79 degrees
Fahrenheit.'' His most recent role was as a psychiatrist in ``Good
Will Hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen, since his early days of putting Howard Cosell in
``Bananas'' and Marshall McLuhan in ``Annie Hall,'' has probably
been more prone to using cameo performances than any current
director.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years his films have included appearances by Benno
Schmidt Jr., former president of Yale University and current head
of the Edison Project educational company; Ms. Ephron, Donald
Trump, writers from Bruce Jay Friedman to Erica Jong, Itzhak
Perlman and his daughter Navah, Elle Macpherson, Saul Bellow, Susan
Sontag, and the former New York City mayor, Ed Koch.
</P>
<P>
   His most recent film, ``Celebrity,'' includes brief appearances
by Joey Buttafuoco, the director Andre Gregory, the fashion
designer Isaac Mizrahi, the actor and singer Robert Cuccioli and
Frank Pellegrino, owner of Rao's, an exclusive Manhattan
restaurant. Pellegrino also appeared in Allen's ``Broadway Danny
Rose'' and `Manhattan Murder Mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pellegrino is hardly the only restaurateur to enter the
cameo sweepstakes. ``Simply Irresistible,'' a forthcoming film
starring Sarah Michelle Gellar and set in the world of New York
restaurants, includes a brief performance by Drew Nieporent, an
owner of Montrachet, Layla, TriBeCa Grill and other Manhattan hot
spots. Viewers can give themselves two insider points if they spot
him.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, where filmmaking is no joking matter, people can
play the same game, but not everyone is taken with the idea of
vanity roles.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Press, director of marketing for Dreamworks, cited Alfred
Hitchcock's famous blink-and-you-miss-them appearances as the rare
examples of a shared joke that worked between a director and his
audience. No one would turn down a cameo by Leonardo DiCaprio (who
did one for Allen in ``Celebrity''), she said, but most cameos seem
of questionable value.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Landis used to do it ad nauseum,'' she added. ``The
problem with cameos is I'm never sure what they're done for. Is it
to say, `Hi, I'm a director, and I have these famous friends,' or
is it in support of the story?''
</P>
<P>
   The producer Don De Line said perhaps New York's fondness for
cameos suggested more of an appreciation for Hollywood than New
Yorkers tend to express.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Mort Zuckerman and Donald Trump have everything
you could want, but I guess they still want to rub shoulders with
celebrities,'' he said. ``New Yorkers tend to mock Hollywood, but
at the end of the day, they're fascinated by it.''
</P>
<P>
   A multimillionaire having fun playing a homeless person may not
be everyone's idea of a good joke. Janet Maslin in The New York
Times described Zuckerman's cameo as a ``Marie Antoinette.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone offered me a dollar afterwards, I was so good, but I
told him I don't accept less than five,'' Zuckerman said.
</P>
<P>
   The rampant cameo turns is yet another example of the blurring
of the line between life and entertainment and of the endless
gradations of celebrity. Advertisers like to pepper their ads with
marginally famous or formerly famous or soon-to-be famous ``niche
celebrities'' who give knowing consumers a sense of being clued in
and hip.
</P>
<P>
   Plimpton may be on to something with his modest proposal for
recognizing the famous who labor in obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think they need to give out a little Oscar, a small
one, to people from other disciplines who appear in films,'' he
said. ``You think of Jerzy Kosinski in `Reds.' Gosh, he was good.
It's not easy. People get tongue-tied. I kept forgetting my lines
in `Nixon.' Why not some recognition?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
