<DOCNO> NYT19990201.0542 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-01 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      02-01 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE CREAM STILL RISES, EVEN FROM BARREL BOTTOM
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Greenspan isn't a mere actor. He's an appliance
on the fritz. Plug him in and watch the mechanism go haywire: he
shakes and rattles, swivels and squeaks so persuasively you half
expect smoke to rise from a crack in his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, his stock in trade is the alien among us, but not in
the vein of Mork from Ork. Greenspan, an Obie-winning performer and
playwright, alights from somewhere beyond the outer limits. Whether
he's intimidating the other guests as a particularly spooky Harold
in ``The Boys in the Band'' or waxing oleaginous in an enigmatic
Mac Wellman extravaganza, he is always strung out in one way or
another, on a supercilious tear or on the brink of total
neurological collapse. And that's why he is ideal for ``High
Life,'' Lee MacDougall's new lowlife comedy at Primary Stages about
a cockeyed gang of junkie grifters who botch an ATM heist and end
up killing one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Any week in New York City, you can find two or three new Off
Broadway plays that, like ``High Life,'' ruminate about lowlifes.
As the nation becomes ever more affluent, it seems, the theater
becomes increasingly obsessed with the drunk, the disorderly, the
dysfunctional. It's not a return to the 1960's and the theater of
social awareness, however; few in this genre are intended as
exercises in consciousness-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, many of these plays seek to capitalize on our insatiable
need for the goriest details and on our appetite for reminders of
what we all might easily become. They are, in their way, extreme
reactions to the sanitized domains of television sitcoms, where the
people and the apartments almost always are more attractive than
the real world.
</P>
<P>
   In ``High Life,'' the diminutive Greenspan is eminently
entertaining as Donnie, the most reptilian and tightly wound of a
quartet of sociopathic drug addicts in this only slightly
diverting, extended sketch of a play. Like the dramatic situation,
Greenspan's performance ultimately trails off into irrelevance. But
before that happens, the actor does something remarkable: he makes
the burnt-out ends of drug-filled days seem, well, funny. It's an
eccentrically winning embodiment of the effects of mind-altering
chemicals, in the tradition of Richard E. Grant's bravura turn as a
tanked-up, out-of-work actor in the cult film ``Withnail and I.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's impression of a human Osterizer is the best thing
about ``High Life,'' because it's so exhaustively resourceful in
ways the script does not appear to call for; even in obvious bits,
as when Donnie reports on his recent bout of pneumonia while
sucking on a cigarette, his work is fresh. Yet despite other
assets, including Casey Childs' crisp direction and Isiah Whitlock
Jr.'s flash-fire portrayal of one of Donnie's homicidal partners in
crime, ``High Life'' remains long on exposition and short on
revelation. In fact, given the plethora of plays these days that
sift society's dregs, the details of ``High Life'' are positively
fungible.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best of these lowlife dramas, with their echoes of
older playwrights like Sam Shepard, succeed because of
self-consciously withering humor (as in ``Killer Joe'') or
delicately textured atmosphere (``Ecstasy'') or devastatingly real
characters (``This Is Our Youth''). But many others are simply
imitative of better plays. They are flawed works that walk on the
dark side chiefly because that's where the theater crowd has taken
them.
</P>
<P>
   Three Off and Off Off Broadway productions that opened in recent
weeks _ MacDougall's ``High Life,'' Jessica Goldberg's ``Stuck''
and George F. Walker's ``End of Civilization'' _ fall into this
latter category. All serve up crime and degradation, but little in
the way of elucidation or even cheap thrills.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goldberg's play, for instance, produced by Rattlestick
Productions at the Theater Off Park, is a Gothic riff on ``Thelma
and Louise'' with a bit of Shepard's ``Buried Child'' thrown in.
Directed by Abby Epstein, it is the tale of two lost young women
working in a video store in ``Middletown, U.S.A.,'' and aching for
an escape from a stultifying life of alcoholic parents, predatory
men, tabloid-television culture and unwanted children.
</P>
<P>
   The relentlessly depressing outlook of ``Stuck'' is the opposite
of what we've come to accept as the American Dream, that children
born into an environment that chokes off hope use the negative
energy to their advantage. ``Hi, stupid baby! Who's the stupidest
baby?'' one of the video store women, played by Jenny Maguire, coos
nastily to the infant daughter she has carelessly brought into her
deadwood world. Ms. Maguire's Margaritah is a former high school
prom queen who falls in love with a right-wing Argentine
businessman (Michael Irby) whose father has bought the town's
pollution-spewing factory; her best friend, Lula (Jennifer Albano)
hits the bars and winds up in bed with the father of one of her old
school chums.
</P>
<P>
   Playing soul mates in benumbed despair, Ms. Albano and
particularly Ms. Maguire are heroically believable, and Ms.
Goldberg is skillful at the portrait of rapport. Evidence of a
sharp intellect is abundant, but as with ``High Life,'' ``Stuck''
lacks the forward thrust of compelling theater. Until the
horrifying final scene, which only reiterates rather than enlarges
the play's themes, the drama lives up to its name. By the time
``Stuck'' ends, it feels as if the story has only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's ``End of Civilization'' at Raw Space tries to add an
air of mystery to the lowlife genre, but all it really adds is
confusion. The play, which jumps around so arbitrarily that the
only time you can be sure of is the one on your wrist, takes place
in that lowlife staple, a tacky motel, where Henry and Lily, a
despairing, unemployed man and his dutiful wife, have taken a room
while he looks for work. During their short stay, a serial killer
starts knocking off job seekers in all the employment offices Henry
visits, while Lily takes up life as a hooker.
</P>
<P>
   The play offers some real howlers: ``I think Henry is going to
kill a lot of people because Henry is feeling very demeaned,'' Lily
helpfully informs the dimwitted detectives on the case. Of course,
it all ends with a single gunshot. This production, directed by
Randy White, inadvertently poses the question at the heart of all
down-and-dirty drama: How low, really, can you go?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is, when the theatrical experience is potent, there
is no bottom to the barrel. As demonstrated by Greenspan's
memorable work in ``High Life,'' the creepiest stage behavior,
leavened by wit, can make the heart soar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-01-99 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
