<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARKLY COMIC ADVENTURE WINS NEWBERY MEDAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By EDEN ROSS LIPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The 1999 Newbery Medal for children's literature
was announced on Monday for a darkly comic novel about a
schoolboy's mysterious adventure. The winning book, ``Holes,'' by
Louis Sachar (Frances Foster Books/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux), is
about a boy named Stanley Yelnats who is convicted for a crime he
did not commit and serves time at Camp Green Lake, a bizarre
juvenile detention center in a dry Texas wasteland. The award is
given by the American Library Association.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Holes,'' which won the National Book Award for young
people's literature in November, was the popular and critical
favorite, it was an exceptionally strong year for both fiction and
nonfiction, and librarians and publishers expressed surprise that
only one honor book, or secondary award, was given, for ``A Long
Way from Chicago,'' a novel by Richard Peck (Dial Books for Young
Readers).
</P>
<P>
   There was something of a wintry theme on the picture book side.
The Caldecott Medal for illustration went to Mary Azarian, a
Vermont artist, for ``Snowflake Bentley'' (Houghton Mifflin), her
account of the life of Wilson Bentley, an early photographer of
snowflakes, illustrated with distinctive woodcuts.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four honor books are also set in the cold: ``Snow''
written and illustrated by Uri Shulevitz (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux)
and ``Tibet Through the Red Box,'' written and illustrated by Peter
Sis (Frances Foster Books/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux). The association
also cited Brian Pinkney for his illustrations for ``Duke
Ellington: The Piano Prince and His Orchestra'' by Andrea Davis
Pinkney (Hyperion Books for Children) and ``No David'' written and
illustrated by David Shannon (Blue Sky Press/Scholastic).
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, the Young Adult Library Services
Association, a division of the American Library Association, has
agreed to the establishment of a separate award for the best young
adult book for readers ages 12 to 18 based on literary merit.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Newbery and Caldecott awards, the winner will be
announced at the midwinter meeting of the association. Only books
published by youth divisions or dedicated children's publishers
will be considered, not adult books with crossover appeal to
adolescents. Curiously a British middle-grade children's novel,
``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,'' is sitting firmly on the
adult best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   Librarians have long championed fiction written especially for
adolescent readers, but publishers' interest has waxed and waned.
Now publishers and the entertainment business are showing renewed
interest in teen-agers' spending power and tastes with the success
of the magazine Teen People and movies like Adam Sandler's ``Water
Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30th-anniversary Coretta Scott King awards were also
announced. The author award went to Angela Johnson for ``Heaven''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster) and the illustrator award to Michele Wood for
``I See the Rhythm'' (Children's Book Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
