<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TECHNOLOGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO PICK TEAM TO ASSESS CHINA'S ACQUISITION OF U.S.
TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to a House committee's finding that
China stole sensitive American military technology over a period of
two decades, President Clinton will name a team of experts to
assess the damage and report back to Congress, an administration
official said on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take this issue very seriously, and we are organizing an
interagency team, including nuclear weapons and
counterintelligience experts,'' said David Leavy, a spokesman for
the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy declined to say whether the president had determined that
the loss of sensitive data to China had, in fact, damaged national
security, the bedrock conclusion of the select House committee
headed by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official who has followed the issue closely
said on Monday night that there had been spirited debate within the
White House over whether there had been a threat to national
security. Leavy conceded that the decision to name a team of
experts to investigate the Chinese activities was a signal that the
damage might indeed have been very far reaching.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy said the damage-assessment team's findings would be
reviewed in turn by a panel of independent experts before they are
given to Congress. He said he could provide no details about who
would make up either the team or the outside panel or how the
members of each would be recruited.
</P>
<P>
   He said the work of the teams would be submitted to Congress
``in a timely fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of military and commercial deals with China has been
explosive in Washington for many months. In December, the Cox
committee, consisting of five Republicans and four Democrats,
concluded unanimously that China had obtained over the past 20
years some of the United States' most sensitive military
technology, including designs for nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Some information was obtained through theft, the committee
concluded, while other material was obtained by American
scientists' sharing knowledge with their Chinese counterparts
during satellite launchings involving both countries.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's findings, highly unusual in their bipartisan
nature, blamed Republican and Democratic administrations alike for
having allowed the security lapses to develop. It called China's
gleaning of American secrets a ``serious, sustained'' activity.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox committee began its inquiry last spring, after The New
York Times disclosed that American satellite makers had helped
Chinese scientists correct failures in their rocket programs and in
so doing had conveyed information applicable to long-range
ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The committee held 33 hearings, all closed, over six months. It
took testimony from intelligence officials, industry executives and
nuclear-weapons experts.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy said the White House agreed with the majority of the
committee's recommendations, which call among other things for
tighter controls on exports of technology and stiff penalties for
American companies that violate those controls.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Cox, the Republican members of the committee were Reps.
Curt Weldon of Pennsylvania, Porter J. Goss of Florida, James V.
Hansen of Utah and Doug Bereuter of Nebraska.The Democrats were
Norm Dicks of Washington, John M. Spratt Jr. of South Carolina,
Robert C. Scott of Virginia and Lucille Roybal-Allard of
California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
